<SLUG> BC-FBN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME FOR BILL R. TO STEP ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, Bill, there is a way out. You have the blessing of
precedent, and it happened in your hometown.
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia McCaskey can fire her son, so can you.
</P>
<P>
   A few details while you roll your eyes:
</P>
<P>
   Do you know that your son, Bill Bidwill Jr., recently received a
phone call from Jake Plummer? A call pleading for Lomas Brown. A
call that didn't produce the answer Plummer expected.
</P>
<P>
   Do you know that Eric Hill, a former employee, had a bachelor's
party in Las Vegas over the weekend? Do you know what some of your
current employees were saying?
</P>
<P>
   Same Old Bleeping Cardinals. And a few other things unfit to
print.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the qualified one _ player personnel boss Bob
Ferguson _ is stuck in an office watching film while your son is
crunching numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, aside from the quarterback, every recent negotiation
spearheaded by Bill Jr. has been a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   For a time on Tuesday, Brown, in fact, wasn't a Brown. Wasn't a
Cardinal, either. Somewhere off in Bidwillian limbo, wondering
whether to block for Jake or crouch for Couch. And leaving us to
wonder whether a third party had once again emerged, trying to
rescue Brown and cover Junior's behind.
</P>
<P>
   You can haggle over Brown's worth. Or how a team sinks $30
million into a quarterback, slaps the franchise tag on a wide
receiver, only to waffle with a man designated to watch the
quarterback's back.
</P>
<P>
   You can dream of Matt Joyce or Anthony Clement filling the void
at left tackle. But you can't debate how the Cardinals have once
again arrived at their favorite intersection _ Vision and
Indecision _ and took the wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
   This is bigger than Brown, more important than the momentum that
can be saved by signing Jamir Miller. This is, once again, about a
dysfunctional front office.
</P>
<P>
   And really, this is about you, Mr. Bidwill. About recognizing
the consequences. Remembering what nepotism smelled like under the
armpits of Buddy Ryan. Realizing how close you could be to the
trophy. And how far away you'll always be when blood runs thicker
than intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after Bill Jr. fumbled and couldn't close a deal with
Andre Wadsworth _ his popular brother had to swoop in and save the
day - conditions in Tempe worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bill Jr. wanted to prove himself. Maybe he chafed at the
bouquets constantly thrown at Ferguson. Whatever, he orchestrated
the Plummer deal all by himself. And, in some ways, he blew the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   That Ferguson was left out of the loop is an important note. The
Cardinals are $15 million under the cap and in a spot of trouble.
The rookie pool will eat up cap space. So will Moore and, perhaps,
Miller. Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Progressive organizations would seek out volunteers to
restructure their contracts, which requires signing bonuses. Except
the Cardinals are dry in that department, floating out $33.5
million of them over the last calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   Think. Was Plummer adamant over a $15 million bonus? Wouldn't
$12 million and a penny to punk Deion have done the trick? Of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Would Ferguson have envisioned this? The record speaks for
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how you felt standing on that field in Dallas, two wins
from the Super Bowl? Surely, you can't doubt his judgment. ``His''
vision.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ferguson might have done Jake last. After everyone
else. Like, on May 15, a few days before that referendum you've
waited on for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there is negative energy. It's your son who's
raising voices while Ferguson is keeping quiet, wondering more and
more how he wants to spend the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's personality has caught fire in this town. He is more
BOB than Bob, like the ballpark but friendlier. A man who can sell
used cars and new stadiums. If you let him.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Bill Jr. needs to leave the organization. After
all, in Chicago, Michael McCaskey will get paid to attend tea
parties. Your son can simply be re-assigned.
</P>
<P>
   One man in charge. One to inflate the footballs. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
