<HEADER>
A5472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     03-03 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Can we give Clyde Drexler extra power-rating
points for candor? Although his Cougars blew a ``million chances''
to obtain the fourth seed in the Conference USA tournament, he
admits they weren't exactly worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our record,'' Drexler said, ``it would have been a
disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we'd have taken it,'' he admitted. ``Yes, we would have.''
</P>
<P>
   So scrambled was the C-USA tournament picture that Houston
tumbled eight spots by losing a three-point game on the final
evening of the regular season. It's unlikely any team in any
conference ever suffered such theoretically grave consequences
because of a single misstep, the result of, among many gaffes, the
Cougars' bricking 17 of 29 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler must have had some painful flashbacks during the ugly
ordeal against Marquette on Saturday night. After all, in his final
game as a player for UH, he saw a seemingly sure-fire NCAA
championship slip from his grasp because he and his Phi Slama Jama
frat brothers found the charity line to be the most uncharitable
place on earth at exactly the wrong moment in history.
</P>
<P>
   That long-ago defeat at the hands of North Carolina State will
hurt forever. What happened against Marquette, however, had no real
bearing on how the world will judge Clyde's debut year as a coach.
These Cougars, minus the two best players off a team that went 9-20
a year ago, weren't supposed to go anywhere, and they won't. Bye or
no bye, they're destined for a quick bye-bye here in Birmingham,
Drexler's mild protestations to the contrary notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   While he senses the Cougars are demoralized by the unhappy way
their season ended, like any coach who ever lived, Clyde wants to
believe good things are still possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we start over,'' he said. ``Our core guys know what needs
to be done. It's a one-game elimination. It gives you a chance to
see what you're made of. We have a couple guys who should be
(angry) after what occurred in the last couple of games. Young
teams sometimes find ways to lose, and we have. But this is no time
to pontificate. It's time to step up and play.''
</P>
<P>
   And, OK, maybe they can play with North Carolina Charlotte. Why
not? Just last week, the Cougars had a chance to beat the 49ers in
the final seconds before Galen Young sank a beauty of a shot, then
blocked Kenny Younger's potential winning 3-point try. That victory
meant the Niners, with a highly respectable RPI of 24, appear
assured of a March Madness berth, although UH might still be able
to spoil the celebration for them.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Lutz, a first-year coach like Clyde, doesn't think the
afternoon should be a gotta-win deal for him, but he concedes his
lads, to a man, had better believe it is. RPI or no RPI, stumbling
to a 10-16 outfit such as the Cougars could spell R.I.P.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tad unfair, the situation Lutz finds himself in. Because
the C-USA decision-makers awarded byes to the top two teams in each
of the divisions, paying no heed to records, 10-6 Charlotte (as
well as 10-6 DePaul) is playing, while 6-10 Southern Mississippi is
resting, waiting for the Niners-Cougars winner on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's just a one-time deal,'' Lutz said, forcing a
diplomatic tone. ``But it's important we figure out what's the
fairest and the best (system) for our league as far as getting as
many teams as possible into the (NCAA) Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   C-USA, expected to be a nationally prominent basketball beast
when formed, hasn't won any awards for excellence of late, with
only No. 9 Cincinnati ranked in the Top 25. The 25-4 Bearcats,
coming off a fourth consecutive conference title, are the lone
absolute lock of the mostly so-so lot.
</P>
<P>
   And the 'Cats have had their lapses, too. A 12-4 record, made
respectable by a recent four-game winning streak, in such a tepid
C-USA race isn't worth roaring about. But they did beat Duke,
something nobody else has done.
</P>
<P>
   After Cincy? Lots of Fricks and Fracks. Five of the six teams in
the National (Disgrace) Division went 6-10 or 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it's gone,'' Lutz said, ``it doesn't really matter who
you play in the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   But playing in the first round is, by any measure, a burden. To
win the tournament, you have to win four days in a row. A demanding
task, that, although Marquette managed same a couple years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Golden Eagles head coach Mike Deane, also sitting ugly
in the C-USA throng at 6-10, his run of 20-victory seasons a faint
memory, might be fired. A rough business, his, as Drexler learns
daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been quite phenomenal,'' Drexler said of how his
inaugural C-USA season shook out. ``I guess it means there's a lot
of parity in our league.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a polite way to explain it. But it's typical Clyde.
Always trying to take the high road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
