<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN MIGHT RE-SIGN WITH CARDS AFTER ALL  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to the Waffle House, formerly known as the Valley of the
Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Following in the large footsteps of Suns/Nuggets/Suns/Nuggets
forward Antonio McDyess, who took indecisiveness to a new level,
Cardinals offensive tackle Lomas Brown has backed off his decision
to sign with the Cleveland Browns and could re-sign with the
Cardinals as soon as today.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's agent, Lamont Smith, negotiated with the Cardinals for
much of Tuesday, one day after Brown said he had agreed to a
three-year deal with Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the situation, however, said Tuesday it appears
more likely now that Brown, an unrestricted free agent, will
re-sign with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals apparently entered the picture Tuesday by
improving their offer to Brown, a 36-year-old left tackle
considered essential to the team's success next season.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Brown accepted Cleveland's contract offer worth $10.5
million over three years, including a $3 million signing bonus, and
was supposed to sign the deal as soon as Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were offering a two-year deal worth about $6
million, including a $2 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had declined to add a third year for Brown because
of his age, but they might have sweetened the two-year deal Tuesday
to equal the $6.4 million he would earn in the first two years with
the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   About $4 million of the Browns' three-year offer is in the final
year of the deal, making it money Brown might not earn. That salary
is not guaranteed, and Brown, who will be 39 then, could be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials and Smith, one of Brown's agent, did not
return phone calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland President Carmen Policy told a radio station Tuesday
that his club was still negotiating with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals did lose one player Tuesday, backup quarterback
Stoney Case, who signed a 2-year, $2 million deal with the
Indianapolis Colts that included a $500,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Case's departure leaves two quarterbacks on the Cardinals'
roster, Jake Plummer and Dave Brown. It's likely the Cardinals will
draft a quarterback in next month's draft, which is considered deep
in quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals chose Case in the third round of the 1995 draft,
but in four seasons he played in just four games, starting one. He
was the third-team quarterback in 1998 and did not take a snap
during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, he will back up Peyton Manning, said Case's
agent, Gary Wichard. ``It's an opportunity to be a snap away (from
playing) instead of two snaps away,'' Wichard said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cardinals continued Tuesday to negotiate with
Steve Baker, the agent for outside linebacker Jamir Miller. Like
Brown, Miller is an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bears are the only team Miller has visited since the
free-agency period opened last month, but they have yet to make him
an offer.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in Miller's decision, in addition to money, will be
how a team plans to use him. He wants to become a pass rusher,
Baker said, something he only occasionally has been asked to do in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's drastically hurt his value,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals were to lose Miller, they probably would have
to fill his spot through the draft or free agency. One veteran
linebacker available is Rob Frederickson, who has played for the
Raiders and Lions and lives in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves living here and would love to play football here the
rest of his career,'' said Frederickson's agent, Eric Metz of
Phoenix. ``Rob would be more than accommodating from a financial
standpoint in order to get here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
