<HEADER>
A5474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UH-DREXLER-HNS &LR;      03-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UH-DREXLER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Most places that he goes on the road, they
are there.
</P>
<P>
   They thrust pens and programs or pictures for Clyde Drexler to
sign, sometimes standing in the rain. At South Florida recently,
walking down the stands to the barrier just behind the bench, they
asked for a signature seconds before tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Cougars won their first Conference USA road game
earlier this season, Drexler exchanged quips during the game with
Memphis students who wanted to know if he coached Gee Gervin on his
floating moves to the basket. ``No, not me,'' Drexler assured them,
smiling. ``His dad (Hall of Famer George Gervin) taught him that.''
</P>
<P>
   More than just another celebrity, Drexler today will coach what
may be the final game of his first season as the University of
Houston coach. The Cougars play North Carolina Charlotte in the
opening round of the Conference USA tournament. The previous three
seasons, it has been one game and out in conference tournaments for
the Cougars, whose last conference-tournament win was against TCU
in 1995 in the first round of the Southwest Conference's tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-October, when he called his first team meeting for the
start of preseason practice, Drexler clearly has relished much of
this new career change. There are other nights, especially after a
one-sided loss like the one at Louisville, when he still can manage
an attempt at a joke. ``I can't lose any more hair,'' he said. ``So
this wasn't much fun, but there won't be any hair lost.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice or during most games, Drexler's familiar, calm
demeanor seldom changes. Not that it can't, because he doesn't long
tolerate what he considers a below-par performance by an official
or one of his players. He was ejected late in the game at North
Carolina State after two technical fouls, but even then he managed
to joke with Wolfpack fans who applied a few verbal needles during
his walk down the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, there were several dozen fans, standing in the rain,
asking for an autograph as he walked to the team's bus.
</P>
<P>
   During a home game against Saint Louis, Drexler kept raising his
voice before the official on the far side of the floor noticed his
obvious anger. A rare expletive helped get Drexler a technical.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's an official or a player, I feel like it's part of the
job to let them know what I expect,'' said Drexler. ``My goal is
the same as when I took the job, to bring the program back to where
it was when I played here. There's no promise of when that will be,
but I'm committed to doing that kind of job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars, as expected, clearly struggled to win 10 of their
26 regular-season games, highlighted by back-to-back conference
road wins at Memphis and South Florida. Gervin, their new point
guard, and juniors Kenny Younger and William Stringfellow are the
only players to start every game. Drexler used 13 starting lineups.
Five walk-ons _ Derrick Fernandez, Jake Ballis, Torrence Botts,
Willie Moore and Tega Moceanu _ combined for 27 starts and about 16
points and nine rebounds a game, more than 20 percent of the team
scoring/rebounding totals.
</P>
<P>
   Every little bit has counted, because, as Drexler has steadily
reminded, ``We have little margin for error.'' Seven of their 10
wins were decided by 17 total points. They lost their final two
regular-season games by five total points to Marquette (65-62) and
UNC Charlotte (68-66).
</P>
<P>
   Gervin and Younger noticed a different aspect of Drexler's
coaching style as the season evolved. ``We got more comfortable
with one another, and we tried to get set in our roles,'' said
Gervin. ``Clyde was usually real calm. He'd have that little smirk,
that little smile, a lot of the time. Then, later in the season, he
was more intense, picking at the little things that were costing
us, letting us know we had to pick things up, that he wasn't going
to tolerate it. It's like he smells blood now with the conference
tournament coming up.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone would prefer more wins, but athletic director Chet
Gladchuk isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly jump-started the program again,'' Gladchuk
said. ``A transition year is tough for any coach and the players
and his staff. We had some trials and tribulations, but clearly a
major step was taken. They rose to the occasion. You could see the
fire in the players' eyes, even in the close losses at the end of
the regular season. I'm extremely pleased with them on and off the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladchuk also has heard the innuendo _ that Drexler, stepping
out of the world of NBA superstardom, will tire of the huge task
before completing his five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it,'' Gladchuk said. ``Clyde is synonymous
with success at every stage of his career. I am convinced he is
dedicated totally to taking this program back to the national
stature it has had. There has never been the slightest indication
he is not focused on taking us to an NCAA championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The first steps back up the ladder have been taken. Stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
