<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLENSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON CLOUDS STADIUM ISSUE AT CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge President Blenda Wilson, who
announced her resignation Tuesday, could still make a decision on
the site of a new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   David Honda, the site-committee chair, said he will submit his
report recommending three options to Wilson within two weeks.
Wilson is expected to finish her term as president in late May or
early June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to affect our report,'' Honda said. ``It will
still be presented to Blenda in a couple of weeks. What she does
with it from there is up to her. I don't know if she'll make the
decision, but there's nothing that precludes her from doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not speak specifically on the football-stadium report
on Tuesday. Larry Cox, director of CSUN public relations, said
Wilson probably won't speculate in the next few days on how she
will treat the site-committee report simply because she hasn't seen
it yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what's in the report,'' Cox said. ``We'll see
what's in the report and go from that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Interim athletic director Sam Jankovich said he was surprised by
Wilson's resignation. He felt the drive to issue a recommendation
for the site of the stadium will not be derailed by her decision to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wilson) will have the responsibility to do what's right by
this program,'' Jankovich said. ``We're going to keep doing the
things we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the table are three proposed sites: an 8,000-seat on-campus
stadium that would be built 75 yards south of the existing North
Campus Stadium; a renovation of Pierce College as an off-campus
site; or a residents' recommendation, which would put a stadium
anywhere but on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovich, whose contract ends in late May, said he will not
stay longer because of the changeover in leadership. He wouldn't
comment on what input he will have in Wilson's decision on the new
stadium. Honda said he thinks Jankovich will have a major
influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume Sam will have a larger say in the decision,'' he
said. ``He's a ball-of-fire guy and he realizes that you have to
have a football stadium on campus to recruit.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-campus-stadium issue has put a strain on university
relations with the surrounding neighborhood. The Lindley West
Coalition vocally opposed an on-campus stadium during each of the
nine open meetings held by the site committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that a decision would be made by the new
president and new administration,'' Coalition president said Pat
LoPresti said. ``We would hope that the new administration would
have the OPPORTUNITY to make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said one of the goals in her final months as president is
to create a better dialogue between the university and the
outspoken homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I regretting that I won't see a football stadium being
built? The only things I regret are issues . . . (such as) the need
to have a better understanding between the university and neighbors
and about (how) the needs of both can be served,'' Wilson said.
``That's an issue I (hope) to get done (by the end of my term.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN head football coach Ron Ponciano, who was on the practice
field Tuesday afternoon when he heard about Wilson's resignation,
said he is concentrating solely on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can control is who I recruit, what we do with
(players) when they are here and when they get their degrees,''
Ponciano said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ponciano savors the opportunity to play on campus in a
superior facility to dilapidated North Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it be nice?'' he asked. ``Yeah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
