r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-REYN     03-03 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-REYNOSO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REYNOSO'S AIM TRUE  
 DIAMONDBACKS PLEASED WITH NEWCOMER'S START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Although Armando Reynoso's fastball has some
get-up-and-go, it is unlikely he will be issued a speeding ticket
like his new Diamondbacks teammate, Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It is Reynoso's consistent control that makes him effective and
is the reason Arizona signed the right-hander to a two-year
free-agent deal that will pay him $2.5 million in each of the next
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter and his staff got the first close look at
Reynoso in a game situation in Tuesday's intrasquad game.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso, 32, pitched two innings, giving up one run on one hit.
He also walked a batter and threw a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good start,'' pitching coach Mark Connor said. ``He
threw free and easy. He doesn't give in to the hitter and is always
around the plate, moving it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Reynoso: ``I'm not a power pitcher, so that's what I have
to do. I can use the fastball when I need to, but I rely more on my
location.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso is hoping the location of his new team will help him
become more relaxed than ever. He arrives from the New York Mets,
home to the deafening roar of jets taking off over Shea Stadium and
the concrete canyons of Manhattan. Now, he is a short trip away
from his home in San Luis Potosi, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of family and friends around here, yes, and
Tucson is familiar because I trained here for four years with the
Colorado Rockies (1993-96),'' Reynoso said.
</P>
<P>
   His happiness also is tied into his health. Though he posted a
combined 13-6 record in two seasons with the Mets, he struggled
because of a partially torn rotator cuff and labrum and bone chips
in his elbow, both requiring surgery in 1997. He spent the first
three months of the 1998 season on the disabled list, then went
7-3.
</P>
<P>
   One of those victories came on Aug. 15 over the Diamondbacks at
Bank One Ballpark. Arizona officials knew he would be a free agent
at the end of the season, and put him high on their list. But
before they would agree to sign him, they asked that their team
physicians be able to give Reynoso a thorough physical examination.
They gave their approval, and the deal was completed on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Reynoso's intrasquad outing was encouraging. The
club is walking a fine line, hoping to increase Reynoso's work load
as spring unfolds, but wanting to be cautious at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Home in Mexico, Reynoso began a moderate throwing program about
a month before reporting to camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' he said. ``This is probably the best I've felt
in the spring in a long time. It gives me encouragement. I just
want to stay healthy and help the team win. Each time I pitch, I
become more and more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller was on the receiving end of Reynoso's pitches on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell he's feeling more comfortable, getting more
confidence,'' Miller said. ``The important thing now for the
catchers is to get a feel for what he likes to throw in certain
situations, like if he gets behind in the count. That shouldn't
take long, though. He communicates pretty well out there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
