u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-BUCKS-NYT &LR;      03-03 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCKS DEFEAT NETS, 94-86 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Jayson Williams appears to be asking the
impossible. On Tuesday night, moments after he and the New Jersey
Nets lost for the seventh time in eight games, he spoke about the
need to ``have fun, play loose and let it fly.''
</P>
<P>
   But as long as the Nets continue to baffle and disappoint
themselves, their coach, their fans and the entire National
Basketball Association, enjoyment will be hard to come by, and the
only thing flying will be rumors of coaching and player personnel
changes.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic and accommodating Williams means well, but the
Nets' problems appear to be much deeper than their state of mind.
To watch them lose to the Milwaukee Bucks, 94-86, before a
Continental Arena crowd of 15,180 was not to watch them give up or
play tentatively.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets played hard. They hustled. They dived for loose balls.
They battled for rebounds and disrupted shots. And still, they were
beaten by a team that had lost four of its last five games,
including two to lowly Toronto and Denver, and was playing without
its injured point guard, Terrell Brandon, whom Bucks Coach George
Karl calls his best player.
</P>
<P>
   Nets Coach John Calipari tried to put a positive spin on the
defeat, saying: ``We had more hustle plays in the second half than
we've ever had here. To say we didn't play hard is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets' rally from a 19-point second-quarter deficit to
take the lead with three minutes remaining means nothing. When you
are as talented as New Jersey but reeling with a 3-11 record, moral
victories are irrelevant and Monday's euphoric
losing-streak-busting victory over Boston seems to be as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This basically negates that win,'' said Kendall Gill, who
endured another poor night, shooting 3 for 14 in scoring 7 points.
``They didn't have Brandon, so I thought we could win this game
going away. But the way we started, we killed ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   With Brandon, who was offered to the Nets this week in a trade
involving Sam Cassell, sitting on the sideline with bruises on his
ribs and left thigh, the Bucks started the slow-footed shooting
guard Vinny Del Negro at the point.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Milwaukee (7-5) was able to break away from the Nets in
the second quarter and hold them off in the end. New Jersey missed
a golden opportunity to get back into the playoff picture because
struggling Charlotte (3-9) visits on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling, man, struggling,'' said Williams, who
grabbed a game-high 11 rebounds but scored just 5 points. ``We've
got to play with more energy. I think we're pressing ourselves too
much. We've go to start having fun, giving high-fives and
chest-bumping. That's when we play our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Allen paced the Bucks with 19 points, and Glenn Robinson had
18. Keith Van Horn led the Nets with 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing for all but the first four minutes of the game,
the Nets mounted a devastating charge over the third and fourth
quarters, turning the double-digit deficit into an 84-83 lead on an
Eric Murdock 3-pointer with 3 minutes 2 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   But the fervent rally might have sapped the Nets' energy,
because Milwaukee ran off 7 straight points to regain control. The
Nets had their chances, but their execution and shooting failed
them. After baskets by Robinson and Del Negro put the Bucks up by
87-84, Kerry Kittles was caught in a sea of defenders, which led to
a shot-clock violation on the Nets. Then, after holding Milwaukee,
Van Horn had a nine-foot bank shot bounce in and out.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson then made two foul shots, and Ervin Johnson one to put
the Bucks ahead by 90-84 with 41 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 14 points at halftime, the Nets showed heart in the
third quarter. Desperately needing to get back in the game after
being booed by the home crowd in the second, New Jersey used a
trapping, three-quarter-court defense for the first time this
season. The unorthodox move by Calipari rattled the Bucks, forcing
them into six turnovers and enabling the Nets to close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure defense made the game hectic and led to numerous
dunks and layups for the Nets. So after shooting a frightening 25
percent in the first half, New Jersey made 11 of 19 field goals in
the third for 58 percent. With Milwaukee buckling under the heat,
the Nets moved within 7 points on a 3-point play by the reserve
center Jim McIlvaine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
