</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-STUDENTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING CHINESE STUDENTS FOUND IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: The Redlands (Calif.) Daily Facts contributed to this
story.) 
BY DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The sudden disappearance of 32 Chinese students
from Los Angeles International Airport Monday turned out to be a
bizarre misunderstanding between two tour companies coordinating
their trip, police said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While authorities investigated the incident as a kidnapping or
mass defection, the mystery was cleared when several of the
students were located and interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The official explanation: The students were no sooner dropped
off at Los Angeles International for the return flight to Shanghai
than they were picked up by drivers for a second tour company to
continue their U.S. visit after completing a four-week English
language course.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the students were safely settled with new host
families, and well within the time limits of their student visas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has truly been a bizarre incident,'' said Los Angeles
Police Department Cmdr. Dave Kalish. ``But it appears it will have
a happy ending.''
</P>
<P>
   The students had completed a one-month English language course
with ELS Learning Centers at the University of Redlands and were
scheduled to return to China on a 1 p.m. flight Monday from LAX,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ELS officials did not know, however, that the students and their
parents had decided to extend their stay with another company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students were taken to the airport, they had their
passports and their airline tickets, they had their luggage
packed,'' said Ray Trantham, director of admissions and student
services for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we were never made aware that they were in any other
program other than our program.''
</P>
<P>
   When the chartered bus arrived at LAX about 10:30 a.m., the
students were met by several men who took the students' passports,
loaded their luggage and drove them away in a caravan of four or
five minivans and sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, immediately investigated as a possible crime,
turned out to be a strange miscommunication, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some obligations by the original tour company and
subsequently another tour company was introduced into the situation
by what we believe were the parents, working through some
intermediaries, that was not known to the original tour company,''
said LAPD West Bureau Deputy Chief Rick Dinse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why it occurred in the way it did is still not clear yet.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also unclear how they arranged the transfer to the second
company.
</P>
<P>
   Trantham said the ELS Learning Center prohibited the students
from contacting people outside the program during their stay to
prevent any attempts at illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese students in particular are at high risk for
defection,'' he said. ``So we maintained strict rules as far as
their being contacted by any friends or relatives who are in the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   People who knew the students in the Redlands area in San
Bernardino County said they saw no evidence of any defection plans.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Schlanser, the ESL program's local international student
adviser, said most of the students made it clear that they were
anxious to return to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these children have been very vocal about their intent
to go home,'' Schlanser said.
</P>
<P>
   Mentone resident Sue Bailey, who hosted one girl, said the guest
never intimated any plans to remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't say anything about not going home,'' said Bailey,
who declined to give the girl's name or age. ``She talked about
being excited to see her mom again.''
</P>
<P>
   Marina Tse, chairwoman of the Chinese American Education
Association and a former State Board of Education member, said the
situation is reminiscent of ``parachute kids'' from Taiwan and Hong
Kong, who are sent alone by parents to study in the United States
-- frequently in Asian-American communities of the San Gabriel
Valley east of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of parents in China or the Orient, they really think
their kids will get a better education in the United States,'' Tse
said. ``So they find any way to get their kids to study here.''
</P>
<P>
   Police located two of the students in suburban Covina early
Tuesday morning and contacted their parents, who said they
authorized the extension of their stay, Kalish said. Seventeen
other students were contacted later.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it was dramatic, it was nothing apparently illegal from
what we can determine,'' Dinse said. ``There is no indication that
any of these kids or their families are trying to have them defect
to the U.S. There has been no request for asylum. They are merely
here on their student visas to attend school. Once they have done
that they fully intend to return to China.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service spokesman Bill
Strassberger said the students apparently had the financial means
to study for an extended period in the United States. Whether that
was their original intention is unclear, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible they wanted to stay longer and they saw this as
a way to do this,'' Strassberger said. ``On the other hand maybe
they came here for a short course with the intention of going back,
and the idea of staying longer was presented to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that regardless of the students' intentions, their
student visas are still valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bizarre situation, but there aren't any immigration
violations in the situation up until now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
