r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-BYU-TEX     03-03 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-BYU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU MAKES QUICK EXIT AT TOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Forget for a second, Marquise Gainous' decision to
bench himself, referees' calls and BYU's once-in-a-lifetime display
of long-distance marksmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Billy Tubbs said TCU's game against Brigham Young had been
decided six weeks ago anyway.
</P>
<P>
   From Tubbs' perspective, TCU's 90-74 loss to BYU in the first
round of the Western Athletic Conference tournament yesterday began
when officials ejected Lee Nailon for fighting against Nevada-Las
Vegas on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a call that maybe cost me a game,'' Tubbs said.
``I've never had a call like the call in the Vegas game that cost
me a season. Because that's virtually what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been the same basketball team since. ... That was a
critical call that I said at the time cost us a chance at the NCAA
playoffs, and I truly believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU has gone 4-6 since and probably has no chance of landing an
at-large NCAA bid.
</P>
<P>
   In losing to BYU, Tubbs and his Horned Frogs (19-10) definitely
looked like a fragment of a team that began this season ranked 24th
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   BYU (12-15) had a losing mark coming in, yet played with a
swagger that used to define TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost that swagger awhile ago,'' Nailon admitted, his
game-high 33 points and 16 rebounds unable to save TCU.
</P>
<P>
   He simply shrugged his shoulders when trying to explain why. He
blamed that Vegas game, although, Gainous' decision, referees'
calls and BYU's shooting display played roles, too.
</P>
<P>
   BYU jumped on TCU, stayed on TCU then easily finished TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Problems began for Tubbs and his Frogs before a single second
had expired. Gainous told Tubbs that he'd be unable to go against
BYU despite being cleared to play by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous, TCU's second-leading scorer and second-leading
rebounder, bruised his left palm almost 10 days ago. He landed
awkwardly in practice on Monday, but X-rays were negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in Marquise's shoes,'' Tubbs said. ``He was really in
a lot of pain, and he felt like he couldn't play. ... Of course, he
wouldn't have stopped them from making those 3s early in the game
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   BYU began by burying seven of eight 3-point attempts, had 10 by
halftime and finished with 13, enough to get a line in TCU's record
book as the most by an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Vranes led BYU's long-distance attack, burying five of seven and
finishing with 19 points, and got help from Mark Bigelow (4-of-7,
20 points) and Nathan Cooper (3-of-6, 24 points).
</P>
<P>
   TCU trailed all game, including double-digit deficits that
lasted for long stretches. Yet, TCU had trimmed BYU's lead to a
pliable 60-57 with slightly less than 14 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then began a symphony of whistles that lasted for almost two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When finished, two technicals had been called (on Tubbs and
Nailon), 10 free throws had been attempted (by BYU) and a 12-point
lead had been secured (by BYU).
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to consider that the turning point of the game,''
Cooper said. ``You could tell it took some of the air out of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU looked to be beaten from then on.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon said he had simply been talking to Ryan Carroll when
referees whistled him for a technical with 12:54 remaining. Tubbs
had been whistled for a technical 22 seconds earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He said he said two words, ``Hey, Mike,'' to Mike Saia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as far as I got,'' Tubbs said later. ``I think they had
a nervy attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU's rally basically ended then, and the final 12:32 became a
countdown to BYU's biggest upset this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we could outshoot TCU and beat them at their
own game,'' Cougars coach Steve Cleveland said.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been TCU's game since the Vegas loss on Jan. 24,
the confidence, the swagger long gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence is the whole game,'' Tubbs said. ``When you lose
that edge everything goes with it. You're not as quick. You don't
jump as high. You're not as excited to play, and then the other
team has an idea that they're going to be able to beat you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
