<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-ARIZSTATE-MOM-AZR     03-03 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOTHER'S LOAD  
 ASU COACH FINDING BALANCE BETWEEN JOB, BABY 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-MOM-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The older children need attention, too.
</P>
<P>
   In simplest of terms, that's the answer to the question that
people are asking everywhere except to Arizona State women's
basketball Coach Charli Turner Thorne's face: Is this woman crazy?
</P>
<P>
   How else does one explain:
</P>
<P>
   Reporting to practice two days after giving birth and just 1{
hours after being released from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Making a recruiting appearance the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Working an overtime game against Arizona another day later.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a 9-day-old on a flight through San Francisco to Eugene,
Ore., for a four-day trip, and a now 3-week-old on a trip to Los
Angeles this weekend. Not to mention the passport that will be
needed for a 15-hour team journey to Australia in late May.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't come up to me and say anything,'' said the
32-year-old Turner Thorne, who gave birth to Conor Troy Thorne on
Feb. 9. But neither did anyone except her mother say anything about
her determination to accompany her team to the Bay area little more
than a week before her Feb. 6 due date. Only when university
lawyers and her conscience prevailed did others admit their relief
that Turner Thorne did not make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly out of politeness, Turner Thorne doesn't hear the
water-cooler critiques of arguably the most publicized collegiate
delivery since Tennessee's Pat Summitt went into labor at a
recruit's home in Pennsylvania in 1990 and demanded that she be
flown home immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell those pilots that if they land this plane any place but
Tennessee, they're going to have a madwoman on their hands,'' the
six-time NCAA champion coach related in her book, ``Reach for the
Summit.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne has never been that over the top _ ``I'm not going
to be the CNN Play of the Day,'' she promised at Pac-10 media day
in November _ but is close enough to make others squirm in an era
when the stay-at-home parent is highly prized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I'm interacting with are the other coaches and
people on the job, and their response has kind of been disbelief,''
said Turner Thorne. ``To me, it's not like I have a choice. It's a
discipline thing and a commitment thing, and that's the way I look
at it. That's the way I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I like to be at home taking a break? Yeah. Am I
thoroughly exhausted? Yeah. But I don't really have an option.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because she has 15 women in her still-emerging third-year
program who were family before Conor was born and have their own
surrogate-parenting needs. And other than the Stanford trip and the
two days after giving birth, Turner Thorne has been there for them
_ all the while dealing with the latter stages of pregnancy and the
early stages of motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not only a coach, but a parent and a counselor helping
18- to 21-year-olds get through that portion of life,'' said her
husband, Will Thorne. ``Parenting is not really new to Charli. It's
just that her other kids can communicate their problems a little
more succinctly than Conor right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorne admits to being ``sheepishly embarrassed'' by the
publicity accorded the in-season pregnancy. Not only in the Phoenix
area but nationally in newspapers from Cleveland to St. Louis to
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard someone say in joking, `Geez, you'd think a working
woman never had a baby before,' '' Thorne said. ``That's just
someone not knowing anything about Charli's situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation that includes grueling hours, constant travel,
pressure to turn around a program that hasn't won since 1992-93,
and the desire to validate Athletic Director Kevin White's faith in
negotiating a new five-year contract that runs through 2004 when
she has yet to achieve a .500 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people can relate to what I've been going through with
this (pregnancy),'' Turner Thorne said. ``Nobody understands my
job. They don't know what I do or what I go through. Anybody who
calls me a typical working mother, that shows a lack of
understanding of my profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Hatfield Clubb couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   She is the Arizona State associate athletic director who
convinced Turner Thorne to tackle the ASU job when there was more
talent in her former program at Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   They discovered within a day of each other that they were
pregnant, and the same doctor ultimately delivered their sons at
the same hospital within three hours of each other.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the road diverges. Hatfield Clubb is on an
eight-week leave of absence, interrupted only by a weekly trip to
the office to ``pass the baby around'' and some telecommuting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honest to goodness don't know how she (Turner Thorne) does
it,'' Hatfield Clubb said. ``But I know her so well and her job so
well, she wouldn't do it any other way. She'd do it the way she is
no matter what anybody thought about it, and she's not being pushed
by Kevin. But selfishly as an administrator, that's why we hired
her because she's got that attitude and never says quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, I hurt for her because she is burning the
candle at both ends. I know it's got to be emotionally hard on her
not to have time to get to know her son.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach's plate is full, but help from family has relieved
some of the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we could do it without back-to-back
grandmas,'' said Thorne, who is in the busy season of his job with
Swank Audio Visuals. ``It would have been overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne's mother arrived first, caring for Conor in the
locker room during some practices at Wells Fargo Arena and making
the Oregon trip.
</P>
<P>
   Now Thorne's mother is here.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne wonders about the serenity of maternity leave, but
not at the expense of a team that despite last week's losses to
Stanford and California is beginning to show her character: focus,
resiliency, competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a different job, I think I might be jealous (of
Hatfield Clubb),'' she said. ``I think if we were struggling and
still had injuries, if things were a little bit disappointing or
frustrating, it would be a lot harder. But we're improving and
continuing to get better. It's really a fun time, and I'm enjoying
the growth we've made over these past three-four weeks. Between the
team and Conor, there's a lot of growth going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Conor's weigh-in of 8 pounds, 3 ounces was the most shocking
part of the entire process for the 120-pound Turner Thorne, who
added 21 pounds during her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sure there was no way I was going to have a baby over 7
and change,'' she said. ``I thought, `I've got to get him up to 7
so he's not this fragile thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've found myself thinking babies are not quite as delicate as
you imagine,'' said Thorne, who is traveling with the team this
weekend. ``Once we take the necessary precautions and cover all the
things we're going to need, I don't expect too much of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's strong as an ox for a newborn. He's awake and alert and
wants to be in the room with other people. He has the intense
stare-through-the-back-of-the-head glare like his mommy when Pac-10
officials interpret a situation differently than she would have
hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne was fretful about traveling to Oregon with even
the strongest of infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just was praying he didn't get sick,'' she said. ``On the
flight back, there was a cougher right in front of us. He slept on
the plane except at the end of the flight from Phoenix to San
Francisco when he was getting hungry, and through the entire
(Oregon State) game despite the band. I was so relieved at the end
of that trip.''
</P>
<P>
   When this second trip is complete and the uniforms put away for
the year, Mary Hauser, a friend, believes the magnitude of what
Turner Thorne has taken on this season will hit.
</P>
<P>
   Hauser, who now coaches the Arizona Elite AAU team, was pregnant
with all three of her sons while coaching at Mater Dei High School
in Santa Ana, Calif. She was close to delivery with her middle
child while coaching in the 1996 state championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many uncertainties you go through, especially at
the beginning,'' Hauser said. ``Why do I feel this way? Should I
feel like this? Is this OK? It's good to have somebody to bounce
things off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauser has been checking for signs of postpartum depression,
which Turner Thorne isn't experiencing, and suspects a letdown is
around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be interesting when she finally has some down time to
realize how she did it all,'' Hauser said. ``With mine, it wasn't
until maybe four weeks after the baby, when the season was over,
that I really felt the most tired. That's the nice part of
athletics, there is a lot of excitement involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauser was amazed to see Turner Thorne at Chandler High School
on Feb. 12, three days after the birth, to scout the Mountain
Pointe-Chandler region championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne felt her appearance was critical because ASU had a
game that prevented she and her staff from attending the 5A state
championship rematch between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell she was pretty uncomfortable,'' Hauser said,
``but if I was a high school player, that would show me how much
she cares.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Sun Devils know as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the same Charli that recruited me last year,'' freshman
forward Theresa Jantzen said in January, when her coach was eight
months pregnant. ``She's still real focused. It's like a
non-factor. I don't even look at her as being pregnant. She is so
strong. I really admire her. I was talking to my mom on the phone
and she said, `I don't know how Charli does it.' I do really admire
her for how strong she is and not letting it become a factor with
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Natalie Tucker is observing a baby up close for the
first time. ``I think he's a little miracle. He's the cutest little
thing. I'm in awe of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was not surprised when Turner Thorne showed up for
practice less than 60 hours after her 3:55 a.m. delivery. ``I
personally knew she was going to do that, that's the kind of person
Charli is. I would have been surprised if she wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Thorne, high school valedictorian and Stanford graduate
who studied at Oxford University for a semester, is no dummy. She
has closely monitored Conor's pre- and post-delivery impact on her
players, intent on it not detracting from their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them have been wonderful,'' she said. ``Some of them
are more comfortable around him, and some of them are more
hesitant. I think it's been kind of a fun distraction for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even beyond the team, the thing I've realized because maybe
I've never taken the time is how much people love babies. I've
never been one of those ooh-ah baby types, but tons of people come
up and just want to see the baby. I've honestly been completely
overwhelmed with how wonderful and supportive everybody has been,
from fans to friends to boosters to other coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Turner Thorne is hoping for a sequel, but determined to do
her part for baby No. 2 to be an out-of-season release.
</P>
<P>
   To preserve a coach's sanity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
