</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_BRUINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SEARCH FOR POSITIVES AS LOSS ENDS MISERABLE TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's finally over.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the Coyotes' losing ways. That continued Tuesday night
at the FleetCenter with a 3-2 loss to the Boston Bruins in a game
in which Phoenix actually played well enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   What's over is their exhausting two-week, seven-game trip, the
Coyotes' longest of the season in more ways than one. They limped
home having lost six, including three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But in losing this time, the Coyotes (30-21-10) provided more
than just a glimpse that better times might lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing yet again without injured forwards Greg Adams,
Juha Ylonen, Mike Stapleton and Brad Isbister, and starting rookie
goalie Robert Esche to give Nikolai Khabibulin a much-needed rest,
the team made major strides against the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   They unleashed 51 hits, including 10 by center Bob Corkum. They
officially were credited with allowing only one giveaway. They got
back to playing as they did early in the season _ and it almost
paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to keep swinging,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld said.
``I know the players are trying to gut it out and I know they're
going to turn it around, but while you're mired in it, it hurts
like hell. The most important thing is that they stay the course
because if we don't stay tenacious and committed, we won't get out
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed a lot of evidence tonight that we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it show on the scoreboard, though, their next time out,
which comes Friday at home against two-time defending Stanley Cup
champion Detroit?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep working like that, we'll come out on the right end
most of the time,'' forward Mike Stapleton said. ``We just didn't
get that final punch that we needed to overcome the hump in this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been a difficult hurdle all season. The Coyotes' record
in games in which they trail by at least two goals, as was the case
Tuesday, isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it?'' Stapleton asked.
</P>
<P>
   It's 0-17-0.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to ask a team to rally from a 3-1 deficit when
that team has managed only 11 goals in its past nine games. As a
result, the Coyotes have lost eight of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked hard and we had a couple chances in the third, but
we just couldn't put them away,'' center Jeremy Roenick said.
</P>
<P>
   Esche was rudely welcomed in his first NHL start by an all-out
attack on the Bruins' second shift of the game. One rush resulted
in three straight shots. Esche stopped the first two, but Cameron
Mann buried the third one for a 1-0 lead only 53 seconds into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes could have thrown in the towel right away and nobody
probably would have blamed them. Not after what they've been
through lately.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they did the complete opposite. They started playing as
they did in October and November. They kept the puck in Boston's
end of the rink. They forced the Bruins into seven bad turnovers.
They won every one-on-one battle.
</P>
<P>
   Their hard work was rewarded when Roenick knocked in a rebound
from a missed shot by Rick Tocchet, who would add another assist on
Phoenix's second goal. Roenick, who had tallied only three goals in
his previous 22 games and none in his past eight, paused
momentarily before a fist-pumping celebration, almost as if he
couldn't believe he actually scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``After eight games, damn right,'' Roenick said of his 20th goal
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum hit a speed bump when Jim Cummins got whistled for
interference, but the Coyotes got it back as soon as they killed
the penalty and Cummins nearly scored on a rush right out of the
box.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, though, the momentum took a turn for the worse. Only
1:45 into the second period, wing Rob DiMaio took a feed in his own
zone from P.J. Axelsson and streaked in to score on Esche for a 2-1
Boston lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Keith Tkachuk in the penalty box after a fight with Jason
Allison, Axelsson made the score 3-1 midway through the second. The
Coyotes cut the lead to 3-2 on Deron Quint's third goal of the
season at the 5:21 mark of the third, his first since being moved
to left wing from defense. But it wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to score, but a win would have been nicer,'' Quint
said. ``Personal stuff is great, but when the team's not
successful, it hurts a little bit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
