<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAINOUS' CHOICE INDICATIVE OF TCU'S SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ On a day when his team most needed him to answer the
roll call, TCU's Marquise Gainous didn't want to talk.
</P>
<P>
   He preferred to sit.
</P>
<P>
   The junior forward and second-leading scorer on the team had a
bruised hand. A wrist sprain. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors cleared him to play in yesterday's Western Athletic
Conference tournament opener. But according to team
representatives, Gainous chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   Marquise Gainous is 22 years old. So let's not mince words here.
</P>
<P>
   How does a kid _ excuse me, an adult _ not play when his team
knows that it needs at least one, and probably two, respectable
showings at the conference tournament in order to gain an NCAA
Tournament invitation?
</P>
<P>
   Gainous didn't answer. But so it's been for TCU in this most
disappointing of basketball seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs couldn't answer the bell against a hot-shooting
Brigham Young team yesterday, losing 90-74. The Frogs haven't
answered much of anything for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not talking,'' a sullen Prince Fowler said, as the Frogs
strode silently to their postgame bus.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs had no answer for a fair-haired BYU team that made 10
of 17 3-point attempts in the first half. The Frogs had no answer _
again _ for a team that double-teamed, body-checked and tugged at
Lee Nailon.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs, coach Billy Tubbs admitted frankly, haven't answered
the challenge since the night of Jan. 23. The game where Nailon was
ejected _ and eventually suspended _ for slapping Nevada-Las Vegas'
Mark Dickel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been the same team,'' Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   TCU was 15-3 going into that home game against UNLV. Without
Nailon, it lost in overtime, lost two nights later at Tulsa and
dropped two more conference games before it could halt the slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into that UNLV game thinking we could beat any team in
America,'' Tubbs said. ``By the time we got back home to play a
game, we were not the same basketball team. We'd had a tremendous
loss of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as costly, Tubbs theorized, was that the Frogs' veneer of
superiority had come crashing down. TCU, remember, was undefeated
in conference play in 1997-98. The Frogs had become regular
vote-getters in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden,'' Tubbs said, ``the other team has the idea
that it might be able to beat you. We lost that edge. And we never
seemed to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   When you have a Mike Jones or a Malcolm Johnson, you work
through those kinds of setbacks. You bear down. You toil a little
harder.
</P>
<P>
   But without Jones and Johnson this season, the Frogs never did
embrace the work ethic that last season's division champs showed.
Tough times seemed to bother this TCU team, not energize it.
Instead of rallying around its tag of being a victim, it hid behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs will get some blame for that, but he was voicing private
concerns about this team's competitive fires as far back as
December. Victim is a role that Billy plays well _ and he played it
to the max here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But Tubbs never got the desired response from his Horned Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   Especially not yesterday against BYU. With Nailon playing hard,
but laboring with foul trouble and wearing BYU defenders on both
flanks, no one stepped up to shoulder the load. Without Gainous,
Nailon was the whole TCU scoring and rebounding show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought \RGainous\S was the critical thing to the game,''
Tubbs admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous, a junior-college transfer from Jacksonville, Fla., had
been bothered by his left hand for about two weeks. He felt it was
hurting his shooting touch. In practice Monday, Gainous slipped and
used the hand to break his fall, further increasing the pain, Tubbs
said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors X-rayed the hand, however, and found no evidence of a
fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in Marquise's shoes,'' Tubbs said. ``I think he was
really in a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But the doctors, the coach added, cleared Gainous to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was his choice,'' Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a choice that young Gainous will have to live with. He
didn't even dress out for the game. Instead, dressed in a purple
warmup suit, he sat on a chair behind the TCU bench, not even
joining in the team huddles.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, there had to be something that an 18.4-point scorer and
8.8 per-game rebounder could do. Play at least some token defense?
Use his five personal fouls?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Marquise Gainous became the symbol of the Frogs' crater
of a season yesterday. Given the choice, they took the quiet and
easy way out. They said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA surely will do likewise.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
