<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAMB-FRAUD-AZR &LR;      03-03 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMB-FRAUD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS OUTLINE INSURANCE FRAUD CASE AGAINST JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The checks had travelled thousands of miles before they reached
the window of J. Brian Lamb's pickup truck, parked just behind the
office where the Chandler justice of the peace held court.
</P>
<P>
   The checks came to Lamb at the end of a marathon
trans-Caribbean, trans-continental journey. They had been written
by truckers for what federal investigators say were bogus insurance
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb and three others allegedly got more than $1.5 million from
the scam. Last week they were slapped with a 37-count fraud
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Newly released court documents gave the best picture to date of
the federal case while Lamb on Tuesday fiercely denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an innocent man, and I'm going to fight this to the bitter
end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not hiding from anything. I'm fighting this head-on.''
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old father of three said his life ``is in a spin
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Postal inspectors laid out part of their money travelogue in
the indictment, which climaxed a four-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money story can be put together from affidavits
that lead U.S. postal inspector James Tendick prepared to support
search warrants on Lamb's truck and home and on the home of alleged
co-conspirator Laura Palacios.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators used wiretaps and surveillance of the
suspects, and they subpoenaed telephone, bank and mail records.
They also drew on investigative files from state insurance agencies
in Arizona and four other states and even an insurance policy they
purchased themselves.
</P>
<P>
   According to inspectors and Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles
Steele, Lamb and his alleged accomplices attracted customers by
mailing fliers that offered cut-rate insurance and by ``falsely
claiming that they worked for and represented certain insurance
agencies'' and brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The scam's first victims, according to Florida state insurance
fraud investigator Seleina Porter, were the truckers who bought the
useless insurance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Porter said the ultimate victims were drivers and passengers
injured in accidents caused by the misinsured drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Porter documented dozens of them. One man was paralyzed, she
said, another was severely burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they were out of luck,'' said Porter.
</P>
<P>
   According to the postal inspectors, by the time the truckers'
insurance premium checks reached Lamb's truck outside the Chandler
Justice Court, they had traveled from across the United States to
Miami, on to the Caribbean island of Antigua and back to a
commercial mailbox in Chandler rented by Lamb employee Palacios.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the tortuous route was intended to confuse
anyone who tried to trace it. They suspect the Antigua connection
may have been used to claim that the operation was not subject to
U.S. taxes or regulations. To complete the money trail, the
inspectors relied on surveillance and wiretaps of telephone
conversations between Lamb and Palacios.
</P>
<P>
   One Tendick affidavit filed in U.S. District Court in Phoenix
said that in a pair of conversations last October and November,
``Palacios told Lamb she had client premium checks and she agreed
to transfer them into Lamb's vehicle at the Chandler Justice
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Tendick's affidavit, Lamb on several occasions took
two final steps on the money trail, both of which kept his name
away from paper records.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavits said Lamb cashed the checks at a south Phoenix
market and then deposited the money in checking accounts of his
alleged co-conspirator, Darin Tarwater.
</P>
<P>
   Tarwater, one of the defendants in the case, is scheduled to
make his initial court appearance Wednesday in U.S. District Court
in Phoenix. Palacios pleaded innocent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth person charged in he case, Nelly Herrera, lives in
Canada and has not been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Tendick gave this step-by-step account of the surveillance of
Palacios and Lamb last May 21:
</P>
<P>
   Palacios went to the Chandler mailbox shortly before &UR; noon and
picked up a Federal Express package from Antigua. The package was
addressed to Transportation Management, one of the allegedly bogus
companies through which Lamb sold insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Palacios drove to the rear alley of the Chandler Justice Court,
parked near Lamb's pickup truck and ``was observed sliding what
appeared to be a large envelope into Lamb's vehicle through the
driver's side window.'' The window was ``cracked open about one
inch.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb took the envelope to Mary Lou's Market on West Mohave
Street in south Phoenix, emerging about 12 minutes later ``carrying
what appeared to be a priority mail envelope and paper bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Tendick's account of the transaction cited subpoenaed Bank of
America records that show that $32,037 was posted to the Mary Lou's
Market checking account the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector closed the Lamb-Tarwater loop on other
check-cashing transactions between Lamb and the market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last Nov. 5, shortly after leaving the market, Lamb
allegedly deposited $2,000 in cash into Darin Tarwater's checking
account at Wells Fargo Bank in Chandler. That transaction is
recorded on deposit records and tape from a bank surveillance
camera, Tendick said in the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, between July 1997 and November of
last year, the market cashed checks totalling $197,000 for the
alleged conspirators. A call to the market was referred to a woman
named Annette, who refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said some of the truckers' checks were cashed in
Panama, the home of Lamb's uncle David Lamb, who left the United
States nearly a decade ago after federal investigators probed
allegations that he ran a similar insurance scam.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in the case of Brian Lamb say they identified a
scam within the scam. They say Palacios carried out this interior
scam with Herrera, who sold insurance for Lamb from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   and Herrera skimmed thousands of dollars in checks for
themselves, Tendick said, and had recently been setting up their
own bogus insurance business. Tendick said wiretaps showed the two
women planned to draw off Lamb's customers by directing sales calls
to their own toll-free number. &QL; 
Jerry Kammer can be reached at 444-8185 or by e-mail at
jerry.kammer(at)pni.com. Republic writer Jim Walsh contributed to
this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
