r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-RAMBIS-AZR     03-03 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-RAMBIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS IS GOOD LISTENER  
 PLAYERS ENJOY HAVING INPUT  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt Rambis wore a black suit and wire-rim glasses. To his left
was Dennis Rodman, with hair that resembled a Brillo pad in the
early stages of rust.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of meeting that can happen only in comic books
and the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But there they were, Clark Kent and The Joker, standing near the
press table as center Shaquille O'Neal stood at the free throw line
Monday night in the second half of the Los Angles Lakers' 97-91
victory over the Suns at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say their exchange didn't include grooming tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was betting Shaq would hit those free throws,'' Rambis said.
``Dennis was betting he wouldn't. When Shaq drained the first one,
I kind of jostled Dennis and said, `Hey, that's my man.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, a decided underdog a week ago, already is ahead in what
some believe is a losing proposition. With Rodman, O'Neal, young
Kobe Bryant and the Lakers' Showtime reputation, Hollywood's
favorite team has all the elements of a ``Titanic'' sequel. Rambis
figures to be the next man overboard. About that, he harbors no
illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cotton Fitzsimmons told me a long time ago, coaches are hired
to be fired,'' Rambis said as he prepared to take his Lakers home
for tonight's game with the Suns at the Great Western Forum. ``So
I'm the next Lakers coach to get fired.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, only one plank is evident in a new Lakers regime.
And nobody is going to walk it. Instead, it is part of a reinforced
platform that has renewed the team's confidence in the week since
Rambis succeeded Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Within a week, the Lakers have gone from a team on a three-game
skid to one on a four-win run. It's not enough to declare a
turnaround. In the NBA, a single week is a little like one slam
dunk. Who remembers?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Lakers themselves are talking as if they
finally found a coach who understands them and their talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what to do now,'' Bryant said. ``Rambis is very big on
roles. Everybody has particular roles that were unclear before.
From top to bottom, I think everybody is a little more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a comfort level achieved through communication. In his
first few days on the job, Rambis has sought advice from everybody,
Rodman included. After Monday night's victory, he ducked behind a
door to the America West Arena practice court for a meeting with
Fitzsimmons, who coached him throughout his three seasons (1989-92)
in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   During the game, he took advice from Derek Harper. With 1:08
remaining, Harper hit a three-point shot that put the Lakers ahead
for good, 87-85. It was Harper's call. Initially, Rambis asked
Harper to drive the lane. But Harper said he had been open
repeatedly for a three-point attempt because Jason Kidd was
dropping off to double-team O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to him, and he kind of waved me off,'' Harper said.
``It was like he was saying, `You take care of it.' As a player,
that really gives you a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis is not far removed from his days as a player. Then, as
now, he was always seeking advice. His survival in the league
depended on his ability to learn and adjust. He played in Greece
before he landed with the Lakers. He was never as talented as most
of the players around him. Yet he was an important piece to the
title teams of Magic Johnson, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and James Worthy.
</P>
<P>
   A key then, he said, was to listen carefully and apply
diligently. Other than the wardrobe, not much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Rodman suggested defensive alignments. Rambis
listened. Once, Rodman walked over to the scorer's table to check
on the foul situation. He passed on the information. Rambis
listened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to love that stuff as a coach,'' said Rambis, who
also called Magic Johnson in Hawaii last week for tips on how to
handle everything from personalities to pressure defense. ``You
have to absolutely love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis said he even thanked Rodman for his suggestions. Of
course, Rambis also fined Rodman for showing up late for Saturday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for isolated incidents, I don't think anyone has ever
criticized Dennis for what he does on the basketball floor,''
Rambis said. ``I don't care what Dennis does off the court as long
as he doesn't hurt anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have hired a staff of 450 to make sure he doesn't get
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just joking.''
</P>
<P>
   Or just hoping?
</P>
<P>
   Rambis has won all the early bets. But the game has just
started. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
