<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR WOMEN DROP THE BALL IN NCAA QUEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Baylor adopted ``Reaching New Horizons'' as
its motto for the women's basketball season, doing little to
downplay expectations of the first NCAA Tournament berth in school
history.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a team that reached the finals of the 1998 Women's
National Invitation Tournament probably began a quiet postseason
last night well short of its implied goal. Baylor fell to Missouri,
60-55, in the first round of the Big 12 tournament at Municipal
Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   In the estimation of Bears coach Sonja Hogg, the loss to the
10th-seeded Tigers eliminated Baylor (16-13) from realistic
consideration as an NCAA participant. Afterward, Hogg actively
lobbied against her team's receiving a return invitation to the
WNIT because the school lost money despite being host to four games
in the 1998 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would like to return to the WNIT, Hogg said: ``No.
I think that would be almost anticlimactic. I say that now and I've
pretty well thought that through.''
</P>
<P>
   In her mind, as well as in the minds of Baylor players, the
1998-99 season ended with the Bears being outhustled and
outrebounded, 49-27, by a Missouri team that Baylor defeated by 24
points on Jan. 27. Missouri (13-14) advances to today's
second-round matchup against Iowa State (20-6).
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, which returned its top three scorers from a team that
finished 20-11 a year ago, watched that trio combine to shoot 27.2
percent against Missouri. Guard Lara Webb (2-of-15) struggled most,
but neither guard Toya Ellis (4-of-10) nor center Kacy Moffitt
(3-of-8) found the going much easier on a night when Baylor shot
31.6 percent and held only three brief, one-point leads in the
final 26 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, meanwhile, watched guard Julie Helm (26 points) and
forward Kesha Bonds (17 points, 14 rebounds) step up repeatedly
during crunch time. Bonds' free throws with 5.7 seconds remaining
sealed the victory. And Baylor's postseason fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to continue playing,'' Moffitt said, addressing
the Bears' postseason possibilities. ``But I don't know if a lot of
people on our team have the drive to compete any more.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
