</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO GRETZKY, BUT THE SHOW DOES GO ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Nicole Kidman came down with a bronchial
infection last week and could not display her acting skill to eager
Broadway throngs, the producers closed ``The Blue Room'' a bit
early. Miss Kidman regrets, and all that.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadway Blues do not have the option of posting a notice in
the lobby of Madison Square Garden, advising: ``Mr. Wayne Gretzky
is indisposed for today's performance. All patrons who would like a
refund may apply at the box office.'' Refunds are just not done in
sports, even if the Great One is watching from on high. Hockey is,
after all, a team game, and the New York Rangers are demonstrating
that.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gretzky went out with a bulging disk in his neck, the
Rangers have gone on a downright rampage, for them, and won two
straight games, before tying the Dallas Stars, 2-2, on Tuesday
night in a game of playoff intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge game,'' admitted Adam Graves beforehand, referring to
the Stars' having the best record in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Then Graves busted onto the ice and scored his 30th goal and
energized the Rangers, who are all making the most of the
responsibility without Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody thought we'd get 5 of 6 points against
very good teams,'' said John Muckler, the somewhat surprised coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers actually lost ground to their competitors for the
last playoff spot in the East. Expansion may have watered down the
talent in hockey, and made the last surviving Canadian teams seem
marginal and remote compared to all these burgeoning Sun Belt
franchises, but expansion has accomplished one positive thing _ it
has made qualifying for the playoffs seem almost respectable.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer a matter of culling a few strays from the pack.
With 27 teams, there is now some legitimate competition for the
eight spots in the East and the West. The Rangers are struggling to
justify their gigantic payroll without their marquee player, the
man who eclipsed George Mikan of the Minneapolis Lakers (Tonight:
Mikan vs. Knicks, the Garden marquee once proclaimed) as the
greatest No. 99 in sports history. Since Gretzky arrived in the
fall of 1996, the Rangers have been doing their utmost to tune into
his other-worldly passes and intuitive feints. As Graves said,
``Sometimes you need a goal and Gretz makes a great play.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky went out, the Rangers had to rethink their
approach. ``We've talked about keeping it simple _ puck in, puck
out,'' Graves said the other day. ``Muck says: `Try to play safe
and sound. Don't take chances.'''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Gretzky is out another week or two, the Rangers
will have more minutes and more challenge to do it themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a healthy fear of the unknown,'' Graves said. ``You
don't want to embarrass yourselves. With Gretz out, you have to do
it yourself. You have to be at your top form. There's a fine line
between doing too much, and being yourself, but collectively, we
can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Deferring to a brilliant teammate _ even one as self-effacing
and generous as Gretzky _ can be a subtle and destructive impulse.
In his absence, other players see the puck skittering on the ice
and they wonder, do they go toward it _ or drift into the corners?
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect example is the first game, when Manny Malhotra comes
out of the gate and pops a big one,'' Graves said, referring to the
big kid who was the top draft choice in 1998, but has been breaking
in slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Then against Philadelphia last Sunday, Petr Nedved scored enough
goals to guarantee headgear for all those damp and chilly days, as
the Rangers try to extend their season without Gretzky, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're concerned because you don't want him to play hurt,''
Graves said. ``We feel the same way about Todd Harvey and the other
guys who are hurt. It tells me something about this team that Gretz
and all of them are waiting in the room after the game, standing
right by the door, shaking hands.''
</P>
<P>
   In professional football, injured players are considered a
distraction, maybe even an unwanted reminder that bones and muscles
and brains do get banged up. In hockey, the injured players are
still part of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Rangers are discovering they can bluster and pass and
even score without Gretzky. ``Gretzky improves us terrifically,''
said Scott Fraser, who has played well in the three games. ``We've
got to have him back and we are anxiously awaiting his return.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest scoring touch in the history of the sport is
currently unavailable, but the other Rangers do not consider
themselves understudies. In sports, they are called teammates. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
