<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-CLIPPERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS PROTECT HOME-COURT STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Mavericks coach Don Nelson gave the game ball to A.C.
Green for his sterling performance last night against the Los
Angeles Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   He could have also given one to Shawn Bradley, Steve Nash,
Hubert Davis, Michael Finley or Gary Trent. All six players played
solid basketball as the Mavericks had their highest scoring output
of the season in ousting the hapless Clippers, 112-99, before
13,492 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks have won four consecutive home games for the first
time since March 25-April 7, 1994. They also have won five of their
past seven games to improve to 6-10 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   Green set the tone with his aggressive play at both ends of the
court. He finished with a season-high 19 points and a season-high
12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the role is, I'm ready to do it,'' said Green, who
entered he game averaging 4.2 points per game. ``Being the leader
on this team, you've just got to get out and sacrifice a lot of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (0-13) appear on the brink of establishing some NBA
history. The NBA record for futility to start the season is 0-17 by
the Miami Heat in its expansion year of 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who had 20 points and nine assists, said the Clippers'
sorry state of affairs was extra motivation for the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be their first win, and you don't want to be
part of history, so to speak,'' he said. ``You just want to go out
and destroy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash got out of the sick bed and scored 16 points for Dallas. He
was 4-of-6 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   Trent had 16 points, while Davis poured in a season-high 18
points and was 6-of-14 from the field. Davis had seven points in
the first quarter, when the Mavericks compiled their highest
scoring quarter of the season and led, 38-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good out there,'' Davis said. ``I think everyone had
really good looks, because everyone was unselfish. It's not a
coincidence that everyone shoots well when they pass the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley contributed 10 points and seven rebounds, and collected
a season-high nine blocked shots. He got two blocks within a span
of one minute as Dunbar High School alumnus Charles Smith
challenged the 7-foot-6 center and failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks had 26 assists. They also shot 50.6 percent from
the field and put more than four players in double-figure scoring
for the first time all season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
