<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5505 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-BRUINS-COYOTES-BOS &LR;      03-03 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BEAT COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-BRUINS-COYOTES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Phoenix Coyotes of the early season were a formidable
opponent _ big, strong, fast, and able to score almost at will.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bruins played them back in October, the Coyotes looked
like world-beaters who surely would contend for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Times are tougher now. The Bruins stood up to everything the
Coyotes threw at them Tuesday night, earning a 3-2 victory at the
FleetCenter that sent Phoenix limping home after a 1-6 road trip.
</P>
<P>
   You want to fight? The Bruins fought. You want to hit? The
Bruins hit. You want to muscle in the corners? The Bruins muscled
in the corners.
</P>
<P>
   The win extended Boston's unbeaten streak to five games (4-0-1)
and made it 3-0-1 on this homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they'd been on a long road trip and we wanted to make
sure we sent them home thinking about it anyway,'' said Bruins
coach Pat Burns. ``It was a big win. It was very important for us
because every game is going to be like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston took the lead less than a minute into the game, on
Cameron Mann's fifth goal of the year. Mattias Timander blasted a
shot from the right point that was saved by goalie Robert Esche,
making his first NHL start. Sergei Samsonov got to the rebound and
fired from the inside edge of the right circle, but Esche turned
that back, too. Mann swooped in down the slot and beat the
netminder with a backhander at the 53-second mark.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the period, the Coyotes pulled even. Former
Bruin Rick Tocchet, who is having a stellar season, ripped a
slapper from the right circle that goalie Byron Dafoe stopped. The
puck bounced in front past Ray Bourque and Jeremy Roenick was on
the left side of the crease to put the rebound home at 10:31.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took the lead again in the early going of the middle
period, with checking-line right wing Rob DiMaio finishing off a
nice individual effort. Tim Taylor relayed a pass up to left P.J.
Axelsson in neutral ice. Axelsson backhanded a pass, banking it off
the boards, to DiMaio, who charged down the left side. He skated
through the left circle, cut in on Esche, and beat him with a
forehander for the 2-1 lead at 1:45. It was DiMaio's fourth goal of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the period, the Bruins built on that lead, with
Axelsson, another member of the top defensive line, scoring what
proved to be the winner at 9:48. Anson Carter passed to Axelsson,
whose shot from the slot sailed over the goalie for his seventh of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The second period also featured a heavyweight bout between the
No. 2 scorers on each team. At the 3:13 mark, Jason Allison took
issue with the Coyotes' Keith Tkachuk crushing Carter, so Allison
went after him. The two squared off and exchanged blows before they
were separated. Allison wound up with two minutes for interference,
and each received five minutes for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, normally not one to fight, said he made an exception
because he thought the Coyotes' best players were the ones crossing
the line between hits and cheap shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to dish it out, they're going to have to take
it, too,'' he said. ``A lot of those guys, they think they're
untouchable. They can go around elbowing guys but they get hit once
and it's like, `What are you doing hitting me?' We matched their
toughness.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the period, DiMaio and Roenick also mixed it up.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes came as close as they would with a goal at 5:21 of
the third period. Defenseman-turned-wing Deron Quint took a
backdoor pass from center Daniel Briere and beat Dafoe near the
right post.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' frustration was evident. As time expired, Tkachuk
smashed his stick against the boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the last game of the trip and we thought maybe they'd
come out and give it everything they got,'' said Dafoe.
``Unfortunately we kept them in the game in the first period, we
kind of took it away in the second, and they came out very hard in
the third. I was surprised. I thought they might have given up, but
it's a team that plays right to the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
