<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VERO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MULLING MOVE FROM VERO BEACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Their options hardly seem like options.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers can sculpt a new spring-training site on the Fort
McDowell Indian Community in Arizona, tailoring every last detail
to their exact specifications, and camp could be a one-hour plane
ride from home.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can sell Dodgertown to Indian River County and the city
of the Vero Beach, lease it back and make alterations to the site.
</P>
<P>
   The issue seems to be clear-cut, and speculation is the Dodgers
are holding their final spring training at Dodgertown. But it is
more than just ``new'' vs. ``used.'' No one with the team is ready
to say the outcome has already been determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is twofold,'' Dodgers CEO and President Bob
Graziano said. ``First, what is the most economical way for us to
go through spring training? Second, what is the best
baseball-operations way to go through spring training?
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the Dodgers responsibility is the relationships we've
been able to build and maintain over the years. The relationships
we've had over the last 50 years is important, but at the same time
it's got to be mutually beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the biggest issue.
</P>
<P>
   Spring training has become big business, with many new stadiums
holding 10,000-12,000 fans. Vero Beach's historic Holman Stadium
has a capacity of 6,500, which decreases its potential revenue.
</P>
<P>
   And the nostalgia and tradition come with a price. The Dodgers
own the 450-acre facility, employ 250 people there and must pay for
maintenance and year-round upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring training here is very expensive and I would venture to
say more expensive than most other facilities because of the nature
of the facility and the services rendered,'' said Craig Callan,
managing director of Dodgertown and a Vero Beach resident.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Fort McDowell Indian Reservation, located
approximately 30 miles northeast of Phoenix, is offering to build a
$30 million complex that could put the Dodgers in Arizona by next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Peaks Sports Complex, as it would be called, would
include a 12,500-seat stadium, six full-sized practice fields, two
half-sized practice fields, a dining facility and a conference
center.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to the Dodgers would be $1 per year for a 30-year
lease, a Yavapai tribe official said, althoughdetails of how to
split the revenue and maintenance costs have yet to be ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is you'd be ripping the heart out of Vero
Beach (if the Dodgers left) because Vero Beach and the Dodgers are
one and the same,'' Callan said. ``But I've researched every team .
. . and if those teams can have a $30 million facility and have
favorable terms, why should the Dodgers settle for anything but at
least that? I think that's only fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sweetheart deal the Dodgers would get, the
location and new facilities are big factors.
</P>
<P>
   While Dodgertown's charm can't be overstated _ players walk
through the crowds to get to Holman Stadium and the practice fields
_ integral parts of the complex are antiquated.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the new complexes in which four baseball practice fields
are clustered together, which makes it easier for the coaching
staff to evaluate players on different fields _ Dodgertown's fields
are grouped in pairs and spread about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier to get around if you know how to drive a
golf cart, and there's been a lot of clubs that left here and
became championship teams,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson.
``You couldn't get me to say anything bad about Vero. It's a jewel
of the intercoastal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grapefruit League travel is also difficult on the team. Only
the Mets, who train at Port St. Lucie, are within 50 miles of Vero
Beach. In Arizona's Cactus League, six teams train in the greater
Phoenix area. All of the National League West teams _ San
Francisco, San Diego, Colorado and Arizona _ train in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   A move appears to makes sense on all fronts. But tradition and
nostalgia, two of baseball's most appealing characteristics, have
kept Vero Beach's hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1948, the Dodgers have trained in Vero Beach. The area
even named a school after the complex, Dodgertown Elementary
School, and a group of community leaders have started a ``Keep Our
Dodgers'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgertown is a one-of-a-kind shrine to the organization, from
Vin Scully Way and Jackie Robinson Avenue to the barracks that
house players and front-office staff, to old-time photos that
capture great Dodgers moments dating back to Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Dodgers would be catastrophic to the area's
economy. Vero Beach city manager Rex Taylor estimated the Dodgers
bring $20-30 million into the community annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would hurt the community because the whole economy is based
upon the six weeks the Dodgers train down here,'' said Frank Brush,
82, a Vero Bech resident. ``I'm from Brooklyn (and the Dodgers) are
why I moved here. The Dodgers have a special relationship with
their fans and this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Vero Beach/Indian River County are proposing to purchase
Dodgertown, with the help of a ``bed tax'' within the county, and
lease it back to the Dodgers. Appraisals for Dodgertown are
expected to be near $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we've been very honest with the county
and city . . is stating that once we make a proposal to them of
minimum requirements, they will be able to sit down and say, `Wow,
can we afford this or not?' '' Callan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the negotiations start. At this point, we haven't
even got there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indian River County administrator Jim Chandler said the
community wouldn't have gotten involved in the process if it
couldn't afford it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers are looking economically at the bottom line and so
are we,'' Chandler said. ``Up to this point, we're considering an
awful lot of things.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers work with Vero Beach in what is being termed
``good faith'' discussions, the Yavapais are waiting for the team
to sign a contract so they can start construction. Conceptual
drawings have been completed by HOK Sports Facilities Group, the
firm that designed Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   When negotiations began with Fort McDowell Indian Community,
Clinton Pattea was the president. Two weeks ago Bernadine Boyd
became the president, although the community's desire to lure the
Dodgers to Arizona hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   Before Pattea left office, word from Arizona was a deal was all
but consummated, which has caused an air of uncertainty at
Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this point I do (feel confident),'' Boyd said. ``We're
optimistic and we're excited about them coming to our area. We were
surprised that Fort McDowell was named as one of the sites they
would want to come to. We've given our proposal to them, but we
haven't received a counterproposal from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are expected to announce a decision shortly after
spring training concludes, but the general feeling is that
Dodgertown won't be inhabited by the Dodgers next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what Vero Beach would be like if (the Dodgers)
left,'' resident Lucille Gladness said. ``It's something that I
hope doesn't happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
