<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CHECKING IN WITH OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world where points count, and goals count more than
anything, Rob DiMaio's value can be easily overlooked. It's the
checker's life. Score a couple of goals and the whole world loves
you. Spend 60 minutes racing around the ice with a fire
extinguisher, pulling on Superman's cape, poking multimillionaires
in the ribs, and nobody knows your name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get stuck with that stigma sometimes,'' said DiMaio, whose
goal, his fourth of the season, helped the Bruins to a 3-2 win over
the Coyotes Tuesday night at the Vault. ``That you're only a
checker.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no shaking that label now, not unless, at the age of
31, the rugged, durable, tenacious DiMaio suddenly reinvents
himself as some latent run-'n'-gunner. He has the legs to be a
scorer. He has the will for it. He has the spatial sense it takes
to be a producer. He lacks only the hands, the finishing touch,
which is always what separates those who dig ditches in the ice for
a living from those who live the sweet life of scoring success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have the ability to score,'' said DiMaio, referring to
himself and his running mates on the Boston checking line, P.J.
Axelsson and Tim Taylor. ``Timmy led the AHL one year in scoring.
And I had some good years, in junior hockey and in the minors. P.J.
can be a scorer. So I don't think you can categorize us as solely a
checking line.''
</P>
<P>
   That was certainly the case against the Coyotes. DiMaio had his
strike, lifting the Bruins to a 2-1 lead in the second. Just over
eight minutes later, Axelsson popped in his seventh this year,
collecting a feed from Anson Carter as he stood alone in the slot,
not a single Phoenix sweater within 10-10-321 dialing distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I stood there for a couple of seconds before I shot,''
said a pleasantly perplexed Axelsson, who also supplied the key
assist on DiMaio's goal, chipping a perfect pass off the sideboard
to send his linemate galloping down the left side. ``I was really
surprised about that.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio looked every bit the sniper on his goal. He raced into
Axelsson's relay and blew past defenseman Keith Carney at the blue
line, his legs buzzing to stay ahead of the former Providence
defenseman. Cutting in from the left circle, he rushed through the
slot and slid a forehander under rookie netminder Robert Esche.
</P>
<P>
   For a second, DiMaio was a highlight clip out of the old
Canadiens skate-and-shoot handbook, a little Lafleur come to life
in a black-and-gold sweater. More rushes like that and he'd have
more career goals than he does career broken noses. It was a piece
of work in the most complimentary sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got their noses dirty, too, that's why they get their
points,'' said coach Pat Burns, referring to his trusted checking
triumvirate. ``Rob gets down on the boards. Like on his goal. He
goes there knowing he'll get by the guy or he'll be completely
creamed. Not everyone wants to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, DiMaio got into a jabbering match with Jeremy Roenick,
another of those big-coin guys DiMaio chases for a living. DiMaio
got hit by Roenick and there was something about the former Thayer
Academy star's style that DiMaio didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leaves his feet when he hits guys,'' said DiMaio. ``I don't
like that. You can really hurt people that way. He tells me he
always hits like that. That's fine, but I told him he's not going
to hit me like that. If he does, then I'm going to do something
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another thing to like about DiMaio. In his world, it's
still OK to get angry at the guys who wear the other sweaters. Too
many games now look like NHLPA pep rallies (feel the love, guys,
feel the love). Many nights are absent big hits and rarely does
anyone say a discouraging word about the other side. Roenick plays
with an edge. DiMaio does the same. The two met and some sparks
flew. The same thing happened when Jason Allison and Keith Tkachuk
banged around in a center-ice rotary. But the DiMaio-Roenick
exchange had a touch of the old Johnny McKenzie ``check this''
attitude in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a knock against Jeremy,'' said DiMaio. ``But I told him, I
find that kind of stuff cheap. Hey, I'm not the cleanest guy in the
world, but I just don't do that. I don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Checkers aren't about style and artistic form. They're about
rolling over the boards every third shift, sometimes more if the
game dictates, and yapping, clawing, even scoring to get the job
done. DiMaio's line was on for both Phoenix goals. In that sense,
he said, the two goals his line scored were just a matter of making
things even.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of us know we can score,'' said DiMaio. ``All of us
believe, if we're given the opportunity to play that way, we can
put the puck in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the checker's dream. And for a night it came true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
