<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5512 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      03-03 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE SUPERSTAR SUZUKI THE NOMO OF POSITION PLAYERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ If it plays in Kobe, can it play in Peoria?
</P>
<P>
   Ichiro Suzuki will have a good idea starting Thursday when the
Japanese superstar takes part in his first exhibition game with the
Mariners. Suzuki is just visiting, but he's embarking on something
no Japanese position player has done: test his talents in the
American major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Since Hideo Nomo joined the Los Angeles Dodgers in 1995, other
Japanese pitchers have followed his lead. Shigetoshi Hasegawa of
the Anaheim Angels led baseball in relief innings last year, and
Hideki Irabu of the New York Yankees and Masato Yoshii of the New
York Mets were effective as starters.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki, 25, is the best position player in Japan, drawing
comparisons to Ken Griffey Jr. for his baseball ability and Michael
Jordan for his celebrity. The left-handed hitter has won five
batting titles with the Orix Blue Wave and has won league MVP
honors three times. He has stolen as many as 49 bases in a season,
and his outfield arm ranks with any in the States.
</P>
<P>
   Though Suzuki can't become a free agent until midway through the
2001 season, at the earliest, it's obvious to those around the
Mariners that he could be a trailblazer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with and against some guys that obviously had the
ability to have success over here,'' said Mariners hitting coach
Jesse Barfield, who finished his playing career with the Yomiuri
Giants in 1993. ``But to me, if anybody could do it and have
success, it's Ichiro, because he's so fundamentally sound in
everything he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki said he isn't motivated by the chance to do for hitters
what Nomo did for pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if I'm the first one or not, I just would
like the opportunity to do it,'' he said. ``I want to face the best
in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki is careful not to disparage the talent in the Japanese
major leagues. Proving to Americans that Japan can produce good
offensive players is of minimal concern. But the fact that Nomo &AMP;
Co. have been joined by no Japanese hitters after five years does
raise the question of why.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the answer is that, from an offensive standpoint, Japan
produces what America already has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their players are more line-drive, gap-to-gap hitters,'' said
Roger Hansen, an M's minor league instructor now working for the
Blue Wave. ``There are tons of those in the States, so how many can
you really bring?''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Colborn, M's director of Pacific Rim scouting, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The style of play we look for is different than what they have
to offer,'' he said. ``We want big, powerful guys with size, and a
lot of their guys are contact hitters and smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   No player in Japan's 135-game season hit even 35 homers last
year, and M's pitcher Jamie Moyer, who played in Japan this winter
with a team of major league stars, said he noticed parks were
smaller and balls didn't carry as well in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Barfield said the game is played differently there, with more
emphasis on the one- or two-run inning. In the first inning, he
said, it's common to see hitters bunting and corner infielders
guarding the line against extra-base hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitching dominates games more,'' said Roger Jongewaard, M's
vice president for scouting and player development. ``Their
pitchers have excellent control, and it's easier to scout pitching.
You see one or two games, and you feel pretty good about what a guy
can or can't do. With a position player, if he has an uneventful
one or two games, you walk away not knowing for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Age and size also matter. With no role models who have made the
jump, Japanese amateurs are less inclined to dream of coming to the
States. Professionally, Japanese players need nine years' service
time before becoming free agents, and many would-be prospects are
too old for consideration when their time comes.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Japanese game emphasizes pitching, Jongewaard said,
many larger Japanese players are pitchers, not sluggers. Colborn
said it's less common to find players with legs as long and upper
bodies as big as a lot of American players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a choice between a player that looked like Joey
Cora and a player that looked like Alex Rodriguez, you'd take
Alex,'' Colborn said. ``That doesn't mean there aren't Joey Coras
in the big leagues, because there are, but a lot of their players
look like Joey.''
</P>
<P>
   Colborn also noted the social difficulties in leaving Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big gamble to leave Japan, psychologically, because
it's such a tight-knit society,'' said Colborn, who was pitching
coach for the Blue Wave from 1990-93. ``They're not brought up to
be as independent as much as Americans are. We're taught to be
individuals, they're taught to consider the group. When you leave,
you lose that security.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the first (position player) that leaves is facing
ostracization, which is exactly what Nomo got. But he redeemed
himself by competing and becoming a hero. The first hitter who
comes over here is blazing a new path. Does he have the
personality, is he strong enough to do it? Those are the main
things, and then, are the circumstances right?''
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki recognizes the same issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baseball part will take care of itself; if you're good
enough to play, you're good enough to play,'' he said. ``His
lifestyle, his strength and his ability to handle stress and
opposition _ it will take the right person to be able to accomplish
all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The eyes of Japan will be watching as Suzuki begins his quest.
The Mariners announced Tuesday that exhibition games on March 5 and
6 will be televised live in Japan by NHK Broadcast Services. Never
before has NHK televised a major league spring training game.
</P>
<P>
   MARINER NOTES: Agent Scott Boras, who represents Rodriguez,
David Segui and other Mariners, chatted with M's vice president of
baseball operations Woody Woodward at practice Tuesday. ``I don't
see anybody tense here,'' Woodward said. ``We'll talk through the
spring and see what we can get done.'' Segui's contract expires at
the end of this year, Rodriguez's after the 2000 season. ... Also
spotted Tuesday: union chief Donald Fehr, who delivered his annual
address to Mariners players. ... Remember all that skepticism over
the composition of the sod at Safeco Field? At least one team
thinks the M's have the right mix. The Arizona Diamondbacks, who
also have a retractable-roof ballpark with a grass field, announced
they are changing their turf to the same blend of 80-percent
Kentucky bluegrass and 20-percent perennial ryegrass the Mariners
will use. ... Griffey took his son Trey to a Lakers-Suns basketball
game in Phoenix Monday night and met Dennis Rodman for the first
time. ``I'm going to get a tattoo,'' Griffey said, without
specifying what kind. A Mariners compass rose, perhaps? ``No,''
Griffey said, smiling. ``I might be traded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
