<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-03 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINER FORECAST SUNNY FOR LONG BALLS ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SQUINT, Ariz. _ Lost my sunglasses on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, what could be expected? I haven't needed them for almost
half a year. I forgot the transport requirements, not to mention
the operating instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Heading to the Mariners' spring training camp, I had no
protection from the local atmospheric treacheries. Due to lack of
exercise, the muscles in my molelike eyes didn't dilate.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't see a thing.
</P>
<P>
   No, there is no place called Squint, Ariz. Yet it is all I can
do.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, through the use of multiple baseball caps and a
cardboard shield, my eyes were sufficiently sheltered to provide me
some bearings. I drove along Bell Road in 80-degree heat until the
strip malls ended and the home-run balls thwacked against the
rental car _ unmistakable evidence of Peoria and the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The next observation didn't need unimpaired vision: The more
both change, the more they remain the same.
</P>
<P>
   The main arterial to the spring training site is now swollen
into one solid conga line of overneoned national fast-food joints
and megastores. Like the Mariners, it's a lot of familiar flash.
And about as unlikely to distinguish itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest,'' said Woody Woodward, Mariner vice president
of baseball operations. ``Regardless of what's been said, Lou
(Piniella) likes hitting, period.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it with a small smile, not intending a criticism but
offering a frank portrayal of the essential M's of the '90s _ good
hit, no pitch or field.
</P>
<P>
   Owing to the fact that the first fake game isn't until Thursday,
it's a tad early to conclude firmly that the '99 Mariners will be a
replica of past Piniella teams.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the take on this squad was apparent months ago.
</P>
<P>
   While the annual offseason rhetoric included the standard
bromides about bumping up pitching and defense _ a refrain that
sounds suspiciously like the old Soviet five-year economic plans to
increase production of tractors and potatoes _ the Mariners failed
to replace Randy Johnson with another No. 1 pitcher, failed to find
a fast leadoff hitter, and didn't add much glovework.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the B-list newcomers to the Mariner veterans, it's
obvious that another formidable array of missiles and artillery is
ready. Again shy of quota: tractors and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Woodward tell it, the situation is epidemic in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to every club this offseason, and what you'll see
starting the season is more than 20 clubs still looking for
pitching,'' he said. ``That includes the Yankees, who need a
left-handed relief pitcher. When you see the kind of money that was
given for pitchers such as Tim Belcher and Todd Stottlemyre, teams
are trying to make their offenses as good as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Add in the '98 jolt created by Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa in
the home-run chase, install Albert Belle in the shoebox of Camden
Yards, and baseball figures to be in for another year of rotund
round-trippin' led, presumably, by the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   While topping the game again in homers (234), the Mariners last
season also set a major league record for fewest one-run wins (they
needed to win their final six one-run games to finish 10-20).
Although that is partly due to bullpen failures, the offense
continued to be mostly an all-or-nothing proposition with limited
capacity for manufacturing runs or creating a late rally.
</P>
<P>
   Players see little reason to abandon the macho tradition, now
given further legitimacy by the ardor that enveloped McGwire and
Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``More fans come to see home runs than they do anything else,''
said Jay Buhner. ``We have one of the most potent offenses in
baseball history. The big gray cloud over us has been pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. claims the home-run chase to be a false god.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home runs are not why I play,'' he said. ``The Yankees didn't
have anybody hit more than 25 home runs, and what did they win _
120 games?''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Griffey emphatically insists he's not a home-run
hitter. Yet his 56 last year was only the seventh-highest total in
history. Like Buhner, Griffey has grown accustomed to the American
League and Piniella-endorsed style that calls for the three-run
dinger as the easiest cure-all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it is in this league,'' said former
National Leaguer David Segui, who said the infrequency with which
Mariner hitters sacrifice an at-bat to advance a runner ``is no
more than on any other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the big-bopper emphasis, coupled with the lack of
pitcher development, adds up to this:
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' total of 583 extra-base hits last year was
third-highest in baseball history, edging out the 1936 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 was the 597 of the '97 Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 was the 607 of the '96 Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   In those three seasons, the Mariners have won one postseason
game.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon has been baseball's Great Squandering _ a
spotlight offense with refrigerator-light pitching and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe my undilated eyes betray me. Maybe all the new players
will change things for Seattle in '99.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe McGwire, Sosa, Belle, Griffey, Vaughn, et al. will
punch little rollers to the right side of the infield to get the
runner to third.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
