<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-PARKER-GILBERT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARKER RETURNS TO PHOENIX AREA PREP SCENE AS GILBERT COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse Parker, the man who implemented the pink bellies that got
Mesa Mountain View's coaches in trouble last season, was handed the
Gilbert High School football program Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the challenge, and it will be a
challenge,'' said Parker, who won 232 games before leaving Arizona
for Texas high school football in 1995. ``I'm looking at it as an
opportunity to sort of start over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, who will meet with Gilbert players today and will begin
work during spring drills in April, will have to change his
wardrobe. He stalked the Mountain View sidelines from the late
1970s to mid-'90s in short-sleeved, red-and-blue striped golf
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got black and gold stripes all over him now,'' said
Gilbert District Athletic Director Joe Pico, who helped Parker
start Mountain View's program in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Pink definitely will be out.
</P>
<P>
   Parker has said he began having players inflict pink bellies to
each other in Mountain View's program in the 1980s as a consequence
of losing off-season conditioning contests so they would know how
it feels to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View coaches continued the tradition after Parker left
in 1995 to try to win a title in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Coach Bernie Busken and assistant Jerry Wheeler
were suspended for one playoff game for violating a Mesa district
policy against such forms of discipline. That issue was addressed
in the interview process, Pico said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a policy like Mesa, but our coaches damn well
understand what happens in terms of pink bellies and cruelty to
children,'' Pico said. ``Jesse understands that. He'll do us
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker is grateful for the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of admiration for Gilbert to be willing to
go out on a limb,'' said Parker, who won four state titles at
Mountain View and one at Camelback. ``Not many educators take the
chance to bring about success.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker returns to the east Valley after ending a coaching stint
in Texas amid controversy over his methods of discipline.
</P>
<P>
   He resigned from Texas High in Texarkana just before the start
of last season because of a dispute over discipline with the new
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obstacles to overcome that I had at Texas High were a lot
more than I realized,'' Parker said. ``I know something about
Gilbert from the past, and we won't have the obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from the Texas experience. The thing that hurt
me the most in the long run was the lack of support within the
administration and even some of the coaches who weren't supportive.
I don't think that will happen at Gilbert.''
</P>
<P>
   Pico said the players will benefit from Parker's strict
discipline and work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game should be in big bold letters: WORK,''
Pico said. ``Parker is in town. We will all get together and become
a family and go to work. Discipline will be in the line of work.
They're going to be working. If you run it halfway, you're going to
run it 15 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker, a highly decorated educator who will teach in the social
studies department, competed for the job with former Alhambra Coach
Paul Hoffland and Gilbert assistants Luis Nightengale and Mark
Nolen, Athletic Director Mark Cisterna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited to have Jesse just based on his accomplishments
in the east Valley,'' Cisterna said. ``I think he's going to bring
high energy to the program. It's hard to argue with his record.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
