<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATS AWAIT BIG UNIT  
 JOHNSON EXPECTS AGGRESSIVE SWINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ If there are extra coins in the University of Arizona
Wildcats' athletics kitty, baseball Coach Jerry Stitt might want to
use them to buy parachutes for his players when they play the
Diamondbacks today at Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   Flame-throwing left-hander Randy Johnson will be on the mound
for the Diamondbacks, and the Wildcats might be inclined to bail
out of the batter's box in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 35, who pitched for the University of Southern
California before turning pro, says he isn't looking to teach the
young whippersnappers a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still hitters and they're still aggressive, whether
they're in college or the major leagues,'' Johnson said Tuesday.
``There's a bit of pride on the line for them and me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get the ball in the strike zone, work on a few
pitches and build a little more stamina each time out, make sure my
endurance is there. I'll probably have only about 30 pitches, but I
don't want to use them all in the first two innings.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Paying tribute &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A moment of silence will be observed before today's game to pay
respect to Ken Robinson, a minor league pitcher who was killed in
an auto accident early Sunday morning in northwest Tucson. &QL;  &QL; 
Playing it safe &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Kelly Stinnett did not play in Tuesday's intrasquad game
and likely will be out a few more days with a bit of stiffness and
soreness in his back just below his right (throwing) shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were the regular season and I needed to, I could play
on it, but there's no sense in pushing it at this point,'' Stinnett
said. ``There's kind of a knot back there that won't let go.
Hopefully, a little rest and some anti-inflammatories will take
care of it.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Where's Womack? &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter says that recent trade acquisition Tony
Womack will play today, but where? The club wants to move him from
second base to right field, but he is unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Womack took more work in the infield during a Tuesday morning
workout, but he also did some shagging in the outfield for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rome wasn't built in a day,'' Showalter said. ``Let's just say
he'll be out on the field _ somewhere.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Lee-doff hitter? &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there is such a thing as a sophomore jinx, first baseman
Travis Lee apparently hasn't heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   He was 4 for 4 in Tuesday's intrasquad game, including a
three-run homer off right-hander Dan Carlson and a double off
left-hander Matt Ruebel. After the double, Lee took off for third
base and made it safely on a head-first slide for the steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he must be working for that leadoff spot,'' Showalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the normal scheme, Lee is expected to hit third or fourth. &QL;  &QL; 
Turning it &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most encouraging signs of Tuesday's game, Showalter
said, was the footwork of Jay Bell around the second-base bag on
double-play attempts. Bell is making the move from shortstop to
second base this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bell was the middle man on a double play started by third
baseman Matt Williams and narrowly had another when he took a throw
from pitcher Aaron Small and got the throw to first a tad late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was over there at second for the final 15 games last year,
and not once was I involved on a double-play ball hit to the left
side,'' Bell said. ``There were a few 4-6-3's, but nothing over
there. So it was good to be able to have that chance today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
