<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UW-PAVILION-SPI &LR;      03-03 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UW-PAVILION-SPI </SLUG>
  
 UW's EDMUNDSON PAVILION, 71, BRACES FOR A MAKEOVER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Experiencing the ultimate midlife crisis, Hec
Edmundson Pavilion is prepared to trade in its white socks and
black wing tips this weekend, promising to emerge in 18 months much
more hip, vibrant, a trend-setter.
</P>
<P>
   Get out the gold chains and deep tans, the city's most
moth-eaten athletic facility is headed for a major makeover. Not
one red brick will be displaced from the outer walls, but the
interior will lose all of its early 20th century feel.
</P>
<P>
   Stodgy Hec Ed is about to become ultra-chic Hectoro Eduardo.
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old building will be vacated this weekend _ or after
possible University of Washington NIT postseason basketball games
are completed _ setting in motion a $39 million renovation project
that begins April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, ceremonial touches have been added to Saturday's
Husky-Cougar men's matchup _ the return of former players and
coaches, a game ball presentation, net-cutting, reception and
opening of a time capsule _ to signal impending change.
</P>
<P>
   Seats and memories will be ripped away, but apparently no one
feels an overwhelming need to retain them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem to want comfort,'' said Marv Harshman, 81, who
played in Edmundson Pavilion as a high schooler and collegian, and
coached there for the Huskies and as an opponent while at WSU. ``At
my age, I think it's kind of nice to have comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone will be the 20 posts that have obstructed views for seven
decades. Gone will be the acoustical tiles that have hung
grotesquely from the rafters for 31 years. Gone will be an
old-fashioned way of serving up a constantly evolving game.
</P>
<P>
   People like Addis Gutmann will tell you the place has always
carried a great deal of charm. The Laurelhurst travel agent and UW
grad, now 68, practically spent his childhood there. He went to
games with his father, climbed through Hec Ed windows with friends
to sneak into Husky football games and was personally acquainted
with basketball coach and gym namesake Clarence ``Hec'' Edmundson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pavilion had its own smell, a warm smell,'' Gutmann said.
``You walked in there and felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, have never cared much for the place. Or
understood how it has survived intact so long.
</P>
<P>
   Humzey Vessin was the student manager for a Kentucky team that
won a national championship at Hec Ed in 1949. For some unknown
reason, he recently stayed up past midnight in Lexington watching a
televised Husky game. He couldn't believe his eyes _ in the
backdrop was the same facility, virtually unchanged after 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Washington was still playing in that old gym
that we played in,'' said Vessin, now 71 and a retired golf
professional. ``That was fascinating to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Beard, a starting forward on the same Kentucky team and
later a convicted point-shaver, played in gyms all over the
country. He played in Europe as an Olympian. With so much at stake,
he wondered what he and his teammates were doing in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gym was not very good at all,'' said Beard, also 71 and
living in Louisville. ``Anybody who took one look at it could tell.
It was not any Madison Square Garden by any means; it was dark and
dank in comparison. I know no one has probably said all that
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a letdown, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Told the building is scheduled for a two-year remodel, Beard
didn't change his tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's 50 years overdue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other VIP visitors were more congenial in their assessment of
the local basketball accommodations. In 1952, Hec Ed hosted its
second NCAA championship event, and what would be the first Final
Four format used ('49 involved a title game and consolation
contest).
</P>
<P>
   Guests this time were the Kansas Jayhawks and their 6-foot-9,
240-pound All-America center, Clyde Lovellette. To the big guy, Hec
Ed was unique. Besides, he had a 33-point, 17-rebound title game on
that floor, one good for MVP honors and an 80-63 victory over St.
John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't matter where we played, in a high school gym,
college gym or arena,'' said Lovellette, now 69. ``We were just
happy to play in it. (Hec Ed) was huge. Most us were farm kids and
it looked like one of the big barns where we used to store things.
We had seen nothing like it.''
</P>
<P>
   People voiced a similar reaction when Edmundson Pavilion was
unveiled in 1927, seven years after a deckless Husky Stadium was
built. The pricetag was $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   The state high school tournament, which was created by Edmundson
in 1923 and hosted in another, tiny UW gym, was moved to the
spacious new arena in '28. For the next 50 years, the place became
a mecca for basketball fans across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a romantic place for a kid like me from a place like
Lake Stevens,'' Harshman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hec Ed's attendance record, which will stand for perpetuity, is
12,961, established during the 1957 state tourney semifinals that
featured a repeat title run by Seattle's Lincoln High. That's 400
more than were crammed into each of the gym's two NCAA title games.
</P>
<P>
   When redone, Hec Ed's new capacity will be just under 10,000, up
from the 7,900 seating arrangement used in recent years. There will
be no more 12,000-plus gatherings, which were made possible by
nearly all bleacher seating and a severe test of fire codes.
</P>
<P>
   The new facility will offer three kinds of seating _ bleachers,
bleachers with backing and theater chairs _ but no luxury boxes.
The ceiling will have a girdered look, with roof support provided
by four super-sized posts placed inauspicuously in the corners.
</P>
<P>
   Gothic art windows to the west will be uncovered on the inside,
with hope that the place can once again enjoy natural light. The
second-level Hall of Fame Room will be extended the length of the
building, giving it a museum atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The pavilion originally was designed as a multi-purpose
facility, handling six or seven men's sports _ including use as an
indoor football field and track _ and housing coaching offices,
classes and intramural gyms. Seating and flooring were meant to be
mobile. After the remodel, everything will be permanently attached.
</P>
<P>
   For ideas, UW officials toured refurbished campus arenas at
Duke, Kansas, Oklahoma State, Butler and Northwestern, and came
away encouraged. The first three have supported Final Four teams,
and the film ``Hoosiers'' was filmed at Butler in Indianapolis.
Only Northwestern, recovering from a gambling scandal, has failed
to enhance its basketball program with its new digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is to maintain the tradition and history of Hec
Edmundson in an updated fashion,'' UW assistant athletic director
Chip Lydum said. ``Instead of renovation, it's restoration.''
</P>
<P>
   Husky men's and women's basketball teams, as well as the women's
volleyball team, will be displaced for a year while Hec Ed is
gutted. The men will play at KeyArena, the women at Mercer Arena
and the volleyball team at the former naval station at Sand Point.
</P>
<P>
   Athletic offices, lockers and the training room have been moved
to the Hec Ed Addition, though the football team will be permitted
to use its existing dressing quarters through spring drills.
</P>
<P>
   While there aren't any protesters chained to the sight-impairing
posts, deploring the desecration of a Seattle landmark, there is
concern among longtime fans that memories might be lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Houbregs tossing up his soft hook from anywhere on the
floor. Rafael Stone, just 5-9, driving down the middle of the lane
and going over UCLA's 7-foot Lew Alcindor, now Kareem Abdul-Jabbar,
to score. Sammy White leaping and hanging in the air like an early
day Michael Jordan before becoming, unlike Mike, an accomplished
major league baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   There also was the bizarre and near-tragic. The Hec Ed roof had
skylights until a 1938 windstorm caused one to fall and injure two
spectators. Then there was the night in the 1940s when timer Bill
Belshaw, using a pistol to start and stop the halves, shot himself
in the hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He swore roundly and they had to take him to the trainer's
room and fix him up,'' said Wendell Broyles, former UW football and
basketball P.A. announcer. ``I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   By sprucing up Hec Ed, people hope to keep the region's wide
array of high school basketball talent from leaving for other
programs. Newness sells.
</P>
<P>
   From what he's seen of the new plans, Harshman thinks new seats
will mean more wins. He always was convinced the crowd was too far
removed from the action, that the noise level was effectively
muffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought old Hec Ed was one of the easiest places for
a visiting team to play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Let the wrecking ball swing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5518 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-ROCKETS-HNS     03-03 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The San Antonio Spurs entered Tuesday night's game against the
Rockets as one of the worst offensive teams in the Western
Confernce.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But they were the best team in the NBA when it came to defense,
and they proved that from start to finish in their 99-82 victory
before 16,285 Compaq Center fans.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, who set an NBA record last season by holding
opponents to 41-percent shooting from the field, are even better
this season, limiting teams to 39.6-percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets got a good look at that defense, shooting 41.3
percent _ and they had to rally to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The fans made their displeasure known, booing the Rockets as
they walked off the court at halftime trailing by 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was embarrassing,'' said Charles Barkley, one of the few
Rockets to exhibit any fire Tuesday night. ``We got our butts
kicked tonight. All we can do is apologize to the fans for putting
that effort out there. I'm not sure what happened, but it was just
embarrassing the way we played. It was an embarrassing effort.''
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much how the postgame analysis went from every
player wearing a Rockets uniform _ embarrassing, disappointing,
puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about a playoff-intensity-type game because it was a
big game, but it just wasn't there, and that puzzles me,'' said
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich. ``I thought that they came out more
aggressively than we did. I thought they made the extra pass, and
we just didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets didn't do much of anything right, playing like a
teen-ager on his first date _ they pretty much had an idea of what
they were trying to do but made all the wrong moves at the worst
possible times.
</P>
<P>
   All those wrong moves were manifested in one six-minute stretch
as the Rockets watched _ and that is the precise word _ the Spurs
work them over for a 17-3 run to end the first half.
</P>
<P>
   And that run went a long way toward ending the game as well.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen couldn't understand the lack of intensity, saying
there was never a time during the game that he thought the Rockets
demonstrated any sort of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, never,'' said Pippen when asked if he was ever happy with
the way things were going Tuesday night. ``Not even from the
(start). We just never played aggressive enough or showed any type
of intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets finished with 20 turnovers _ the fourth time in
their past six games they had turned the ball over at least 20
times.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Duncan was a force inside, scoring 23 points, pulling down
14 rebounds and blocking five shots for the Spurs (7-8).
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Hakeem Olajuwon struggled for the Rockets, making
just six of 19 shots to finish with 12 points and 11 rebounds. Like
the Spurs, the Rockets also nudged their way a bit closer to .500
at 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   Cause for concern?
</P>
<P>
   You betcha.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to worry about our intensity lately,'' said Pippen,
who finished with 21 points, eight rebounds and five assists. ``We
haven't come out with any fire or any sense of urgency. We're not
being aggressive enough on offense. It looks like we're back on our
heels, unsure of what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rocket Mario Elie knew exactly what he wanted to do,
getting the Spurs out and running, and getting some revenge on his
former employers, by scoring five of his 15 first-half points in
the 17-3 run that ended the first half, a spurt that gave the Spurs
a 53-37 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a team that entered the game averaging a paltry 87.9
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling it early, and it was really nice to come back to
Houston to play,'' said Elie, who sat out the second half with a
strained left hamstring. ``It was good to see my old buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to pardon the Rockets if they don't feel the same
toward Elie after watching him torch them in the first half. That
first-half pounding earned the Rockets a sustained serenade of boos
as they trudged off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That never makes you feel good, but I don't blame them with
the way we were playing,'' said guard Brent Price of the booing.
``We probably deserved it tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come with our best game faces on, and as Rudy said,
if you can't get up for a game like this with a team you might be
battling in the playoffs, then something's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a game where there's not much to say about it,''
Olajuwon said. ``It was just a terrible game. Period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0110EST &QL; 
