</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCKY STARS GET TIE WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The power play was powerless, the puck- handling
putrid and the defensive lapses laughable.
</P>
<P>
   Last night's 2-2 tie against the New York Rangers was one of the
the Stars' worst performances this season, players said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always heard about the circus here at Madison Square
Garden,'' Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said, ``And I finally got
to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the Dumbo plays and the clownlike bumbling, the
Stars left the venerable Garden with one point. What's so bad about
that?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to get a point,'' Ludwig said. ``At the same
time, we're disappointed we lost a point.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the game was a wash _ a wakeup call that the Stars
are moving down the road and they need to leave the circus tents
behind, along with a limp power play and some bad habits formed by
a week of nonpractice. When the team buses arrive in Long Island
today, they'll have a much-needed practice, coach Ken Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've had one practice in three weeks, and there were
times that we looked like it tonight,'' Hitchcock said of the team
playing its ninth game in 16 nights. ``We had made the decision
that we would focus on nothing but the games and throw all of our
energy into the games, and we have had some success with it. But I
think it's caught up to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' power play was the worst example of bad timing. It
went 0-for-7 and actually hurt the team's momentum. Not only did
the Stars not get chances with the man advantage, they yielded some
of the Rangers' best chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt that we really got \Rcheated\S by the referee,''
Hitchcock joked. ``We felt pretty strongly that he didn't give us
the opportunity to decline all of those power plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all the bad news, the Stars were able to hold off a
sizzling Rangers team and neutralize one of the hottest lines in
hockey _ Petr Nedved, Adam Graves and John MacLean. While Hitchcock
said he felt that line won a chess match with Mike Modano's line,
the final score sheet read one goal for each line. The Rangers'
line had scored five goals on Sunday against the vaunted
Philadelphia Flyers line of Eric Lindros, John LeClair and Keith
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Chip in a hard-working goal for the Rangers' third line and a
well-timed goal (27.7 seconds left in the second period) by the
Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk, and the result was a well-earned draw.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 38-11-10 and keep alive their nine-game (7-0-2)
road unbeaten streak. They have 86 points, 16 better than
second-place Phoenix in the Western Conference. The Coyotes lost a
3-2 game to the Boston Bruins last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, despite a spirited effort, lost ground in their
race for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. With
wins by the Boston Bruins, Montreal Canadiens and Washington
Capitals, the Rangers are four points out of a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Rangers exit a run against the Coyotes, Flyers and
Stars with five out of six points _ and that's a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been nice to get the win,'' Nedved said. ``But I
thought it was a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing he didn't talk to Ludwig, who claimed the Stars made
like a vacuum for much of the darned night _ or words to that
effect. But maybe that's a lesson to be learned, he mused.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the key _ we can play 15 to 20 minutes of a 60-minute
game and still get a point out of it,'' Ludwig said. ``If that
doesn't knock you on the side of the head and tell you that if you
do play well, you're going to get the win, I don't know what
will.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
