<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
 
DiSARCINA TRIES TO COPE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina finished an
interview Tuesday morning in the Tempe Diablo Stadium clubhouse,
and as he walked away mumbled, ``Now I get to go and do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   He is struggling with being away from the team while he recovers
from a broken bone in his left forearm. The injury occurred Feb. 21
when he stepped out of the batting cage and was hit by coach George
Hendrick's bat.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina is wearing a hard cast from his hand to his biceps and
will be examined today by Arizona Diamondbacks physician Dr. David
Zeman. Doctors have told him it'll take four to six weeks for the
bone to heal, but DiSarcina is planning to be ready by Opening Day,
April 6 vs. the Indians at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard right now, just being removed from the
guys,'' he said. ``I firmly believe spring training is the start of
the season, the camaraderie, the championship feeling. I'm lucky in
a way because I already know a lot of the guys well, but when you
bring into the clubhouse guys like Mo (Vaughn) and Tim Belcher,
unless you're on the field with them, it's tough to get a good vibe
with them. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Pumped up: Center fielder Jim Edmonds hit two home runs in
Tuesday's intrasquad game _ one off Shigetoshi Hasegawa and one off
Troy Percival. He also hit one in Monday's intrasquad game.
</P>
<P>
   He said he took two days off after the end of last season and
went straight to the weight room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I take a whole month off, but it drains your energy,''
he said. ``So I thought I'd try something different.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the horn: Belcher started and went two innings in the
intrasquad game. He gave up two runs and three hits, including a
two-run home run by Troy Glaus. ``By no means was the ball jumping
out of my hand,'' Belcher said. . . . Vaughn struck out three times
in the game. . . . Chuck Finley, bothered by a muscle strain in his
back, played catch for about 10 minutes and is listed as
day-to-day. Manager Terry Collins said he hopes Finley will begin
throwing off the mound by the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5523 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     03-03 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO CARES ABOUT THESE BRICKLAYERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It would be easy for someone just moving into this
locale, someone who hadn't been hanging around for the last decade
or so, to believe that folks around here have gifted the Mavericks
with some sort of cushy lifetime pass to be sorry and get away with
it.
</P>
<P>
   No win, no problem, man. Get 'em next year. Or the next. Or the
next. Or whenever. ``Yawn...''
</P>
<P>
   That, pilgrim, would be mistaking numbness for resignation.
There's a distinct difference.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-Dallas is notorious as a winners-only town, and no
one's going to show up on the latest turnip truck from Yankeeville
and try to tell us we've gone soft on the biggest losers in North
Texas professional sports history.
</P>
<P>
   I submit the more than 10,000 empty seats at Reunion Arena last
night as defense exhibit A.
</P>
<P>
   Here the Mavs were, needing only to beat the winless Los Angeles
Clippers to stitch together their first four-game home winning
streak in more than five years, and Reunion Arena looked like it
had been quarantined.
</P>
<P>
   A plethora of empty green seats saw the Mavs dump the Clippers,
112-99, for their fifth victory in their past seven games.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think this little run fools anybody, then you need to
take another look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get the impression that the Metroplex has tolerated
this little `slump' the Mavs have been in,'' TV analyst Bob Ortegel
said before the Mavs lifted their season record to 6-10 after a 1-8
start. ``I think fans here are very frustrated with the situation.
It's just gotten to the point where there's almost nothing more to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the numbness we're talking about. There comes a point at
which the limits of disgust and loathing just can't be pushed any
further. The Mavs are 233-521 in the past decade. No one willingly
accepts that kind of futility, but when you get chafed raw long
enough, you do eventually get calloused.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs have won more than 28 games (36-46 in 1994-95) only
once in the past eight years. It has been nine years since they
last made the playoffs (1989-90), and they were swept in three
games by Portland. They've played host to exactly one playoff game
in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd won three games in a row, and I turned the talk shows on
the other morning on the way to work,'' coach Don Nelson said,
``and we were getting roasted. I didn't get the idea that anybody
was taking it easy on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should they be.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest, I haven't figured out whether Nelson, along with
Pat Riley one of two three-time NBA coach-of-the-year winners, is
savior or snakeoil salesman, the builder of franchises or the
seller of dreams that will never come true.
</P>
<P>
   Is he the basketball genius we so desperately want to believe
in, or is he simply playing on house money with nothing to lose as
he cashes Junior Perot's ample checks?
</P>
<P>
   I'm beginning to fear it's the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I like about Nellie is that he doesn't deny
that he's responsible and if it doesn't happen, it's his fault,''
Ortegel said. ``Sometimes you've just got to ride with a guy. You
get a guy with Nelson's credentials, you tend to stay with him a
little longer than someone with lesser credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   Richie Adubato, Gar Heard, Quinn Buckner and Jim Cleamons, for
instance, may they rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   You can debate, however, whether the Mavs team that was in place
when Nelson arrived _ Sam Casell, Jim Jackson, George McCloud,
Chris Gatling, Eric Montross, Jamal Mashburn _ was a better team
with a better future than the one he put on the court last night.
At least that team had its No. 1 draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson has already traded next year's first-rounder, almost a
lock to be a lottery pick, to Phoenix for disappointing point guard
Steve Nash. Maybe the Suns knew what they were doing when they
listed him third on their depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Not that having a first-rounder is a guarantee that Nelson can
find a player. An accent, sure; a ``game,'' maybe not. Chris
Anstey, a first-round pick out of Australia, rarely leaves the
bench these days. Now he has been joined by struggling Dirk
Nowitzki, the German whiz kid Nelson traded for when he could have
drafted Boston rookie Paul Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I thought \RNowitzki\S would at least be able to
do is score,'' Nelson said. ``We've had to bring him along slower
than I thought we would.''
</P>
<P>
   Salary-cap restraints might even keep Nelson from being able to
keep fast-developing Gary Trent next season.
</P>
<P>
   There's a sense that the Mavs, with Perot willing to let Nelson
do what he wants, are simply waiting until the new arena opens,
hoping that renewed interest then will buy them even more time.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't count on it. The whispers that Tom Hicks will
eventually find a way to add the Mavs to his growing sports empire
grow louder almost daily. There'll be no more free lunch _ not even
for Nelson _ if that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look as positive as I said it was'' before the
season, Nelson agreed. ``We haven't come together as quick as I'd
hoped, but I'm not discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that he does not speak for all of us.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
