A5527 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-T     03-03 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS COMMITTEE WATERING DOWN THE HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Frank Selee?
</P>
<P>
   He died almost 90 years ago. What's the point?
</P>
<P>
   Did the Baseball Hall of Fame's Veterans Committee suddenly dig
up new information on the former Cubs manager that wasn't available
50 years ago to people who actually knew him?
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Hall of Fame has only been in existence for 63
years. Surely if Selee was that deserving, somebody would have made
sure he was enshrined in Cooperstown long ago.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the workings of the Veterans Committee, the Hall of
Fame's version of a mop-up crew, making sure all those oversights
of the Baseball Writers Association of America are rectified.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday the 12-man committee elected four more: Selee (who
probably was an excellent manager), slugging first baseman Orlando
Cepeda, umpire Nestor Chylak and Negro League star pitcher Smokey
Joe Williams, a native Texan born in Seguin.
</P>
<P>
   Enough.
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   No more electing any 19th century players, who have all long
since either gone to a far better place than Cooperstown or to a
place where the Hall of Fame is the least of their worries.
</P>
<P>
   And no more electing 20th century players who were unable to
muster the 75 percent needed in the regular election.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously it's nice when you hear Cepeda say: ``This is the
greatest day of my life. When I first heard it, I started crying,
my wife started crying. It's a wonderful feeling, beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Veterans Committee has long out-served it's original
intent of inducting worthy 19th century candidates, a duty it was
assigned 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's one final mission should be to make sure the appropriate
Negro League stars are considered. Once that's done, the committee
should be finished.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the voting to the baseball writers, who for the most part
are unbiased and much stricter.
</P>
<P>
   Cepeda, even without considering his 1975 drug arrest, was a
borderline candidate. He had a nice career with some outstanding
moments but hardly more sterling than Jim Rice, Dwight Evans, Dave
Parker or many others with similar statistics. None of those guys
are Cooperstown-bound.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball writers aren't perfect. My feeling is they botched
it completely by not electing Gold Glove third baseman Ron Santo, a
mistake the Veterans Committee will probably fix at some point. The
lack of support for catcher Gary Carter is also puzzling.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the writers have set their standards high. The
Veterans Committee almost ruined the Hall of Fame in the 1970s when
Frank Frisch, the former Giants and Cardinals star, became chairman
and elected almost every teammate and drinking buddy from the 1920s
and 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Next time you have the Baseball Encyclopedia out, look up Travis
Jackson and Fred Lindstrom and try to figure out what the committee
was thinking there.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball writers also do a much better job than their
AFL-smitten pigskin counterparts, and the past Football Hall of
Fame election proves that.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Lawrence Taylor controversy. Completely overlooked
was that the voters elected Buffalo Bills guard Billy Shaw, an NFL
reject who starred in the rebel league in the 1960s. But they have
yet to consider Green Bay Packers guard Jerry Kramer, who was a
five-time All-Pro on one of the greatest teams ever.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw should have waited at least as long as Frank Selee.
</P>
<P>
   The Veterans Committee has done well in electing Negro League
stars and non-playing personnel, although Dick Williams remains a
major oversight. The man got the San Diego Padres into the World
Series; what other proof is needed.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to players, the committee has only served to
water down the Hall of Fame with borderline candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Enough is enough.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
