<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND THROWS FROM MOUND WITHOUT PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers closer John Wetteland took a
significant step toward being available for Opening Day, throwing
batting practice yesterday for the first time this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland suffered a soft-tissue injury to his right ankle Feb.
22, when his ankle ``locked'' while he was throwing in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good session out there and showed myself and whoever
else was interested the ability to throw 15 minutes with decent
stuff,'' Wetteland said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider manager Johnny Oates among those most interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good on the mound,'' Oates said. ``As far as the
physical part, he went the full 15 minutes. He threw the ball well,
and he threw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland reported no pain afterward, but swelling restricted
the ankle's range of motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw well, and I felt fine until I took off the wrap and
saw the swelling,'' Wetteland said. ``That puzzles me because it's
around the area that's not injured, and I threw twice as long
\RSunday\S without it swelling. It's not painful at all. There's
just some swelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland appeared encouraged by his workout, in which he threw
all four of his pitches: fastball, curve, slider and changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``What? That's 15 minutes already?'' Wetteland asked after his
final delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Because he's right-handed, Wetteland uses his right foot to push
away from the rubber and drive toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no small-time injury for a pitcher,'' catcher Joey
Goodwin said, ``and he's out there throwing for 15 minutes when I
haven't seen him throw live B.P. this spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, a non-roster invitee to camp who was the Rangers'
bullpen catcher for five months last season, was one of several
hitters who faced Wetteland yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it wasn't John Wetteland's big-league fastball, but
he definitely had something on it,'' Goodwin said. ``He wasn't just
flipping it in there.''
CLAYTON LOOKING FOR WALKS
</P>
<P>
   Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin, whose .383 on-base
percentage led American League leadoff hitters last year, serves as
a model for shortstop Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin dramatically increased his on-base percentage by drawing
a career-high 73 walks, 29 more than his previous best.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton drew a career-high 53 walks in 1998, and the Rangers
want more improvement so Clayton can take advantage of his speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any one thing you want to improve, it's getting on
base, no matter how you do it,'' Clayton said. ``I made some pretty
significant progress for me last year, and I feel it's something I
can improve upon.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will be without three regulars for the exhibition
opener Friday against Cincinnati in Sarasota, Fla. Right fielder
Juan Gonzalez, first baseman Rafael Palmeiro and third baseman Todd
Zeile will remain in Port Charlotte for their workout, along with
reserve infielder Luis Alicea and catchers Gregg Zaun and Cesar
King, manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers excused pitcher Dan Kolb from yesterday's workout to
tend to a personal matter.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
