<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-BOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOOK, LEWINSKY LASHES OUT AGAINST STARR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a book to be published later this week, Monica
Lewinsky is so critical of the independent counsel Kenneth Starr
that several of her friends and associates say they fear that Starr
will become angry and try to revoke her immunity agreement and
prosecute her.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky says in the book, ``Monica's Story'' by Andrew
Morton, that she was so despondent at her treatment by prosecutors
who confronted her at the Ritz-Carlton hotel in Pentagon City, in
suburban Virginia, on Jan. 16, 1998, that she briefly considered
killing herself in their presence, said two people familiar with
the contents of her book.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky is described as being deeply sympathetic to the
president. Immediately after she was confronted by Starr's
prosecutors, Morton writes that Ms. Lewinsky ``said she had this
overwhelming thought: She must warn the President.''
</P>
<P>
   Plato Cacheris, one of Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers, said on Tuesday
night that neither he nor her other lead lawyer, Jacob A. Stein,
had seen the book's manuscript or galleys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monica and Andrew Morton did this on their own,'' Cacheris
said. ``We did not vet the book.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate about how Starr would react.
</P>
<P>
   But several friends of the Lewinsky family said on Tuesday that
they were worried that Ms. Lewinsky's remarks might backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big concern to us,'' an associate of Ms. Lewinsky said
on Tuesday night. ``She's bound by this agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the immunity agreement under which Ms. Lewinsky testified
about her affair with President Clinton and efforts to cover it up,
Starr did not permit Ms. Lewinsky to discuss his office's conduct
in a two-hour interview with Barbara Walters to be broadcast on ABC
on Wednesday night. But Ms. Lewinsky was free to discuss Starr's
office with Morton because her agreement did not apply to the book.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Ms. Lewinsky says that after one of Starr's
prosecutors told her she faced 27 years in jail if she refused to
cooperate with their criminal inquiry of the president, she
contemplated throwing herself out a window on the hotel's 10th
floor, where she stood at the time with several prosecutors, the
people familiar with the book said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky says she ``couldn't bear to go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would come out an old lady and no one would ever want to
marry me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She continues: ``I thought there was no way out other than
killing myself. If I killed myself, then there would be no
information and I wouldn't have to deal with the hurt and the
trouble I had caused the President.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky complains in her book that her efforts to call her
lawyer and her mother were rebuffed by prosecutors and agents.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky said that on Jan. 16, 1998, prosecutors had
confronted her with a copy of her false affidavit in which she
swore that she had not had an affair with Clinton. But at that
time, Ms. Lewinsky's lawyer, Francis Carter, had still not filed
the affidavit yet with a federal court in Little Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has said his office was sent the affidavit anonymously by
James A. Moody, a lawyer for Linda R. Tripp who had obtained it
from lawyers for Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's prosecutors are facing an investigation by the Justice
Department on their conduct in the Lewinsky inquiry, including
whether they had improperly tried to coerce Ms. Lewinsky to
cooperate with their investigation while her lawyer was not present
and had improper contacts with lawyers for Ms. Jones that were not
disclosed to Justice Department lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In her grand jury testimony, Ms. Lewinsky said that after she
told the prosecutors that she needed to consult her mother, Marcia
Lewis, a prosecutor, Jackie M. Bennett, told her: ``You're 24.
You're smart. You're old enough. You don't need to call your
mommy.''
</P>
<P>
   Under her immunity agreement, Ms. Lewinsky is not allowed to
speak with the news media without Starr's permission. For months,
Starr had insisted that Ms. Lewinsky remain silent. Several weeks
ago, he permitted her to speak with Ms. Walters only after
insisting that she not discuss her knowledge of the continuing
investigation or any issues involving Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Charles G. Bakaly III, the spokesman for Starr, did not return
telephone calls on Tuesday night. But in the past, Bakaly has
defended the treatment of Ms. Lewinsky as ethical. In his testimony
before the House Judiciary Committee in November, Starr said Ms.
Lewinsky was incorrect that prosecutors had barred her from calling
anyone she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it clear to the witness that she was, in fact, free to
leave,'' Starr said then. ``And the Ritz-Carlton, shall I say, is a
fairly comfortable and commodious place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
