<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PETERMAN-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEATH OF A CATALOG 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word ``bankruptcy'' has an air of finality, but the reality
often does not. Companies go bankrupt, then re-emerge with former
creditors as the owners. Customers may not even notice.
</P>
<P>
   But such will evidently not be the case with J. Peterman, the
catalog clothing company that gained fame, and hubris, from being
satirized on the ``Seinfeld'' television show. The costs of opening
13 stores, combined with a poor Christmas season, left it short of
money and in bankruptcy. With no buyers having appeared, it has
stopped taking phone orders and its assets will be liquidated in a
court auction on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The J. Peterman catalog never used photographs, instead
combining florid prose with drawings that were none too precise.
Perhaps it was the stark reality of seeing the actual product at
the stores that led to the company's demise. In any case, J.
Peterman has joined a not-very-select group of retailers _
including Korvette's and W.T. Grant _ whose creditors decided they
were worth more dead than alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GOLDWATER-ARCHIE     03-03 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOLDWATER-ARCHIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LIVING ON AT RIVERDALE HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  ( nk ) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 3:
</P>
<P>
   There is no immortality quite like the immortality of the
comics. John Goldwater, the man who in 1941 invented Archie, Betty,
Veronica, Jughead and the other denizens of Riverdale High, died
last Friday at the age of 83. Bob Montana, the artist who gave
those characters faces, died in 1975. Yet life in Riverdale goes
on, updated but otherwise almost unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   True, Veronica now has a column on the Archie Comics Web site,
where you can e-mail her directly, and Reggie has lightened up on
the hair tonic. The girls seem to have a more knowing look than
they used to, as well as more revealing wardrobes. But Archie's
eyes have always popped out of his head at the sight of Betty and
Veronica, and he still seems transfixed by a desire that is only as
deep as his attention span is long.
</P>
<P>
   For 25 years John Goldwater was president of an organization he
helped found _ the Comics Magazine Association of America, whose
Comics Code Authority insured that the comics it certified were as
clean as a table top in the Riverdale Chok'lit Shop that Archie and
his friends frequented. Nobody looks to the comics for realism, of
course, certainly not the 15 million people who buy ``Archie'' each
year. Nor do they buy it because it unleashes fantasies of power,
like the superhero comics. What ``Archie'' offers, instead, is the
fantasy of surviving adolescence, forever. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5543 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACADEMY-AWARDS-2TAKES     03-03 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACADEMY-AWARDS-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARDS ABOUND, BUT THE ACADEMY RULES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With only two weeks to go until the Oscars, my local movie
theater is running a promotional spot for this year's Academy
Awards show. There they are, all the memories _ James Cameron
crowing, David Niven fielding the streaker, Cher winning for
``Moonstruck'' in the bird headdress _ in a pitch meant to trumpet
Oscar's glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the night that brings the whole world together and sets
Hollywood apart!'' the ad exclaims. Since when do we need
reminding?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, America's love-hate relationship with the
most divine of traditional awards shows should mean a red-circled
date on the calendar. Yet each year, the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences comes closer to weakening its franchise and its
hold on our collective imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Little gold gentlemen abound: this very Sunday evening, the
Screen Actors' Guild will be handing out its own Oscar clone (the
Saggy?), a svelte statuette that is now poaching on the academy's
terrain for the fifth year in a row. At least from afar, this looks
like a reasonable alternative. And the Screen Actors' Guild didn't
forget to nominate Joseph Fiennes.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the academy must still be reeling from its
splashiest challenge yet: January's Golden Globe Awards telecast,
in which the year's hottest screen celebrities lit up a rival
television show while thanking the Hollywood Foreign Press
Association from the bottoms of their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the once tacky Golden Globes event has become so
glittery that it's now a serious spectacle in its own right _ even
if the small, starstruck Hollywood Foreign Press Association could
better spend its time explaining why ``Jack Frost'' is a top-10 hit
in Ireland than annointing great artistic achievements of the year.
</P>
<P>
   With substance so easily eclipsed by flashy packaging, we are
fast approaching the time when a glittery television show and a
prize for Gwyneth Paltrow will be enough to guarantee any
award-givers' credibility. But however quickly these back-patting
rituals proliferate, and however interchangeable they become, the
blue-chip status of the Academy Awards miraculously survives.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it's a leap of faith that we still choose to make.
It's a link to the past magic of American filmmaking and the hope,
against heavy odds, that such magic still exists. It's the memory
of fabulous, half-imaginary Hollywood in the face of the workaday
film industry and business as usual. And it's the essence of our
current awards-show fever. None of this copycat hoopla would exist
if the Oscar show itself weren't such an addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Though period pieces _ men with guns and women with handmaidens
_ dominate this year's nominations, Oscar night always works as a
barometer of current attitudes; that remains a large part of its
fascination. We can always look back and head-scratch about what
brought forth the year of ``Gandhi'' or ``Forrest Gump.'
</P>
<P>
   ' And this time we can wonder not so much about the
preponderance of war stories and costume dramas as about the
striking absence of films dealing with contemporary life. Among
this year's various nominees, the few that do grapple with the
present are either fraught with pain (``Affliction,'' ``A Simple
Plan,'' ``American History X,'' ``A Civil Action,'' ``One True
Thing'') or fearful of an Orwellian future (``Pleasantville,''
``The Truman Show''). As the best original screenplay nominee
``Bulworth'' demonstrated, a film that tries to take on
contemporary political or social realities is such a rarity these
days that it's a shock to the system.
</P>
<P>
   Count on the television cameras to seek out Warren Beatty not
only when that screenwriting prize is handed out but also when Elia
Kazan receives his Lifetime Achievement Award. As the director of
``Reds,'' Beatty should be among those whose reactions to that
controversial choice will be most revealing. Outspoken opposition
to this overdue honor for Kazan has already colored this year's
event.
</P>
<P>
   But the facts remain that he is a figure of vast and enduring
artistic influence, one of the visionary directors of this century,
and that acknowledging such work is part of the academy's mandate.
Political censure never has been. It will be an important measure
of the academy's mettle if audience members can make their feelings
known without diminishing the dignity of the evening.
((italics)That(end italics) remains the job of outrageously-dressed
actresses and winners who won't shut up.)
</P>
<P>
   The hard decision to honor Kazan is consistent with other
difficult choices to be made this year. The best picture category
is always a tough horse race, but this year it's a killer. At least
there is one ringer amid such formidable nominees as ``Saving
Private Ryan,'' ``Shakespeare in Love,'' ``The Thin Red Line'' and
``Life is Beautiful'': ``Elizabeth,'' a flamboyant throwback to the
days when academy voters imagined themselves to be edified by
historical spectacle, even though sex, violence, scheming and fancy
royal costuming were really all any audience had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   I have yet to encounter anyone who learned much about England's
16th-century religious wars by watching a saucy young queen with a
gifted hairdresser find her way to the throne.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever hopes there were to pass off ``Elizabeth'' as an
edifying experience should surely have been punctured (despite Cate
Blanchett's intelligent allure in the title role) by the advent of
``Shakespeare In Love.'' In the year when no hit movie lacked a
twin, ``Shakespeare in Love'' was everything that ``Elizabeth''
meant to be, and so much more.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here was beauty with brains: a glittering, splendidly
entertaining film ablaze with wit and romance, and the one that
achieved the year's most amazing feat. Even harder than finding
humor amid the Holocaust or catapulting present-day viewers back to
Omaha Beach was re-inventing Shakespeare as pin-up of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the delights of ``Shakespeare in Love,'' it's
quietly unmistakable that ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the cinematic
achievement of 1998. It was by far the most visceral, moving and
meaningful experience to be had in a movie theater this year, and
the one with the deepest ramifications for those who saw it.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg's rekindling of the all-but-lost values of
patriotism, sacrifice and moral outrage at the savagery of war came
as an enormous surprise, not only because it became an improbable
box office winner but because it refuted all known wisdom about
when and how a film ought to arrive on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   None of the master planners or focus groups who govern the film
industry could have guessed that a ``Saving Private Ryan'' throws
conventional wisdom to the winds. A film this serious and
substantial makes its own rules, and lingers in the memory long
after easier filmgoing experiences have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the long shadow of ``Saving Private Ryan,'' the nominations
for the year's other war epic, ``The Thin Red Line,'' acknowledge a
different kind of honor from the academy. Regardless of whether it
wins prizes, Terrence Malick's comeback film has received the vote
of confidence it deserves and shows how nominations are often ends
in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Other legitimate but left-field choices like Edward Norton for
best actor in ``American History X'' and Roberto Benigni's ``Life
is Beautiful'' in the best picture category deliver the same kind
of prize-free validation.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd-pleasing Benigni is sure to win something, somewhere,
but it's not apt to be in the best actor category either _ not with
Nick Nolte and Ian McKellen so deserving of that award. (Though
arguably Tom Hanks did his best work ever in ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' two-time winners play the Oscar game by different rules.)
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Affliction'' and ``Gods and Monsters,'' for which Nolte
and McKellen are respectively nominated, must be among the year's
least widely seen major films, both are works sure to impress
academy members who do see them. The same is true of ``Central
Station,'' though the performance of Fernanda Montenegro as an
embittered, complicated and heartbreaking character is far and away
the best actress' work I saw last year.
</P>
<P>
   No matter: Gwyneth Paltrow was a breathtaking presence in
``Shakespeare in Love'' and far outshone most of her previous work.
(Her first film appearance, in ``Flesh and Bone,'' remains
indelible.) By all the measures that make Hollywood a dream
factory, she deserves to be crowned an Oscar queen.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Paltrow is, along with the costume designer Sandy Powell
(both ``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Velvet Goldmine''), the closest
this year's Oscar show may come to a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, what a pleasure it is to report that the
documentary category features five strong candidates and is
entirely up for grabs this year. ``Dancemaker'' (about the
choreographer Paul Taylor) and ``Lenny Bruce: Swear to Tell the
Truth'' were both nominated, in a year with many strong
behind-the-scenes films about entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   And both ``Regret to Inform,'' about widows of the Vietnam War,
and ``The Last Days,'' another somberly affecting Holocaust film,
are also in the running. But I'm partial to ``The Farm: Angola
U.S.A.'' and its deeply surprising portrait of no-exit life in a
Louisiana prison.
</P>
<P>
   It does what award-winners should always accomplish: It takes
audiences where they could not otherwise go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
