<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5545 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIAL-FILMS-2TAK     03-03 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIAL-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MILLENNIUM IN PERSPECTIVE, WITHOUT HOOPLA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Karen Durbin is the film critic for Mirabella magazine. Her most
recent article for the Arts and Leisure section was about Liv
Ullmann and Ingmar Bergman.  
 By KAREN DURBIN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Dec. 31, 1999. Jesus arrives in New York with his assistant
Magdalena on his arm and a vexing question on his mind: should he
start the Apocalypse or not?
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, a travel agent invites his closest friends to escape
the millennial hoopla by retreating to a primitive island paradise
off the French coast, only to discover that, freed from the demands
of his busy urban life, he becomes someone he can't stand.
</P>
<P>
   The inhabitants of a serenely beautiful red-clay village in Mali
pass the time visiting, doing chores, listening to the radio and
trying to call distant relatives from the post office telephone.
Desperately poor, they live with the kind of unself-conscious
simplicity that the Parisian travel agent seeks.
</P>
<P>
   These are story lines from ``2000 Seen By,'' a series of roughly
hour-long millennial films from seven countries that opens in New
York on Friday for the first leg of a tour around the country. The
three films described are, respectively, by the American director
Hal Hartley, the French filmmaker Laurent Cantet and the
Mauritanian-born Abderrahmane Sissako, whose family lives in Mali.
</P>
<P>
   The series also includes a smartly silly screwball comedy from
Spain's Miguel Albaladejo; a tale of star-crossed Hungarian lovers
by Ildiko Enyedi (the only woman filmmaker in the group); a darkly
comic dystopia by the Taiwanese director Tsai Ming liang set in a
crumbling, rain-soaked housing project whose inhabitants fall prey
to a mysterious plague, and a politically pointed fable by Alain
Berliner in which Belgium marks the millennium with a vicious civil
war between its two main ethnic groups, the Flemish and the
Walloons.
</P>
<P>
   Portmanteau film projects tend to be traps for second-rate work,
but this collection is an exception to the dismal rule. Ming
liang's ``Hole'' and Sissako's ``Life on Earth'' are the standouts
in the series, but even the least successful films are far from
duds. If Hartley's jazzy-looking ``Book of Life'' is more than a
tad literal-minded, things pick up whenever Martin Donovan's grumpy
Jesus appears on screen in a Brooks Brothers suit with the singer
P.J. Harvey as his punk Magdalene.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the terminal romanticism of Ms. Enyedi's ``Tamas et
Juli'' is redeemed by a bluntly graphic sex scene lighted and
staged with such startling originality that it remains etched in
one's mind long after the rest of the film has faded into one of
the picturesque mists that the director favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``2000 Seen By'' is the brainchild of Carole Scotta and Caroline
Benjo, two young partners in Haut et Court, a French production and
distribution company specializing in independent cinema. The women
struck a deal with Arte, the European cultural television channel,
which provided seed money in exchange for broadcast rights.
</P>
<P>
   To insure the project's global scope, they solicited proposals
from an international roster of directors and selected 10 for
production. (The Brazilian, Canadian and German films broke away
from the series and are being released individually.) The only
full-length feature that remains is ``The Hole,'' at 89 minutes,
with the other six films running 60 to 70 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Like all but the best short stories, movies of less than feature
length can feel like minor work. But the brevity of these films
turns out to have unexpected virtues. With ``The First Night of My
Life,'' for example, Miguel Albaladejo manages to pack eight vivid
characters, an ingeniously complicated plot, stylish visuals and
deft social commentary into little more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when American films have fallen prey to a mystifying
case of bloat, such artistic economy is both a tonic and a
reproach.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the specter of another sort of bloat is invoked
simply by the occasion. Fox Lorber, the series' United States
distributor, is releasing these films now, says Wendy Lidell, a
company vice president, because ``I want to be ahead of the
curve.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be so much of this millennium branding, so
much stuff coming out, I don't know when interest will peak,'' Ms.
Lidell says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The approach of the last millennium triggered mass panic
and the threat of hysterical violence. Today, Y2K glitches aside,
the worst danger we're likely to face is hysterical boredom.
</P>
<P>
   The most overanticipated New Year's Eve in 1,000 years is
threatening to roll in on a tidal wave of conspicuous consumption
and commercial tie-ins. The T-shirts alone may bury us all.
</P>
<P>
   As a subject for a movie, the millennium arrives pre-bloated, at
once too grand and too trivial. On one hand, it seems to demand
work that not only predicts the future but survives it. On the
other, people can't even agree on when it begins (mathematically,
with the first nanosecond of 2001, but viscerally, a year earlier,
when all those nines turn into zeroes).
</P>
<P>
   Like all attempts to fix time, to pin it down and make it stop,
``the millennium'' is an artificial construct, fragile and doomed
to deflate. Once the last horn is tooted, what remains but the
novelty of writing the date with odd-looking numbers?
</P>
<P>
   Most of ``2000 Seen By's'' directors solved this problem with
their own deflationary tactics, treating the subject obliquely and
with humor. ``The concept of the year 2000 was really a pretext to
gather filmmakers together whom we believed in,'' Carole Scotta
says. ``When they submitted their synopses, we were happy to see
that they dealt with the subject in very personal ways.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the most personal film is Sissako's ``Life on Earth.''
Ms. Scotta describes the way he worked. ``Abderrahmane convinced
Arte to let him go to his father's village with an idea but no
script. He stayed for two weeks, taking notes. Then, still with no
script, he went back with a four-person crew. The actress in the
film wasn't planned; this beautiful woman on her bike passed in
front of his camera, and he decided to make her a central
character. Abderrahmane really conceived this film in the
editing.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a movie of such uncommon delicacy and melancholy
grace it looks like the result of months of careful planning.
Deploying a soundtrack that moves seamlessly from a Schubert
quintet to the artful tenor of the great Malian singer Salif Keita,
Sissako weaves his day-in-the-life footage into a compelling lament
for a beloved country impoverished by colonialism and stranded in
time.
</P>
<P>
   The village is African, but French is the only language anyone
speaks: the eloquent French of the anticolonialist Martinique
writer Aime Cesaire (``Do not be a sterile spectator/A screaming
man is not a dancing bear'') being read aloud on the local radio
station, and, finally, the millennial broadcast from Paris,
babbling inanely about the Eiffel Tower as the symbol ``of our
entry into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The villagers, who have all they can do to maintain a shaky
foothold in the 20th, listen carefully, and then pick up their
chairs and go home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
