<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5548 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-03 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN things are going bad _ really bad, like they were for the San
Antonio Spurs before the slump-busting Rockets brushed off the
welcome mat Tuesday night _ everything is magnified.
</P>
<P>
   Every miss looks devastating. Every lazy turnover looks
boneheaded. Every blown play, every flat-footed moment, makes fans
start screaming ``Pig'' even when Anthony Miller is sitting on the
bench in his warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The team is horrible. The coach is a bum. Something needs to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I caused El Nio, and I also tripped Mary Decker,''
Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said of his troubles, which some
believed would have led to his firing today had the Spurs continued
their misery against the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   But Popovich is alive and coaching. The Spurs apparently have a
pulse. Perhaps the more pertinent question is, Do the Rockets?
</P>
<P>
   The troubles that Tuesday's 99-82 Spurs walk over the Rockets at
Compaq Center brought forth need no magnification. They were as big
as a JumboTron, as vexing as a bad vertical hold.
</P>
<P>
   They slapped 16,285 fans in the face. They were real.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like we were playing with strangers,'' Rockets coach
Rudy Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days after the Spurs were run out of their own gym by
Utah in maybe the most humiliating San Antonio effort since Santa
Anna, the Rockets showed every flaw in their increasingly worrisome
game.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every hustle and effort statistic that has for years
been the cornerstone to Rockets glory went San Antonio's way.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive rebounding was again nowhere near adequate, with San
Antonio earning an 18-10 edge. Shooting (41 percent) was miserable
and made to look worse by the Rockets' putting up 20 fewer shots
(95-75) than the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon was 6-for-19 and on a few occasions
uncharacteristically pushed away from his favorite spots on the
baseline and in the lane. Othella Harrington was 1-for-6, Brent
Price 2-for-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets committed more turnovers (19-12) and had more fouls
(20-15), sure signs of a team feeling its way across the floor _
tentative, flat-footed and confused.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a bunch of strangers, as Tomjanovich put it, saying
hello to misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we really need to do is get to know each other,''
Tomjanovich said. ``In this game, practice and organization is
everything. Guys have the freedom to do what they do best. We need
fire. It mystifies me that we don't have it. We were dead.''
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed mystifying, particularly when the opponent was a
team widely considered the most disappointing in the NBA thus far.
It's time to worry.
</P>
<P>
   No longer should the lockout-shortened season be wholly blamed.
No longer should the addition of Scottie Pippen be a crutch. No
more should rookies in key roles, or Olajuwon's adjustment to
playing with Pippen, or the backcourt's still trying to find its
main man, be talked about.
</P>
<P>
   Everything should be talked about. It's time to search for a
cure and fast.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley said he wouldn't go crazy over Tuesday's effort.
It's just one game, he said. But it was one like the bad one
against Atlanta earlier. It was one that only briefly even was
close.
</P>
<P>
   And considering all the troubles the Spurs have experienced and
all the pressure heaped upon Popovich's shoulders, the Rockets now
have lost exactly one fewer game than San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   When Pippen was asked if it's still too early to worry, he
shrugged and hesitated. Then, he stated the obvious: ``No. Not
really. It's not too early to worry. It seems like we're not sure
what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Worry.
</P>
<P>
   It never has been more obvious than Tuesday that uncertainties
and holes are clear. And nowhere is it more clear than in the
much-talked-about backcourt, where the trio of Brent Price, Bryce
Drew and Matt Maloney watched the Spurs' Avery Johnson put on a
scorching performance.
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson finished with 18 points, 13 assists and only two
turnovers, Price finished with six points and only one assist with
four turnovers. Drew was 0-for-4 from the field, and Maloney did
not play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever they put in at point guard, we have to support them
100 percent,'' Barkley said. ``We'll get better. The bad thing is
losing to a bad team.''
</P>
<P>
   But what did it say about the Rockets?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have guys understand that it's just not always X's
and O's,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It's emotion and chemistry. It's got
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's still not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
