<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-20-DATES-FILM-2TAKES-     03-03 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20-DATES-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SINGLE GUY LOOKING FOR LOVE (THROUGH A LENS)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ted Loos' most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
second-generation European film actors.  
 By TED LOOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For his first film, Myles Berkowitz set up his camera
and hoped for the worst. Inspired by Ross McElwee's personal
odyssey ``Sherman's March,'' a funny, rambling first-hand account
of that director's fraught relationship with women, Berkowitz
decided to film a series of his own dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to make a mean, vicious little comedy about
dating,'' said Berkowitz, who at the time was both recently
divorced and professionally stumped in Hollywood. The resulting
movie, ``20 Dates,'' nudges real life along by orchestrating its
humorous situations. Closer in technique to MTV's ``Real World''
than to ``Sherman's March,'' it is cinema verite that has slipped
on a banana peel.
</P>
<P>
   By bending the rules to send up the conventions of romance,
Berkowitz, 36, produced a movie that defies genre labels. ``It's a
screwball romantic comedy, it's a document of single life today,
it's guerrilla filmmaking,'' Berkowitz said recently over dinner in
SoHo, reeling off the possibilities in eager-to-please fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The Groucho Marx-style nose and glasses that Berkowitz wears in
one brief scene would probably not pass muster with the Maysles
brothers, Barbara Kopple or other rigorous documentarians.
</P>
<P>
   ``A documentary to me is putting a camera down and watching real
life happen,'' Berkowitz said. ``And I consciously provoked
situations. I'm a provocateur. So it's not fair to call it a
documentary. But is it real? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the editing room, where 120 hours of film was whittled down
to 88 minutes, there was one rule, said Berkowitz: ``We were going
for laughs.'' The film, which opened in New York on Feb. 26, got
enough laughs at last year's Slamdance festival, the alternative
film festival that has grown up around Sundance, to win its
Audience Award _ and a distribution deal with Fox Searchlight.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have seemed alternately irritated and charmed by
Berkowitz's antic film. ``Ingeniously conceived, `20 Dates' is a
laugh-out-loud chronicle of the struggling filmmaker's hunt for a
girlfriend (and, not incidentally, a cool Hollywood job),'' said
Eric Harrison of The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the focus on comedy allowed the director to include a
tongue-in-cheek cameo by the screenwriting guru Robert McKee, known
for his Story Structure classes. McKee tells Berkowitz, his former
student, that he may be ``incapable of love.''
</P>
<P>
   McKee calls ``20 Dates'' a ``mockumentary,'' a descendant of
``This is Spinal Tap'' and Federico Fellini's ``Clowns.'' And while
Berkowitz doesn't embrace the ``mockumentary'' label, since none of
the material was scripted, he acknowledges the debt. ``Part of the
fun of this movie is wondering whether it's real or not,'' he said.
``It provides a certain energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know him say that Berkowitz is not lacking that
quality himself. ``Myles has tremendous energy _ the kind of drive,
to be fair, that you need to succeed in Hollywood,'' said McKee. On
screen, Berkowitz comes across as alternately annoying and
endearing, an effect he was conscious of at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most obnoxious things about the movies from
first-time filmmakers is that they always try to come off as great
people,'' said Berkowitz. ``Well, you know what? That's not
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in person, erkowitz works to get a laugh. When an unsmiling
waiter at Monzu comes over to take his order, Berkowitz begins
bantering with him, to no effect. Only a story of his own days as a
waiter _ Berkowitz once instructed an obese diner to order a small
dinner salad and got fired for it _ produces a laugh. The filmmaker
almost sighs with relief.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the humor in ``20 Dates'' comes at the
director's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so self-effacing in his way,'' said the film's associate
producer Barbara Cameron, a friend of Berkowitz who provides some
female perspective on camera. ``He makes himself the buffoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Through friends and colleagues, Berkowitz was able to find women
who would agree to be filmed; this was Los Angeles, after all. Some
of the resulting experiences will be familiar to anyone who has
been on the dating front lines: a handshake offered to avoid a
good-night kiss, or the first time holding someone's hand.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But when he tried a hidden camera, the film did produce some of
the viciousness that Berkowitz had originally envisioned. When he
tells one unsuspecting date that she has been on camera all night,
she becomes visibly upset and walks out. By the end of the project,
Berkowitz had fended off two lawsuits; all participants eventually
signed release forms.
</P>
<P>
   In the final version, Berkowitz didn't include anything the
women objected to. Behind the scenes, one of the film's two editors
was a woman, and female friends urged him toward full disclosure.
``Usually, the women said: `Please show that. I went out with jerks
like you and I want to see it!''' said Berkowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the camera caught the one event the filmmaker never
expected. He fell in love with one of the dates, Elisabeth Wagner,
in the middle of the project.
</P>
<P>
   But he also had to finish his film, since his producer _ who
actually thought he was getting a cheap sex comedy _ insisted on
exactly 20 dates. The dilemma, and the way Berkowitz improvises a
solution, provides the momentum for the rest of the film.
</P>
<P>
   This unlikely triumph of love ``came out of a place of total
desperation,'' said Berkowitz, speaking about his career. ``I was
at wits' end.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker, who grew up in Pelham Manor, N.Y., and attended
Horace Mann High School in the Bronx, began his film career acting
in television commercials for Pepsi, Burger King and the Army. That
paid for his undergraduate years at the Wharton School of Business.
He tried acting in New York for a while, and then moved west.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 years before starting ``20 Dates,'' Berkowitz had
found Hollywood success sporadic at best, though he had created and
starred in a short-lived cable show, ``The Beef,'' and had written
for HBO's ``Tales From the Crypt.'' He also took part in
``thousands of meetings'' about film projects that never came to
fruition, in addition to many jobs as a waiter (he didn't get fired
from all of them).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was coming to the time when I had to move on,'' he said.
``I thought: `But I'm not done yet. I'm going to go down
fighting.''' Berkowitz decided to combine, as he says in the film,
``my two greatest failures: my professional and personal lives.''
Shot on videotape with a crew of two, ``20 Dates'' cost about
$70,000 to produce.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Berkowitz realizes that he was not in as much
control of his project as he thought. ``I got lost in this,'' he
said. ``I didn't know what was real and what wasn't. I kept telling
myself, `I am filming my life right now _ with the hope of
eventually having the life I want _ so that I can film things.' I
was so confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wagner provided the film's most potent reality check.
Berkowitz began by chatting up a beautiful woman in a decorating
shop, hoping for a funny, cinematic rejection; they plan to get
married in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``What ended up happening was so much better than anything I
could've written for a Hollywood movie,'' said Berkowitz. ``Now my
movie has a Hollywood ending. Of course, it's hard to believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
