<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5553 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLY-OPERA-2TAKES-$ADV     03-03 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLY-OPERA-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN A LOWLY VAGABOND CAN BE LOVE'S FOOL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal, The Atlantic Monthly and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Verdi's ``Falstaff,'' which preceded it on the boards of La
Scala by nearly three and a half decades, Ermanno Wolf-Ferrari's
``Sly'' plays fast and loose with Shakespeare, in the process
enriching the material almost past recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Falstaff, who marched straight from Shakespeare's quill
onto the Great Stage of Archetypes, Sly is a character even his
begetter promptly forgot. But Giovacchino Forzano, a man of letters
and the theater active at La Scala in the first half of this
century, saw in him untapped potential.
</P>
<P>
   A play resulted, and eventually an opera, which receives its
belated American premiere on Wednesday at the Washington Opera.
Jose Carreras, absent from the American operatic stage since 1987,
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Who is Sly? In ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' a drunken beggar and
occasional tinker. In most modern productions of the play, he never
appears. But in the full text, you will find him in the very first
line, brawling with the hostess, refusing to pay his bill (shades
of Falstaff with Mistress Quickly in ``Henry IV'').
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, he collapses in a stupor. Discovering him thus, a
lord has him transported to the castle, dressed up and, when he
awakens, treated as a nobleman at last restored to sanity after
years of madness. He is reunited with his ``wife'': a pageboy in a
dress. By chance, a troupe of strolling players shows up (shades of
``Hamlet'') and is put to work performing ``The Taming of the
Shrew.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, except for one quick intervention, the few pages of
Shakespeare's framing play break off. A related comedy of obscure
origin, known to scholars of the Elizabethan theater as ``The
Taming of a Shrew'' (``A Shrew'' for short), supplies a few extra
bits of byplay and the predictable conclusion of Sly's
``awakening'' into sober reality (shades of Nick Bottom the weaver
at the close of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'').
</P>
<P>
   For other authors _ Cervantes in ``Don Quixote,'' for instance,
or Calderon in ``Life Is a Dream'' _ tricks like the one played on
Sly set off investigations into existential mysteries of identity
and character. In ``Shrew'' (``The'' or ``A''), it is a joke and
nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, where poetic justice sometimes reigns, when others have
been laughing at his expense, a fellow named Sly should by rights
get to laugh last. But Forzano saw the deception as the cruel setup
for a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   His Sly is scarcely more than a vagabond, lucky when he can stay
one step ahead of the law. An offstage bailiff _ the evil twin, as
it were, of the Night Watchman in Wagner's ``Meistersinger'' _
haunts him in a voice like an ogre's, threatening arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Shrew'' suggests how traumatic such a wretch would find that
prospect. When characters in the play he is watching are faced with
imminent apprehension, Sly stops everything. The stage events are
``in jest,'' his ``servant'' reassures him. ``I say we'll have no
sending to prison,'' Sly insists, unpacified until the script is
altered and the fugitives escape.
</P>
<P>
   But in the opera, poverty is not Sly's sole defining
characteristic. Forzano blesses him with the soul of a poet: but a
sad one, a second Hoffmann condemned to please the alehouse rowdies
with coarse songs it gives him little joy to sing. Secretly, he
longs for a love he knows the world too well to hope for. For love
and also for justice for all: an impossible dream particularly
poignant from one who has nothing.
</P>
<P>
   His Quixotic _ Messianic? _ vision of mounting to the sky
dispensing justice does not materialize. But a classy Dulcinea
comes his way in the person of Dolly, the bored, discontented
mistress of the Earl of Westmoreland, puller of the plot's strings.
</P>
<P>
   Playing along against her will as Sly's wife, she is won by his
innocence and tenderness. The bleak final act takes place in
prison, where through servants Sly is offered the post of
Westmoreland's house poet or buffoon. The party is definitely over:
apart from a single mood-setting chord, the servants sing their
humiliating lines without accompaniment. In despair over his lost
love, Sly slashes his wrists with a broken bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1900 and 1914, while in his 20s and 30s, Wolf-Ferrari
had produced a handful of comedies after Venetian plays of the 18th
century, with music to match. During the subsequent war years, he
fell virtually silent, too shattered to compose. The New Grove
Dictionary of Opera cites the toll on his ``hypersensitive yet
childlike temperament,'' arguing that a ``disturbed state of mind''
is evident in ``Sly,'' particularly in the hero's prison monologue.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such subject matter demanded somber hues. But
elsewhere in the opera, the composer's delight in antique
gallantries is still much in evidence.
</P>
<P>
   By 1927, when ``Sly'' opened at La Scala, long after Strauss'
``Rosenkavalier'' and Stravinsky's ``Pulcinella,'' such pastiche
was no longer fresh. Milan's influential Corriere Della Sera noted
that ``Sly'' ``makes no pretense of modernity.'' But modernity is
not everything, and the reviewer reported a cordial reception,
seconded by his own. Aureliano Pertile, remembered as Toscanini's
favorite tenor, appeared in the title role. Ettore Pa-nizza was the
conductor.
</P>
<P>
   Other productions over the decades have been sparse. Fritz
Busch, pre-Glynde-bourne, led ``Sly'' in Dresden in 1928. The 50s
brought performances in East Germany, under the direction of Kurt
Masur. (Heinz Fricke, who conducts in Washington, appeared in a
minor tenor role.) In 1955, there was a BBC broadcast in English,
with Rudolf Kempe presiding.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To Robert Maxym, an unsung American maestro of surprising
credentials (degrees in history and Russian, research in
psychopharmacology, systems administration at IBM), goes the credit
for the first recording, in German, which documents a staging in
Hanover in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The score came to the attention of Carreras in connection with a
contemplated revival at La Scala, but he came down with leukemia
and the project was dropped. At his request, the Zurich Opera House
staged the work last May.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly available on the Acanta label, the Hanover version
revealed a score as noteworthy for its intricacy of detail as for
its broad, sure emotional sweep. Gorgeous melodies are the better
for being used thematically, gaining depth and meaning as they
recur and vary.
</P>
<P>
   The tavern scenes brim with vigor. Sensory pleasure receives its
due in pages that shimmer, gleam and sparkle. The inner world of
Sly's longings _ inalienable human sentiments to which a cynical
world denies a pauper's right _ glows in more golden, more inspired
hues, lending what in Forzano's text might look like sheer
self-pity a nobler, Virgilian compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Polaski, who has gone on to make an international career
as Brunnhilde, Ortrud and Elektra, lent Dolly the warm, ringing
tones of a gleaming Wagnerian and capped the evening with an
unwritten high C. (Like Sly, this character needs a name more in
line with her nature and her music: Amalia, perhaps, or Leonora.)
</P>
<P>
   Sly's part covers a vast spectrum from abjection to elation, not
excluding humor, pathos and romance. Hans-Dieter Bader filled the
bill handsomely. Klaus-Michael Reeh conveyed the breeding and
brutality of Westmoreland, who knows, like Scarpia, just when to
shed the velvet glove. The chorus, with a major role to play,
played it well; a humming episode, a la ``Madama Butterfly,''
particularly sticks in the mind.
</P>
<P>
   These are lean times for full-length opera recordings, but with
Carreras creating a market, the moment has come for a new ``Sly.''
And from his office in Barcelona, the tenor promised one, on his
calendar for 2000, in Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds better that way,'' said the tenor, whose own first
exposure to the work was through the Hanover recording. (That
``Sly'' has survived principally through German connections would
not have bothered Wolf-Ferrari, whose bloodlines were as much
German as Italian. He lived much of his life north of the Alps; one
of his operas is written in German.
</P>
<P>
   That German houses translated his Italian operas would not have
bothered him, either. It was standard practice, even in Berlin and
Vienna, and the thing was done right. Inevitably, though, German
pulls ``Sly'' in the direction of Strauss and Wagner.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that Carreras, at 52, is leading the way, other Latin tenors
with a streak of morbid romance may well follow. Placido Domingo,
the artistic director of the Washington Opera, revealed last week
that the piece has haunted him for years. He, too, now plans to
sing it on at least two continents, recycling the Washington
production by Marta Domingo, his wife. (A transfer to the Los
Angeles Opera, where Domingo soon takes over as general director,
seems a foregone conclusion.)
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, Carreras, who at this point can speak with the most
experience, characterizes Sly as a lirico-spinto part with strong
declamatory elements, in the manner of Mascagni and Giordano. Which
suggests that Domingo, now 58, might in his prime have worn it like
a glove.
</P>
<P>
   At performances later this month, Washingtonians will see and
hear the American Ian DeNolfo, 31, the winner of the 1996 Lauritz
Melchior Heldentenor Foundation award, with a contract for a
Washington ``Otello'' in his pocket. Sly's days as a forgotten man
may be numbered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
