<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNAKEBIT-THEATER-ART-     03-03 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNAKEBIT-THEATER-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE STUDIES WITH A FAITH IN MUTABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7)  
 (af)  
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The actor David Marshall Grant knows a thing or two
about plays with big messages. His Broadway debut was in ``Bent''
by Martin Sherman, a visceral look at homosexuality and identity in
Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Tony Kushner's sweeping tale of AIDS and
redemption, ``Angels in America,'' in which Grant played Joe Pitt,
the sexually confused Mormon lawyer, for which he received a Tony
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But the writer David Marshall Grant has gone his own subtle,
idiosyncratic way, as can be seen in his first play, ``Snakebit,''
which has just settled in for a commercial run at the Century
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened briefly late last year in Greenwich Village,
Peter Marks, writing in The New York Times, said it was the
``intimate sort of Off Broadway experience that has you picking
apart the recognizable characters long after the curtain calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that you would necessarily want to trade places with the
three main ones, all at various stages of anxiety or depression.
There is Michael (played by Geoffrey Nauffts), a gay social worker
whose lover has just left him for a younger man; Jenifer (Jodie
Markell), an ex-actress whose career has devolved into making ``the
greatest wheatless, dairyless, sugarless brownies in the world,''
except that she is spiking the mix with fructose; and Jonathan
(David Alan Basche), Jenifer's husband and Michael's oldest friend,
a combative actor whose family maxim was, ``Let them hate, so long
as they fear.'' A fourth character who enters late, is played by
Michael Weston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a comedy,'' said Grant, with a grin. ``So much of
suffering is hilarious when viewed at a distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, much of ``Snakebit'' has a tone of bittersweet
autobiography, which the author, 43, acknowledges, particularly
when the specter of disease is raised. Grant's mother suffers from
multiple sclerosis, and he has lost friends to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snakebit'' also has much to do with his feelings about Los
Angeles, where the play is set and where he lived for 12 years
while pursuing a film and television career. He likened the
experience to working in a feudal society. ``If you're not a movie
star, you're a serf,'' he said. ``If your movie doesn't make enough
money, you go to the rack. Unless you hit the jackpot, it wears on
you. You start being conditioned by what `they' like. I felt
sometimes like my identity was being drained from me and replaced
with a cynical effort to please.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant is the third child of two doctors. His older brother and
sister became psychiatrists, while he quickly veered toward
theater. He attended the Yale School of Drama and, in 1979, landed
on Broadway in ``Bent'' at 24. Four years later, he headed for the
West Coast. With blue eyes and a boyish face, he had some success,
landing parts in movies, including ``American Flyers'' (1985),
``Bat 21'' (1988) and ``The Rock'' (1996), and a recurring role as
the artist Russell in the television series ``Thirtysomething.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the early 1990s, he found himself ``falling between the
cracks'' of leading-man roles and those of character actors. He
also wanted to return to New York and the theater. He began writing
``Snakebit'' in 1991 to examine ``the notion of what happens when
something terrible happens to one person and something great
happens to another.''
</P>
<P>
   The first draft took about six months to finish and was staged
in Chicago in 1993 by the actor Campbell Scott. A year later, Grant
and Joe Mantello, who had played his lover in ``Angels in
America,'' took the play to the New York Stage and Film summer
workshop at Vassar College in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., where Mantello
staged it.
</P>
<P>
   Plans were made for a production by the Circle Repertory Company
in 1995, but scheduling difficulties and the company's financial
woes conspired against it. Finally, Ilana Levine, who is playing
Lucy in the Broadway musical ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown,''
brought the script to the theater company Naked Angels, which
agreed to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   The play opened in November to very favorable reviews at the
Grove Street Theater, with Jace Alexander directing.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, like Grant, has been an actor (in John Sayles' film
``Matewan'' and in Stephen Sondheim's musical ``Assassins,'' for
example). The director said the fact that Grant had acted made him
flexible: ``A writer who is not experienced will hold onto his text
for dear life. David understood that cutting is part of the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   So are changes. Grant said there has been a shift in the play's
philosophy. In earlier versions, Michael, the social worker, was
the hero, a victim of heartless love interests and thoughtless
friends. But eventually, Grant said, he began to feel that
Michael's plight was being romanticized: ``Michael's very much
stuck in his identity as a victim. And he has so internalized the
unfairness around him that he has begun to lose his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, Grant made a small change in the final
scene, giving Jonathan, the impatient actor, a speech that Grant
said changed the play's message from ```Oh, look, life's so unfair'
to `Oh, look, life's so unfair _ what are we going to do about
it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Mantello, who has known Grant for nine years, said: ``David
honestly believes you can make things better. He's earnest almost
to a fault. He's not anybody's poodle, but he'll give people the
benefit of the doubt, even if they don't deserve it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5556 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSI-FAN-TUTTE-OPERA-     03-03 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSI-FAN-TUTTE-OPERA-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE TITLES, `COSI' BECAME `WOMEN ARE LIKE THAT'  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many Mozart experts and opera buffs will no doubt dismiss a
recent release of ``Cosi Fan Tutte'' from Sony Classical with a
knowing huff. It is a reissue of a 1952 recording, with Fritz
Stiedry conducting the orchestra and chorus of the Metropolitan
Opera Association, as it was then called (Masterworks Heritage MH2K
60652; two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Stiedry, who was born in Austria, was an eminent opera
conductor. And the cast would seem to be impeccable. Eleanor
Steber, one of the most acclaimed Mozart sopranos ever, and the
respected mezzo-soprano Blanche Thebom are the sisters Fiordiligi
and Dorabella.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrando and Guglielmo, the self-absorbed suitors of those
endearingly inconstant women, are sung by Richard Tucker, in his
tenorial prime, and the beguiling baritone Frank Guarrera. The
soprano Roberta Peters, captured in her early days as a
fresh-voiced soubrette, is the clever maid Despina. The robust bass
Lorenzo Alvary sings the cynical bachelor Don Alfonso.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Mozart's opera, written in Italian, is performed in English.
``Cosi Fan Tutte'' becomes ``Women Are Like That.'' And the
recitatives are accompanied not by a historically appropriate
harpsichord or fortepiano, as they would be today, but by a modern
piano.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, to listeners who have become accustomed to the
lighter, lyric voices favored in Mozart recordings in recent
decades, Tucker, with his Radames-size tenor, may sound amusingly
old-fashioned. And although Stiedry conducts a shapely, unmannered
performance, he allows the singers no freedom to add embellishments
to their melodies, even where, as historians now realize, Mozart
clearly intended them.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the score is cut: not just occasional bits of
recitative but also entire arias, including two of Ferrando's in
Act II.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the recording is a joy. The pleasure comes partly from
nostalgia. For American opera audiences in 1952, ``Cosi Fan Tutte''
was still on the margin of the repertory. This recording represents
an attempt by a mostly American cast to make the work come alive
for American listeners. Thus the use of English translation.
</P>
<P>
   Singers sing more communicatively when they know that listeners
understand what they are singing about. And listeners listen more
attentively when the text is in their native tongue. All of that is
obvious, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. The coming of titles to the opera house has changed
everything. By and large, American audiences embrace them as a
workable solution to a longstanding problem: how to present a
foreign-language opera as it was conceived yet make it
comprehensible to an English-speaking audience.
</P>
<P>
   The main drawback of titling is a division of attention, as you
try to immerse yourself in a musical-dramatic performance while
reading projected texts. But surely, the current boom in opera's
popularity in America is due in large part to titles, which are
especially helpful in less familiar repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Met's presentation of a talky, discursive opera like
Strauss' ``Capriccio'' last season have been as popular without
titles? It's doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   But the emergence of titling has meant the demise of the honored
tradition of performing opera in translation. Purists, of course,
have always howled in protest at the practice of translating texts
lovingly set to music. It's a travesty, they say; it negates the
nuances the composer devised to support and, in a sense, transport
the original words. And it is true that to accommodate existing
music, a translator has to refashion the words completely, with
results that can be stilted and sometimes silly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the awkwardness has to be measured against the increased
immediacy that results when an audience hears a work in its own
language. And those who argue that translating a libretto violates
a composer's intention have no historical leg to stand on. For
pragmatic theatrical creators like Verdi and Wagner, the idea of
routinely performing operas in languages audiences did not
understand would have been unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   True, Verdi did not have ``Aida'' translated into Egyptian for
its premiere in Cairo. In this unusual instance, he undoubtedly
assumed that Egyptians wanted the exotic experience of hearing a
genuine Italian opera. But when ``Don Carlos,'' a grand opera in
French written for the Paris Opera, was presented in Italy, Verdi
revised it in Italian translation.
</P>
<P>
   And though Wagner fretted constantly about the quality of
translations when his operas were performed in France, he never
questioned the necessity of translating them.
</P>
<P>
   Though Mozart found the Viennese public's taste for Italian
opera a bit odd, he complied with it. (It wasn't all that odd,
actually, since in Mozart's day Vienna was overrun with Italian
musicians and, musically, practically a bilingual city.) But when
he had a chance to write a German work for a German house in
Vienna, he leapt at it, as with ``Die Zauberflote.''
</P>
<P>
   No one would assert that performing opera in English translation
for American audiences is always preferable. But it is a valid and
rewarding alternative, and there should be a place for it. One of
my fondest early musical memories is of sitting in the fourth row
at the New York City Opera for Mozart's ``Marriage of Figaro'' in
English, with an American cast topped by a young soprano named
Catherine Malfitano and an emerging bass named Samuel Ramey.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Opera Theater of St. Louis is one of the few
companies in America that perform operas with non-English librettos
exclusively in English translation. The English National Opera
upholds the tradition abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The American soprano Phyllis Curtin, a renowned voice teacher
and a longtime advocate of opera in English, stresses the value of
the practice particularly for students. ``If you are trying to
learn to act in a language neither you nor your audience
understands, you become generalized,'' she said recently. ``And
nothing in art should be general.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Curtin had many memorable experiences performing opera in
the language of the audience in some of the world's foremost
houses, including ``Cosi Fan Tutte'' in Vienna. In the 1950s, it
was customary there to do Mozart's Italian operas in German
translation. But mostly due to the influence of the conductor (and
self-appointed Austrian cultural czar) Herbert von Karajan, Ms.
Curtin said, the practice was discontinued, and the Mozart operas
were presented in Italian.
</P>
<P>
   The results were dismaying, she added, even when her partners
included long-celebrated Viennese artists like the tenor Anton
Dermota and the bass-baritone Erich Kunz.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their 60s Dermota and Kunz sounded fresher than most
singers in their 30s,'' Ms. Curtin said. ``And they were wonderful
and funny actors. But after we switched to Italian, all of a
sudden, because the Viennese audience didn't understand them in the
same way, these two consummate artists started acting like the Marx
Brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Titling systems are credited with lessening the penchant for
exaggerated acting that has long characterized opera when performed
in languages foreign to audiences. Now singers can be subtler. But
here, too, Ms. Curtin believes, there remains a downside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The titles can't be read fast enough,'' she said. ``So someone
may glance up or glance down just at the moment of a singer's
lovely, fresh or important gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the main reason for singing opera in English
translation has less to do with the shortcomings of titling systems
than with the heightened quality of communication that can result,
as this reissued recording of ``Cosi'' makes abundantly clear.
</P>
<P>
   From the first scene, with Ferrando and Guglielmo baited about
the constancy of their sweethearts by Don Alfonso, the performance
pulls you in. The translation used is by the veteran team of Ruth
and Thomas Martin. Ferrando's jaunty first utterance _ beginning,
``La mia Dorabella capace non e'' _ becomes: ``To doubt Dorabella
is simply absurd! Completely absurd! She'll always be faithful and
true to her word!'' Not Tom Stoppard, but it's cute, bouncy and
singable.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker and Guarrera deliver the text with crisp, clear
enunciation. Obviously, it's easier to project the text in a
recording situation. A frequent complaint about opera in English
translation is that the words cannot be understood from the stage,
especially in huge houses, a problem that has been compounded over
the years because opera singers have so few opportunities to
acquire skill for singing in English. And audiences, for their
part, have grown unaccustomed to paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   I have often been exasperated by lazy singers with
incomprehensible English diction. Yet often in such situations, one
member of the cast will make every word completely clear. So it can
be done, and this recording shows how involving the results can be.
</P>
<P>
   Even Alvary, who sings Don Alfonso with a pronounced Italian
accent, does a fine job of making the English text clear.
</P>
<P>
   Steber is marvelous, though devotees of the opera will have to
adjust. In the great aria ``Come scoglio,'' where Fiordiligi
describes her faithfulness as unassailable, like a fortress, the
English words are startling: ``Strongly founded, a marble tower,''
the first line is rendered here.
</P>
<P>
   But the inflated poetic tone of the words actually captures the
comic implausibility of the moment: whom is she kidding, you ask?
And one senses Steber's excitement at the chance to bring what was
then a connoisseur's opera to the larger record-buying public.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's ardent singing will not meet everyone's idea of
Classical style, but it is beautifully phrased and vocally
splendid. Ms. Peters makes a spunky Despina, and her English
diction is a model of clarity. Blanche Thebom brings vocal richness
and musical integrity to the role of Dorabella. The use of a piano
to accompany the recitatives is refreshing, a sort of unstuffy,
American way of making sung operatic dialogue sound up-to-date.
</P>
<P>
   The one major drawback is the cutting of the score, especially
regrettable in a recording. This performance essentially documents
an acclaimed 1951 Met production, in English, directed by Alfred
Lunt.
</P>
<P>
   The few cuts were deemed helpful to the dramatic pacing of the
evening. And the impact of a staged performance comes through
vividly here. That immediacy was the point of this important
recording, and remains its great attraction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
