<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-VICTIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIMS SOUGHT THE EXOTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With UGANDA-KIDNAP) (sw) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American couple killed in the Bwindi Impenetrable Forest in
Uganda on Monday had been so captivated by the idea of going to see
rare mountain gorillas that they persuaded another couple to
accompany them.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Haubner, 48, and Susan Miller, 42, the two Americans who
were among 12 people killed in an attack by Hutu rebels, had been
executives for the Intel Corp. since the mid-1980s. They were based
in Hillsboro, Ore. The trip to Africa was their third, including
their honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went last year, enjoyed it very much, but didn't get to
the country where the gorillas were last year. This year they were
hoping to do that,'' said Rita Studd, the mother of Susan Studd,
46, who survived along with Bob McLaurin, 44.
</P>
<P>
   Awakened by gunfire, they fled their tent and hid. On Tuesday
they were in Kampala deciding whether to fly back with the bodies
of their friends, Ms. Studd's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   The family of the victims issued a statement saying, ``We are
shocked by this news and we are trying to cope with this
devastating situation as best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the driveway of the couple's suburban home
overlooking Portland was jammed. Stunned friends and relatives
gathered inside. Haubner had a grown son from a previous marriage
who lives in Portland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
