<HEADER>
A5585 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEATHDRUG-DOCTOR-SFCH     03-03 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHDRUG-DOCTOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NORTHERN CALIFORNIA DOCTOR CHARGED WITH MURDER IN DRUG DEATHS  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  REDDING, Calif. _ Medical providers in the Shasta County area
are reeling in the aftermath of drug-related charges of murder and
fraud brought against Dr. Frank Bensell Fisher.
<P>
   Fisher ran a controversial clinic in the town of Anderson that
specialized in treating chronic pain. He was arrested February 18
along with Redding pharmacy owners Stephen and Madeline Miller.
</P>
<P>
   They are being held at Shasta County Jail, with Fisher's bail
set at $15 million, on three counts of murder and two dozen other
charges stemming from an alleged conspiracy to bilk the Medi-Cal
state health insurance system. They are expected to appear
Wednesday before Superior Court Judge James Ruggiero, when pleas
may be entered.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say the conspiracy netted more than $2 million in
bogus Medi-Cal claims for potent painkillers. Fisher, at the core
of the alleged scheme, is said to have recklessly prescribed potent
narcotics at high dosages to people who had no medical need for the
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, he had a huge caseload of some 3,000 patients,
running as many as 400 people a week through his Westwood Walk-In
Clinic in downtown Anderson. Besides the three alleged murder
victims, officials are looking into at least three other possible
drug-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is not the first pain doctor to land in legal troubles
for prescribing high doses of opiates.
</P>
<P>
   But medical and legal experts say he appears to be the first in
California, and possibly the country, to face multiple counts of
murder in connection with prescribing narcotics, in particular a
slow-release form of opiate painkiller called OxyContin.
</P>
<P>
   During an exclusive interview with The Chronicle last week at
Shasta County Jail, Fisher, 45, denied any wrongdoing, saying he
ran a legitimate medical practice that specialized in treating
intractable pain suffered by an underserved, mostly low-income
clientele.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say it was all done for the money. And Fisher
admitted his practice may have cleared some $200,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   However, circumstances of the deaths he is said to have caused
raise questions about some key aspects of the prosecution's case.
Interviews with several of Fisher's patients and other pain
specialists showed that he is not without supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the guts to stand up to the system for people like
us,'' said Teresa Hignite, 28, of Redding, a student and mother of
two whose family received Medi-Cal-subsidized care at Fisher's
now-closed Westwood Walk-In Clinic in Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her husband, whom Fisher had on a regimen of
high-dose opiates to control the pain left by a San Diego freeway
accident 10 years ago, Hignite is among several hundred people now
scrambling to find an alternative source of medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Working late one night last week at the Shasta Community Health
Center in Redding, medical director Ann Murphy called it ``a
calamity, a disaster on the scale of a natural disaster, like an
earthquake.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people have contacted local medical centers
seeking help. A few have shown up at emergency rooms in acute
withdrawal from high-dose opiate regimens Fisher had prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Millers shut down, other local pharmacies have
been reluctant to prescribe narcotics even when the drugs are
ordered by other doctors trying to wean people off the medications.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the alleged murder victims _ Bruce Johannsen Jr.,
19, Rebecca Mae Williams, 34, and Tamara Stevens, 38 _ died with
what investigators considered to be high levels of oxycodone, the
active ingredient in OxyContin, in their system.
</P>
<P>
   However, determining the exact cause of the deaths may be
complicated by the very fact that all three apparently were used to
taking strong doses of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Pain specialist Harvey Rose of Sacramento, who has survived
scrapes of his own with drug-enforcement authorities, noted that
long-term narcotic use builds tolerance to effects that typically
can kill someone taking the medication for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   He said that even while he was troubled by Fisher's high-volume
style of operating, it was not necessarily wrong to prescribe high
dosages as long as care was taken to document that the drugs were
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say there is no upper limit that can be considered toxic
for all patients. Doctors are supposed to start with a low dose,
then work up until symptoms are relieved with the least severe side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   Other questions arise concerning some of the circumstances of
each death:
</P>
<P>
   -- Williams was found dead in August with severe head trauma
after a vehicle accident. She had been the passenger in a pickup
truck that crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Forensic pathologists said that the woman was already dead or
dying when the accident occurred and that the real cause of death
was a ``lethal level'' of oxycodone they found in her blood.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pathologists, Dr. Gregory Reiber, readily conceded
during a telephone interview that it was impossible to pinpoint the
exact time of death. He said the drug was ``inferred'' as the cause
based on the blood concentrations, along with indications that the
head injuries, although massive, caused relatively little bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   -- Johannsen, who died last July, is listed as having choked on
vomit ``due to oxycodone intoxication.'' However, there is no
indication that he had been a patient of Fisher's for several weeks
leading up to the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, backed by members of his staff, said he had booted
Johannsen out of his practice for suspected drug misuse. Although
specifics could not be confirmed, several people said Johannsen was
getting controlled substances from street sources when he died.
</P>
<P>
   -- Stevens, the third alleged murder victim, was initially
considered to have been a suicide, although her husband, Robert
Stevens, said Tuesday that he did not believe she deliberately
overdosed.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he did not believe Fisher was responsible for his
wife's death in September. Stevens said that she had many serious
health problems and that he felt certain she died of natural
causes, not the drugs she was taking.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the forensic report shows she had prescriptions for
a number of opiates and other medications at her disposal. She is
said to have overdosed on a combination of these drugs, although
none showed up at levels individually high enough to explain death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
