A5592 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEPLER-MANUSCRIPT-SFC     03-03 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEPLER-MANUSCRIPT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ANCIENT HOROSCOPE FOUND AT UC-SANTA CRUZ  &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CRUZ, Calif. _ An astronomer burrowing in the library at
the University of California at Santa Cruz has stumbled upon a
400-year-old horoscope handwritten by Johannes Kepler, the
astronomer who discovered the fundamental laws of planetary motion.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Misch, an astronomer at UCSC's Lick Observatory atop
Mount Hamilton near San Jose, was researching in the university's
library not long ago and found a framed piece of ancient paper,
scrawled like chicken tracks with symbols, diagrams and some words
in German.
</P>
<P>
   In his spare time, Misch is a book collector, and he knows
German, so after puzzling over the mysterious paper, he realized
what he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty thrilling moment,'' he said in a university
report released Tuesday. ``I knew right away this had potential to
be a pretty spectacular discovery. As I looked the document over,
my hand was shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   One bit of the writing said in German that it was ``written in
the hand of Kepler, from the collection of Kepler Manuscripts in
Pulkovo.'' Pulkovo is an observatory founded near St. Petersburg,
Russia, nearly 200 years ago, and the inscription was signed ``W.
Struve'' and dated May 13, 1864.
</P>
<P>
   Friedrich Georg Wilhelm von Struve was then the director of the
Pulkovo Observatory and founded a dynasty of distinguished
astronomers that ended with his great-grandson, the late Otto
Struve, a radio astronomer who discovered matter in interstellar
space and calculated the existence of planets far beyond the solar
system.
</P>
<P>
   The rare Kepler document records the birth of an Austrian
nobleman named Hans Hannibal Hutter von Hutterhofen, who was born
Sept. 10, 1586, at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Kepler's accomplishments have long ranked him as equal to
Copernicus and Galileo, but in the 16th century, astronomers often
had to moonlight to make a living, and Kepler _ a phenomenal
mathematician _ apparently drew up elaborate horoscopes for wealthy
clients, even though he didn't believe in astrology.
</P>
<P>
   Misch traced the records of the Kepler manuscript and found that
it had been bought in Germany for the Lick Observatory in 1896. He
sent it to a Berlin firm specializing in old manuscripts, and it
was authenticated by the company, whose archives hold another copy
of a Kepler horoscope. The nobleman's fate, as limned in the Zodiac
signs as interpreted by Kepler, now lies in the university library
at Santa Cruz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
