A5601 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HP-SPINOFF-SFCHRON &LR;      03-03 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HP-SPINOFF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HEWLETT-PACKARD TO SPLIT INTO TWO COMPANIES  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hewlett-Packard Co., the Silicon Valley pioneer
whose growth has slowed while other technology giants have
prospered, said it will split off its noncomputer business into a
separate company and replace chief executive Lewis Platt.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, announced Tuesday, are the most wrenching in the Palo
Alto company's long and storied history. They suggest that Hewlett
Packard's hands-off management style and progressive workplace
practices may not cut it in the fast-paced Internet environment
that Silicon Valley has become.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford engineering students William Hewlett and David Packard
started their company in a garage in 1938. Hewlett-Packard's nearly
unremitting success turned the company into the world's
second-largest computer maker and gave an aura to its corporate
culture, known simply as ``The HP Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a bid to boost its profits and stock price, the company
plans to separate its original business _ measurement equipment for
the semiconductor, telecommunications and medical industry _ from
its giant computer and printer operations, which accounted for 85
percent of its $47.1 billion in revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-and-printer company will keep the name
Hewlett-Packard. A name has not yet been chosen for the new
measurement business, which will be run by its current general
manager, Edward ``Ned'' Barnholt.
</P>
<P>
   The measurement company, with annual sales of about $7.6
billion, probably will be spun off in a public offering later this
year. Hewlett-Packard is considering selling about 15 percent of
the new company's shares to the public and distributing the rest to
its stockholders. It would be the largest initial public offering
in Silicon Valley history. Hewlett-Packard officials expect no
significant workforce reductions as a result of the split.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcements drew polite applause from Wall Street,
which pushed the firm's stock up $2.75 a share to $68.63.
</P>
<P>
   Investors hope that Hewlett-Packard's move could parallel the
success of AT&AMP;T's spin-off of Lucent Technologies, the
telecommunications equipment maker. Lucent raised $3 billion in a
public offering in 1996 and has been a resounding success, posting
nearly $1 billion in earnings last year on revenues of $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Platt, who has run Hewlett-Packard since 1992, will continue as
chairman, president and chief executive officer until the spin-off
is complete and a successor can be found. He said it was his
decision to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm approaching my 58th birthday, and that makes now the
appropriate time to begin planning for my successor,'' he said.
Hewlett-Packard's customary retirement age is 60.
</P>
<P>
   Platt, along with board members Sam Ginn and Richard Hackborn,
will search inside and outside of Hewlett-Packard for a new CEO.
Leading internal candidates include Ann Livermore, who runs the
company's new online commerce business, and Carolyn Ticknor, who
heads the LaserJet printer division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ann Livermore is someone who has been really pretty visible
over the last year and is certainly well thought of,'' said Tony
Scott of the A.T. Kearney executive recruitment firm in Redwood
Shores.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said internal candidates are likely to have an edge,
although Hewlett-Packard could look for an alumnus. One possible
candidate is Richard Belluzzo, who was heir apparent to Platt
before leaving Hewlett-Packard to become CEO of Silicon Graphics
last year.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Hewlett-Packard's board said that Platt has
been a driving force behind the company split and is not being
forced out. ``This is his choice, and that's the real scoop,'' said
the source, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Platt said the move is designed ``to sharpen the strategic focus
of our businesses, improve their agility and increase their
responsiveness to consumers and partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving quickly has not been Hewlett-Packard's forte in recent
years. Because it is decentralized, with each main business unit
semiautonomous, the company has been unable to respond rapidly to
changing market conditions. Most notably, it has failed to cash in
on the Internet the way IBM and Sun Microsystems have.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hewlett-Packard has had difficulty reining in
expenses, despite salary cuts for top managers, a cutback on
corporate travel and shutting down the entire company for two weeks
in December.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard also has suffered from cutthroat price wars in
the market for personal computers and printers, as well as from the
economic downturn in Asia, which torpedoed its measurement
business.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's profits last year declined 6 percent from the
previous year to $2.9 billion. And revenues increased only 10
percent to $47.1 billion in a banner year for many technology
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's stock also has been flat for the past year.
Its first-quarter earnings beat expectations, but the company
expects only a modest increase in sales for the rest of this fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Steve Dube of Wasserstein Perella in New York said the
split-up was long overdue. Platt, he said, should not have to
oversee $7.6 billion a year in noncomputing business when he has a
$39 billion computer company to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``HP's been a computing company for over a decade, and it should
be run as a computer company,'' Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Bruce Raabe of Collins &AMP; Co. said it's wise to separate
the computing and measurement operations, because they have
different customers and distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, this move will be good for the shareholders,
because it will allow the market to value those businesses
separately,'' said Raabe.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Hewlett-Packard may have been reluctant to split off
the measurement business is that it represents the origins of the
company. Hewlett-Packard's first product was an audio oscillator.
The fledgling company sold eight of them to Walt Disney, who used
them in making the film ``Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent financial woes, Hewlett-Packard's measurement
businesses are leaders in their respective fields and are expected
to bounce back as the Asian crisis stabilizes.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts speculated that Hewlett-Packard in effect is
putting its measurement business up for sale. ``I wouldn't be
surprised in some of the medical and test and measurement
businesses if people came out of the woodwork'' to make offers,
said Daniel Kunstler of J.P. Morgan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
