<HEADER>
A5716 &Cx1f; tab-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-ADVISORY-NYTSF     03-03 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Tai Chi for seniors' blood pressure ... Women's health exhibit
has some surprises ... Acupuncture and back-pain relief ...
Screening for colorectal cancer ..... Possible link between
C-sections and allergies ... Significance of thallium stress test.
</P>
<P>
   Here are summaries of the MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE stories
sent to subscribers for use on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like sales information for your newspaper or Web site,
please call The New York Times Syndicate at 800-535-4425 or e-mail
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS MAY NOT NEED TO WORK UP A SWEAT to knock down their
blood pressure. Tai chi, an ancient Chinese exercise, is just as
effective in reducing blood pressure as aerobic workouts, according
to a study in the latest issue of the Journal of the American
Geriatrics Society. (TAI-CHI-MED -- 500 words)
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S THE LEADING CAUSE OF DEATH AMONG WOMEN? The answer, which
may surprise many people visiting a new museum exhibit in Baltimore
devoted to women's health, is heart disease. The exhibit, ``The
Changing Face of Women's Health,'' is designed to provide
information on women's health. It opened Tuesday at the Maryland
Science Center, and will tour science museums across the United
States until 2003. It gives visitors a hands-on way to look at some
of the major health issues facing women. (WOMENS-HEALTH-MED -- 650
words)
</P>
<P>
   A TREATMENT BASED ON CHINESE ACUPUNCTURE is the key to unlocking
chronic pain in the lower back, according to a new study. The
results of the study, published Wednesday in the Journal of the
American Medical Association, could sway even those doctors who
have reserved skepticism about the effectiveness of non-Western
treatments. Unlike preceding studies, this one contrasts the
effects of the treatment with placebo, giving the results a
scientific edge previously lacking. (BACK-PAIN-MED -- 700 words)
</P>
<P>
   A LARGE STUDY HAS FOUND that annual screening for colorectal
cancer could cut deaths from the disease by one-third. Colorectal
cancer is the second leading cause of death among cancers
nationwide, killing more than 56,000 people every year. The
American Cancer Society recommends annual colorectal-cancer
screening for people older than 50, but fewer than half of people
in this age group undergo the test. (COLORECTAL-CANCER-MED) -- 500
words)
</P>
<P>
   THE WAY A BABY IS DELIVERED may affect his or her odds of
developing allergies, according to preliminary research presented
at the allergy conference in Orlando on Tuesday. In the past two
decades, rates of allergies have been on the rise. During this same
period, the number of elective Caesarean-section deliveries has
increased as well, leading Finnish researchers to suspect that
there might be some link between the two trends. (ALLERGY-NEWS-MED
-- 350 WORDS)
</P>
<P>
   DR. ERIC ANDERSON ANSWERS HEALTH QUESTIONS. This week:
</P>
<P>
   -- Are there exercises to correct the curvature of the upper
back caused by childhood kyphosos?
</P>
<P>
   -- How significant are results of a thallium stress test?
(HEALTH-ADVICE-MED -- 500 words)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about our features, visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate.)
</P>
