<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIE-40-HNS &LR;      03-03 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-40-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBIE: LORDY, LORDY, LOOK WHO'S 40! 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over second e in Renee byline) 
 
By RENEE KIENTZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ She was born Barbie Millicent Roberts, springing into
the world fully grown, like Venus rising from the sea. Shapely,
wrinkle-free, with pouty lips and pert breasts, and hair that
flipped just so, Barbie began her reign in controversy: Some moms
thought her just a bit too developed. She was a doll, for goodness
sake.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, long after the little girls who made her the
world's best-selling fashion doll grew up to raise daughters of
their own, Barbie still is pert and perky with nary a sag or laugh
line. No control-top hose, no Lasting Color, no reading glasses for
this perennial spring chicken. She's still fresh and fine, changing
hairstyles, designer duds and careers like an ingenue with the
world at her pointy little feet.
</P>
<P>
   She's still controversial, too.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you believe, the foot-high vinyl bombshell is
an inspirational symbol of girl power or the black hole of feminine
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   She's a toy or she's a totem to materialism.
</P>
<P>
   She represents the best of America _ bright, beautiful, an
amazing success story (1 billion sold!). And the worst _
superficial, perennially immature, unable to commit to career or
long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A LITTLE HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's official birthday is March 9, 1959. The date marks her
introduction to the world at the New York City American Toy Fair.
Barbie No. 1 wore a black-and-white-striped bathing suit, had
arched come-hither eyebrows and holes in her feet (the better to
stand her up, my dear). She came blond or brunette.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Handler, Barbie's mom and co-founder of Mattel, the company
that Barbie built, was convinced that dolls with adult features
would spark girls' imaginations. That they'd want to dress them in
myriad outfits, create little fantasies around them. Ruth was
right. And the rest, as they say, is herstory.
</P>
<P>
   Ken, by the way, came along in 1961. Barbie needed someone to
escort her to the prom, someone who could look good in a tux. Can't
have a beautiful bride without a groom, even if he was a dud.
</P>
<P>
   Kandy Ferriby, owner of the Doll Company in Spring, Texas,
sounds dismissive when she says Ken was and is ``just an accessory
to Barbie. He's just another possession for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferriby says vintage Barbies go for hundreds of dollars, even
thousands. Ken? How's 30 bucks sound?
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Mattel has produced battalions of Barbies and
Barbie spinoffs besides Ken _ little sisters, friends and pets, to
say nothing of townhomes, dream homes, country homes _ and none
hold a candle to Barbie as icon or industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONEY, HONEY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Barbie brought $1.9 billion home to Mattel. Not bad for
a one-time fashion model who can't hold a job. She makes millions
more for retailers like Target and FAO Schwarz and for dealers who
sell her likeness online and off.
</P>
<P>
   Log onto eBay, the online auction house, search the keyword
``Barbie,'' and watch a listing of 7,000-plus items unfold before
you. A virtual Barbie mall. Christian Dior Barbie! Portrait in
Taffeta Barbie!! Mint! Barbie as Scarlett set (with Ken as Rhett)!
</P>
<P>
   Off-line, there are doll shows, Barbie-only auctions, clubs and
boutiques. Ferriby estimates her all-doll consignment shop is
one-quarter Barbies. She also sells on eBay from time to time and
via a doll Web page (www.dolls4u(at)flash.net). She didn't even
want to get into Barbie collecting at first. ``There's too much to
know.'' But Barbie and the business proved irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Life was simpler when Barbie was just a doll.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CAN BARBIE COME OUT TO PLAY? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' says Bobbie Willis, whose 2,700 Barbies put her in the
top circles of Houston collectors, ``everybody that buys a doll
thinks they are going into the business. Everybody wants to be a
dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Or an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rifts in Barbie Collector Land: In this corner, those
who would collect the pristine Barbie and her official ensembles,
dressing and housing her as the god Mattel intended.
</P>
<P>
   In that corner, those who see Barbie as a fantasy cipher, a
mannequin to be costumed, coiffed, manipulated in fanciful
dioramas.
</P>
<P>
   There's another rift, too, a small one.
</P>
<P>
   Since Collector Mania seized the Barbie world in the '70s, many
Barbies have never even seen the light of day. Purchased for the
sole purpose of escalating in value, they have been kept in their
boxes and stored away by tens of thousands of collectors. Now, says
Ferriby, some Barbie fans are saying she should be enjoyed,
touched, felt and played with.
</P>
<P>
   They're calling it the Unbox the Barbie movement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A BAD GIRL? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are those who would like to see Barbie boxed
and buried. Or at least punished.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites especially give free rein to the anti-Barbies (at
least, until told to cease and desist by Mattel's vigilant legal
department). Distorted Barbie created alternative dolls (Kate Moss
Barbie, Fat and Ugly Barbie, Satanic Barbie).
</P>
<P>
   There's a Lesbian Barbie page (for 18 and over).
</P>
<P>
   Barbie jokes. Heard about the new Divorcee Barbie? She comes
with all of Ken's accessories.
</P>
<P>
   She's been the subject of college courses, protests, vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a group calling itself the Barbie Liberation Army
switched voice boxes on hundreds of talking Barbies and GI Joes.
``Eat lead, cobra!'' she roared.
</P>
<P>
   Though this probably wouldn't be what she'd have in mind (which,
by the way, if she had one, would be about the size of a squirrel's
brain), Barbie would be the first to admit a little criticism can
be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, it led, after all, to her finding employment
as more than a model, nurse or teacher. Later it would alter her
world view, and her skin tone, as the Ultimate Anglo morphed into a
doll line more reflective of the planet's human hues.
</P>
<P>
   Change, thinking out of the box, can be good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BARBIE LOOKS AHEAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Middle age is no big deal these days. Gloria Steinem was talking
about her own milestone, not Barbie's, when she said ``THIS is what
40 looks like,'' but what the heck.
</P>
<P>
   Steinem wasn't present at the birthday bash thrown by Mattel
recently, but other celebrities were. Rosie O'Donnell was there,
kicking off a partnership between Mattel and Girls Incorporated, a
national girls' advocacy program. Or maybe she was there to cop
that very special limited edition 40th-anniversary Barbie made just
for the occasion and given only to guests at the gala.
</P>
<P>
   This should be quite a year for Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   On March 9, Barbie's supposed to ring the bell (we wonder, with
her head?) at the New York Stock Exchange. Wall Street will be
renamed Barbie Street for the day.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the mail-order gardening giant Jackson &AMP; Perkins will
offer the `Barbie' rose, a pink miniature.
</P>
<P>
   Also this spring, the U.S. Postal Service plans to unveil a
Barbie stamp. Just like Elvis, another American icon, except
there's only one version of Barbie's stamp _ ever-young, svelte.
</P>
<P>
   Parties, roses, stamps. Pretty heady stuff, but Barbie's been
'round the block a time or two (in a bright pink Corvette, no
less). She'll take the congratulations in stride, maybe just like
Steinem did.
</P>
<P>
   This is what 40 looks like, America, she might say. Take it or
leave it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
