<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DONNY-MARIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYTIME TV VIEWERS EMBRACE THE MAGIC OF `DONNY &AMP; MARIE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The star of ``L.A. Doctors'' hunched over his patient,
determined to prove worthy of his medical license as he performed a
delicate operation.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Ken Olin worked his way in slowly, slowly, slowly, then _
careful ... careful _ he removed a man's arm bone. A medical
marvel, conducted with tweezers and without blood or pain.
</P>
<P>
   If you weren't watching ``Donny &AMP; Marie,'' you missed it. And if
you aren't watching ``Donny &AMP; Marie,'' you're missing one of the
best hours of entertainment available on daytime TV today.
</P>
<P>
   Some may consider that statement an indictment of daytime
television. Maybe it is. Having Olin play with the box game
Operation doesn't sound like the ingredient of a Top 30 show in
prime time.
</P>
<P>
   But in daytime, ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' is No. 2 among the national
crop of new talk shows (No. 1 is ``Roseanne'').
</P>
<P>
   This is what you're missing.
</P>
<P>
   One day it could be Olin sweating over some tweezers, the next
it could be an hour at the piano with Stevie Wonder. One day it
could be a behind-the-scenes visit on the set of ``Jeopardy,'' the
next it could be singer Mariah Carey talking about when she was
poor, or Donny rapping ``Puppy Love'' with Snoop Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a good reputation around town, which is 90
percent of this game you play, which is to make sure people have a
good time,'' says Marie Osmond. ``Our growth has been phenomenal.
It's because people are having a good time and guests are treated
well, and it's different. It's the kind of show where you can have
a Stevie Wonder and you can do the whole show around the piano. I
don't know other shows where you can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the ultimate guest to have on,'' says Donny Osmond of
Wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Donny even wept as Wonder sang ``Overjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of my favorite songs of all times, and my idol was
sitting two feet from me, singing it,'' Donny says. ``It was a
great moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder may be the ultimate guest, ``but there's so many people
we'd like to have on and talk to,'' says Donny. ``The nicest thing
about the history of Marie and myself, we can relate to practically
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   She was a little bit country, he a little bit rock 'n' roll back
in January 1976, when their sticky-sweet variety show stood
television on its ear, surviving 2 1/2 seasons (or two seasons
longer than cynics predicted).
</P>
<P>
   Before that, they were recording phenoms, as soloists and as
members of the singing Osmond Family. When ABC-TV canceled the
variety show, they each carved out solo singing careers. Marie also
dived into doll-making, series television (1995's ``Maybe This
Time,'' with Betty White) and a tour of ``The Sound of Music.''
Meanwhile, Donny raced cars and starred in 1,800 touring
performances of ``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat.''
</P>
<P>
   Today they've been working for 36 years. She's 39. He's 41.
She's pregnant with her seventh child; Marie and her husband,
record producer Brian Blosil, have three boys and three girls at
home. Donny and his wife Debbie have five sons, ages 1 to 19.
</P>
<P>
   The talk show was a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to understand is that Donny and Marie have been
asked to get together for 20 years, and this really was, to us, the
best way to do it,'' says Marie.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a way to provide some stability in the family life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I'm living in New York or on the road touring, it is
very nice to sit down some place,'' says Marie. ``My kids are going
to the same school. I go to work every day. I have my weekends off.
When I work Broadway, I work six days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   She lives in Los Angeles, where their show is shot, but Donny
commutes weekends to his Salt Lake City home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult,'' he says. ``I've got my videophone (Donny's a
computer buff) and I call my family and see them every day. And I'm
home on the weekends. ... From what I've been doing the last six
years, it is an improvement (over eight shows a week in far-flung
theaters).''
</P>
<P>
   Two of his boys are taller than 5-foot-9 Donny, and the
second-oldest, Jeremy, has put together a punk/ska band called
Sudden Urge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to see him play once,'' Donny says with a laugh, ``and
the bill included Strange Itch, Bend Over and Sudden Urge. I
thought, `What is my son getting into here?'''
</P>
<P>
   When the shoot takes a break in June, Donny will go to England
to do a film version of ``Joseph.'' He also has an autobiography,
``Life Is Just What You Make It,'' due out in May.
</P>
<P>
   Marie: ``I thought it was called `My First 2,000 Years.'''
</P>
<P>
   Donny: ``It's not a typical autobiography. It's more of a
feeling of what it was like to grow up in this business and have
the roller-coaster rider that I've had. It's not a book about
complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie: ``You know, I think everybody should write a book because
it's a lot cheaper than a shrink.''
</P>
<P>
   Donny: ``Well, it's been a cathartic experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Their playful jabs in this three-person conference call play out
just like you'd imagine it would, like you'd expect a brother and
sister to act. It's hugely appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting chemistry we have,'' admits Marie.
``First, I don't know anybody who's been in the business 36 years
and still going. And also the fact it's a male-female relationship,
and we have definite differences of opinion. And also that we're
siblings. I think 99 percent of talk is chemistry, and I think we
have a unique chemistry as siblings.''
</P>
<P>
   Not generally discussed _ though they will, if asked _ is the
role God plays in their lives. They are devout Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more a way of life and it's something you can't
inflict on other people, because it's such a personal thing,'' says
Donny. ``It does dictate the way we live, but we're certainly very
normal people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Donny said, we don't talk about it,'' adds Marie. ``We
don't sit there and promote it or whatever. But it is what made me
what I am. I believe you should be balanced like four legs on a
chair and I think your religious beliefs is one of those legs. And
if you don't stay balanced, you end up falling over.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like all legs are in place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
