<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE A GOOD TRIM TO PONYTAIL PLANT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ I have a 20-year-old ponytail plant. During the warm
months I keep the potted plant outside. But during the winter I
bring it indoors. The plant is now about 12 feet tall and is
touching the ceiling of my ``highest'' room. Should I cut the plant
off?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, you can prune the top off. Take the plant outdoors and
prune vigorously toward the large onionlike base so you won't have
to repeat the process too soon. Take more rather than less. The
result may be as many as three or four new sprouts, giving you a
more handsome plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beaucarnea recurvata,'' or ponytail plant, likes sun or
partial sun and a well-draining soil. The more it's pampered, the
faster it grows. Mature plants are much more cold-hardy than potted
young ones.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Lythrum hybrids often are recommended for perennial gardens
in this area. I recently read both species and hybrids are
potentially invasive. Do you think it's safe to grow lythrum
(loose- strife) in our gardens?
</P>
<P>
   Are there any other annuals or perennials that should not be
grown here because of their invasive potential?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Lythrum salicaria,'' or purple loose- strife, is the
species that is so invasive, choking wetlands and nudging out other
vegetation. It becomes unmanageable with abundant moisture, and
some states outlaw it.
</P>
<P>
   ``L. virgatum,'' sometimes sold at special plant sales in this
area and found occasionally at some nurseries, has narrow foliage
and showy spikes of pink and purple flowers that appear summer into
early fall. ``Modern's Pink'' and ``Modern's Gleam'' have not been
threatening in any local garden that I know.
</P>
<P>
   I have been told the hybrids are sterile, but I have also read
that these could possibly interbreed with the bad cousin that grows
wild and therefore sets seed. So I would be cautious about growing
a hybrid if I lived near an area infested with ``L. salicaria.''
</P>
<P>
   What may be invasive in my garden may not be in another, but
plants that I've attempted to remove include an alstroemeria that
even thrives in the lawn. This plant hides anything below 2 or 3
feet in height. Commonly called parrot lily or Peruvian lily, ``A.
psittacina''(formerly ``A. pulchella'') has red flowers with green
tips. It is pretty, but I recommend you avoid this easy spreader or
you just may be digging tubers every weekend. Other species are
better behaved.
</P>
<P>
   Wedelia is a wonderful ground cover for large areas, but this
trailing perennial can quickly escape into off-limit areas. It's
pretty, too, with dark green glossy foliage and bright yellow,
daisylike blooms that appear nearly year-round. This is a good
seaside plant.
</P>
<P>
   Some might argue ruellia is invasive, but I don't rate this
perennial as a pest. Both the tall and short ``Katie'' ruellias are
so carefree they belong on the ultimate low-maintenance plant list.
The tall types produce purple or pink blooms for months on end. The
``Katie'' begins to flower, in my garden, later in the year, but
then really puts on a show. Both spread, but they don't choke out
other plants, and I don't find removing unwanted ruellias that much
of a problem. Others may say I'm crazy.
</P>
<P>
   I put ``Physotegia virginiana,'' or obedient plant, in the above
category as well. This native perennial produces late summer
lavender blooms on plants up to 3 to 4 feet tall. A grouping of the
snapdragonlike blooms can be attractive. But the plants spread, and
in a few years you may have more than you want. However, I find
them easy to pull.
</P>
<P>
   I really have no serious qualms with annuals. Chocolate plant
(``Pseuderanthemum alatum'') is a big-time re-seeder, but because
this makes a nice ground cover in summer shade, I don't mind its
presence. The foliage is brown with silver splotches on top and
gray underneath. Tiny but deep purple blooms appear on slender,
tall stems in late summer and early fall. The plants are among the
first to succumb to frost. When there is no really cold weather,
the plants may return from the roots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
