<HEADER>
A5816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-RENAISSANCE-HN     03-03 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RENAISSANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAISSANCE BREAKS MOLD BY EMPHASIZING DIRECT BOOKINGS 
 
 &HT;    SYD KEARNEY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ``Coloring outside the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are descriptions Renaissance Cruises uses to describe
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saddam Hussein of the travel industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the descriptions some travel agents have slapped on
the Fort Lauderdale, Fla.-based cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   The difference of opinion focuses on the company's aggressive
marketing policy. Renaissance is making waves with its
direct-to-the-consumer marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   About 95 percent of all cruises are sold by travel agents. Some
lines market their product exclusively through agencies; they set
up toll-free telephone numbers and Internet sites as educational
tools only and refer bookings to agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance has taken the opposite approach.
</P>
<P>
   Brochures urge cruisers to ``book direct and save.'' ``Savvy
travelers'' are directed to the company's Web site for the lowest
prices. ``Available only by calling Renaissance Cruises direct'' is
a marketing mantra.
</P>
<P>
   You may have pulled their advertising from your mailbox
recently. Have an American Express card? You've been offered a
Mediterranean cruise with the ``exclusive'' chance to save $3,600
per cabin. Order from the Speigel catalog? You've been given the
opportunity to book a Tahitian cruise and get a $400 gift
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance is unapologetic about its marketing policy, which
looks to bypass the travel-agent community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the level of support we get from travel
agents,'' says Renaissance executive vice president Frank Del Rio.
``But we want to create demand at the consumer level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the travel-agent community came of age 40 years ago,
there were four airlines, three hotel chains and two rental car
companies. There were one or two cruise lines. Tour packages didn't
exist. Travel agents had a limited product line to represent and,
therefore, they did a very good job of representing those products.
Today, there are 50 airlines, dozens of motel chains, 30 cruise
lines. ... A travel agent can't be an expert on every product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can provide the customer with better information than the
typical travel agent because we are the experts on our product,''
Del Rio says. ``Our personal travel consultants are experts in only
one thing: Renaissance cruises. Their expertise empowers the
customer so that they can make the best possible decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The personal travel consultants are a hit with many passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Houstonian and veteran cruiser Loyce Hicks enjoys
planning her vacations with her counselor at Renaissance. Hicks and
her dentist husband, Paul, were aboard one of the first sailings of
the R2 in December. It was her fourth Renaissance Cruise, and the
couple already is booked on an October trip to Tahiti aboard the
new R3 ship.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hicks' first time to cruise on the line's new R-Class
fleet. The company began in 1989 with an eight-ship fleet. The
ships were intimate all-suite vessels that accommodated 114 guests.
Only two of these ships _ the Renaissance VII and Renaissance VIII
_ are still sailing.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks gave the R2 a thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is an absolutely beautiful ship. I really enjoyed
the 114-passenger ships. It seems like things moved more smoothly
(on the smaller ships). But we've been on ships with more than
2,000 passengers. This was a good size.''
</P>
<P>
   The R2 carries 684 passengers. It is the second of a planned
six-ship fleet in which all the vessels are identical. R1 and R2
began sailing in 1998 and both offer Mediterranean holidays. The R3
and R4 will debut in 1999, plying the waters of the South Pacific.
The R5 and R6 are expected to begin sailing in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a ship this size built with these
amenities,'' Del Rio says. ``The closest is maybe the Royal Viking
Sun, which was built in early '80s. And I understand her design was
mid-'70s. The trouble today is she doesn't have any balconies.''
</P>
<P>
   Balconies are becoming a must-have amenity for cruise ships. And
they were just one of the customer requests taken into account when
the R-Class fleet was designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out what customers want in a cruise line, instead of
what cruise lines want to build,'' Del Rio explains. ``Nobody ever
said they wanted to cruise on a ship with 2,000 strangers. People
don't want megaliners, but they go because it's the only thing to
go on.''
</P>
<P>
   And what are cruisers' priorities?
</P>
<P>
   Balconies, restaurant options, open seating and a smoke-free
environment, according to Renaissance research.
</P>
<P>
   Got it, got it, got it, got it, Del Rio notes.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to keep prices extremely low,'' Del Rio says.
``On our Internet site (www.renaissance cruises.com), we've created
the Dare to Compare page. It lists product attributes compared to
the newest ships of Royal Caribbean, Holland America and Princess
Cruises _ three cruise lines we compete with. If you look, we are
$2,000 to $7,000 less per cabin for a comparable itinerary. That's
an incredible value. We think we have a pretty good formula.''
</P>
<P>
   With its value-consciousness and casually elegant fleet,
Renaissance may possess a good formula, but what they don't have is
name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Niche products are small by comparison to the big guy,'' says
Del Rio, referring to cruise line's exotic destination-oriented
itineraries that include the Greek islands, the South Pacific,
Scandinavia and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our product is a little more complex. And the public may not
be as familiar with our destinations,'' Del Rio says.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance's alliances with companies such as American Express,
AARP (American Association of Retired Persons) and America On Line
may speed that process.
</P>
<P>
   These alliances ``put our product in front of savvy consumers,''
Del Rio says. ``It puts us face to face so we can directly speak
our message. These third-party endorsements are welcome and a
testament to our product.
</P>
<P>
   But another third-party endorsement, that of the travel-agent
community, may continue to elude Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the 10-year-old cruise line capped its commissions
paid to travel agents at $500 per cabin or $250 per person. That
meant war to many agents, who battled back by steering clients to
other cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   In late November, the cruise line shifted its policy again by
offering a 10 percent commission on its cruises. Some agents have
declared the policy change a victory, but it is too soon to tell
whether agents will forgive and forget and begin hawking
Renaissance cruises again.
</P>
<P>
   Houstonian Joe Galloway, president of the American Society of
Travel Agents and owner of Trans-Continental Travel, is one agent
who won't be sending customers to Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   His objections to the cruise line have nothing to do with its
direct marketing campaign, he says, but with some problems that
arose when his customers were displaced from Renaissance cruises
just weeks before sailing. The incidents happened several years
ago, but once bitten ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problems with the product,'' Galloway says, ``but
our business is one of trust.''
</P>
<P>
   And as far as the direct marketing is concerned?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are good marketers,'' Galloway says, ``but they aren't
necessarily the best buy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
