<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-RENAISSANCE-PACKAGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENAISSANCE TOUR PACKAGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renaissance is the cruise forerunner in direct booking and
advertises that its best deals are reserved for those who bypass
travel agents and book direct via phone or online. Call
800-525-5350 or access the company's Internet site at
www.renaissancecruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site recently began touting a $200 per cabin discount
for booking online.
</P>
<P>
   A travel agent also can book a Renaissance cruise. And online
travel sellers such as Expedia.com and America Online work with
Renaissance and frequently advertise special discounts and
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance packages ``cruise tours'' that include air fare from
New York, cruise, pre-cruise and post-cruise hotel stays, as well
as ground transfers.
</P>
<P>
   The R2 package, offered year-round, encompasses 14 days and
includes hotel stays in Barcelona and Lisbon. Ports of call during
the 10-day cruise are Cadiz, Malaga, Almeria, Palma de Mallorca and
Mahon in Spain, Tangier and Casablanca in Morocco, and Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance's Web site is listing prices for May cruise tours as
starting at $3,799 per person (double occupancy) for a C category
stateroom with balcony. The 14-day trip with an inside stateroom in
May goes for $2,799 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Always inquire about any available discounts.
</P>
<P>
   A sister ship, R1, focuses on the Greek Islands, sailing between
Athens and Istanbul with stops in Israel, Cyprus, Crete and Rhodes.
Its 14-day cruise tours are priced similarly to the R2.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the R3 will debut and begin a year-round itinerary in
the South Pacific. Among stops on these 10-day cruises: Tahiti,
Moorea, Rangiroa, Huahine and Bora Bora. Renaissance is advertising
an early R3 booking rate of $2,999 per person (double occupancy)
for a cabin with balcony and air fare from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance expects that its R4 will begin sailing in the South
Pacific in December, in time for a millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
