<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5818 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-03 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARRY-ON MEALS FLY WITH PASSENGERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Ordering food ``to go'' has never carried such
long-distance implications.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be when we requested ``takeout,'' the fish tacos were
intended for home or office. Now, chances are we're taking them to
St. Louis or Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At 35,000 feet above normal seafood level.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, hungry airline passengers are striking back. If flight
attendants aren't permitted to serve us a meal, then we'll serve
ourselves, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Have you taken to the skies recently? Even before the Boeing 737
lifts off the runway, one traveler is munching on a bologna
sandwich, another on a fruit salad, still others on chicken,
cheeseburgers, pasta and egg rolls. All purchased prior to
boarding.
</P>
<P>
   What's next, corn on the cob?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST AND FANCY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airport concessionaires can barely stock enough brown bags and
plastic utensils. Area hotels tempt guests with meals prepared for
consumption aloft. I figure fast-food chains, not wanting to risk
missing our business at terminal locations, will be opening outlets
in remote parking lots any day now. Anyone for a McSky Burger?
</P>
<P>
   Even the Petroleum Club of Houston has joined the crusade,
creating ClubAir, a menu of ``Club-quality'' cold meals specially
packaged for members in a briefcase-like container. And, no, I'm
assured that this is not some sort of, er, crude joke. Options
include a chicken breast stuffed with shrimp and crab meat and
served over couscous; smoked salmon with thinly sliced bagels; a
smoked tenderloin salad; and, for kids, a peanut butter and jelly
sandwich. Most meals are priced, a club announcement says, ``equal
or slightly more than the current price per barrel of oil,
something most members hope will reverse itself soon and
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder we're packing sack lunches. As a cost-cutting
measure, airlines have all but abandoned hot meal service on most
domestic flights. And for those just now adjusting to the packaged
snacks some carriers offer as we board the aircraft, take note that
Delta is removing the cold sandwiches from its SkyDeli bags on 140
flights, and replacing them with crackers and cheese or carrots and
dip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NO OBLIGATION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I can understand the airlines' position. For one thing, their
prime responsibility is to transport us safely and efficiently _
not feed us. Just because they used to provide us a free
three-course meal doesn't mean they are mandated to continue.
</P>
<P>
   For another, we've sent a clear signal that we don't mind
carrying food aboard. We continue to pack airplanes in record
numbers. Some of the highest passenger satisfaction ratings are
accorded to Southwest Airlines, which, Department of Transportation
figures show, spends 20 cents per passenger on food compared to an
overall average of $3.17 (down from almost $5 eight years ago) by
major U.S. airlines on domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
   You can wager a prime cut of Kansas beef that if we began
choosing one carrier over another primarily because of its dinner
fare _ not price fare _ we'd suddenly see frantic competition to
provide us the tastiest cuisine. Need evidence? Just look at
international flights, for which airlines are hiring innovative
chefs to enhance menus, not cut them back.
</P>
<P>
   What amazes me is that airlines don't seem to care what edibles
we take aboard their property. Airport management pays little or no
heed to foodstuffs we cart through terminals. I keep expecting the
security attendant at a screening station to say, ``Sorry, sir,
your computer and camera bag are fine, but that five-piece bucket
of chicken isn't allowed.'' But nobody blinks.
</P>
<P>
   I got to thinking the other day, as I tossed another lottery
card into the trash bin, that if someone really wanted to get rich
quick and studied this carry-on meal situation and came up with a
theme and a promotion ...
</P>
<P>
   And that's when it struck me: Next time concessionaire contracts
are up for consideration at Houston airports, I'm going to propose
the construction of food stands directly adjacent to gate check-in
counters.
</P>
<P>
   But not just any food stands. Destination stations, that's what
I'll call them. They'll require little room; I'll set up a kitchen
elsewhere. And I'll market (at a reasonable price) specialty items
that not only satisfy your taste buds, but also put you in the mood
for arrival hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Headed to Philadelphia? I'll sell you a cheese steak. San
Francisco? A loaf of sourdough bread or a bay shrimp cocktail. New
Orleans? Po-boys and beignets. Baltimore? Crab cakes. Chicago? A
slice of deep-dish pizza. Boston? Baked beans.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, scratch that last item. Those airline seats are jammed in
tight, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, once the airlines learn of my idea, they'll adopt it
themselves and reap the profits. Isn't that the next logical step,
anyway? If hamburger chains and hotels and even the 53-year-old
Petroleum Club can make money selling us airline food, shouldn't
that grab the attention of airline bean counters? How much would we
be willing to dole out for an old-fashioned airline steak or
chicken dinner? (Ugh, remember those?) With an ice-cream sundae for
dessert? Enough that the airline could turn a profit?
</P>
<P>
   Don't scoff: While airlines are phasing out their food business,
they remain very much in the bar business. Even Southwest. Why?
Because it, unlike the free-food business, is a money-maker.
Remember when those miniature bottles cost $1.50? Now, we pay an
airline $4 if we're lucky.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to a serious closing thought. Incidents of air rage
by unruly passengers have increased 400 percent over the past five
years, according to industry reports cited by Business Traveler
magazine. Many analysts attribute the increase to the ready
availability of alcohol combined with the sparsity of food.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're determined to imbibe, don't do so on an empty
stomach. Stuff that brown bag with goodies. Join the Petroleum
Club. Ask for extra carrots and dip.
</P>
<P>
   At least until my destination stations are open.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
