<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-R2SHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAMPERING PASSENGERS WITH R-CLASS SHIPS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ The R2. Deck 8. Cabin No. 8058. Category B.
Ocean view with balcony.
</P>
<P>
   That's a cold description of the warm stateroom that was our
home for a week.
</P>
<P>
   The R2 made its debut recently as the second _ hence the 2 _ of
four new ships to be launched by Renaissance Cruises during a
14-month period. The R2's regular route covers the Mediterranean
and coastal Spain; its specialty is a 14-day Lisbon-to-Barcelona
tour that includes round-trip air fare from New York, a 10-day
cruise and hotel stays in Lisbon and Barcelona for prices starting
at about $3,000 per person (double occupancy).
</P>
<P>
   The R2 holiday is destination-intensive, offering nine ports of
call in 10 days. Shore excursions provide the opportunity to visit
a Gothic cathedral and taste ``tapas'' in Seville, Spain; to rock
the kasbah in Tangier, Morocco; to meet the famous rock apes of
Gibraltar; and to explore the legendary Alhambra, a 13th-century
Moorish castle in Grenada, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   While the ports and shore excursions provide enriching
experiences, the ship itself is delightful.
</P>
<P>
   When complete, the R-fleet will comprise four nearly identical,
684-passenger ships _ much smaller than the 2,000- to
3,000-passenger megaliners being churned out by Carnival and Royal
Caribbean, but larger than veteran Renaissance customers have come
to expect. Renaissance cruises have traditionally been on small
all-suite ships with a passenger count of about 100.
</P>
<P>
   The traditionally styled R-Class ships feature oversized
staterooms, 93 percent of which have ocean views. More than 60
percent include private balconies. And the entire fleet is
smoke-free.
</P>
<P>
   The cabins have all the features one would expect as well as
some nice details, such as superior storage space, 24-hour room
service and remote-controlled televisions with CNN, ESPN and
first-run movies.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers choose among four restaurants, and an open-seating
policy accommodates those who don't like to be told when and where
to dine. In keeping with the line's informal style, dining-room
names are succinct.
</P>
<P>
   The Panorama Buffet _ whose name refers to airy wrap-around digs
on Deck 9 _ is the spot for casual dining morning, noon and night.
The buffet, a favorite of the ship's officers, often surprised with
its gourmet offerings. We were delighted to find escargot-stuffed
tarts and delicate soups beside the ubiquitous carving station and
dessert bar.
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance dubs the Club Restaurant its most sophisticated. I
found the room oversized and stuffy. Its Continental menu and
Muzac-inspired live entertainment are aimed at the over-50 crowd
that gravitates to the restaurant nightly. Formal breakfasts and
lunch also are served at the Club.
</P>
<P>
   Two small specialty dining rooms _ the Grill Room and the
Italian Restaurant _ are more appealing. The long skinny dining
rooms wrap around the aft of Deck 10 and share a kitchen, which
separates the restaurants with Wizard of Oz-like magic.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants are intimate, and the service is polished. A
thick tuna steak and Caesar salad at the Grill Room was the
culinary highlight of the week, followed closely by a
shrimp-and-pasta concoction at the Italian Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no additional charge for dining in the Grill Room
or Italian Restaurant, reservations are a must. Reservations also
are advised for the Club, particularly if you desire a romantic
table for two.
</P>
<P>
   But a wait for a table is never a problem on the R2. All
restaurants are accoutered with comfortable lounges. Particularly
nice is the Club's bar, whose faux antiques and genteel furnishings
remind one of an old English inn.
</P>
<P>
   Some cruise-goers may be disappointed by the lack of a midnight
buffet. Renaissance joins Disney and several other cruise lines in
opting out of these sporadically attended eat-fests. That would not
be a problem except that restaurants shut down at a distressingly
early 9 p.m., leaving night owls with stomach growls two options:
order off a limited room-service menu or hang out at the Casino or
the Sports Bar until late-night hors d'oeuvres are offered by
tray-toting crew members.
</P>
<P>
   Cruisers have several entertainment and leisure options:
</P>
<P>
   _ Library: R2's may be one of the best at sea. Besides having
hundreds of books, this room offers an inviting space in which to
linger. The focal point is a lovely faux fireplace and a gaily
painted ceiling that gives you the allusion of sitting in an
atrium. Its narrow, wrap-around design also provides several
private nooks for reading or daydreaming.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sports Bar: This huge space is dotted with large-screen
televisions that were tuned most days and nights to snooker
tournaments and downhill skiing. Its forward position on Deck 10
also makes it a wonderful observation lounge. Most days it was
quiet and free of sports fans. At night, a band entertained on a
small stage, and a tiny casino area with 10-cent slot machines was
well-used.
</P>
<P>
   _ Casino: Small but pleasant (when was the last time you visited
a smoke-free gambling room?), the ship's casino is a friendly
gathering spot in the evening. Its long bar has an elegant saloon
feel, and the British casino staff is unfailingly cheerful. The
casino offers roulette, blackjack, two poker tables and about a
dozen slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cabaret Lounge: Evening entertainment ranged from the plucky
Paramount Performers, who never met a show tune they couldn't
croon, to a fine classical pianist and an extremely bad comic,
whose idea of a joke was to poke fun at hearing aids, the
absent-minded and his audience. His mean-spirited jokes didn't play
well with the sophisticated and mature audience.
</P>
<P>
   On a brighter note, a flamenco show before the ship left port in
Cadiz, Spain, featured local performers who played to a packed,
appreciative house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spa: The British company Steiner provides programs and
services in the ship's spa, which includes a full-service salon and
fitness center. While prices are not exorbitant, guests might get
the hard sell on lotions and potions. The spa also offers slimming
and skin treatments and a private deck for sunning. The fitness
center is state of the art with a terrific ocean view.
</P>
<P>
   On R2 _ and other Renaissance vessels _ there are no formal
nights, no sequins, no regimentation. No poolside contests, no
bingo announcements.
</P>
<P>
   There are also no children.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the cruise line formalized its no-children
policy: All cruisers must be at least 13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
