<HEADER>
A5822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CRYSTAL-HNS &LR;      03-03 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRYSTAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRYSTAL EARNS ACCOLADES WITH FOCUS ON ENRICHMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, life on the high seas: breakfast in bed; tanning beside a
pool, mai tai in one hand and a paperback in the other; rolling the
dice on a game of chance; dancing and partying into the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   As on most ships, you could do all that aboard the Crystal
Symphony and Crystal Harmony. And in style.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could:
</P>
<P>
   _ Listen intently as novelists Judith Krantz or Mary Higgins
Clark, broadcast journalists Walter Cronkite or Linda Ellerbee, or
actors Eva Marie Saint or Michael York discuss their craft.
</P>
<P>
   _ Savor a cooking demonstration by Andr Soltner, Jacques Pepin,
Wolfgang Puck or Jeremiah Tower.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ponder personalized golf tips from two-time U.S. Open champion
Billy Casper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attend lectures on anthropology, geography, history, art or
politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Partake in a wine tasting presided over by a master sommelier.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take classes to learn about the Internet and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large majority of our guests aren't on board to
vegetate,'' says Crystal Cruises president Joseph Watters. ``They
want to be educated. They want their lives to be enriched.''
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy has previously been almost the exclusive domain
of cruise lines that specialize in yachtlike vessels (with
Silversea, Seabourn, Radisson Seven Seas and Cunard's Sea Goddess
fleet at the forefront) or whose emphasis is on long-distance
voyages (Cunard's Queen Elizabeth 2).
</P>
<P>
   It would never work, critics scoffed, on ships that carry 940
passengers and operate itineraries that average less than two weeks
in length.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Carnival and Princess continue to achieve success
with their ``Fun Ship'' and ``Love Boat'' approaches, Crystal's two
vessels have carved out a singular niche while earning
unprecedented passenger satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   For four consecutive years, readers of Conde Nast Travelers
magazine have accorded Crystal honors as ``best large ship line.''
Similar accolades have come the past three years from Travel &AMP;
Leisure magazine, whose most recent reader poll gave the line the
highest ratings of any vacation opportunity worldwide. Almost every
major guidebook bestows its top ratings on the Symphony and
Harmony.
</P>
<P>
   A recent sailing through the Panama Canal aboard the 4-year-old
Symphony demonstrated why Crystal merits such acclaim: By stressing
cultural enrichment, diverse itineraries and alternative dining
options, the Los Angeles-based line is at the cutting edge of what
many see as cruising's future. And yet its understated luxury,
attention to detail and personalized service hark back to an era
before megaships created, in effect, bustling cities at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Symphony and Harmony (launched in 1990) are just
mainstream enough _ interspersing traditional Caribbean and Alaskan
itineraries with others dubbed ``Silk and Spice'' between Bombay
and Singapore and ``Black Sea Rendezvous'' from Athens to Rome _ to
appeal to first-time and established cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, their midrange size (50,000 tons) entices those put
off by seagoing behemoths but who appreciate amenities unavailable
on smaller vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing, too, covers a broad spectrum. Some passengers are
well-heeled enough to pay up to $10,000 per week for a penthouse
with private verandah and butler service. And yet advance-purchase
brochure rates for 11-day Panama Canal sailings start at under
$3,000 per person _ considerably less than most other
luxury-oriented lines charge _ and a good travel agent can usually
secure a discount.
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to Watters' suggested passenger preferences,
these ships are ideally suited to individuals who want to vegetate.
Indeed, splurge for a stateroom on the Penthouse Deck, and it's
tempting never to venture outside. Need your suit jacket pressed?
Shoes shined? Dinner served course-by-course on the verandah? Just
ask your personal butler. One passenger inquired if the bed could
be rolled onto the balcony; another wanted her teddy bear's clothes
changed daily. Requests granted.
</P>
<P>
   Even standard staterooms are huge by industry standards and
feature picture windows (except for 19 inside cabins on the
Harmony), twin beds that convert to queens or kings, showers and
tubs, television with VCRs and 24-hour room service.
</P>
<P>
   As for activities, Crystal Symphony hotel director Herbert
Yaeger says, ``The challenge is always to come up with something
special that nobody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Several enrichment lectures are conducted on each itinerary,
with one series devoted to the geographic region the cruise covers.
New this year is a partnership with the New Yorker magazine through
which staff artists, writers and editors are making presentations
during segments of the Symphony's current world cruise.
</P>
<P>
   A Computer University at Sea is among the most popular
attractions. Depending on the cruise length, beginner and advanced
courses are offered.
</P>
<P>
   Shore excursions range beyond the usual shopping sprees and city
tours. On the Symphony's world tour, 16 modes of
land-transportation options include elephants, rickshaws, dune
buggies and dugout canoes.
</P>
<P>
   The line's Wine and Food Festival, offered on select sailings
throughout the year, attracts premier chefs and wine experts from
all over the world. Typically, a chef offers two cooking
demonstrations, interacting with passengers, then prepares a
specialty dinner. Two wine tastings are conducted. Each ship's wine
list includes a minimum of 200 offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Participating chefs this year include Soltner, retired
proprietor of New York's Lutece; Michael Mina, executive chef at
San Francisco's Aqua; Alan Wong of his namesake Honolulu
restaurant; Horst Pfieffer, chef-owner of New Orleans' Bella Luna;
and television personalities Pepin and Norman Van Aiken.
</P>
<P>
   Everyday cuisine is superb, with lunch and dinner specialties on
the Symphony's Panama Canal sailing including roasted French duck
with caramelized orange sauce; potato-crusted halibut with tomato
and olive sauce; paella Valencia; medallions of Scandinavian
venison; California cioppino; Moorish pork kebabs; and smoked
salmon quesadillas.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressive are two alternative restaurants: Prego, an
Italian eatery; and Jade Garden, which features Asian delicacies.
(Japanese-themed Kyoto replaces Jade Garden on the Harmony.) These
are open nightly to all passengers by reservation and at no extra
charge. (A $5 per person gratuity is recommended.)
</P>
<P>
   An evening repast at Prego featured an appetizer tower of
grilled, marinated vegetables with slices of lobster, sauted prawns
and scallops in truffle vinaigrette; Caesar salad prepared
tableside; mushroom soup served in an oregano bread cup; a roasted
rack of herb-crusted baby lamb; and a lemon mousse with meringue.
</P>
<P>
   Themed buffets are as colorful as they are bountiful, and unlike
most lines Crystal shows the good judgment to present them at
midday _ when passengers are hungry _ rather than in late evening.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment on each cruise includes four full-scale musical
revues and several variety shows. Well-known singers, dancers and
comedians are often featured. Afternoon recitals showcase classical
music.
</P>
<P>
   A new shoreside golf program on nine specified itineraries
offers guaranteed tee times at 21 of the world's most challenging
golf courses. A teaching pro is aboard every cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Each ship offers two swimming pools, a spa and salon, two main
showrooms, movie theater, Caesars Palace at Sea casino, card room,
book and video library and several lounges.
</P>
<P>
   The Crystal Harmony will operate Panama Canal sailings from
March through May, then sail round-trip between San Francisco and
Alaska during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Symphony will spend the summer and early fall in Europe,
then move to Asia and the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   A travel agent can provide brochures and make reservations. Or
call 800-820-6663 for a brochure. Access www.crystalcruises.com on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
