<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5828 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE     03-03 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDITORS: THIS IS PART TWO OF A TWO PART FILE)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Media mogul Ted Turner recently had to issue an apology to
the Polish people and government because of an ethnic Polish joke
he made about the pope. Turner also apologized recently for
remarking that adultery shouldn't be included among the Ten
Commandments. Does he claim any particular religious affiliation?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Or at least none that anyone is aware of, said Caroline
Harkleroad, spokeswoman for Turner Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that a rap performer was arrested
for wearing a bulletproof vest. Can you explain?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 30-year-old performer, who goes by ODB (real name:
Russell Jones), was taken into custody Feb. 16 by the Los Angeles
Police Department for what a LAPD spokesperson termed ``a minor
traffic violation.'' According to E! Online, the arrest report said
Jones, who wasn't able to produce a driver's license, was ordered
to get out of his car. After noticing he was wearing body armor,
officers ran a warrant check and discovered a prior felony
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the problem: It's a no-no for anyone convicted of a
violent felony to wear a bulletproof vest. The body armor charge
itself is a felony. This was the rapper's fifth arrest since July,
according to E! Online. OBD/Jones was released on $18,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: News reports say Montana is implementing a daytime speed
limit, which it didn't have until now. How does Montana's accident
rate compare with that of other states?
</P>
<P>
   A: Such a comparison isn't possible, said Tim Hurd of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, because Montana is
a ``very rural state'' with many highways that are lightly
traveled. To make a comparison with anyplace else, even another
rural state, would be ``apples and oranges,'' he added, and
therefore not valid. Montana's new 55- to 75-mph limits are
expected to take effect May 28, ending its status as the only state
in the nation without a daytime speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was Rutgers University ever a member of the Ivy League?
</P>
<P>
   A: A Rutgers InfoDEX spokeswoman said the New Jersey institution
has never been part of the Ivy League. Its members are Brown,
Columbia, Cornell, Dartmouth, Harvard, Pennsylvania, Princeton and
Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has happened in the case of a man who said he won a
fighter jet in a contest?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's still in the courts. The case involved John Leonard, who
in August 1996 tried to force PepsiCo Inc. to come up with a
Harrier jet that it appeared to be offering as a contest prize. In
a TV commercial, PepsiCo had depicted a computerized simulation of
a Harrier as a prize available to anyone accumulating 7 million
points in its Pepsi Stuff contest. To earn that many points, a
person would have to drink 16.8 million cans of Pepsi. But Leonard
said when he called the company, he was told he had the option of
buying ``Pepsi Points'' for 10 cents each. He then raised money
from several investors and presented Pepsi with 15 original points,
plus a check for $700,008.50.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi maintained that the commercial was a spoof, and when the
jet wasn't forthcoming, Leonard's Miami lawyers filed a lawsuit.
PepsiCo, too, filed suit, seeking to have Leonard's claims declared
frivolous, and seeking reimbursement for the company's legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Pentagon has said the $33.8 million fighter jets
would have to be ``demilitarized'' before being offered to the
public, which meant rendering them unable to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When and under what circumstances was the Pledge of
Allegiance introduced, and when was it changed to include the words
``under God?''
</P>
<P>
   A: The pledge to the flag was first published Sept. 8, 1892, in
the juvenile periodical The Youth's Companion, in this form: ``I
pledge allegiance to my Flag and the Republic for which it stands;
one nation, indivisible, with liberty and Justice for all.'' Public
school children first recited the pledge as they saluted the flag
during the National School Celebration that same year, marking the
400th anniversary of the discovery of America.
</P>
<P>
   The words ``the flag of the United States of America'' were
substituted for ``my Flag'' in 1924, and the pledge was recognized
officially by the U.S. government in 1942. In 1954, at the urging
of President Dwight Eisenhower, the Congress legislated that
``under God'' be added. The move to do so was spearheaded by the
Knights of Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was Ted Turner's full quote on adultery being eliminated
from the Ten Commandments? Where did he make his remark?
</P>
<P>
   A: In remarks first reported by The Washington Times, then
repeated by other news organizations, Turner said the Ten
Commandments are ``a little out of date.'' He then went on to say,
``If you're only going to have 10 rules, I don't know if
(prohibiting) adultery should be one of them.'' The comments came
in remarks Turner made Feb. 16 to a meeting of the National Family
Planning and Reproductive Health Association in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting spokeswoman Caroline Harkleroad said there
was no audio or video recording of the speech, and Turner had no
script, so it's not possible to provide any more information about
the exact wording. After the remarks were reported, Turner's office
released this statement: ``Mr. Turner regrets any offense his
comments may have caused and extends his heartfelt apologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some years ago, the popular rock duo Milli Vanilli created a
scandal when it was revealed that they didn't actually perform
their own songs, lip-synching instead to someone else's voices. Was
it ever revealed who their real singers were?
</P>
<P>
   A: Rob Pilatus and Fabrice Morvan identified the real vocalists
on their 1989 Grammy-winning album ``Girl You Know It's True'' as
Johnny Davis, Charles Shaw and Brad Howell. Pilatus and Morvan
later were stripped of the Grammy. In 1998, Pilatus was found dead
in a hotel room in Frankfurt, Germany. A combination of alcohol and
pills was suspected as the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've noticed lately that Tiger Woods isn't using his usual
caddy, whose name, I believe, is Fluff. Do you know any details?
Also, what is Fluff's background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Woods used Bryon Bell, a friend of his since junior high
school, a few times recently, but Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan is still
Woods' caddy, according to IMG, Woods' management company.
</P>
<P>
   Working for some 40 players since his first job at the Greater
Hartford (Conn.) Open in 1976, Cowan is one of the sport's most
entertaining and enduring figures. An accomplished golfer himself,
Cowan was the No. 1 player on the 1969 golf team at William Penn
College in Oskaloosa, Iowa. He turned pro in 1971and took up
caddying for PGA players in 1976. He caddied for Peter Jacobsen for
19 years, one of the longest relationships between a caddie and a
professional golfer on record. In August 1996, Cowan signed on to
dispense golf clubs and counsel to Woods.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that Cowan got then nickname from his resemblance to
former pro Steve ``Fluff'' Melnyk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard a lot about the Jerry Falwell-Teletubbies flap,
but I haven't seen any actual statement Falwell himself made on the
subject. What exactly did he say?
</P>
<P>
   A: The controversy deals with an article in the February issue
of National Liberty Journal, of which Falwell is publisher. The
article contained a ``Parents' Alert'' about children's television
programming, with one item headlined ``Tinky Winky Comes Out of the
Closet.'' It reported that the sexual orientation of the
Teletubbies character ``has been the subject of debate since the
series premiered in England in 1997,'' and pointed out that Tinky
Winky ``has become a favorite character among gay groups
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   On its Internet site _ http://www.falwell.com _ the Falwell
organization says this: ``Dr. Falwell has never seen the
Teletubbies TV program. Dr. Falwell has never commented in any way
on the Teletubbies. He did not `out' Tinky Winky.'' The Internet
statement says J.M. Smith, senior editor of the National Liberty
Journal, wrote the Parents' Alert. It adds, ``Editor Smith . . .
did not attack the Teletubbies or call for a boycott of the
Teletubbies. He simply documented information that had already been
reported in Time, People, The Washington Post, CNN, E-Online and
other national media over the past year.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell spokeswoman Laura Swickard confirmed to Q&AMP;A that Falwell
did not write the article in question. But she added that Falwell
was the author of a press statement on his Internet site. In it, he
writes: ``. . . while I'd like to laugh along with those who are
encouraging parents and critics to `lighten up' about children's
programming in general, and Teletubbies in particular, I find this
issue far too important to the future and well-being of our
children. . . . As a Christian, I believe that role-modeling the
gay lifestyle is damaging to the moral lives of children. I find
the flat denials of such a portrayal by Teletubbies producers to be
disingenuous and insufficient in answering the questions that have
been raised about the Tinky Winky character . . .''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
