<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5834 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE     03-03 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS04-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who can I contact to find out if I have any GI Bill
educational benefits left?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Department of Veterans Affairs has a new toll-free
telephone number for veterans and dependents to obtain information
on VA education benefits: 1-888-442-4551. The number operates 24
hours a day, seven days a week, and provides detailed eligibility
criteria and general background on VA programs, said VA spokesman
Tom Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans, reservists and National Guard members receiving
education benefits under the Montgomery GI Bill also may obtain
detailed information on their personal benefits account through the
new automated system. Callers can get specific questions answered
by education case managers during regular business hours.
</P>
<P>
   For Internet users, information also is available at
http://www.va.gov/education . Or call 1-800-827-1000, which will
connect you to your nearest VA regional office.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few years ago, I read that a white person has never been
sentenced or put to death in this country for the killing of a
black person. In view of the sentencing to death of John William
King in Texas for the killing of James Byrd Jr., can you confirm if
this is true?
</P>
<P>
   A: White people certainly have been executed for killing black
people in this country, but statistics have been disproportionate.
Since capital punishment resumed in the United States in 1977,
according to records compiled by the NAACP Legal Defense Fund, 11
whites have been executed in the United States for killing blacks,
while 142 blacks have been executed for killing whites. Only one
white man has ever been executed in Texas for killing a black man,
and that was in 1854. The case involved a feud between two farmers,
which climaxed when one killed the other's favorite slave.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Dollar bills have the letters A through L in a circle to the
left of the image of George Washington, with the names of cities
below. Why does it end with L, and why are only certain cities
named?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are only 12 letters (A through L) because they
correspond to the nation's 12 Federal Reserve Banks, said Edward
Sheehan of the Bureau of Engraving and Printing. The banks also
have a number. They are: Boston (1, A), New York (2, B),
Philadelphia (3, C), Cleveland (4, D), Richmond (5, E), Atlanta (6,
F), Chicago (7, G), St. Louis (8, H), Minneapolis (9, I), Kansas
City (10, J), Dallas (11, K) and San Francisco (12, L).
</P>
<P>
   The bank that authorizes a note can be determined by looking at
the black Federal Reserve seal on the bill. The name is printed
within the seal's border. The district's letter is in the center
and also begins the two serial numbers in the upper right and lower
left. The district's number appears at four places: on each side,
placed above and below the center.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do members of the Federal Reserve System Board of Governors,
such as Alan Greenspan, have limited terms in office, like members
of Congress? Or are they appointed for life?
</P>
<P>
   A: They aren't appointed for life. All board members are
nominated by the president and confirmed by the Senate. A full term
is 14 years; a member who serves a full term may not be
reappointed. The chairman (currently Greenspan) and the vice
chairman (Alice M. Rivlin) are named by the president from among
the members and are confirmed by the Senate. They serve a term of
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan took office as chairman June 20, 1996, for a third
four-year term. He originally took office as chairman _ and to fill
an unexpired term as a member of the board _ on Aug. 11, 1987. He
was reappointed to the board to a full 14-year term, which began
Feb. 1, 1992. He has been designated chairman by Presidents Reagan,
Bush and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about the Mediterranean diet? A
recent newspaper article indicated that it's supposed to help
prevent heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Mediterranean diet calls for more bread, more vegetables,
more fish, less red meat (replacing meat with chicken), some fruit
daily, and the use of canola oil and olive oil as the sources of
fat. It also replaces butter and cream with a special margarine
made with canola oil. A study done in France compared such a diet,
common in Mediterranean countries, with that of Northern Europeans,
which uses more animal fat, and found a dramatic reduction in new
manifestations of heart disease in people recovering from a
previous heart attack. Evidence presented at the American Heart
Association's annual meeting in 1996 also showed that the
Mediterranean diet may lower blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was it the voice of Shirley Jones that we hear singing in
``The Music Man,'' or was someone else's voice dubbed in?
</P>
<P>
   A: Dubbing in another singer's voice for Shirley Jones, who had
the role of Marian Paroo, would be like dubbing Frank Sinatra's
singing in ``Guys and Dolls'' or Barbra Streisand's in ``Hello,
Dolly!'' Unthinkable, in other words. Jones had demonstrated her
movie star quality, both acting and singing, several years earlier
in the film versions of ``Oklahoma!'' and ``Carousel.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubbing voices in big-screen musicals isn't entirely unknown,
however. Every film fan knows that Marni Nixon provided the singing
voice of Eliza Doolittle in the movie version of ``My Fair Lady,''
a role portrayed by Audrey Hepburn. But some other dubbed movie
voices may surprise you: Nan Wynn, not Rita Hayworth, sang the
sultry lyrics to ``Put the Blame on Mame'' in ``Gilda''; India
Adams sang Cyd Charisse's numbers in ``The Band Wagon''; Nixon
dubbed all of Natalie Wood's songs in ``West Side Story.'' Louanne
Hogan dubbed so many screen songs for Jeanne Crain that she was
known as ``Jeanne Crain's voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you update me on the status of the Chinese gymnast who
was paralyzed in an accident at the Goodwill Games? Where can
donations be sent?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sang Lan, 17, who broke her neck in a fall July 21 at the
Goodwill Games in New York, has been deemed fit to return to China
and is expected to make the trip in June. ``I'm very happy to go
back, but I will miss New York,'' she told a New York reporter
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Sang, who came to the Goodwill Games as the 1997 Chinese
national vault champion, remains paralyzed and unable to move from
the neck down. Although she must use a wheelchair, Sang has
stabilized sufficiently for doctors to approve the trip. The New
York Daily News reported that the teen has been under pressure from
the Chinese Gymnastic Association to return home, where she's a
national hero. Winston Sie, with whom Sang and her mother have been
staying, said the teen would undergo acupuncture, massage and
herbal remedies when she is back in China.
</P>
<P>
   Donations can be made to the Sang Lan Fund and mailed c/o Dr.
Kristjan Ragnarsson, Mount Sinai Medical Center, One Gustave L.
Levy Place, New York, NY 10029.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you print the address for President Clinton's legal
defense fund, for those who want to send a contribution?
</P>
<P>
   A: Checks can be sent to: Clinton Legal Expense Trust, Dept.
6007, Washington, DC 20042-6007. The maximum amount that can be
donated by an individual is $10,000 a year. Information:
202-347-0119.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some years back, quarterback Johnny Unitas completed an
amazing string of passes to lead the Baltimore Colts to victory
over the New York Giants in a championship game. Can you refresh my
memory about the details?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was in 1958. With two minutes to play for the NFL
championship, the Giants were ahead 17-14. The Colts were on their
own 14-yard line. Unitas completed seven consecutive passes to set
up a game-tying field goal with seven seconds left, then engineered
a 79-yard drive in sudden-death overtime that won the game, 23-17.
</P>
<P>
   You used the word ``amazing.'' It really was, considering that
Unitas was wearing a 9-pound protective corset of foam rubber and
steel because of three broken ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some time ago, I read that the heiress to the Levitz
furniture fortune was missing and her home was messed up. Was she
ever found?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The widow of furniture mogul Ralph Levitz was last seen
Nov. 18, 1995, and was reported missing two days later.
Investigators said they found a blood-soaked mattress and signs of
a struggle at her home overlooking the Mississippi River in
Vicksburg, Miss. She was 62 at the time of her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Covington, FBI case agent in Jackson, Miss., who is
handling the Levitz case, told Q&AMP;A that it's still an open
investigation. ``We are pursuing any and all leads that come to our
attention with the same aggression that we used when she was first
reported missing in 1995,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
