<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thank you, Jasper, for giving hope
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As a child, I looked forward to going
uptown with Mama. Walking along the dusty road that led from our
neighborhood to the business center of our small, rural Florida
town, she would meet friends and engage in candid conversation
usually kept from children. Although I always tried to feign
disinterest, I listened intently as the adults talked.
</P>
<P>
   It was on such a trek uptown that I heard Mama and one of her
friends talking about the troubles of Mrs. Williams, who attended
our church. ``That poor woman's had such a hard life,'' Mama
commented.
</P>
<P>
   As the conversation between Mama and her friend continued, I
learned that a few years earlier, Mrs. Williams had lost her only
child when the young man was accused of insulting a young white
girl as she returned home after a trip. Allegedly, Mrs. Williams'
son, who was doing yard work nearby, called out, ``Miss Smith, the
sight of you will cure the sore eye.''
</P>
<P>
   For this breach of racial protocol, police accused him of making
a sexual pass, arrested him and hauled him to jail. During the
night, he was castrated in his cell and left to bleed to death.
Without explanation, the sheriff offered Mrs. Williams her son's
body. No one was charged in the killing. No newspaper reported it.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that every black person has a lynching story. The
story of Mrs. Williams' son was the first of many such acts of
racially motivated depravity I was to learn of as I grew up.
Ultimately, it was not the brutality of the crimes that was
indelibly etched into my memory. Rather, it was the premise that
whites who committed such atrocities could act with the confident
expectation that no legal action would be taken against them. So
black people, potential targets for callous cruelty, had to live
with the parallel expectation that we are perpetually vulnerable to
such abuse because of our skin color.
</P>
<P>
   That early lesson prepared me to expect the worst. Thus, the
most surprising aspect of James Byrd Jr.'s murder in Jasper, Texas,
last June was not that men chained him by the ankles and dragged
him almost 3 miles behind a pickup truck until, still alive and in
excruciating pain, he was decapitated by a culvert.
</P>
<P>
   For many like me, who can cite a litany of cases marked by
blatant disregard for blacks' humanity, an even greater shock than
the atrocious killing is the fact that law officials in a small,
rural town _ Jasper's population is 7,000 _ acted swiftly to gather
evidence and arrest suspects. No cloak of silence by people of
integrity condoned the unconscionable cruelty inflicted on Mr.
Byrd. The media thoroughly reported the gruesome details of this
racially motivated crime. Public officials did not shirk their
prosecutorial duties because the victim was black and his accused
slayers white.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after a jury found John W. King guilty, he was
sentenced to death. The other two alleged accomplices face trial
this summer. Mr. King, a self-declared white supremacist said to be
proud of his action, surely will appeal, but for now he is the
452nd person on Texas' Death Row and the only white person
sentenced to die for killing a black person.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict accords Mr. Byrd the human dignity every citizen
deserves. The people of Jasper have publicly declared an end to the
tradition of making the murder of black men a permissible sport.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this new call to conscience does not bridge the chasm
that divides us nationwide. During the past decade, there has been
a dramatic increase in the number of hate groups across this
country. Even more disturbing, many white youths, emboldened by
anonymity, are using the Internet to connect with a network of
hatemongers, all convinced that their human worth depends on
establishing their racial superiority over others.
</P>
<P>
   Rooting out all racial tyranny, historically established in
practice and embedded in American traditions, may be impossible.
Still, the conviction of Mr. Byrd's killer lowers the expectation
that people of moral conscience will tolerate race-motivated
atrocities. For now, that's significant progress.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
