<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hey, remember the alamo?
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Servoice
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You'd think a business that has ``Alamo'' in its
name would do something to celebrate Texas Independence Day.
Something. Anything. Swap chili recipes. Serve nachos. Hurl insults
at somebody from New Jersey. Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   But after checking with these outfits, I found out I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 businesses listed in the Austin phonebook incorporate
Alamo in their titles. I called or visited several of them, and I
couldn't find one that was whooping it up Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Huber, owner of Alamo Sound Productions, celebrated Texas
Independence Day by _ dig this _ changing the oil in his 1977 Dodge
van in front of his house in South Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if you live in South Austin, changing your oil is
sort of a spiritual thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get much more glamorous than that; I'll be up to my
elbows in oil here in a few minutes,'' said Huber, who also planned
to wax his Mustang as part of his Texas Independence Day
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Huber uses Alamo in his business name because he had an Austin
band called Alamo Choir.
</P>
<P>
   The reason he used Alamo in the band name was that he'd had
several bands before, and he wanted Alamo Choir to be the last. And
he needed a name that would fit that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be my famous last stand, as far as a band
goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure. Many people in Austin celebrated Texas Independence
Day. On the Capitol grounds, hundreds of folks lined for barbecue
to take part in Ellis County Day.
</P>
<P>
   Around 12:35, they ran out of meat.
</P>
<P>
   Get a rope. Running out of meat at a Texas Independence Day
barbecue. That's like Pamplona running out of bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of barbecue, on Tuesday morning, Jim Bowie Jr. said he
would celebrate Texas Independence Day by barbecuing in his back
yard in East Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie, 66, a retired admininstrator for the Gary Job Corps in
San Marcos, has a good time being named Jim Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   ``See, I'm black,'' he said. ``And I spin this yarn about being
there (at the Alamo) with the Gonzales's and the Valenzuelas and
the Garcias, and start laughing.'' Actually, there were some black
people at the Alamo, said George B. Ward, of the Texas State
Historical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie carries a small pocket knife he tells everybody is his
Bowie knife. He's one of four Jim Bowies listed in the Austin phone
directory
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I know anybody named Davy Crockett? Sure don't,'' Bowie
said. But being named Jim Bowie has caused him trouble at least
once.
</P>
<P>
   He says around 2 o'clock in the morning several years ago he got
an angry phone call from a guy who was mad because somebody named
Jim Bowie had been going out with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, 'Man, I haven't been any place tonight,' `` Jim
Bowie Jr. recalled. ``I couldn't make him understand it wasn't
me.'' He should have told the guy he was really Col. William B.
Travis.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Alamo Glass, they weren't even sure why the place was
named Alamo Glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company has been in business over 30 years under that
name and I have no earthly idea how it got its name,'' said Karen
Ash, who runs the office.
</P>
<P>
   So the place has been around almost as long as the Alamo? ``It
feels like it sometimes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Alamo Hanger &AMP; Supply on North Lamar, they weren't
observing the day either. So why is it called Alamo Hanger &AMP;
Supply?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it sounded better than something like Jeff's Hangers
or whatever,'' said Dawn Proud, an employee.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Alamo Rent A Car at Robert Mueller Airport. ``I
haven't heard anything,'' said the lady who answered the phone when
I asked her if the company was celebrating Texas Independence Day.
``But you can call corporate.''
</P>
<P>
   Why bother? Corporate's in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
