<HEADER>
A5837 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX     03-03 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Averting our eyes is worse than seeing
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``This is hard, but you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Laqueta Flowers repeated the words of the district attorney to
herself, over and over. That's how the 41-year-old schoolteacher
steeled herself for her task as a juror: looking through page after
page of autopsy photos of James Byrd Jr.'s dismembered body, while
a pathologist described how he died. How he twisted and turned,
seeking relief from the excruciating pain of brush-burn abrasions,
as he was dragged along a bumpy road, a logging chain tied around
his ankles. How he was alive, during that three-mile stretch of
road, until his head was torn off by a concrete drainage duct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't turn this page,'' Flowers told herself as she opened
the black folder containing 14 crime-scene photographs. She turned
it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The jury listened conscientiously to the gruesome testimony and
took less than three hours to deliver a verdict. They convicted
John William King, a 24-year-old white supremacist, of murder.
</P>
<P>
   As I listened to Flowers speak on NPR's Morning Edition, I felt
ashamed of my own reluctance to look at this tragedy. I hadn't
wanted to think about it, to write about it. It was too horrible to
imagine what Byrd suffered, too painful to think how far we have to
go in eradicating racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton historian and retired teacher Margaret Peters thinks it's
important we don't avert our eyes. The murder warrants all the
national attention it has received, all the soul-searching. ``It
signals to people we haven't made the great strides we think we
have,'' said Peters, author of Dayton's African American Heritage .
``This country has never come to terms that this is a racist
country, anything that happens like that is an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters is reminded of a James Baldwin essay in which the
celebrated novelist compared America to a sick person who doesn't
know he's sick: ``If a country is sick and won't look at its past,
the country is not going to be all that it should be either. As a
nation we have never faced up to the fact we have always said one
thing and done another.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's horrifying murder didn't surprise Peters: ``Think of all
the people who have been lynched with no punishment. Think of the
photo of a lynched man who is being burned. There were all these
smiling faces plain to the camera. There were little kids there and
women and girls.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no justice for countless lynching victims. No justice
for Emmett Till, for Medgar Evers, for four little girls in a
Birmingham church. In many quarters, there was sympathy for the
killers, not the victims.
</P>
<P>
   This crime is as heinous as the rest, a measure of how far we
haven't come. But at least there is outrage. And there is justice:
King is the first white person in modern Texas history to be
sentenced to death in the murder of a black person.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Collins, 23, the only black on the jury, told NPR, ``Nobody
should be tortured that way. . . . This man knew what was happening
to him up until the point to where he was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the jury was making a statement: ``We're just
letting everybody know that we're not going to accept this at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict represents progress, but Peters warns against
complacency: ``Look a the growth of the Klan. There have been a lot
of legal changes, but all the laws on the books don't mean that
much if people don't change the way they think and feel.''
</P>
<P>
   We cannot avert our eyes; we cannot forget James Byrd. We must
honor his memory by examining our own hearts and actions, by
fighting racism wherever we find it.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard, but we must do it.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
