<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't forget to pick brain of older generation for future wisdom
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ With the days ticking down toward a new
millennium, it's easy to overlook how different our lives are today
compared to how Americans lived only 100 brief years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial and technological advances have accelerated Americans
through so many changes during the past 10 decades that today's
young people must find it difficult to understand that they are
breathing the same air as people who grew up without television,
microwave ovens, air-conditioning or shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans remember living in the rural areas where the food
was cooked on wood stoves, the water drawn from hand-dug wells and
the houses lighted with coal-oil lanterns.
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 percent of America's rural residents had electricity by
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Some of today's elderly mall walkers can remember when their
parents had to hitch the family horse or mule to a wagon before
they bounced their way to town to do the week's shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Although I've just ordered a new 500 MHz Pentium III computer
with 128 MB SDRAM and a 17 GB hard drive, I also have a working
knowledge of outhouses, butter churns and lye soap. I've gone from
scrub boards to mother boards.
</P>
<P>
   I remember listening to an old Civil War veteran tell about a
young fellow soldier getting shot in the private parts, which he
considered humorous. I've heard people talk about moving west in
Conestoga covered wagons.
</P>
<P>
   John L. Walker of Waco can remember more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 89 years old and don't have much time left,'' Walker wrote
recently after reading a guest column by Mattie Trantham about life
in the 1940s and '50s in neighboring Mexia.
</P>
<P>
   Trantham compared Mexia's crumbling downtown with the years of
her youth when the town bustled with commerce and life.
</P>
<P>
   Walker remembers Mexia from an earlier time, until his family
moved from Mexia in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   There was that time when ``a desperado came to town,'' he
recalled. Because there were no phones, a concerned Mexia citizen
``had to grab a horse and ride over to Groesbeck, the county seat,
to get the sheriff.'' The sheriff rode the 12 miles into town and
cornered the desperado at a ``small eating place'' where the two
men ``had a shoot-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidently the sheriff was a good shot and very confident. ``The
sheriff hit him (the desperado) six times but in no vital place.''
The desperado ran out the back door and ``down towards Ross
Avenue,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sheriff, having shot six times, was out of bullets,''
Walker said. With his six-shooter empty and having not bothered to
bring extra ammunition, the sheriff interrupted his pursuit to stop
by the local hardware store for more ammunition. But the store was
sold out of that caliber. The sheriff rode back to Groesbeck,
reloaded and continued his pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the outcome was obvious, Walker didn't bother to
finish the story. He did, however, tell about how after Mr.
Humphrey discovered oil and ``some smart aleck in order to keep the
dust down'' poured oil on Mexia's dirt streets and caused a huge
mess.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is difficult to grasp that there are a lot of
people even older than Walker who have experienced an amazing
journey. Their memories sound like stories from time travelers.
</P>
<P>
   For their own sakes, young people today should seek out the
stories of elderly relatives and neighbors who, like Walker,
``don't have much time left.''
</P>
<P>
   As rapidly as technology continues to accelerate, future
generations will be spellbound with the retelling of these
firsthand stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean you actually met someone who remembers when there
were no computers? You really mean they lived in houses with no
electricity? What did they use, photovoltaic?''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas. E-mail: RNethaway(AT)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
