<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5839 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUHN-COLUMN04-COX     03-03 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUHN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The boxer and the fighter
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Greg Link was 6 years old, riding his bicycle one
day in Kettering in the summer of 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He fell over the handlebars and landed on his chin.
</P>
<P>
   How many thousand kids fall off their bikes every day in
America?
</P>
<P>
   How many get up, mom puts a bandage on the cut and it's
forgotten two days later?
</P>
<P>
   How many spend the rest of their lives bouncing between
piercing, all-day headaches; recurrent vomiting; seizures; painful
spinal taps, and never-ending shunt surgeries?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's sure if that was the cause,'' said Connie Link of her
son's 14-year battle for a normal life. ``But the headaches started
about three months after the fall, and that's the only thing we can
tie to it.''
</P>
<P>
   An infection? A virus? Nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   It's called benign intercranial hypertension. Fluid builds up
between the brain and skull and begins to squeeze the brain. Normal
bodies drain and replace that fluid three times a day. Greg's body
refused to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he was misdiagnosed as having migraine headaches and
treated with pills. Finally, after three years of no relief,
someone got it right.
</P>
<P>
   Thus started two years of spinal taps to remove the fluid.
Thirty spinal taps in all. Long needles shoved into his back.
Needles that too often missed and hit nerves instead, leaving Greg
unable to walk the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how painful spinal taps are?'' said Brian Link,
Greg's older brother. ``Then they started in with the shunt
surgeries, and the valves didn't work right or the tubes got
plugged, and they kept operating on him over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty surgeries,'' Connie Link said. ``Twice they cut into
his eyes and put slits in his optic nerves to help drain the
fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be sitting there in pain, looking forward to the next
surgery, with the attitude that this would be the one that
worked,'' Brian said. ``And I just said to myself, 'What a special
kid.' He blows my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Link is 20 now and still fighting the good fight. Brother
Brian is 23 and works in Cincinnati for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
It was Brian who set in motion the highlight of Greg's mostly
pain-ridden existence.
</P>
<P>
   Greg fell in love with boxing in 1993. ``I don't want to sound
too dramatic,'' he said, ``but it's two guys, one-on-one, with no
teammates to bail them out. I see a comparison between my fight
with this disease and what boxers do.''
</P>
<P>
   He adopted Pernell ``Sweet Pea'' Whitaker as his favorite after
watching highlights of Whitaker's controversial 1993 draw with
Julio Cesar Chavez. Greg, age 13, thought Whitaker clearly won the
fight, but was impressed even more by Sweet Pea's demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just accepted it,'' Greg said. ``He just calmly said, 'They
robbed me. I'll let the fans decide.' I liked that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw himself in Whitaker, cheated but unbowed; down but
unbroken.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, as Greg's shunt failed again and he was about
to go in for another operation, brother Brian got one of Greg's
boxing magazines, found the address for Main Event, the boxing
promotion organization, and wrote a letter to Shelly Finkel,
Whitaker's manager, asking for an autographed picture.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, it came. ``To Greg,'' it said. ``Stay strong.''
And it was signed, ``Sweet Pea.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg's spirits were lifted, but reality set back in just as
quickly. He enrolled at Wright State in the fall of 1997 after
earning a diploma from Alter High through home study with the help
of a dedicated tutor named Nan Becker. But a WSU math teacher told
Greg she had an ``attendance policy'' and if he missed more than
five classes, whatever the reason, his grade would be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Greg said he tried to explain his situation, but she wouldn't
listen. He withdrew from school and slid ``into a funk.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian wrote another letter to Finkel, and Finkel, a marvelous
man, quickly arranged a phone call from Whitaker to Greg. ``He told
me to hang in there and don't give up,'' Greg said. ``And then he
said the next time he fights, he was going to fly me in as his
personal guest.''
</P>
<P>
   One fight fell through, but when another fight was scheduled,
Finkel called and started the arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Two Fridays ago, Brian and Greg flew to New York where the VIP
treatment awaited. They were met at the airport by a chauffeur
holding their names on a cardboard sign, and he drove them to a
hotel across the street from Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They did the New York scene _ ate, gawked, walked the streets,
counted cabs, rejected guys selling watches for next-to-nothing. On
fight night, they were in Row 8 at the Garden. ``My heart never
stopped pounding,'' Greg said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker lost to Felix Trinidad, but worse, had his jaw broken
in the process. Greg and Brian were supposed to meet Whitaker after
the fight, but Sweet Pea went to the hospital, and the meeting
never happened.
</P>
<P>
   A stretch limo took them to the airport the next morning and
they flew back to Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   A week-and-a-half later, Greg is still in awe.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat in his family room Tuesday morning, Greg Link showed
no signs of the disease that flogs him every day. He is 6-foot-1, a
solid 195 pounds, and his spirit is larger than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wake up with a bad headache,'' he said, ``then I get up and
for the next two hours it slowly goes away as the shunt drains the
fluid. Then it comes back and just keeps getting worse the rest of
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes to bed around midnight, but never goes to sleep. At 2 or
2:30 a.m., he slips one of his collection of 200 fight videotapes
into the VCR and watches. If he still can't sleep, he puts in
another one. He has seen them all 20-30 times. He knows the punch
sequences by heart. Doesn't matter. This is Greg Link's escape. At
4 or 4:30, he closes his eyes again and finally finds peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Pernell Whitaker did restored my faith in professional
athletes,'' said Greg's father, Bill, a project planner for auto
parts manufacturer Valeo. ``This shows they're not all bums. That
there are some hearts there.''
</P>
<P>
   He's watched his son fight for 14 years. So he damn well knows
what heart is.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
