<HEADER>
A5840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDIES-COMMENTARY04-     03-03 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIES-COMMENTARY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENT: Studies may be hazardous to your health
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Monday's headline, ``Working moms can
quit feeling guilty, study says,'' prompted me to launch my own
study on just how many studies are out there.
</P>
<P>
   My findings? 519 in the last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   My study also showed that if you don't like a study, just wait a
while. Another study will come along to say just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   But the working mom study goes to show that you never can tell
about studies.
</P>
<P>
   Harken back to the early 1980s and you'll find a University of
Massachusetts study linking working moms and developmental problems
in their children. And yet when the same 6,000 children were
tracked to age 12, retesting showed early developmental differences
had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being employed is not going to harm the children,''
psychologist Elizabeth Harvey concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Both studies then and now are flawed, of course, because they
neglect the role of guilt in child-rearing. The increased
guilt-load of the working mom meant they strove mightily to
compensate, closing the gap on the guilt-free stay-at-homes.
</P>
<P>
   Look for my brilliant analysis to trigger blizzards of studies
setting guilt-quotient (G.Q.) minimums for successful
child-rearing, followed by later studies to show the first studies
were full of beans.
</P>
<P>
   Examples abound. Oat bran? I need only quote The Washington Post
from April 1991: ``Oat bran's reputation as a cholesterol fighter,
exalted and then sullied by conflicting scientific studies, is on
the rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Got that? First oat bran was good. Then not so good. Now good
again. Forget the cholesterol issue, I just want somebody to tell
me how to stop having these disturbing dreams about a naked Wilford
Brimley trying to entice me into a hot tub full of Quaker Oats,
saying, ``Come on in. It's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of nightmares, I have read wildly contradictory studies
insisting that dreams are A.) profoundly meaningful or B.) mental
gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of gibberish, a study yet to be refuted showed that
jet lag could be cured by shining an ultra-violet light on the skin
behind the knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were flabbergasted,'' admitted Dr. Michael Menaker, a
biologist at the University of Virginia. ``For three days we tried
to find flaws in the experiment and we couldn't.'' (Expect ``The
Jet Leg'' to be marketed before the opposing studies are released.)
</P>
<P>
   You're familiar with the self-esteem movement? Until quite
recently, you couldn't swing a cat without hitting some expert
linking all that is bad in children _ academic failure, drug use,
bullying _ to low self-esteem. Turns out there were never any
studies saying any such thing. The links were assumed to exist.
</P>
<P>
   When it finally occurred to researchers to test the connection
between self-esteem and academic achievement, all studies agreed
for once: There wasn't any.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists Harold Stevenson and James Stiegler tested the
academic skills of elementary students in the United States, China,
Japan and Taiwan, and found that the Asian students excelled, but
the Americans had higher self-esteem. Albert Bandura, a Stanford
psychology professor, published research showing that self-esteem
``effects neither personal goals nor performance.''
</P>
<P>
   As for bullies and their self-esteem, I turn to a New York Times
report from 1996: ``Contrary to popular belief, bullies are not
inwardly anxious, insecure children. Rather, when tested, bullies
tend to score high in self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Another casualty of my research into what studies show before
they change their minds and show something else was my assumption
that there is such thing as a mid-life crisis. I had rather counted
on it _ had looked forward to it, in fact _ and now feel rather let
down to find that it, too, may be a myth.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day I read that far from being a time of failing
health and personal turmoil, ``middle age for many is the most
fulfilling time of life,'' according to a 10-year study sponsored
by the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   According to social psychologist Orville Gilbert, professional
killjoy, nine out of 10 middle-aged men and women surveyed said
they never experienced a mid-life crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Even menopause was cited as no big deal by Alice Rossia, a
professor of sociology at the University of Massachusetts. ``For
most middle-aged women,'' the study said, ``menopause is a benign
experience, a far cry from the view of many contemporary writers.''
</P>
<P>
   So as I read this, if female menopause is overstated, then male
menopause has got to be a scam by somebody at Chrysler with far too
many back lots full of red Sebring convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   Have we learned anything? Yes. And no. Studies show that we
aren't getting enough garlic, fish oil, sleep, leafy greens, tomato
sauce, soy products and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we are. We just have to wait for the next study.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
