<HEADER>
A5841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN04-COX     03-03 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going back to my old school
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ As ultra-cool and cynical (not to mention
smart aleck) students of Baylor University in the 70s, my future
husband and I would often make fun of the rabid alumni who returned
to campus, decked out in green and gold from head to toe. Most
delightful were the dignified gentlemen in dark green slacks
sporting a gold stripe up the seams and a matching gold jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Ahem.
</P>
<P>
   Paul and I returned last week, more than a little hopeful that
our second child might choose to attend our alma mater. We
discovered with our first that you truly reap what you sow. Having
been reared by parents who judiciously followed a philosophy of
producing independent thinkers and doers, she choose a school seven
states away.
</P>
<P>
   The Legacy Weekend, as last week's recruiting visit was billed,
was aimed at children of alumni. If Kathryn Alana picks Baylor and
the largest Baptist university in the world picks her, she will be
the third generation in our family to attend classes there, and
upon graduation, one of about a dozen members of both of our
families who are BU alumni.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend offered an opportunity to see the campus and left me
amazed at how much things change and how much they really don't.
</P>
<P>
   We visited Penland Hall, a men's dorm that was inhabited by
freshman men when I attended. My freshman dorm was across the
street and had no dining hall, so we ate at Penland. The food was
bad and the lobby smelled like a gym. And there was always a group
of boys in that lobby checking out the chicks and trying to make
time. They were amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, we saw Penland's refurbished lobby and its cafeteria
that would rival many restaurants. The lobby looked better, but it
still smelled. And those same guys who hung out there 20 years ago
were still there, but this time they ignored me and focused on
Kathryn and her friend Lauren. I still thought they were amusing.
My husband had little comment. I think I heard him mutter,
``apes.''
</P>
<P>
   We explored much of the campus, admitting to only some of the
mischief we had created. We wandered to Cameron Park and told the
tale of Lovers' Leap. We ate at Cupp's Drive In, one of the few
remaining greasy spoons near campus, now a neighbor to such chain
outlets as Schlotzsky's and Burger King. I saw the duplex where I
lived my junior and senior years, now surrounded by new apartment
complexes and condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   We visited beautiful campus mainstays such as Old Main and Pat
Neff Hall, and the ultra modern music and fine arts buildings. We
gawked at so much more that is being built, but discovered Baylor
is still a small place where you always see somebody you know. We
ran into Paul's fraternity brother, Faron Cain from Hallsville,
escorting some legacies of his own around campus.
</P>
<P>
   We lamented not returning more often and secretly hoped that our
child would give us an excuse to do so. How did she ever become so
independent?
</P>
<P>
   And we promised not to get the green outfits with the gold
stripes, but gave ourselves permission to be just a little
sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal, Longview, Texas. E-mail:
</P>
<P>
   awalker(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
