<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5843 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-HAIR04-COX     03-03 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HAIR04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAIR FARE: Designers enhance their creations with shear
determination
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the runway, hair can be an extension of a
designer's look.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, sometimes it's just hair extensions.
</P>
<P>
   The last day of Fashion Week featured some heavy hitters _
Calvin Klein, Vera Wang, Han Feng and Donna Karan. Here is a peek
at what their hairstylists whipped up, and why:
</P>
<P>
   HAN FENG _ Guy Laurent ``I was thinking Princess Leia, but much
more simple. The key was to use as few accessories as possible.''
He divided each model's hair into a number of portions, depending
on the shape of the model's face, and used plastic bands to wrap
them into place. (Models had to cut them out of their hair.)
</P>
<P>
   VERA WANG _ Rolando Beauchamp ``Her collection was in greens and
browns, kind of earthy. Sort of a calico cat. When I saw the
clothes, I thought calico.'' He glued in hair extensions in colors
slightly different from the model's own _ to fit the calico idea _
then used thinning shears on the ends. ``I don't think hair should
ever be blunt on the ends.''
</P>
<P>
   DONNA KARAN _ Odile Gilbert ``It is what a woman would do at
work _ they have a pencil and make sort of a chignon. It's very
much Donna Karan when you see her.'' Instead of using a pencil, she
used lengths of glass piping from a laboratory in her native
France. Then she used anti-frizz spritz for a little shine.
</P>
<P>
   CALVIN KLEIN _ Peter Butler ``The clothing was so structured we
wanted something simple and easy, to look like the women did it
themselves. I wouldn't call it a chignon or anything as classic as
that.'' He used a little dry mousse for texture, then put the hair
in a ponytail, twisted a few times and pinned it.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
