<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE-BIRTHDAY _ People, the ``mother of all human interest
magazines,'' turns 25 years old Friday (March 5). It's the magazine
that most shrewdly anticipated and capitalized on our national
obsession with celebrity. People was a punchline in ``The Big
Chill,'' when it served as an emblem for empty fluff (''It's just
good investigative journalism'' deadpanned Jeff Goldblum, who
played a People reporter), but, in fact, has expertly gauged what
we want to read about. With 33 million readers and spinoffs such as
InStyle and Teen People going strong, and ongoing expansion into
television and cyberspace, the franchise looks durable. A look at
the People phenomenon. (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-MILAN _ MILAN, Italy _ First report from Milan fashion
shows. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   COXNET- FOOD 0226 _ A pot of gumbo attracts like a magnet. It
pulls you to smell the smokiness of the dark brown roux, to dip in
a spoon and bite into a succulent chunk of sausage or a tender
shrimp, to sip the hearty broth and feel the tickle of pepper at
the back of the throat. Talk about Lou-easy-ana heaven. (Crider,
Austin American Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   RECIPE: Chicken and Sausage Gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPICE _ Sure, we Yanks have our varied pauses that refresh,
and happy hours abound, but they don't come close to equaling the
civilizing, meditative, revitalizing, reflective ambience of taking
tea. We can only speculate what all that cozy, civilizing daily
reflection would have done for us. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet FOOD page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CARAMELIZED _ You see the descriptor on the menu _
caramelized _ and in an instant, you're a kid again on the midway
at the county fair. Your Mom is trying to get you enthused about
the pig races, but you're too busy crunching into that caramel
apple, smacking up the sticky-sweet-burnt coating. ``It's nostalgic
and homey. Everybody loves the idea of caramelizing,'' said Anne
Quatrano, chef of Floataway Cafe. The descriptor is showing up on
more and more restaurant menus _ and it's not just for desserts.
Quatrano's menu features caramelized onion pizzas and pork chops
with caramelized turnips. We cooked with her and offer those
recipes and more along with tips for bronzing our favorite foods.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO and LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CARAMELIZED-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Caramelized
story centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
Italian Cream Cake. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ A weekly beer column by the Michael
Skube of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This week: Bock Beer.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TOOLS _ A look at the tools for a cutting-edge kitchen, as
defined by Anne Willan, founder of La Varenne and author of 18
cookbooks. We took her to a cookware store to show us what to buy
and look for in equipment. Your won't believe what she said about
rolling pins. Or this weird zester grater that she thinks is the
greatest new thing. (Crider, Austin American-Statesman). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-TOOLS-WILLAN _ Who is this woman? How does she cook? What
does she think? (Crider, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CUMIN _ The increasingly popular and pungent spice takes its
roots from a tiny seed. (Heller, Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BRIEFS _ Food shorts. (Heller, Dayton Daily News). WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COOKBOOKS _ WEST PALM BEACH , Fla. _ What does it take to put
one of these community cookbooks together, and do they really sell
beyond your church, or women's club or firehouse? A look at small,
but profitable recipe collections, and the people whose job it is
to badger people into giving recipes. (Norris, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MATISSE _ Review of ``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry,''
exhibit at Fort Worth's Kimbell Art Museum through May 2. This is
perhaps the major art exhibit in Texas for the first half of '99,
and the Kimbell attracts arts lovers regionwide. (Schade, Austin
American-Statesman). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-PREVIEW _ AUSTIN _ The music industry calls it ``spring
break,'' as its swarms invade the streets of Austin, Texas, with
the margarita-swilling abandon of collegians in Daytona. For the
Austin economy, it is ``Christmas in March,'' though local hotels,
clubs and restaurants consider it more like Mardi Gras and the
Super Bowl rolled into one. It is best recognized by the
unpronounceable acronym of SXSW, though it is more properly known
as the South by Southwest Music and Media Conference (by day, and
the South by Southwest Music Festival by night). (McLeese, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
</P>
