<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, March 4, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ ``This is hard, but you can do
it.'' Laqueta Flowers repeated the words of the district attorney
to herself, over and over. That's how the 41-year-old schoolteacher
steeled herself for her task as a juror: looking through page after
page of autopsy photos of James Byrd Jr.'s dismembered body, while
a pathologist described how he died. As I listened to Flowers speak
on NPR's Morning Edition, I felt ashamed of my own reluctance to
look at this tragedy. I hadn't wanted to think about it, to write
about it. It was too horrible to imagine what Byrd suffered, too
painful to think how far we have to go in eradicating racial
hatred. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ Last week, after a jury found John W. King
guilty, he was sentenced to death. The other two alleged
accomplices face trial this summer. Mr. King, a self-declared white
supremacist said to be proud of his action, surely will appeal, but
for now he is the 452nd person on Texas' Death Row and the only
white person sentenced to die for killing a black person. The
verdict accords Mr. Byrd the human dignity every citizen deserves.
The people of Jasper have publicly declared an end to the tradition
of making the murder of black men a permissible sport. Still, this
new call to conscience does not bridge the chasm that divides us
nationwide. (Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STUDIES-COMMENTARY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Monday's headline,
``Working moms can quit feeling guilty, study says,'' prompted me
to launch my own study on just how many studies are out there. My
findings? 519 in the last year alone. My study also showed that if
you don't like a study, just wait a while. Another study will come
along to say just the opposite. (Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ With the days ticking down
toward a new millennium, it's easy to overlook how different our
lives are today compared to how Americans lived only 100 brief
years ago. Some of today's elderly mall walkers can remember when
their parents had to hitch the family horse or mule to a wagon
before they bounced their way to town to do the week's shopping.
John L. Walker of Waco can remember more. (Nethaway, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ You'd think a business that has
``Alamo'' in its name would do something to celebrate Texas
Independence Day. Something. Anything. Swap chili recipes. Serve
nachos. Hurl insults at somebody from New Jersey. Whatever. But
after checking with these outfits, I found out I was wrong. About
30 businesses listed in the Austin phonebook incorporate Alamo in
their titles. I called or visited several of them, and I couldn't
find one that was whooping it up Tuesday. (Kelso, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WALKER-COLUMN _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ As ultra-cool and cynical (not
to mention smart aleck) students of Baylor University in the 70s,
my future husband and I would often make fun of the rabid alumni
who returned to campus, decked out in green and gold from head to
toe. Most delightful were the dignified gentlemen in dark green
slacks sporting a gold stripe up the seams and a matching gold
jacket. Ahem. Paul and I returned last week, more than a little
hopeful that our second child might choose to attend our alma
mater. We discovered with our first that you truly reap what you
sow. (Walker, Longview News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
