 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No. 423 - March 3, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 423 -- March 3, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. WILL OSCAR CHOOSE LOVE OR WAR? Steven Spielberg's ``Saving
Private Ryan'' is the heavy favourite in the Oscar race for best
picture. But ``Shakespeare in Love'' is also a strong contender.
Will the winner be love or war? By Jay Carr. BPI. 1,300 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
JULIAN LENNON ``Did you intend to come back with another album?''
An emphatic ``No'' is the quick answer from Julian Lennon, the
once-shy son of Beatles icon John and his first wife, Cynthia. The
new album, ``Photograph Smile,'' is a triumph of grit and
perseverance for a Lennon who was considered finished in the eyes
of the industry. Julian is not afraid to lash out at the business,
nor to criticize Yoko Ono for what he perceives as diminishing his
role in the Lennon legacy. By Steve Morse. BPI. 1,100 words +
photo. 3. SCHOOL OF JACQUOT ``All stories are about the masks that
people wear to reveal or to conceal certain aspects of the rapport
between men and women,'' says French director Benoit Jacquot. He is
gaining bigger and bigger audiences at home and abroad for quirky
films that deal with the profound moments of personal
relationships, revealing what makes some work and others
dysfunction. By Dan Yakir. BPI. 800 words + photo. 4. ALANIS
MORISSETTE Alanis Morissette, who is far better known as the rock
singer who sold 28 million copies of her album ``Jagged Little
Pill,'' went to Calcutta and spent a day helping the sick and
infirm at a healing centre run by Mother Teresa's Missionaries of
Charity. She came back from India and wrote and recorded her single
``Thank U,'' which distills some of her spiritual learning. By
changing from the simpler girl/boy subject matter of the first
album to more complex spiritual issues, Morissette knows that she
has lost some of her listeners, especially the younger ones. By
Steve Morse. 1,200 words + photo. 5. MISS MOSS Fresh from a highly
publicized sabbatical - in a London psychiatric and rehab clinic -
celebrity super-model Kate Moss discusses her revamped views on
life, work and partying hard. By Bridget Foley. From W magazine.
1,000 words + photos. 6. A REAL-LIFE ROMANTIC COMEDY Myles
Berkowitz had an acting career that was going nowhere - until he
came up with the idea to film his dates and turn the experiences
into a feature film. The result is ``20 Dates,'' a surprising,
reality-based romantic comedy that has been a hit on the festival
circuit. The movie proves that Berkowitz has the one crucial
component for Hollywood success : a willingness to go to any
extreme to make it big. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
MICHELLE PFEIFFER AND A MOTHER'S NIGHTMARE A disappearing child
figures in Michelle Pfeiffer's new film, ``The Deep End of the
Ocean.'' Pfeiffer - who also co-produced the film - plays a young
mother whose child vanishes in a crowded hotel lobby, not to be
seen again for years. Pfeiffer admits that acting out every
mother's worst nightmare made her heart pound. ``After doing this
movie, I never let my kids out of my sight,'' she says. By Cindy
Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 8.
BILLY JOEL : IT'S STILL ROCK AND ROLL, BUT HE'S
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR MORE Billy Joel has had his share of idols and
musical inspirations since he started writing songs more than three
decades ago (they include Jerry Lee Lewis, Elvis Presley, Ray
Charles and John Lennon.) On March 15 he will be inducted into the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. But these days Joel finds a more
appealing model in the composer George Gershwin. He has surprised
his fans by announcing that he has given up writing lyric-driven
pop songs in favour of sweeping instrumental melodies. By Gary
Graff. 1,000 words + photo.
</P>
