<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, March 3, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-DRUG-LAWS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Bishop Howard Hubbard and the Rev.
Al Sharpton. Upstate conservative Sen. John DeFrancisco and Queens
liberal Assemblyman Jeffrion Aubry. They're people who have almost
nothing in common, with one exception: They want to soften the
state's Rockefeller drug laws that mandate prison sentences of at
least 15 years for offenders caught possessing or selling
relatively small amounts of drugs. By LARA JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   THREE-STRIKES (San Francisco) _ A new study, partly based on San
Francisco statistics, says that California's ``three-strikes'' law
is not responsible for the 37 percent reduction in crime throughout
the state over the past four years. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   HEADWATERS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Politicians put a majestic
face on the Headwaters deal signed this week. Buying about 10,000
acres of redwood groves, some with stunning trees 1,500 years old,
was akin to creating a new Yosemite along the misty California
coast, they said. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE-40 (Houston) _ On March 9, Babs turns the big 4-0. My,
she's aged well, but what, really, has it gotten her? She's still
single. She's still searching for a career she can stick with.
She's still ... plastic. But that's OK. She's also still beloved by
millions of little girls, maybe even more so by their mothers. By
RENE KIENTZ.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader who has a 20-year-old
ponytail plant that is 12 feet tall and is touching the ceiling
wants to know how best to trim the plant. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MANAGERIAL-STYLE (San Francisco) _ Even if you build a better
mousetrap, your business still might fail and your employees still
might be miserable if you have a mousy CEO. There are all sorts of
horror stories about overbearing bosses and indecisive managers,
but management consultant Patrick Lencioni says the problems at the
top have more in common than you might think. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST-IMPRESSIONS (San Francisco) _ Even when he was busy
writing bestselling motivational books and making speeches around
the country, Harvey Mackay made sure he hired two key people at his
Mackay Envelope Corp.: the company president and the telephone
receptionist. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   H-P-SPLIT (San Francisco) _ The announced split of
Hewlett-Packard into two separate companies was fueled by Wall
Street pressures that its late co-founder once vowed to avoid. ``We
have never sold any stock,'' David Packard proclaimed in a 1952
lecture to securities analysts. ``And I hope we never have to.'' By
MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   H-P-ANALYSIS (San Francisco) _ Splitting itself into two
businesses makes perfect sense for Hewlett-Packard Co. By
announcing Tuesday it would create two separate companies, Wall
Street analysts said the Palo Alto-based technology giant shouldn't
be hampered by its arcane equipment testing and scientific products
divisions anymore. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   H-P-QUESTIONS (San Francisco) _ H-P Chief Executive Lewis Platt,
a 33-year H-P veteran who also announced Tuesday he'll retire once
the split is finished, answers questions. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-DONNY-MARIE (Undated) _ Famous siblings Donny &AMP; Marie Osmond
are devoted to God and family _ and it comes across on their
daytime talk show. ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' is No. 2 among the national
crop of new talk shows. By MIKE McDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Ordering food ``to go'' has never
carried such long-distance implications. Used to be, when you
ordered fish tacos for ``take out'' you were taking them home or to
the office. Now, chances are you're taking them to St. Louis or Los
Angeles. And at 35,000 feet above normal seafood level, too. By
HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-RENAISSANCE (Undated) _ Renaissance, the Florida-based
cruise line, is making waves with its direct-to-the-consumer
marketing campaign. If you want to save a buck, bypass the
travel-agent community and take a look at what Renaissance has to
offer. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   With: TRAVEL-RENAISSANCE-PACKAGES
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-R2SHIP (Lisbon, Portugal) _ The R2 made its debut in
December as the second _ hence the 2 _ of four new ships to be
launched by Renaissance Cruises during a 14-month period. The R2's
regular route covers the Mediterranean and coastal Spain. While the
ports and shore excursions provide enriching experiences, the ship
itself is delightful. By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CRYSTAL (Undated) _ By stressing cultural enrichment,
diverse itineraries and alternative dining options, Crystal Cruises
is at the cutting edge of what many see as cruising's future. ``The
large majority of our guests aren't on board to vegetate,'' Crystal
Cruises President Joseph Watters says of the Los Angeles-based
line. ``They want to be educated. They want their lives to be
enriched.'' By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-LING (San Francisco) _ ``Wow, cool, an Asian girl with
attitude!'' That was high school senior Fam Saechao's initial
assessment of Ling, the newest and nastiest character on prime-time
TV's hottest hit, ``Ally McBeal.'' Asian America _ and a lot of the
country _ is abuzz about Ling Woo and the scene-stealing Chinese
American actress, Lucy Liu, who plays her on the Fox show. By ANNIE
NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PINK-WINES (Albany, N.Y.) _ In wine stores, in wine journals and
even at the recent Albany American Wine Festival, rose wines are
getting more attention than they have seen since you drank Mateus.
And even if the public's interest in roses has grown only slightly
in recent years, winemakers are betting on pink making a comeback.
By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It is with a heavy heart and not
a little nausea that I resign from the Bill Clinton defense team. I
have run fresh out of the benefit of the doubt and can no longer
bend way over backward. Saddest of all, the cost of keeping a
staunch defender of reproductive rights sitting in the White House
just climbed out of my price range. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
