<HEADLINE>
WEB PUBLICATIONS BREAK AWAY FROM PRINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the difference between reading a newspaper or magazine on
the Internet or in print? The articles tend to be the same in both
versions, and aside from saving a few dollars, the only real
difference is that one can be read on the subway and the other
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   But this is beginning to change. The number of articles written
exclusively for Web sites of newspapers and magazines is growing,
according to a study to be released Tuesday by Middleburg &AMP;
Associates, a public relations and marketing agency.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth annual Media in Cyberspace Study was based on a survey
sent to managing and business editors at 1,400 newspapers and 2,000
magazines last fall and completed by 192 newspaper editors and 170
magazine editors. The study focuses on two aspects of the
relationship between the print media and cyberspace: the elevation
of newspaper and magazine Web sites to the status of full partner
with their print counterparts and the willingness of journalists to
use the Internet to find sources and to use e-mail to get
information from them.
</P>
<P>
   The study reports that the growth in Web sites over the last
four years has been sharp. In the 1995 study, 25 percent of
respondents said that their publications had a Web site; in 1998,
that figure had more than doubled, to 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And as the number of Web sites has proliferated, the amount of
original material on the sites has grown as well. Only 11 percent
of respondents who worked at magazines with Web sites said that the
sites had less than 5 percent original content, down from 27
percent in 1997. Newspaper respondents reported a drop to 22
percent from 39 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``News organizations have clearly broken away from the trend to
use Web sites solely as a delivery tool,'' said Don Middleburg,
chairman and chief executive at Middleburg, who was co-author of
the study with Steven R. Ross, associate professor of professional
practice at the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism.
``They've begun treating them as a new medium.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the growing use of multimedia elements _ mainly audio
and video recordings _ on Web sites as the prime example of this;
nearly a third of the respondents said that their publications
integrate multimedia material into Web articles.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists working at these publications are also making a
greater use of the Internet. A majority said the most important
information they find on it is contact information. But once they
have that information, journalists are still relying on
old-fashioned methods for evaluating the trustworthiness of
sources; most of the respondents said they would rather see the
face or at least hear the voice of a new source before exchanging
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   After that initial meeting though, many preferred e-mail to a
phone call or lunch date.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW J. ROSENBERG
</P>
<P>
   Praise From `60 Minutes'
</P>
<P>
   Last March, the CBS News program ``60 Minutes'' attracted a
burst of attention with an interview in which Kathleen Willey, a
former White House volunteer, accused President Clinton of making
unwelcome sexual advances toward her in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, ``60 Minutes'' drew volleys of criticism for not
checking Ms. Willey's background thoroughly enough, as other news
organizations reported inconsistencies in her various accounts,
along with reports that she had been pursuing a book deal.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months later, NBC News had an exclusive interview in
which Juanita Broaddrick, a former Arkansas campaign volunteer,
accused Clinton of unwanted sexual advances _ indeed, of rape _ 21
years earlier. In this case, the TV network attracted criticism
from some quarters for ``suppressing'' the interview, as NBC brass
spent weeks double-checking Mrs. Broaddrick's account.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, ``Dateline NBC'' executives did not want a Kathleen
Willey-type boomerang flying back in their faces. Even after the
interview ran last Wednesday night, some critics said Mrs.
Broaddrick's uncorroborated, 21-year-old account and her motives
for disliking President Clinton were such that it should not have
been broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Don Hewitt, the executive producer of ``60
Minutes,'' who ordinarily criticizes the standards of ``Dateline''
at the drop of a hat, think this time?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `Dateline' did a very creditable job,'' he said.
``They checked it out, and they put in the caveats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is she telling truth?'' he added. ``I don't know. If I didn't
know his track record for wagging a finger at the American people
and lying to them on national television, I might have taken what
she said with a grain of salt. But as it is, I agree with Patricia
Ireland: If it's a `he says, she says' story, he ain't got a very
good track record on that subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ireland, the president of the National Organization of
Women, made a statement along those lines Thursday, when asked
about Mrs. Broaddrick's story.
</P>
<P>
   In both the Willey and Broaddrick cases, President Clinton
issued statements denying the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Considering his praise for NBC's due diligence in checking its
story, did Hewitt have second thoughts about his own handling of
the Willey interview? He said he had ``no regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All Kathleen Willey said to Ed Bradley was exactly what she
had told a grand jury under oath,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-28-99 1655EST &QL;
</P>
