<HEADLINE>
TWO ALLIANCES AIM TO CREATE PC ALTERNATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two separate industry alliances to be announced Monday share a
similar target: creating alternatives to the personal computer _
and to Microsoft Corp.'s operating systems _ for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   In one announcement, IBM, Motorola, Sun Microsystems, Lucent and
10 other companies have agreed to create a new set of standards
based on Sun's Java programming language to interconnect a next
generation of smart devices ranging from computers and cell phones
to washing machines and dishwashers.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate deal, the regional telephone company U S West and
Network Computer Inc., a spinoff from the database software giant
Oracle Systems, plan to announce a schedule for trials of a new
service to be named AT-TV which will integrate the telephone, the
television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the new service will compete with both Microsoft's
WebTV and the At-Home cable modem service. Although the timing of
At-TV's availability has not been announced, U S West executives
said that trials would begin later this year and that commercial
service would begin in the 14 states the company serves before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is the first U.S. success for NCI, which has made
progress in the interactive set-top box business in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``NCI has been trying for a long time to find a domestic deal,''
said Gary Arlen, president of Arlen Communications, a research firm
based in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said that the U S West trials would be carefully
watched because the new service offered an interesting twist in the
long-held goal of merging the telephone and the television into a
single, interactive device.
</P>
<P>
   U S West executives said that the new system would employ Caller
ID technology to display the name of a caller on the television
screen and give the viewer the option of accepting the call on a
speaker-phone built in to the NCI set-top box. The set-top box
would also store an electronic phone book and would enable a
television viewer to make phone calls without picking up a
telephone handset.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to leave your couch, said Jeffrey Kagan, a
telecommunications industry analyst. ``This is the long-awaited
blending of different technologies, and it should be a natural fit
for Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   U S West executives said they would release pricing information
at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The new Java alliance is a technology partnership to be called
the Open Service Gateway Specification. In addition to IBM, Sun,
Motorola and Lucent, participants include Alcatel, Cable &AMP;
Wireless, Enron Communications, Ericsson, Network Computer Inc.,
Nortel Networks, Oracle Corp., Philips Electronics, Sybase Corp.
and Toshiba.
</P>
<P>
   The standard is in part an effort to pull together the
proliferating consumer electronics networking standards, which
currently consist of an alphabet soup of code names and acronyms
like Bluetooth, CAL, CEBus, HAVi, HomePNA, HomePnP, HomeRF, Jini
and VESA.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives said standards like Open Service Gateway
Specification are needed because existing telephone and power
networks in the home are being transformed into data networks to
link increasingly intelligent appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see a shift of focus toward a broader range of
intelligent devices, some of which we won't think of as computers
at all,'' said Mark Bregman, general manager of IBM's pervasive
computing division.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted a generation of home appliances like a washing
machine that would come with an LCD panel and a Web browser. Such
appliances would in the future be able to communicate with the
Internet and with other gadgets in the home, possibly over the
home's electrical wiring.
</P>
<P>
   While no one expects consumers to surf the Web while they wash
their clothes, such systems would enable manufacturers to directly
diagnose and update appliances via the Internet, he said. However,
he also acknowledged that such powerful capabilities would also
raise new security challenges.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-28-99 2153EST &QL;
</P>
