<HEADLINE>
U.S. INQUIRY CAUSES EBAY STOCK TO FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The online auction site Ebay, which has already gained the
attention of New York City consumer officials, now says it is under
federal investigation for ``possible illegal transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a terse release about the inquiry late
Friday, withholding details about the substance ``to protect the
investigations,'' but saying that it was ``fully cooperating.''
</P>
<P>
   It said an unspecified branch of the federal government
requested company documents on Jan. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock split 3-for-1 Monday, and closed at $323,
down $11 from Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Ebay announced that it would ban the sale of
firearms on the site, effective this Friday. That move came in
response to a report that weapon sales, governed in the off-line
world by a complex set of rules that differ from state to state,
were impossible to monitor in the geographically boundless online
community.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the company have also confirmed in recent weeks
that they are cooperating with the New York City Department of
Consumer Affairs, which is investigating accusations of fraudulent
activity on the part of a seller of sports memorabilia through
Ebay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-01-99 2116EST &QL;
