 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
CompuServe2000 enters the present 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, there was an online service called CompuServe.
It was ugly, clunky and hard to use. Pricing varied across the
service, so a few hours on CompuServe could cost a fortune if you
ventured into certain areas or forums. To top it off, CompuServe
didn't give its users screen names _ it gave them numbers, numbers
randomly assigned and impossible to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Then came America Online, which was easier to use, offered
uniform pricing and allowed users to have names instead of numbers.
To make a long story short, AOL blew CompuServe out of the water
and eventually acquired the company in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   AOL immediately set to work giving CompuServe a makeover
designed to make it more appealing, more sophisticated _ and more
like AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Now called CompuServe2000, the revamped service launched this
week. It's sleek, it's cheap ($9.95 a month for 20 hours) and it's
jam-packed with news from brand-name partners like The New York
Times, CNet, Marketwatch and WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe2000 looks like AOL's bookish older brother. If you
can find your way around AOL, you'll have no trouble with
CompuServe. The familiar AOL menu bar retooled for CompuServe is in
cool green-and-blue tones with slick pull-down menu bars. News
pages are packed with links to national and international articles
from a variety of sources. Members get to select screen names
rather than receive a randomly assigned number.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is a mass market, family-oriented site. CompuServe is more
adult, more business-oriented,'' says CompuServe Chief Operating
Officer Audrey Weil, one of the executives brought over from AOL to
drag CompuServe into the 21st century. ``The CompuServe user
doesn't surf the Web,'' Weil says. ``They want to find information,
get on and get off.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, this is not the place to be if you just want to send
instant messages to your friends after school or talk about
Leonardo DiCaprio in a chat room. Instead, the talk is more
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place for colleagues to chat with each other,'' Weil
says. The service is aggressively pursuing users with specific
specialities such as physicians, pilots, lawyers, journalists and
investors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Weil, CompuServe2000 will not compete with AOL but
will complement it.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key things for AOL Inc. is to have multiple brands
in cyberspace,'' she says. For all its great success _ the one
thing AOL has never been able to do well is attract business users
and the pocket-protector set who have been fans of CompuServe for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe is confident its new look will also attract new
users, who need and want information but don't want to bother with
search engines, URLs, portals, pornography, hackers and other
perceived hazards of the Web. Weil says of the 17 million new users
logging on every year, more than half are adults looking for an
online service that's customized, easy to use and offers high-speed
access.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe is an inexpensive alternative delivered in a format
many users are already familiar with and has content partners that
are already big-name Web players anyway. CompuServe is a kind of
``Web lite,'' offering novice users instant access to information
and community. However, the service does have Web access for users
who do want to venture onto the Web just as AOL does, and
CompuServe's portal, http://www.compuserve.com will also be the
start-up page for MCI WorldCom's new Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   CompuServe2000 does offer a flat-rate pricing plan for unlimited
use, but Weil says most users _ 80 percent _ prefer to use the
``pay as you go'' plan and only 20 percent have the unlimited usage
plan. ``Twenty hours of use is one hour every business day,'' she
says. And with 2 million professional users as opposed to AOL's 16
million general users, discussions and forums are likely to be more
focused and free of the ``age/sex check'' messages that plague many
AOL discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Film critic) Roger Ebert loves the forums,'' says Weil of one
of CompuServe's celebrity members. ``He says he loves the level of
communication and discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
