 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
A little lying is part of the online culture 
By Mark Clothier  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among its other pluses is an occasional minus: The Internet is a
haven for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Web can be full of lies, which is part of its appeal. In a
Web chat room, a short, lumpy unemployed person can become tall,
svelte and gainfully employed. And no one knows the difference.
</P>
<P>
   All well and good if you're just making small talk. But it's
hardly a way to start something real. Then again, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently some of us do. The March issue of Yahoo! Internet
Life takes a look at the tendency to lie online.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a wake of a year that was all about lying, it's easy to
pick up the habit. While the president was being pilloried for his
peccadilloes ... millions of people were practicing the art of
deception every day on the Internet,'' reads the cover story.
</P>
<P>
   But Web users seem to like the lie. The article cites Georgia
Tech's census of Web habits, considered by the magazine the ``most
prestigious general census of Web habits.'' According to the
article, privacy has replaced censorship as the issue most
important to Web users. More than 40 percent of Web users gave
false personal information occasionally, and 10 percent said they
lied at least half the time.
</P>
<P>
   The March issue also ranks America's top wired cities for 1999.
Atlanta placed ninth, behind San Francisco; Austin, Texas; Seattle;
Washington, D.C.; Boston; San Jose, Calif.: San Diego; and
Minneapolis. Atlanta was ahead of Dallas-Fort Worth, Raleigh-Durham
and Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta placed ninth in percentage of adults using the Web at
home and seventh in the number of sites per capita. Atlanta did not
crack the top 10 in two categories: percentage of adults using the
Net at work, which was led by Austin, and Web hosts per capita, led
by San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics were compiled with help from Matrix Information
and Directory Services, an Austin firm that tracks Internet usage
</P>
<P>
   E-stickers
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Television Workshop, the people who bring us
``Sesame Street,'' are taking the stick out of stickers.
</P>
<P>
   Its site, http://www.ctw.org
</P>
<P>
   /stickerworld/1,2614,26265,00
</P>
<P>
   .html, features e-stickers, electronic images you can put on
your Web page.
</P>
<P>
   The Sticker World site is part of the Children's Television
Workshop Kid City site, at http://www.kidcity.org. Kid City is an
online site geared to those between the ages of 6 and 12.
</P>
<P>
   The site lets kids vote on whether they like television shows,
cartoons, bands and celebrities, and offers running tallies of the
votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Sticker World site lets kids build their own Web pages and
decorate them with the e-stickers, electronic images that come in
the form of graphics to interactive games and puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Television Workshop is a nonprofit company that
uses television, the Internet, CD-ROM, print, film and product
licensing to entertain and educate kids.
</P>
<P>
   Online historic preservation
</P>
<P>
   An organization focused on preserving the past has taken a firm
step into the future. The Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation
has launched a Web site, http://www
</P>
<P>
   .georgiatrust.org.
</P>
<P>
   On the site is a monthly calendar of events and information
about the various preservation funds, as well as conferences and
tours. The site also offers links to properties for sale and
photographs of the trust's house museums.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia trust, founded in 1973, is the largest statewide
nonprofit preservation group in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Trust for Historic Preservation operates three
historic houses, sells endangered properties, offers design
assistance to 30 Main Street communities in Georgia, and lobbies
for money and laws to help preservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
