<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5885 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE02-COX &LR;      03-03 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE02-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Learn about hacking to prevent being hacked 
By Bill Husted  
C. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There you are, a solid citizen of the Net, not particularly
interested in breaking into anything more sensitive than the
refrigerator ... maybe not fat, but happy. So why in the world do
you need to know anything about breaking into computers?
</P>
<P>
   Well, why should you know anything at all about locks? After
all, you don't have any plans to break into houses. Now that there
are real _ if sometimes overblown _ security risks on the Net, you
need to know a little about hacking in order to understand how to
protect yourself against it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start by saying that some old-line computer veterans hate
the notion of calling folks who break into computers hackers. The
term hacking was once more commonly used for a person who was good
at writing programs and computing in general. But nowadays, a
hacker is a person who enjoys learning about ways to break into
computer systems and networks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best primers on that type of hacking is comprised of
the information and links you'll find at the Mining Company's
Internet/Network Security site at http://netsecurity.miningco
</P>
<P>
   .com/. You'll find, for instance, the Modern Hacker's Desk
Reference, a fairly easy-to-understand tutorial on hacking. Once
you've read that, you'll understand the lingo. Then you can follow
one of the dozens of links on this page to sections that explain
some of the programs used to invade other computers and networks.
Some of the material is fairly advanced, but none of it should be
totally incomprehensible once you've learned the lingo. Pay special
attention to the links that take you to areas devoted to protecting
your computer against invasion.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need the jargon you learn at that site because one of the
rules of hacking seems to be that any self-respecting hacker speaks
in technobabble. You'll sure find plenty of that at the next site,
but it is based on a print magazine that was one of the first
widely circulated periodicals for hackers: 2600.
</P>
<P>
   The site of that same name is located at http://www.2600.com
</P>
<P>
   /mindex.html. And there's no use mincing words, the viewpoint
here is definitely pro-hacking. You'll find a list here, for
instance, of Web sites that have recently been invaded and
conquered by hackers. There's a little bit of an attitude here,
too. But if your only exposure to hackers in the past has been ones
you've seen in movies or read about in books, it should be an
interesting visit.
</P>
<P>
   Just as there are good witches and bad witches in the old
storybooks, there are good and bad hackers, too. Some hackers _ at
least in their public philosophy _ avoid illegal break-ins and
study hacking as an art. A good hacker, for instance, feels obliged
to let a company know if he discovers flaws in a network, site or
program that make invasion easy. These hackers are best represented
by a group called Happy Hackers. If you go to http://
</P>
<P>
   netsecurity.miningco.com
</P>
<P>
   /library/weekly/aa052598
</P>
<P>
   .htm you can read an interview with Carolyn Meinel, the founder
of the group's Web site. (You can find a link on the same Web page
with the interview. The Happy Hacker site was working sporadically
last week.)
</P>
<P>
   One warning. Even though the group itself seems to be a good
one, some of the language in the interview is not. So parents
should preview the interview for suitability before suggesting it
to any young hackers in the family.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to keep up with what's new in hacking, you can
subscribe to a free publication from the Happy Hackers (just go the
Happy Hacker Web site) to subscribe.
</P>
<P>
   None of these sites will turn you into a hacker. But that
probably isn't a career goal, anyway. You will learn enough to know
that (1) the threats from hackers are overblown, but (2) there are
some real dangers out there in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-01-99 1108EST &QL;
</P>
