<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5891 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV21-COX     03-03 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A: MICHAEL DELL, CHAIRMAN OF DELL COMPUTER CORP.
 &HT;    With CHINA-DELL-$ADV21.
 &HT;    Moving in International and Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., March 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JERRY MAHONEY 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dell Computer Corp. Has big plans for Asia,
beginning with a major foothold in the People's Republic of China.
The hope is that Dell's formidable sales strategy of
``direct-selling'' to the computer customer will catch on with
China's large, fast-growing consumer market, mimicking the
company's success in Europe. Cox News Service correspondent Jerry
Mahoney spoke with Dell Chairman Michael Dell recently about the
China operation.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Are you happy with the progress of the China operation
to date?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: China's running nicely ahead of plans. And we've been
really thrilled with the reaction from customers so far to the
direct-sell business model. I have two trips already this year
planned to China, including a Fortune magazine global forum we're
sponsoring with a couple of other companies in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you quantify the start out of the gates in China,
compared to other new markets?
</P>
<P>
   A: We don't really break it out at that level but it's off to a
very, very nice start. This is a market that several years ago was
not in the Top 20. Now, a lot of people would say it's the
third-largest market in the world. And it looks like it could be
the second-largest market in the world in a couple of years,
overtaking Japan. It's really quite remarkable what's going on over
there.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that you want to be the world's No. 1 producer of
PCs?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, it would be good. I think part of it depends on what
our competitors do, what other mergers or acquisitions may occur in
the marketplace. We've been pretty clear in our statement about
saying we think we can grow faster than the market. You could kind
of plot out our current growth rate and that would suggest that in
a couple of years we start to become No. 1 in more and more
markets. But that's more of a mathematical equation than a
prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But it still is the goal of Dell to be the No. 1 PC maker in
the world at some point?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure. We wouldn't have a goal to be No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does Dell have to accomplish in China to reach that goal
eventually?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, I think we're a long way away from that in China today.
We're establishing a base and building our business. Actually, our
first goal in China is that we want to be the No. 1 American
computer company in China.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Compaq is that now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And then what? What's the share there?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, the share is moving around quite a bit for all the
companies because the market is growing. And if you look at the
size of the market three years from now, it's likely to be huge
compared to what it is this year. So it's advancing quickly, but we
have very small share there today.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will China be like in five years?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think the Chinese market is going to be the fastest-growing
large market, by far. There will be, I think, some challenges in
the economy there. It's not likely to go straight up forever, but
by and large this is going to be the fastest-growing market that we
and many companies have. As you get increased industrialization in
China, the computerization and the whole communications revolution,
I mean, the computer industry is in a great position there. If you
look at the growth of the telephone industry, you can kind of see a
precursor to what we think computing will look like in China. And
it has a lot of potential for our company. (Dell China President)
David (Chan) was a key exec in our Asia business, and now he's
totally dedicated just to China. We're spending a lot of time there
. . . because we think it's going to be a very key market for us.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you assess the progress so far of your China
manufacturing and sales operations?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's very positive. It's quite impressive to see them kind of
knocking down milestones in terms of quality, order run rates, and
capacity. Customer visits are much faster than we've seen in any
other operation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think could be improved in China? What success
here has surprised you?
</P>
<P>
   A: You still have a roll-out of communications going on across
the country that doesn't reach all of the population. The relevant
thing for us, of course, is that people who have telephones are our
primary target before the people who don't. So, the end of the
railroad track is way out there for us.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
