<SLUG> BC-CPT-Y2K-REPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL'S REPORT DETAILS Y2K THREAT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By GREG McDONALD  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ No need for alarm yet, but the nation's lawmakers
are worried that on midnight Dec. 31 all hell could break loose if
the so-called Year 2000 computer bug is not resolved.
</P>
<P>
   A special Senate committee charged with investigating the Y2K
problem released a report Tuesday detailing disturbances that could
occur nationwide and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although rating the possibility as ``low-to-medium,'' the panel
report raised the specter of everything from an accidental Russian
nuclear missile launch to civil unrest brought on by economic
collapse in some countries. All this as a result of tiny computer
chips in many systems failing to process information correctly
because they were not built to recognize the calendar year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate panel also warned that there could be minor to
significant disruptions in everything from utility services and
health care delivery systems to transportation and general business
operations. Disruptions in food distribution, energy and water
systems also could occur because governments and businesses have
failed to prepare for the possibility that many computer systems,
which use a two-digit dating method for data storage, may read the
year 2000 as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Americans, especially in rural areas, could
experience limited, short-term problems in services considered
crucial to their modern-day lives, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Y2K threat is real and heightened by the ubiquity of
microchips and our dependence on just-in-time delivery for
everything from groceries to medicine,'' said Sen. Bob Bennett,
R-Utah, who chairs the special Y2K committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said the problems would amount to only ``a bump
in the road'' as the world enters the new millennium. ``It will not
be crippling, and it will not last for an undue length of time,''
he said at a news conference held to release the panel's report.
</P>
<P>
   In a move aimed at helping some of America's smaller businesses
prepare for the year 2000, the Senate voted 99-0 Tuesday to provide
up to $500 million in loans through the end of this year to
companies that could be significantly affected or forced out of
business because of Y2K problems. The money will be used in most
cases to help companies fix their own computer systems and
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate committee vice chairman, Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., cautioned Americans against panic, saying that they ought
to prepare for the Year 2000 as if they were readying for a
hurricane or winter storm, not the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, he said it would be a good idea for Americans
to put aside some canned goods and water, and perhaps a little cash
as well, to help them cross that bridge _ to quote President
Clinton _ into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no need for stockpiling,'' Dodd stressed, adding that
``a few days of water and food'' should be sufficient to get people
through in areas that might be affected more severely by power
outages or other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd, however, said predicting what will happen is difficult.
``We are guessing here, as everyone is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd predicted that there would be no widespread power outages.
At worst, he said, there would be minimal failures for up to 72
hours or less in areas where smaller utility companies may not have
the resources to devote to Y2K compliance.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the committee found that most of the nation's 3,200
independent utility companies are behind in their efforts to
address the problem. But the panel's report notes that the electric
utility industry ``as a whole is configured to handle
interruptions, blackouts and natural disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A prolonged, nationwide blackout is not likely to occur,'' the
report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers are not particularly concerned about power
problems, they are worried about the possibility of serious
interruptions in the nation's health care system, which was found
to be lagging in efforts to deal with the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dodd said that 90 percent of the nation's
hospitals, and especially those in rural and inner-city areas, have
not begun to address potential problems if computer systems fail or
the microchips used in life support and analysis systems
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The committee described the U.S. health care industry as ``the
worst prepared ... for the Y2K glitch'' and noted that the lag in
correcting the problems could interrupt the supply chain of
pharmaceuticals that hospitals, clinics and even drug stores rely
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the health care industry's lack of
preparedness will necessarily mean the loss of life, but it could
seriously impact care for millions of Americans dependent on
prescription drugs and regular medical treatments to stay
healthy,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   He also raised concerns about the government's Medicare program,
which he said had not carried out any testing to determine whether
its payment delivery system will continue to work. ``We can only
hope that Medicare's billion-dollars-a-day in payments to hospitals
and caregivers continue to find their way through the high-tech
maze,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report also emphasized what it described as the
``high probability'' of economic disruptions in Latin America, Asia
and Africa. It also singled out Venezuela and Saudi Arabia as key
world oil suppliers that are at least a year or more behind in
preparing for potential Y2K problems. In addition, Japan, Mexico,
China, Germany and Taiwan were cited as being behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett emphasized that the failure of other countries to
address potential problems could have a severe impact on the world
``because of the interconnectedness of our information systems in
every economic sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., who sponsored the bill aimed at
helping small businesses fix Y2K bugs, told lawmakers that the
``outlook is not good'' for the nation's small-business owners as
the new millennium approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many small companies have not yet begun to realize how much of
a problem Y2K failures could be for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill must be approved by the House to become law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee also began consideration Monday
of another controversial measure that would limit the amount of
damages awarded in Y2K-related lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Various estimates of how much it will cost the U.S. government
and private sector to address the Y2K problem ranges from a low of
$50 billion to a high of $150 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
