<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CARAMELIZED-RECIPES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sugar meltdown recipes
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Let's start with true confessions. When I tried to
make my first caramel sauce last year, it took three attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The first time, I cooked the sugar and water too long and it
scorched. The second time, I was gun-shy and didn't cook the
mixture long enough. It was thin, runny and lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   The third time _ I discovered the candy thermometer. I brought
the mixture to about 340 degrees, and then pulled it off the fire.
</P>
<P>
   It was deliciously right on, and I've made it several times
since.
</P>
<P>
   This confession is intended to encourage you, not dissuade you.
It's also intended to wink you in on a few secrets so maybe your
first time with bronzing sugar will be a success.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use a heavy-bottomed saucepan. This is essential to allow the
sugar to dissolve and cook to the high heat required without
burning.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recipes that call for adding a little water to the sugar are
usually easier, according to Rose Levy Beranbaum, author of ``The
Cake Bible'' (Morrow, $30) and ``The Pie and Pastry Bible''
(Scribner, $35). Both give detailed directions for caramelizing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Our recipe tester Margaret Ann Surber suggests that if you
remove the spoon from the mixture at any point, rinse it off or get
a new spoon before returning it to the pan to stir. Sugar can
crystallize on the spoon. Also, early in the process, you may want
to brush the sides of the pan down with a pastry brush to clear any
crystals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure sugar completely dissolves before you bring the
mixture to a boil. Stir constantly until boiling begins. At this
point, things will start moving fast, so you may want to turn the
heat down a little to finish it at a slower pace, occasionally
swirling the pan.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use an accurate candy thermometer. Sugar caramelizes between
330 and 350 degrees. Beyond that, it will taste scorched and
bitter. Less than that and it will be pale and thin (though some
recipes may call for such a light syrup).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep a pan of cold water nearby that you can set the caramel
pan in once you remove it from the heat in order to stop the
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   To practice, we recommend the recipes for old-fashioned caramel
cake and the caramel pots de creme.
</P>
<P>
   Caramelizing vegetables and fruits is somewhat easier.
Generally, dry-heat cooking methods are used (which often involve
fats). Floataway Cafe chef Anne Quatrano likes to start with a high
heat to give a little sear to the veggies, but she reduces the heat
quickly, and then cooks slowly. Practice with Quatrano's recipe for
caramelized turnips. They go great with pork chops. We also offer a
recipe for pork tenderloin and caramelized apples that's a classic.
</P>
<P>
   Because meats and fish don't have significant natural sugars,
sugars have to be added in order to caramelize. Sweet marinades
work; so does coating in sugar, searing, and then deglazing the pan
with a liqueur/soy sauce mixture, as with the caramelized salmon
recipe. It's unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Caramel Pots de Creme
</P>
<P>
   Makes 7 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 hour Chilling time: several hours
</P>
<P>
   Here's our adaptation of Floataway Cafe's popular caramel pots
de creme. It's an excellent recipe to practice the caramelizing
technique _ its base is the caramel syrup. And how can you go wrong
with the addition of cream and eggs? Rich and rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   1cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2cups heavy
</P>
<P>
   cream
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup water
</P>
<P>
   6egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, combine half-and-half and cream and heat
almost to a simmer. Turn off heat. Meanwhile put sugar and water in
a large, heavy-bottomed saucepan and cook over lowest possible heat
until sugar has dissolved completely. The mixture must not come to
a boil before all the sugar crystals have dissolved. You may stir
gently during this process to make sure it melts evenly, but you
must rinse the spoon or use a clean spoon each time to prevent
reintroducing sugar crystals into the mixture. When sugar has
dissolved, increase heat to medium-high and boil until a deep
caramel color is reached, at about 340 degrees. Be patient; this
process may take up to 25 minutes. Cover your hand with a towel and
very slowly add the hot cream and half-and-half mixture into the
caramelized sugar. Slowly whisk a third of the hot caramel-cream
mixture into egg yolks to temper. Pour yolk-and-cream mixture back
into the remaining hot caramel cream. Strain and pour into seven
4-ounce ramekins or pots de creme pots. Put ramekins in a baking
pan and fill pan with water halfway up sides of ramekins. Bake 25
to 30 minutes or until set. Cool slightly, then refrigerate for
several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 381 calories, 4 grams protein, 29 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 68), 28 grams carbohydrates, 248
milligrams cholesterol, 40 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Caramel Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings Preparation time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes Cooling time: 1 hour, 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This very old-fashioned recipe comes from the recent rerelease
of the 1950 ``Betty Crocker's Picture Cook Book'' (Macmillan,
$27.95). Where else could we get such an old-fashioned recipe _
always a blue ribbon winner at the county fairs? This calls for the
trickier dry method of burning sugar _ so be sure to use a very
heavy-bottomed pan (I've even used an iron skillet). Serve it
within a day.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/3cups granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   Additional cool tap water
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup soft vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   3eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2cups sifted cake flour or 2 1/3 cups sifted all-purpose
flour
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   For the caramel icing:
</P>
<P>
   Reserved caramelized sugar (from cake recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4to 4 1/2 cups sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: Grease and flour two 9-inch round cake pans, then
line with rounds of wax paper. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Caramelize 1 cup sugar by placing it in a medium-size, heavy pan
over medium-low heat. Melt, stirring constantly, for about 10
minutes, until a straw-colored syrup forms. Remove pan from heat
immediately. Slowly add the 1/2 cup boiling water, stirring
constantly, being careful to avoid spatters and steam. Stir until
lumps dissolve. (If lumps remain, reheat for 10 to 15 minutes,
covered, on low heat.) Pour 1/4 cup of the caramelized sugar into a
measuring cup and add enough extra cool tap water to make one cup
liquid. Reserve remaining caramelized sugar for the icing.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, cream shortening and remaining 1 1/3
cups granulated sugar on high speed of electric mixer. Add eggs and
mix thoroughly. In a medium bowl, sift together flour, baking
powder and salt. On low speed, stir flour mixture into shortening
mixture alternately with caramel liquid. Mix until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared pans and bake 25-30 minutes or until
toothpick comes out clean. Cool on wire racks 10 minutes, then
remove from pans and cool completely, about 1 hour. Frost with
Caramel Icing.
</P>
<P>
   For caramel icing: Add enough cream to reserved caramel mixture
to equal 1/2 cup. Place in a small saucepan with butter and heat
until butter melts. Pour into large mixing bowl and gradually beat
in confectioners' sugar, salt and vanilla on medium sped of
electric mixer. Adjust for spreading consistency using cream to
thin or confectioners' sugar to thicken.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 471 calories, 3 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 23), 90 grams carbohydrates, 51
milligrams cholesterol, 346 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pizza With Caramelized Onions, Pancetta and Blue Cheese
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings (two 10-inch pizzas) Prep time: 30 minutes
Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   On any given day at Floataway Cafe, the caramelized onion pizza
is a top seller at lunch. No doubt it's the combination of sweet,
buttery onions, pungent cheese and salty pancetta. Here, we give
you an adaptation developed by food tester Linda Hogue. It allows
for the quickest possible way to caramelize onions, but the truth
is, if you turn the heat down low and let them cook for 20 minutes
to an hour, you'll get an even sweeter result.
</P>
<P>
   4medium onions, thinly sliced (about 5 cups)
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4ounces pancetta (Italian bacon) or Canadian bacon, cut in small
pieces
</P>
<P>
   6ounces crumbled blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons coarsely chopped fresh sage
</P>
<P>
   leaves
</P>
<P>
   For the pizza dough:
</P>
<P>
   2cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1package ( 1/4-ounce) quick-rise yeast
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup warm water (110-115 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   Caramelize onions by cooking in a Dutch oven with butter over
medium heat for 8 to 10 minutes, or over lower heat for a longer
period. Stir occasionally; remove from heat when onions are soft
and brown, but not too dark. Reserve onions and prepared pancetta,
blue cheese and sage leaves while making dough.
</P>
<P>
   For the dough: In a large bowl, stir together flour, salt and
yeast. Stir in warm water and olive oil until blended and dough
comes away from side of bowl. Turn out on lightly floured board and
knead 5 minutes. Shape dough into 2 balls; cover and let rest 15
minutes. Roll or pat each dough ball into two 10-inch rounds and
place on pizza pans or cookie sheets sprinkled with cornmeal (to
prevent sticking). Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Spread onions
evenly over the dough, then top with pancetta, blue cheese and
sage. Cover and let rise 15 minutes. Bake for 20 to 25 minutes
until dough is cooked and cheese is soft and lightly browned.
Remove to cutting surface and slice to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 185 calories, 7 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 39), 21 grams carbohydrates, 19 milligrams
cholesterol, 459 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Caramelized Golden Tofu
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings Preparation time: 5 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Madison borrowed this recipe from famed chef Barbara
Tropp to include in ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone'' (Broadway
Books, $35), and we understand why. The beauty of tofu is the way
it soaks up flavors. Here the flavors are darkly sweet and slightly
salty. Serve over rice or as a side to a nice veggie stir-fry.
</P>
<P>
   11-pound package Chinese-style firm tofu, cut in slabs about 3/4
inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2tablespoons light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   Drain tofu, then blot with paper towels. Cut in 3/4-inch cubes.
Heat the oil in a medium nonstick skillet over fairly high heat.
Add the tofu and fry several minutes, turning occasionally until
golden, about 15 minutes. While they should color, don't let them
get dry and hard. Sprinkle lightly with salt.
</P>
<P>
   While tofu is cooking, mix the soy sauce and sugar in a small
bowl. Heat a wok or heavy skillet, add a tablespoon of the oil used
to fry the tofu or fresh peanut oil, and swirl it around the wok or
pan. When hot, add the soy sauce mixture, reduce heat to medium and
add the tofu. Toss well, then simmer for 2 minutes. Add water and
cook until the sauce coats the tofu with a syrupy glaze. Turn off
the heat. Let the tofu cool in the syrup for 10 minutes, then
transfer to a serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 466 calories, 28 grams protein, 28 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 55), 32 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 1,057 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Caramelized Salmon
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes Chilling time: at least 4 hours
Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   I often travel to Southern California, and when I get the
chance, I love to eat at Walt's Wharf in Seal Beach. My favorite
there is chef Mark Tydell's caramelized salmon. I admit when I saw
the recipe, I was a little daunted. While there are several steps,
each is really simple. The cilantro/ginger rub and the balsamic soy
sauce can be prepared a day ahead. I'd recommend trying the recipe
completely at least once, and serve over garlic mashed potatoes.
But for a quick fix, you can skip the balsamic soy stripe and the
lemon grass buerre blanc.
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup finely chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   4skinless salmon fillets (6 to 8 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   For the balsamic soy stripe:
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup low-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   For the lemon grass beurre blanc:
</P>
<P>
   1cup white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   2medium shallots, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   2stalks lemon grass, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup unsalted butter, cut in tablespoon-size pieces (1 1/2
sticks)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the Grand Marnier glaze:
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup low-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   For the caramelizing coating:
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   5turns cracked black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Combine cilantro and ginger. Coat salmon fillets with mixture
and refrigerate at least 4 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   For the balsamic soy stripe: In a small saucepan, combine the
1/2 cup soy sauce and 1/2 cup balsamic vinegar over medium heat.
Reduce until thickened to about 3 tablespoons, about 15 minutes.
Refrigerate. (Can be made a day ahead of time.)
</P>
<P>
   Just before cooking the salmon, make lemon beurre blanc: Combine
the white wine vinegar, rice wine vinegar, wine, shallots and lemon
grass in a medium saucepan and reduce over medium-high heat until
liquid is almost gone, 15-20 minutes. Add the cream, return to
boil, then reduce heat to low and begin whisking in butter, a few
tablespoons at a time, until all is incorporated and sauce is
smooth. Add salt and pepper to taste. Reserve warm until ready to
use.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook the salmon, combine 1/4 soy sauce and Grand
Mariner in a cup and set aside. Heat oil in a skillet over
medium-high heat. Combine black pepper and sugar in a dish. Press
one side of the salmon fillets into the mixture. Saute, sugar side
down, to caramelize the sugar, about 2 to 3 minutes. Quickly,
before the sugar turns, pour the Grand Marnier glaze into the pan,
swirling and stirring well to dissolve the caramelized bits.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the salmon over. Lower the heat to medium. Cover the pan
and let the salmon finish cooking 5 to 8 minutes longer, until
medium. Place the finished fillets over a bed of garlic mashed
potatoes. Ladle lemon grass beurre blanc over and around the
salmon. Drizzle a decorative pattern of the balsamic soy stripe
over the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 846 calories, 38 grams protein, 60 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 64), 41 grams carbohydrates, 201
milligrams cholesterol, 1,762 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pork Tenderloin With Caramelized Apples and Apple-Brandy Cream
Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Prep time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is versatile _ you can substitute pears, pear brandy
and pear nectar. But we like the classic apple version. The
caramelized apples here pair so well with the pork; and the thyme
in the cream sauce is just the right accent.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4pounds pork tenderloin, trimmed, cut crosswise in
1-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   4apples, peeled, halved, cored, cut in 1/3-inch wedges
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4teaspoons dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup Calvados or Applejack
</P>
<P>
   1cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   Place pork slices between pieces of plastic wrap. Using meat
mallet, pound pork slices to 1/4-inch thickness. Set aside. Melt 2
tablespoons butter in large nonstick skillet over high heat. Add
apples and sugar; saute until apples are tender and deep golden,
about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 tablespoon butter in another large nonstick skillet over
high heat. Sprinkle pork with salt and pepper. Working in batches,
add pork to skillet; saute just until cooked through, about 2
minutes per side. Transfer to plate. Cover. Return skillet to
medium heat. Melt remaining 1 tablespoon butter. Add shallots and
thyme; saute 2 minutes. Add Calvados; boil until reduced to glaze,
scraping any browned bits, about 2 minutes. Add cream and apple
cider; boil until thickened to sauce consistency, about 5 minutes.
Season with salt and pepper. Reheat apples if necessary. Spoon into
center of platter. Arrange pork around pears. Pour sauce over pork.
_ Bon Appetit, February, 1996
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 590 calories, 34 grams protein, 40 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 61), 26 grams carbohydrates, 203
milligrams cholesterol, 205 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE
</P>
<P>
   Caramelized Turnips
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Prep time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 20-25
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chef Anne Quatrano gave us a lesson on caramelizing in her
kitchen at Floataway Cafe. These turnips made a bed for a thick
pork chop, which then is often topped off with a dab of caramelized
apples. But hey, we could eat just a plate of these. For a nice
variation, try this same recipe with two pounds of fennel, thickly
sliced.
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons clarified butter
</P>
<P>
   2pounds turnips, peeled and cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon granulated
</P>
<P>
   sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons whole unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat clarified butter in saute pan until smoking hot. Add
turnips and cook until brown, tossing to brown on all sides.
Deglaze pan with maple syrup and sprinkle the turnips with sugar.
Add stock and simmer until almost all the liquid is gone. Swirl in
butter, season with salt and pepper and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 123 calories, 3 grams protein, 8 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 60), 12 grams carbohydrates, 21 milligrams
cholesterol, 70 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
