<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CARAMELIZED04-CO     03-03 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CARAMELIZED04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sugar meltdown
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You see the description on the menu _ caramelized _
and in an instant, you're a kid again on the midway at the county
fair. Your mom is trying to get you enthused about the pig races,
but you're too busy crunching into that caramel apple, smacking up
the sticky-sweet bronzed coating.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you recall that caramel square wrapped in cellophane
your grandfather slipped you with a wink. The sugar melts in your
mouth; your heart melts for Pops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so nostalgic and homey. Everybody loves the idea of
caramelizing,'' said Anne Quatrano, chef and owner of Floataway
Cafe and Bacchanalia along with partner Clifford Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the carrot at the bottom of the roast beef pan,'' she
explains. ``You know, that sweet taste followed by the slightly
burnt flavor _ that little taste of the fire at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   That little taste of the sweet tinged with fire is being touted
on more and more restaurant menus these days, so much so that Food
&AMP; Wine magazine spotted caramelizing as a top menu trend for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   There it is on the Park 75 menu at the Four Seasons Hotel _ a
parfait with mango sorbet and caramelized bananas. Canoe is serving
a cake topped with a ring of caramelized fresh pineapple. At
Floataway, a tart with caramelized lemon slices and the classic
caramel pots de creme are favorites.
</P>
<P>
   But Floataway also demonstrates that caramelizing isn't just for
the dessert card. A big seller at lunch is a blue cheese and
caramelized onion pizza. At dinner, a hearty pork chop arrives on a
bed of caramelized turnips.
</P>
<P>
   While hot at the moment, caramelizing is hardly new. It's hard
to pinpoint who was the first to burn sugar, but the first mention
of caramel in English print comes in 1725, according to the
Dictionary of American Food and Drink.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, caramelizing is the melting or burning of sugar.
Sugar will liquefy and become a syrup in colors from golden to dark
brown when it reaches a range of temperatures of 320 degrees to 350
degrees. Beyond that it burns.
</P>
<P>
   This is the caramelizing we are most familiar with _ it's the
foundation of the candy coating on the apple, the blue-ribbon
``burnt sugar'' cake or the creme brulee with a mottled paper-thin
crust of sugar on the top.
</P>
<P>
   But for foods with natural sugars, like many fruits and
vegetables, the process of browning slowly in a dry heat or with
fat is caramelizing. The sugars are unlocked to reveal a sweet
taste and a bronze sheen. Meats and fish can be caramelized, too,
with the addition of sugars to the marinating and browning
processes.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Royal, chef of the Angus Barn in Raleigh, recently shared
his grandmother's secret for a caramelized pot roast _ 7-Up.
``She'd dust the roast in flour and brown it on all sides, then put
it in a Dutch oven with vegetables, add a can of 7-Up and roast.
The sugars of the 7-Up would caramelize, and it was so delicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, if only caramelizing could be so easy all the time. The fact
is, many home cooks avoid it because it is tricky and takes time
and practice.
</P>
<P>
   Turning table sugar into a caramel syrup can be most difficult.
A pan with a heavy bottom is essential _ that allows the sugar to
melt without burning. So is a watchful eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``One split second can make a difference. You have to go far
enough without going too far,'' Quatrano said. ``People get nervous
and the most common mistake is stopping too soon.''
</P>
<P>
   That will yield a syrup too thin for many recipes; going too far
will yield a completely scorched and bitter syrup. Practice _ and
an accurate candy thermometer _ will make perfect. And the effort
will be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing natural sugars out of vegetables and fruits is easier.
Root vegetables such as turnips and carrots and fruits like apples
and pears lend themselves gracefully to the method. The key here is
cooking slowly at a low heat without the moisture of water or
steam. Onions are one of the best foods to caramelize _ they add a
special touch to everyday pizzas, burgers and omelets. But for
many, the thought of cooking onions for an hour seems too
troublesome. Quatrano believes the taste will change the attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to shy away from caramelizing because it takes
time,'' Quatrano said. ``But it's time well rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
