<HEADER>
A5934 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE04-COX     03-03 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quick and easy-does-it dishes
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is something a little melancholy about that TV commercial
that shows the little boy and his mom coming into a rather gloomy
kitchen, obviously after a long day at work for her and day care or
preschool for him. While he is sitting at the table looking
wistfully at his mom, she reaches into the freezer for what looks
like a frozen pizza. She then looks down at his cute little face,
has a guilt attack, says something like, ``I'm going to make you a
real meal tonight'' and reaches for a can of soup. Cut to the next
scene, where mom and kid are talking over a feebly steaming bowl of
tomato soup and she says something like, ``What did you learn in
school today?'' and he says, ``How to share. . . . '' The end.
</P>
<P>
   It almost breaks your heart. Not that there is a thing wrong
with tomato soup. But just how much wattage can a can of soup
generate in a house that has been empty all day and badly needs an
infusion of warmth?
</P>
<P>
   Taking only a few minutes' more time than it took mom to zap
that soup, there easily could have been another scenario _ one
filled with the sounds of food being prepared, with a child eagerly
helping, savoring aromas coming from sizzling and bubbling pots and
pans.
</P>
<P>
   Then the anticipation of good things to come is followed by the
security and feeling of well-being that come from a full tummy and
a mom or dad who's there to fill it. All in all it's a far better
stage to engage in some real quality time and genuine sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of time, energy or extended family to pitch in no longer is
a valid rationalization for not putting together a family meal at
least a couple of times a week _ not with the Internet standing
ready to provide help for time-starved cooks.
</P>
<P>
   The first (and maybe only) place you need to visit is the Mining
Company, which provides hundreds of experts they call ``guides''
that mine the Web, gleaning and organizing the best sites you are
interested in and saving you time. Lynn Nelson is the guide for
busy cooks at http://busycooks.miningco
</P>
<P>
   .com/ and she practically takes you by the hand spelling out how
many minutes in the day and week are necessary to plan for and make
a family meal.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a wonderful free weekly e-mail newsletter that
features information on quantity cooking for the freezer and how
you can spend one weekend a month in the kitchen and take the rest
of the month off.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the table of contents for a jolt of inspiration and
confidence that no matter how busy you are, you need not give short
shrift to this vital family function. There is help, and it's here.
</P>
<P>
   Another great site is ``Fast Frugal and Fabulous'' at
http://www.fabulousfoods.com/recipes/fast/fast.html, which gives
menus and step-by-step instructions for dinners that you can whip
up for less than $15 and in under 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At http://www.ivillage.com/content/0,1625,2099(tilde)188,00.html
you will find 15-minute meals and a useful menu maker that creates
a full dinner menu in a click and includes a shopping list,
suggestions on how kids can help and how to use leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget about that soup. Go to
http://www.campbellkitchen.com/recipesearch.asp. and click for
recipes taking 30 minutes and you will be faced with a whopping 562
examples.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some more excellent ``fast food'' sites:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.food-guide.com/QuickMeals/EasyMeals/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.mymenus.com/menu09.html
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  http://www.compucook.com/meals/30min.asp?menuID &QC; 76
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  
http://family.go.com/Categories/Food/Features/family199801/famf/famf
18fast
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  
http://www.mccormick.com/recipe.nsf/Easy+Meal+Ideas?OpenView&AMP;Start &QC; 1
&AMP;Count &QC; 2
</P>
<P>
   Cheesy Vegetable Macaroni
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 main-dish servings Prep time: 10 minutes Cooking time:
10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   2medium zucchini, sliced (about 3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1jar (28 ounces) three-cheese
</P>
<P>
   spaghetti sauce (3 cups)
</P>
<P>
   4cups cooked corkscrew macaroni (about 3 cups dry)
</P>
<P>
   1cup shredded mozzarella cheese (4 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   In 10-inch skillet over medium heat, heat oil until hot. Add
zucchini and cook, stirring often, until tender-crisp. Add sauce
and macaroni. Heat through, stirring occasionally. Stir in cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 438 calories, 18 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 30), 63 grams carbohydrates, 22
milligrams cholesterol, 1,186 milligrams sodium, 5 grams fiber.
</P>
