<HEADER>
A5939 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON-0304-     03-03 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON-0304-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: HEZBOLLAH SHARPENING PUBLIC RELATIONS MACHINE, WAR
MACHINE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ As we ambled around a mountain village in
south Lebanon recently, our Lebanese translator attempted a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to an Israeli encampment on a hill nearby, he suggested
that the two journalists in our little group take the lead.
Otherwise, he quipped, the Israelis might spot our Hezbollah guide
and open fire.
</P>
<P>
   But, our guide hardly looked like a target in a guerrilla war.
Clean-cut in his slacks and sweater, he was the best-dressed of our
bunch. And, he was working his cellular telephone -- one with a
microphone that dangles from the ear -- like any good PR man does.
</P>
<P>
   He works in the Hezbollah press office and is trying to spruce
up the Party of God's image in the west.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after Hezbollah killed seven Israelis, including a
brigadier general, their press machine was in high gear. They
displayed captured Israeli equipment, held press conferences and
released battlefield video.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded me of my recent trip to Lebanon, where I saw a
Hezbollah that has gone from kidnapping journalists to simply
``spinning'' them.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah was born in 1982, when Israel invaded Lebanon and took
over the nine-mile strip of that neighboring country's southern
border that it still occupies today. Iranian financing has kept it
going strong and constantly updating its warfare.
</P>
<P>
   It's a group on the hinge of world opinion. The Israelis and the
United States consider the guerrillas terrorists, but the United
Nations calls them by the more neutral name, ``resistance'' forces.
In Lebanon, they are considered heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Hezbollah collection boxes, painted like the Dome of the
Rock mosque in Jerusalem, stand outside many stores in downtown
Beirut, the capital city. In Baalbek, a tourist town where
Hezbollah dominates, shops sell desktop Hezbollah flags. Several
party members serve in Lebanon's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   My trip to the south was confirmed sitting in a dingy office in
south Beirut with a Hezbollah sheikh, who was sporting a burgundy
blazer and tasseled loafers. He copied our passports and asked us
about the circulation of our newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   He also gave us glossy propaganda pamphlets. One showed e-mail
messages to Hezbollah's Internet home-page.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, our guide met us at a specified cafe and
took us to an unmarked office above a perfume shop in the port city
of Tyre. It's one of the safe houses Hezbollah maintains for
meeting outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the Americans will stop hating us,'' said Sheikh Nabil
Kaouk, Hezbollah's leader for southern Lebanon. ``We are dying from
American weapons (used by Israelis) and they don't feel guilty
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaouk, a tall 35-year-old, cuts an elegant figure in the brown
cape and turban-like headgear of Shiite Moslem clerics. He spoke
politely while aides served us strawberry juice.
</P>
<P>
   We covered politics and Hezbollah history. When questioned about
his family, Kaouk talked about a son who was getting married. But
then he got edgy and said we should not be discussing his family.
An occasional target of Israeli assassination attempts, he clearly
wondered about our intentions.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked him why Hezbollah now meets with journalists rather
than kidnaps them, Kaouk denied that Hezbollah staged the
kidnappings. Those denials are widely refuted by experts.
</P>
<P>
   But, Kaouk said that just shows how Israel's supporters have
tarnished Hezbollah's reputation around the world. He asked us to
write what we had seen and added, softly, ``Thank you for coming
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
