<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Popular cream cake a rich treat
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than a dozen readers sent their versions of
Italian Cream Cake, requested recently by Teresa Martin of Stone
Mountain (Ga.), who said she enjoyed it as a child growing up in
Saginaw, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Most recipes were similar to this one, sent by e-mail by Pauline
Pullen. It includes coconut and pecans in both the cake and the
rich cream cheese frosting.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Italian Cream Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 1 hour, 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the cake:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting:
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 pound box confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Few drops of milk, if needed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Grease and flour three 9-inch cake pans and set aside. Preheat
oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the cake: In a bowl, cream margarine and shortening with
electric mixer. Add sugar and beat until smooth. Add egg yolks, one
at a time, beating well after each addition. In another bowl,
combine flour and baking soda. Add to shortening and sugar mixture
alternately with buttermilk, beginning and ending with flour. Do
not overmix at this point. Add vanilla, coconut and nuts. In
another bowl, beat egg whites until stiff. Fold whites into batter.
Pour into pans and bake 25 minutes, or until pick inserted in
center comes out clean. You may want to shift pans halfway through
baking time for even cooking. Cool on wire rack for 10 minutes.
Invert cakes onto the racks and cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: In a bowl, beat cream cheese and margarine
well. Add confectioners' sugar and vanilla and mix well. Add a few
drops of milk if needed to reach spreading consistency. Fill and
frost cake, then sprinkle with coconut and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 757 calories, 7 grams protein, 41 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 93 grams carbohydrates, 110
milligrams cholesterol, 352 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Our church is compiling a cookbook as a part of our upcoming
150th anniversary celebration. I would like to include instructions
for making hominy and for sauerkraut. Can someone help?'' Jannetta
Johnson, Lawrenceville (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Do you have a recipe for Butter Bean Fricassee, or do you
know where I can get one?'' Sharon Horne, e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Years ago we had a great recipe for corn muffins at Decatur
High. It did not have flour in it. I lost my recipe, and if anyone
has it I would like a copy. ''
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Pullen, e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
