<HEADER>
A5936 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     03-03 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dogwood welcomes spring with full-bodied bock beer
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brewing and religion have a long history, beginning
with monks who brewed for king and court and sometimes for God.
Less well-known is the place of Martin Luther, a pivotal figure in
the 16th-century Protestant Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor who nailed heretical edicts to the church door in
Wittenberg, challenging the authority of the pope, could enjoy a
stein of good German beer. In fact, Luther's portrait once adorned
the label of Einbeck beer. Michael Jackson tells us that Luther
``was twice fortified by gifts of Einbeck beer. One gift was for
his wedding; the second occasion was when he confronted (Emperor
Charles) at the Diet of Worms. Einbeck could hardly have conceived
a more effective advertising endorsement.''
</P>
<P>
   These were bock beers, stronger brews served as the hard winter
of Northern Europe was yielding reluctantly to spring. But no one
thinks of Martin Luther when bock beer is poured. Instead,
Americans imagine something scraped from the bottom of the barrel.
Generations of beer drinkers have asked if bock wasn't the remnants
dredged up in anticipation of a new batch for spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past two months I'll bet I've answered that question
once a week,'' Dogwood founder Crawford Moran says. ``So we have to
go over the story again.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure how bock beer came to be imagined in that
way, and Germans aren't much more certain themselves. The best
guess, Jackson surmises, is that bock beer came to be identified
with the town of Einbeck in Lower Saxony, and that in time
``Einbeck beer'' was abbreviated to ``beck beer'' (having no
reference to Beck's Beer from Bremen). Among Bavarians, this guess
continues, ``beck beer'' came to sound like ``bock beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the name's origins, it's a beer for hearty appetites,
malty and full-bodied but not as rich or dark as the even stronger
Double Bocks. Lagers tend to have wider affinities with food than
ales, and bock is a natural complement to everything from smoked
sausages and sauerkraut to rack of lamb.
</P>
<P>
   When Moran and head brewer Matt Speece began thinking about a
spring beer, they wanted something to round out their lineup of
seasonals _ a Belgian White in summer, an Oktoberfest in fall and,
new last December, a winter ale brewed from barley, oats and rye.
Like the Oktoberfest, the bock would be available in draft only.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three seasonals knocked out,'' Moran says, ``and we
wanted to do something different. There aren't that many bocks on
the market, so we thought, `Why don't we try one?'''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the archaic state law that limits beer to 6 percent
alcohol by volume, Dogwood's isn't as strong as what you'd find in
Germany. Even so, it's a remarkably smooth lager that begins soft
on the palate and finishes with a toasty malt accent.
</P>
<P>
   In a spring brewing season that's barely under way, it's one of
the highlights. There might not be many. The beers of winter come
easily to mind, whether they be rich stouts and porters or a
supreme German Doppelbock such as Ayinger Celebrator. Summer beers
are no mystery either _ tart Belgian Whites, clovey hefeweizens,
crisp lagers in the Munich or Berlin style.
</P>
<P>
   But spring in the South suggests no style in particular _ which
is why the first of the spring beers on local shelves have no
common denominator. From Redhook comes a top-notch Nut Brown Ale;
from Bert Grant's, a zesty dry-hopped SpringFest Ale, brewed
exclusively with Yakima Valley Willamette hops; and from Samuel
Adams, a Kolsch-style beer simply called Spring Ale.
</P>
<P>
   None of these compares easily with the others, and even less do
they compare with a bock. A specifications sheet calls the Bert
Grant's a brown ale, but it's one only in the looser, Pacific
Northwest sense. It's delightfully hoppy for the style, and one of
the better beers this pioneering craft brewer has made.
</P>
<P>
   The Redhook, like all Redhook beers, is exquisitely polished,
with no rough edges. This is a brown ale in the English style, and
far superior to a marquee name such as Newcastle.
</P>
<P>
   If the Samuel Adams Spring Ale impresses least, it's only
because a Kolsch, the pride of Cologne, is among the most delicate
of all styles, light on the palate and yet not Lite in any sensual
way. Few American brewers have brought off a true Kolsch beer, but
Samuel Adams comes closer than most.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise was how well a small Atlanta brewery
specializing in ales rather than lagers, handicapped by a state law
that knows nothing of brewing styles, could turn out so finished a
bock. Martin Luther was, by all accounts, a man of unbending
convictions, but he'd have blessed the brewers at Dogwood's.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
