<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS04-COX     03-03 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio mini reviews
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Steve Dollar and Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Photograph Smile''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Lennon. 4tune/Pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe it's been almost 15 years since John Lennon's
first-born son released his debut album ``Valotte'' and amazed the
world with an uncanny vocal impression of his father. It's even
harder to believe that Julian, now 35, is still mimicking Dad, long
after the world has ceased to be amazed. ``Photograph Smile,'' the
younger Lennon's fifth album and his first following a seven-year
sojourn from the music business, takes its every idea from Papa
John's oeuvre _ both with the Beatles and solo. ``Cold,'' with its
vocal effects and grandiose strings, recalls ``Strawberry Fields
Forever'' and other Fab Four forays into psychedelic pop, and the
jangly tune ``I Don't Wanna Know'' sounds like an outtake from
``Help!'' But, as ever, Julian lacks fire; if his work
</P>
<P>
   was half as passionate as his father's, he might be on to
something.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hot Rock'' Sleater-Kinney. Kill Rock Stars. 13 tracks.
Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the head-spinning buzz generated by its last two
albums _ ``Call the Doctor'' and ``Dig Me Out'' _ Washington state
trio Sleater-Kinney is of a cooler mind for its latest effort. The
upside of that is this punk-influenced act's powerfully tight
musicianship, which has become a stronger factor since the addition
of drummer Janet Weiss (Quaso, Elliot Smith). Guitarists/vocalists
Carrie Brownstein and Corin Tucker bob and weave around forceful
beats, or lock into repeated-note patterns that transmit like
personal semaphore codes. The focused intensity is heightened by
Tucker's oscillating wail of a voice, which miraculously seems to
conflate Ella Fitzgerald and Johnny Rotten. The downside is that
``The Hot Rock'' suffers from its single-minded theme (sample
titles: ``Banned From the End of the World,'' ``The End of You,''
``Living in Exile''). When a voice whispers, ``We're gonna party
like it's 1999,'' you really wish it wasn't ironic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Drive Me Wild'' Sawyer Brown. Curb. 11 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Looking for breezy, Pablo Cruise-style pop? This new CD from
country's most energetic band is a low-stress excursion through
what used to be the stuff of Top 40 hits _ hummable tunes and
I'm-in-love lyrics that would be perfect about 20 minutes into
``Dawson's Creek.'' Nothing is offensive here, or particularly
memorable. Many tunes sound like clones of others. ``Break My Heart
Again'' is Don Henley's ``Last Worthless Evening,'' while Steve
Earle's ``I Ain't Never Been Satisfied'' is reworked into a track
called ``We're Everything to Me.'' Nothing pops out like the ``I
ain't first class/but I ain't white trash'' cheekiness of the
group's past hits. But like a bag of Cheetos, this is a fun
indulgence while it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton, Steve Dollar and Miriam Longino write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
