<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inventive twist on tale of Cinderella
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ever After'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   In this swell revamp of the Cinderella story, Drew Barrymore
plays the lead, renamed Danielle. She's a 16th-century French lass
whose wealthy dad dies, leaving her at the mercy of evil stepmom
Anjelica Huston and a couple of snooty stepsisses. Yeah, you know
the drill.
</P>
<P>
   But this time out, there's no fairy godmother with a wand
helping Danielle play dress-up at the ball. Instead, her own
intelligence and bravery _ plus a little help from inventor
Leonardo da Vinci _ are what capture the prince's eye (played
nicely by Dougray Scott).
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a swoon-fest for the young, but also a savvy
revisionist twist on the tale that even grown-ups can dig. Grade:
B+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
