</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAP04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Infectious Eminem's offensive edge
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many in hip-hop's core following have privately hoped that white
rappers would remain forever frozen in Vanilla Ice.
</P>
<P>
   Just the notion that this street music would, like blues and
R&AMP;B, be taken and reconfigured for mainstream consumption by some
Backstreet Boy is really disturbing to some.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem is disturbing for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Michigan native, born Marshall Mathers, makes his debut on
the arm of Dr. Dre, the producer who introduced skillful lyricist
Snoop Doggy Dogg on the 1992 hip-hop classic ``The Chronic.''
</P>
<P>
   Check one: Street credibility accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Now give the combo another check for coming up with the
well-produced ``Slim Shady LP'' that, with a dose of well-hidden
humor, manages to be both infectious and incredibly offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about slipping a 15-year-old drugs to have sex with her
(``Guilty Conscience''), taking a toddler to the river to dump
Mommy's body (`` '97 Bonnie &AMP; Clyde'') and the tonsillectomy of the
first lady without the benefit of anesthesia (``Role Model'') _
it's all here. And clearly, skillfully delivered by the nasal
Eminem over some of the most lithe tracks the usually
keyboard-laden Dr. Dre has done in years.
</P>
<P>
   Guess you can consider this hip-hop's big payback to the
millions in the mainstream who supported rapper-turned-rocker
Vanilla Ice in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Slim Shady LP''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem.
</P>
<P>
   Aftermath/Interscope. 20 tracks. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
