<HEADER>
A6043 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     03-03 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS HAVEN'T BEEN CONVINCED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the television babblemeisters posed the question: Is
there anything Bill Clinton could be accused of that would damage
his standing in the polls?
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the president of the United States has been accused
of perjury and obstruction of justice. Unofficially, he has been
accused of everything from chronic moral turpitude to murder.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the public-opinion polls have pegged his job
approval rating at somewhere between 60 and 70 percent, depending
on the severity of the pending allegation. The rating goes and up
down in direct proportion to the charge: The worse the crime, the
higher the job approval.
</P>
<P>
   So now comes the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll showing the
president's job approval at 66 percent in the wake of an Arkansas
woman's claim that Clinton raped her in a Little Rock hotel room 21
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors of polling would say that this proves once again that
the national polls are defective or rigged _ or both. Detractors of
the American people would say that the poll proves once again that
Clinton's constituents have reached a new low in their relentless
descent into moral depravity.
</P>
<P>
   Can it be? Is it possible that most Americans don't care if
their president is a rapist?
</P>
<P>
   No. It is not possible. Just as it wasn't possible that most
Americans didn't care if their president cheated on his wife, lied
under oath and tampered with witnesses in a legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Of course they care. If the president had committed such
offenses under different circumstances _ different from those of
the Great Sex Scandal of 1998, that is _ they might have cared
enough to demand his removal from office, or even his
incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   But the American people just plain didn't believe that Clinton's
misdeeds in the context of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky _
and his efforts to keep that relationship secret _ added up to the
sort of high crimes alleged by his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   As for Juanita Broaddrick's claim that Clinton assaulted her in
1978, the majority of respondents in the USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll
said they doubted Broaddrick's story. It's not that Americans don't
care if the president raped Broaddrick; it's that they don't
believe that he did it.
</P>
<P>
   Their skepticism is justified. Any objective observer who
watched Broaddrick's interview on NBC's ``Dateline'' would have to
say that her story had some holes in it. Some might say _ as an
editor friend of mine used to say about the occasional defective
news story _ that Broaddrick's version of events had holes big
enough to drive a truck through.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are obvious. If Broaddrick was raped, why didn't
she call the cops? If she was raped, why did she say she wasn't
when asked about it under oath many years later? If she knew
Clinton to be a violent criminal when he was attorney general of
Arkansas, why did she stand idly by and allow him to climb the
political ladder all the way to the White House?
</P>
<P>
   She told ``Dateline'' that she was afraid Clinton would destroy
her if she revealed what he had done to her.
</P>
<P>
   Well, at the time that he allegedly did whatever he did to
Broaddrick, Clinton was a political novice who was far from
accumulating the power and influence that would allow him to savage
someone's reputation with a snap of his fingers. It was far more
likely that Broaddrick could have destroyed Clinton if she'd gone
public with her accusation way back in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton has not offered an alternative version of the
alleged incident, of course, we have no way of knowing how his side
of the story might stack up against Broaddrick's. On the other
hand, why should Clinton even be expected to tell his side of
something that happened all those years ago _ or maybe didn't
happen at all?
</P>
<P>
   The American people are smart enough to understand all this.
Their lack of outrage about this unprovable accusation against the
president is not a sign of depravity.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sign that common sense is alive and well in America.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
