<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTODY-BATTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS ISSUES CLOUD CUSTODY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith and Nanci Bohne believe their town is the perfect place to
raise their 5-year-old granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   An apple orchard rises behind their house. Down a winding road,
the scent of dried flowers, apples, and fresh earth fills the
country store the Bohnes run on their 50-acre family farm.
</P>
<P>
   But Westford, Mass. shares another quality with many bucolic
bedroom communities: It is almost all white _ and the Bohnes'
granddaughter, Alexandria, is half black.
</P>
<P>
   That issue is the crux of the custody battle between the Bohnes
and Alexandria's other grandparents, Mary and George Goullaud, who
live in a two-family house in Malden, a hardscrabble city near
Boston that is also mostly white but with a far larger minority
population.
</P>
<P>
   The custody case has become a battle between two concepts of
community _ an upscale, largely insular suburb and a diverse but
economically struggling city.
</P>
<P>
   Both sets of grandparents are white, but have raised children of
color. Both are devoted to raising their granddaughter. But the
Goullauds argue that they _ and their city _ are more comfortable
with racial differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case represents two solid families petitioning the court
for custody of a beautiful little girl,'' the Goullauds' lawyer,
Wayne Murphy, said. ``It presents the unique situation of deciding
what is in the best interest of a biracial child.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandria Lee Goullaud is the daughter of Jennifer Goullaud, a
white Malden woman, and Jeffrey Bohne, a black man who was adopted
as a child by the Bohnes and brought up in affluent Westford.
</P>
<P>
   Both alcoholics and heroin users, the two young people never
married; in fact, they never had much more than a brief dalliance,
according to court records. The Bohnes did not even know about
Jennifer Goullaud or the baby until a month after Alexandria's
birth on Jan. 12, 1994. A friend of their son informed them.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandria was raised by her mother mostly in the Goullaud
household, with virtually no contact with the father, court records
show. But almost from birth, Alexandria spent time with her
Westford grandparents, and began overnight visits with them when
she neared her first birthday, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, while Mary Goullaud cared for two other grandchildren,
Jennifer allowed Nanci Bohne, 55, and her husband, Keith, 54,
temporary custody of Alexandria for seven months, while Jennifer
lived in a drug-rehabilitation facility in Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, three weeks before Alexandria's 4th birthday, police
found 25-year-old Jennifer Goullaud dead of a heroin overdose on
the bathroom floor of a Salem, N.H., fast-food restaurant.
Alexandria was on an overnight visit with the Bohnes when the young
mother died.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Bohne, 30, a homeless addict in Lowell, Mass., is in
touch with his parents, and sees Alexandria under strict
supervision when she is at his parents' home.
</P>
<P>
   The bright-eyed youngster, who loves wearing purple dresses and
eating salad, spends three days a week in Westford and four days in
Malden, according to a court agreement. Both families have said in
affidavits that it is time for her to have a permanent home,
particularly because she will begin kindergarten next fall.
</P>
<P>
   A court-appointed investigator, Stoneham clinical psychologist
Robert Stier, concluded in January that Alexandria should live with
the Bohnes. In his report, he said that the Bohnes seemed more open
to involving the Goullaud family than the Goullauds were about
involving the Bohnes. He also wrote that the child's bedroom in
Westford had more toys and books than the one in Malden. Finally,
he noted that Alexandria told him she wanted to live in Westford.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this has nothing to do with money and toys _ it is not
just about goodies in Westford,'' said adoption specialist Joyce
Maguire Pavao, director of the Center for Family Connections in
Cambridge, Mass., bristling at the description of toys and
bedrooms. ``It could be that Malden may actually remind her more of
her sadness. That is her mother's family, and there is not as much
emotion attached to her father.''
</P>
<P>
   The Goullauds, meanwhile, say life in Westford would be
alienating for a biracial child. Their house in Malden, by
contrast, is the center for an active extended family of aunts,
uncles, cousins, and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Goullaud, 55, is a public school teacher with a master's
degree in counseling; George, 64, is a retired United Parcel
Service worker.
</P>
<P>
   The Bohnes and their attorney, Carol Weinstein Boileau, declined
comment for this story, citing Alexandria's right to privacy and
the pending court case which begins March 3 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the Bohnes and the Goullauds, like all
custody cases, will ultimately hinge on the court's interpretation
of the ``best interests of the child'' _ who not only has to juggle
the death of her mother and absence of her father, but also the
social obstacles she will face as a woman of mixed race.
</P>
<P>
   But specialists have differing opinions on which criteria should
be given the greatest weight, especially regarding the issue of
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family that best understands the needs of a child of color
is best suited'' to raise the child, declared Joe Kroll, director
of the North American Council of Adoptable Children based in
Minnesota. ``The key thing is understanding the impact of race on a
child in this country. Families that can prepare a child for that
are the better families.''
</P>
<P>
   Kroll stressed the importance of ``living where the child can
experience his own culture and see same-race adults regularly,
understanding the reality of racism, and helping the child learn to
accept his own cultural or racial ancestry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard Law School professor Elizabeth Bartholet, a family
law and civil rights specialist who is against using race in
deciding guardianships and adoptions, said the ``race card'' in a
custody battle like the one swirling around Alexandria should be
considered irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case like this, you won't have the most problematic form
of considering race, which is the bias (in favor) of placing
children with the parent who looks like them racially,'' Bartholet
said, because the competing grandparents are white. ``When you
eliminate that, it looks to me like this is a tough case where the
court will have to look at a whole range of factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartholet argued that using race can overwhelm other matters
that could prove important in deciding on a permanent home for any
child _ for example, which community has better schools.
</P>
<P>
   The race factor, said Bartholet, ``limits black children's
opportunities to have a range of adoption opportunities. The
presumption is that it is best to be surrounded by same-race
bodies, when the world is more comlex than that. Middle-class black
families certainly think there is more to it than (race).''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Goullaud argues that she and her husband are best suited to
raise Alexandria because in addition to living in a racially
diverse city, Goullaud has helped raise the biracial child of her
28-year-old daughter, Christine. As a teacher in Boston suburbs
Chelsea and Somerville, Goullaud said, she has long worked with
children of many backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest public school data, Westford schools are
95.5 percent white, 3.4 percent Asian, and only 1.1 percent black.
Malden schools are 63 percent white, 13.4 percent black, 17 percent
Asian, and 6.6 percent Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   But if, as Mary Goullaud suggests, the court should consider
which family is most adept at crossing color lines, then the Bohnes
could have claims of their own.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, the Bohnes adopted Alexandria's
father, Jeffrey, who was born in Connecticut with fetal alcohol
syndrome. The court records do not discuss his home life prior to
his adoption by the Bohnes at age 4.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey suffered from emotional and behavioral problems, as well
as learning disabilities, as a child, for which the Bohnes sought
help for him, the records show.
</P>
<P>
   The records say that he is unprepared and uninterested in being
a parent, and does not object to his parents' quest for
guardianship. Jeffrey Bohne could not be located for comment at or
near the Middlesex Shelter in Lowell, where sources say he often
resides. He did not return a message left for him at the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Stier, the court-appointed investigator who interviewed both
couples, wrote in his Jan. 27 report that the Bohnes said they are
aware of the ``complexities of raising a biracial child in their
community. They see in Westford a community more ethnically diverse
than previously . . . and they see in Alexandria a different child,
with far fewer problems and more potential than Jeffrey.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
