<HEADER>
A6091 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-03 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS HAS MORE MANAGERIAL MOVES THAN YOU THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ C'mon, admit it. You think Jimy Williams is
an utter goober.
</P>
<P>
   You've had that impression since his introductory Boston press
conference, otherwise known as the ``bump-your-booty'' media
session. His folksy ways make him prime fodder for ridicule in
oft-snobby New England.
</P>
<P>
   You can't even believe he's from California, because when most
people in our part of the world think of our most populous state
they think of Southern California or the Bay Area, and not the vast
interior. They think of traffic jams, not fruits and vegetables.
The San Joaquin Valley might as well be on Jupiter as in Central
California.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``other'' California is the Steinbeck California, and
it's also Jimy's California. ``It's an agricultural state,'' he
points out. ``There are a lot of remote areas. A lot of cows
chewing a lot of cuds.'' He comes from people who get their hands
dirty, and he is proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   But a goober? Forget it. He is a college graduate (Fresno State)
and he is a very good reader of people. He's got the Boston media
scene figured out, and don't you think he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in competition, both with yourselves and with the other
papers in our division, just like we are,'' he says. ``I understand
that. You've got to express yourselves in an individual manner, and
I know I'm not always going to like it. But, I'll tell ya, your job
isn't easy. First, you've got to get the news, and then you've got
to convey it. To me, that's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world of La Russas and Valentines and Johnsons, Jimy
Williams is a very soft sell. He would never, ever, think of using
the word ``genius'' in connection with managing a baseball team.
``I don't know of any geniuses in this business,'' he says, ``and,
if there are, it's the players who made 'em that way.''
</P>
<P>
   If the word ``genius'' is not in his vocabulary, neither is the
word ``arrogant.'' Years ago Charlie Dressen used to tell his
Dodgers to ``keep it close and I'll think of something.'' You won't
be hearing that from Jimy Williams. ``Personally,'' he confides,
``I don't think a manager can ever win a game, but he can certainly
lose them.''
</P>
<P>
   People on the outside seemed to appreciate what he did last year
more than people inside 495. The Red Sox won 93 games and got into
the postseason with a team needing massive amounts of TLC. If Joe
Torre's gang had won 100 games, rather than 114, Jimy Williams
might very well have been the American League Manager of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   It was a team that cried out for lineup manipulation, and that
happens to be a Jimy Williams specialty. It takes a fair amount of
probing to get this modest man to analyze himself, but he will
admit to one managerial strength. ``What I try to do is identify
the strengths and weaknesses of each player and then place them
only in situations where they can have the best chance of
success,'' he says. A corollary would be, ``And I try to keep
everyone on the 25-man roster as sharp as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams believes a man is on his team for a reason. ``If a man
is on a major league roster, then he is supposed to be a major
league player,'' he says. ``So I'll play him. I believe regulars
need days off. I don't think it's necessary to play 162 games. Many
of them don't understand that the day off is as much or more a
benefit mentally than it is physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching these guys all the time, looking for signs. Maybe
a guy isn't adhering to his usual routine. Sometimes you can tell
something is wrong just by the way they walk into the clubhouse. So
I'll try to get to them before they hit the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the quintessential company man, and he never will
understand why a cynical city like ours regards that as a bad
thing. We live in the strangest of all baseball cultures, and it's
really bizarre now because while the fans and even the media
relentlessly personalize the Red Sox experience, the current
manager does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't lose Mo Vaughn from my team,'' he says. ``That's
because it isn't my team, it's our team. We are all in it together
here, and I'm not going to cry about Mo Vaughn because I like the
players we have. As long as these kids put out the effort and play
with honest intensity, I can't complain. I like this team because I
saw what it did last year, and it was more than Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``How good can we be without that power? I don't know. Nobody
does. But instead of a home run, can you win with a clutch two-out
single? Can you win with a key sacrifice bunt? Sure. Can you win
with pitching and defense, both of which I think we have? Sure.
We'll find out.''
</P>
<P>
   While accepting the reality that within the group of 25 there
has to be at least one player who has harbored a grievance against
the skipper, I think it can safely be said that he is just about
universally popular in the clubhouse. Players appreciate the
honesty. Players appreciate the fairness. Players appreciate the
essential decency. And, guess what? Players appreciate the
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made Duquette look awfully good last year,'' says one
veteran. ``And he'll do it again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not a genius. He's not a blowhard. He's just an
unpretentious guy from the heart of California who understands how
to run a baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
