<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES, THE CITY WE LOVE TO HATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No one visits Los Angeles, it seems, without a
theory in hand. Once planted under the palm trees, soaking up the
sun, Easterners and Europeans can't resist the temptation to
``explain'' this most self-explanatory of American cities. Lovely
climate; add jobs, bring water, build highways. Voila! Megalopolis.
</P>
<P>
   But simple explanations never suffice for the self-appointed
guardians of Western (European) culture. Under the pens of the 20th
century's greatest writers, Los Angeles emerges as dark, menacing,
and catastrophe-prone, an ``Apocalypse theme park,'' in the words
of the LA theoretician du jour, Mike Davis. The only similar bolus
of silliness in the English language is men writing about the
mysteries of women. (And now, women writing about men.)
</P>
<P>
   A few examples suffice. Once in LA, Thornton Wilder, the bard of
Peterborough, N. H., declared: ``God never meant man to live
here.'' William Faulkner called LA ``the plastic ---hole of the
world.'' In his essay, ``Death in Hollywood,'' Evelyn Waugh (it
could just as well have been Aldous Huxley, another whiny Brit
lining his palm at the Hollywood trough) predicted that Southern
California would collapse and revert to desert.
</P>
<P>
   In her just-published memoir, ``Angels &AMP; Aliens,'' Sarah
Lawrence College writing teacher Mary Morris describes her brief,
forced exile in Orange County. Waking up on her first California
morning, Morris sees her neighbor ``dressed in a string bikini,
zinc oxide on her nose, wear(ing) a cordless Walkman that projects
two antennae from her head, and I know that I have come to Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Like the army of hacks preceding her, the otherwise
talented Morris has loaded up on cliches for her swoop through
Southern California. Car washing, she reports, is an ``odd
ritual.'' And a visit to the La Brea tar pits provokes the
Easterner's inevitable epiphanic meditation on LA's heart of
violence (saber-toothed tigers!) and destruction. ``In this city,''
Morris writes, ``catastrophe lurks everywhere.'' Then she returns
to New York. . .
</P>
<P>
   What's really going on here? In his 1994 book, ``Translating
LA,'' Boston-born Peter Theroux notes that ``very few LA books seem
to have been unpremeditated. . .It is a place that no one wants to
see through native eyes.'' He's right, and his own book is a
partial corrective to the trashing-LA trend. Theroux is an
Arabic-English translator and also a volunteer English tutor.
Having lived in Beirut, he understands the dynamics of a
multiracial mega-city, and he appreciates the difference between a
city people are fleeing from and a city people are fleeing to.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the reasons underlying Easterners' dread of
Los Angeles:
</P>
<P>
   --Hispanophobia. The men who created the first 200 years of
American history hailed from Europe north of the Alps. The Spanish
settled California, so its social as well as physical climate was
Mediterranean. Boston's own Richard Henry Dana nearly died from
culture shock in 1834 Monterey, presaging the Eastern elite's
discomfort with the languid lifestyle in La-La land.
</P>
<P>
   --Hollywood. Nothing galls the Eastern intelligentsia more than
the success of Hollywood, the most powerful cultural force in the
world. It turns out that people would rather watch a Sylvester
Stallone movie than read a David Foster Wallace novel. Who would
have thunk it?
</P>
<P>
   --Snobbery. Easterners sneer at the purveyors of LA's ``new''
wealth (the families Chandler, Ahmanson, Hammer, and Getty) as if
the tribes Rockefeller and Morgan had been endowing world culture
since before the Flood.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern Californians' greatest sin of all is happiness.
Their climate is inviting, the scenery gorgeous, and their attitude
disturbingly upbeat. This must be threatening; otherwise, why would
we relentlessly mock their smog, trumpet their natural disasters,
and deride their quest for spiritual self-satisfaction? Because, as
H. L. Mencken noted, nothing bothers the Puritan more than the
haunting fear that someone, somewhere is having a good time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
