<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      03-03 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERLONI FORGING AN IDENTITY WITH RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Mike Stanley walked by Lou Merloni, mock
disgust on his face.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Big League Lou,' that's his new name,'' said Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham Kid shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, he's mad at me,'' said Merloni with a grin, ``because
Nomar and I were at the same restaurant he was the other night with
a friend, and we didn't stop by his table to say hello.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Stanley probably would have had no idea what to call
Merloni, unless he glanced at the name above the locker. ``Minor
League Lifer'' would have been a more plausible handle than ``Big
League Lou'' for Merloni, whose name never even appeared in the
fine print when the Sox' top prospects were being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Merloni's only connection to the Red Sox' future, it seemed, was
his close friendship with Nomar Garciaparra, his former minor
league infield partner who achieved stardom while Merloni was still
muddling through Double A.
</P>
<P>
   But that all changed last year, through a chain of events that
began with Merloni making a favorable impression on manager Jimy
Williams during spring training. Merloni didn't make the club out
of camp, but he went down to Pawtucket and tore up the
International League, batting .386 with eight home runs in just 27
games.
</P>
<P>
   Then his pal, Garciaparra, did his part, sustaining a separated
shoulder while diving for a ground ball in Kansas City, with the
Red Sox ahead by 11 runs. Two days later, Merloni was making his
big league debut against the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We joke around about that,'' Merloni said. ``Nomar tells me he
faked it. `What a friend,' he says. `I faked the injury for you.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, dressing at the adjoining locker, sticks by his
story. ``It's true,'' he says solemnly.
</P>
<P>
   But it was during Merloni's debut in Fenway Park five days later
that truth took a header, and fantasy prevailed. The kid who grew
up in Framingham, went to Providence College, and imagined such
moments only in his backyard, hit a home run into the left-field
screen off Royals pitcher Jose Rosado in his first at-bat on Yawkey
Way.
</P>
<P>
   For a comparable moment, you'd have to go back to the
19-year-old from Swampscott, Tony Conigliaro, back in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I did it,'' Merloni says now. ``The biggest
thing about that at-bat is that it went five, six, seven pitches. I
went deep into the count, 3-and-2, hit a couple of foul balls, and
because of that I was more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to talk to Tony's brother, Richie Conigliaro,
at the writers' dinner. He was in the stands when Tony C did it.
It's one of those things that you know, 50 years from now, will
still be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, the amazing thing for me was just getting up there.
Even if I had struck out, I'd say the same. But the way it worked
out was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Garciaparra returned, Merloni remained a valuable
part of the Sox mix, starting 11 games at second base after Mark
Lemke went down and even making three starts at third. Twice he had
three hits in a game, and he showed a knack for hitting with
runners in scoring position (12 for 28, .429).
</P>
<P>
   But late in May, shortly after Garciaparra's return, Merloni ran
into the rolled-up tarp in Yankee Stadium while pursuing a foul fly
down the right-field line. His left knee ached, and though he
played through the pain for a month, he eventually was forced onto
the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   What was originally diagnosed as inflammation in the knee, then
a deep bone bruise, was eventually determined to be a stress
fracture. Merloni was activated in September, but by then he'd
missed so much time that the Red Sox couldn't use him down the
stretch or in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the injury had been correctly diagnosed from the outset,
he said, he doubts the outcome would have been any different. The
anxiety might have been less, but the time needed to heal would
have been about the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a bad break,'' he said. ``Physically, I was healthy when
I came back, but I wasn't close to being baseball-ready. As a rule,
I don't get nervous because I'm prepared out there. But if I'm on
the field and I'm not prepared, the tendency is to go `Geez.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So Merloni was only a spectator when the Red Sox lost in the
playoffs to the Indians, but when asked if last summer's injury was
the worst setback of his career, he shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even consider that as tough to deal with as some of
the things that happened in the minors,'' he said. ``I know when I
was up here, I did what I had to do to play well and help the team
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting hurt, yeah, that was frustrating, because you know you
can do so much more. But even though I was hurt, I showed them I
could play up here. The minors, that's a dogfight, just to prove
you can do it. When you have a setback there, that's much tougher
to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Benjamin left this winter as a free agent to sign a
two-year deal with the Pirates, Merloni was the logical candidate
to become the team's utilityman. Because he doesn't turn 28 till
April 6, Merloni hasn't abandoned the notion that he can play
second base on a regular basis in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even after last season, my name didn't even come up when
people talked about second base,'' he said. ``That's OK. It's been
that way my whole career, and I just use that as a way to motivate
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, the importance lies in being in the big
leagues, not so much where you play once you're there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't like I've solidified myself as a part of this team,''
he said. ``But I think I've answered some questions about whether I
can play.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly feel that way in Framingham. Last winter, 1,500
people showed up at a dinner to honor the pro ballplayers from the
town. They retired Merloni's number, and renamed a field at the
high school after him. The dinner also raised $11,000 for kids'
baseball programs in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself not to think about what was going on last season
until it was over,'' he said. ``But since then? Sure, I've sat back
and enjoyed it. I've watched a few films over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   (itals)The windup, and the 3-2 pitch from Rosado. There's a long
drive, deep to left field . . .(unitals)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
