<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SKEPTIC NOW TELLS OTHERS TO FIND THEIR ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandra Adler thought she was going crazy. For years she had kept
hearing voices. Her husband told her she needed help. So she
started seeing a psychiatrist. But the voices wouldn't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Until one day, at the suggestion of someone in her therapy
group, Adler went to a lecture on angels. ``I was at a point in my
life where I was depressed and I was grasping for straws,'' she
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   That lecture more than 30 years ago was a turning point in her
life. Adler became convinced that the voices in her head were her
guardian angels trying to communicate with her.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Adler travels the country and the world spreading her
message that we all have guardian angels who are trying to reach
us.
</P>
<P>
   From the crowds she draws, it is clear that many people believe,
or want to believe, in angels. Adler, who holds a master's degree
in counseling from the University of Michigan, is one of many
speakers who has successfully tapped into the spiritual
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Adler says the challenge is recognizing an angel's call. Goose
pimples or a sudden case of the chills, Adler says, are actually
signs from angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels come close to us to let us know that they are there to
protect us or to let us know know that we are doing the right
thing, '' said Adler, who is vice president of Inner Peace
Movement, a nonprofit group in Washington, D.C. that offers
workshops on angels. ``Most people have had the experience of
following a hunch or an intuition and having it work out. Well,
that's one way that angels are helping us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Inner Peace Movement says it has trained more than 100,000
people in the United States to communicate with their guardian
angels.
</P>
<P>
   Adler readily admits that many people find her ideas difficult
to grasp. That's part of the reason she spends so much time on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she says, she had her own doubts. ``I was the biggest
skeptic in the world,'' says Adler, who lives in Las Vegas. ``I was
a school teacher and we did not teach about this in school.''
</P>
<P>
   She became a believer after she started becoming involved with
Inner Peace Movement, which was founded in 1964. ``The Inner Peace
Movement doesn't do anything for you, but it will show you how to
do it for yourself,'' said Adler, speaking by telephone from
Jackson, Miss., where she was lecturing last week.
</P>
<P>
   These days angels are a hot commodity on film and in print.
``Touched by an Angel,'' in which angels come to the aid of
troubled souls, is a hit show for CBS. Dozens of volumes on angels
fill the new age and spirituality sections of bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Angels are central to Roman Catholicism and Judaism, cited in
the Bible as divine messengers. Some theologians argue that logic
cannot prove the existence of angels. Other scholars argue that
reason cannot disprove their existence either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't prove anything, but if you experience it for
yourself then you know it's true,'' Adler says.
</P>
<P>
   There are four ways guardian angels try to get in touch with us,
Adler says. One is through intuition _ hearing a voice within.
Another is through vision _ noticing a shadow out of the corner of
your eye.
</P>
<P>
   A third way angels communicate is through prophecy, having
dreams come true or knowing who is calling before we pick up the
phone. And finally, Adler said there is ``gut feeling.'' Some
people describe the sensation of ``feeling someone tap them on
their shoulder and when they turn around no one is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Adler recounts a story told by a woman who attended one of the
lectures in Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The woman was in the hospital waiting for surgery to begin to
remove a cancerous tumor from her breast. As she was lying waiting
for an X-ray she said she felt a hand touch the back of her neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they looked at the X-ray the cancer was gone,'' Adler
said. ``She asked the doctors who had touched her neck and they
told her that no one had. At that moment she knew it was her
angel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --In a strongly worded pastoral letter, the Most Rev. Sean
O'Malley, bishop of the Diocese of Fall River, Mass., Sunday
denounced capital punishment as a violation of Jesus's teachings
and a failed deterrent to violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere does Jesus offer violence as a solution to set things
straight,'' wrote O'Malley. ``He does not will the death of the
sinner, but rather that the sinner be converted.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley cited national surveys of police chiefs and
criminologists showing that the death penalty is considered a poor
way to deal with crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our country to be characterized by justice, not
revenge; by safety, not violence; by life, not death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
