<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-FANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETING SAVVY HELPS NBA BOUNCE BACK WITH FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within minutes of the National Basketball Association officially
returning to business at 2 p.m. on January 22, e-mail and faxes
from the league offices in Manhattan began arriving in the 29 team
offices around the country and in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The coordinated message _ devised over the course of the
six-month lockout, and reiterated frequently through the start of
play February 5 _ was that franchise executives, coaches and, most
of all , players should participate in a grand marketing strategy.
The goal, as articulated in one e-mail message: ``Re-establishing
the standing and reputation of the NBA and its teams with fans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are inviting NBA fans back to our game,'' another e-mail
advised the franchises. ``Demonstrate that we recognize NBA fans
(itals)do not owe us(unitals) renewed support, and show that we are
committed to earning back their support...Ground communications in
substantive policies and actions that demonstrate the NBA and its
teams accept full responsibility for any damage done to the bond
between the league and its players and NBA fans.''
</P>
<P>
   In a performance that amounts to a marketing slam dunk, the NBA
has roared back this month with fan support equal to or exceeding
pre-lockout levels. The league has defied the conventional wisdom
that its long labor dispute would harm the NBA and create a long,
difficult recovery.
</P>
<P>
   By developing grassroots, guerilla, marketing tactics even
before the lockout ended , the NBA has marshalled the support of
its players, its network television partners and its corporate
sponsors in a massive campaign to make amends with the fans. Long
accepted as the best at marketing among the four major professional
sports leagues, the NBA used the tactics to quickly build on the
successes of the past 20 years, when it established enduring
relationships between the game's biggest stars and their fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been able to handle what easily could have been a
real near-death experience, and turn it into what now looks like a
blip on the screen,'' said Glenn Rifkin, the Acton, Mass. author of
``Radical Marketing,'' which includes a chapter on the winning
strategies and tactics of the NBA. ``The NBA has responded
brilliantly to this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Network television ratings are up almost 20 percent _ from an
average of 4.6 on NBC last year to 5.5 through Thursday night's
games, and from an average of 1.7 on TNN last year to 2.0.
Television executives and league officials say that some local
cable television broadcasts in areas directly surrounding the
franchises are performing even better.
</P>
<P>
   Home-game attendance since the lockout has either increased or
remained the same as last season among 14 of the NBA's 29 teams,
according to a survey conducted by Street &AMP; Smith's SPORTSBUSINESS
Journal. Another 11 teams are showing declines of less than 10
percent. And only four are showing anything like the sharp declines
experienced by baseball franchises throughout 1996 and much of
1997, during that league's strike.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's marketing effort was devised after much preparation.
``It was really a strategy that evolved along a few lines all
through the lockout, back as early as October,'' said Rick Welts,
chief of marketing for the NBA. ``At one point, we actually had one
group we called the Re-entry Group working in one room on what
issues we would face if some games were cancelled, but we returned
to play this year. And, in another room, we had a different group
working on the issues that would arise if we lost a full season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by the end, when the lockout was over, everyone knew what
we were going to do and what their role would be,'' Welts said.
</P>
<P>
   The result, observers say, is that the NBA has accomplished in
about three weeks what it took Major League Baseball almost three
seasons to do: repair the breach between the fans and the game. And
baseball needed the riveting home run record race between Mark
McGwire and Sammy Sosa _ to get the job done after its disastrous
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been amazing, the speed with which fans have come
back,'' to the NBA, said Richard Lapchick, director of the Center
for the Study of Sport in Society at Northeastern University. ``And
we're talking about fan support at a surprising level for a game
that sometimes isn't even being played that well, yet, given that
some of the players are still a little out of shape.''
</P>
<P>
   In late December, before it was clear any games would be played
this year, the NBA invited officials from across the spectrum of
league interests to a major meeting in Manhattan. Representatives
of the television networks, key sponsors, general managers,
coaches, former players and marketing officials and consultants all
attended.
</P>
<P>
   Respected figures like Atlanta Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens and
Miami Heat coach Pat Riley held forth on what they thought the NBA
needed for the re-entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time the meeting broke up, it became pretty clear what
the real issues would be,'' Welts said. ``And it all revolved
around how to bring fans back to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   When the lockout finally ended, everything was in place. The NBA
office in New York told all 29 franchises that three things were
mandatory: hold a practice that would be free to the public, play a
pre-season game that would be admission-free at least to
season-ticket holders, and provide at least 500 tickets for every
game of the shortened schedule for $10 or less.
</P>
<P>
   NBA officials distributed ``Communication Goals and Supporting
Objectives'' to each of the teams. And in a long series of
memoranda called ``Re-Launch Issues,'' it continually kept all of
the franchises abreast of how individual teams were accomplishing
the goals.
</P>
<P>
   The league also sent camera crews and representatives to all the
free practices to provide footage for what has become a series of
public service announcements broadcast by both NBC and TNN during
NBA games. The announcements show players practicing with fans in
team drills, throwing souvenir t-shirts into the crowd, high-fiving
school children and autographing Valentine's Day cards that were
mailed to every season-ticket holder in the league.
</P>
<P>
   There were even some cameo shots of players like the Celtics'
Kenny Anderson manning one of the ticket booths at the Fleet Center
on the first day of sales, collecting money, and handing out the
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Media reports in the early days after the lockout followed
exactly along the NBA's marketing lines.
</P>
<P>
   Starved for any pro basketball action, especially as the NFL
season wound down to the Super Bowl, at least four Boston
television stations led their sportscasts on the night of the
Celtics' open practice with reports that were at least a few
minutes long _ about as long as it gets on local sportscasts. All
the reports were glowing appraisals of the team's attempt to
reconnect with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle cry when this lockout ended was `reach out and
touch the fans,''' WCVB-TV's Ed Harding gushed on one of the
broadcasts. ``And, boy is it working!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole effort of apologizing to the fans and restoring
their confidence in the game ended up providing for the sort of
coverage that we could not have paid for,'' said Stuart Layne,
executive vicepresident of marketing and sales for the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Even the announcement, a week after the tentative settlement, by
the game's star nonpareil Michael Jordan that he was retiring,
seemed to rebound right into the league's marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he cuts across so many lines, Michael's announcement
had the unintended effect of focusing the attention of the casual
fan, and even many non-fans, on the fact that the NBA was back,''
said James Farr, operations manager for the Black Sports Agents
Association a California-based group. ``It's almost scary to think
of what political and world events his retirement pushed off the
front pages, and it was a great reminder for key target
audiences.''
</P>
<P>
   The close cooperation of the players, and their willingness to
work with the league and the franchises, has been one of the
brightest aspects of the NBA's effort. Officials familiar with the
bargaining that occured as the lockout wound down say that NBA
Commissioner David Stern and National Basketball Players'
Assocation President Hunter talked about the need for close
cooperation to maintain the business health of the game _ and all
of the faxes and e-mail messages reinforced that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have definitely heard David say that once they had a sense
that they had the makings of a deal, one of the things both
parties, the players and the league, said was, `We have to make it
clear that we owe something to make it up to the fans,' '' said
Kevin O'Malley, senior vicepresident for programming at Turner
Broadcasting. ``They knew before they agreed to be back that, once
they were back, they were in this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers say that beyond the tactics of dealing with the
emergency, the NBA made a series of smart strategy decisions about
the lockout itself that provided a powerful thrust for launching
the post-lockout marketing.
</P>
<P>
   By canceling the first 32 games of the season, and in effect
starting a whole new season late, the NBA helped assure that the
break in the action was not cataclysmic, observers say. By
contrast, Major League Baseball stopped action in midseason and
never played the World Series, alienating its fans. NBA and team
officials privately confirm that scheduling the lockout at the
beginning of the season, rather than during it, was all part of the
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be assured that one of the things we did learn is that
you are going to lose enormous support if you start a season and
then stop it, especially if you lose the championship games,'' a
high-ranking league official said.
</P>
<P>
   And the NBA returned just at the time when the nation
collectively turned its sports gaze from the National Football
League to basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is any coincidence that some of the deadlines
the league was setting toward the end of negotiations was timed
around the Super Bowl,'' Rifkin said. ``David Stern envisions the
NBA as a living brand, and he can't just assume that everything be
in the proper place all of the time. He is a master at working at
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
