<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIGEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC NEEDS LUCK AS 13TH SEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You want to talk about long shots in the Big East
men's tournament? Look no further than the Boston College Eagles.
After finishing last in the conference with a 3-15 record (6-20
overall), the Eagles have the dreaded 13th seed _ as almost all the
league coaches had predicted in a preseason poll _ and face the
unenviable task of hobbling into a first-round game against
fourth-seeded Syracuse, a team that has posed the biggest matchup
problems for them this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have that seed,'' said BC coach Al Skinner, whose team
wrapped up the regular season with a 78-59 loss at Notre Dame
Sunday, ``but we're a much different team than everyone had
predicted. People were talking about how we weren't going to win a
game and that we were going to be the worst team in the Big East
ever, and obviously that's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's most disappointing to me is that we're not
healthy at this point in time. We're already shorthanded and we're
already undermanned, and for us not to be healthy we really cannot
put forth our best foot. But you've got to play the cards that
you're dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of Wednesday's Syracuse-BC game will advance to the
quarterfinals Thursday to face the winner of the matchup between
No. 5 seed Villanova and No. 12 seed West Virginia. Top-seeded
Connecticut, which earned a first-round bye along with No. 2 seed
Miami and No. 3 seed St. John's, will face the winner of the
matchup between eighth-seeded Notre Dame and No. 9 Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, No. 7 Providence squares off against No. 10
Georgetown for the right to face the Hurricanes, and No. 6 Rutgers
will face No. 11 Pittsburgh for a berth against the Red Storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having to play only three games is a competitive advantage,''
said UConn coach Jim Calhoun. ``And it is even more of an advantage
big picture-wise for the next week (in the NCAA Tournament).''
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles have more pressing concerns, namely injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Michael Cotton is still ailing with a right foot
sprain he suffered Feb. 17 at Georgetown. Although he was not
expected to play against Notre Dame, Cotton suited up and started.
</P>
<P>
   ``His foot is still pretty sore and he really shouldn't have
been out there,'' Skinner said. ``But he's making a tremendous
sacrifice for the team just to get out there, because he really
should not be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotton is probable for the game against the Orangemen, and BC
will desperately need his court presence to help freshman forward
Brian Ross battle 6-foot-8-inch junior Etan Thomas, who led the
Orangemen with 25 points and 9 rebounds in a 73-56 rout at BC Feb.
24.
</P>
<P>
   That completed a sweep for Syracuse, which pinned a humiliating
39-point loss on BC, 90-51, at the Carrier Dome Jan. 21. That was
the second most-lopsided game in Big East history and BC's worst
conference loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that when you watch film on them, you see
BC play well,'' said Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim, whose team has a
4-2 tourney record vs. the Eagles. ``I've seen 'em play well
against a lot of teams. I saw them play well and beat Seton Hall. I
saw them play well and beat West Virginia. I saw them play well
against UConn. So we know they're capable of playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to guard against the fact we've had two very good
games against them. We have to be concerned about that and that's
been uppermost in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ross, ``They're definitely a bunch of arrogant kids, so
they're probably going to come in thinking they can walk all over
us again. But we're just going to have to play hard just like we
have all year. But I know that, just like a lot of the freshmen,
I'm really excited to get the chance to play at Madison Square
Garden for the first time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
