<HEADER>
A6124 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINING IN THE NEW `MASTERS OF THE UNIVERSE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From out of nowhere, it seems, day traders have emerged as a
modern-day menace. Congress is worried about them. So is Richard
Syron, head of the American Stock Exchange, Frank Zarb, chairman of
the National Association of Securities Dealers, and securities
regulators in many states, including Massachusetts. Just Tuesday
William Galvin, secretary of the Commonwealth, took action against
a day-trading firm, the fourth such crackdown in the last few
months.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the day is: How worried should the rest of us be
about day trading and what exactly should we do about it?
</P>
<P>
   In case you've missed it, day traders are mini ``masters of the
universe.'' Using powerful computers, they buy and sell stocks at
an incredible clip, hoping to make money on small movements in
price. Estimates put the number of active day traders in the
country at between 10,000 and 15,000. Anecdotal evidence suggests
the vast majority of people who try it lose money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a grave concern that people are being roped into this
without understanding the risks,'' says Philip Feigin, president of
the trade association for state securities regulators. For Feigin
and others, the number one issue in day trading is disclosure.
Simply put, do investors know what they are getting into?
</P>
<P>
   ``The philosophy of day trading is very different from normal
investing,'' says Galvin. ``In many cases I don't believe that
difference has been explained to customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin's office filed a complaint Tuesday against TCI Corp. for
deceptive marketing. In its advertising, the state charges, the
firm told prospective customers they were likely to achieve profits
and that they could earn ``six- to seven-figure incomes per year.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a second fear about day trading: that it could have
harmful effects on the stock market in general. Robert Glauber, a
former undersecretary of the US Treasury, now at Harvard
University's Kennedy School of Government, worries what might
happen if prices of the hot stocks favored by day traders suddenly
take a dive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone tried to get out the door at the same time, would
they all be able to fit through?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are paid to worry about such questions. They are also
paid to make sure that investors are getting good information and
that crooks are put out of business. Beyond that, however, it is
not clear regulators can or should do anything about day trading.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, day trading is a logical, if extreme, step along a
path we have been traveling for some time. Joseph Nocera called it
the ``democratization of finance.'' In a 1994 book called ``A Piece
of the Action,'' Nocera traced the history of financial innovations
like the credit card, the mutual fund, and the discount brokerage
and concluded they all had something in common: They gave ordinary
people access to the financial system. With the credit card, people
got short-term loans; with the mutual fund, they got a chance to
invest in stocks, once the exclusive province of the well-to-do.
</P>
<P>
   The ``money revolution'' that Nocera described has been a mixed
blessing. On the plus side, middle-class people have been able to
salt away money in 401(k) plans, a big boost to their retirement
savings. On the other side, those same people can wind up with
nothing if they make poor investment choices. People with checkered
credit histories now have the convenience of using a credit card.
They also have a chance to go bankrupt if they don't meet their
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   With day trading, the average guy can do what was once possible
only for professional traders. How much more democratic can you
get? That same average guy can also lose his shirt. When Galvin's
office took action last year against a day-trading firm called
Block Trading, they found that 67 of the 68 customers at the Boston
office lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the word out about those miserable results _ full
disclosure _ may do more to put a lid on day trading than all of
the enforcement actions put together. How many people, after all,
would flock to an investment that all but guaranteed they would
come out losers? As John Kenneth Galbraith put it in his book,
``The Great Crash'': ``Speculation on a large scale requires a
pervasive sense of confidence and optimism and a conviction that
ordinary people were meant to be rich.''
</P>
<P>
   As more ordinary people discover that getting rich isn't that
easy, they may lose their enthusiasm for day trading. And if, after
hearing an explanation of the risks, they still want to play, who
are we to stop them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
