<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6125 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2     03-03 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES AND ALLIES SAY MICROSOFT HAS STUMBLED IN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. is one of the most profitable
companies in any industry. Its earnings stun Wall Street. Its sales
confound competitors. Its chairman is the wealthiest man on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
   And yet despite its legendary competence, the world's dominant
software company appears to have bungled the basics in a crucial
task: defending itself against federal antitrust charges.
</P>
<P>
   With the landmark Microsoft trial on a six-week recess before
hearing from a few final witnesses, a striking range of people now
say the company is in danger of losing the case. That's due in
large part, critics say, to Microsoft's own courtroom missteps that
have ranged from botched video demonstrations to a fundamental
miscalculation in legal strategy.
</P>
<P>
   If Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of federal District Court in
Washington rules against Microsoft, he could order new constraints
on the Redmond, Wash., company's business practices and open
Microsoft to a rush of private antitrust suits. (A ruling is
thought to be at least three months off.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The company's presentation is stunning in its ineptitude,''
said Rich Gray, a Silicon Valley antitrust attorney who has
followed the trial closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be used for years in law schools to teach students
how not to try a case,'' said Dan Small, a Boston trial lawyer who
wrote the American Bar Association manual on preparing witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Thierer, a Microsoft sympathizer at the conservative
Heritage Foundation, said the company has all but lost. ``It
appears that the government has successfully taken down
Microsoft,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft cautions not to judge its case only on the courtroom
action. Much of its defense lies in the hundreds of pages of
written testimony and economic analysis that are part of the trial
record, but which have not received much attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think courtroom theatrics are important, then the
government is doing a good job,'' said Mark Murray, a Microsoft
spokesman who attends the trial each day and then wages a public
relations campaign on the courthouse steps. ``If you think creating
a trial record is important, then the government's case is pretty
threadbare.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government faces high legal hurdles in proving
that Microsoft misused monopoly power to crush its rivals.
Microsoft may have failed to use its court time to best advantage,
but that does not lighten the legal burden for the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 19 states charge that Microsoft has
illegally used a monopoly with its Windows operating system to hurt
rivals, such as Netscape Communications Corp. and Sun Microsystems
Inc. Both companies make products that could shatter the dominance
of Windows, software that controls the basic functions of 90
percent of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not illegal for Microsoft to operate a monopoly, the
law bars it from using monopoly powers to eliminate competitors or
to push into new lines of business.
</P>
<P>
   With money to buy the best defense around, Microsoft hired the
well-heeled firm of Sullivan and Cromwell. The firm is working in
tandem with Microsoft's in-house counsel, William Neukom.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that Microsoft has made two types of errors.
</P>
<P>
   First, they say, Microsoft failed to highlight its best argument
_ that consumers have only benefitted from its aggressive behavior
_ because it has been too busy countering every government claim of
a bullying tactic. Microsoft could have acknowledged that it plays
rough, but argued that this helped produce a healthy, competitive
software industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are alive and well and vigorous in the software market,
and prices are low,'' said Thierer of the Heritage Foundation.
``But Microsoft got too bogged down in fighting over legalities and
never got to say this.''
</P>
<P>
   The second criticism is that the Microsoft team was
ill-prepared, a crucial error given its courtroom adversary. The
government's lead lawyer, David Boies, was hired for his deftness
in handling complex litigation, including IBM Corp.'s defense on
antitrust charges, which the federal government abandoned after 13
years. Boies has had little trouble capitalizing on every Microsoft
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been several mistakes, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   Take the deposition of Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, which the
government played for the court on videotape. In it, Gates appeared
forgetful and argumentative, wrestling with prosecutors over the
meaning of words like ``compete'' and ``concerned.'' When Gates
claimed that he was not focused on attacking rivals like Netscape,
or that he had little role in key business decisions, the
government was able to produce e-mail messages written by him that
suggested a different story.
</P>
<P>
   The company appeared to ignore the public relations aspect of
the tape. Microsoft lawyers should have known that Gates's body
language and linguistic parsing would hurt him in court, said
antitrust specialist William Kovacic, a visiting professor at
George Washington University Law School. ``You have to make the
video a chance to tell your story,'' he said. Instead, Microsoft
allowed the government ``to tell the judge that this company is
untrustworthy, ruthless, perhaps deceitful, and you should not
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more shocking to some lawyers was Microsoft's handling of a
second video.
</P>
<P>
   This one was meant to bolster Microsoft's argument that its
browser and its Windows software are a single product.
</P>
<P>
   The government says that they should be sold separately and that
Microsoft merged them only to hurt Netscape. If consumers receive
Microsoft's browser for free when they buy Windows, they have no
incentive to buy Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's video was meant to show that Windows runs poorly
when its browser is removed. But under questioning by Boies, a
Microsoft executive was forced to admit that what had been
characterized as a demonstration on one computer was actually a
compilation of work on several computers, with the tape spliced
together.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2     03-03 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 WASHINGTON: ... spliced together.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``That was just a head-shaker _ you can't believe it's
happening,'' said Gray, the California lawyer. ``It's incredible
that lawyers at any level of competence would allow you to bring in
evidence that wasn't what they said it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, witness after witness for Microsoft has been flummoxed
by Boies, who is expert at using a witness's own writings to
contradict his courtroom testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executive Dan Rosen, for example, took the stand last
week to testify about a crucial June 1995 meeting with Netscape.
The government claims that during the meeting Microsoft illegally
offered to divide the market for Internet browsers so that each
company would keep its own niche and would not compete against each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen testified that he had not even seen Netscape's browser
until July, suggesting he could not have been worrying about it at
the June meeting. But Boies produced an e-mail by Rosen showing he
had the browser in April, forcing Rosen to recant.
</P>
<P>
   It's an open question whether Microsoft's credibility is truly
damaged and how much it will matter once Jackson retires to his
office to study the full record, including testimony not aired in
court and plenty of economic data.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the stuff that makes a splash while people are in the
courtroom does not really matter,'' said Ronald Cass, dean of the
Boston University School of Law, a Microsoft ally who has appeared
at company news conferences. The judge, he said, will focus less on
theatrics than ``on the actual evidence and how it stacks up.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is how some outside observers score the case so far:
</P>
<P>
   --Is Microsoft a monopoly?
</P>
<P>
   If the government cannot prove Windows is a monopoly, then it
can't claim Microsoft is illegally using monopoly powers to hurt
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Monopolies hold power because customers have little or no choice
of alternative products. But Microsoft has argued that if it failed
to innovate, it would soon lose its leadership role in the dynamic
software market. And its economics expert said that if Microsoft
truly controlled the market, it would charge as much as $2,000 for
Windows instead of $50.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kovacic and many other observers bet that Jackson will
view Windows' 90 percent market share as evidence of monopoly.
Moreover, Compaq Computer Corp. executive John Rose, testifying for
Microsoft, acknowledged that there was no real alternative to
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will bet you the price of a double mocha latte that Mr.
Rose's comment will be quoted in Judge Jackson's opinion,'' Kovacic
said.
</P>
<P>
   --Did Microsoft illegally use its monopoly power to attack
rivals, such as Netscape?
</P>
<P>
   The government said that Microsoft threatened to strip Compaq
and Gateway 2000, a major computer seller, of the right to sell
Windows if they did not back away from Netscape and adopt the
Microsoft browser. Officials from other companies, such as America
Online, said they chose the Microsoft browser only because
Microsoft promised them favorable placement in the Windows package.
</P>
<P>
   If true, Microsoft may have illegally used its Windows monopoly
to hurt Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has sought to show that these deals were partnerships
designed to help customers. Moreover, the company said, the
government has not refuted a key Microsoft argument: that Microsoft
has not blocked Netscape from getting its product to customers.
``They will distribute about 150 million copies this year,'' said
spokesman Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic said he suspected the judge would not find this argument
convincing. ``This is an area in which the law tends to be
government-friendly,'' he said. ``The government probably has an
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gray said the government has probably not made its case,
because it has not shown that Microsoft has anything approaching
control of the browser market.
</P>
<P>
   --Did Microsoft illegally try to divide the browser market with
Netscape so that the two companies would not compete?
</P>
<P>
   Despite testimony to the contrary from Gates and other Microsoft
executives, the government has produced internal Microsoft e-mail
messages showing that the company was worried about the threat from
Netscape at the time of the 1995 meeting. The result, said Gray, is
``a fairly compelling case'' from the government.
</P>
<P>
   But showing that Microsoft feared Netscape does not mean that
the government has proved Microsoft actually made an illegal offer.
According to Kovacic, case law requires that an offer to divide a
market be unambiguous. He believes that Microsoft may have created
enough doubt to escape the charge.
</P>
<P>
   --Did Microsoft illegally tie its Internet browser to Windows?
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft's video demonstration turned into a fiasco,
many observers say the company could win on this point. That is
because a federal Appeals Court last year opened the door for
Microsoft to combine the products if it could show any consumer
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing from 24 witnesses over 62 days since October, the
trial recessed Friday for six weeks or more as Jackson hears a
criminal case. The government and Microsoft will then present
rebuttal witnesses, who have not yet been named.
</P>
<P>
   The government has not yet proposed what remedy it will seek if
it wins. The judge could force Microsoft to abandon certain
business practices, such as contracts that discourage partners from
working with Netscape. He could force the company to remove its
browser from Windows. The most extreme penalty _ breaking Microsoft
into a Windows and non-Windows company _ is considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, there is as much mystery in how Microsoft
allowed itself to stumble as there is in how Jackson will rule.
Gates is known as a hands-on manager. Did he micromanage the
defense? Did the lawyers work well with the technology people?
</P>
<P>
   Said Kovacic: ``We won't know until there is that insider's
account of who did what.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
