<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO SHOW A LESSON IN HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think there's nothing more to learn about the history of women
in sports? A new HBO special is out to prove you wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dare to Compete: The Struggle of Women in Sports,'' which
debuts Monday at 10 p.m., traces American society from the
Victorian Age through the passive 1950s to Title IX and the
present, and by the time Sheryl Swoopes talks about the joy of
seeing little girls wearing her basketball jersey you will
understand the debt she owes to Suzanne Lenglen and Babe
Didrickson, to Billie Jean King and Wilma Rudolph, to Pat Summitt
and Ed Temple and Sen. Birch Bayh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that sports is a birthright,'' says Anita DeFrantz,
a 1980 Olympic rower who is now an International Olympic Committee
vice president, in the film. For women, claiming _ even recognizing
_ that birthright has seldom been easy, as narrator Lauren Hutton
explains. After all, in the 1800s, even the increase in mobility
granted by the invention of the baby carriage was seen as a social
threat.
</P>
<P>
   In that light, the emergence in the early 1900s of Lenglen as
one of the first female athletes to become superstars can be better
grasped. In winning five straight Wimbledon titles beginning in
1919, Lenglen employed a dance-like style that looked more like
ballet than what we think of today as tennis. Such grace and style
could hardly be threatening, and perhaps helped mitigate her
prickly temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the more refreshing aspects of ``Dare to
Compete'' is its willingness to acknowledge that women who are
athletes are also human, and that men are not always villians. The
segment on Didrickson, considered by many the greatest athlete male
or female of this century, is particularly enlightening, with
priceless footage and astute narration; while a look at Rudolph's
Tennessee State women's track team of the early 1960s, the Tiger
Belles, reveals a surprising secret behind their success that still
reverberates today.
</P>
<P>
   As the film winds down with glimpses of contemporary athletes
celebrating their successes _ soccer icon Mia Hamm sliding
gleefully on her stomach across a soccer field, ice hockey gold
medalist Angela Ruggiero flinging back her head and shouting to the
heavens _ viewers can't help but wonder if ``Dare to Compete, Part
II'' will someday bring us footage of feats we can't begin to dream
of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This documentary will be an educational resource, as well as
entertaining television,'' said Kendall Reid, senior producer of
the project. Let's hope so. It should be required viewing in every
classroom and every locker room.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kleinmann sets pace at BU
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larissa Kleinmann has been burning up the track at Boston
University. Only a freshman, Kleinmann recently won the 1,000
meters, 3,000 meters and mile, as well as anchoring the winning
4x800 relay, at the America East women's meet _ all within a span
of four hours. Needless to say, she was named the Outstanding
Performer, and BU won the women's title for the second time in
three years. Kleinmann, who came to the Terriers from her native
Germany, will run the 5,000 at the NCAA Indoor Championships. And
she goes in as one of the favorites: her 16:08.29 is the fastest
collegiate time in the country this year. If all goes well, she'll
also run the 3,000 on Saturday . . . Patricia I. Brown, who retired
in 1992 as a Suffolk University law librarian, recently received a
certificate from the National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown
for her contributions to women's baseball as a member of the
All-American Girls Professional Baseball League, in honor of the
10th anniversary of her induction into the hall. Brown was a
righthanded pitcher for the Kenosha Comets, Chicago Colleens and
Battle Creek Belles around 1950.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
