<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKING LAURIE'S GONE, BUT MEMORY STILL GLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I learned how to smoke in 1981 in a desert field
across from Shadow Mountain High School, the same place I graduated
from.
</P>
<P>
   I took my first drag with my two best friends _ who were also
learning how to smoke _ and, as we felt our heads float off our
bodies while a light ringing sensation zoomed through our veins, we
decided that it was a good idea to lie down in the dirt before we
fell down. It was a magic I'd never felt before, not even with Pop
Rocks and Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years later and six weeks ago, I'm pretty sure I kissed
my last butt goodbye. As a result, at night I can breathe and it
doesn't sound like wind chimes. Last week, I (begin ital) ran (end
ital) to the phone. I coughed yesterday and nothing shot out of my
mouth. Without the smoke smell, I can now wear clothes over and
over again before washing them.
</P>
<P>
   Since I felt healthier, I thought I probably looked cuter, too,
and bought myself a pair of overalls. My sense of smell has also
improved, and as a result, I can smell things _ like my husband _
more distinctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you just have a cigarette?'' I asked him as he was
climbing into bed one night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 3 o'clock this afternoon,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, now that I've quit smoking, my nose is just bionic,'' I
said. ``It's like getting a transplant. I'll bet in a couple of
weeks, I'll be able to locate missing children!!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow. How talented of you,'' my husband responded. ``I would
think that with your $6 million nose and the pungent odor in the
kitchen sink, you'd know that the dishes urgently need washing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please take a shower before you get next to me and pollute
these fresh sheets with that dirty smell,'' I mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss Smoking Laurie,'' my husband said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy! What did (begin ital) you (end ital) have for lunch, Mr.
Turd Tongue? An ashtray sandwich? Pew-eee! You smell like you've
been rolling around on the floor of a racetrack! It's just flooding
out of your pores!!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what,'' my husband began. ``I know you think you look
cute in those overalls because you've been wearing them for 16 days
now, but you really look like a Walton. Smoking Laurie would never
have worn those.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the NEW and IMPROVED Laurie,'' I stressed. ``All of my
senses are now heightened! With the nose of a wolf and the lungs of
a newborn!! I'm going to live much longer now!''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a treat,'' my husband replied wearily, turning out the
light.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I decided that I should reward myself with the
money I used to spend on smokes, so I put on my overalls and got a
ticket for ``200 Cigarettes,'' a new movie I heard was pretty
funny. As soon as the lights went down, the characters in the movie
started smoking and they never stopped. Taking place in 1981 _ the
same year I started smoking _ the movie doesn't have one scene when
a cigarette isn't being lit, puffed on or waved around. One smoke
gets fired up as another one is ground out.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie progressed, nearly a carton (which is 200
cigarettes) was being smoked before my eyes. I honestly began to
wonder why I had quit. My mouth watered, my stomach almost growled
with desire. My mind began to ask mean little questions. Hadn't
smoking been an integral part of me? Hadn't it been a give/give
relationship? Hadn't I gotten something back every time I lit up?
Wasn't quitting smoking like killing the jolly, hacking part of
myself, saying goodbye to a split personality that was more fun
than I was or getting a merry, cheerful demon ripped out of me by a
well-meaning priest?
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything has changed for me. Watching TV has become
just sitting on the couch, staring. Talking on the phone is a
nuisance, simply making my chin sweat now that all of the flair is
gone. When I'm around the same friends I took my first puff with in
the desert, I'm the odd man out. I'm the one who says, ``Oh, go on
ahead without me, you guys,'' as I'm looking down at the ground,
kicking at the dirt. ``I'm not allowed to in my religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in my car in the parking garage after the movie was
over, I turned the key in the ignition and realized that, like my
husband and my friends, I missed Smoking Laurie, too. Secretly, I
had been mourning her death. I had been trying to fool myself,
thinking, ``She's just on vacation with the Marlboro Team'';
``Look, there she is in the sky, exhaling a horizon full of nimbus
clouds''; or, ``She went to live on a farm in the country where she
could smoke all day.''
</P>
<P>
   But the truth was that Smoking Laurie was dead, and I had to
accept that. I have my pictures and I have my memories, but she
wasn't coming back. And while I understood I had gone to see that
movie to test myself, I owed something to her memory. She may have
been gone, but she wasn't forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   On the way home, I pulled the car into Coco's down the street
from my house. I walked proud and I walked tall to the hostess
station, and when she saw me, she smiled and said, ``Smoking or
non-smoking?''
</P>
<P>
   ``GUESS,'' I asserted.
</P>
<P>
   She stared at me for a moment. ``Well . . .'' she started with a
wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me step into the light,'' I said, giving her a better
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah,'' she said suddenly. ``Follow me, please. Right this
way.''
</P>
<P>
   I smiled as she sat me in a booth with an ashtray as the crown
jewel of the table, sparkling flawlessly like a white diamond.
Somewhere up there, I knew, Smoking Laurie was looking down on me,
because I heard her laugh fondly as she took a drag and then
coughed hard enough that she saw stars.
</P>
<P>
   She'll be with me always, even if I never pick up another
cigarette as long as I live.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you almost had me there,'' the hostess said, handing
me a menu. ``The overalls really threw me off. None of the Waltons
smoked, did they?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by e-mail to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
