<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-TALENT-ART-BO     03-03 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-TALENT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG COMPANIES SEEKING EXECUTIVES HAVE ROOM AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She began her working life as a junior high school teacher, ran
a health management organization, was president and chief executive
for 10 years at a big suburban hospital, and then turned
entrepreneur, opening a chain of women's health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   The clinics didn't live up to financial expectations, and now
Rina K. Spence has shifted gears again, joining Consensus
Pharmaceuticals Inc., a start-up biotechnology company in Medford,
Mass., as interim chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Spence, at 50-something, has strong administrative experience,
but cheerfully admits she knows little about biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   So, two evenings a week, she heads to Harvard University's
Extension School, sitting in on classes in biomedical sciences and
molecular biology. ``I love it,'' she said. ``I'm absolutely
fascinated by the sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   More than just a personal odyssey, Spence's transition is
emblematic of major changes occurring in how key jobs are being
filled at many of the promising young companies that get their
initial bankroll from venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a longstanding problem in hiring technical help to
translate good ideas into salable products and services, venture
capitalists are finding a shortage of executive talent with the
broad experience they believe necessary to launch new companies.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, venture capital funds that put billions of
dollars into these enterprises and oversee their growth are
abandoning hope of finding such people fast enough _ particularly
for Internet-related companies, at which stiff competition can
force a development schedule of as quickly as three months.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, said Jonathan Flint of Polaris Venture Partners in
Waltham, Mass., ``a lot of people are staffing their CEO positions
with people with a lot less experience, or are restructuring the
managerial hierarchy to take this into account.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of this trouble is of the venture funds' own making.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a buoyant economy and rapid technological change, as
well as smart picks, portfolios of companies backed by venture
capitalists have produced enviable, 30-percent annualized returns
for investors in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging theirs is a high-risk game, the funds also
have touted this record to raise nearly $38 billion over the past
two years to pump into more young companies. According to the
National Venture Capital Association, 5,153 companies received
venture help in 1997 and 1998, five times as many as between 1994
and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As a rule, inventors with good ideas seldom boast equal skill in
management, which is why they go to venture capital managers to get
started. These managers, along with their commitment to bankroll
the project, agree to find a chief executive _ ideally, someone who
understands the product or service, has a strong marketing
background, and, most desirably, was successful in running other
start-ups, preferably to the point of an initial public stock
offering or a sale or merger.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, with such explosive growth, the number of
people who can fill that bill hasn't kept pace. And according to
professional executive recruiters, candidates who might be induced
to jump from existing jobs into new ones are also few, because
they're generally satisfied with their present status.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people tend to be excited about where they are,'' said
Bentley H. Beaver, managing director at Onstott Group, a Wellesley
Mass., executive-search company. ``There's nothing causing them the
slightest discomfort, at least not enough to move, and the road
ahead for them is all green lights. Why should they?''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a typical chief executive search takes at least
four months, Beaver said. And where nine out of 10 searches could
be wrapped up within that time five years ago, he said, only 60
percent meet that target these days.
</P>
<P>
   Confounding the situation is the almost exponential growth of
the Internet sector. The most recent PricewaterhouseCoopers venture
capital survey found that more than 40 percent of all New England
companies getting venture funding during the fourth quarter of 1998
identified themselves as Internet-related.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is a sector plainly still in diapers. The Internet's
business potential blossomed into public view less than six years
ago and its most experienced people tend to be under 30 and are
unseasoned in the ways of board rooms and banking houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most experience you are going to find in anyone (in the
Internet sector) is three years,'' said Michael Frank, a partner at
Advanced Technology Ventures of Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   One compromise, Frank said, is to find someone who knows the
field to which an Internet proposal is tied _ an experienced toy
merchandiser for a Web site selling educational aids, for example _
backed up by a younger chief technology officer who, conceivably,
could be mentored in chief executive skills while in this job.
</P>
<P>
   But, Frank said, with a great sense of urgency in the
venture-capital world to push Internet-related companies to market
as quickly as possible, ``some of these people are being asked to
assume key positions perhaps sooner than they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint, at Polaris, said another frequent technique is to elevate
a top-flight marketing expert to a chief executive. The reasoning
is that in the current frenetic marketplace for Internet stocks, a
new company's prospects for success rest heavily on getting its
product to market as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But that, in turn, has brought a shortage of skilled marketing
people to fill the positions these people vacate. Flint's answer is
to break the traditional marketing job in two: one person working
on strategy and the other on execution.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology is a problem area, too, for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The field, while now 20 years old, is seen still full of promise
for eventually discovering important drugs. But it has yet to yield
many successes. Many companies have failed outright or have run out
of money as the development of these therapies has taken far more
time and money than expected. Others are still plugging away at
their original missions _ their executives of 10 years ago still on
the job, deeply committed intellectually, and in potential
stock-option profits, to finishing the job.
</P>
<P>
   Linda D. Sonntag of Axiom Venture Partners of San Francisco,
said such thin pickings in a highly specialized field means a
typical search for a biotech chief executive takes six months to a
year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sonntag who was responsible for hiring Spence, former
chief executive at Emerson Hospital in Concord, Mass. and founder
of the ultimately unsuccessful Spence Health Centers chain of
women's medical clinics, to run Consensus Pharmaceutical.
</P>
<P>
   Consensus plans to do drug screening for other pharmaceutical
companies using a peptide-based technology discovered at Beth
Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston. Axiom and InterWest
Partners of Menlo Park, Calif., put up $4 million in venture
capital funding last summer to back Consensus's growth. CareGroup
Inc., parent of BI-Deaconess, also has an equity stake under a
licensing agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to get the company going, and at a location close to
BI-Deaconess, Sonntag and her counterpart at InterWest, Arnold L.
Oronsky, faced traveling to Boston almost weekly to perform chief
executive tasks themselves until a permanent choice could be made.
</P>
<P>
   But, Sonntag said, the company's business plan also held the
seeds for reconfiguring the corporate structure. Lewis Cantley, the
BI-Deaconess doctor who discovered the technology, already was
slated to become a company director. And a colleague of Cantley,
Dr. Lee Josephson, had been named chief scientific officer to
oversee product development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't necessarily need someone deep into the science'' to
be chief executive, said Sonntag. ``We needed someone good at
striking deals and negotiating contracts with big drug companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonntag said Spence, who spent much of her time at Emerson in
negotiations with insurers and other third-party providers, had
those qualities. The two had met in 1995 at a conference held
annually in Arizona by the Women's Health Alliance, a group of 20
women prominent in health care across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the alliance met again last fall, Spence had just sold her
health center chain, which, while generating $5 million in revenues
during their best year, failed to generate the amount of business
she and her investors had expected. Spence told Sonntag she was
interested in taking on something new.
</P>
<P>
   Sonntag described Consensus. The proposed structure ``would be a
very unusual alignment,'' she said, ``in that (Spence) knew nothing
about biotechnology.'' But, she added, ``It made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Consensus now has six employees in a building fitted out for
biotechnology research in Medford: Spence, an administrative
assistant, and four scientists. A part-time chief financial officer
minds the books until Consensus is big enough to need someone full
time.
</P>
<P>
   That could be soon, Spence said. She and chief scientific
officer Josephson plan to hire nine more people by May. Sonntag
said the search for a permanent chief executive is ongoing. Spence,
asked if she was a candidate, answered: ``That's a good question. I
don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1349EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6136 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-JONES-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     03-03 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-JONES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... in 1951.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Doubleday opened an office in Paris, Jones returned to the
publisher, working as an assistant. ``I was a glorified
secretary,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   One day, the English translation of ``The Dairy of Anne Frank''
came into the office and her editor handed it to her with
instructions to reject it. She didn't agree, and conveyed her
excitement about the book to win her point. ``It took a little
persuasion,'' she says. Then softly, ``It had that picture of Anne
Frank on the cover.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones arrived at Alfred A. Knopf publishers in 1957, she says,
when ``it was just Alfred and Blanche,'' a husband-and-wife
publishing firm. ``Mastering the Art of French Cooking'' was sent
to Knopf in 1960 by Avis DeVoto, wife of the historian Bernard
DeVoto. She lived in Cambridge and scouted for manuscripts for
Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishing was a gentleman's profession,'' Jones says. ``It
was civilized; it wasn't crass like advertising. Knopf had an
emphasis on quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Knopf held its sales conferences at the New York Harvard Club.
Jones was the only woman editor. ``Blanche Knopf and I had to be
escorted to the ladies' room. It was really the men's room. Someone
stood guard outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Julia Child's book went to Jones because she worked on French
translations and everyone knew she loved French food. It came from
a more senior editor, Angus Cameron. Child was acting as the agent
for her coauthors, Simone Beck and Louisette Bertholle. ``Angus
helped me persuade the Knopfs,'' Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   Just as she has done for all cookbook manuscripts since, Jones
began cooking from the pages of Child's book. ``It was the answer
to a prayer. A real teaching book. There was nowhere to go to learn
how to make boeuf bourguignon.'' She discovered that it was
``important to dry the meat, to saute a few pieces at a time.''
Cookbook editing opened up a new world.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston publisher Houghton Mifflin had already refused the
book, she says. Their comment was: ``Who wants to know that much
about French cooking?''
</P>
<P>
   I did, replied Jones.
</P>
<P>
   One day, while talking to former New York Times food critic
Craig Claiborne, he told her that he wanted to write about how she
and Evan roasted lamb on a spit in their penthouse apartment. ``If
you let me write a piece on you and Evan,'' said Claiborne, ``I'll
look at `Mastering' seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne wrote the glowing review that launched the book. James
Beard, at Jones's insistence, organized the book party and Dionne
Lucas hosted it at her restaurant, the Egg Basket. The entire New
York food community _ some 25 people at the time _ was in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Though Child became Jones's most celebrated author, all of her
subsequent authors wrote for the home cook and all became famous in
their field. James Beard wrote his bread book for her and Madhur
Jaffrey worked on Indian recipes. Marcella Hazan did most of her
Italian books with Jones until the relationship dissolved a few
years ago. Edna Lewis, a descendant of slaves, wrote about her
Southern heritage, Joan Nathan about Jewish cookery. Egyptian-born
Claudia Roden delved into Middle Eastern cuisine, Anna Thomas
researched vegetarian cooking. The late Irene Kuo deconstructed
Chinese cooking, as did Ken Hom.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had lunch a half-dozen times with Vogue food critic
Jeffrey Steingarten before she decided to take on his popular ``The
Man Who Ate Everything.'' When she finally did ask, he said, ``I
thought you'd never pop the question.'' He makes her laugh.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Jones lives in Manhattan during the winter and moves
to East Hardwick for the summer. She was widowed three years ago
and lives alone now, but she likes the peacefulness of Vermont and
often hosts her authors. She and Evan used to spend a month in
Vermont every summer, but that isn't enough now, so she moves her
office north. ``You feel, after so many years, you've earned a
little privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing is different these days, too. She's the only staff
member left from the days of Alfred and Blanche Knopf. Today, she
says, quality isn't everything. ``So much rides on promotion.'' A
public personality, someone cooking on television, for instance,
will sell thousands of books. ``That has been more of a factor than
whether the book makes a genuine contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she's editing a book for two big personalities: ``Julia
Child and Jacques Pepin Cooking at Home'' is due to appear in the
fall as a companion to a television show of the same name. In spite
of these celebrities, Jones remains fiercely devoted to the home
cook. ``I would hope that I've done some books to encourage people
to cook _ not as drudgery but to get satisfaction, to bring
families back together.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughs again when she's asked how long she will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone once asked John Kenneth Galbraith, `Are you still
doing this?' Does it mean, he wondered, `Are you still alive?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they'd probably do perfectly well with someone else,''
Jones says modestly, ``but this way there's continuity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
