A6138 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REMEMBERING-ABBEY-AZR     03-03 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMEMBERING-ABBEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARD ABBEY REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE NEWBERG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's been 10 years since Edward Abbey departed this
life.
</P>
<P>
   Buried somewhere in Arizona's Cabeza Prieta desert are the
remains of the author and environmentalist, who died March 14,
1989.
</P>
<P>
   To know Ed Abbey was to have an opinion about the man who wrote
``Desert Solitaire'' and ``The Monkey Wrench Gang,'' about a group
plotting to blow up Glen Canyon Dam.
</P>
<P>
   People either agreed with him or dismissed his words as drivel
from an extremist's mind. We contacted a few people who knew the
man behind the words and asked them to share their memories.
</P>
<P>
   Tucson author Chuck Bowden met Abbey while on an assignment to
interview Earth First! founder Dave Foreman, who was staying at
Abbey's home. After answering the door, Abbey rushed to find a copy
of a book Bowden had written so he could autograph it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just was quite taken,'' Bowden said. ``It's classic Abbey,
as far as knowing him as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship was based mostly on their mutual love of the
written word. Rarely did they discuss environmental politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we agreed, and it would be pretty damn boring,''
Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Abbey's life and legacy is one that few writers will ever
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became a legend. I don't know how the hell you do that,''
Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Community College English professor Dick Kirkpatrick
</P>
<P>
   encountered Abbey when he spoke at Scottsdale Community College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brazenly suggested that I was selling his books to my
students and the least he could do was talk to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not a word was heard until the day he was scheduled to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly there was this large shadow in the door, and the guy
said, `Who the hell is Kirkpatrick?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Abbey came back on other occa sions to speak to students. Some
loved him, others despised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several of his severest critics were students of mine. He
loved it. He enjoyed that kind of confrontation,'' Kirkpatrick
said. ``There were people who deified him at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Kirkpatrick drove cross-country with his friend to
visit Abbey's parents in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed was dying the whole time,'' he said. ``He led me to believe
that things were OK at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Sanders owns a rare-book store in Salt Lake City. He
befriended Abbey in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of got me involved with the Earth First! movement at
the time,'' Sanders said. Sanders was in on Earth First! actions
such as unfurling a plastic ``crack'' down Glen Canyon Dam.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever questioned whether Abbey approved of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always knew exactly where you stood with Ed Abbey. He was
just real straightforward with everybody,'' Sanders said. ``He had
a wonderful sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Communicating by phone with Abbey could be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless it was something urgent, I never, ever called Abbey. He
would say what he had to say and hang up,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Gungle took an advanced non-fiction writing class from
Abbey in the late '80s at the University of Arizona. He wrote his
thoughts via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Abbey had a reputation among UA English Department graduate
students as a terrible teacher. . . . Ed's poor reputation was not
because he didn't care. Rather, it was that this man whose literary
reputation was larger than life was unsure of himself in the
classroom. If he thought an essay was pretty good but a few class
members were critical, he'd scratch out the original grade right
there in front of us and replace it with something lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the funny thing is that Abbey had this reputation
as a crusty, cantankerous son of a bitch, when as a teacher he was
one of the nicest damn guys I've ever met. He didn't have the ego,
the big-fish-in-a-small-pond mentality that you get all too often
on campuses across the country. The year after I had him in class,
I saw him on campus a couple of times, and each time he'd go out of
his way to come over and find out how I was doing. There's a whole
Edward Abbey mythology, replete with his legendary exploits and
larger-than-life persona. But at its center was just a pretty
regular guy with a sharp pen.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
