<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6139 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-03 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING THEIR OWN BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After bagging groceries at a Boston supermarket for two years,
Rajib Momen's career goals became crystal clear: He wanted freedom
and flexibility first, then financial secu rity.
</P>
<P>
   So Momen quit his minimum wage job and launched a computer
service and Internet firm from his parents' home, charging clients
$50 per hour to upgrade and repair their computers or help them
access the Net.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Momen expects his flegling company, The World's
Greatest Bulletin Board Service, to gross $50,000 _ not bad for a
17-year-old Boston Latin School senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to be my own boss, and make my own hours,''
Momen said. ``This is a lot more profitable, and much more fun than
working a regular job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rajib Momen might be young, but he's not too young to earn a
place among a new generation of entrepreneurial upstarts whose
members are more likely to point to a business plan than a resume
when discussing career goals.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by such role models as Microsoft chairman Bill Gates and
Dell Computer founder Michael Dell, many are savvy beneficiaries of
the high-tech revolution who are using their technical skills to
create Web-based products or computer services that cater to an
expanding market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation really doesn't want to do the whole corporate
America thing,'' said Martha Winberg, a spokeswoman for the
National Federation of Independent Business in Washington, D.C.,
which represents 600,000 small business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have seen the layoffs; they've seen what has happened to
their parents, and they have decided, `This is not the lifestyle I
want,' '' Winberg continued. ``They would rather make no money and
be their own boss, than make money and have people telling them to
go and do gerbil work.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are no statistics documenting this trend, the Young
Entrepreneurs Organization in Alexandria, Va., says its membership
has grown to 2,300 since its inception nearly a dozen years ago.
The average member? A 33-year-old chief executive of a company with
$7 million in annual revenues. The youngest member is 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a greater sense of individualism among young people
today, and this means people under 35, including teens,'' commented
Gerald Hills, the Coleman chair of entrepreneurship at the
University of Illinois at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   While Hills doesn't know how many young people are becoming
their own bosses, he points to the growth of his own program as an
indication that times have changed. Unlike their parents, he said,
young people are more apt to see work at a company as a stepping
stone to business ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1982, the year I came to the University of Illinois, we had
25 student in the program. Today? We have at least 350, and we're
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hills has developed a national collegiate entrepreneurs
organization, widely known as CEO, that expects to have 20,000
members in 400 campuses by 2003. The organization's first
conference last fall attracted 400 students.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-year-old David Koretz of Rochester, N.Y., acquired his
entrepreneurial know-how early _ from his grandfather, who
manufactured socks, and his parents, both entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Koretz, who is now on leave from Babson College in Wellesley,
Mass., began selling seashells when he was 7. At 14, he started
Compucepts, a computer repair company that became the nucleus for
an electronics distribution company with international clients.
</P>
<P>
   Koretz's latest venture, Network Marketing International LLC,
uses the Internet to collect sales and marketing information for
corporate clients. The fee? $25,000 to $50,000 per year for major
searches, and about $200 for smaller ones. ``Even the smallest
business can buy information through the Net now,'' noted Koretz.
``So, we've opened up an aspect of marketing to a lot of people who
had no access before.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which received an undisclosed amount of venture
capital from Thomas Golisano, founder of Rochester-based Paychex
Inc., the corporate payroll management firm, expects to handle $15
million in sales by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Experts attribute the push to incorporate to several factors,
ranging from corporate downsizing to an array of high school and
college entrepreneurial programs that have encouraged students to
weigh the pros and cons of business ownership.
</P>
<P>
   One such program is the National Foundation for Teaching
Entrepreneurship (NFTE) in New York City, which helps high school
youth turn their talents into profits. Among NFTE's graduates:
Rajib Momen, who attended a summer NFTE training camp at Babson
College when he was 14.
</P>
<P>
   NFTE graduate Malik Armstead, 27, is a New York financial
analyst turned soul food restaurant owner. Armstead was 24 when he
quit his job and used $20,000 in savings to launch a Brooklyn soul
food takeout eatery called The Five Spot in a brownstone he had
leased. He expects the eatery to net close to $300,000 this year.
Armstead recently purchased the building that houses his restaurant
and two adjacent buildings, and says he plans to add a bar, a full
sitdown restaurant, and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that a bank would consider his company a high risk,
Armstead initiated a direct transaction with his landlord for three
brownstones valued at $500,000, including the building that houses
his takeout restaurant. ``Essentially, with the direct transaction,
I went to my landlord and worked out the terms of a mortgage, which
is 20 years at 9 percent interest,'' he said. ``I gave him a
$100,000 downpayment for the brownstones and he wrote up a mortgage
note for the remaining balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Armstead started his business career early (he bought
snacks with his allowance and resold them at higher prices in
elementary school), he credits a summer at an NFTE business camp in
Pennsylvania with giving him business know-how.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always been good in math and science and was considering
a career in those fields, but that summer opened my eyes to
business,'' he said. ``I finished my senior year in high school,
and then went to Morehouse College in Atlanta to study finance.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Armstead, Momen credits the NFTE training camp with helping
to increase his business acumen. ``NFTE showed me the ropes,'' said
Momen, whose mother has a jewelry business. ``NFTE showed me the
legality involved in running a business. It taught me how to
register my business, and the teachers in the program encouraged
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Momen began thinking about starting his own computer repair
company when he was 12, but ``it was never like this. It was just
this idea about helping people with computers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com, or 617-929-2069.)
</P>
</TEXT>
