<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-JONES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDITH JONES: COOK OF THE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judith Jones's office on the 21st floor of Alfred A.
Knopf publishers is piled with manuscripts and books, which spill
onto a couch, a coffee table, and against a window overlooking the
East River. A computer sits beside the desk, but Jones hardly uses
it except for e-mail. She edits her manuscripts the old-fashioned
way: by hand, line by line, with notes in the margin. Her writers
will tell you she reads every word.
</P>
<P>
   They're not just anyone's words. The pages that have been under
her scrutiny belong to such French philosophers as Jean-Paul Sartre
and Albert Camus, whose translations Jones edited early in her
career. There are novels by Anne Tyler and John Updike, a
collection by New Yorker writer Philip Hamburger, and a host of
cookbooks from the likes of Marion Cunningham, James Beard, M. F.
K. Fisher, Madhur Jaffrey, Edna Lewis, Claudia Roden, Jacques
Pepin, Marcella Hazan (until recently, ``when we happily parted
ways''), and Julia Child. From the volumes, you can pretty much
figure out how American culinary culture, and other aspects of
ordinary life, changed in the last four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Child was Jones's first cookbook author, an unseasoned writer in
the hands of a young, enthusiastic editor. It wasn't entirely an
accident that the cumbersome manuscript of ``Mastering the Art of
French Cooking'' landed on Jones's desk 40 years ago _ she was
known as an unabashed Francophile. And having landed there, it's no
mystery that Child's first book changed the course of cooking in
America. ``I knew it was a gem,'' says Jones, who took the
manuscript into her kitchen and then pushed hard to see it
published.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who celebrates her 75th birthday next week, calls Child
``the best writer around. She has good, visceral language.'' As
Jones says, ``Julia doesn't say `place' '' but uses words like
``plop,'' which the editor prefers. Child describes Jones as ``very
thorough, lovely to work with, always supportive, but never
domineering.''
</P>
<P>
   Other authors say she can hone anything, pull out the voice,
make the reader feel as though there's company on those pages. They
say that she's gifted with language, that working with her is a
privilege, that she never insinuates herself into someone else's
manuscript, but she's a tough editor, relentless about details,
with deep sensibilities for the reader. Sometimes her authors admit
they don't ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   Like all good editors, Jones stays in the background, modest to
a fault. ``Whenever I meet someone who knows Judith,'' one of her
authors says, ``they tell me another story about her, things she
will never ever tell you about herself.'' One day, talking to an
author, Jones mentioned Sylvia Plath, the troubled young poet who
took her own life. Jones had edited Plath's first book of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Salem cookbook author Nina Simonds has only superlatives to
describe Jones after they traveled together to Asia last year for
research on ``A Spoonful of Ginger,'' due out in April. Simonds,
who was working with Jones for the first time, says: ``She is
intimidating at first and very formal. But then her genuineness and
her kindness come through. She's so open to everything, and the
fact that we survived traveling together through six countries is a
supreme testament to her warmth.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion Cunningham agrees. When she first met Jones in 1974 to
work on the revision of ``The Fannie Farmer Cookbook,'' Cunningham
worried that ``I wasn't going to measure up.'' Cunningham flew from
her home in Walnut Creek, Calif., before Easter weekend to stay
with her editor and to go over the galleys. Jones invited
Cunningham to go to church with her on Easter Sunday. As Cunningham
recalls: ``She said she belonged to the Episcopalian Church. It was
a beautiful place, she said. She was the deacon. Did I want to take
communion?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can,'' Cunningham told Jones. ``I was raised
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Yes, you can,' she said.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham disagreed. But she didn't say anything.
</P>
<P>
   When she went to church, she took communion. ``I finally decided
that I was more afraid of Judith than of God,'' says Cunningham.
``Much, much later I told her about it. She laughed. She has a very
good sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith Jones sits primly, bolt upright, and has perfect, old
school manners. She is a practical woman. She wears a well-made
suit and black pumps that still have some life in them. Her
cultured voice sounds vaguely British.
</P>
<P>
   She's a Yankee, not on both sides but on the side she prefers.
She was born to an English mother and a father who came from
Vermont. They lived what she describes as ``a typical middle class
life'' in Manhattan. The young Judith Bailey attended Brearley
School, which was private and academically rigorous. At home, a
maid did all the cooking (her mother wasn't interested). They spent
summers with her father's family in East Hardwick, Vt., near the
Canadian border. Jones adds: ``I remember stamping my feet as a
child, saying, `I'm a Vermonter.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After Brearley, she went to Bennington College in Bennington,
Vt. (class of 1945), a school so progressive that her choice
surprised her high school classmates. ``Brearley was very academic
and Bennington had a reputation for being experimental,'' Jones
says.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Graham and Merce Cunningham taught at Bennington, as did
the poet Theodore Roethke and the critic Kenneth Burke. ``I was
there during the war. We had a victory garden and we had to do the
work. One professor felt we should get our feet dirty. We were free
spirits. The teaching was so good.''
</P>
<P>
   When she graduated, she returned to New York to work for
Doubleday. For her vacation she went to Paris, and ``I could not
bear to leave.'' She asked for a month's extension, which stretched
into 3 1/2 years. There, she met Evan Jones, who was editor and
publisher of the picture magazine Weekend. Together they learned
about cooking and it became a lifelong passion. They went to the
markets and listened to the butcher's instructions for coq au vin.
They married in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
