<SLUG> BC-PINK-WINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE WINES ARE MAKING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's a proliferation of pink.
</P>
<P>
   In wine stores, in wine journals and even at the recent Albany
American Wine Festival, rose wines are getting more attention than
they have seen since you drank Mateus. And even if the public's
interest in roses has grown only slightly in recent years,
winemakers are betting on pink making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because even though the growth of rose sales has
been slow, 13 percent between 1991 and 1997, white wine sales only
grew 12 percent during the same time. By contrast, sales of red
wines jumped 151 percent during that six-year period, according the
Wine Institute, an industry council.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry specialists contribute the enormous jump in red
wine consumption to the revelation that moderate drinking of red
wines can be beneficial to your health. By combining the healthful
attributes of a red wine varietal with the style of a white
zinfandel, wineries may be launching the next big trend in
California wine.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter Home, which pioneered the popular white zinfandel in the
1970s, has introduced a merlot rose, a dark pink wine the company
touts as having ``merlot taste ... white zinfandel refreshment.''
</P>
<P>
   White zinfandel, a sugary pink which remains the second largest
selling varietal in America, according to the Wine Institute, lost
favor with wine drinkers who thought they had more sophisticated
palates. The varietal, which is still made in mass quantities by
nearly all larger California wineries, became unfashionable when it
was snubbed by ``serious'' wine drinkers who called it ``candy'' or
``soda pop wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, other pink wines, most not nearly as sweet and
some actually dry, became unfashionable, too, and people shied away
from them as well.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed people would blush if they were seen drinking blush.
And though some white zinfandel drinkers graduated to more accepted
varietals such as chardonnay and merlot, others left wine
completely and went to the graduate school of chocolate martinis.
</P>
<P>
   But most white zin drinkers stuck with it (accounting for its
remaining popularity).
</P>
<P>
   ``They drink light wines because they like them,'' Stan Hock,
spokesman for Sutter Home, says in the September issue of Wine
Business Monthly. Like white wines, roses vary in dryness but none
of them are so dry that they will rip the enamel off your teeth.
And, generally, roses are not aged in oak, so they lack the tannins
associated with red wines and the characteristics of the fruit are
predominant.
</P>
<P>
   Though still on the sweet side (or ``semi-dry'' as wineries call
it) Sutter Home's Merlot Rose is not nearly as syrupy as its
zinfandel predecessor. Neither are other California pinks created
from varietals more commonly known for red wines such as Simi
Vineyard's Rose of Cabernet Sauvignon (1997) and Etude's Pinot Noir
Rose (1997). These wines are relatively fruity and go particularly
well with Mediterranean food and the spicy flavors of Cajun or
Caribbean cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   Other roses, most notably the Tavels from France's Southern
Rhone region, such as Domaines Ott (1995) Cotes de Provence, are
drier and more herbal on the palate. These pair well with salmon,
chicken or other light meats.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``The Wine Collector's Handbook,'' by Linda Johnson
(Lyons Press, 1997), most simple roses are best served chilled,
between 43 and 46 degrees. Place the bottle in a bucket of ice
water for about 20 minutes prior to serving. Refrigeration, which
should be set below 40 degrees for food safety reasons, is too cold
for storing wine. And remember, you shouldn't be embarrassed to
drink pink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1413EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
