<HEADER>
A6164 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINK-WINES-SIDE-HNS &LR;      03-03 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINK-WINES-SIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINK WITH ENVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With PINK-WINES)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some wine terms, followed by selected wins:
</P>
<P>
   Rose (roh-ZAY, French for pink) refers to wines of a pink or
rose-colored hue. Rose wines are usually made from red grapes, but
the skins are removed early in the winemaking process to prevent
them from turning the wine deep red. In France, the only rose wines
that may be made by blending white-grape wines with red-grape wines
are rose champagnes.
</P>
<P>
   Blush _ The American generic name for rose wines. Usually made
in the classic French style by removing the skins of red grapes
early in the winemaking process but, in the United States, may also
be made by combining white wines with red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Rosado _ Spanish for rose.
</P>
<P>
   Rosato _ Italian for rose.
</P>
<P>
   Tavel (ta-VEHL) _ A region in France's southern Rhone region
where what some consider the best rose wines are made. Tavel wines
are generally dry and made primarily from grenache grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Dry _ A wine that lacks sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   Semi-dry _ A sweet but not sugary wine.
</P>
<P>
   (Source: ``Wine Lover's Companion'' by Ron Herbst and Sharon
Tyler Herbst (Barron's, 1995); ``Beginner's Guide to understanding
Wine'' by Michael Schuster (Fireside, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some selected wines (prices may vary):
</P>
<P>
   Foxy Lady (Non vintage), Hunt Country Vineyards (New York) _
This blush from the Finger Lakes region is pale pink in color with
beige tones. Of the six we tasted, this had the most candy-like
nose with deep berry aromas but on the palate it had a clean,
almost effervescent feel. Sweet but not at all syrupy with hints of
blackberry. Good picnic or hot tub wine. $5.99.
</P>
<P>
   Merlot Rose 1997 Sutter Home (California) _ Celestial rosy red
in color with a leathery and fruity bouquet. Slightly sweet, high
in alcohol, unctuous and mouth filling. Serve with grilled fish,
chicken, vegetables, salads or light pasta. $5.99.
</P>
<P>
   White Merlot Vin de Pays D'oc 1996 Fortant (France) _ Almost
brownish in color. Thin and high in alcohol on the nose. Essence of
strawberries and spices with a round finish. Try it with light
chicken dishes, shrimp or non-tomato vegetarian dishes. $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   Pinot Noir Rose 1997 Etude (California) _ Pink with a floral,
jammy bouquet. Flavors of raspberries with a slightly mineral
freshness. Serve with poultry, spicy foods or Mediterranean fare.
$18.99.
</P>
<P>
   Rose of Cabernet Sauvignon 1997 Simi (California) _ Slightly
sweet but doesn't linger. Crisp, almost effervescent. Serve with
grilled tuna, spicy poultry dishes. $11.99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
