<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRST-IMPRESSIONS-HNS     03-03 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-IMPRESSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST IMPRESSIONS CAN MAKE OR BREAK BUSINESSES, EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even when he was busy writing bestselling
motivational books and making speeches around the country, Harvey
Mackay made sure he hired two key people at his Mackay Envelope
Corp. in Minneapolis: the company president and the telephone
receptionist.
</P>
<P>
   It makes a lot of sense. One job is first in the employee
organizational chart, the other is first in making an impression on
customers _ and potential customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get a second chance to make a first impression,''
the dandruff shampoo commercial says. That's basic advice, but it
gets ignored by companies and workers _ and we aren't just talking
about a few flakes.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some first impressions that often get overlooked:
</P>
<P>
   _ Check, please.
</P>
<P>
   I went to a new restaurant a while back. Prices were reasonable
and the food was excellent, better than a lot of places the
restaurant critics rave about.
</P>
<P>
   The place went out of business in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   Am I surprised? No. The kitchen was painfully slow and our
waitress had all the charisma of a mutual fund prospectus. They
left a bad aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant failed for the same reason a lot of restaurants
fail: It flunked the first-impression test. People who open
restaurants usually do it because they love food and cooking, but
they need either managerial expertise or tremendous luck to make it
work.
</P>
<P>
   If the restaurant had done a better job with employees _ like
guaranteeing that waiters would make good money, even if business
was slow, and having a bigger kitchen staff than necessary at first
_ it would have lost a lot more money at the start, but would have
done much better at making that crucial first impression.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trying new things.
</P>
<P>
   When established companies merge or launch products, they're
making a first impression all over again. When you walk into your
branch of Friendly Neighborhood Bank and find it's been taken over
by Money-Sucking Conglomerate, you're likely to be more sensitive
about things like customer service until the merged bank proves
itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the workplace, the same sorts of things can happen when
workers get promoted or companies improve technology.
</P>
<P>
   If you get promoted, treat it like you're with a new company.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone took for granted that you could do your old job, but
now bosses and colleagues will be watching more closely to make
sure you're not in over your head.
</P>
<P>
   When companies improve technology, a typical worker's first fear
might be that it's going to wipe out jobs. So if it won't, say so
right away.
</P>
<P>
   The other mistake companies make with technology is not having
enough technical support people available when a product gets
added. If something new causes a couple of hours of frustration,
workers can roll with that. But if it causes a couple of weeks of
frustration with no obvious benefits, you've got a serious threat
to morale.
</P>
<P>
   _ When things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There's a great Danish proverb: ``Life is not holding a good
hand; life is playing a poor hand well.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how good your company is or how good you are at your
job, mistakes happen. It's how you handle them that makes the
difference between success and failure.
</P>
<P>
   Look at how smart companies handle mistakes. If a product is
screwed up, they do voluntary recalls. If somebody with a dinner
reservation has to wait 20 minutes, they give them a glass of wine
or free dessert. When people need customer service, they talk with
somebody who can help them, not a person with a single-digit IQ who
has to ask a supervisor for everything.
</P>
<P>
   If you're an employee and you make a mistake, a lot of times the
hardest thing to say is, ``I screwed up.'' But if you did screw up,
say so _ then do whatever you can to make it right.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starting a job.
</P>
<P>
   People often overlook the details when they start a job. Don't
make your boss or co-workers have to tell you twice how to do
something; if you can't memorize it, take notes. And quickly make
your boss realize that if you're assigned to do a task, it will get
done _ and done right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1420EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
