<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGERIAL-STYLE-HNS &LR;      03-03 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGERIAL-STYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PITFALLS OF BEING AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even if you build a better mousetrap, your
business still might fail and your employees still might be
miserable if you have a mousy chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   There are all sorts of horror stories about overbearing bosses
and indecisive managers, but management consultant Patrick Lencioni
said the problems at the top have more in common than you might
think.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to oversimplify and say there's one thing a good CEO
needs, it's self-esteem,'' said Lencioni, president of The Table
Group in Emeryville, Calif., and author of ``The Five Temptations
of a CEO,'' a fable he uses to illustrate the main weaknesses
leaders have to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Lencioni said the five temptations are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Choosing invulnerability over trust.
</P>
<P>
   Managers with poor self-esteem are reluctant to let employees
challenge their ideas, Lencioni said. People in this category often
are overly concerned with having a powerful image rather than
letting workers understand their thoughts, weaknesses and emotions.
They are afraid of appearing vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers don't usually take advantage of that,'' Lencioni said.
``There's power in being open.''
</P>
<P>
   These managers also are liable to hire inferior workers because
they don't want to bring in anyone who might eventually pose a
challenge for their job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discouraging conflict.
</P>
<P>
   If the chief executive doesn't like to be challenged, that can
discourage managers from challenging other managers' ideas.
Lencioni added that even some chief executives who are open to
criticism will discourage conflict at meetings because it makes
them uncomfortable, so they will create artificial harmony instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get buy-in without conflict,'' Lencioni said.
``Trying to avoid conflict at meetings is a great way to put people
to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   He said managers frequently complain about attending so many
meetings, but often it's because either the meeting is unnecessary
or because it started in a boring fashion, without any issues to
draw attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the meeting's fault; it's the manager of a bad
meeting,'' he said. ``The same thing that makes a screenplay
interesting makes a meeting interesting. There needs to be good,
role-playing characters, there needs to be a plot and, essentially
in every story, there needs to be conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Lencioni said that managers who discourage conflict also will
find it hard to hire top people, those who want to challenge the
status quo in order to achieve something more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Being too afraid of having to change a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision is almost always better than no decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Lencioni said chief executives sometimes are unclear about the
company's direction because they keep waiting for more information
to come in. While making a well-informed decision is important, he
said executives often wait so long that the company drifts without
any substantial improvement for months or even years.
</P>
<P>
   They are usually better off deciding on a course based on the
information they have, then changing it later if developments make
it impractical, Lencioni said. But, he added, those with weak self-
esteem may be unwilling to do that because they are too afraid of
what people will think if they make a ``wrong'' decision.
</P>
<P>
   People with bosses like that should push for clear direction,
Lencioni said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Being more concerned about popularity than accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one is particularly painful. Am I going to tell the
person the truth about their performance or am I going to dodge the
issue?'' Lencioni said this is different than creating artificial
harmony. Just as parents are often hesitant to discipline their
children, some executives are reluctant to come down on weak middle
managers because they don't want to jeopardize their popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about firing them. Firing them is the ultimate
cop-out.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the temptation he has the most trouble with, he said,
and is the one executives want to talk about the most. Firing
people is easier because those people instantly disappear from your
sight, but criticizing people and telling them how to improve is
difficult because you still see them every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let them off the hook and as a result they don't
perform, they won't respect you,'' Lencioni said. ``If you've never
come down on someone, your reward doesn't seem as valuable. And if
you've never rewarded someone, coming down on them doesn't seem as
important.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Being more interested in protecting their status than
achieving results.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the top spot is a dream for many workers, and
Lencioni said some executives are more concerned with enhancing
their own reputation instead of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hire people who are `yes' people because they won't hold
you accountable for your results,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lencioni said politicians like President Clinton often run into
problems with this temptation; their goal is keeping their job.
``Anyone who wants to be president since they were 16 years old
probably is too drawn to the status of the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
