<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-USOC-REACT _ WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Olympic Committee wants
the White House to place the scandal-ridden IOC under federal laws
that will force leaders of the games to live up to the ``noble
ideals they profess.'' Saying strong action was needed to avoid
``the loss of the Olympic Games,'' USOC president Bill Hybl said
today he would ask President Clinton that the IOC be identified as
a public international organization under the Federal Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act. He said he expected other nations ``to
support this initiative as an important way to truly level the
playing field'' for all cities seeking to stage the Olympics. Hybl
said the USOC's executive committee had approved all the
recommendations made by the ethics panel led by former Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 20.
</P>
<P>
   With list of recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and
congressional Democrats are rolling out an ambitious legislative
agenda, looking to gain a tactical advantage over Republican
lawmakers still wrestling with their plans. Clinton scheduled a
meeting today with House and Senate Democrats to present their 1999
``Families First'' agenda, a four-page political wish list topped
by a bid to set aside 77 percent of projected federal budget
surpluses for Social Security and Medicare. Rep. John Lewis will be
there. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   PORK _ WASHINGTON _ A museum for first ladies in Ohio and one to
honor Frank Sinatra in New York, a water taxi for Savannah and an
$86 million courthouse for Jacksonville, Fla., are among this
year's prime pork items listed by the annual Pig Book put out by
Citizen's Against Government Waste. (Malone).
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-TRUST _ WASHINGTON _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt,
who was recently cited for contempt by a federal judge in
connection with his handling of Indian trust funds, appears
Wednesday at a joint hearing of the Senate Indian Affairs and
Energy and Natural Resources Committees. (Dart).
</P>
