<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6241 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-COLLIER04-COX     03-03 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLLIER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite physical ailments, Collins is a success at Ga. Tech
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When North Carolina State hosted Georgia Tech on Jan. 2,
Wolfpack athletics director Les Robinson joked that Yellow Jacket
forward Jason Collier was the story of the '99 basketball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' Robinson said, ``that he leaves Bobby Knight's
program to go to Bobby Cremins' program and then gets an ulcer.''
</P>
<P>
   The ulcer was just one in a series of physical problems that
caused Collier to lose 18 pounds from his original 250. In
mid-December, six days before Collier was to make his Georgia Tech
debut a year after transferring away from Knight and Indiana
University, he got the flu.
</P>
<P>
   After being hospitalized and taking fluids intravenously,
Collier returned to practice and sprained his right ankle. Then
after his second game, he vomited blood for an hour and was
diagnosed with the ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the 7-footer has been one of Tech's few success
stories in a 15-14 season.
</P>
<P>
   When the Jackets open Friday against North Carolina in the ACC
tournament, they will have one last chance at redemption. ``It's
like a second season, and we need to win three games,'' Collier
said. ``There are teams that have done that. N.C. State, a couple
of years ago, made it to the finals. Who's to say we can't do
that?''
</P>
<P>
   If the seeds hold, Maryland and then Duke would follow North
Carolina. If Tech goes to any postseason tournament, it probably
would be the National Invitational Tournament .
</P>
<P>
   If Tech does get an NIT call, Collier wants to go. ``I don't
have much time,'' he said, ``and it's a chance to play more games.
It would kill me not to be in some kind of postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Collier no longer will address his problems with Knight, but one
of the main ones was the coach's insistence that Collier limit his
game to the inside.
</P>
<P>
   At Tech, he has gone inside and out _ and thrived. He also has
returned to the Catholic church, which he stopped attending at
Indiana. When Collier decided to transfer to Tech, Cremins promised
Collier's mother that he would get her son's religious life back in
order. Under Cremins, a coach with a gentler approach than
Knight's, Collier is one-tenth of one point away from leading the
ACC in scoring, at 17.6 points a game, and is 7th in rebounds at
7.1. Collier wears No. 52, the same worn by his father, Jeff, who
played for both Whack Hyder and Dwayne Morris at Tech, 1973-76.
``He's had a real good year, especially considering the time he had
to take off,'' the father said. ``He's frustrated from the
standpoint that the team's not doing that well. He wanted it to be
a good year for coach Cremins.'' During the recruiting process,
Jeff Collier said, ``We met the who's who in college basketball,
and we all thought that coach Cremins was, if not the class act of
the group, very high in the group. Coach (Mike) Krzyzewski (of
Duke), (North Carolina's) Dean Smith and coach (John) McLeod (of
Notre Dame) are also class acts. Coach Cremins is a very genuine
individual, and Tech's very lucky to have him. I've seen both sides
of the fence there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with another 7-footer, Alvin Jones, in the lineup, Tech has
struggled on offense, with a freshman, Tony Akins, at point guard
and Jon Babul, Jason Floyd and T.J. Vines playing out of position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get people the ball,'' Collier says tactfully.
``You have to know when to throw it in and who to throw it to.
You're not going to be able to throw Alvin a bullet pass. I have
trouble with bullet passes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Collier said, ``If Jason and Alvin work together this
summer, they could be very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Collier has played well, he concedes that he has
spent many an unhappy night this season. ``I hate to lose more than
anything,'' he said. ``When we lose, I get in this wild mood. I go
back to the room and sit for three or four hours thinking about it,
blaming myself, when I know I shouldn't. It's very frustrating. . .
. We're fighting to be above mediocre. We've lost 14 games this
season, and I only lost 11 games my entire high-school career. It's
humbling and frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
