<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.   
   
   
   
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Asian Peanut Sauces Take Critics' Shelling  
   
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO  _ If grocery store aisles are any indication, Asian
foods continue to gain popularity. But just as popular are
shortcuts to getting dinner on the table. We recently found nine
brands of Asian peanut sauces at Bay Area markets _ a product that
fits both bills.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted the sauces on their own and with baked
unseasoned chicken as a dipper. Overall, the panel was
disappointed, complaining that many of the products lacked peanut
flavor and others were out of balance with too many competing
elements.
</P>
<P>
   First place went to  &UR; House of &LR;   &UR; Tsang  &LR; (111/2 ounces,
$3.79-$3.99 at many supermarkets). One panelist thought it was a
bit simple, but it had nice flavor. Two others commented on the
prevalent lemongrass flavor. Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Thai Kitchen  &LR; (12 ounces, $3.99 at Andronico's) came in second.
Two panelists lamented the poor oily appearance; one wrote:
``tastes a heck of a lot better than it looks.'' Two others thought
it was too sweet but liked it overall. One panelist noted it would
be particularly good on noodles. Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to the least expensive brand,  &UR; Dynasty &LR;  (seven
ounces, $2.49 at Safeway). Three panelists complained about its
vinegary-hot flavors; one joked that it would be good mixed with
Thai Kitchen's sauce. One would buy it, two might buy it, and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped significantly to No.4, which went to  &UR; Satay &LR; 
(eight ounces, $5.49 at Whole Foods). All the panelists disliked
the overly strong flavor of coconut milk, but one thought it had
decent peanut flavor as well. Two panelists labeled it
``one-dimensional.'' Two would buy it, one might buy it, and two
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ebara &LR;  (111/2 ounces, $3.89 at Safeway) nabbed fifth place. Two
panelists did not like all the competing flavors, and two panelists
thought it was heavy on soy sauce. One might buy it; four would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Four products scored too low to rate: Annie Chum's, Pacific Rim
Noodle House, Woh Hup and San J.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna
Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe for All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland
Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1509EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0215 </DOCNO>
