<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6252 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICKCOOK-SF-SFCHRON &LR;      03-03 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with  enough
leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes 
 plus suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus 
 suggestions in optional trim.   THE WEEKEND COOK: Chuck, the Kindest Cut of All for Pot Roast  
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO  _ Many cuts of beef can be braised or cooked as a
pot roast, but some of them yield stringy, dry meat. The chuck is
different. It's the ideal cut for moist heat because a decent
amount of marbling throughout the muscle bastes the meat as it
cooks and keeps it tender. I learned this ever so deliciously one
night at the dinner table of my friend Suzanne.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suzanne rolls her eyes when I tell her she is one of those
marvelous cooks who can turn cardboard into foie gras. But it's
true. Even so, I believe her when she says that in the case of
braising and pot roasting beef, the cook's success depends on the
cut of meat. She swears by a boneless chuck roast.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think Suzanne's culinary wizardry ends at the meat
counter, let me tell you how good she is at combining herbs and
spices in unexpected but sensible ways.
</P>
<P>
   In the Master Recipe, there is something unusual in the heady
perfume of cloves and basil that gives the all-American pot roast
an exotic twist. Somehow, Suzanne knew that the menthol-like
flavors of both clove and basil would give the long-simmered,
wine-based sauce an unexpected freshness.
</P>
<P>
   The Master Recipe is the dish I had for dinner at her house. She
served garlic-scented chard bruschetta as an appetizer, a heap of
roasted vegetables and mashed potatoes with the meat, and
pear-gingerbread upside-down cake for dessert. It was a cold night,
there was plenty of wine and six of us around a beautifully set,
candle-lit table were lucky enough to be warmed and sated in style.
Typically Suzanne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MASTER RECIPE: CHUCK ROAST BRAISED IN WINE WITH CLOVE &AMP; BASIL
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is written for 2 pots to accommodate the 3 roasts,
but if you have one pot large enough to hold the roasts in a single
layer, use it, and saute the onions for a few minutes longer. The
sauce is thin and very flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 bottles dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   12 large garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   15 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   21/4 teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 boneless chuck roasts, each 2 to 21/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces thinly sliced pancetta, diced
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 celery stalks, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup minced basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the wine, garlic, cloves, salt and pepper in a large
bowl; stir until the salt dissolves. Add the chuck roasts, turning
them a few times in the liquid. Cover and refrigerate, turning the
meat occasionally, for at least 6 and up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the meat from the marinade; blot it dry with paper
towels.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the olive oil between 2 large, heavy pots and place over
high heat. When the oil ripples, add the meat and brown on all
sides, turning as necessary. Remove the meat; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Discard all but 1 tablespoon fat from each pot. Return the pots
to medium-high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the pancetta between the pots; saute, stirring, for 3
minutes. Divide the onions, carrots and celery between the pots.
Saute, stirring frequently, until the onions are golden, about 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add 1 cup water to each pot; bring to a boil over high heat and
simmer for a minute. Divide all the marinade ingredients between
the pots. Add 2 roasts to 1 pot, the third roast to the second pot.
Cover and bring to a boil over high heat. Reduce heat to
medium-low, cover, and gently simmer until the meat is very tender
but not dry, 13/4 to 2 hours. Add the basil during the last half
hour of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the meat from the sauce. Degrease the sauce. Slice 11/4
roasts into about 3/8-inch-thick slices. Arrange on a platter or
individual plates. Ladle 31/2 cups sauce with vegetables over the
meat. Serve with 5 cups Cheddar-Parmesan Mashed Potatoes (see
recipe).
</P>
<P>
   Cool, cover and refrigerate the remaining 9 cups sauce with
vegetables for use throughout the week. Degrease the chilled sauce,
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 445 calories, &LR;   &LR; 48 g protein, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 26 g fat (10 g saturated), 161 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 334
mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WEEKEND RECIPE: CHEDDAR-PARMESAN MASHED POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds Yukon Gold potatoes, skin on, cut into 11/2- to 2-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hot milk
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups grated extra sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Ground white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: Boil the potatoes in a large pot of water with 2
tablespoons salt until they are very tender, 15 to 18 minutes;
drain.
</P>
<P>
   Return the potatoes to the pot and mash until they are slightly
lumpy. Fold in most of the milk. Add the cheeses and pepper,
folding until thoroughly incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Add as much of the remaining salt as desired, then add the
remaining milk if the potatoes need thinning. Mix thoroughly but
don't over-mix or the potatoes will become gluey.
</P>
<P>
   Serve about 5 cups of the potatoes with the braised chuck roast.
Cool, cover and refrigerate the remaining potatoes for use later in
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 9 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 410 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 47 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 17 g fat (10 g saturated), 51 mg cholesterol, 486 mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: PICADILLO-STYLE TOSTADA
</P>
<P>
   he picadillo mixture comes together very quickly. Purchased
guacamole and salsa add to the ease of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups braising sauce (with onions, etc.) (from Master
Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   Pinch ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   3 cups finely diced or shredded chuck roast (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   15 pimiento-stuffed green olives, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup toasted almonds, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small head iceberg lettuce, shredded
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup guacamole
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup salsa
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place the tortillas on a baking sheet and bake until toasted, 10
to 15 minutes. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Whisk the braising sauce and water into the tomato
paste until well-combined. Add the vinegar, red pepper flakes and
cinnamon. Bring to a boil over high heat. Stir in the meat and
simmer, stirring frequently, until the sauce is almost completely
reduced, about 7 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Fold in the olives, raisins and almonds. Season with salt, if
necessary, and more pepper if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the mixture among the tortillas. Top with a layer of
lettuce and dollops of sour cream, guacamole and salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 5 tostadas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TOSTADA: &LR;   &LR; 505 calories, &LR;   &LR; 28 g protein, 31 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 32 g fat (11 g saturated), 88 mg cholesterol, 356 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 8 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: SWISS CHARD &AMP; BRAISED CHUCK WITH MASHED POTATOES
</P>
<P>
   The chard may be chopped on the weekend. Store in a plastic bag
and keep refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 cups Cheddar-Parmesan Mashed Potatoes (from Weekend Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hot milk, if needed
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch Swiss chard (about 11/4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 cups shredded or chopped braised chuck (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chuck roast braising sauce (with onions, etc.) (from
Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat the mashed potatoes in a double boiler, stirring
occasionally, until they are hot, 10 to 15 minutes. Add some or all
of the milk if they are too stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Cut out the thick white ribs from the chard leaves (save for
another use, or discard). Chop the leaves into medium-sized pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water and salt in a large pot. Bring to a boil over
high heat. Add the chard, tossing until wilted, then reduce the
heat and simmer for 3 minutes. Stir in the meat and braising sauce.
Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer for 5 minutes. Season with
pepper and additional salt, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the potatoes among 5 bowls, making an indentation in the
top of each. Top with the chard mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 540 calories, &LR;   &LR; 38 g protein, 43 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 24 g fat (13 g saturated), 113 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 757
mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
More Ideas for Leftovers &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chuck roast, mashed potatoes and braising sauce made on the weekend
yield even more quick fixes during the week:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hashed Mashed with Broccoli. &LR;  Dice the stems from a head of
broccoli. Cut the florets into small pieces. Boil the stems in
salted water for 2 minutes. Add the florets; boil for 3 minutes.
Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a little olive oil in the pot. Add 2 cloves of thinly
sliced garlic; saute until golden. Add 3/4 cup water; boil until
reduced to 1/2 cup. Add the broccoli and simmer until it is very
soft, 5 to 10 minutes. Season generously with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon olive oil in a nonstick pan. Add leftover
mashed potatoes and saute, folding them over periodically, until a
thin crust forms. Divide among serving plates; top with the
broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hot Borscht. &LR;  Dice and boil a potato and 1/2 green pepper in 2
cups water. When the potato is almost tender, add a little shredded
cabbage, a thinly sliced carrot, 3 cups of leftover braising sauce
and some diced braised chuck, plus chopped dill and caraway seeds
to taste. Simmer for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add canned julienned beets and their liquid. Simmer for 2
minutes. Season with salt, pepper and vinegar. Serve hot, topped
with sour cream.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quick Black Bean Chili. &LR;  Saute a diced green pepper in oil
until limp. Add 3 cups leftover braising sauce with onions and 2
cups diced braised chuck. Season with ground cumin, chili powder,
salt and pepper. Simmer for 2 minutes. Add drained and rinsed
canned black beans. Simmer for 5 minutes. Stir in the juice of a
lime.
</P>
<P>
   Top with sour cream; accompany with cornbread.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pot Roast Pot Pie. &LR;  Thicken a few cups of the leftover braising
sauce with onions with a roux. Stir in some leftover diced braised
chuck, sliced mushrooms, frozen defrosted peas and a very thinly
sliced carrot. Transfer the mixture to an ovenproof casserole. Top
with a thick crust rolled from frozen puff pastry or other frozen
pastry. Make a slit in the crust. Bake at 375 until the crust is
golden and the filling bubbly, 30 to 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Filler Up. &LR;  Use leftover diced chuck and as much of the
braising sauce as desired for taco fillings, Sloppy Joes, pasties,
enchilada fillings and stuffings for vegetables such as zucchini
and peppers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maria Cianci
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
