<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-ANCH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses 
 more than a half-century old. 
 &HT;       
   
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Maytag Put Suds Back in Anchor Brewery  
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  When Abe Lincoln was president and San Francisco
basked in the prosperity that came with the cry of ``Gold!'' small
breweries were as prevalent as Starbucks coffee shops are now.
<P>
   Today, only one brewery with ties to that era remains in San
Francisco _ Anchor Brewing Co., which had survived multiple owners
and a bankruptcy death threat before it was rescued in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The man who stepped in was Fritz Maytag, who was moved to
preserve this San Francisco landmark and propel it to international
prominence.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag, an Iowan and Stanford University graduate, is from the
family whose enterprises include The Maytag (appliance) Co. and
Maytag Blue Cheese. When he bought the brewery, he had a
fascination with science but no skill in brewing. ``I had mold
experience but no yeast experience,'' he jokes. ``I dropped out of
grad school and dropped into the brewery.''
</P>
<P>
   Love made him do it. In 1965, Anchor was at its nadir, going
bankrupt. ``They were selling the old wooden beer kegs on the
sidewalk for 50 cents, just for the toll across the Golden Gate
Bridge,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Kuh, who owned the Old Spaghetti Factory in San Francisco's
North Beach neighborhood and had a soft spot for the local brewery,
told Maytag about Anchor's apparently imminent demise. Go see it,
Kuh encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did. I fell in love. With then owner Laurence Steese, with
Anchor's San Francisco heritage, with fermentation, with the idea
of making beer, the whole thing,'' Maytag says.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag was just what Anchor needed _ he had resources, vision, a
love of science and his father as inspiration. When Frederick Louis
Maytag II was head of a nationally known company synonymous with
washing machines, he started an artisan cheese company as a labor
of love.
</P>
<P>
   Before Maytag came into its life, Anchor brewed just one beer _
Anchor Steam. It was available only on tap, was often poorly made,
Maytag says, and was sold to a handful of local bar and restaurant
owners _ ``true believers,'' Maytag calls them, who loved it for
being local and didn't mind its quirkiness. Customers even had to
come to the brewery, originally on Pacific Avenue between Larkin
and Hyde streets, to pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   Although the brewing facility that became Anchor dates from the
mid-1860s, Anchor acquired its name in 1896. ``We don't know why
the owners chose the name,'' Maytag says, ``although the image of
an anchor as a tool is ancient, magical, powerful and associated
with ports.''
</P>
<P>
   After Prohibition, an employee named Joe Allen bought Anchor and
ran it until 1958. Laurence Steese, the next owner, moved it to
Eighth Street between Bryant and Brannan streets. Maytag bought
into the company in 1965, bought out Steese in 1969 and moved the
brewery to Potrero Hill in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   As president and brew master, Maytag made it his mission to save
Anchor and also preserve the art of classical brewing. By 1972,
says Maytag, Anchor was the most modern small brewery in the world
as well as the most traditional brewery in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't take modern shortcuts in brewing, and we charged
twice what Michelob charged. I was considered bizarre in the
business,'' says Maytag, who, in a crusade to revive the art of
hand-crafted beers, was a David in an industry of Budweiser
Goliaths. Maytag and a handful of others with a passion for
traditional brewing were instrumental in pioneering the resurgence
of the microbrewery.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor now produces seven brews, including a traditional
festival beer (Christmas beer) and a wheat beer, which the company
believes was the first of its kind produced in America after
Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Steam, with instant name recognition in the Bay Area and
an international reputation, is the company's flagship brew. How
the word steam became linked to beer is unclear, Maytag says, but
in the 19th century, steam was a local nickname for draft beer made
quickly under primitive conditions. Steam is now a trademark of
Anchor Brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Anchor occupies an immaculate, handsome facility on
Potrero Hill. Its annual production is 100,000 barrels, very small
by industry standards. The beers are sold in 49 states, Japan and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Maytag opened a small distillery on the premises to
produce traditional American rye whiskey, christening the spirit
Old Potrero. Since whiskey is distilled beer, Maytag regards Old
Potrero as a natural progression of brewing. A revival of the kind
of whiskey made in George Washington's Day, Old Potrero is
pot-distilled from 100 percent rye malt. As far as Maytag knows, it
is the only single-malt rye being produced in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Production of the unusual product is limited; only 2,000 bottles
have been distributed. The 750 ml bottle retails for $90 at some
liquor stores in San Francisco. The whiskey is also served at some
restaurants, including Moose's, Rumpus and Enrico's, all in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor also distills a minuscule amount of premium gin called
Junipero, which retails for $28 for a 750 ml bottle. It's served at
mc2, South Park Cafe and Scala's Bistro, among other San Francisco
restaurants. Maytag describes it as intense, spicy and complex.
``It makes a great martini.'' Even this has local flair, with a
name that blends the major flavor component of gin and the name of
a Franciscan friar who established the California missions.
</P>
<P>
   Local beer. Local whiskey. Local gin. What else is brewing? Two
more ``fun'' products, says Maytag, for possible spring release. He
will say little more, other than they are bottled. Still, this much
seems bankable: They will fit right in with Anchor's mission of
superior quality and production _ the natural, traditional way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
