</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-VODKA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe 
 for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success.  
   
   
   
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Cool Cukes Are Reborn in Vodka  
   
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The name of the restaurant _ Infusion _ gives you
a clue about what to order. On any night you can find up to a dozen
different flavored, or infused, vodkas: jalapeno, watermelon,
pineapple, vanilla and my favorite _ cucumber.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clear liquid takes on a pure, intense flavor of the
cucumber. It's great served as an ice-cold aperitif from the
freezer or over ice. It's also great in a Bloody Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Sothern, the former general manager, got the idea for
making infused vodkas while taking a few days off to visit a spa in
Calistoga where cucumber slices were floated in the drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned, he talked to staff members about making a
cucumber infusion, but they weren't convinced it would work, so the
idea was quickly forgotten. A few months later, an elderly Russian
woman tried one of the flavored vodkas and told Sothern about a
cucumber infusion her grandmother used to make. The staff started a
batch the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The technique is simple and effortless. All you need is the
``flavoring'' agent and a good-quality vodka. Period.
</P>
<P>
   These infusions are the backbones of Infusion, a trendy
South-of-Market restaurant that features a robust, eclectic menu
and live entertainment. The menu might include spicy tortilla soup
with chicken and lime, spicy rock shrimp and corn risotto, or an
excellent grilled pork chop with spicy apple barbecue sauce. As you
can see, spicy is the key word, and these refreshing flavored
vodkas help cool the palate.  &LR; Infusion, 555 &LR;   &LR; Second St. (near
Bryant Street. San Francisco; (415) 543-2282. &LR;   &LR; Lunch weekdays;
dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Bauer is The Chronicle's food editor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
INFUSION'S CUCUMBER VODKA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 (750 ml) bottle vodka
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 hothouse cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Peel the cucumbers and cut into 1/8-inch rounds (you'll need
about 5 cups).
</P>
<P>
   Place the cucumber slices in a large, clean glass container and
pour in vodka to completely cover them. Cover the container and
store at room temperature for 2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When the vodka is ready, strain it through a fine mesh sieve
lined with a paper coffee filter or two thicknesses of damp
cheesecloth. Pour into a clean bottle (the original vodka bottle is
fine), seal tightly and store in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Serve straight up like a martini, use in a Bloody Mary, or mix
with club soda over ice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER OUNCE: &LR;   &LR; calories, &LR;   &LR; g protein, g carbohydrate, g fat (g &LR; 
 &LR; saturated), mg cholesterol, mg sodium, g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE SECRETS &QL; 
 &QL; 
The flavoring. The cucumber adds an exciting, refreshing note to
the vodka. &QL; 
The freezer. Storing the vodka in the freezer, where it becomes
thick and syrupy, makes it even more refreshing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
