<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Today The Chronicle begins ``At the Source,'' a 
 new column profiling Northern California growers, anglers and 
 artisans who make our region such a culinary wonderland. Over 
 the next few months, we'll take you from field to forest to 
 factory to look at the wealth of ingredients that stock our 
 larders. As a bonus, ``Georgeanne's Kitchen'' by columnist 
 Georgeanne Brennan will offer tips for using the bounty in 
 fresh, innovative ways. 
 &HT;       
   
 AT THE SOURCE: Fruit of the Forest Journeys to Table  
   
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; NAPA VALLEY, Calif. _ &LR;  ``These yellow mushrooms may look like
chanterelles, but they aren't chanterelles _ because there are no
chanterelles in America.''
<P>
   With that generalization, French chefs dismissed Connie Green
when she offered them the fruit of her foraging 20 years ago.
Today, Green has a waiting list of chefs _ including French chefs _
who can't get enough of those yellow mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our chanterelles are the largest in the world and the
meatiest,'' says Green, who abandoned two careers for the joy of
tramping through the forests and glens of Northern California and
the Pacific Northwest. She now pursues the plentiful yet elusive
darlings of upscale cuisine, wild mushrooms: black trumpets,
hedgehogs, morels, candy cups, c &LR; e &LR; pes, matsutakes and
chanterelles, large and small.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Green no longer finds time to forage more than a
couple of days a week, relying on a loosely knit band of pickers _
from 12 to 40 at a time _ to deliver the goods for her 6-year-old
company, Wine Forest Wild Mushrooms of Napa Valley, which she
operates from her home in the Mayacmas Mountains. The business
supplies an average of 1,400 pounds of cleaned mushrooms each week
to Campton Place, LuLu, Zuni Cafe, Jardini &LR; e &LR; re, Masa's, Green's
and French Laundry.
</P>
<P>
   These pickers travel the mushroom trail, as Green calls it,
which stretches north from Northern California through the Pacific
Northwest and occasionally into the Yukon and Alaska. They live in
campers, pickup trucks or motels as they follow the fruiting season
of the treasured 'rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their independence, Green says, they are also
interdependent, and she often serves as a messenger conveying
information among individuals or small groups. She calls them the
new cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   On a bad day, a picker might make only $9; on a good day, it
could be $400.
</P>
<P>
   Green inspects all mushrooms delivered to her _ much of them
freighted from small airports _ before she takes them to her chef
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Green is an expert in identifying the various species of wild
mushrooms, as are her pickers. She occasionally takes chefs on
outings to teach them about wild mushrooms _ it's important for
them to know about the source of their ingredients, she feels _ and
she still thrills to the hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mushrooms,'' she says, ``have magic about them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tips for Using and Storing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Connie Green's business card identifies her as the head huntress of
her company, Wine Forest Mushrooms of Napa Valley. Her 25-year love
affair with wild mushrooms grew from aficionado to part-time
mushroom forager to full-time mushroom entrepreneur. Naturally, she
has strong opinions on mushrooms &LR;  matters and offers these tips:
</P>
<P>
   Mushrooms are not as perishable as many people think. Avoid
getting them wet, but store them in a slightly damp cloth or fabric
bag in the refrigerator and use them within the week (storage life
will depend on the species and the freshness of the fungi when
purchased).
</P>
<P>
   Green cleans her mushrooms before delivery, using a damp brush
to lift off particles of dirt, then dries the fungi on racks under
fans.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing mushrooms, she generally opts for simplicity,
without too many other flavors masking the essential taste.
Roasting is a great option for such mushrooms as chanterelles and
hen of the forest _ just brush with a little flavored butter and
roast at fairly high heat. Roasting or grilling enhances the flavor
of many mushrooms, Green says, among them the matsutake, the prized
(and pricey) Japanese fungus that's gaining popularity among top
chefs. Never saute it, she advises. Instead, grill it over very
high heat.
</P>
<P>
   For sheer indulgence, she suggests chanterelle soup. Roast
chanterelles, add stock, puree some of the mushrooms and chop some
into meaty morsels, add plenty of cream and garnish with chives and
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karola Saekel &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN: Cooking Wild Mushrooms &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Georgeanne Brennan &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Wild mushrooms give a wonderful flavors-of-the-forest kind of feel
to any dish they're used in. And they may be used in a multitude of
ways. Here are just a few suggestions on how to enjoy them:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Warm Chanterelle, Escarole and Baby Spinach Salad.  &LR; Coarsely
tear the pale yellow inner leaves of escarole into bite-sized
pieces, then arrange them on individual salad plates. Add a few
leaves of baby spinach to each. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Quarter large chanterelles lengthwise, leave small ones whole.
Saute in a nugget of butter, with a little salt, pepper and fresh
thyme, for about 3 or 4 minutes, just until the mushrooms begin to
soften. Divide evenly among the salad plates.
</P>
<P>
   Add some minced shallots to the pan juices, and saute for 2 or 3
minutes, just until soft. Deglaze the pan with red wine vinegar.
Remove from the heat, add a little olive oil, mix well and pour a
little over each salad. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wild Mushroom Crostini.  &LR; Grill slices of baguette, then rub
them with peeled garlic cloves. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Finely chop a selection of wild mushrooms, adding a few brown
mushrooms if desired. Season with salt, pepper and rosemary and
saute in olive oil until softened. Add minced Italian parsley, then
spoon onto the grilled bread slices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Breaded Puffball Mushrooms.  &LR; Cut firm puffballs into 1/4-inch
thick slices. Heat a little butter and olive oil in a skillet over
medium heat. When the butter is foamy, dip the mushroom slices into
beaten egg, then into freshly made breadcrumbs seasoned with salt,
pepper, parsley and a little finely grated Parmesan cheese. Saute
for about 2 minutes per side, until golden. Serve immediately with
lemon or aioli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Creamy Wild Mushrooms with Basmati Rice.  &LR; Coarsely chop a
selection of wild mushrooms, adding portobello, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the rice.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a bechamel sauce, and when it is almost ready, saute the
mushrooms in butter, seasoning them with salt, pepper and fresh
thyme. Stir them into the sauce, along with the pan juices. If
desired, add chopped roasted red pepper and chunks of chicken
breast.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, spoon over the rice and garnish with a sprinkling of
pasilla or other chili powder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Skewered Wild Mushrooms.  &LR; Thread mushrooms on skewers. Place
them in a shallow dish and sprinkle with a mixture of olive oil,
minced garlic, minced parsley, salt and pepper. Turn to coat, then
marinate for several hours, turning occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Place on a grill or under a broiler and cook for about 3 or 4
minutes per side, just until slightly golden.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, alternate the mushrooms with thin slivers of beef.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wild Mushroom Tart.  &LR; Quarter large mushrooms lengthwise, leave
smaller ones whole. Saute the mushrooms and minced shallots in
butter, adding salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375. Roll out a sheet of thawed, frozen puff
pastry. Leave whole, or cut into individual sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine fresh goat cheese, a little salt and pepper, and the
juices from the mushrooms; mix well to form a paste, adding a
little chicken broth if necessary to thin the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pastry on a baking sheet, folding up the edges to make
a crust. Poke with the tines of a fork. Bake for 15 minutes. Remove
from oven, spread with the goat cheese and top with the mushrooms.
Sprinkle with a little olive oil and bake another 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in Yolo
County, is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The Food and Flavors of
Haute Provence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
