<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6259 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORAGE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-03 2783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORAGE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS: Recipes and sidebars follow the main story.  
   
   
 WILD ABOUT WEEDS  
 Bay Area forager hunts untamed edibles her own back yard  
   
   
 By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  As spring approaches, most Bay Area gardeners eye
their yardswith hope and chagrin. There are tomatoes to plant and
roses to mulch _ but first there are all those darned weeds.
<P>
   Or, as Margit Roos-Collins might put it, all those delicious
weeds. For Roos-Collins, the Berkeley author of ``Flavors of Home:
A Guide to Wild Edible Plants of the San Francisco Bay Area''
(Heyday Books, 1990), the chickweed, nettles, wild onions and
purslane that pepper untended yards belong on the dinner plate, not
in the Dumpster. By learning to recognize a few wild edibles _ and
by steering clear of the toxic ones _ Bay Area gardeners, hikers
and other outdoor enthusiasts can graze at nature's table, says the
author. Where legal, foraging for wild fruits, nuts, greens and
roots can be a year-round pastime, she says, and a profound way to
experience one's surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Roos-Collins led a private Bay Area foray that
included fellow weed enthusiast and cookbook author Paula Wolfert.
</P>
<P>
   On a short hike in a woodsy location that she asked to keep
unidentified, Roos-Collins pointed out dozens of wild edibles, from
coast strawberries and sea figs (neither fruiting yet) to at least
a dozen of the wild leafy greens from nature's winter buffet.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike wild mushrooms, which can require a sharp eye to find,
the greens were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's your mallow,'' Wolfert said, pointing to a clump of
furry, rounded leaves less than 10 feet from the trailhead.
</P>
<P>
   In Turkey, she said, cooks stuff the large mallow leaves with
rice or meat as they might stuff grape leaves. In Tunisia, they
steam the leaves, then beat in oil and spices to make a dip for
bread. The nutrient-rich green is so high in vitamin A _ second
only to polar bear liver, says Roos-Collins _ that too much can be
toxic.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the trail, she points to a shady patch of
scallionlike foliage with delicate, nodding white blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of San Francisco has these in their back yard,''
Roos-Collins says. ``I've seen truckoads of it going out of
people's yards. They try desperately to eradicate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, gardeners could exploit these wild onions and their
faintly oniony blossoms in salads and fish preparations.
Jean-Georges Vongerichten, the New York celebrity chef, scatters
the blossoms over salads, Wolfert says.
</P>
<P>
   In a thicket of 8-foot-tall wild fennel, a holdover from last
year, Wolfert bends a seed head down and shakes its contents into
her hand. ``Too bad you can't photograph smell,'' she says, holding
out a palm filled with dark, licorice-scented seeds. In Provence,
restaurants stuff whole fish with wild fennel stalks before
grilling and toss dried fennel stalks on the coals. In Italy, cooks
gather the pollen from fennel flowers and use it to season pork, a
practice showing up here. ``All the chefs are talking about it,''
Wolfert says. ``It's going to be huge.''
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny slope beyond the overgrown fennel, Roos-Collins finds
a seasonal treat: young radish shoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the prize at this time of year,'' she says, pointing to
tiny clusters of the tender greens all over the slope. ``If I'm
only going to teach people one plant, that's the one.'' It's easy
to recognize, easy to like when cooked and present in abundance.
The tiny pastel blossoms, which have a slight horseradish taste,
are so fragrant on a sunny day, she says, ``you can smell the
sweetness coming off the flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   On just such a sunny slope years ago, nibbling on radish
blossoms, Roos-Collins first understood why foraging resonated so
deeply for her. The revelation led to one of the most moving
passages in her book, testimony to nature's ability to provide.
``Understanding that I still had a place at the animals' table was
such sweet relief that it made me cry,'' Roos-Collins wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, humans have chosen agriculture to feed everyone more
easily and to allow time for other pursuits, she acknowledges. But
recognizing nature's providence _ ``that there was food set out for
me,'' Roos-Collins says _ was a deeply spiritual experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love plants,'' she says. ``I love watching them grow,
watching the sunlight on them, the way they smell when you brush
them. Foraging slows me down. It makes me sit still in one place
and focus on their taste, their feel, their smell, their growth
habits. It makes me feel I've really been in a place that I was
otherwise just walking through.''
</P>
<P>
   As parks clamp down on foraging, Roos-Collins sees opportunities
vanishing for people to have similar encounters with nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to preserve resources not just for today but
for future generations,'' says Tracy Fortmann, a communications
officer for the Golden Gate National Recreation Area. ``People say
to themselves, `Well, I'm just going to take one flower,' but we
have 20 million visitors a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Park officials acknowledge some of the edibles that foragers
seek are pesky non-native weeds that keep native plants from
flourishing. But allowing uncontrolled foraging can harm the
environment, they say, as people trample into off-trail areas,
damaging native habitats, disturbing streams and promoting erosion.
Even respectful foraging can cause problems, they argue, if
observers see someone fill a bag with chickweed and conclude that
it must be all right to pick wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions on foraging sadden Roos-Collins, a former
environmental lawyer who sympathizes with the park managers'
concerns. But surely, she argues, foraging could be controlled and
monitored in the same way hunting and fishing are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would give us the chance to buy a license for
foraging and put more rangers on the trail _ whatever it would take
to make it work,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In the frequent edible-plant walks he leads in the Bay Area,
Adam Seller emphasizes conscientious foraging. ``I focus on
teaching people how to look at a place and see whether it's
reasonable to take anything at all,'' says Seller, a professional
herbalist. But he has no qualms about what he calls ``sustainable
harvesting,'' which has contributed to the human diet in most
places through most of time.
</P>
<P>
   Many Bay Area immigrants come from foraging cultures, Seller
says, and foraging has nurtured them here. Even the United States
has a foraging tradition, he says, particularly in the Southwest
and the rural South. Today, many of his plant-walk customers are
African-American women who want to learn the weeds their Southern
grandmothers used to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Others join his walks in preparation for Y2K, when, they
believe, all computer systems may crash and only the prepared will
survive. ``The millennium has been good for my walks,'' Seller
says.
</P>
<P>
   In his early spring forays, he might point out curly dock, a
long, narrow leaf that tastes like sorrel; stinging nettles, which
thrive in the Berkeley hills and are delicious in soup; and
fragrant wild plum blossoms he steeps in rice vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Bay Area chefs have embraced these wild foods,
among them Reed Hearon of Rose Pistola and Black Cat; Todd
Humphries, former chef of Campton Place; and Paul Bertolli of
Oliveto.
</P>
<P>
   At Oliveto, Bertolli kneads cooked nettles into pasta dough or
pounds them with olive oil to make a sauce for wild steelhead. He
steams mussels with California bay leaves and adds wild mustard
greens to salads served with rabbit. He pounds wild fennel seeds
into powder, mixes it with salt and flavors pork roast with it, and
he adds the chopped feathery leaves to vinaigrettes. He also heats
the crushed seeds gently with olive oil to make a highly scented
condiment for fish and pork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It animates your cooking when you can connect with the source
of the food,'' Bertolli says. ``It's the same feeling you get when
you make something from scratch, the satisfaction of being with the
process from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pomponio Creek Produce, an organic farm near Pescadero,
Martin Bournhonesque harvests the nettles that turn up on plates at
Oliveto, Chez Panisse, Boulevard and Zuni Cafe. ``In the last two
years, nettles have gone from a pesky weed to a profitable crop,''
says the astonished grower. ``I sell every last leaf in my field.''
</P>
<P>
   He also harvests milk thistle, wild watercress and
lamb's-quarter for chefs; Hearon puts the milk thistle, along with
other greens, in a ravioli filling.
</P>
<P>
   With park foraging frowned upon, organic farms like Pomponio
Creek may provide the most promising setting for would-be foragers.
In their fertile beds untouched by herbicides, sour grass,
lamb's-quarter and chickweed flourish _ plants that most farmers
would prefer not to have and aren't set up to sell. Wolfert says
that, when she lived on the East Coast, one farmer gave her a
``lifetime right to weed,'' so she could scour his beds for
purslane and mallow for recipe testing.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfert predicts American farmers will soon begin
cultivatingwild edibles to satisfy a growing demand from chefs.
That's happening in Crete, she says, as people move from farm to
city and can't forage for the wild greens they love. But if
supermarkets of the future carry thistles and nettles, will that
eliminate the lure of foraging?
</P>
<P>
   Not for Roos-Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to Andronico's or Monterey Market, and it's fantastic,''
she says. ``There are always five or six gorgeous-looking greens
for sale. It's not that there's more variety in the wild; there's
probably less, because there's only what can grow in this climate.
But as you forage, you're tuned in to seasonal changes. There's a
greens season now, then a flower and wild strawberry season, then
berries and nuts in the fall. The natural seasonal rhythm is
something people are sorely missing, and foraging gives that
back.''
</P>
<P>
   She worries the strict park regulations governing foraging will
make the natural world into an art object to be observed but not
touched. For Roos-Collins, who has savored the warm fragrance of
Douglas fir tea and the pleasing chewiness of local seaweed, the
hands-off approach ``is clearly an inadequate way to relate to
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RADISH OR MUSTARD PIE &QL; 
Adapted from ``The Flavors of Home,'' by Margit Roos-Collins
(Heyday Books,1990).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 cups radish or mustard leaves, rinsed and coarsely
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten  &LR; _ &LR; Nutmeg to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Worcestershire sauce to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a skillet over moderate heat. Add the
onion and saute until tender, about 8 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chopped greens to the onion and cook, stirring over low
to moderate heat until the leaves wilt. Combine the onion/greens,
the grated cheeses (reserving a little cheddar for the top) and the
eggs. Season to taste with nutmeg, salt, pepper and Worcestershire
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon into a 9-inch pie pan, cake pan or ovenproof skillet; top
with the reserved cheddar.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the pie is firm and the top begins to brown, about 30
minutes. Slice and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 200 calories, &LR;   &LR; 13 g protein, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 16 g fat (7 g saturated), 101 mg cholesterol, 237 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MALLOW LEAVES WITH TUNISIAN SPICES
</P>
<P>
   From ``Mediterranean Grains and Greens,'' by Paula Wolfert
(HarperCollins,1998). Serve with semolina bread for dunking.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts stemmed young mallow leaves (about 3/4 pound) or
miner's lettuce, purslane, chard or beet greens, well washed
</P>
<P>
   3 large garlic cloves, unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon harissa (Tunisian hot sauce)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   2/3 teaspoon ground caraway seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: Steam the trimmed greens and garlic cloves until
tender. Press out all the moisture. Peel the garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the garlic, greens, salt, harissa and spices in a food
processor. With the machine running, add the olive oil and just
enough hot water to make the mixture slightly soupy. Correct the
seasoning and add lemon juice to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 55 calories, &LR;   &LR; 2 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 5 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 20 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ask Before Taking Plants From Parks &QL; 
 &QL; 
With a few exceptions, removing plant material from a park _
whether it's a national, state, county, city or regional park _ is
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   A few state park districts allow berry or nut gathering and
limited mushroom gathering, a decision made by each district. Some
parks allow you to nibble as you hike but don't let you take
anything out.
</P>
<P>
   Limited mushroom collecting is permitted in designated areas of
Land's End in San Francisco, and the San Francisco Mycological
Society typically receives permits to forage for its annual
mushroom fair.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Wayne, natural areas director for the San Francisco
Recreation and Parks Department, says her office might issue
permits to people seeking to weed _ don't say forage _ some of the
non-native greens in city parks.
</P>
<P>
   Before foraging in any park, call the appropriate administrative
office to inquire about policies, limits and whether the plants
have been sprayed with insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   Recreational _ not commercial _ foraging is permitted in
national forests. However, National Forest Service spokesman Dave
Reider encourages would-be foragers to call the nearest National
Forest Service office to inquire about ecologically sensitive areas
or endangered plants.
</P>
<P>
   Some national forests require permits for gathering some types
of plants. Rules vary among forests, so check before picking. Also
keep in mind that, although national forests belong to everyone,
some land within the forests' boundaries is privately owned.
Rangers can provide information to help keep visitors from
trespassing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Janet Fletcher &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; Tips for Foragers
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Margit Roos-Collins offers the following advice for new
foragers:
</P>
<P>
   Don't taste a plant unless you're certain that it's edible.
</P>
<P>
   Learn to recognize common poisonous plants in this area, such as
poison hemlock and lupine. Poison hemlock often grows among other
edible wild plants, such as chickweed. If you recognize it, you can
pick it out or, better yet, forage elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need comprehensive knowledge of wild plants to begin
foraging. To start, learn to recognize four or five wild edibles
and look only for those. ``How hard has it been to walk into a
grocery store and recognize strawberries from melons?,''
Roos-Collins asks. ``It's no different in the wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Take only a small portion of any plant species so you're not
compromising its ability to reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Be mindful that your foraging site is a place of beauty. Pick in
a way that leaves the least evidence you have been there. Don't
pick off leaves and let the bare stalk remain, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Take only what you can use.
</P>
<P>
   Sort wild greens carefully at home to remove grass or bits of
other plants that might be harmful. Wash them well. Treat them just
like supermarket greens, steaming or boiling them or, if tender,
adding them to salads. ``They are really just the same,''
Roos-Collins says. ``All that's different about the ones in the
supermarket is that we gather the seeds and grow them in a
systematic way. Experiment and have fun, but don't feel like they
need special rules.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Janet Fletcher
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
