<SLUG> BC-H-P-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET ANALYSTS WELCOME HEWLETT-PACKARD SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Wall Street analysts say splitting the
Hewlett-Packard Co. into two businesses _ one specializing in
computers and printers, the other focusing on electronic test
equipment and medical technology _ is a good move for the
technology giant.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the Palo Alto-based company is intended to give the
computer-maker a more competitive edge in a crowded field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The test and measurements operations and the computer-based
divisions weren't synergistic,'' said George Elling, a technology
analyst at Lehman Bros. in New York. ``And the measurement business
dragged down the overall shareholder picture of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard's computer and printer business accounted for
about 85 percent of the company's $47.1 billion sales for fiscal
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The other company, as yet unnamed, will be devoted to four
equipment testing and products units, which pulled in $7.7 billion
in sales last year. Those divisions reported sales losses in the
first quarter ended Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Eisenbarth, a portfolio manager at Collins &AMP; Co., an
investment bank in Larkspur, Calif., said splitting the assets into
two groups should make Hewlett-Packard's mission clearer to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is maybe a solution to alleviate those problems,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The four equipment testing and scientific product divisions that
will become one company are:
</P>
<P>
   _ The test and measurement division, which makes devices that
test the viability of telecommunications products _ such as
cellular phones _ and networks. These devices are sold to
manufacturers, including Motorola and Nokia.
</P>
<P>
   This division, which accounted for more than half of
Hewlett-Packard's testing sales last year, also develops quality of
service measurements for Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The chemical analysis division, which makes and sells
equipment for use in the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   _ The components division, which makes parts for electronic
gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The medical products division, which makes a variety of
hospital and out-patient devices, including patient-monitoring
systems and ultrasound imaging systems.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hewlett-Packard sells more than 19,000 testing and
scientific products.
</P>
<P>
   But by creating a separate company for these devices,
Hewlett-Packard has moved away from the business that launched the
company in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, founders Bill Hewlett and David Packard sold their
first product, called an audio oscillator, to Walt Disney Co.,
which used the device to test sound levels on the animated classic
``Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eisenbarth said the testing industry in particular is mature
and not as profitable as the computer hardware sector.
</P>
<P>
   Galen Wampler, president of Prime Data Inc., a Carlsbad,
Calif.-based market research company that follows the high-tech
instrument industry, said the testing products sector had its
heyday in the 1970s, when defense contractors were the main
customers. But demand for testing equipment has slowed in recent
years, Wampler said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite sluggish projections for testing equipment and
scientific products, analysts said putting the four units under a
separate roof should allow them to grow faster because they will no
longer have to vie for resources at a bigger company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should achieve better growth rates than being part of the
overall Hewlett umbrella,'' Eisenbarth said.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, he added, would be ``fairly big and could grow
through acquisition'' in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The testing company's new chief executive, Edward ``Ned''
Barnholt, said he anticipated big growth ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got tremendous opportunities in telecommunications,'' he
said. ``We see big opportunities in the wireless arena. The whole
Internet is driving a lot of opportunities for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard said it was considering an initial public
offering of about 15 percent of the testing company's outstanding
shares by year's end that would be the largest-ever technology IPO
for Silicon Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
