<SLUG> BC-H-P-SPLIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH GIANT DEFIES A FOUNDER'S PRINCIPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ The planned split of the Hewlett-Packard Co.
into two separate companies was fueled by Wall Street pressures
that its late co-founder once vowed to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never sold any stock,'' David Packard proclaimed in a
1952 lecture to securities analysts. ``And I hope we never have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   In his company history, ``The H-P Way: How Bill Hewlett and I
Built Our Company,'' Packard explained why he wanted to avoid Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   He said the markets are a two-edged sword. Publicly traded stock
gave Hewlett-Packard the currency needed for acquiring new
companies, but Packard complained of Wall Street's fixation on
short-term profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``(T)hat effect is frequently unrelated to the basic strength
and long-term prospects of the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Packard's vow to avoid the public markets came years before many
Silicon Valley moguls were even a glimmer in their parents' eyes,
yet in 1952, the year of Packard's lecture, Hewlett-Packard Co. was
already considered a mature, but decidedly off-beat, success story.
</P>
<P>
   At that lecture, Packard regaled the crowd of analysts at a
downtown San Francisco meeting hall with tales of a casual office
culture, now a modern-day given, but unheard of in then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere at Hewlett-Packard is informal, and departments
mix freely,'' wrote a San Francisco Examiner business reporter
covering the lecture. ``Employees use few memos, never hold a
conference and rarely write a report.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Hewlett-Packard was already 14 years old, having been
created in a Palo Alto garage in 1938, backed by $538 in cash and a
used Sears drill press. (Today, that garage is a historical
landmark noted as the birthplace of Silicon Valley.)
</P>
<P>
   Founders William Hewlett and Packard, two young Stanford
University-trained engineers, started the company to ``manufacture
and merchandise our own manufactured goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The order of names on the company masthead was determined by a
flip of a coin, according to Packard's breezy ``The H-P Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard, whose father was a lawyer and mother a high school
teacher in Colorado, had a distorted thumb after childhood
experiments with gun powder. Hewlett, the son of a San Francisco
doctor, was a child math whiz who was dyslexic.
</P>
<P>
   They met in Stanford engineering classes and bonded their
friendship during fishing trips.
</P>
<P>
   According to company lore, Hewlett was seen as the idea man,
while Packard was considered the hands-on manager. One of their
first products was the Model 200B audio oscillator, used to control
sound volume and quality for Walt Disney Studios' full-length
``Fantasia'' cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   The company would go on to become the dominant force in
electronics, laying the bedrock for the Silicon Valley's dominance
in the computer age.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard is credited with producing such varied devices
as fetal heart monitors (1967), programmable scientific calculators
and light-emitting diode displays (1968), the first commercial data
processing machines (1973), the first random access memory
computers (1974), the first affordable laser printers (1980) and a
pioneering e-mail system (1982).
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the company became a behemoth. Today,
Hewlett-Packard's catalog lists more than 25,000 products. It
employs more than 124,000 people in offices around the globe, and
produced $47.1 billion in sales in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Packard died in March 1996. Hewlett retired in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the stock markets that Packard had vowed to avoid
finally persuaded the Hewlett-Packard management to announce it
would divide itself into two separate entities.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's electronics, especially its measures and
medical equipment, could be counted on to produce steady long-term
profits, its computing business could not create the go-go
performance that other Silicon Valley companies were producing, in
part because the casual workplace that was Packard's pride had
become bogged down in corporate complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Cost-cutting and restructuring fueled a short-lived recovery,
but it ebbed, in part because of lagging non-computer sales.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Hewlett-Packard reported that sales had risen only
4 percent companywide, a sharp drop from the 20 percent growth seen
in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   A huddle with corporate consultants produced Tuesday's stunning
news that Bill Packard's company would bow to Wall Street pressures
and split. The commercial electronics that Hewlett-Packard
pioneered will be produced and sold by a new, separate, as yet
unnamed company. The present Hewlett-Packard will retain its
high-growth computer and Internet technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street ``pressures were a significant factor in the
decision,'' said Edward ``Ned'' Barnholt, executive vice president
and general manager of Hewlett-Packard's Measurement Organization,
who will head the as-yet-named company. ``Investors have to be
listened to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
