 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, March 4:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW (Washington) _ The long-awaited Monica
Lewinsky interview, tonight on ABC with Barbara Walters; to be
followed by the long-awaited book. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-MEDIA (Undated) _ Watching Monica Lewinsky. By TV
critic Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEMS (Washington) _ The president leads a unity rally
with Democrats on Capitol Hill to emphasize their post-impeachment
agenda. The Republicans will counter with an anti-tax rally as both
parties adopt a campaign footing. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   COUNSEL-LAW (Washington) _ Bob Bennett and others testify before
a Senate hearing on independent counsel law. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Arguments on an immigration case that
focuses on how the United States should evaluate crimes committed
in immigrants' home countries by people seeking political asylum.
Other developments. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-NY (New York) _ Mrs. Clinton visits New York,
visiting a school and hosting a fund-raiser at the Plaza, amid
increasing speculation about her possible run for the Senate seat
of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who is retiring.
Meanwhile, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a likely
Republican rival should she run, took the opportunity to travel to
Washington for the day. By Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NJ (Newark, N.J.) _ President Clinton raises money for
Rep. Torricelli and may talk about racial profiling and law
enforcement. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-AVIATOR (Camp Lejeune, N.C.) _ Final arguments in the
court martial of the Marine pilot whose jet struck the ski gondola
cable. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   LEISURE-WORLD (Los Angeles) _ In a sign of the growing clout
demanded by the elderly, residents of Leisure World, the giant
southern California retirement complex, have voted to turn
themselves into a city, called Leisure Woods, population 18,000,
all over 55. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-FOREST (Boston) _ In what is described as the largest land
protection deal ever, a family has agreed to sell development
rights to 800,000 acres of Maine forest to forest association. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FOREST (San Francisco) _ More on the Headwaters agreement:
How will environmentalists keep tabs on the company, what are plans
to turn it into a park? By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-SCHOOLS (Detroit) _ The Michigan state Senate votes to
give control of the troubled Detroit school system to the mayor. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS (Houston) _ The first of the octuplets is allowed to
come home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-CANCER-HAIR (Undated) _ Hair from breast-cancer
patients has a different structure from healthy women's hair,
researchers in Australia report today in the journal Nature. The
findings, they say, could lead to a simple and reliable screening
method for breast cancer using a single hair. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECT (Johannesburg) _ President Mandela sets June 2 for
elections to choose his successor and new a new South African
Parliament. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ To Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's apparent surprise, Ariel Sharon, his foreign minister,
proposes a unity government with Labor and withdrawal from Lebanon.
Lebanon is now a major campaign issue as Ehud Barak, the Labor
Party chief, pledges to withdraw in a year if elected. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ The past, present and future of
PRI, the governing party, is at the center of a tremendous debate
here this week, as President Ernesto Zedillo and some 2,000 party
stalwarts prepare to celebrate the party's 70th anniversary. By Sam
Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND-U.S. (Chiang Mai) _ Madeleine K. Albright put a human
face on foreign policy Wednesday, listening to a group of young
Thai women explain how American aid money had helped turn them away
from drugs and prostitution and toward meaningful jobs. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Developments in the troubled Yugoslav
province. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   BANANA-TRADE (Washington) _ More on the U.S.-Europe trade
conflict. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors' sales rose 18 percent
last month, to 382,261, well above estimates of a 6.4 percent
increase. For the industry over all, February sales amounted to
14.6 million units, analysts estimate, up from 13.4 million units
in January. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   JONES-NINE-WEST (Undated) _ More about Jones Apparel's purchase
of shoemaker Nine West. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   DIRTY-CAR-FACTORIES (Undated) _ The Council of Economic
Priorities, a corporate gadfly group, issues a report saying that
the auto companies that make the most-fuel-efficient, and thus the
least-polluting, cars are the ones that run the dirties factories.
By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Rio de Janeiro) _ An update of economic
developments in Brazil. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-HONGKONG (Undated) _ Ending months of speculation, Hong
Kong says it is holding talks with Disney about the construction of
a theme park in the city. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON-ADDITIVES (Undated) _ RJR Nabisco Holdings reaches a
settlement with the FTC under which it will add a disclaimer to
Winston ads that will say the cigarettes are not safer just because
they contain ``no additives.'' By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was down
26 points, or 0.3 1 percent, and the Nasdaq index was down 13
points, or 0.6 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 1.8 percent in Tokyo
and closed little changed in Hong Kong. They decreased 2.7 percent
in Frankfurt, 0.3 percent in London, and 0.4 percent in Mexico.
They were flat in Brazil. On the American debt market, the long
bond was off 21/32 point, with the yield at 5.66 percent. By Robert
D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The weekly Economic Scene column. By
Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   William Safire's ``Essay.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
