<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6298 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FOREIGN-PAPERS-NY     03-03 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FOREIGN-PAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T GET THAT PAPER? TRY ITS SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WAYNE ROBINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was growing up a newspaper buff, there was no greater joy
than to take my allowance money to what was known as the
Out-of-Town news stand in Times Square. Spilling out of this
long-gone kiosk were newspapers from Topeka to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Though a similar store still exists in the neighborhood (the
resourceful Hotalings on W. 42nd St. between Broadway and Sixth),
because of the Internet you no longer need to live in New York to
keep up with the out of town news.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web it's possible to keep up with the news in every
corner of the planet from any corner of the planet. Whether it's a
shark-fishing ban in Tonga (www.tongatimes.com), or rugby scores in
New Zealand (www.evpost.co.nz/), the Internet's out-of-town
newsstand gives you the world, 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   To get started, the American Journalism Review's Newslink
(http://ajr.newslink.org/searchn.html) lists 4,925 newspapers on
line, categorized by continent, content, and frequency of
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Other gateways for the the wanderlustful news junkie include
(www.Newsdirectory.com), which lists 7,500 newspapers and magazines
with English-language on line content, and the Kidon Media List
www.dds.nl/kidon/media-link/papers.shtml, which is especially
useful if you read the local languages and want to scan through 9
papers in Minsk or 10 in Sofia.
</P>
<P>
   The stories to be found in these newspapers give a glimpse of
the world beyond what's available from major news outlets, print or
otherwise. The Yemen Times (www.yementimes.com), for instance, an
independent weekly published in Sanaa, the capital, did a
resourceful job a few weeks ago in presenting the context for the
recent kidnapping and disastrous rescue of British and Australian
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But even more interesting was a deeply personal letter from the
paper's editor, answering a government accusation that he was
``working for Western intelligence agencies, international Zionism,
and the Masonic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   In Katmandu, the Nepal News web site (www.nepalnews.com) offers
a news digest from various Nepali outlets, links to more than a
dozen of Himalayan nation's individual periodicals, the local top
music hits, a weather page, and an astrology package.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist in The Independent (www.south-asia.com/independent)
in Katmandu recently sneeringly accused a journalist from a rival
paper of writing an ``advertorial'' in favor of a controversial
hotel project, saying that it amounted to ``a desecration of the
opinion page.''
</P>
<P>
   Less contentious, perhaps, is the astrology page
(www.nepalnews.com/zodiac.htm), which offers horoscopes with a
fascinating twist: Based on the Nepalese Lunar calendar, one's
zodiac sign is determined not by birth date, but by the first two
letters of one's name.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of Australian newspapers on line. But why visit
Sydney or Melbourne when you can call up the 7,000-circulation
twice-weekly, 108-year-old Murray Pioneer?
(www.riverland.net.au/pioneer).
</P>
<P>
   Murray is a small town in an agricultural region, which is why
one story, ``California Citrus Freeze to Help Prices,'' may have
been particularly relevant to local readers.
</P>
<P>
   No matter where you go, you can't avoid crime. The Haveeru Daily
on line (www.haveeru.com/english/index.html), in the Indian Ocean's
remote Maldives islands, told of an expatriate Sri Lankan hotel
employee who was stabbed to death after an alcohol-fueled argument
with a fellow resort worker.
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans had ever heard of the Falklands Islands in the
South Atlantic until Great Britain, which owns the islands, and
Argentina, which claims sovereignty, resorted to war in 1982 to
resolve their dispute. The Falkland Islands News Network
(www.sartma.com), which includes the Teaberry Express, the
Antarctic Sentinel, and the Falkland Islands Newsletter, will bring
you up to speed if you wonder what's been going on in the Falklands
since then.
</P>
<P>
   You may want to know that the 12th West Falkland Ram and Fleece
show was a resounding success, and that Main Point Farm won first
prize in the Full Wool Ram Hoget category.
</P>
<P>
   Near the North Pole, nearly close enough to hail Santa, are the
Inuit people of the Canadian central and eastern Arctic. The
Nunatsiaq News (www.nunatsiaq.com), published weekly since 1993,
offers a link in which you can download the Nunacom font to view
the text in the Inuktituit language.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the English content these last few months has dealt with
the forthcoming political transition to self-government for the
Inuit.
</P>
<P>
   Want to buy a Corolla in Andorra? Try the classifieds of Diari
d'Andorra (www.solucions.ad/Diari/clas/classi.html). But there's a
catch; Diari doesn't have an English edition. (This is one of the
realities of exploring distant countries.) So if you want to
haggle, you had better speak Catalan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6299 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2     03-03 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVALUATING PENTIUM III: YOU SAY YOU WANT EVOLUTION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computers based on the new Pentium III microprocessor are now in
the stores, and that is happy news indeed for anyone shopping for a
new PC _ not necessarily because the Pentium III is a such a great
chip, although this third iteration does have its charms.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the arrival of the Pentium III's is welcome because it
means that prices for most lesser PCs are going to come down soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium III's have a slight speed advantage over the Pentium
II's that they will eventually replace. The Pentium III's also work
with a new set of instructions that can be used by software makers
to improve the performance of multimedia applications, especially
speech recognition, digital photo editing, streaming audio and
video over networks.
</P>
<P>
   But the speed gains of this first batch of Pentium III's are
incremental compared with the Pentium IIs, and the software that
will fully exploit the parallel processing power of the new
instructions is going to dribble out over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   By the time such software is widely available, perhaps six
months from now, and by the time a critical mass of Internet Web
sites have set up new features to take advantage of the added
power, Intel will have switched to a new manufacturing process that
will greatly increase the speed of future Pentium III's well beyond
the current levels.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Pentium III is an evolutionary advance over the
Pentium II, not a revolutionary one. Intel will promote it with a
$300 million advertising budget, the most ever spent to market a
microprocessor, so the evolution will definitely be televised. But
they can start this evolution without me.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going wait a while until there is a compelling reason to
upgrade. In general, I upgrade when I can answer ``yes'' to any or
all of the following: (1) Will the new machine provide me an
immediate 50 percent improvement in performance over what I am
using today? (2) Is the old machine o annoying that it causes me to
have facial tics? (3) Did I just win the lottery.?
</P>
<P>
   Experienced PC users have also learned that it is wise to wait a
few months after any new technology, hardware or software, is first
put on sale. Although the Pentium III uses the same core as the
Pentium II, Intel thought that it was different enough to warrant a
new number. Remember, the early bird gets the bugs as well as the
worm.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another incentive to wait is the tempest over Intel's
decision to add a unique Processor Serial Number identifier to
every new Pentium III chip. Intel added the feature in the interest
of improving security and privacy, a company spokesman said, but
some privacy watchdog groups say that feature threatens privacy of
protecting it. The debate is still under way. More on that later.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the best thing about the debut of the Pentium III is that
computer makers will cut the prices of machines based on the older
Pentium II and Celeron chips. The Celeron, especially the faster
versions of it, represents the best value among Intel's chips for
home PC users.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium II's are a good value for business applications, and
Intel cut prices for the chips by 15 percent to 20 percent earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's main rival in the PC microprocessor competition,
Advanced Micro Devices, just introduced its own challenger to the
Pentium III, called the K6-3. AMD has vowed to keep its chip prices
25 percent below Intel's, so when Intel cuts prices, AMD cuts
prices.
</P>
<P>
   In January, more AMD-based PCs were sold at retail than
Intel-based PCs, the first time that had happened.
</P>
<P>
   In short, basic PC prices are going to drop across the board in
the months ahead. Since most people do not need the special power
of the Pentium III _ need, as opposed to want _ they can take
advantage of the better deals ahead on Celeron, Pentium II and
AMD-based machines.
</P>
<P>
   The faster versions of these chips will perform almost as well
on common business applications _ word processing, e-mail,
spreadsheets, data bases and the like _ as the Pentium IIIs.
According to PC Week Labs, the Pentium III offers a performance
advantage of no more than 8 percent for common business
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if your favorite business application involves
pulping the guy in the next cubicle in a Quake death match over the
company network, you will definitely want a Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If you spend most of your day designing new 3-D molecules,
working with Adobe Photoshop files, downloading audio and video
files from the net, relying on voice recognition software to get
your work done, or playing games with 3-D graphics, a computer
based on the 500-megahertz version of the Pentium III offers
immediate performance improvements.
</P>
<P>
   For those who demand immediate gratification and cannot wait,
the two Pentium III 500-MHz systems I like best are the Dell
Dimension XPS T-500 (for its superior value) and the Sony PCV-L600
(for its innovating styling). I did not test the Gateway
Performance 500GN, which has been praised by other testing
laboratories as the best system for game players.
</P>
<P>
   The Dell system cost $2,398 and came with 128 megabytes of RAM,
a 12.9- gigabyte hard drive, a 16MB high-end graphics card, a 4.8X
DVD drive with a decoder card for watching movies, a 17-inch Sony
Trinitron monitor, a premium Altec Lansing sound system with a
subwoofer bigger and heavier than the computer itself, a Zip drive,
Microsoft Office, and the usual standard features.
</P>
<P>
   The Sony, also known as the VAIO Slimtop LCD Computer, had less
impressive technical specs and performance compared with the Dell,
and it cost more: $2,999. But for people who want 500-MHz Pentium
III power in a stylish, compact system that will fit on the
smallest desk, the Sony, with its flat-panel monitor, is the way to
go.
</P>
<P>
   The first practical demonstration of the new power of the
Pentium III that I was able to test was on the Sharper Image's Web
site (www.sharperimage.com), the gadget store. There, thanks to the
new processing power of the Pentium III chip, I was able to call up
a three-dimensional image of a nose-hair trimmer. Using mouse
commands, I rotated the gizmo swiftly and smoothly so that I could
see it from any angle, and even zoom in on details.
</P>
<P>
   Although a 3-D image of a ``nose-hair groomer'' is a humble
start, it was the first peek at the future of electronic commerce,
when people will be able to see how a sweater, for example, looks
from the back, or in a different color.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where the Processor Serial Number comes in. The PSN
is a unique identifier that is burned into the Pentium III chip,
the silicon equivalent of a Social Security Number. Intel says the
PSN is a security feature that is designed to help computer network
administrators to keep out unauthorized users, and help banks and
merchants cut down on fraud in electronic commerce transactions.
</P>
<P>
   On the darker side, the unique identifier could make it possible
to track individual machines _ in effect, individuals _ when they
are on line, whether posting messages to a political or health news
group, downloading dirty pictures, or shopping on line.
</P>
<P>
   Intel asserts that the computer owner can choose whether the PSN
is ``on'' or ``off,'' in effect denying Web sites the ability to
read the PSN automatically. Several programming experts counter
that they can read the PSN remotely, using clever hacks, even if
the owner has the PSN feature turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Intel acknowledges that its safeguards are not 100 percent
effective, given that a malicious hacker could in theory sneak a
peek at the number when it is turned ``off'' by surreptitiously
planting a Trojan Horse program on the user's computer.
</P>
<P>
   But if a hacker went to that much trouble, the PSN would be the
last thing I would worry about. I would be more concerned about my
e-mail, my Quicken files and other private data.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has indicated that it plans to extend the PSN feature to
its entire product line over time. I'll wait for even better
machines and better assurances of privacy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
