<HEADLINE>
CAULIFLOWER SOUP EVEN A CHILD CAN LOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nikki Mahaffey e-mails looking for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to have the recipe for cheese and cauliflower
soup that is served at the tearoom in Antiques &AMP; Moore antique mall
in Arlington (Texas). Over the Christmas holiday, I took my
8-year-old granddaughter there for a special grandma/granddaughter
outing and she said the soup was so good we'd have to get seconds.
(This from a child who does not like cauliflower.) I would love to
be able to make it for her on her next visit to Grandma's house.''
</P>
<P>
   For being such a good grandma, here's the recipe, courtesy of
Doris Perritt and Helen Bowers, who manage The Rose Garden Tea
Room.
</P>
<P>
   THE ROSE GARDEN'S CAULIFLOWER AND CHEESE SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 large head cauliflower
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 finely minced celery ribs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half, heated until hot
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper, cayenne pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cut tough stem from cauliflower. Soak head of cauliflower in
cold salted water for 10 minutes. Drain and break the head into
florets. Place florets in saucepan with about 2 inches of water.
Cook about 8 to 10 minutes. Drain the cauliflower, but reserve the
cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   Place florets in a food processor and pulse 2 to 3 times to
break up the florets. (This can also be done with a sturdy fork.)
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in large saucepan. Saute the onion and celery in the
butter until tender. Stir in 1/2 cup flour and mix well. Bring to
the bubbling stage.
</P>
<P>
   To the flour, add chicken stock and the reserved cooking water.
Stir well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cauliflower and the heated half-and-half. Season with
salt, pepper and cayenne pepper. Add the shredded cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Soup may be garnished with dried parsley.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the soup warm, place in a double boiler over steaming
water.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 459 calories, 38 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 15 grams protein, 111 milligrams cholesterol,
319 milligrams sodium, 75 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   For other children: You might not like cauliflower, but who
doesn't like cookies? Here's the requested recipe for cookies made
with cornflakes. It was sent in by Beth Mewhinney, Stephenville,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   CRUNCHY CHEWS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 4 1/2 dozen (1 1/2-inch) squares
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dark corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup super chunky peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups cornflakes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup peanuts or broken mixed nuts (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Grease 13-by-9-by-2-inch baking pan.
</P>
<P>
   In saucepan, mix together sugar and corn syrup. Bring to a boil,
stirring constantly, over medium heat. Boil 1 minute. Mix in peanut
butter. Turn into prepared pan. Stir in cornflakes and nuts. Press
together firmly. Cool. Cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per bar including mixed nuts: 52 calories,
2 grams fat, 9 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol,
25 milligrams sodium, 31 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
