<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYLITE(SMILE)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 2901 Wed., March 3: 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (NYLite items can be published if desired; &LR;  please credit the
contributor. Contribute to NYLite and get a NYT rolling-writer
style pen.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On the Friday before Valentine's Day, Ricardo Aguero walked into
the Madison Avenue Bookshop and picked up ``Here Is My Heart,'' a
book of poetry, as a gift for his wife, Lynn Hackstaff.
</P>
<P>
   When she joined him for a late lunch, she, too, handed him a
gift, nicely wrapped, obviously a book. A researcher at a surgical
clinic, she had gone to the bookstore between patients that day and
bought the same volume for him.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, who met in an online chat room, had been married for
only five months and both were surprised, and pleased, that they
knew each other's tastes so well. Should they return one of the
books? If so, which one? The result: The twin volumes are cozily
nudging each other on the bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I took a bus to Manhattan that dropped me and my cane
off on an upstairs platform at the Port Authority terminal, so I
sent my granddaughter ahead to see if the escalator was working.
</P>
<P>
   While I waited, a gentleman paused beside me and the following
exchange occurred.
</P>
<P>
   He: ``See, I use a cane, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Me: ``Well, they help get us where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   He, leaning forward confidentially: ``I'm 90 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, triumphantly: ``I'm 91{ years old.''
</P>
<P>
   He lightly planted a kiss on my cheek and departed.
</P>
<P>
   I was giggling when my granddaughter returned. Of course she
wanted to know why. I described the episode and her response was
``He's got some nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, she's not even 30, and she's a feminist to boot.
</P>
<P>
   _ HORTENSE GUTMANN
</P>
<P>
   Two first-graders were walking down the stairs at their school.
Tia Biasi heard one say to the other: ``It's like yogurt. You don't
have to buy the fat, because it's free. You just have to buy the
yogurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Two well-dressed businessmen were striding purposefully up
Eighth Avenue in Chelsea when they came upon a large flock of
pigeons feasting on bread crumbs that someone had scattered on the
corner. Sean O'Malley, who was nearby, heard one of them say to the
other, ``Oh, excuse me a second!'' The man then made his way into
the midst of the pigeons, bent low, hands on knees, and asked,
``Any messages?''
</P>
<P>
   THE JEALOUS GOD
</P>
<P>
   Marilynne Blakely was window shopping from her car when she
spotted a yellow spring suit. Shortly afterward, she made her first
visit to the shop, which happened to be a favorite of her mother's
friends. She asked the saleswoman the fabric of the suit _ it was
polyester. The saleswoman, noticing Mrs. Blakely's disappointment,
quickly added, ``Our ladies don't like to wrinkle.''
</P>
<P>
   I have recently been reminiscing about Second Avenue when I
lived there as a child in the 1930s. We lived behind our jewelry
store on Second, between 78th and 79th streets. A theater was on
the corner of 79th, sometimes playing talkies and sometimes silent
films. Jimmy, the manager, would let us in free. Sometimes we would
swipe sweet peas from a store down the street and then run for our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Second Avenue El roared and clattered overhead. We could
converse only between trains. The sun that peeked through the
tracks and railway ties danced wildly on the cobblestones below
whenever a train passed by.
</P>
<P>
   When I looked all the way down Second Avenue to where everything
seemed to converge, I believed that was the edge of the world, and
if I could only stand on top of a ladder on one of the rooftops, I
could touch the sky.
</P>
<P>
   _ EMANUEL BERGER
</P>
<P>
   A very elderly woman was walking ahead of Helene Bell in the
cosmetics department at Bloomingdale's. A saleswoman carrying a
tray of ``free gift with purchase'' products approached the woman
and asked if there was anything she would like to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lovely offer, but I don't need anything at the
moment,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   The saleswoman replied: ``That's no problem. Our products have a
shelf life of two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman smiled at her. ``The difficulty is, I'm not sure of my
shelf life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   David B. Angerman, like everyone else, has heard New York
described as Fun City. Still, when he saw the sign at the 86th
Street subway station, he was pleased to know that residents
uninterested in participating in the fun had been taken into
consideration. The sign read:
</P>
<P>
   No Fun
</P>
<P>
   Pass
</P>
<P>
   Sold Here
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical Saturday morning at a Bronx neighborhood
supermarket. Ed Gruber was waiting his turn and observing Irving,
the counterman, who was seemingly frenetic but totally in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else?'' Irving asked an indecisive shopper. ``I don't
know,'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a special on smoked sturgeon,'' he announced. There was
a long pause. ``Is it fresh?'' she asked. ``As fresh as a smoked
sturgeon can be, lady.'' he replied. She finally made up her mind:
``All right, give me six slices.''
</P>
<P>
   Irving was waiting for that. ``We ain't got no more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
