<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6327 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANICS-TEXAS-TEX     03-03 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STORY OF STRUGGLE AND SUCCESS IN TEXAS' GROWING HISPANIC
POPULATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Filiberto and Obdulia Rios sit side-by-side
in antique chairs, two of the most prized possessions of their
daughter-in-law Yolanda.
</P>
<P>
   They look out a picture window on Ryan Place Drive in one of
Fort Worth's most historic neighborhoods, as they talk about their
family, their tailoring business, and the life they've pieced
together through three decades of hard work in this city.
</P>
<P>
   It's Sunday morning, and the house fills with the chatter and
laughter of their three children, seven grandchildren and some
family friends. The smell of bacon and barbacoa drifts into the
room from the kitchen. It's a warm, happy, brick home with hardwood
floors and modern conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing like the place in their native Mexico that
Filiberto, 60, and Obdulia, or Lula, 58, remember now. In 1965,
they lived with their three small children in a two-room shack in
the border town of Acuna, Mexico, where in winter months they
nearly froze from the cold. The $20 a week that Filiberto made from
his small tailoring business barely began to meet the family's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Filiberto's youngest brother, Jose, wrote to the
couple from Fort Worth, urging them to join him.
</P>
<P>
   Filiberto said the decision was not hard. ``I never felt at home
in Mexico,'' he recalls. ``I didn't see any future for my
children.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, with a 15-day work permit, Filiberto came to Fort Worth
and stayed far beyond the time allowed by the law. After six
months, he sent for his family to join him, betting on an uncertain
future.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rios family joined the increasing number of Hispanics
who come to Texas each year to find a new life, to find hope for
their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Hispanics make up 28 percent of the state's population.
If current trends continue, say demographers, in 30 years, families
like the Rioses are expected to make up almost half of the Texas
population.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, then, the faces of la familia Rios are not only
the faces of the Texas of today, but the faces of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   After securing his 15-day permit, Filiberto Rios packed his 1946
blue Chevy and made the 12-hour trek to Fort Worth in 1965, leaving
behind his wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   While life still proved hard initially, Filiberto's income more
than tripled to $65 a week when he began work at Caudle's, a
menswear store on Camp Bowie Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, that was a lot of money,'' Filiberto says.
</P>
<P>
   Just half a year later, with a promise from his employer that he
could keep his job, Filiberto sent for his family. They came with
just the clothes on their backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, we could get only a 15-day permit,'' Filiberto says.
``To bring more than that, would have placed suspicion on us.
Besides, we really didn't have more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   His eldest son, Edward, was 4; his daughter Edith was 3 and
Filiberto Jr. was 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   They settled on the city's north side in an old dilapidated
house. The rent was $15 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first year was very tough,'' Filiberto recalls. ``We had
less than most people who said they were poor.''
</P>
<P>
   And because the family was here illegally after the 15-day
permit had run out, Rios had the added expense of sending young
Edward to a private Catholic school. A year later, the family
applied for and was granted permanent residency.
</P>
<P>
   Rios says he was determined to provide for his family, to
nurture his dream of opening his own business. His first priority
was to save enough to buy a home. By limiting the family's spending
to the bare necessities over the next three years, he had the $600
down payment for a house he'd set his sights on. The mortgage
payment was $55 a month.
</P>
<P>
   By this time, Filiberto had found another day job at R.E. Cox's
department store on West Berry Street. At night, when he wasn't
attending school to learn to speak English, he took in extra work
from customers he met at Cox's. Lula was also attending night
classes and learned more about the tailoring business. Whenever
they could, the two stayed up late, making alterations in the
family's garage.
</P>
<P>
   By 1980, Filiberto reached the goal he had had since his
childhood: Tailoring by Rios opened at 6918 Camp Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The three generations of the Rios family gather almost every
day, either at work at the shop, or to visit and eat, as they do
here at Edward's home in Ryan Place.
</P>
<P>
   Amid laughter, Lee Sanchez, a family friend, wonders aloud how
they spend so much time together and remain successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with him 24 hours a day,'' said Lula Rios, referring to
Filiberto.
</P>
<P>
   A slow, silent grin stretches across his face and Filiberto
responds: ``She's very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky or not, Edward Rios said that what has happened for his
family is nothing short of amazing.
</P>
<P>
   In 20 years of business, Tailoring by Rios has developed an
impressive list of commercial clients, including Banana Republic,
The Wardrobe, John L. Ashe and Harolds, while keeping many of its
original customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the success has been hard-won. Edward Rios says he abandoned
his dream of becoming an accountant to help his father. Filiberto
Jr. gave up becoming an auto mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the two sons and daughter Edith, who has an associate
degree in business, take on various duties at the shop. Edith, 38,
manages the business office; Filiberto Jr., 37, oversees the
commercial accounts and deliveries; and Edward, 39, is the general
manager. The two brothers also do most of the fittings and
alterations. The siblings' seven children, who range in age from 7
to 17, are also there to help on most weekends, answering the
phone, sweeping the floor or taking out the trash.
</P>
<P>
   The store is open Tuesdays through Saturdays, but Filiberto Sr.
often shows up on Sundays and Mondays to do general maintenance on
the machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more work than money,'' said Edward Rios, ``but it's a
decent living for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his family's future, Edward remains optimistic, sure now of
the dream his father once bet on. It's ``better than the lottery _
because with hard work, you can't miss,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
