   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In a battle of dueling
legislative agendas, President Clinton challenges Republicans to
set aside 15 percent of budget surpluses to rescue Medicare as he
and congressional Democrats announce a ``Families First'' plan for
the year. For the GOP, House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert and Majority
Leader Richard Armey offer rival priorities, including an
across-the-board tax cut. By STEWART M. POWELL And JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-AGENDA (Washington) _ The Congressional Budget Office
reports that President Clinton's budget proposal would break
spending caps for next year by $30 billion. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL (Washington) _ The independent counsel act
is either a bulwark protecting Americans against the powerful
``spin machine'' of the White House or ``a nuclear weapon in the
arsenal of partisan politics.'' Those divergent views and others
are heard by a Senate panel as Congress tries to decide whether to
scrap the controversial law. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-IMMIGRATION (Washington) _ The Supreme Court hears
arguments on whether immigrants with alien status can be deported
even if they can prove they face persecution in their homeland. By
STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SENATE (Washington) _ Seeking to head off a flood of
lawsuits against companies that fail to correct their year 2000
computer problems, the Senate Commerce Committee narrowly approves
legislation that would limit their liability and impose a 90-day
cooling off period so they could solve the problems without going
to court. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN-MAFIA (San Antonio) _ Ten reputed members of the
notorious prison-based Mexican Mafia are convicted in federal court
of racketeering charges. The 10 were accused of plotting robberies,
drug deals and at least 15 murders. By MARRO ROBBINS.
</P>
<P>
   MAFIA-LEADER (San Antonio) _ As a leader of the Mexican Mafia,
Robert ``Beaver'' Perez was by most accounts a powerful man. But
for all his influence, painstakingly illustrated in a trial in
federal court that resulted in 10 convictions, Perez was in many
ways just another guy from San Antonio's poor West Side. By
THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-MEXICO (McAllen, Texas) _ Two American couples fishing
on the Mexican side of Falcon Lake near Zapata, Texas, have spent
the last three weeks trying to retrieve their expensive bass boats,
which were seized by Mexican environmental officials who claim they
were fishing without proper licenses. The U.S. consulate agrees the
punishment is outrageous, but officials there have other fish to
fry. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS-HOSPITAL (Houston) _ Three of seven surviving
octuplets are released from the Texas Children's Hospital in
Houston. (Photos of the babies are not available. The Nigerian-born
couple sold photography rights to a British tabloid for $250,000.)
By ERIC HANSON.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-TAX-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas House Ways and Means
Committee is scheduled to vote on Gov. George W. Bush's emergency
severance-tax relief measure for producers of marginal oil and gas
wells. Republican sponsors say they have enough votes to emerge
from committee and win the votes needed on the House floor required
for the bill to take immediate effect. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-CLIPPERS (Houston) _ Even for the Los Angeles Clippers _ a
franchise that is indelibly linked with ineptitude _ this is
getting ridiculous. Winless through their first 13 games of the
season, the Clippers are hitting new lows as they prepare for a
matchup against the Houston Rockets. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets are running out of
excuses. Most of their injured players are back from the disabled
list. The schedule is starting to lighten a bit. Yet they still are
limping along with an 8-7 record and five losses in their past
seven games. By MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-EVERETT (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ A year ago, Carl Everett entered
the Houston Astros camp as a major question mark. He was coming off
a season marked by personal turmoil and on-field struggles. One
season later, Everett has answered all the questions emphatically
and heads into the 1999 season as the Astros' everyday
centerfielder. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ALOU (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ Moises Alou undergoes surgery to
repair the anterior cruciate ligament in his knee, a procedure that
likely will keep the slugging Houston Astros outfielder on the
sidelines for the entire 1999 season. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-HOUSTON (Birmingham, Ala.) _ The Houston Cougars and coach
Clyde Drexler try to keep their season alive as they play North
Carolina-Charlotte in a first-round game at the Conference USA
postseason basketball tournament. By JERRY WIZIG.
</P>
