<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6331 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CYCLING-2TAKES-NY     03-03 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CYCLING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE TOUR DE FRANCE, AND BEYOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ian Austen, a writer and amateur racing cyclist, has covered the
Tour de France and other major races.  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until Greg LeMond showed that an American could win the Tour de
France, following professional cycle racing from the United States
was a desperate business. Race results from the tour and other
races like the Giro D'Italia and the Tour of Flanders typically
came weeks, if not months, late through the pages of outrageously
overpriced European magazines like the old Miroir du Cyclisme.
</P>
<P>
   LeMond's extraordinary success _ he won the Tour de France three
times, first in 1986 _ unquestionably increased cycling coverage,
both in print and on television. But despite that, timely reporting
remained largely concentrated on just the Tour de France. Now the
Web has changed all that.
</P>
<P>
   Through a variety of sources, American fans are now being
informed as quickly and almost as well as their European
counterparts. All that is lacking now is live, full-motion video;
Web experiments last year by France 3, one of the two broadcasters
of the Tour de France in its homeland, suggest that some form of
that may not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   That may put fans ahead of the cycling press. The dirty secret
of covering the Tour de France, which I have done, is that the
journalists rarely see the racers in action. Instead, they crowd
into French cars for hours of white-knuckle driving through huge
crowds ahead of the racers to catch the finish of the race on
television. Be grateful: no Web site recreates that. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Cycling Sites &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.cyclingnews.com Commonly known as Bill's, for Bill Mitchell,
the economist who founded it, this Australian site relies on more
than 50 volunteers to gather race results from around the world. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.procycling.com A British site with daily news on
road-racing, track and cyclo-cross, an off-road running and riding
competition. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.fatnick.com A British site with complete results on six-day
track racing, a sport Americans once dominated. The site's name is
a reference to its creator, Nick Rosenthal, an amateur racer from
Manchester who calls himself ``horribly unfit.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.lancearmstrong.com The online diary of Lance Armstrong, only
the second American world road-race champion, and his wife,
Kristin. Armstrong has recovered from testicular cancer, and last
season he showed in several races he's still among the world's best
cyclists. The coming weeks will presumably be centered on
Armstrong's recovery from a dislocated collarbone he recently
suffered. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Official Tour de France &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.letour.fr &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's doping scandal _ with police raids and riders'
strikes _ wasn't exactly an image builder for France's greatest
annual sports ritual. But the Tour de France remains cycling's most
watched and most important event.
</P>
<P>
   While Web sites have become standard features of most sporting
events, the Societe du Tour de France took to the Web relatively
early and has become a model for many race organizations.
</P>
<P>
   American cycling fans, unlike much of the world, cannot catch
the tour live on television. But once again this July, the site
will offer continual text updates in English and French and still
photos during each of the 21 racing days.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of the site, the live reports came from
writers who were clearly more comfortable with a language other
than English. That changed last year when James Startt, an American
cycling journalist based in France, began preparing the English
dispatches. He also winds up the day with a newspaper-style report.
</P>
<P>
   Slackers who go to the tour site while they are supposed to be
working can activate a tiny window with a rolling race update in a
corner of their monitor while ostensibly dealing with, say, a
spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, if the tour organization keeps its promises, Web
visitors will be as well informed as the team managers, journalists
and others roaring along the actual race route by car. The Web site
will include a direct audio feed of Radio Tour, an internal radio
network that describes the action by using a team of motorcycle
spotters and officials in the race director's car.
</P>
<P>
   Its commentary _ in French, sometimes awkward English and
Spanish _ is understated in the extreme. ``The main pack is
accelerating,'' is about as colorful as the commentary gets,
unless, of course, there's a crash. And listeners who do not want
to be baffled must print out the race start sheet from the site in
advance because Radio Tour refers to riders by their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The site also includes details about each day's route, archived
results from every stage of tours since 1995, a searchable history
section, a ``great moments'' area and regular news updates through
the season on the teams that qualify for the race.
</P>
<P>
   The tour organization also runs 13 other events _ including the
famous Paris-Roubaix race over the cobblestones of northern France.
Most of them are covered by the site, but not as grandly as the
main event. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Tour Saga &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (World Media Live; $29; Windows 3.1 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the audio effects and striking music that open
this Tour de France history capture the sound of being there. They
are a clever mix of blaring horns, revving motorcycles, roaring
helicopters, buzzy radio transmissions and the unmistakable voice
of Daniel Mangeas, the official race announcer, blasting from
loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the real thing, however, you can shut off the CD-ROMs
sound when the racket becomes overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   This CD-ROM tries hard to make what is essentially a collection
of historical statistics entertaining. And it largely succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The database consists of histories and statistics for every Tour
de France since its start in 1903 up to 1996. With that are
biographies of about 1,000 riders and a large number of photos.
</P>
<P>
   The material is available in French or English and packaged in
several different ways. A banner across the opening page groups the
race history into nine different eras, generally named for the
dominant rider of the time. Individual years can also be selected.
And users can look up a rider and use hyperlinks to get the history
of any year that person rode the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the amount of material presented depends on
how far back you go. The histories of the earliest editions can be
quite brief and the results limited to top placings.
</P>
<P>
   The histories and results from 1981 onward are much more
complete. Those years even begin with a short video commentary by
Stephen Roche, the Irish rider who in 1987 performed the rare feat
of winning the Tour de France, the Giro d'Italia and the world road
race championship. Now a television commentator, Roche gives'
introductions that are heavy on personal anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   The excellent and cleanly reproduced historical photographs are
from the archives of Miroir du Cyclisme and its predecessor, Miroir
Sprint. But the 24 videos on the disk are extremely disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   The ones covering the tour up until 1981 are mostly Pathe
newsreels, complete with their original staccato French commentary
and furious orchestral music. The newreels condense a month's
racing into a little more than a minute and seemingly always
concluding that the overall winner is indeed a great champion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately the transfer to the CD-ROM has left the newsreel
images so muddy and dark that it is often almost impossible to make
out what is happening, let alone distinguish riders. The post-1981
videos show Roche standing in front of a tree recalling his
glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest failing of the Tour Saga is that it cannot be
updated by the user. While it has a link to the producer's European
cycling Web site, Velocity (www.worldmedia.fr/velo), there is no
easy way to download to a hard drive its reports and photos from
the tour since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While several very good books do a better job of capturing the
essence of the race, nothing in English comes close to the Tour
Saga CD-ROM as a reference source. And of course, no book lets you
hear Daniel Mangeas. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Total Cycling Encyclopedia  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Infostrada, $30; Windows 95 and 98.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quick: Who won the 1937 edition of Belgium's one-day race known
as the Fleche Wallonne? That's right, it was Adolf Braeckeveldt, a
Belgian who averaged a relatively sedate 18 mph but nevertheless
headed a group of 19 who were the only riders among 84 starters who
made it to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that you don't care about Braeckeveldt, who had only
two victories in his career. But just as baseball breeds a type of
fan for whom no statistic is too obscure, ancient cycling results
have their own following.
</P>
<P>
   Until Infostrada's CD-ROM came along last year, the definitive
sources for settling arguments about riders' performances were
generally two fat books issued annually by publishers in the
Netherlands and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, however, went beyond the careers of current riders,
leaving earlier results to several incomplete and hard-to-obtain
history books, none of which are in English.
</P>
<P>
   The Total Cycling Encyclopedia, by contrast, cannot be accused
of lacking scope. It says it contains 110,000 results dating back
109 years. And it has a Web site link that can update information
with relatively little fuss. All this is produced in eight
languages on a single disk.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who ignore its amateurish graphics will find that the
CD-ROM mostly lives up to its claims. Pull-down menus allow users
to search the data by race, year or rider name.
</P>
<P>
   But the English translations are not always successful. In one
case, the publishers have confused the World Cup, a somewhat
unimportant season-long points competition, with the World
Championships, a prestigious title decided by a one-day race.
</P>
<P>
   An added feature is a package of profiles of notable European
mountain passes. But they are presented as poorly rendered graphs
that offer little sense of the passes' grades; they more closely
resemble charts of Amazon.com's recent share price. (For ordering
information, see the www.sportplaza.com/tce site.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Union Cycliste Internationale  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.uci.ch &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the Tour de France doping affair, the Union Cycliste
Internationale has become as controversial in many cycling circles
as the International Olympic Committee is in the Olympic community.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is the sport's governing body, so it still sets
the rules, ranks the riders on a complex point scale, organizes the
world championships and tries to promote all things on two wheels.
Its Web site reflects that broad role.
</P>
<P>
   For the championships and mountain bike and road bike World Cup
events, it offers rapid and complete results along with
high-quality photos and sometimes a race report. Similarly, the
riders' points rankings _ which determine, to a large extent, their
pay _ are also available, along with mountains of mind-numbing
rules. You can, for example, try to decipher the union's latest
attempt to standardize frame design.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is too obscure for the UCI. For example, the site
includes a large section on artistic cycling, a sort of figure
skating on bicycles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Velo News Interactive &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.greatoutdoors.com/velonews &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Velo News, based in Boulder, Colo., is not America's largest
cycling magazine. That title belongs to Bicycling. But nothing
matches Velo News in terms of the attention it pays to amateur and
professional racers (both road and mountain biking) in the United
States and their counterparts overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to several experienced contributors, Velo News was the
first American magazine to deliver informed and sometimes critical
reporting on cycling. At its best, the magazine delivers insider
news with outsider independence.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the occasional feature, very little of the magazine's
contents make their way onto the site. The Web version mostly
offers a frequently updated cycling news service along with chat
groups.
</P>
<P>
   This season, for the first time since the magazine went on line,
Velo News has no full-time correspondent based in Europe. The
online director, Tim Johnson, said staff members would travel
overseas for major races. He plans to cover any gaps with Agence
France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   The United States-based staff includes John Wilcockson, a
knowledgeable veteran of several cycling publications here and in
Britain. But if too much of the site winds up coming from Agence
France-Presse, Velo News may lose the distinctive style that has
made it a regular stopping point for many cyclists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1616EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6334 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-RESEARCH-NYT &LR;      03-03 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-RESEARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUES TO SEPARATE GOOD DATA FROM BAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Calif.)   (af)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first rule of information found on the Web (and many other
places as well) is this: be skeptical. You wouldn't buy a stock,
write a check or believe a contentious statement from an unknown
source off line _ so bring the same challenging attitude to
information found on line.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be shy about going off-line to check something: go to
a library, pick up a phone or call your own doctor to check.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a handful of suggestions to help surfers assess
information found on line.
</P>
<P>
   Know the source. If you recognize the source and are sure that
particular source is running the site, you are likely to be on
solid ground. Don't forget, though, that some of the people running
sites are trying to confuse you: www.amnesty-tunisia.org, and
www.amnesty.org/tunisia, for instance, carry opposing messages.
Don't forget that hackers can sometimes commandeer legitimate
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Check to see if the site is objective, or at least takes account
of opposing points of view.
</P>
<P>
   Pay close attention to when a site was most recently updated.
The last revision dates of some sites can be determined via the
Netscape Navigator browser. Click the View option and go to ``Page
Info'' to see information on when the site was last revised. Other
sites have ``last updated'' lines _ which in themselves are, of
course, hard to check.
</P>
<P>
   Gauge a site's credibility by seeing who runs it. To check, go
to rs.internic.net and use the ``whois'' search of the database of
registered domain names run by InterNic, an organization that is
the registry for the most recognized categories of Internet
domains. (Be aware, though, that this information is not
conclusive.) When you have an idea of who runs the site, you can
better judge its information.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to whether a site's address (called a uniform
resource locator, or URL) ends with a .com for commercial, .org
(technically for non-profit organizations), .gov for government,
.net for network or .edu for educational.
</P>
<P>
   While many .edu sites describe bona fide research, others are
individual homepages, with information that is harder to verify. It
is also true that anybody with a little bit of money can get a .org
or .net site, so the suffix is not definitive _ a strip miner could
register lovetheenvironment.org. Foreign websites have different
suffix: .ca for Canada, .ru for Russia and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Ask yourself if banner advertisements compromise the content of
the page, or lend it credibility, representing an advertiser's
implicit vote of confidence in the site.
</P>
<P>
   If you see a tilde () in a web site's address, that's usually a
sign of a personal home page. The tilde might occur in an .edu
address, suggesting that the page's owner is a professor or student
at a college or university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are they're not a major, major entity,'' said Reva
Basch, author of ``Researching On Line for Dummies'' (Dummies
Technology Press 1998), of tilde site-owners. Often a clue that a
site is a personal page is an address that includes ``geocities,''
``tripod'' or www.members.aol.com/namehere.
</P>
<P>
   If you run across unfamiliar topics or web site authors, run
their names through a search engine or Dejanews.com _ which is a
search engine of news groups _ to see what others have said about
it or them or him or her.
</P>
<P>
   Dejanews is a huge and often highly fractious collection of
personal opinions, some of them highly misleading or
incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   Think about contacting a web site owner directly, perhaps using
an e-mail address or phone from the site, or perhaps using the
fruits of your InterNic search.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have doubts about a person's credentials, send him an
e-mail,'' said Paul Gilster, a technology columnist in Raleigh,
N.C., and beware sites that offer no address or do not respond.
``You should be able to use the technology to solve the problem the
technology creates.''
</P>
<P>
   A long and complicated web address is another warning sign, but
someone trying to find out more about a site with an ungainly
address can delete parts of it from right to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm presented with information like that, I always like to
back up level by level, slash by slash and see where I am and what
other information is there like that,'' Ms. Basch said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Quint, editor of Searcher magazine, also sees the value
of exploring a site from top to bottom. ``I'm coming through the
front door,'' she said. ``I want to look around at the building
before I find myself at somebody's broom closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to hyperlinks, the small web addresses appearing
at the bottom of the screen when you move the mouse across a web
page. ``A good page, one using the Internet well, not only has
internal links, but also points outward to other parts of
information,'' Gilster said. ``If I have a good idea, it's to my
advantage for you to look at other ideas, to prove you that mine is
the best. Web pages that are completely inward turning, where all
the information only points to the same server, should raise an
alarm flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilster likes the Northernlight.com search engine, which offers
free searches of magazines, with small fees for viewing entire
articles. By searching for people there, he can confirm that they
have been published in more traditional, edited publications. He
also likes Google.com, a search engine that factors in the number
of other sites linking to it when ranking search results.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Grassian of the UCLA College Library urges surfers to
look for sites that refer to print and other off-line resources.
</P>
<P>
   Look for sites like Cnet.com that include a page of corrections,
which are rare but appreciated, (provided the corrections aren't
too plentiful.) Beware of sites with lots of spelling and
grammatical errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe anyone doing serious work would put up a
web page loaded with that sort of problem,'' said Gilster. Lack of
attention to such detail could indicate less-than-rigorous content.
(Some sites run by non-English speakers can be an exception.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
