<HEADER>
A6340 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIEFTAINS-TEX     03-03 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIEFTAINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHIEFTAINS CHARM WITH TRADITIONAL IRISH MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late on a Saturday night in the quiet Irish countryside of the
1940s, a house party jams in an old woman's cottage. The room is
crammed, the music is jaunty jigs and reels, the dancers are
kicking up their heels, their faces flushed with the peat fire's
heat and their own exertion as drink flows and the music plays into
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is right out of an Irish tourism commercial, but for
Paddy Moloney, the founder of The Chieftains, it was regular
entertainment as he spent the summers with his grandmother, Julia
Conroy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd dance and sing until 8 a.m. or so and go to Mass, then
everybody would come home, have breakfast and go to bed.'' says
Moloney, who formed the band 36 years ago in Dublin and has since
guided it to six Grammys, including last week's nod for Traditional
Folk Album for the soundtrack to the PBS series ``The Irish in
America: Long Journey Home.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Saturday nights in Ireland were Moloney's first musical
education. Not only did he hear instrumentals that would inform his
work, but he also heard a cappella ballads such as ``Lowlands of
Holland,'' ``Deserted Soldier'' and ``Raglan Road.'' Now it is
those songs, and others, that form the basis for ``Tears of
Stone,'' the Chieftains' latest CD and their tribute to female
vocalists. The idea was to merge the band's faultless ensemble
playing with different female vocalists _ a combination, Moloney
says, that he has always found intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always loved female vocalists singing with us,'' he says.
``The blend of vocals is better for me than with male singers.''
</P>
<P>
   The 14 songs on ``Tears'' find the band playing subtly, and
often very quietly, as women such as Joni Mitchell, Bonnie Raitt,
Natalie Merchant, Sinead O'Connor and Mary Chapin Carpenter do
ageless songs such as the above, as well as ``A Stor Mo Chroi,
Magdalene Laundries'' and ``Factory Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Moloney actively began approaching singers to
appear on the record. He had a ``wish list'' of several vocalists
(among them O'Connor, Mitchell, and Sarah McLachlan). Once he had
worked through the red tape _ publicists, record companies, etc. _
work on ``Tears'' progressed slowly, with sessions fit in around
the Chieftains' constant road work and the women's schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was worth it. Because female singers dominate the
charts (and the Grammy nominations) at the moment, and because it
features so many popular singers, ``Tears'' is virtually assured of
success. Moloney doesn't make a big deal out of this, but it's
obvious he's happy with the timing. (''If you can't beat them, join
them,'' he says.)
</P>
<P>
   For years the Chieftains put out excellent, insular records of
traditional Irish music, with Moloney's playing on the uilleann
pipes and Matt Molloy's flute firmly anchoring the proceedings.
They became an institution in Ireland by the late '70s and then
began devoting more of their time to soundtrack work. They also
began an ongoing series of collaborative CDs with musicians from
China to Nashville to Spain, highlighting their ability to blend
with different sounds and cultures.
</P>
<P>
   But it was 1995's ``The Long Black Veil'' (which paired them
with Sting, Sinead O'Connor, Mark Knopfler, the Rolling Stones, Tom
Jones and several others) that put them on the map. It sold more
than 500,000 copies (a career high and an enormous amount for a
traditional Irish group) and earned the band a Best Pop
Collaboration Grammy for their work with Van Morrison on ``Have I
Told You Lately That I Love You?''
</P>
<P>
   Moloney seems to know that the band needs to get back to simply
recording traditional music on its own, something critics have been
suggesting for years. The band's next CD, due out next year, will
be called ``The Chieftains in Ireland,'' and exactly what the title
implies: The band traveling around the island, digging into the
different regional styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a particular style of playing the fiddle in Kerry, and
up in Galway, 60 or 70 miles away, it's completely different,'' he
says. ``And there's different themes, different battles in
different places people wrote about, different poets who lived in
different parts of the country who wrote songs. You can go on and
on.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1622EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6343 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NH-HANOVER-2TA     03-03 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NH-HANOVER-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANOVER'S SNOWY PLAYGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
 (bl)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I wasn't even in Hanover, N.H., yet, and I already felt I had
escaped New York City. A few days before leaving, I received a
postcard from Pierce's Country Inn, where I had made reservations
for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be serving breakfast,'' read the handwritten note.
``Lots of good places for dinner in town.'' Then it continued in
curly cursive letters with directions to the inn. ``Reg and
Nancy,'' it was signed.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend with the Pierces, I sensed, was going to be too brief.
</P>
<P>
   And there was lots to do in Hanover. Just far enough from the
ski resorts and major tourist sights, this part of New Hampshire is
accessible and affordable (our budget was not to exceed $500).
There is little traffic getting there and almost no pressure to
plan anything, so it's easy to take advantage of its offerings in a
single weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Hanover centers on Dartmouth College. Even for a
tourist, it's inescapable. ``A voice crying in the wilderness,''
the school's motto, is an image embraced by students and town
residents alike. Hiking and cross-country skiing are part of the
daily ritual; Patagonia is the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   And it just so happened that a friend, Matthew, and I planned to
go during the biggest celebration of the season, Winter Carnival.
In addition to the outdoor activities we had in mind, there would
be events at the college _ concerts, campus tours and, of course,
the famous keg-jumping competition, which involves jumping a row of
beer kegs, Evel Knievel-style, on ice skates.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, we drove north from Boston, where it was warm
and balmy. As we passed bare trees and brown woods, my hopes for
snowshoeing and skating sank. We were almost at Hanover, just over
two hours from Boston, before we saw frozen ponds and mountains.
Real mountains.
</P>
<P>
   But when we arrived at Pierce's Country Inn, a red barn-shaped
house high in the hills above Hanover, it was snowy, all right. And
completely silent. The only voices crying in the wilderness were
ours.
</P>
<P>
   The inn seemed closed; no one answered our knocks. Just then, a
car pulled up and out came a man in a Dartmouth sweatshirt.
``They're probably napping,'' he said, as he pushed open the door
and began calling out for Reg and Nancy. A moment later Reg Pierce
appeared, a tall, elderly man, with sharp greyish-blue eyes and
white hair.
</P>
<P>
   He took us to our upstairs room, which was a mild shock to the
system. It had mint green walls and linoleum floors, mismatched
towels _ cream, blue, stripes _ and faded flowered comforters on
the two single beds. (Our bare-bones private bath was also painted
green.) The room's best feature was a view of a forest and a ski
hill no longer used. Luxury it was not, but it was warm and
welcoming, and for $60 a night, there was no real disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy and I are going into town for a few things,'' said
Pierce, ``but we'll be back later and I'll build a fire, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most B&AMP;Bs, there were no signs with rules posted in the
house, and if there were any rules, the Pierces never told us about
them. We felt like guests in their home.
</P>
<P>
   We headed into town to scope out the weekend's activities and
get our bearings. We parked by the large, handsome college green,
where the lines between Dartmouth and the town of Hanover blur.
Surrounding the green are Baker Library, the Hanover Inn and
Hopkins Center, administration and classroom buildings. ``Dartmouth
Row,'' along the east side, is said to be one of the finest groups
of early college buildings in the country. We took a short walk,
passing a fraternity house with men in shorts playing ``beer pong''
(a variation of table tennis in which losers must drink a cup) on
the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Then a car, covered with plywood to look like a tank and painted
black, with two students hanging out the sunroof, rumbled by.
``Death Mobile'' was scrawled on the side. Something was afoot.
Three days before, we later found out, James Wright, the president
of Dartmouth, had announced that the school was planning to make
major changes in the fraternity and sorority system. A black cloud
loomed over the light and festive Winter Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   Without enough time to get in any skiing before dinner, we took
a stroll around town and were relieved to learn that our cell
phones didn't work this far north and that Starbucks had not yet
wriggled its way into this small community.
</P>
<P>
   We went to the Hood Museum of Art to see the almost
3,000-year-old low-relief panels from the palace of King
Ashurnasirpal II in what is now Iraq. In the mid-19th century,
British archaeologist Austen Henry Layard discovered the panels and
stripped them from the palace. Dartmouth acquired 6 of the 55
panels exported to the United States. Though small, the museum,
where we paid the suggested donation of $3 each, has the solid
collection of an Ivy League teaching museum with paintings by
Rothko, Claude Lorrain and Picasso. A temporary exhibit with works
by such photographers as Cindy Sherman and Henri Cartier-Bresson
was a welcome surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we walked to Baker Library and descended into the
basement study room. There, covering the walls, are the vibrant
political murals painted by the Mexican artist Jose Clemente Orozco
in the 1930s. And you can enjoy them free.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for a drink. We crossed the main campus green in the
center of which stood a sad and pitted snow sculpture, an
all-too-appropriate symbol of this year's carnival. We ended up at
Zins, a wine bar and restaurant in the Hanover Inn, the old-time,
formal hotel on one side of the green. The menu, which had a
well-balanced list of California wines, offered some wines in
flights. I ordered _ and got carded doing so _ a flight of
sauvignon blancs: from California, France and New Zealand. Matthew
ordered one of red rhone varietals.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to eat an early dinner so we could catch the Winter
Whingding, a performance by a cappella groups at the college. We
had been told Cafe Buon Gustaio, an Italian trattoria in town, was
the restaurant of the moment, so we decided to splurge. Ninety-two
dollars and a lot of melted cheese later, I hoped the restaurant's
moment was passing.
</P>
<P>
   We moved on to the Hopkins Center, where the Rockapellas, one of
Dartmouth's women's a cappella groups, were deep into their
program. (And we were so late they let us in free.) Afterward, we
relaxed by the fire back at Pierce's Inn. The living room, its
ceiling criss-crossed with hand-hewn beams and walls covered with
family photographs, is just as tattered and mismatched as the
bedrooms and just as charming.
</P>
<P>
   There was a note from the Pierces on a yellow pad by the
staircase asking us to cross off our names to let them know we had
returned, followed by ``Sleep well.'' Which we did.
</P>
<P>
   Snow had fallen overnight. At the breakfast table, by a fire
already going strong, Pierce appeared in an apron. He offered us
blueberry or plain pancakes, English muffins or eggs. We chose the
blueberry pancakes, which were fluffy, salty and so filling I
thought for a moment about going back to bed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But we had a busy day planned. First, we stopped in at the 1929
stone building on Occom Pond that houses the Silver Fox rental
shop. Matthew had brought his own skates, so I rented a pair for
$6.
</P>
<P>
   The pond was dotted with skaters: there were mothers pushing
strollers, young kids with helmets waving hockey sticks, even dogs
cautiously roaming the ice. On the shores a handful of people were
busily carving snow sculptures for the Occom Pond party that
afternoon. The theme was dogs. There was a Snoopy atop his doghouse
and an igloo large enough to walk through.
</P>
<P>
   We skated around a few times, then rested on a beat-up sofa on
the ice. Before leaving, we rented cross-country equipment; skis,
poles and boots for 24 hours were just $26.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost time for the legendary keg-jumping competition, so
we hurried into town. When we arrived at Psi Upsilon, though, there
were no signs of kegs or skating surface, just fraternity brothers
gathered in groups in the yard. I asked what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The keg jump has been canceled this year,'' said Mike Rand,
who happened to be president of the fraternity. Instead, they were
going to have a rally. ``It should be good,'' he said.``I mean,
obviously, we'd rather be jumping kegs.''
</P>
<P>
   And we decided we'd rather be exploring Main Street, a short
manageable strip that's uncrowded even on a Saturday afternoon.
Then it was on to the Dirt Cowboy Cafe for a rest and a much-needed
dirt cowboy, an espresso topped with steamed half-and-half _ a
delicious jolt for $1.75.
</P>
<P>
   As we were leaving the cafe we could hear the cries of students
at the Psi Upsilon rally. It was time to leave town.
</P>
<P>
   We crossed the Connecticut River into Norwich, Vt., a small,
pretty town just over the border. We stopped at Dan &AMP; Whit's
General Store, on Main Street. Inside was an unexpected delight.
Fishing rods, gasoline siphons, pickles and scrapple shared shelf
space with no rhyme or reason. There were suspenders and wines from
Spain, Potato Head and kazoos. And everything was dirt cheap. We
picked up some curiosities: maple syrup, local cheese and boiled
cider.
</P>
<P>
   On our way in we had smelled beer brewing, so before we left, we
tracked it down at the Norwich Inn, which also houses Jasper
Murdock's Alehouse. Starving, we each had a rich, creamy Bally
Shannon dry stout and shared an order of grilled calamari, another
deal for $18. The menu for the main restaurant was so appealing
that we made a reservation for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   On our way back to the Pierces, we stopped along the road at a
golf course, and went cross-country skiing. The conditions were
less than perfect (somewhat icy), and I am a less-than-perfect
cross-country skier, so while Matthew glided along flawlessly, I
spent much of the outing on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   When we returned to the Norwich Inn for dinner, we were reminded
of how small a place we were in. At the next table was the same
family we had sat next to at dinner the night before. Only this
time they were dining with Dr. C. Everett Koop, the former surgeon
general who is senior scholar of the Koop Institute at the college.
He was reminiscing about Winter Carnival when he was a student at
Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have huge snow sculptures on the green,'' he said
smiling, ``They used to bring in snow from northern New Hampshire
for it.'' We eavesdropped for a while, then became distracted by
our meal, which was refreshingly good.
</P>
<P>
   I had Wellfleet oysters that tasted like a distillation of the
ocean, and ravioli filled with a puree of Vermont chevre and
sun-dried tomatoes and drizzled with a tarragon oil. Matthew had a
gently peppered lobster bisque and grilled rare venison with yellow
beets and a mustard tarragon oil. The desserts were even better. A
simple raspberry Napoleon, though way out of season, was a perfect
balance of crisp and creamy, and the caramelized crust on the Grand
Marnier creme brulee cracked like ice on a pond.
</P>
<P>
   This was just the beginning of our evening, however. We had to
hustle to the Hopkins Center again _ this time for a jazz concert
with Maria Schneider, a guest composer. After such a serious
dinner, going into a dark concert hall with relaxing music was not
the best idea. We went straight to the Dirt Cowboy Cafe for another
dirt cowboy to wake us up. There was one more event.
</P>
<P>
   We had heard through a friend about a bluegrass band playing in
the neighborhood. Arriving at the house on School Street around 11,
we blended as best we could into the crowd of baggy pants and
baseball caps, even stomaching a little Bud Light from the keg out
in the snowy alley. The band, a group of five college students,
proved to be the best entertainment of the weekend. We lasted until
midnight, then went back to the Pierces and collapsed in bed.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, Mrs. Pierce cooked us french toast and bacon
while we told her husband all that we had done during our stay,
including going to Dan &AMP; Whit's. ``That's an institution,'' he
said. ``You've been to Dan &AMP; Whit's, boy, you've seen a real
American classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Boston, we took one more crack at
cross-country skiing. This time we tried the neighbor's field,
suggested by Pierce. As we scaled the hill, an elderly woman
approached us. It was the owner of the property. ``Where you
from?'' she asked. ``New York City,'' I said. She frowned.
``Yuck.'' Just then, her husband staggered out of the woods, his
eyes teary from the cold air and a large pruner over his shoulder.
``We need more tracks on our property,'' he said. ``Go and have a
good time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of welcome we were getting used to in New
Hampshire. And so we continued on.
</P>
<P>
   Around a college green &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lodging
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pierce's Country Inn,  &LR; 261 Dogford Road, Etna, N.H., (603)
643-2997, has 12 rooms with full, half or shared baths, twin or
double beds, for $60 or $62, plus $4.75 for a full hot breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   At the  &UR; Norwich Inn,  &LR; Main Street, Norwich, Vt., (802) 649-1143,
through May doubles start at $55, suites at $109, with Continental
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Dining
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jasper Murdock's Alehouse  &LR; at the Norwich Inn is open for lunch
and dinner Tuesday to Sunday. Pub fare such as eggplant and
mozzarella ragout over penne ranges from $5.95 to $8.50. The inn's
main dining room has a more formal menu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rosey's Cafe,  &LR; 15 Lebanon Street, Hanover, (603) 643-5282, is
open daily for breakfast and lunch, serving sandwiches, baked
goods, coffee, teas, juices and unusual root beers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dirt Cowboy Cafe,  &LR;  7 South Main Street, Hanover, (603)
643-1323, has 28 kinds of coffee as well as teas, ice cream,
pastries and a juice bar. Open daily 7:30 a.m. to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Zins Wine Bistro,  &LR; Hanover Inn, Hanover, (603) 643-4300, is
open Monday to Saturday from 11:30 a.m. to 10 p.m., Sunday 1:30 to
10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Diversions
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hood Museum of Art,  &LR; Dartmouth College, Wheelock Street,
Hanover, (603) 646-2808, is open Tuesday to Saturday, 10 a.m. to 5
P.M, Wednesday to 9 p.m., Sunday noon to 5 p.m.; $3 suggested
contribution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Silver Fox Ski Touring Center  &LR; at Occom Pond, in Hanover, rents
cross-country skis, skates and snowshoes. Information: (603)
646-2440.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Hopkins Center  &LR; at Dartmouth College, Wheelock Street,
houses three major performing spaces, several small concert halls
and two galleries. Coming events include the premiere of Martha
Clarke's ``Vers la Flamme'' on April 2 (tickets, $20.50) and the
jazz singer Cassandra Wilson on April 13 ($18.50). Call (603)
646-2422 for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
