<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6351 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NEIGHBORHOOD-SITE     03-03 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NEIGHBORHOOD-SITES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLACES FOR NEIGHBORS TO GATHER ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM R. LONG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For staying in touch with neighbors around the corner
or even next door, it may come to this: the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   A Denver company called E.Central is offering neighborhoods in
11 metropolitan areas access to an Internet tool that residents can
use to communicate among themselves and with local governments.
</P>
<P>
   The system, called Neighborhood Link (www.neighborhoodlink.com),
sets up online neighborhood Web sites that include Web pages for
the neighborhood association and for other groups and individuals,
as well as areas for notices and announcements, newsletters,
interactive discussions and links to various city officials and
departments. It's all easy to use and free.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood Link's oldest site, which opened in October, has
been set up to serve 1,186 neighborhoods in Denver. There are also
sites for the Portland, Ore., area, which also has a site for
Vancouver-Clark County, Wash.; Sacramento, Calif.; San Diego;
Colorado Springs; Minneapolis-St. Paul; Phoenix; Tucson, Ariz.; San
Antonio; the Tampa Bay, Fla., area, which also has a site for
Clearwater-St. Petersburg, and Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The sites are catching on slowly. Ted Pinkowitz, president and
chief executive of E.Central, said that in Denver, 285 neighborhood
associations had begun using their Web pages and that online
discussions were going on at 100 neighborhood sites. Among all the
Web sites, there are discussions at 320 neighborhood pages, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   E.Central, which also has a Denver city guide on line and is an
Internet service provider, plans to provide the neighborhood
service in more than 20 markets by the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind Neighborhood Link is not unique. Local
neighborhood associations and other civic organizations in many
cities use free Web sites provided by nonprofit community networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tons of them,'' said Bruce T. Henderson, director of
the New Media Center at the University of Colorado at Boulder. The
Seattle Community Network (www.scn.org), for example, lists more
than 100 sites in the Neighborhoods section of its prize-winning
Web site. Such nonprofit networks, often known as freenets, are
commonly financed by grants. A directory of freenets around the
world can be found at www.lights.com/freenet.
</P>
<P>
   But Neighborhood Link differs from the freenets in that it
intends to make money from advertising. ``It's really significant
that they're looking at local advertising because that's really the
franchise of newspapers,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Neighborhood Link's grass-roots contents will attract
enough viewers, and therefore advertisers, to thrive is an open
question, Henderson said. ``It's hard to tell these days what's
going to catch on and what's not,'' he said. Success may depend on
whether volunteers in neighborhood organizations keep the sites
current with content that can draw visitors, he said. Volunteers
called neighborhood coordinators help Neighborhood Link get its
sites up and keep them running.
</P>
<P>
   Six sponsors, including AT&AMP;T and the Conoco oil company, are
advertising on the Denver site. Each paid $30,000 to get its banner
advertisements and links on the neighborhood Web pages for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkowitz's goal, of course, is to draw viewers to attract
advertisers. When the numbers warrant it, Neighborhood Link will
charge much more for advertisements and links than sponsors now
pay, Pinkowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Hudson, a spokesman for Mayor Wellington E. Webb, said
Denver and other local governments thought Neighborhood Link was a
good idea. ``The city is very welcoming of the concept,'' Hudson
said, ``because it's just going to revolutionize the way
neighborhoods and organizations can communicate with the community
and with themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that in poorer neighborhoods, only a small
percentage of homes had computers with Internet access. But he said
the city's 22 branch libraries had computer kiosks where people
could log on to Neighborhood Link. ``I think people will use it,
and they'll use it as a great source of information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan DuBois, chairman of a Denver neighborhood umbrella
organization called Interneighborhood Cooperation, has been an
active advocate of Neighborhood Link.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a tremendous idea,'' DuBois said. He said the
network made it easy for his organization to disseminate
information to neighborhoods about zoning changes, new ordinances
or dealing with the city government.
</P>
<P>
   But like many of the sites in Denver's Neighborhood Link system,
Southbridge IIs is just starting to be promoted. Karen Walczak, the
neighborhood coordinator for that site, said most residents did not
learn about the site until December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had good response from people who have looked at it,''
Ms. Walczak said. ``I think people will use the notice board, and
probably the discussion area.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many homes in Ms. Walczak's neighborhood do not have
Internet access, she predicted that the percentage would rise
rapidly. ``In a couple of years, so many people will be on the Web,
this will be a great thing to have,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
