<HEADER>
A6360 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CHIP-DRAWINGS-NYT     03-03 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CHIP-DRAWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATURES ON THE HEAD OF A CHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla.)   (af)  
 By BRUCE HEADLAM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michael Davidson first started photographing silicon chips
through a microscope 10 years ago, he wanted ``to promote circuitry
as an art form.'' Four years ago, his microscope excavated another
kind of art from the microprocessor's metallic layers: a drawing of
Where's Waldo.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought it was an example of reverse
engineering,'' said Davidson, a research scientist with the Natural
Magnetic High Field Laboratory in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he had come across a longstanding, clandestine practice
of chip designers: impressing a microscopic, non-functional cartoon
or drawing into the surface of the chip. Since then, Davidson has
photographed more than 60 chip designs.
</P>
<P>
   In December, he made his gallery of photomicrographs, including
images of lizards, buffaloes, cartoon characters and one of the
space shuttle, available through his laboratory's Web site
(microscopy.fsu.edu).
</P>
<P>
   ``We all did it,'' said Dan Zuras, a chip designer at
Hewlett-Packard who has two designs on the site. ``Eighteen or 20
years ago, they were all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the designs were etched into the uppermost, metallic
layers of the chip, creating the impression of an image in relief
on the chip's surface. The cartoons grew out of the ritual of
having chip designers sign or initial the chips they had worked on.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Zuras drew a roadrunner on a then-fast
Hewlett-Packard 1AK9 chip in 1982. ``Back in those days, I knew
where every one of the 153,000 transistors were on the chip. I knew
it so well that I signed it, like writing your name in wet concrete
after you've poured a driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chips featured inside jokes or references. One of
Davidson's favorites is The Con Artist, a drawing of a shady street
peddler hawking contraband watches, chosen because, according to
chip designers at Hewlett-Packard, the company had used inferior
clock circuitry on the low-cost microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson, a chip designer, once contributed a drawing of
his chow chow Nikki to a MIPS Technologies chip, the R4000. ``I've
never seen a chip with more graffiti on it. There must have been
100 pieces, mostly names and initials.'' So why did he draw Nikki?
``Well, I loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, some chip companies, like Intel, have banned the chip
graffiti because the designs can interfere with the checking
process.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kuhn, a mask layout designer at Silicon Graphics and
well-known chip artist who drew the Where's Waldo image, hopes that
the craft retains its underground quality, within limits of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an official mandate. But I wouldn't put in
anything that would offend the people on my team or would be in
poor taste, although I've been tempted,'' he said, adding ``I don't
have a grant from the NEA or anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1632EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-TRUST04-cox     03-03 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-TRUST04-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BABBITT WARNED TO CLEAN UP INDIAN TRUST PROBLEMS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington category
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Displaying photos of Bureau of Indian Affairs
records piled in trash bags and beside mop buckets, Sen. Ben
Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., warned Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt on Wednesday to clean up ``the Indian trust funds mess''
that has tied up billions of dollars owed to tribes and individual
native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be clear that the money in these accounts -- or that
is supposed to be in these accounts -- is Indian money that has
been entrusted to the United States,'' said Campbell, a member of
the Northern Cheyenne tribe and the Senate's only native American.
``It is not federal money.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district judge has already found Babbitt and Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin in contempt of court over a ``shocking
pattern of deception'' and a failure to produce documents sought by
Indian account holders who are suing the government for
mismanagement of the funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to re-litigate issues that are properly before
the court,'' said Campbell, chairing a joint hearing of the
Committees on Indian Affairs and Energy and Natural Resources.
``But there is clearly massive mismanagement in the Bureau of
Indian Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying after being threatened with a subpoena, Babbitt
promised to work with Congress and the court on a problem he said
dates to the General Allotment Act of 1887. The law divided Indian
lands into individual and tribal parcels and put the property into
trusts administered by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have apologized to the court ...and intend to do all that
we can to be fully responsive to the court's orders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   The contempt citation by U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth came
in a class action suit led by Elouise Cobell, a Blackfeet tribe
descendant. The suit charged that native Americans have been denied
information and funds about revenues from their land because of
federal mismanagement of the trusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank trust departments throughout the United States are
responsible every day for collecting, managing and disbursing
hundreds of billions of funds to those who put their trust in
them,'' said Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, chairman of the Energy
and Natural Resources Committee. ``Why, then, can't American
Indians expect the same level of accountability from their
trustees?''
</P>
<P>
   Murkowski and other Republicans on the committees said the
Interior Department should concede it cannot manage the trusts and
should turn the job over to outside experts.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no excuses,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R- Idaho. ``Why
can't we be smart enough to hire the right people to do the job?''
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trusts for tribes, the Bureau of Indian Affairs
oversees more than 340,000 individual trust fund accounts. Those
individual beneficiaries complain they can't find out what lands
they own and what funds they are owed from leases for grazing,
farming, oil, mineral or timber rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are billions of dollars at stake,'' said Campbell. ``The
(Interior) Department's Tribal Reconciliation Project was unable to
reconcile some $2.4 billion in tribal funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the $2.4 billion hasn't been ``lost,'' but is stuck
in the federal treasury because documents that show who's entitled
to trust benefits have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Money in the bank won't buy him a car if he has no access to his
money, Campbell retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the problem is complex because -- after five
generations -- the original trusts are now jointly owned by
thousands of individual Indians. He showed an account belonging to
Kevin Gover, the Assistant Interior Secretary for Indian Affairs
and a Pawnee descendent, with a gross value of 36 cents and annual
revenue of 7 cents.
</P>
<P>
   It costs taxpayers $35 a year to administer the account, Babbitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said the Interior Department should pay off
beneficiaries with tiny interests and close the accounts. They
offered to support any needed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The larger problem of sorting out the trust problem was
addressed in 1994 with the enactment of the Indian Trust Fund
Management Reform Act. That law called for a ``special trustee'' to
take charge of the effort. However, the special trustee, Paul
Homan, abruptly resigned in protest in January after Babbitt
ordered his office reorganized.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying at the hearing on Wednesday, Homan said the
reorganization deprived him of ``the authority and the resources''
to do his duties so he had no choice but to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the Department of Interior can no longer be
trusted to keep and produce trust records,'' he testified. He said
Congress should set up an independent agency to manage the Indian
trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt has asked Congress for $100 million next year, a $60
million increase from this year, to work on the accounts. However,
Republicans on the committees said the Interior Department has not
complied with the 1994 law to deal with the problems and increasing
funding might be ``throwing good money after bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
