<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6367 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DC-DINING-2TAK     03-03 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DC-DINING-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINING OUT, NOT JUST FOR THE FOOD, IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `d' code)  
 (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Overheard in a New York restaurant: ``Do you think the chef will
tell us where he gets his quail?''
</P>
<P>
   Overheard in a Washington restaurant: ``What are the chances of
Hillary taking on Giuliani?''
</P>
<P>
   When New Yorkers go out to eat, they go for the food. When
Washingtonians go out to eat, they generally spend the evening
rehashing current events. Out-of-town visitors come either to see
the Capitol and the White House or to lobby their occupants; no one
comes to Washington just to eat. Perhaps as a result, there are
good, even very good restaurants, but none that qualify as either
incomparable or ultra-hip.
</P>
<P>
   The up side is that the $25 first course is almost unheard of in
Washington's restaurants. The best and grandest this
price-conscious city has to offer cost around $200 for two with
wine and tip.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Washington is in the midst of a serious restaurant
boom, and some new places are so hot that the only weekend
reservation you can get is at 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   If you are transfixed by the inner workings of a fine kitchen,
you might choose the casual elegance of Michel Richard Citronelle
in Georgetown. If you want to see where journalists and federal
officials _ past and present _ hang out, try Ardeo. Should you
desire an evening surrounded by silk damask draperies, where voices
don't rise above a murmur, Lespinasse is definitely the choice. But
if you long for the hipness of New York or L.A., the closest you
will come to it is D.C. Coast, where the best, and maybe only, way
to communicate with your dinner companions is via your cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Richard Citronelle
</P>
<P>
   Michel Richard's sense of fun, which makes his food so enticing,
is part of the charm of his recently redesigned restaurant,
Citronelle. A subdued changing light show plays against the walls
so that the room is never static. Its focal point is the glassed-in
open kitchen; one recent customer was chided by his companion for
paying more attention to the goings-on in the kitchen than to their
conversation. If the kitchen fascinates you, ask for a table in
front of the windows, or better yet, gather a group and reserve the
chef's table in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many restaurant menus where the descriptions of the
food are endless, Richard's menu is deceptively simple. The
sensibility is French: the flavors and surprising textures of his
creations unfold as you eat them. Crunchy shrimp as a first course
are coated with shreds of phyllo called kataifi, the crispness
delightfully contrasted with little beads of pearl pasta and a
velvety sauce of red pepper with a touch of lemon grass. The
intensity of the porcini mushrooms is perfectly modulated by the
cauliflower in a creamy soup punctuated with bits of cooked
cauliflower. Richard's rendition of seared foie gras combines the
expected _ apple _ with the unexpected: a tiny portion of Belgian
endive cole slaw mixed with the apple and an acidic counterpoint,
black bean balsamic sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Richard's playfulness is a rustic dish like chicken
in a pot, the broth and the meltingly tender chicken suffused with
the fragrance and flavor of black truffles. A medallion of rare
tuna crusted with black peppercorns is topped with a napoleon of
mashed potatoes between layers of paper-thin disks of toasted
brioche.
</P>
<P>
   After looking over the wine list because it is well chosen,
extensive and expensive, turn to the sommelier, Mark Slater. This
is one of the rare restaurants where it is worthwhile letting him
choose for you. That night he selected a 1996 Witness Tree Vintage
Select Pinot Noir from Oregon for $65.
</P>
<P>
   Even though each table is served a plate of delightful petits
fours after dinner, we shared Richard's delectably whimsical
version of Reese's peanut butter cups, a mousse of peanut butter
and chocolate in a tart topped with a croquembouche of puffed cocoa
coated in chocolate. Every kid should be so lucky. Or try an
intensely citrus lemon tart with lemon basil.
</P>
<P>
   Since I am a devoted fan of Citronelle, I am known there, but
legions of Washington eaters agree that despite being one of the
city's most expensive restaurant, it is a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Lespinasse
</P>
<P>
   This is Washington's special-occasion restaurant; special
because the food now lives up to the resplendent Belle Epoque
setting. It is a grand room with pale yellow leather chairs and
blue carpet, chandeliers and a massive bouquet of flowers.
Lespinasse appeals particularly to those who like to dress up for
dinner. The rewards are fine service, very good food and, above
all, serenity. How delightful that your nearest neighbor cannot
hear a word you are saying.
</P>
<P>
   Here you definitely want to concentrate on what is being put in
front of you, the contemporary French creations of Sandro Gamba,
who has worked in France's best kitchens, where he earned his own
Michelin star.
</P>
<P>
   Gamba arrived in Washington this fall at the age of 28 to take
over Lespinasse, a sister of the much acclaimed restaurant of the
same name in New York's St. Regis Hotel. The original Washington
version failed to attract a following and closed for two months
this summer. The new chef is making people sit up and take notice
with his modern approach to French food.
</P>
<P>
   While Gamba learns his way around American ingredients, the menu
has been kept small. A shellfish ragout of perfectly poached
seafood is subtly flavored with ginger and chervil. Turbot, coated
with a turbot mousse, is splendid with a sauce of dried figs and
olive oil. The foie gras, crisp on the outside, melting at the
center and drizzled with a port wine reduction, is as fine a
rendition as you could want. When white truffles come back in
season next fall, see if you can order the ambrosial white truffle
risotto.
</P>
<P>
   A symphonic arrangement of baby lamb provides a tiny rack, thin
slices of leg and loin and braised strips bathed in a lamb jus
perfumed with Moroccan spices. The roast squab is an imaginative
plate: a boned leg stuffed like a sausage, one fillet poached and
one roasted. It is served with a beet salad and truffled
tortellini.
</P>
<P>
   Among the desserts, my favorite was a poached glazed fig perched
on a paper-thin crust of crepe resting on plum compote with a
garnish of honey ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Lespinasse may have one of the best wine lists in Washington,
with 7,500 bottles. Prices start at $25 for the house wine, but
they climb rapidly from there. We had a 1997 Acacia Carneros Pinot
Noir for $47.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   D.C. Coast
</P>
<P>
   Even if you didn't like the food at D.C. Coast _ yes, yes, the
only water in Washington is the Potomac River _ you would have to
admire what the owners have done to restore the first Art Deco
skyscraper built in Washington. Designed for a bank, it had the
misfortune to be finished just before the 1929 stock market crash
and lived in ignominy as space for Western Union and McDonald's.
For 70 years, no one saw the soaring two-story-high ceiling on 14th
and K Streets. As business moved west, the street-floor space of
the building was vacant for years. Then, in the mid-'90s,
professional offices moved east again and the building regained its
former splendor.
</P>
<P>
   Even before you enter this grand space, a 10-foot statue of a
Greek mermaid on a 4-foot pedestal lets you know that fish is
important here. She is flanked by two fabulous 1930s bullet-shaped
frosted glass chandeliers, topped with lights that look like
vanilla ice cream cones. Huge oval mirrors above the bar make
people-watching easy from any corner. And they are worth watching,
especially at the bar, divided from the dining room by an
undulating wall.
</P>
<P>
   The bar is what makes D.C. Coast Washington's restaurant of the
moment. Anything goes, from jeans with cuffs to silver sequined
dresses. The smoke from the bar, which can include cigars after
9:30, along with the din, add nothing to the dining experience, so
if you go for the food instead of the scene, ask for a table on the
mezzanine.
</P>
<P>
   Like the restaurant itself, Jeff Tunks' food is writ large, and
portions fill the oversized plates. His dishes are intensely
flavored with accents of the Pacific, the Gulf of Mexico and the
Chesapeake Bay. Those that work are well balanced, like the fresh
and light Tahitian-style tuna tartare served in a coconut with
deep-fried wonton wrappers or the moist halibut coated with a
woodsy crust of porcini mushrooms served atop wonderfully garlicky
mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   In season don't miss the chef's version of a regional specialty:
crab cake and a crisp soft-shell crab are served with corn, pickled
okra relish and a spicy lemon butter. There are good meat dishes,
too, such as the crusted barbecued lamb shank with lusciously
creamy stone-ground grits and the tender piece of rib eye. Those
who have room should go directly to a combination made in heaven:
bananas and chocolate with a rum caramel sauce; second choice is a
classic quivering creme brulee.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Tunks goes overboard with sweetness in savory dishes,
as in the wild rice hash that was served with smoked quail. And
sometimes the dishes are not as refined as they should be, such as
the Chinese lacquered duck in a Peking pancake.
</P>
<P>
   A plus is the wine list, fairly priced with most bottles between
$30 and $35. A Ravenswood Lodi Zinfandel was $31. The service is
pleasant, not annoyingly familiar, and you get a sense of what
young and hip means in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ardeo
</P>
<P>
   If you go early to Ardeo, something between a neighborhood and
destination restaurant, you will see the government and
journalistic officialdom that used to run Washington. By 8 p.m.,
they have been replaced by those who make Washington run right now.
(Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Vernon Jordan are among
the patrons.)
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Park, the pleasant residential neighborhood where
turn-of-the-century officials decamped to escape the summer's
oppressive humidity, has a thriving restaurant scene, accessible
without a car because it is a block from a Metro stop.
</P>
<P>
   The air at Ardeo is always filled with tantalizing buzz words,
overheard bits of conversation: ``Sidney,'' ``Linda Tripp,''
``Kennedy's office.'' If you go for the scene, ask to be seated on
the first floor; if you want to talk, ask for the second.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome restaurant is in a long narrow space that seats
140, hidden behind a nondescript store front. The decor is retro,
the walls hung with stylized 1940s paintings, black and white
drawings and Art Deco fixtures. The food is anything but retro, and
it works more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   To take the edge off your appetite, the waiter appears with
superb bread from the bakery next door, served with an addictive
garlicky bean dip.
</P>
<P>
   The chef, Fred Przyborowski, likes to add meat to his fish
dishes, which makes them much richer than expected. Oxtail-salsify
ragout intensifies the sweetness of the seared scallops. The beer
in which the tender and plump mussels are steamed adds a pleasingly
malty accent. Foie gras is its usual buttery self, served with thin
crisp-fried potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuna marinated in mirin, the Japanese wine, is cooked just the
way I like it: seared on the outside and rare in the center. And
you can smell the lovely aroma of a perfectly cooked pasta sauced
with an intensely flavored mixture of mushrooms even before it
arrives at the table.
</P>
<P>
   The dessert of choice is praline semifreddo with dried cranberry
and balsamic vinegar sauce. The contrast of the cold sweet
creaminess and the sharpness of the sauce make it a delightfully
indulgent end to a meal.
</P>
<P>
   Portions are large; the prices are relatively low; the wine list
_ we had another Ravenswood zinfandel, this one a 1996 Vintners
Blend for $27 _ is reasonable, with many selections in the
$30-to-$40 range and a fair number of half bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Ardeo offers an opportunity to see Washington at play, or as
close to play as this town ever gets.
</P>
<P>
   Bill of fare
</P>
<P>
   All major credit cards are accepted. Prices are for dinner for
two with a bottle of wine, tip and tax.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Richard Citronelle, Latham Hotel, 3000 M Street, NW;
(202) 625-2150. Dinner nightly, lunch Monday through Friday.
Smoking in the upstairs bar only. $200.
</P>
<P>
   Lespinasse, Carlton Hotel (scheduled to be renamed the St. Regis
in April), 923 16th St., NW at K Street; (202) 879-6900. Dinner
Tuesday through Saturday, lunch Tuesday through Friday. $175.
Smoking in the adjoining library lounge only.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. Coast, 1401 K St., NW at 14th Street; (202) 216-5988;
Dinner Monday through Saturday, lunch Monday through Friday.
Smoking at the bar only. $110.
</P>
<P>
   Ardeo, 3311 Connecticut Ave., NW, a block from the Cleveland
Park Metro stop on the Red Line; (202) 244-6750. Dinner nightly;
Sunday brunch. Smoking at the bar only. $95.
</P>
</TEXT>
