<HEADLINE>
STUDY ATTACKS CALIFORNIA'S `THREE-STRIKES' LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new study says that California's
``three-strikes'' law is not responsible for the 37 percent
reduction in crime throughout the state over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Tuesday by the nonprofit Justice Policy
Institute in San Francisco, contradicts a report released last week
by California Secretary of State Bill Jones lauding the law.
</P>
<P>
   The competing findings were made public just as legislators in
Sacramento are rethinking the 1994 law, which allows nonviolent
offenders to be sentenced to a minimum of 25 years, and up to life
in prison, on their third conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In California, convictions for property crimes, such as
shoplifting or bicycle theft, can count as a third strike. Most
states with similar laws require the third offense to be a violent
crime before a criminal can get a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Policy Institute study notes that crime decreased at
a greater rate in San Francisco, where comparatively few
three-strikes cases were prosecuted, than in six other urban
counties that used the law more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco registered its great drop in crime even though
it was not enforcing three-strikes as it could have,'' said Dan
Macallair, a co-author of the Justice Policy Institute study. ``We
did a county-by-county comparison that shows three-strikes is not
responsible for the drop in the state's crime rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that felons in their 30s and 40s were eight
times more likely to be sentenced under the three-strikes law than
those in their 20s. More than 40,000 people have been convicted of
second and third offenses, a quarter of the state's prison
population. About 4,400 of them were sentenced to 25-years-to-life.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, author of the law, said, ``The numbers pretty much speak
for themselves.'' He accused the institute of turning the
statistics ``around to make it appear that three-strikes is
ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Jones said that in the five years since the
three-strikes law was enacted, fewer crimes were being committed,
and fewer new inmates were going to prison while more career
criminals remained behind bars longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three-strikes has revolutionized the way we combat crime in
this country,'' Jones said. ``By closing the revolving prison door,
we have created an effective deterrent to crime that has helped
reduce the crime rate in California by 38 percent in just five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he would fight any effort to modify the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no equivalent five-year period in the history of
California where we've seen this dramatic a reduction in crime,''
he said. ``The message of deterrence to the repeat criminals has
gotten through.''
</P>
<P>
   But Macallair and other criminologists said that robust economic
growth, demographic changes and a decline in the popularity of
crack cocaine had driven the state's decrease in crime.
</P>
<P>
   The law was overwhelmingly passed by the Legislature in 1994,
signed on an emergency basis by former Gov. Pete Wilson and
ratified by the voters by a margin of 72 percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, has introduced a bill to
require a third conviction be a violent or serious felony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6373 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GAME-SHARK-NYT &LR;      03-03 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GAME-SHARK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEATING DEATH HAS NEVER BEEN EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheating is big business in video games. To Interact, the
company that manufactures Game Shark ``enhancement devices,'' it's
worth $40 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Interact is the fifth-largest video game company in America. It
makes no free-standing hardware. It doesn't publish a single
software title. It has, however, sold two million pieces of plastic
and silicon that plug into the back of a Sony Playstation or the
cartridge slot of a Nintendo 64 to give the player invincibility,
extra weapons, superpowers and access to hidden areas and bonus
levels.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to fight the boss on the 17th level (and brag about
it in the schoolyard), you don't have to invest 30 hours to master
the game. Just plug in a Game Shark, which contains hundreds of
cheat codes for all the hottest games in one package.
</P>
<P>
   From a technological standpoint, cheat codes are nothing new.
The factory that manufactures Game Sharks, in Manchester, England,
was cranking out similar devices for the Commodore Amiga in 1979. A
device called the Game Genie turbocharged thousands of eight-bit
Nintendo consoles in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Game Shark's cheat codes function on the same principle as its
predecessors. But it can do what early devices could not because
the world of consumer electronics has changed radically.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference can be summed up in two words: cheap
memory. As any PC owner knows, the price of computer memory has
taken a nose dive since the 1980s. Back then, it was much too
expensive to put memory chips in a game peripheral, so there was no
room to store codes.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to use a cheat code on your Nintendo machine with
a Game Genie, you had to enter it manually every time you played,
and the device could handle only one code at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The Game Shark comes with hundreds of codes and a user-friendly
software interface because four-megabyte memory chips cost $8.
Cheap memory is what made beepers and cellular phones and
Tamagotchis economically viable, and it makes the Game Shark a more
robust and profitable device.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap memory also makes stored information a more important part
of the experience. People buy a Game Shark for the cheat codes
stored on it, not for the raw device.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Interact is an information vendor. So the
information has to be current. ``Previous manufacturers of cheat
devices treated them like toys,'' said Todd Hays, Interact's chief
executive. ``They made them as cheaply as possible, in one big
batch, and shipped them all at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that just wasn't going to work _ you've got to be
able to promote these things year-round. So we invested in a help
line, an 800 number for codes, a 900 number for really advanced
codes. We invented Web site support. And we always ship very fresh
product _ we treat it like a loaf of bread. If there's a hot new
game coming out tomorrow, the Game Sharks we're shipping today will
have a whole new fresh stash of codes.''
</P>
<P>
   Generating those codes involves a squad of full-time hackers who
crank video games through high-powered computers and software
algorithms. ``On a television,'' Hayes said, ``all you can see is
the result of the programming. What we see is a million lines of
actual code, and we have seasoned hackers that go through and look
for aberrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hacking stations are hooked up to a logic analyzer, and
we've written software for it _ find all locations in the game
where life equals zero. Boom, at the end of the game, and here and
here and here _ these are all the places where you might die. Then
you go and look at the code, and you might find a way you can avoid
that place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find all sorts of things. We even find things that the
software company never meant for you to see, places you can't get
to from normal game play. Sometimes developers put things in there,
like the Tiger Woods game that Electronic Arts published _ there
were some lines of code buried in there that produced a pretty
offensive scene from `South Park.' Electronic Arts found out about
it and recalled the product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare for something like that to get past quality control,
but it happens _ a lot of these programmers are so creative and so
artistic, and they're cooped up in these little rooms, and it's a
challenge for them to get something past their boss. It's an
anti-Establishment, rebel thing to do _ let's see if the bug police
can find it.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the hardware hackers at Interact are the ultimate
gamers, uncovering everything that is meant to be found, as well as
a few things that are meant to stay buried. Software, by its very
nature, is a palimpsest _ there are always layers that no one is
supposed to see. A piece of hardware loaded with cheat codes is a
lens that reveals those layers.
</P>
<P>
   The larger question is whether the use of this device qualifies
as cheating. What a Game Shark allows you to do is have more
extensive access, at your discretion, to the software you already
own.
</P>
<P>
   In game play, that is called cheating. But if you buy a book and
skip to page 200, or rent a movie and fast forward to your favorite
scene, does that count as cheating? If you're doing scientific
research and discover a technique that yields vast quantities of
high-quality information at blinding speed, does that qualify as
cheating?
</P>
<P>
   If the object is to gain knowledge of a system, which is the
ultimate object of any computer game, then what separates cheating
from learning? And if using a Game Shark isn't cheating, then what
is?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Hayes said. ``That's a good question. I
suppose if you changed the game code itself. Like, there's another
company that makes devices, and their claim to fame most recently
was a nude Lara Croft code for Tomb Raider. We went in and
investigated this, and it turned out that there was no nude Lara
Croft in the game, that what they'd actually done was take skin
tone from other parts of the game and paste it over her bathing
suit so that she (italics)looked(end italics) nude. But she was
never actually nude. And they are currently being sued by Eidos,
the publisher, for intellectual property infringement. If
something's buried in the game, I'll unbury it. But I'm not going
to make something up or interfere with the integrity of the code.''
</P>
<P>
   In a medium subject to infinite manipulation, outright
fabrication is still a no-no. Cheating may be ill defined, but it's
fairly easy to spot an outright lie. Look for the topless virtual
celebrity, then check for neck seams.
</P>
<P>
   Game Shark; for Sony Playstation and Nintendo 64, $49.99; for
Game Boy, $29.99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
