<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AND GOP JOCKEY OVER LEGISLATIVE AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Republicans battled Wednesday
over the post-impeachment agenda for Congress _ a struggle pitting
Democrats' bid to use the federal budget surplus to rescue Social
Security and Medicare against a Republican plan for an
across-the-board tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetorical skirmish flared just eight days after a
bipartisan summit between the president and congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton traveled to Capitol Hill to rally with Vice President Al
Gore, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., at a meeting of House and
Senate Democrats to proclaim Democratic unity behind an agenda
dubbed ``Families First.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' new-found unity stems in part from Democratic
solidarity in preventing the GOP-led Senate from removing Clinton
from office after impeachment by the House in the sex-and-cover-up
scandal involving former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' agenda calls for federal aid to modernize
schools, cut class size, expand patients' rights within health
maintenance organizations, hiking the minimum wage and offering
targeted tax cuts to parents home with children and relatives
caring for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had been ``encouraged to see some of the
Republicans backing away from the irresponsible across-the-board
tax cut that is too costly _ in favor of standing with us for
targeted tax cuts benefiting mostly middle-class working
families.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton cautioned that ``strong differences'' remain between
the rival parties' legislative agendas, adding: ``We must resolve
them in a way that benefits the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke just hours before Lewinsky was scheduled to break
14 months of public silence to appear on a prime-time interview
with Barbara Walters on ABC News' program ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance on Capitol Hill at the Library of Congress,
Clinton challenged Republicans to set aside 15 percent of the
projected $4.4 trillion federal budget surplus over the next 15
years to rescue the financially-ailing Medicare system that
provides federal health care insurance coverage to millions of
elderly Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already won GOP backing for his proposal to devote
62 percent of the budget surplus to bolstering the Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held out the prospect of a tax cut but only after there
is bipartisan agreement to funnel 77 percent of the surplus to
protect the solvency of Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Clinton said, the White House and Republicans in Congress
``can have an honest and principled disagreement about how much and
what kind of tax cut'' to finance with the remainder of the
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who hopes to succeed Clinton in the White House, jovially
denied that the gathering had campaign overtones. ``Now this is not
an election rally,'' Gore observed. ``This is the beginning of a
congressional term.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders underscored their different priorities in
separate appearances on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., tweaked Democrats for their attempt to seize the
advantage in setting the agenda for the GOP-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see that three months after the Republicans
announced their agenda, the Democrats are getting around to doing
the same,'' Lott's spokesman said. ``We have already made
significant progress on our agenda, which emphasized education,
strengthening national security, among others.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas, held a rally
with Reps. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., and Rick
Lazio, R-N.Y., to drum up support for the across-the-board tax cuts
favored by some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said Republicans plan to hold town meetings and rallies
across the country before the April 15 deadline for filing federal
income tax returns in order to alert taxpayers that they are
bearing ``the highest-ever'' tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said House Republican leaders favor devoting the bulk of
the federal budget surplus to shoring up Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Armey added: ``But we strongly disagree with him over what to do
with the remaining money. If we don't return this money, President
Clinton will spend it on more big government.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Republicans hope the American people will view the
projected budget surplus as ``an overcharge'' by the federal
government that they want returned to them in the form of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders agreed Tuesday to push legislation that protects
Social Security payroll tax revenues from being used for anything
other than strengthening the pension system or paying down the $5.3
trillion federal debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
