<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR THE BEST GAME? HERE'S ONE FOR EVERY DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (js) 
 By CHRIS ANDERSON   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Joe Garagiola was in New York one day, and was
driving to Yogi Berra's house when he got lost. Garagiola stopped
at a pay phone and called Berra for directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know exactly where you are,'' Berra assured Garagiola. ``So
don't go the other way, come toward me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And somehow,'' Garagiola said years later when retelling the
story, ``I always found my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of like finding spring training stadiums, really. You
don't always need a map to lead you to the treasure.
</P>
<P>
   To find McKechnie Field in Bradenton, for example, just look for
the old stadium that makes games feel like county fairs.
</P>
<P>
   To find Charlotte County Stadium in Port Charlotte, look for the
alligator in the pond that awaits home runs.
</P>
<P>
   To find Chain of Lakes Stadium in Winter Haven, follow the scent
of the orange groves nearby.
</P>
<P>
   To find Al Lang Stadium in St. Petersburg, look for the boats
sailing on the bay in the background.
</P>
<P>
   To find Grant Field in Dunedin, listen for loudness tucked
inside a sleepy city.
</P>
<P>
   What if you could take off for a month and see a Grapefruit
League game every day?
</P>
<P>
   We have devised the ultimate road trip for baseball fans. The
Last Great Adventure. The best games each day in every stadium from
Orlando to Fort Myers, beginning from the first day of play on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And remember, if you get lost looking for Legends Field in
Tampa, stop the car, close your eyes and listen.
</P>
<P>
   That way, you'll be certain to hear Berra, the former Yankee
manager and great philosopher, say:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to the fork in the road, take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Toronto vs. New York Yankees at Tampa, 1:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The defending World Series champions remain intact, and Legends
Field is as good as the Yankees are. Followed by dinner in Ybor
City, there is no better way to start spring.
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   Detroit vs. Pittsburgh at Bradenton, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' 31st spring opener at McKechnie Field, and spring
training's version of Wrigley Field makes watching the Pirates and
Tigers not nearly so painful.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore vs. Minnesota at Fort Myers, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Albert Belle played his first game with the White
Sox in this stadium. After the game, Belle claimed he was a changed
man. Oh well. Maybe he makes the trip with his new team, the
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   Texas vs. Boston at Fort Myers, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, City of Palms Park was the talk of spring
training. It remains a great setting with its towering palm trees
and definitely worth seeing. So are two playoff teams from last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Monday
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay vs. Texas at Port Charlotte, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Arrive early, because Juan Gonzalez (Texas) and Jose Canseco
(Tampa Bay) taking batting practice on the same field is one of the
great shows in spring training. Arguably the best stadium to catch
BP homers at.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees vs. Houston at Kissimmee, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Osceola County Stadium does not really stand out, but the Astros
and Yankees do. Last year's World Series champions vs. the NL
Central champions. The only downside is that Randy Johnson left
Houston for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, March 10
</P>
<P>
   Houston vs. Atlanta at Lake Buena Vista, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Sports Complex has 30 sports venues on its site,
including what is the most impressive new stadium in spring
training. Watch a game between two division champions and then eat
at the All-Star cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, March 11
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis vs. Kansas City at Haines City, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Here it is. The game you've been waiting for. The only chance,
within a reasonable drive, to see the Cardinals' new shortstop,
Edgar Renteria. Oh yeah, and maybe some guy named McGwire. Who
knows if he'll make the trip, but it's worth the effort to find
out.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, March 12
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland vs. Detroit at Lakeland, 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   No team has trained in one Florida city longer than the Tigers
have in Lakeland.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, March 13
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles vs. Cleveland at Winter Haven, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Say 5,000 fans show up for this game and pay an average of $7
per ticket. That's $35,000. It would take 2,857 spring games to
equal Kevin Brown's $100 million contract with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, March 14
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees vs. Atlanta at Lake Buena Vista, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so spring games are virtually meaningless, and the
superstars don't always play, but the Yankees and the Braves could
be the 1999 World Series preview.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, March 15
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees vs. Cincinnati at Sarasota, 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The first time the Yankees play the Reds in Sarasota, and a sure
sellout at Ed Smith Stadium. Last year's game was rained out. Greg
Vaughn, recently traded to Cincinnati from San Diego, is the
Grapefruit League's newest attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, March 16
</P>
<P>
   Toronto vs. New York Yankees at Tampa, 7:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens against the Yankees in a night game at Legends
Field would be one of the spring's highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, March 17
</P>
<P>
   New York Mets vs. Houston at Kissimmee, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   New York catcher Mike Piazza used to hit in this stadium as a
Florida State League player making a minor-league salary. Now, with
a new $90 million contract, he could buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, March 18
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta vs. Toronto at Dunedin, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto has been unhappy at Dunedin Stadium for years, but it
still has a certain charm. With its restaurants and shops, a walk
down Main Street before the game is worth the time.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, March 19
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees vs. Tampa Bay at St. Petersburg, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, starters don't travel to away games. It doesn't
matter with the Yankees. No matter who they bring, you always see
someone good.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, March 20
</P>
<P>
   New York Mets vs. Atlanta at Lake Buena Vista, 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Spring might mean the most to the Mets. They failed in the final
weekend to make the playoffs last year, spent a ton of money in the
off-season and a sense of urgency surrounds the team.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, March 21
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland vs. Philadelphia at Clearwater, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The first and only stop at Jack Russell Stadium, which has been
around since 1955. Clearwater Beach is 3 miles away and Cleveland
shortstop Omar Vizquel is as smooth as its sand.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, March 22
</P>
<P>
   Boston vs. Pittsburgh at Bradenton, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   No more Mo, but the Red Sox still have a loyal following.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, March 23
</P>
<P>
   Houston vs. Cleveland at Winter Haven, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the McGwire-Sosa home run chase last year was Manny
Ramirez's season for the Indians. Not a big spring draw, but he
should be.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, March 24
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees vs. Texas at Port Charlotte, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   You know what the best thing is about seeing the Yankees play?
You know you'll see a competitive game, even though it's spring.
Everyone wants to beat the Yankees, including the Rangers, losers
to New York in last year's Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, March 25
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles vs. Houston at Kissimmee, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have been talking about moving to Arizona. A
Grapefruit League fixture, their time in Florida may be running
out.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, March 26
</P>
<P>
   Houston vs. New York Yankees at Tampa, 7:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like sunshine and baseball in the afternoon.
Throw in some barbecue smoke, however, and night games in spring
are just as good.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, March 27
</P>
<P>
   Boston vs. Tampa Bay at St. Petersburg, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay is the team that stays in Florida after everyone else
leaves. The lineup you'll see this summer will start to take shape
by now.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, March 28
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore vs. Boston at Fort Myers, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a chance to see Baltimore's Will Clark in a new uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, March 29
</P>
<P>
   Texas vs. Tampa Bay at St. Petersburg, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   With the Final Four fast approaching at nearby Tropicana Field,
the buzz in the air makes St. Petersburg the place to be.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, March 30
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees vs. Cincinnati at Sarasota, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect spring day.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, March 31
</P>
<P>
   Boston vs. Pittsburgh at Bradenton, 1:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect spring stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, April 1
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland vs. New York Yankees at Tampa, 1:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect spring ending.
</P>
<P>
   (Chris Anderson writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.
This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
