<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL APPROVES BILL LIMITING YEAR 2000 LIABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to head off a flood of lawsuits against
companies that fail to correct their year 2000 computer problems,
the Senate Commerce Committee narrowly approved legislation
Wednesday that would limit the firms' liability.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would cap punitive damages at $250,000 and require a
90-day cooling-off period before any lawsuit could be filed. The
90-day period is designed to give companies time to fix any Y2K
problems and avoid a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's author, Senate Commerce Chairman John McCain,
R-Ariz., noting that most Democrats are strongly against the
legislation, said it will have to be revised before it reaches the
Senate floor in order to have a chance of being enacted. The
commerce committee's nine Democrats voted against the bill while
all 11 Republicans supported it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the bill is to provide incentives to prevent
Y2K failures, to fix the problems which do occur and to avoid
costly litigation,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, fewer than 50 Y2K-related lawsuits have been filed, but
some experts predict thousands will be launched when the so-called
Y2K problem begins _ that is, once some computer systems or
products with embedded computer chips fail on or after Jan. 1.
Unless they are fixed, these computers will misread the year 2000
as 1900.
</P>
<P>
   One lawsuit filed by a Warren, Mich., grocery-store owner has
already been settled for $260,000. In testimony before the Senate
Judiciary Committee earlier this week, the store owner, Mark
Yarsike, said he faced disaster when he first opened his store in
1995. The $100,000 computer system that ran the store's cash
registers immediately crashed because, as he later found out, it
couldn't handle a credit card with an expiration date of 2000 or
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not make one sale,'' he said. ``People began drifting
out. ... We heard comments like `I'll never come back here.'''
After spending several weeks trying to get the system's
manufacturer, Atlanta-based TEC America Inc., to fix the system,
Yarsike installed another one and took TEC to court. Yarsike said
small businesses like his could be hurt if Y2K liability
legislation is enacted.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-day cooling-off period was first suggested by Sens.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who included
it in their own legislation, which is nearly identical to the
McCain bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both the McCain and Feinstein-Hatch bills would require anyone
intending to file a Y2K-related lawsuit to first give a defendant
written notice of the problem. The defendant would have 30 days to
respond in writing and an additional 60 days to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats opposing the Y2K measures say they could give
businesses an incentive to wait to fix any Y2K problems until after
they happen.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., called the McCain bill a
``get-out-of-jail-free card.'' He said market forces are working to
address the Y2K issues, adding that some businesses have already
cut off suppliers and other vendors that have not fixed their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., argued that the legislation is
necessary to allow companies to put 100 percent of their efforts
into coping with Y2K problems this year rather than worrying about
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said he recently met with owners of four small computer
software companies in the Seattle area who are in an ``absolute
panic over Y2K lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain bill would also impose proportionate liability rather
than so-called joint and several liability. This would limit a
company's liability to the proportion of its fault in causing a
problem and is aimed at preventing plaintiffs from going after the
wealthiest defendants in lawsuits where several defendants are
named.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the proposed legislation is too
broad and could improperly override state contract and tort law.
Most Y2K lawsuits would be filed in state courts.
</P>
<P>
   A similar measure is pending in the House that is supported by
Republicans and by some Democrats from high-tech areas such as Rep.
James Moran of Alexandria, Va., and Calvin Dooley of Hanford,
Calif. The main difference between the House and Senate bills is
that the House measure would cap lawyers' fees at $1,000 per hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
