<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VINCE-GILL-MUSIC-NYTR     03-03 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINCE-GILL-MUSIC-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCE GILL'S MANY TRIBUTES TO TRADITION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DeYOUNG   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The traditions of country music are important to Vince Gill.
Though he has a record 17 Country Music Association awards and last
week took home his 12th Grammy, he acknowledges his debt to the
music's forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   For his latest album, ``The Key,'' Gill wrote a collection of
songs in a variety of classic country styles, from Buck Owens'
twangy Bakersfield Sound, to the gut-wrenching love ballads of
George Jones and the easy shuffles of Nashville Sound pioneers Ray
Price and Floyd Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Key'' doesn't go down as smoothly as some of Gill's
earlier, multi-platinum albums, like ``I Still Believe in You'' or
``When Love Finds You.'' However, the 42-year-old singer-songwriter
says, making a hit was never discussed at the recording sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a labor of love, and such a joy hearing those
kinds of things coming through the speakers, it was important to
me,'' Gill explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This record felt like my whole life, as opposed to just a
period of it. In that I remember what Ray Charles' records sounded
like, from when I was growing up. But there were still a whole lot
of things that I've learned, musically, since I've been
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Key'' is dedicated to Gill's father, Stan Gill, a federal
appellate court judge, who died last year. Young Vince learned to
play guitar by sitting in with his dad, who knew just three or four
banjo chords but joyfully played all the country music hits of the
day in the family's Oklahoma City living room and with a weekend
combo.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of his father, Gill says, made him start thinking about
those old songs. ``I'll always believe that this'll be a
tremendously important record in my entire career,'' he explains.
``I kind of knew what I wanted the record to sound like, and in my
simple way to say, `This is something I missed; this is something I
love.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether it's as commercially successful as `I
Still Believe in You,' it's not a failure. Huge success to me is
just to make the music; music's always about that to me. The
success is in making it, not in where it winds up and how many it
sells.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in my heart, it was what I intended it to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill says making ``The Key'' was fun, and something of a cinch,
because a lot of Nashville session musicians have been working
since the old days. ``I think the players had a blast,'' he
explains. ``Pig Robbins played on all those records. He knows what
they sounded like. He was the guy. John Hughey played on all the
Conway Twitty records, and on down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people understand how great those players are,
that do what they do. You can go to them and say `This has got kind
of a Buck feel right here' and they know exactly what you're
talking about. They are so great, and so chameleon-like, that
wherever you want to point them, they take it. They understand it.
It's really impressive to see musicians with enough talent to be
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Vince Gill has never strayed from his country music
roots. Although he's as well-known as Garth Brooks or Shania Twain,
he makes himself accessible to his fans, participating in dozens of
charity events in Nashville every year. He has affably hosted the
CMA show since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   For every big-city, big-money arena tour, he takes a swing
through state fairs and smaller venues in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a balance in your life,'' Gill explains.
``It's not always about who's got the most ... what is it they say,
`The guy who dies with the most toys still dies' ''?
</P>
<P>
   He's also a frequent performer on the Grand Ole Opry stage.
Playing the Opry one or two weekends a year is a requirement once
you become a member; however, it pays less than $100 per night, and
many artists won't come off the road, where they might make 50
times that for a single concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's selfish not to go there if you're a member,''
Gill says, ``if you've been successful in your career and they
think enough of you to say `We'd like to make you a member of this
great tradition.' And you go `OK, thanks, I'll take that, but I'm
never coming back.' Then what good has any of it done?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like investing in people. I love the fact that I knew Roy
Acuff. I knew Minnie Pearl. And I know Jimmy Dickens and I know
Brother Oswald, and those people know I care about 'em. Honestly
care about them and appreciate what they've done. And that's the
easiest way to tell them thank you, and to tell them that I do, to
go and be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill says he loves the fact that the Opry regulars aren't
concerned with chart positions and video shoots, like those who run
in Nashville's fast lane. ``I think everybody gets caught up in the
things that are very temporary, and that's the success of
themselves and their popularity,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fault people for being the way they are ... I just
like it. It's that simple. I wouldn't have the opportunities that I
have, and have had for the last 15, 16 years in this country music
world, if it hadn't have been for Roy Acuff out there at the Opry
every Saturday night, promoting it, supporting it, loving it. And
all those people love it. Think what the Opry'd be like if none of
those people went?''
</P>
<P>
   Gill's reputation as a nice guy precedes him in Nashville.
Before his divorce last year from singer Janis Gill, he had only
made headlines for his charity work. An avid golfer since his
teens, he lent his name to the city's biggest Pro-Celebrity golf
tournament. ``The Vinny'' supports Tennessee's Junior Golf program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that I'm any different than I've ever been,''
Gill explains. ``It maybe shocks people that having success and a
lot of those things hasn't really had an effect on me. It's not
something that I consciously say: 'You're going to be the nicest
guy in town.' I just respond to people and treat 'em decently.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also a frequent guest performer on other artists'
recordings, from the well-known to the unknown. Last year, he
produced a song for his friend and frequent singing partner Patty
Loveless, and he was at the helm of Sonya Isaacs' debut album, due
out this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly not gonna run from playing music,'' he says. ``I
just like playing music and singing songs. I think a whole lot of
it is the musician factor. Being a musician - I think that
mentality is pretty steeply ingrained in me.''
</P>
<P>
   He stops himself, then chuckles. ``Not all musicians are nice
guys. I just am what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bill DeYoung is Arts &AMP; Entertainment Editor of The Gainesville
Sun.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
