<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRUCK-AWAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO GET DROWSY DRIVERS OFF THE HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some truck drivers drink coffee when they start to feel drowsy
during long hours on the road. Others pull over and take quick laps
around their trailers, naps in the back of their cabs or, in some
cases, amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   But some truckers do nothing, or feel nothing, until they simply
nod off at the wheel. The result is often an accident, sometimes
fatal to themselves and other motorists.
</P>
<P>
   As a remedy, the federal Department of Transportation is testing
devices that can monitor a driver's alertness and issue a warning
before it is too late. Officials say some of these instruments may
someday be required, though that day is probably many years off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truckers are by and large good drivers,'' said Ronald
Knipling, chief of the research division for the Federal Highway
Administration's Office of Motor Carriers and Highway Safety. ``But
they are pushing the hours.'' Sometimes, he added, the rules on how
long a trucker can drive at a time are not adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Among the instruments under development to combat drowsiness is
a pen-size infrared camera that would be mounted on the truck's
dashboard and would shine infrared light, which cannot be seen by
people, into the driver's eyes. It would measure the amount of
light reflected off the driver's retinas. When the level became too
low because of droopy eyelids, the camera could trigger a sound,
shake the driver's seat or release peppermint spray inside the cab.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators still have to determine what degree of eyelid droop
signifies fatigue. It may be difficult to arrive at a definitive
answer because people may not show fatigue in the same way and
because the shape of the eye and eyelid can vary from person to
person.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with an infrared camera is that it works only at
night. Sunshine makes the measurements unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   According to government statistics, only 1 percent to 2 percent
of truck accidents are caused by drivers' falling asleep. But
Knipling suspects that fatigue contributes to many more accidents
by slowing drivers' reaction times and making drivers less alert.
</P>
<P>
   The government currently regulates fatigue in the trucking
industry indirectly, by limiting the number of hours a driver can
work. But Knipling said those laws could eventually be replaced by
rules saying that drivers can be on the road as long as technology
determines that they are alert.
</P>
<P>
   Another device in the works could alert drivers if they weave
between lanes. Called a lane tracker, it would watch the road and
beep if the driver had trouble steering a relatively straight line.
</P>
<P>
   To differentiate between an intended lane change and drowsiness,
the tracker would have to observe wobbly driving over several
minutes. Prototypes are still being debugged by private companies
and the final product is expected to be expensive, Knipling said.
</P>
<P>
   The devices that are ultimately successful will probably have to
cost less than $1,000 each, Knipling said. And alerting drivers to
their drowsiness will have to be done subtly, he said, because a
loud alarm could be distracting enough to cause an accident on its
own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
