<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-PRODUCTS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA AGENCY SEEKS COMMERCIAL DEALS FOR NOVEL USES OF CITRUS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By PAUL POWER JR.   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Florida citrus farmers have plowed hundreds of
thousands of dollars into trying to develop new food products that
might include orange or grapefruit as ingredients. After concocting
items such as orange-based barbecue sauces, fruit bars and a
pudding-like treat made from citrus pulp cells, food scientists
aligned with the Florida Department of Citrus are scouring the
country for companies that will take the prototypes from the lab to
American shopping carts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was going to take some time,'' says Dan Santangelo,
executive director of the Lakeland-based citrus agency, which gets
nearly all of its $70 million budget from a tax on growers. ``We're
still excited about the possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities are one thing; inking a deal is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to develop new commercial ways to use the state's
citrus products _ to stimulate demand for oranges and grapefruit
and thus profits for farmers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of Florida's oranges are squeezed into
orange juice, which is about a $3 billion market in the United
States. The remainder is sold fresh, though some by-products are
directed into flavors and essences.
</P>
<P>
   Executing hush-hush confidentiality agreements with dozens of
food companies, agency staff members have circled the country,
pitching novel food and ingredient uses _ from citrus salsa to
high-fiber orange flour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy task,'' says Don Zink, a former research and
development manager for Nestle USA. ``It can take a lot of selling,
especially if what you propose hasn't been looked at in-house.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Citrus has been saying it is on the cusp of an
important deal.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the agency reported in an annual summary, ``A leading
food manufacturer has made a verbal commitment to introduce four
salad dressings and four sauces based on our prototype recipes
which will include at least 25 percent Florida citrus.''
</P>
<P>
   That statement was a bit optimistic, but Santangelo says he is
still hopeful for a breakthrough with dressings or food sauces,
perhaps later this year.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest ways to break through is when a company's
competitor adds an adventuresome new taste or product, says Zink,
who now is food safety manager for Nestle. ``If that is perceived
as a possibility, other companies may follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunkist Growers Cooperative, which is based in Ontario, Calif.,
has boosted sales in other countries by licensing its name for
juices, snacks, vitamins, baking mixes, jellies and sodas.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus agency staffers in Florida have looked at similar
agreements, and Santangelo says he would like to see companies like
Nabisco and Pepperidge Farms using the state's citrus products.
</P>
<P>
   Under one arrangement, food companies would pay an as-yet
unspecified fee to use a ``Made with Florida Citrus'' label on
packages.
</P>
<P>
   The citrus agency's real intent appears to be to find ways to
use lots of orange juice in individual products.
</P>
<P>
   How much? Well, in the case of salad dressing, the group
envisions products with 25 percent juice.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo says he also was optimistic about citrus being used
in fruit bars.
</P>
<P>
   Though some potential uses of citrus sound far-fetched, it was
Department of Citrus scientists who were credited with devising a
way to pack frozen concentrated orange juice about 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo, who came to the citrus agency about six years ago,
has tried to rekindle innovation, pushing the agency to investigate
processing technology using microwaves as well as new uses for
grapefruit and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest obstacles the department's effort has run
into is turnover within food companies, Santangelo says. As soon as
a possible door is opened, it can close when key people are
reassigned or leave the company.
</P>
<P>
   The citrus agency is now approaching food scientists directly at
national conventions, says Bill Stinson, scientific research
director for the group.
</P>
<P>
   Stinson can see a time when citrus is processed not for its
juice but for its health-enhancing compounds, a growing consumer
area called ``nutriceuticals.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, he believes the agency can find a commercial home
for new food uses. ``I think we are getting very, very close to
getting off the dime.''
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Power Jr. writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. This
story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
