<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LESLIE LAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Ails Camellia?
</P>
<P>
   Q. My mother has a camellia plant that is about 49 years old. It
has buds all over it every year. The buds, however, open only about
halfway, then the petals turn brown, and the buds fall off the
plant. Why does this happen? Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   A. If the plant is growing somewhere near the northern edge of
its range, in southern New Jersey, for instance, it may simply be
getting blasted each year by frost. Many old-fashioned hardy
camellias (C. japonica) are vulnerable this way. And if the plant
is growing in a pot and being moved indoors for the winter, the bud
drop could be due to dry air. Camellias need higher humidity than
most living rooms provide.
</P>
<P>
   But if your mother's plant is a japonica, the most common kind,
and if it's living in what's called ``the camellia belt'' _ a more
or less frost-free zone that starts in southern Virginia, goes all
through the Deep South and then snakes along until it winds up in
the Pacific Northwest _ the problem is probably a fungus disease
called petal blight. Dr. William Ackerman, a research
horticulturist now retired from the Agriculture Department, said
that petal blight is epidemic through that area.
</P>
<P>
   There are three ways to deal with petal blight, said Dr.
Ackerman, who was Camellia at the National Arboretum in Washington.
The first is sanitation. If you can rake up and discard or burn all
fallen blossoms and buds as soon as they drop, you may be able to
prevent reinfection. Unfortunately, the spores also travel on the
wind, and ``cleanup won't help much,'' he said, unless the
neighbors for at least half a mile around are willing to work as
hard at it as you are.
</P>
<P>
   Solution 2 is to live outside the camellia belt _ the fungus
isn't a problem north of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Solution 3 is to plant a fall blooming species, which would be
less prone to blight. Japonicas are spring bloomers, with flowers
that come any time between January and May. Fall bloomers flower
between September and December. They include C. sasanqua, which is
almost as hardy as japonica, C. hiemalis, which is a bit more
tender, and most of the varieties developed by Dr. Ackerman, whose
introductions are among the hardiest, capable of surviving as far
north as Long Island and along the southern New England coast.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ackerman's camellias do not bear his name, but nurseries
that sell them usually point out their Ackerman lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Sources include Roslyn Nursery, 211 Burrs Lane, Dix Hills, N.Y.
11746, (516) 643-9347 (catalog, $3); Fairweather Gardens, P.O. Box
330, Greenwich, N.J. 08323, (609) 451-6261 (catalog, $3), and
Camellia Forest Nursery, 125 Carolina Forest Road, Chapel Hill,
N.C., 27516, (919) 967-5529 (catalog, $2).
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
