<SLUG> BC-HOME-TEXTILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUITED-UP SOFAS: SHOES AND BAG TO MATCH? 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID COLEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not since the resourceful Scarlett O'Hara swept down
the grand stair in a red velvet gown made from Tara's drapes has
fashion enjoyed such an intimate affair with the decor tastes of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   From luxe cashmeres to of-the-moment Ultrasuede, upholstery and
decorative home textiles are in the middle of a rare burst of
synergy: some of the most popular new fabrics are remarkably
similar to those on fashion's runways.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise, given how many fashion designers
are proclaiming fervent passions for high-tech stretch nylons or
blanket-weight cashmeres. And decorators, too, should know their
textiles, haunting the swatch-strewn halls of fabric showrooms as
they do.
</P>
<P>
   Area I.D., a new furnishings store at 262 Elizabeth St., quickly
laid claim to the trend. The owner, Debra LaChance, reupholsters
her mid-century-modern pieces in matte jersey, cashmere and other
clothing fabrics, tracking down the same fabrics used by Isaac
Mizrahi, Ralph Lauren and Donna Karan. A 1974 Herman Miller
sectional ($800 a piece) wears skintight black nylon Mizrahi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for pieces with great bones,'' said Ms. LaChance, a
former fashion consultant. ``And we reupholster them in the newest,
greatest fabrics we can find.'' A 1950s sofa in washable Ultrasuede
is $2,400.
</P>
<P>
   At Wyeth, 151 Franklin St., the owner, John Birch, said that he
has been reupholstering ``almost 100 percent'' of the modern
furniture his store stocks in clothing fabric _ from chairs in
military-inspired olive twill to sofas in Scottish keeper's tweed
(pieces start at $6,000). Birch, who has worked in store and
display design for Ralph Lauren and Giorgio Armani, has equally
fashion-conscious customers, including the designer Helmut Lang.
</P>
<P>
   Birch was inspired to start using clothing fabric for upholstery
by his own search last year for a steady hotel room in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was so upholstered,'' he said, making it sound like
a synonym for infested. ``I don't want to sit on something that
makes me feel like I'm in a flower patch. I'm accustomed to
clothing fabrics. They're more livable.''
</P>
<P>
   While the vogue for extreme minimalist decor is on the wane, the
Spartan color palette of white, gray and camel inspired by Lang,
Jil Sander and Calvin Klein is now waxing at the D.&AMP; D. Building,
that citadel of prints at 979 Third Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gray flannel was definitely hard to find a couple of years
ago,'' Tom Beeton, a Los Angeles decorator, said, by way of
example. ``Now you can go to any number of sources. It's much
easier to find.''
</P>
<P>
   ogers &AMP; Goffigon, a to-the-trade fabric showroom in the D.&AMP; D.
Building known for its small but luxurious selection of
blanket-like wool and cashmere upholstery flannels, expanded its
range of grays last month in response to customer demand. (List
prices: $78 a yard for wool; $427 for cashmere). Color was just
part of this fashion-conscious decision, said Jack Flynn, a
co-owner. ``We're interested in fine weaving, which is not always
the focus of our industry,'' he said. ``I think that upholstery
fabrics should feel as good as they look.''
</P>
<P>
   At Nancy Corzine, another to-the-trade company in the D.&AMP; D.
Building, it is simple, rich camel hair ($96 a yard) and gray
cashmere flannel ($270 a yard) that are among the biggest
upholstery sellers. ``We just covered all of Luther Vandross'
apartment with it,'' said Ms. Corzine, brandishing the flannel.
</P>
<P>
   Beeton finds such kindred spirits among textile suppliers still
relatively rare. He lucked across a bolt of the sturdy nylon that
Prada uses for its famous backpacks at a giant fabric wholesaler.
Corzine and Donghia (also in the D.&AMP; D. Building), he said, are
among the few fabric companies in step with the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Without Rogers &AMP; Goffigon, Victoria Hagan, the interior
designer, said she'd be at a loss for fabric. She also goes to the
source, textile houses like Rosen &AMP; Chadick, at 240 W. 40th St.
Open to any and all, Rosen &AMP; Chadick has a wide range of
clothing-based textiles. Ms. Hagan has used striped men's suiting
and shirting fabrics for upholstery and for wall treatments. ``It
lends a room a different kind of formality, one that's not so
commercial,'' said Wayne Nathan, a designer with Ms. Hagan.
(Prices: $30 a yard for flannel; $60 for camel hair; $125 to $150
for cashmere).
</P>
<P>
   Some fashion fabrics _ taffeta, for example _ are not ideal with
energetic children or rambunctious pets. ``With some of these
fabrics, you're making a decision between fashion and durability,''
Ms. LaChance admitted. David Chadick, an owner of Rosen &AMP; Chadick,
said: ``If you're upholstering a sofa in camel hair or cashmere,
it's more for show. You're not going to want to sit on it all the
time.'' (The same goes for other fabrics like Shantung and dupioni
silk). They can pill and bag, and maintenance isn't easy. ``Dry
clean only,'' Chadick said.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion conscious may be glad of such shortcomings: all the
more reason to redecorate. As they say of trends on Seventh Avenue,
there's one born every minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
