<SLUG> BC-LITHGOW-ALBUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBUM BRINGS OUT THE KID IN LITHGOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NANCY HEWITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
 
 
LOS ANGELES _ John Lithgow has just added a notch to his
well-rounded performing belt: singer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Singin' in the Bathtub'' marks Lithgow's foray into the
musical world of family entertainment. This compilation of 16 songs
is not what you'd expect of an album geared to kids and their
folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're old novelty songs,'' he says. ``Some are more than 50
years old. We keyed off songs I loved as a child, because of their
clever lyrics. They're irresistible.''
</P>
<P>
   The album came as an outgrowth of Lithgow's love of entertaining
children. In 1990, he did a live performance for 30 kids with only
his guitar for accompaniment _ and loved it. ``Doing it
(performing) for kids live is a real ball,'' he says. ``They get up
and dance while I'm singing.''
</P>
<P>
   Television audiences have gotten to know him as the high
commander of an alien expedition in the NBC sitcom ``3rd Rock From
the Sun'' and spokesman for a long-distance telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, this soft-spoken actor was known mainly for
Oscar-nominated roles in films such as ``The World According to
Garp'' and ``Terms of Endearment'' and stage roles in dramas such
as ``M Butterfly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lithgow is no stranger to television.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, he won the first of three Emmy awards for ``The Doll,''
an episode of Steven Spielberg's ``Amazing Stories.'' His second
and third Emmys came in 1996 and 1997 for his role as ``3rd
Rock's'' Dick Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   Working on an album was a challenge for the actor, who fit in
rehearsals and recordings between tapings of ``3rd Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a couple of months breaking in songs,'' he says,
noting that this included performing them for small groups to gauge
reaction. Then, he headed into the studio from September through
November of last year. ``In planning the album, everything was
dependent on my schedule. We decided it had to be first-rate.''
</P>
<P>
   This mix of old but familiar songs includes such standards as
``At the Codfish Ball'' and ``Swinging on a Star.'' But Lithgow
admits to a few favorites of his own. ``I love `Singin' in the
Bathtub,' `Everybody Eats When They Come to My House'' and
`Triplets,' which is an old Danny Kaye song. Kids love songs about
siblings.''
</P>
<P>
   And even before the release of his first album, Lithgow is
already planning a second one, and is on the hunt for more curious
songs.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he would like to do some live performances _ regularly
_ and mentioned UCLA's Royce Hall as a possible location for a
concert this year. ``The idea is to create a yearly tradition at
big venues like Royce Hall,'' he says. ``I really want to do
concerts and sing with the band.'' The band he refers to is Bill
Elliott's Swing Orchestra, which accompanies him on the album.
</P>
<P>
   And performing for families holds real appeal. Part of it is
``the thrill of singing these songs with a big band,'' he says. The
other part is that he loves swing music and loves to entertain.
``Kids nowadays are so into swing (music). You feel like dancing to
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
