<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-SANANTONIO-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A $1,000 WEEKEND: THE RIGHT PACE IN SAN ANTONIO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 7)  
 (bl)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texans like their weekends, whether it's bobbing around in a
bass boat in East Texas, promenading along the strand in Galveston
or riding the trail on a Hill Country dude ranch. But San Antonio
has got to be the king of the weekend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This city of just over 1 million people is just the right
distance from most of the state's population centers to feel like a
real journey, and it's got just the right number of attractions to
last two or three days at an easy pace.
</P>
<P>
   It's also refreshingly different from almost every other place
in Texas, a kind of Spanish colonial theme park with good
restaurants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio seems to swell on the weekends, at least in its
tourist precincts. While a lot of the city's visitors come for the
endless procession of conventions _ people wearing name tags are
bumping into each other 365 days a year down on the Riverwalk _ the
weekenders make San Antonio bulge.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My assignment here _ a weekend in San Antonio with my wife,
Barbara Whitaker, and two daughters, Kate, 9, and Laura, 3,
spending as close to $1,000 as possible _ seemed a little daunting
at first. San Antonio is not an expensive city and while it does
have several first-class hotels, even they are priced well below
what a medium-priced hotel would cost in New York or Los Angeles.
But one must never, of course, underestimate the American family's
ability to spend money.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My first inclination was to stay at Le Mansion del Rio, the
fanciest of the hotels right down in the thick of the Riverwalk,
the city's central showpiece, where shops and restaurants line the
concrete banks of the San Antonio River just below street level,
spanned by graceful Spanish-style bridges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Le Mansion del Rio was all booked up. My experience is that
Le Mansion del Rio is always booked up. I have tried on six
different trips to stay there and the answer is always, sorry,
better luck next time. Too bad, it looks like a nice place.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we went for the Hyatt Regency Hill Country Resort,
which is an entirely different sort of San Antonio experience.
Situated just outside the Interstate loop that surrounds the city
and across the highway from Sea World (closed for the winter), it
is set in a thickly wooded and gently rolling enclave that was once
a ranch and is now home to the sprawling, Western-style hotel, an
18-hole golf course, two swimming pools and an 18-acre water park
that includes a meandering man-made stream for tubing, slides,
waterfalls, a short stretch of sandy beach and a couple of hot
tubs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The standard room that we were offered was $210 a night, but
this didn't seem like enough to get us to our $1,000 limit so I
asked about upgrade packages. Yes, they said, there is a romance
weekend champagne package that comes with a bottle of champagne,
valet parking and free breakfasts. Fine, I said, but when we got
there it turned out that the package was $198, cheaper than the
nonchampagne fare. Go figure.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We arrived just after dark, too late to drive into San Antonio
that evening, so we decided to eat at the resort and wander around.
The room was small but nicely appointed, with sturdy furniture of a
Western theme and a balcony overlooking the gardens, and it never
seemed cramped, despite the two children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Antlers, the resort's fancy restaurant near the golf clubhouse,
is dominated by a huge chandelier made of interwoven deer antlers
and the menu was a mouthwatering mix of Southwestern and
Continental fare. But it was all booked up. So we wandered down to
the Springhouse Cafe, the moderately priced restaurant. So far, all
I'd spent was $5 to tip the bellhop, and every effort to live it up
first class had been met with frustration. That $1,000 was looking
more and more elusive.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, we managed to do all right at the Springhouse Cafe,
spending $74.27 for dinner, including the seafood buffet and a
couple of glasses of wine for the adults and ribs and a hamburger
for our daughters. On the way out, we dropped another $10.29 at the
resort's general store, a soup-to-nuts emporium geared to making it
possible to spend several days at the resort without ever leaving
to buy anything. We got milk and cereal for early morning
emergencies and a couple of Haagen-Dazs bars. The ice cream went
well with that bottle of champagne, which, sadly, was domestic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total for day one: $287.56. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The word among Texas parents on the Hill Country Resort is that
it's a great place to take the family, especially if there is at
least one golfer in the group, and that it's a place you can spend
the entire weekend happily without leaving. None of us were
golfers, but the rest seemed true. At least, if the weather had
been warmer. But it was a bit too chilly to contemplate tubing.
Only the heated pool, steaming ominously in the brisk morning air,
was remotely tempting and both girls plunged in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The resort's grounds are lovely: thickly wooded and crisscrossed
with meandering paths for walkers and bikers. While it may not be
as sharply rolling as the more dramatic Hill Country farther to the
northwest, it has the same sort of flavor, with twisted Texas trees
and wide open spaces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We had to hustle the girls out of the pool, though, because it
had one drawback: it was free. And breakfast had been free, too. We
had to start spending money fast. The day was wasting.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We drove into downtown San Antonio, a 20-minute trip, and parked
at the Rivercenter Mall, a retail complex at the foot of a towering
Marriott hotel at the eastern end of the Riverwalk system. Our goal
was the IMAX theater, where they show a film called ``Alamo: The
Price of Freedom,'' which we had been reliably informed was a
pretty good introduction to the story of the Alamo and a way to get
your children more excited about seeing the place.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I bought a map of the city ($5.33) and Kate, my 9-year-old,
bought two postcards (54 cents) before we came to one of those mall
stores that sell candy. You grab an empty plastic bag and fill it
up yourself from dozens of plastic tubs of candy. Normally, we
steer clear of such places but this time, why not? Everybody got a
bag. Licorice, gummy things, nuts, ribbon candy, chocolate. Total
cost: $8.15.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the movie, which was a little less informed on the
strategy of the battle and a little more rah-rah than I would have
liked, were $7.50 for the adults and $4.75 for the children, and it
lasted about 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From there it was a short walk to the far end of the mall,
downstairs and around the corner to the Menger Hotel, where Teddy
Roosevelt gave a rousing speech recruiting Rough Riders. The
historic Menger bar is said to be modeled on the one in the House
of Lords in London.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just outside and across the street is the Alamo, or what's left
of it. The famous chapel facade is there, suitably aged and almost
vibrating with mythic intensity. The facility is owned by the state
of Texas but run by the Daughters of the Republic of Texas, the
group that a century ago fought to save the crumbling old structure
and turn it into a shrine to Texas independence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The little side rooms have become secular chapels honoring the
men who fought and died there, complete with flags and pageantry,
and the display cases around the central nave are filled with
memorabilia and items linked to the most famous of the Alamo's
defenders, William Travis, Jim Bowie and Davy Crockett.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An adjacent building holds a museum with more artifacts, as well
as a cogent history of the city and the site. And the jam-packed
gift shop contains as many books, toy soldiers and coonskin caps as
any family could possibly want. But the line was too long, so we
passed. The Alamo is free, though I did slip $5 into a donation
bin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We hustled down to the Riverwalk, a couple of blocks away, to
blow some cash. We walked up and down, trying to figure out where
to eat, finally settling on a faux British pub called Kangaroo
Court. Fish and chips and hamburgers, plus a couple of beers, set
us back $49.11. We were not reminded of London. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BacK at the Hill Country Resort, Barbara and the girls hit the
pool again and I bought a cigar ($8) and sat out on Aunt Mary's
Porch, a wooden platform on the north side of the central lobby
overlooking the woods and a very pleasant place to read a book or
have a margarita.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That evening we had booked a table for a river barge dinner
along the Riverwalk put on by Boudro's, one of best of the
Riverwalk restaurants, specializing in a kind of cross between
Southwest and Cajun. We paid for parking ($5) and got there early,
so we stopped next door at a cafe called Republic of Texas for some
drinks ($10.16) before beginning our candlelit float around the
Riverwalk. It went over big with everyone. The food was terrific
(steak in a chipotle sauce or a grilled and glazed salmon) and the
passing scene _ mariachi bands, crowded riverside cafes, colored
lights and hordes of strolling tourists _ was fascinating. We chose
a decent bottle of wine and it brought the total tab to $171.33. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, we walked back to the Alamo and hired a horse-drawn
carriage to clomp us around the old, dark city for 25 minutes ($30
with tip). The narrow downtown streets, Gothic skyscrapers next to
modern cubes and the occasional silhouette of a Spanish church, are
strangely empty at night. All the action is down on the Riverwalk,
all around but out of sight, except for those moments when the
carriage passes over a bridge and the light bleeds up from below
along with the crowd noise and the music, and it's like passing
near a party to which you are not invited. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this was more like it. Total tab for the day: $515.12 ($198
for the room and $317.12 for other stuff).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our final morning, we had our usual free breakfast (coffee,
juice and pastries, plus the last of the cereal) and took turns
watching the girls. I got a massage at the health center ($75
including tip) and Barbara got a manicure ($36). For their morning
treat, the girls got another swim in the steaming pool and one
stuffed animal each from the gift shop ($23.38). Then we packed up
and hit the road (the bellhop got a $10 tip this time and the valet
got $5), stopping on the way out of town for a big Mexican lunch at
a place I like called La Fogata in an otherwise unremarkable
neighborhood in northwest San Antonio. Sitting in an outdoor
courtyard with a tinkling fountain, we had a huge lunch of fajitas,
sizzling green onions, enchiladas and quesadillas that set us back
$42.18.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, back on the road, we paused to load up on mineral water
and sodas ($8.22) and headed back home to Houston.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total cost of the day: $199.78.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Total cost for the weekend: $1,002.46.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I guess I shouldn't have had that last beer.
</P>
<P>
   The essentials
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hyatt Regency Hill Country Resort, 9800 Hyatt Resort Drive, San
Antonio; (210) 647-1234, fax (210) 520-4077. Standard double room
$210 a night, golfing and other packages available, children free.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kangaroo Court, 512 Riverwalk; (210) 224-6821. Lunch with drinks
for two $20 to $25.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boudro's, 421 East Commerce St.; (210) 224-8484. Barge dinner
cruises at 6:30 p.m.: $34.50 (drinks extra), $17 for children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   La Fogata, 2427 Vance Jackson Road; (210) 340-1337. Lunch with
drinks for two, $15 to $25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republic of Texas, 429 East Commerce St.; (210) 223-4881.
</P>
<P>
   What to See
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo, 300 Alamo Plaza, open every day except Christmas and
Christmas Eve, from 9 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Monday through Saturday and
10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Sunday; (210) 225-1391. Admission is free,
donations voluntary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rivercenter IMAX Theater, Rivercenter Mall, 849 East Commerce
St., (210) 225-0000, for a film about the Alamo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Menger Hotel, 204 Alamo Plaza, (210) 223-4361, where Teddy
Roosevelt recruited Rough Riders. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
