<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-H     03-03 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LAWYER CALLS FOR END OF INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer for President Clinton urged Congress
Wednesday to kill the independent counsel law, which he called the
``nuclear weapon'' of partisan politics, but a former Watergate
prosecutor said the statute protects Americans against the White
House's powerful ``spin machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bennett, who represented the president in the Paula Jones
sexual harassment lawsuit, told a Senate panel, ``The act has
become a vehicle for subjecting public officials, and those around
them, to seemingly perpetual scrutiny more intense than any private
citizen would have to endure.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said the law's ``hair-trigger'' provision for appointing
a special prosecutor means that even the most ``flimsy''
allegations put forth by either party must be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than freeing prosecutorial discretion from political
bias, the act has become the nuclear weapon in the arsenal of
partisan politics,'' he told the Senate Government Affairs
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett also said the statute has ``ruined'' the lives of many
innocent people who have run up enormous legal bills in the course
of independent counsel investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal people just can't afford to keep a lawyer around for
the many years that it takes to end these investigations,'' he said
in calling on Congress to the let the law expire on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Ruth, former head of the Watergate Special Prosecution
Force in the early 1970s, told the panel that the independent
counsel act was needed to protect the country from the modern
public relations tactics of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my fear that the White House spin machine could lead one
to believe that another Saturday Night Massacre could succeed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday Night Massacre refers to the night of Oct. 20,
1973, when President Richard Nixon ordered Attorney General Elliot
Richardson to dismiss special Watergate prosecutor Archibald Cox
after Cox refused to drop a subpoena for Nixon's incriminating
White House tapes. Nixon also ordered Ruth's office abolished.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson refused to follow the orders and resigned. Nixon then
asked Deputy Attorney General William Ruckelshaus to fire Cox, but
Ruckelshaus also refused, leading to his own dismissal. After two
days, Cox was fired, but the Justice Department investigation of
Nixon continued, and Ruth's office remained in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe how thin the line was during those days
as to whether our office was going to be eliminated,'' Ruth said.
</P>
<P>
   Public outrage over Cox's firing and later over the tapes'
revelations of Nixon's other actions obstructing justice eventually
led to his resignation in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's hearing, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who
favors keeping an amended independent counsel act, said: ``You have
to wonder if Nixon had done a spin job on Cox, would there have
been a public outcry over his firing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Watergate scandal, Congress passed the
independent counsel act in 1978 to ensure that presidents would be
fairly investigated.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires the attorney general to seek appointment of an
independent counsel when there is substantial and credible evidence
of a crime by any one of 49 top federal officials, including the
president. A panel of three federal appellate judges then picks an
attorney for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans opposed the law when it was passed and later
cited as an example of a politically inspired investigation the
probe by Independent Counsel Lawrence Walsh into the Iran-Contra
arms-for-hostages deals of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when a three-judge panel appointed Kenneth Starr to
investigate Clinton, Democrats have repeated the GOP criticisms of
the law.
</P>
<P>
   But while the statute has lost favor with many in Congress,
several members of the Senate committee said Wednesday it is needed
to ensure that the public remains confident that investigations of
high-level officials are fair and complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one thing that's going to keep this law around,
it's that we can't go back _ that the public expects some type of
mechanism to investigate the president that is without reproach,''
said Sen. Fred Thompson, committee chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
