<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6470 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TRUCK-TECH-2TAKES     03-03 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRUCK-TECH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
18 WHEELS, GPS AND RADAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Wis., Neb.)   (af)  
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONTARIO, Calif. _ The air outside the TA Trucking Center was
laced with more than diesel fumes from the hundreds of 18-wheelers
parked in neat rows at this interstate crossroad.
</P>
<P>
   As drivers finished their dinners, they rumbled out of the
parking lot, but not out of touch, because their satellite dishes
and computers kept them linked to headquarters with radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks are also equipped with sensors and alarms that warn
them of potential crashes. The result is truck dashboards that look
like cockpits. Even though some people may think of long-haul
trucks as no more sophisticated than Studebakers, many of them rely
on technology that far exceeds what is available in the most
expensive Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucks have changed so much since I started driving that it's
like the difference between covered wagons and jet planes,'' said
Marilyn Cochrane, a neatly coiffed and manicured driver with 17
years of experience who looks nothing at all like the
rough-and-tumble image of the long-distance trucker.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is her truck all horsepower and no finesse. She spoke as she
drove in a light drizzle past the Los Angeles suburbs on Interstate
10 in a truck equipped with digital monitors and an array of
buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the trucking industry praise these devices for improving
safety, insuring that loads arrive on time and increasing drivers'
comfort. The technology can be expensive and requires extra
maintenance, but trucking companies say it pays for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers, however, say the gadgets have changed their
profession for the worse. Now that trucks can be tracked by
satellite and even tailgating can be recorded for a boss to review,
some drivers complain about the vanishing independence of life on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   The trucking industry's transformation is readily apparent in
the shiny red rig Ms. Cochrane drives. It is equipped with flashing
lights and electronic buzzers that warn her when cars are getting
too close.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm system depends on two sensors. One, on the front
bumper, looks with radar for obstructions in the lanes ahead, while
another monitors the blind spot near the cab's passenger door.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cochrane said this system, built by Eaton Vorad
Technologies, of San Diego, has helped her avert crashes on several
occasions, like the time a car passed her on the highway shoulder.
But on this day, the chimes and flashing lights were often set off
when things were fine _ going off, for example, when Ms. Cochrane
waited behind a car at a traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK baby, I hear you,'' she said, patting the dashboard after
one such series of beeps. ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though false alarms are common, Max L. Fuller, co-chairman
of U.S. Xpress Enterprises, the parent company of U.S. Xpress, Ms.
Cochrane's employer, said that collision-avoidance technology was
worthwhile and had helped reduce the cost of accidents for the
company by nearly two-thirds in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   The system also acts as a sort of back-seat driver by recording
the performance of the person behind the wheel. It tracks how often
drivers use the brakes and how closely they follow cars on the
highway so the information can be downloaded, by inserting a memory
card into the truck's computer, and analyzed by company management.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of these reviews, some drivers have been warned
about tailgating, said Fuller, whose company is based in
Chattanooga, Tenn. Those who are especially aggressive must take
driving classes to reduce the risk of getting into an accident or
causing too much wear on their rigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that isn't enough, they need to go to another company,''
Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   One remedy for drivers who follow others too closely _ or an
option for those who want make driving as effortless as possible _
is to add what is called a Smart Cruise control. That feature, part
of the Eaton Vorad system, can be set to keep the truck from
getting any closer to another vehicle than the distance the truck
could travel in a fixed time period, like three seconds. The driver
does not have to touch the brakes or gas; Smart Cruise takes care
of it.
</P>
<P>
   If the truck is too close to the car ahead, the device
automatically slows the truck's engine, and, if that is not enough,
downshifts the transmission.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone seeking to escape the world of keyboards and e-mail,
trucking is probably not the answer. On-board computers that
connect drivers to dispatchers via satellite are perhaps the most
common technology on trucks these days.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study in 1998 by the American Trucking
Associations, 72 percent of major trucking companies have computers
aboard at least some of their rigs. But the overall figure is
probably much lower because only 6 percent of small trucking
companies have similar equipment.
</P>
<P>
   With computers, a driver (while parked) can, for example, send
headquarters a message when picking up a load, receive directions
and get instructions about the next assignment. The typing often
includes abbreviations because after a certain point, companies
must pay extra for each letter and blank space that is transmitted.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Ms. Cochrane was about to put her truck in gear, a beep
sounded in the cab to tell her that e-mail had arrived. She reached
over to the keyboard in front of the passenger's seat, looked at
the tiny screen and read a motivational message from a company
executive that was probably sent to every driver in the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``As U know, freight gets a little soft this time of year,'' the
message said, referring to the typical slowdown during winter.
``Our service must be flawless.''
</P>
<P>
   Many on-board computers come with Global Positioning System
technology that allows companies to know where their trucks are at
all times. With some systems, it is quite clear when a lazy driver
is parked at the beach instead of rolling through the desert.
</P>
<P>
   The information that arrives at the home office of the Schneider
National trucking company, in Green Bay, Wis., is so detailed that
trucks appear as dots moving along city streets on maps on a
computer screen. The system helps determine areas where the company
has too few trucks and can find stolen trucks.
</P>
<P>
   One such case involved a trailer full of Levis. ``Fortunately,
the thief didn't know that the truck was satellite-monitored,''
said Donald J. Schneider, president of Schneider National. ``The
police knew exactly where the truck was the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Trucking executives say GPS devices are necessary because the
value of cargo in a single trailer can easily surpass the price of
several houses. The information allows clients to know how soon
their goods will arrive, a significant point because many car
manufacturers and groceries keep costs down by keeping very little
in warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Before GPS technology and on-board computers became common on
trucks, drivers frequently had to telephone headquarters to tell
dispatchers where they were and when they had dropped off their
loads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without global positioning, you're at the driver's mercy,''
said Dick Reiser, executive vice president and general counsel for
Werner Enterprises, a trucking company based in Omaha. ``They might
call and say they were in Denver, but they really might be in
Cheyenne or Salt Lake City. We wouldn't really know.''
</P>
<P>
   While many drivers have embraced the infusion of technology into
their profession in recent years, others are quite critical. Jeff
Allen, who owns his own truck cab and travels with a pet rabbit in
the passenger's seat, has a television, a VCR and a microwave in
the back of his cab, but there were no gadgets on his dashboard to
speak of that could be seen recently under the soda cans and food
wrappers that had accumulated in two weeks on the road.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the TA truck stop, Allen said it was no one's
business what he was doing as long as he did not get into an
accident. But that attitude is more a matter of principle, he said,
than an effort to hide illegality. ``If my company is going to dial
me up 24 hours a day, it's an invasion of my privacy,'' Allen said.
``When I'm in my truck, I'm in my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies provide computer technology to contract drivers,
and some require that drivers hired on contracts provide their own
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Allen once worked for a company that tracked his whereabouts
electronically. In response, he occasionally taped a metal bucket
over the satellite dish on the back of his tractor to block the
signal.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's dispatcher asked about his communications gaps only
once. In that case, he was trying to hide the fact that he was
behind schedule and was speeding to make up time. ``They asked: `We
were tracking you and you were in Los Angeles, then we looked and
you were in Flagstaff. What happened?''' Allen recalled. ``I told
them I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of technologies seemed to get universal approval from
the nearly dozen truckers interviewed at the truck stop. They all
liked the prepass cards that allow drivers in good standing to
avoid waiting in line at many state inspection stations.
</P>
<P>
   If trucks are equipped with the cards, which act like radio-wave
transponders, drivers can roll by on the freeway without stopping.
Computers in the inspection station automatically recognize the
truck by scanning from a distance the prepass card mounted on the
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Equipping a truck with the latest technology does not come
cheap. Computers and sensors can add nearly $15,000 to the cost of
a tractor (which pulls the trailer); a tractor sells for about
$120,000 without these new bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, satellite systems do fail, and computers do crash.
And some trucking companies stick to the simpler forms of
communication technology: cellular phones, CB radios and beepers,
which all have limited ranges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technologies are good, but they can only do so much,'' said
Fuller, of U.S. Xpress. ``If you hire the right driver, they can
exceed whatever technology you can put in place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
