<HEADLINE>
FLAT SCREEN: FAST FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: (AT) in the e-mail address in the last graf should be
replaced with the typographical symbol.) 
(js) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the difference (besides price and size) between
regular monitors and the new flat ones?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: There are many complex issues involved, but perhaps the
biggest difference between conventional desktop computer monitors
and the new flat-panel displays is that they use different
technologies to display images. Most desktop monitors use
cathode-ray tubes, or CRTs. A CRT monitor gets its illumination
from three electron guns firing at the phosphor-coated glass
screen. Because of all the internal hardware, CRTs tend to be
large, hot and bulky. They also flicker more.
</P>
<P>
   Like laptops, the flat-panel displays use liquid-crystal display
(LCD) technology. An LCD screen is illuminated by a fluorescent
backlight. These monitors have been known to cause less eye fatigue
than a CRT monitor. The new flat-panel displays cost much more than
CRT monitors, take up much less room and flicker less.
</P>
<P>
   While LCD screens have often been accused of having inconsistent
color and fuzzier pictures, several manufacturers have come up with
prototypes that have pictures sharper and clearer than those on CRT
screens. If you are making a purchase and want to read some reviews
of products first, try the
computers.yahoo.com/computers/peripherals/monitor page at Yahoo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
