<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT &LR;      03-03 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYER URGES CONGRESS TO ABANDON INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer for President Clinton said Wednesday that
after years of supporting the independent counsel statute he now
views it as a legal ``nuclear weapon'' that cannot be fixed and
should be allowed to lapse when it expires later this year.
</P>
<P>
   At a Senate hearing, the lawyer, Robert S. Bennett said:
``Rather than freeing prosecutorial discretion from political bias,
the act has become yet another weapon, indeed a nuclear weapon in
the arsenal of partisan politics. Partisan politics infects every
phase of the process. The public now views the independent counsel
process as largely a political process.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett is a veteran Washington defense lawyer who has
represented Clinton in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit.
Bennett has for years defended officials caught up in independent
counsel inquiries, including top Republicans, like former Defense
Secretary Caspar Weinberger, and Democrats, like former White House
Deputy Chief of Staff Harold Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett told the Governmental Affairs Committee, which is
considering reauthorization of the statute that beyond allowing the
law to die, that existing independent counsels should be shut down
and their work turned over to the Justice Department when the law
expires.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law, enacted in 1978 as an important
post-Watergate reform, was designed to remove politics from
inquiries of high-level executive branch officials. But instead,
lawmakers from both parties have assailed the law as a political
vehicle to use against presidents and their high level appointees.
</P>
<P>
   But at Wednesday's hearing, senators expressed reservations
about eliminating the independent counsel law altogether, primarily
because such a move would leave the Justice Department with a
greater role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to begin preparing eulogies,'' said Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., who has urged colleagues to look for ways to
change the law instead of killing it.
</P>
<P>
   If independent counsel law was abandoned, Attorney General Janet
Reno would wield greater authority in politically sensitive cases
involving high level officials. But Republican lawmakers have long
questioned her objectivity, bitterly criticizing Reno for
protecting the Clinton administration when she repeatedly refused
to seek an independent prosecutor in the campaign finance case.
</P>
<P>
   But Nathan Lewin, an attorney who represented former Attorney
General Edwin Meese III when Meese's financial dealings were
investigated by an independent counsel, said the law should be
maintained in some form. Lewin said that in Meese's case, a
decision by the independent counsel not to charge Meese with a
crime was a far more powerful statement than if it had come from
any official at the Justice Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
