   These sports stories for release Thursday, March 4, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-USOC-REACT _ WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Olympic Committee wants
the White House to place the scandal-ridden IOC under federal laws
that will force leaders of the games to live up to the ``noble
ideals they profess.'' Saying strong action was needed to avoid
``the loss of the Olympic Games,'' USOC president Bill Hybl said
today he would ask President Clinton that the IOC be identified as
a public international organization under the Federal Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act. He said he expected other nations ``to
support this initiative as an important way to truly level the
playing field'' for all cities seeking to stage the Olympics. Hybl
said the USOC's executive committee had approved all the
recommendations made by the ethics panel led by former Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 20.
</P>
<P>
   With list of recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (s) sports and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   SEC/ACC TOURNAMENTS
</P>
<P>
   BKC-SEC-PREVIEW _ ATLANTA _ There appears to be new blood in SEC
basketball circles this season. In a league long dominated by
Kentucky, several teams appear ready to challenge the Wildcats for
league supremacy as the postseason tournament begins today at the
Georgia Dome. Surprising Auburn, led by junior Chris Porter, was a
landslide winner in the SEC West and claimed the conference's
regular-season title. Guard Tony Harris helped Tennessee dethrone
Kentucky at the top of the SEC East and Mike Miller was one of
several freshmen who helped Florida contend for the Eastern
Division title until the final week of the season. Kentucky has won
six of the last seven tournament championships, but it appears that
another team could earn the title this season. (Wilkinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-ACC-COLLIER _ CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ If Georgia Tech hopes to
have any success in the ACC tournament, it will have to depend on a
player who has yet to play in an ACC tournament game in his career.
Forward Jason Collier has emerged as Tech's top player since
becoming eligible in December, leading the team in scoring and
earning second-team All-ACC honors. But Collier has yet to play in
the conference's postseason tournament and is looking forward to
the opportunity to help Tech possibly earn an NIT berth. (Arey,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-ACC-PREVIEW _ CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ ACC tournament advance.
(Barnhart, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-MADDUX _ LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ QandA with Greg
Maddux. (Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-NOTES _ LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _Braves notebook.
(Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-DODGERS-PREVIEW _ VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Just call it progress:
The Los Angeles Dodgers, under Fox ownership, are now prepared to
leave the sacred Dodgertown in Vero Beach for more luxurious, and
cheaper, digs in Arizona. (Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20.
</P>
