<P>
   COLUMNISTS
</P>
<P>
   BISHER-COLUMN-TRIBUTE _ ATLANTA _ I know of no man who loved
golf more than Tom McCollister. He loved to play, he loved to talk
it, he loved to walk it. Once had a hole-in-one in the Atlanta
Classic pro-am. He had a sweet swing that I envied. Mine looked
like a logger trying to fell a tree. He was good company on a golf
course. I raged in despair. He took the breaks as they came and
moved on. That was just his nature, as it was when he was moved
from the golf beat to the snarling world of stock-car racing. He
took it and moved on, did well and soon had the respect of those
guys used to living at 190 mph. After all those nomadic years on
the stock-car run, this was to be a homecoming. No more accursed
jams trying to get to the track. Home at last. Return to the
Masters. Back to what he loved. Golf. And what happens? One mile
from home, the car of another person he had never seen and his car
come together at an intersection, and Tom McCollister is gone. This
is one of the saddest days of our life around here. (Bisher,
Atlanta Journal) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NUHN-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Gary Nuhn tells the story of a boy
with a brain injury, a supportive family, and a boxer _ Pernell
Whitaker _ who took the time. (Nuhn, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
