<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE04-CO     03-03 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online banking seen as a blueprint for change
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine a financial secretary who keeps track of your
bills, pays them when due _ and lives on the Internet or the hard
drive of your computer.
</P>
<P>
   That's the promise of electronic banking: to automate the
routine chores of paying bills, checking bank balances and
balancing your checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   After years of false starts, the software and financial industry
are starting to deliver on that promise. Today, if you have a
computer and a modem, you can pay bills electronically. You also
can check on bank and credit card balances, stop payment on
electronic checks and send messages to your bank.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic ways to bank electronically. First, you can
do so directly through the Internet. Banks such as NationsBank and
Wachovia let you perform most banking services through a Web page.
Those services include viewing statements and paying bills.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need any special software, other than a Web browser,
and can view your banking statements from any computer, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Your second choice is you can bank online through a software
package such as Quicken or Microsoft Money. First Union and
SunTrust are banks that use this method. You have to first buy the
software, which typically sells for between $40 and $60.
</P>
<P>
   The software, using a modem in your computer, contacts the bank.
The bank then sends your banking information electronically into
the software.
</P>
<P>
   How well does electronic banking work? For the past year, I have
been testing it as a consumer. I used the popular personal finance
software Quicken. With it, I paid bills and maintained an
electronic banking account with SunTrust Bank, based in downtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   SunTrust will not say how many electronic banking customers it
has, but officials say the number is higher than they expected.
``We're been very pleased with the results so far,'' says John
McGuire, president and chief executive of SunTrust Online.
</P>
<P>
   He says SunTrust will add a Web-based banking service this
summer similar to that offered by competitors NationsBank and
Wachovia. ``I think the market is right to make a move to the
Internet,'' says McGuire.
</P>
<P>
   I found SunTrust's service, which is representative of what
other banks and software companies are offering, to be secure and
reliable. Not once did either SunTrust or Quicken misstate my
balance, make incorrect charges against my account or lose any of
my money. Every charge I made, whether by check or debit card, was
recorded in my electronic balance.
</P>
<P>
   But electronic banking is far from perfect.
</P>
<P>
   For one, your electronic balance often is not up to date. The
reason is twofold.
</P>
<P>
   Most merchants don't accept electronic payments, says Celia
Saino, Intuit's product manager for the Mac version of Quicken.
Saino says Quicken or SunTrust must pay them by check, which adds
four to five days to the time between when you pay and the payment
clears your bank.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, SunTrust and other banks typically wait at least 24
hours before updating your electronic balance, says Saino.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken also can't identify written checks. What you'll see in
your electronic statement is that check number so and so has
cleared _ but it does not identify who cashed the check.
</P>
<P>
   While not as bad, debit card purchases also can be hard to
identify. Often what shows up in your statement is not a merchant's
name but an unintelligible string of numbers or an address.
</P>
<P>
   I have one monthly payment, my mortgage, that Quicken always
fails to recognize and reconcile with my electronic checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   In short, electronic banking is for the patient and forgiving,
and for those who like trying the newest thing. If that describes
you, here's what you'll need to bank electronically:
</P>
<P>
   I'd recommend a computer with the most modern operating system.
That means System 8.5 with the Mac and Windows 98 with PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Next you'll need a modem, the device that lets your computer
communicate with other computers through a telephone line. Modems
are either built into computers or sold separately.
</P>
<P>
   All electronic banking programs work through software. With
Internet banks, that software is embedded in the Web page and is
invisible to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't choose an Internet bank, you'll need to buy one of
the personal finance programs mentioned earlier. Each program walks
you through the process of setting up electronic bill payment and
banking. You don't need a bank to pay your bills electronically.
These programs have their own services that enable that.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll need a bank to do anything more than bill paying.
Each of these programs has a list of participating banks. You'll
have to sign up with the bank yourself, but it's easy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
