<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPER-BRIGHT-HEADLIGH     03-03 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-BRIGHT-HEADLIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERBRIGHT HEADLIGHTS THAT, LOVED BY DRIVERS, CAN BLIND
PEDESTRIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By PHILIP NOBEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Laurie Cribbs bought her new Lexus LS 400 for its
luxurious appointments, but what really impressed her were its
trend setting superbright headlights. ``I noticed them right away
because I didn't like to drive at night before,'' Ms. Cribbs said
recently from the offices of Marriott International in Potomac,
Md., where she works as a senior financial manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my car now, it's like night and day. The headlights light
up everything so much, it's very noticeable. With the brights on,
it's like daylight.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The technology that tamed the night for Ms. Cribbs is called
High Intensity Discharge, or HID, and it is an increasingly
hard-to-miss sight on the nation's roads. HID headlights throw a
broad field of intensely clear light _ so white-hot that it appears
to burn blue at the edges.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits for drivers are equally clear. Compared to standard
yellow-white headlights, HID cuts through the night with light that
more closely approximates the spectrum of light from the sun.
Darkness is banished as the car drives forward into its own private
pocket of renewable daylight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But because of its intensity, HID could cause problems for
pedestrians caught in its glare. The same light that's so easy on
the eyes of someone driving one of the high-end imports that now
offer the technology can be blinding for those on the other side of
the windshield. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Beschle, engineering manager for HID design at Osram
Sylvania, a leading manufacturer of automotive lighting, says that
it is the novelty of the lights that is catching people off guard.
``It looks so different that people stare at it,'' he said. ``And
if you stare at any bright light, it will bother you.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Ferris, a spokeswoman for Lexus, has come to the same
conclusion. ``When I see them I think, `Are they different, or are
they blinding me?''' she said. ``I've decided that they're just
different.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HID is as different from a typical halogen headlight as a
100-watt bulb is from stadium lighting. In place of a glowing
filament, HID generates light by charging a sealed chamber of inert
xenon gas, a cousin of neon from the far right-hand column of the
periodic table.
</P>
<P>
   To turn the lights on, the xenon is blasted with 10,000 volts of
electricity, which arcs through the gas. A much lower voltage,
regulated by an electrical ballast, is then used to maintain the
scalding glow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, this technology comes at a cost. Currently, HID
is common only on imported luxury cars from Lexus, Mercedes and
BMW, and on two American-made cars, the Acura TL and the GMC Envoy.
Around the world, however, there are now 55 models that support HID
lights.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, where an industry source estimates that one car in
five uses them, they are beginning to be standard equipment even on
midrange cars like the Volkswagen Golf. Sally Moran, vice president
for sales and marketing at Osram Sylvania, claims that an HID
invasion of the American market is inevitable, perhaps as soon as
the 2003 model year. ``It's coming. It's coming to the U.S. It'll
be on our cars soon,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (For those unwilling to wait and unable to afford a car with
true HID, look-alike halogen lights are being marketed by Sylvania
and other companies under names like Cool Blue, Bluevision and
Plasma Blue.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of New York City, at least, HID is still a
curiosity: an occasional blue flare that punctuates the flow of
yellow headlights rolling down the avenues. But in greater numbers
_ two on every car _ what effect will they have? How will urban
areas absorb a light that was developed to overcome the darkness of
the autobahn and interstate? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leni Schwendinger, a lighting designer and founder of Light
Projects, a New York studio that focuses on public art and
architecture, is concerned that HID headlights are ``asking a lot
of people's pupils.'' Because the HID light is so much brighter,
she says, it will make surrounding areas seem darker by contrast,
initiating a game of catch-up that could ultimately lead to higher
light levels everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But she did not discount the appeal of the hot blue lights: ``It
seems like a dangerous, weaponlike moving body is bearing down on
you,'' she said. ``At the same time, the purity of the light is
sort of sublime: elegant and ominous at the same time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
