<SLUG> BC-THAILAND-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THAILAND, ALBRIGHT HEARS HOW U.S. AID FIGHTS DRUGS AND
PROSTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIANG MAI, Thailand _ Madeleine Albright put a human face on
foreign policy Wednesday, listening to a group of young Thai women
explain how U.S. aid money had helped turn them away from drugs and
prostitution and toward meaningful jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It was unusual for a U.S. secretary of state to be sitting at a
table with rural women one third her age in an out-of-the-way town
in northern Thailand. Proudly, Albright acknowledged as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing things secretaries of state didn't do,'' she told
the women, some in the ornate dress and headgear of the Hilltribe
people. ``Partially because they interest me but more importantly
because they are new elements of American foreign policy.'' In the
United States, she said, ``combating drugs is a job for the
secretary of state.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright met with trainees from the New Life Center and Thai
Women of Tomorrow to highlight what money from the U.S. Agency for
International Development can do.
</P>
<P>
   The programs, which were visited two years ago by Hillary Rodham
Clinton, claim success in educating and then giving vocational
training to girls who have been rescued from opium-addicted
parents, or from brothels and drug dens.
</P>
<P>
   Albright arrived in Thailand primarily to boost the government
in its painful path of economic reform after the financial crash in
1997. The Thai economy is still shrinking, but Clinton
administration officials said the worst appeared to be over.
Foreign reserves, which had sharply diminished, have begun to build
up, and there are signs of the return of foreign investment.
Washington is encouraged by the government's efforts to restructure
the banking system, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But before meetings in Bangkok, Albright wanted to show the
importance of dealing with the social side of the financial crisis
and to demonstrate her interest in the well-being of women.
</P>
<P>
   In rural Thailand, young women are expected to become the
breadwinners for elderly parents and relatives. Without jobs, they
become vulnerable targets for traffickers in women and prostitution
rings.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women at the roundtable session with Albright,
Chanpen Promsen, 21, told how after finishing school she had stayed
at home looking after the family.
</P>
<P>
   A former teacher got in touch with her and suggested she go to
Bangkok for six months vocational training under the Women for
Tomorrow program. She had returned home, Ms. Promsen said, and was
now employed as a garment worker. ``I'm making money and can
support my family,'' Ms. Promsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the morning, Albright took a 20-minute drive through
tropical vegetation of banana and bamboo trees to the village of
Nong Hoi where the Thai royal family has been helping farmers grow
fruit and vegetables instead of opium.
</P>
<P>
   The Thai government has made substantial progress in eliminating
opium-growing in northern Thailand, which is part of the area known
as the Golden Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Albright went out of her way to praise the Thais for curbing
opium growing by the introduction of crop substitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in marked contrast to the country of Burma, where they
are not doing the kinds of things you are doing,'' she said. In the
last two years, she said, Washington has contributed $1.3 million
to the crop substitution program.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic-covered hot houses bearing carrots and cabbages laced
the terraces of the village, and Albright was shown around a
vegetable stand by Prince Bhisadej Rajani, a cousin of King
Bhumibol Adulyadej.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are saying no to narcotics and yes to vegetables,''
said Albright, who was dressed for the tropics in an ankle-length
cotton purple skirt and jacket and black straw sunhat.
</P>
<P>
   With a can of locally produced guava juice in one hand, Albright
listened to the prince explain that growing vegetables was not only
good social policy but good economics, too.
</P>
<P>
   Local farmers who used to earn the equivalent of $100 a year
from opium now earn about $1,200, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's stunning,'' Ms. Albright said. ``It's not as though
they are losing money, they are making money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
