<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PET-ALLERGY-ART-2TAKE     03-03 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PET-ALLERGY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEARING THE AIR WHEN THE DOG MUST STAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When I adopted a big Labrador mutt from the streets
of Red Hook, Brooklyn, I never dreamed I'd be allergic to her. But
every time she flopped down on the floor, little clouds of hair
drifting into the air, I sneezed. My eyes itched. I developed what
felt like a chronic cold. If she slept in my room, I'd wake up with
that tight feeling in my chest so familiar from an asthmatic
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get rid of the dog,'' my doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Control the problem at its source. That's the first advice any
health official will give you. But by then, I was hooked on Red,
and so was Hemingway, the white Great Pyrenees who lives
downstairs. I didn't want to break up the pack. I called an allergy
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open the windows,'' said Dr. David Valacer, director of the
Children's Allergy, Immunology and Respiratory Center at New York
Presbyterian Hospital. ``The dander will be diluted by the air
brought into the house.''
</P>
<P>
   That was my routine, until the cold weather set in. I'd vacuum
the rugs and floors, then open the windows to let out all the dust
and dander that my old vacuum cleaner had belched into the air. But
come winter, I was watching waves of heat roll out the windows
along with the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Valacer said I could try an air cleaner as a third, less than
perfect line of defense. ``We commonly recommend them to people
with chronic respiratory problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's how I plunged into the world of air cleaners. It's one
thing to test them in sealed laboratories, as engineers do for
Consumers Union and the Association of Home Appliance
Manufacturers, but how would they work in my overheated, dog-ridden
Brooklyn apartment?
</P>
<P>
   And another thing: How was the consumer supposed to wade through
the variety of air cleaners _ HEPA filters (an acronym for ``high
efficiency particulate arresting''), ionizers, electrostatic
precipitators _ and the promises of clean air that go with them,
and choose a good one? Or are we all being suckered into buying a
$300 machine that's really just a placebo?
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association cites indoor air pollution as a
high-priority health risk, because Americans spend about 90 percent
of their lives indoors. They are breathing hair sprays, cleaning
agents, toxic chemicals in wallboard, furniture and carpets, as
well as allergens produced by dust mites, cockroaches, rodents,
dogs and cats.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, asthma, particularly in children, has
increased from 9.9 million cases in 1988 to the lung association's
projection of 17.3 million in 1998. Asthma-related deaths rose from
4,597 in 1988 to 5,667 in 1996. Though the lung association and the
Environmental Protection Agency suggest that air cleaners can cut
pollutants, they warn that they are not cure-alls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent air devices can clean particles and gases from the air,
but the question is, does that benefit health, and can you clean
enough?'' asked Dr. John Samet, epidemiology chairman of the Johns
Hopkins University School of Hygiene and Public Health. ``By and
large, they can't clean a lot of air. For some problems, like a
cat, they're not strong enough, because cat allergen is so
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   So are allergens from dust mites, those microscopic organisms
that thrive by feeding on our skin debris and spread allergens
through their fecal matter. ``It could be that exposure comes when
you lie down on the couch and breathe the little cloud of dust that
arises,'' Samet said. ``Or the baby crawling on the floor with his
nose grinding into the carpet. An air cleaner is not going to do
much for that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic kinds of air cleaners _ mechanical filters
and electronic cleaners _ and some are hybrids of the two.
</P>
<P>
   HEPA filters are the workhorses of the mechanical class in the
burgeoning world of air cleaners, now a $200 million industry. HEPA
filters, which are used with fans, are made of densely packed glass
fibers, which snag 99.7 percent of airborne particles as small as
0.3 microns (still larger than a virus). But don't think they'll
clean up fumes from the trash transfer station down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``HEPA filters will remove some particulates from the air, but
they won't address gases, which produce odors, and need more than
filtration,'' said Frank Iacopelli, the engineer at Consumers Union
who headed a 1992 study of air cleaners. Some, HEPA models
included, use activated charcoal or zeolite to attract gases _ a
process called adsorption _ but the adsorbent can be used up
quickly. ``I've seen some air cleaners with very small charcoal
filters that could be used up in a matter of days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other air cleaners operate by electrical attraction. The
simplest kind, a negative-ion generator, charges the air with
negative ions, which attract positively charged particles _ pollen,
dog hair, tobacco smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, those particles have to go somewhere,''
Iacopelli said. ``So now they're clinging to the furniture, the
walls and the positively charged carpet, so the minute you walk
over it, they're thrown back in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Electrostatic precipitators solve this problem somewhat by
drawing particle-laden air past collector plates in the unit. You
have to clean the plates, but the machines are quieter than
HEPA-filter devices.
</P>
<P>
   Beware of ozone generators, which are often sold door to door.
They're promoted as air cleaners capable of breaking down odors and
gases, but the EPA and Consumers Union warn against them, because
they can actually increase toxic gases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how much ozone these things produce,'' said Dr.
Richard Shaughnessy, a chemical engineer and program manager of
indoor air research at the University of Tulsa. ``And ozone is not
effective in reducing particles or removing gases.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there is no standard for measuring air cleaner
performance, though the Association of Home Appliance
Manufacturers, a voluntary group, has established what it calls a
clean air delivery rate, representing the number of cubic feet of
clean air a unit puts into the room each minute. A high rate is a
good sign, but also pay attention to the unit's efficiency, and
choose a model that suits your room size.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So I went down the list from the manufacturers' group and chose
some top-rated units. I also tried an ionizer from Sharper Image,
which came highly recommended by a friend with respiratory
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Honeywell Enviracaire, with a HEPA filter, is the size of an
overnight case and has a pleasing shape, which reminded me of an
ocean wave. I turned it on high for a few hours, with two dogs in
the room, and the air got much less doggy. But I got more and more
agitated by the loud fan, so I turned it down to low and went to
bed. With the windows closed, I got so hot I thought I had a fever.
Another night, my landlady downstairs borrowed it after frying fish
and reported that it cleared the air in about an hour. Her husband
couldn't bear the noise.
</P>
<P>
   The Friedrich C-90A, an electrostatic precipitator, was top
rated in Consumer Reports in 1992. After I vacuumed with the
windows closed and let the dogs jump around, it cleared the air in
an hour and was quieter, at high, than the HEPA fan models. But
it's bulky _ as big as a Friedrich air-conditioner _ and costs a
high-end $499.
</P>
<P>
   Bionaire sent two models, one with an ULPA filter, which goes
HEPA one better, by filtering out particulates at a rate of 99.99
percent at 0.1 micron. It also has an ionizer. I blew cigar smoke
around the room and turned the unit to high, and the ionizer as
well. After an hour, the smoke was gone, but not the stale cigar
smell, and the air had an acrid odor from the ionizer. The machine
was so noisy that I turned it off.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the Bionaire ``odor removing'' model better. It's an
adsorption type, using a powerful fan to draw odors through a
carbon and zeolite filter. It's also a cute, round unit, about the
size of a hatbox. The fan was loud at high, but it cleared the air
of cigar smoke in about half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   I tested Vornado units one rainy day when the dogs' wet fur was
flying, and the HEPA filters worked well for clearing the air of
fur. They were too noisy for me. I had the same problem with a
Hunter Fan model, which has an ionizer and a fan that draws
particles through two filters. It did a fair job of clearing the
air, but I thought I was living inside an aircraft hangar.
</P>
<P>
   This is a personal thing, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The noise doesn't bother me; it's like white noise,'' said
Tara Adler, who has four Honeywell Enviracaire units. She has three
cats and smokes. And she shares the house with a man who's allergic
to cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The filters are a lifesaver,'' Ms. Adler said. ``We run one in
the dining room, one in the workroom, one in the bedroom, and one
goes wherever we need it. At first, we were running them on high
all the time, and our electric bill shot up $90, so now we run them
more selectively.'' The noise bothers her domestic partner, though,
so he turns the bedroom unit on in the evenings, then turns it off
when he goes to bed.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharper Image ionizer was gloriously silent _ it has no fan
_ and it has a sleek, space-age design. A narrow tower has a
four-pronged set of plates that look like a tuning fork. You clean
them off when they get gray with particles. It got rid of the dog
fur, but I hated the way the air smelled _ like bleach. That's the
smell of ozone, and ionizers make some but not enough to be
unhealthful, the experts say, unless they are improperly
maintained. (The Food and Drug Administration has set a limit of 50
parts per billion as a safe level in the home.)
</P>
<P>
   I didn't like the idea of adding any ozone to my house, so I
opened a window _ a no-no if you want optimal performance in an air
cleaner. Opening a window on my street brings in more pollution, of
course. It's the same problem as someone smoking in the room. ``The
air cleaner is continually trying to remove smoke, but you're
continually adding,'' said John Sabelli, a staff engineer for
Intertek Testing Services in Cortland, N.Y., which tests the units
in the manufacturers' association program. ``Still, you'll have a
lower level of smoke than if you didn't have the air cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't expect an air cleaner the size of a hatbox to clean
your whole house. ``It's like putting an air-conditioner
outdoors,'' Sabelli said. ``You're not going to cool the whole
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine. I would crack the windows and operate my favorite _ the
Honeywell _ only when that dog hair reached tornado levels. I could
turn it up to high and leave the house for a few hours. I would
turn it off when the noise got to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want,'' Sabelli said. ``Quiet, or clean air?''
Yeah. Outside the lab, life is full of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to do a bit of research before plunging into the
wonderland of air cleaners. Here are a few places to start:
</P>
<P>
   American Lung Association: www.lungusa.org or (800) 586-4872. It
has a good report, ``Residential Air Cleaning Devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Protection Agency: www.epa.gov/iaq will lead you
to research on subjects from indoor pollutants to the dangers of
ozone generators.
</P>
<P>
   Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers: www.aham.org or
(312) 984-5800. The association tests air cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union: Web site is www.consunion.org. Researchers will
test air cleaners this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
