<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-MODERN-2TAKES-     03-03 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-MODERN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE PLANS AN ARTS BLITZ OF THE WEST COAST  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash.)   By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delacroix, Cezanne, Manet, Monet, Matisse ... and, and? While
people around the world are lining up to see French masters, not to
mention expatriates like van Gogh and Picasso who spent most of
their careers in France, the country's contemporary artists are not
carrying on the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Germany can boast of international art stars like Gerhard
Richter, Anselm Kiefer and Sigmar Polke. Britain can take pride in
Lucian Freud and young Brit Pack artists like Damien Hirst and
Rachel Whiteread. The United States has Jasper Johns, Richard
Serra, Bruce Nauman, Elizabeth Murray, Cindy Sherman and many more.
</P>
<P>
   But France?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Arman, but he is of a different generation,'' said
Pierre Buhler, the French cultural counselor in New York. ``And
Christian Boltanski. Annette Messager and Sophie Calle have had
some success here. You know Kiefer is now working in France. But we
will not appropriate him.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is galling to a nation ever eager to proclaim its
cultural superiority.
</P>
<P>
   The French government, in inimitable dirigiste fashion, is now
trying to intervene. If all goes as planned next fall, dozens of
galleries, contemporary art centers, museums and art schools on the
West Coast will participate in ``Cote Ouest: A Season of French
Contemporary Art.'' The promotional material for the event, which
was planned by the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs, says it is
``the biggest initiative to date to promote foreign art in the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   To pull it off, France had to dangle a few enticements. Through
its embassy in the United States and the Association Francaise
d'Action Artistique, a government-financed agency, it paid for
American museum and gallery curators to visit France to view
available art. It offered subsidies to art centers that agreed to
show work in the United States. It promised to bring French artists
to the United States for workshops and lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Etant Donnes, a French-American Fund for Contemporary Art,
volunteered to help museums find American corporate and foundation
sponsors for exhibitions. The principal benefactors of Etant
Donnes, aside from the Florence Gould Foundation in New York, are
all French: Air France, Banque Nationale de Paris and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   When everything is added up, government and private support for
``Cote Ouest'' may exceed $1 million, which is not extraordinary.
In 1998 French government agencies spent about $500,000 promoting
their contemporary artists in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   French artists lag nonetheless, the magazine L'Express observed
last fall in an article about New York's rule over the art world.
Michael Kimmelman, the chief art critic of The New York Times, was
among the experts interviewed by the magazine. ``For the visual
arts, France is now considered to be the rear guard among the great
European nations,'' he said. Though it was the center of the art
world until World War II, he added, ``France pretty much dropped
off the map'' by the 1960s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Buhler brushed off such talk. ``It's possible that our artists
are not known enough and were not marketed or did not market
themselves enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans agree. Shoshana Wayne, who owns a gallery in
Santa Monica, Calif., and who intends to participate in ``Cote
Ouest,'' cited the publicity coups by France's rivals. ``There is
very good work being done in France right now,'' she said, ``but
the galleries, the museums, the collectors and the government are
not creating a scene the way they do in London.''
</P>
<P>
   But many more experts say the reasons for France's decline in
artistic standing run deeper. Some cite a dearth of French
collectors of contemporary art and France's failure over the years
to generate the wealth that begets new collectors. Others say that
French artists suffer because they shun the commercial system that
creates ``hot'' art stars. It is also possible that French art is
simply in a fallow period.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts say that France's arts bureaucracy, which gives
generous grants and even helps artists find studios, has stifled
rather than fostered creativity. ``We have the impression of an
institutionalized system, where creativity is sustained by the
state,'' Kimmelman told L'Express. ``And this induces a certain
complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly at the risk of reinforcing such impressions, then,
France is organizing ``Cote Ouest.'' ``We in the embassy and in the
AFAA decided to go as big as we could,'' Buhler said. They invited
West Coast curators and dealers to Paris to visit museums,
galleries and artists and subsidized the trips. ``About 10 went,
possibly more,'' Buhler said. Thomas Collins, an associate curator
at the Henry Art Gallery of the University of Washington, for
example, spent a week and a half in France last fall, visiting
about 18 studios, about 10 art centers and several galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Buhler said: ``The whole thing snowballed, and now we have
such demand. It's unprecedented to have an exhibition stretch over
so many miles.'' Come October, he hopes, 12 museums, 5
universities, 9 alternative spaces, 3 public art projects, 19
galleries and an art fair will take part in ``Cote Ouest.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; nn
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be a little hype, as well as hope, in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Contemporary Art in Los Angeles, for example, is
on the list and did send a curator to Paris to research French
artists, courtesy of the event's French sponsors. But the museum
will not take part. Kathleen S. Bartels, the museum's associate
director, said that a fall show ``didn't fit in our schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art said that its
schedule for October through January was fully booked by the time
the French approached them, although the museum is cited in the
organizers' news release as a participant.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Sobieszek, the photography curator at the museum,
explained the discrepancy. In a history of photographic portraiture
that he has been working on for 30 years, he is including French
items, from 1830s daguerreotypes to current work of Orlan, a woman
who alters her appearance through numerous plastic surgery
operations and then photographs herself. ``I already had some
French stuff in it, but I haven't changed the show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there was no temptation: ``If I did a whole project,''
Sobieszek said, ``they offered me up to $20,000, and they said they
would bring the artist out.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are a number of participants. Collins, curator of the
Henry Art Gallery, said that the gallery would show works by Gilles
Barbier. In San Francisco, the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts
plans to exhibit sketches and sculptures by Jean-Michel Othoniel,
and Camera Work will show photos by Stephane Couturier. Several
commercial galleries are planning exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wayne, the gallery owner in Santa Monica, said: ``I thought
this was a great opportunity. I can't talk about the money, but
that's not the reason I'd do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point it is hard to determine whether ``Cote Ouest''
will succeed or what criteria should apply in judging it. ``From a
P.R. standpoint, it couldn't fail to gain attention,'' Collins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other art experts doubt that ``Cote Ouest'' will change
attitudes toward French art. ``Given the efficiency of
communications today, works of art of interest and quality float to
the surface of public perception pretty quickly, internationally
and nationally,'' said Lucy Mitchell-Innes, a dealer and the former
head of Sotheby's contemporary art department in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good artist gets shows in New York with ease today, and
Paris is not some forgotten, out of the way place,'' she said.
``One really has to look at what's being made there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
