<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-USOC-REACT _ WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Olympic Committee wants
the White House to place the scandal-ridden IOC under federal laws
that will force leaders of the games to live up to the ``noble
ideals they profess.'' Saying strong action was needed to avoid
``the loss of the Olympic Games,'' USOC president Bill Hybl said
today he would ask President Clinton that the IOC be identified as
a public international organization under the Federal Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 20.
With list of recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (w) Washington and (s) sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and
congressional Democrats are rolling out an ambitious legislative
agenda, looking to gain a tactical advantage over Republican
lawmakers still wrestling with their plans. Clinton scheduled a
meeting today with House and Senate Democrats to present their 1999
``Families First'' agenda, a four-page political wish list topped
by a bid to set aside 77 percent of projected federal budget
surpluses for Social Security and Medicare. Rep. John Lewis will be
there. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   PORK _ WASHINGTON _ A museum for first ladies in Ohio and one to
honor Frank Sinatra in New York, a water taxi for Savannah and an
$86 million courthouse for Jacksonville, Fla., are among this
year's prime pork items listed by the annual Pig Book put out by
Citizen's Against Government Waste. (Malone).
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-TRUST _ WASHINGTON _ Displaying photos of Bureau of
Indian Affairs records piled in trash bags and beside mop buckets,
Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., warned Interior Secretary
Bruce Babbitt on Wednesday to clean up ``the Indian trust funds
mess'' that has tied up billions of dollars owed to tribes and
individual native Americans. (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GARLAND _ Trying again for interview with Elizabeth Garland,
anthropology student who escaped from Rwandan rebels who killed
foreign tourists in Uganda. (DeBrosse, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   AUS-BUSH-VS-PEROT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Bush vs. Perot II? In 1992,
the Dallas billionaire got in the race and may contributed toward
getting the elder George Bush out of the White House. The national
chairman of Perot's Reform Party said Wednesday he hopes Perot gets
in the 2000 presidential race. And the party's state chairman says
the younger Bush is not presidential material. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AUS-COP-SHOOTING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ An Austin cop shot someone in
Southeast Austin late Tuesday night. Guy was carrying a tree
branch. Third cop shooting in the past six weeks. (Banta, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FISH-DEAD _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Jet black'' waste from
a citrus-processing plant south of Fort Pierce has been leaking
into the North Fork of the St. Lucie River, killing fish and
microscopic marine life along a 7-mile stretch of the waterway,
state officials said Monday. (Swartz, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _ Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
