<HEADLINE>
BACK TO THE OLD GRINDSTONE FOR TRIPP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; , who turned to a
royalty specialist when she wanted a ghostwriter,  &UR; Linda Tripp &LR; 
approached  &UR; Penny Junor &LR; , who has written biographies of  &UR; Di &LR;  and
 &UR; Charles &LR;  _ and who said no thanks. ``She's the most hated woman in
America,'' said Junor, in remarks quoted in the New York Post,
``and while I feel there is a certain amount of sympathy for
Monica's situation, I can't find it in my heart to feel the same
for Linda Tripp.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, with a literary career nipped in the bud, the poor woman
had to go back to work. After a year of pulling down her $94,098
salary while ``working from home,'' Tripp returned to an office
Wednesday as a public affairs specialist in the Defense Manpower
Data Center in Rosslyn, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's job is to ``fulfill the data needs of Pentagon brass,''
a Defense Department spokesman told the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WORD PLAY'S THE THING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When mystified customer  &UR; Barbara Lewis &LR;  wrote to Yves Veggie
Cuisine, inquiring as to why one of their products is labeled
Veggie Burger Burgers, the company's Consumer Relations Coordinator
got to the heart of the matter:
</P>
<P>
   ``In response to your question, the reason for calling our
product Veggie Burger Burgers is purely marketing strategy _ as we
thought of it as being a `hook' for the consumer. Apparently we
were right!''
</P>
<P>
   _ Taking the advice of BayTV's Chef Joey,  &UR; Jane Walsh &LR;  intended
to use Alta Vista's translation capability on a recipe she found in
Spanish on the Web. Among the ingredients required for Meatball
Soup for six people: 6 cups of broth of head of cattle; 1/2 &LR;  pound
of back of worn out pig; 1 cup of mass for tortillas; 1 spoonful of
worn out onion, 1 marinate to color salt; 1 cup of worn out
chicken; and 1 spoonful of chiltoma pricked.
</P>
<P>
   _ Is it polite to jump in and help a person fumbling for a word?
</P>
<P>
   ``After a certain age,'' writes  &UR; Susan Roane &LR;  in ``What Do I Say
Next?'' (Warner; $14), ``some of us do forget words or lose our
train of thought. As my friend Lana told me, `Since I turned 50, I
lost all my nouns!' If you remember, feel free to jump-start that
train of thought. It shows you're listening, and we love those who
listen.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Randy Jurado Ertll &LR; , spokesman for the California League of
Conservation Voters, was a victim of spell-check and double
entendre when he was identified in a story in the Lynwood Press, a
Los Angeles area newspaper, as  &UR; Randy Guard Earth &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD SPORTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday &LR;   &LR; was National Sportsmanship Day, in honor of which
 &UR; Shane Murphy &LR; , author of ``The Cheers and the Tears: The Crisis in
Youth Sports Today'' (Jossey Bass; $15), reminds parents, students
and athletic directors to stop the clock, call a time-out and think
about it. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading about those high school boys forced to wear panties
for missing rebounds,  &UR; Chris Beach &LR;  was struck by the real-life
evidence. &LR; :  &UR; Dennis Rodman &LR;  is one of the NBA's most successful
rebounders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reminiscing about the 1987 night she won an Oscar for her
performance in ``Children of a Lesser God,''  &UR; Marlee Matlin &LR;  had
some not very pleasant memories of her co-star and then-boyfriend,
 &UR; William Hurt &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Hurt, 35, had been up for an Oscar for his role in the movie,
too, and had presented Matlin, 19, with the Oscar. In the limo
alone afterward, she recalled in a recent speech quoted in the New
York Daily News, Hurt turned to her and said, ``Just because you
have that little man (the Oscar) sitting next to you, do you really
think you deserve it?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nominated for an Emmy for best host of a daytime talk show,
 &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR;  took herself out of the competition. ``Last year I
was given the lifetime achievement award,'' she said, ``and after
you've achieved it for a lifetime, what else is there?''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; George Stephanopoulos &LR;  earned $4 million last year, says
Forbes magazine, making him the richest of the retired Clinton team
members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the clothes as part of my overall philosophy, like the
pursuit of goodness is my life's work, the fragility of life. I do
soak some of the clothes in eucalyptus, which is associated with
clarity and healing. And I dust them with nutmeg, which is
associated with Aphrodite.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Designer Elisa Jimenez telling Vogue about the Zen of dress
designing.
</P>
</TEXT>
