<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: THE GAME OF THE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The conundrum faced by many novelists, particularly mystery and
romance writers, is what to do when their sales have been poor and
booksellers will stock only a few copies of their new work.
</P>
<P>
   It's the slipperiest terrain there is for an author, and many
grapple with it in the way they are best trained to do, by creating
their ultimate fiction: reinventing their authorial lives with
fictional identities, pseudonyms. Sometimes more than one. Indeed,
an author often has a separate publisher for each literary life, a
sort of captain's paradise of publishing with the craving for
something fresh and hopefully exciting at each end of the shipping
lane.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to fool the booksellers' computers into believing that a
new talent is at work is not the only reason for a second- or
third-name policy. Even some successful writers do it. There is,
for instance, the desire by an author to stretch in another
direction, to pop into a genre different than the one that made the
writer famous. There is a common belief in publishing that, with
few exceptions, a writer who can produce more than one book a year
is not terribly good, so some authors churn out one book a year for
one publisher and another under a different name for a second
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   And occasionally the use of a new signature is transsexual. A
male writes as a woman, and vice versa. Ralph McInerny, for
instance, writes the Father Dowling mysteries, which form a
television series. But as Monica Quill, he also writes the Sister
Mary Teresa mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the writer's publisher, without intending to, makes
what amounts to a satire out of the whole contrivance. This month
Dutton published both a new hardcover and a paperback reprint by
the prolific literary novelist Joyce Carol Oates. The publisher
decided to piggyback the fictional Rosamond Smith onto the fame of
the real Ms. Oates, so on the cover of each the author's
identification was ``Joyce Carol Oates Writing as Rosamond Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Oates, who writes literary fiction under Oates and leaner
mystery novels under Smith, said she was perplexed by the two-name
covers but just assumed that there was a devilishly clever business
reason for it. The editor for both Oates and Smith, Rosemary Ahern,
explained that the ``secret of her pseudonym was known in some
quarters, and we persuaded Joyce to let us use both names to find
out if there was an audience for upscale mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   This thimblerigging of authors' identities is not only an
accepted device but an honored publishing one as well, one that
helps nourish the illusion that a big, if not best, seller is just
around the corner. The champion was probably John Creasey, who
wrote mysteries under 28 different names. Agatha Christie was also
Mary Westmacott, and John Dickson Carr ingeniously fooled readers
by becoming Carter Dickson. Ross Macdonald, a master, was also
Kenneth Millar, and Ed McBain and Evan Hunter are one. Lawrence
Sanders is Lesley Andress and Mark Upton.
</P>
<P>
   The edgy Ruth Rendell has a kinder and gentler self, Barbara
Vine. And Amanda Quick, who writes historical romance fiction for
Bantam Books, is also Jayne Ann Krentz, who produces what are
called ``contemporaries'' for Pocket Books. Even the
mega-best-selling Stephen King recreates himself as Richard Bachman
and John Swithen. So, too, does Ann Rice, as Anne Rampling and A.N.
Roquelaure. The list is endless.
</P>
<P>
   One reason successful genre writers use different names is to
make sure that they are not scaring off their clientele. Mary
Higgins Clark, who is always herself, said that ``if a writer feels
that her audience expects a certain kind of book, when you try
something else, it makes sense _ even if everyone knows who it is _
to use a new name.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued, ``If you've developed a loyal audience, that
audience expects something of you, and you are better off leaving
it intact.'' She said that her first book was about George
Washington, ``and it slithered out of a few bookstores and was
remaindered as it came off the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Slumbering beneath the surface of this publishing shell game is
sales, or, more precisely, lack of sales. Walter Wager, a mystery
writer and secretary of the Mystery Writers' Association of
America, said that ``publishers have a Hollywood outlook _ if you
don't sell a lot of copies, they want to drop you.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few, there is seldom big money in mysteries, which
is why mystery writers are the most frequent users of pseudonyms:
they want to trick bookstore computers to get a fresh start, Wager
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the association, the average advance for a mystery
paperback by an unknown author is $3,500 to $5,000; for an
unknown's hardcover, $5,000 to $7,000. A first printing for a
mainstream mystery _ with clues that the reader discovers the same
time the detective does _ averages about 5,000 to 7,000 copies,
except for stars like Ms. Clark. Unless the book hits, or there's a
clamor for it from the movies or television, there's really not
much money to be made creating these literary puzzles. That's the
reason so many series of mystery novels are based on one detective.
It's easier to sell them in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara D'Amato is a mystery writer and the new president of the
association. She is also president of Sisters In Crime, another
mystery writers' professional group of which 30 percent is actually
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers often feel that a writer's name gets typecast.
There's a certain publishing history on the bookstore's computer,''
Ms. D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a store ordered 15 of the writer's last book, it will
likely order no more than 15 of the next one if it hasn't sold.
It's hard for a writer to break out into higher sales that way. By
using a different name and changing publisher, you're not fooling
anybody; you're just starting out fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   So for many, any edge helps, and each new selling device brings
high hope. It is not recorded that people lined up to buy the works
of Quintus H. Flaccus. But when the pseudonym Horace was put on the
cover, ``The Odes'' became a best seller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
