<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, March 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Strong winds will buffet the Northeast Thursday morning as a
vigorous storm center moves north from upstate New York. A narrow
band of heavy snow driven by strong winds from the northwest will
prevail early Thursday morning from northwestern Pennsylvania to
western New York. The snow should taper to a few flurries by
midday. Farther east, a band of early-morning showers and a few
thunderstorms accompanied by strong winds will sweep through
eastern New England. Areas of coastal flooding will occur early
Thursday morning where winds from the southeast gust over 50 mph at
exposed coastal locations. In the wake of the showers, shifting
winds will cause dry air to surge from the Middle Atlantic states
to southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeast, gusty winds near the Atlantic coast will
gradually diminish as a ridge of high pressure moves east from the
Tennessee Valley. Except for a few early clouds near the Carolina
coast, sunshine will be plentiful throughout the region. Afternoon
temperatures will average a few degrees below the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and patchy light snow will occur near a front from
northern Iowa through the eastern Dakotas. Farther south, sunshine
will be mixed with a few clouds as winds from the south draw milder
air from Texas toward the central Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Developing low pressure over the interior West will produce
patchy snow over the mountains of western Colorado and and eastern
Utah. Meanwhile, onshore breezes will promote scattered showers
near the Northwest coast and intermittent snow in the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: From Sea to Stormy Sea
</P>
<P>
   Angry seas off the coast of Oregon swelled to heights of 40 feet
Tuesday night as a potent low pressure system armed with
hurricane-force winds swept into the Pacific Northwest. One
offshore buoy registered swells of 46 feet, a mark representing the
highest seas in recent memory, according to the National Weather
Service at Portland. The maximum wind gust was 92 mph, recorded by
the U.S. Coast Guard. Though not as fierce as the storm in the
Pacific Northwest, an expansive low pressure system over Quebec
will lash parts of the Northeast Thursday with powerful winds.
</P>
</TEXT>
