<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGE-RATES-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Mortgage rates have been climbing since Greenspan's remark  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Goodbye, Goldilocks. Hello, Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year, lenders and homeowners have celebrated the
``just-right'' Goldilocks economy that featured low mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, the
nation's top cop on the economy, hinted that the U.S. economy might
be running too hot, and the markets went into a tizzy.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's seeming willingness to increase interest rates to
cool the economy sent an already tumbling bond market even lower,
pushing yields higher. And mortgage rates, which closely track
bonds, surged higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mortgage rates didn't creep up,'' said Kansas City mortgage
lender James Nutter Jr., executive vice president of James B.
Nutter &AMP; Co. ``They shot up like a rocket, and unfortunately in our
business, rates go up faster than they come back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates on 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages shot past 7
percent in recent days as homebuyers scurried for the best deals,
and lenders worried that renewed inflation fears could increase
interest rates. Just a few weeks earlier, smart shoppers could find
mortgage rates as low as 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the average mortgage rate has increased four weeks
in a row, according to the Freddie Mac, which buys mortgages from
lenders, packages them as securities and sells them to investors.
Freddie Mac's weekly survey found an average rate of 6.89 percent,
the highest rate since mid-November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that it will go past 7 percent this week,'' said
Robert Van Order, chief economist at Freddie Mac, based in McLean,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   That jump would end a nine-month streak of average rates below 7
percent, the longest stretch since Freddie Mac started tracking the
market. In early October, the national average fell to 6.49
percent, a 31-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Higher mortgage rates mean borrowers would pay more for money to
buy and fix their houses.
</P>
<P>
   Rates on a standard mortgage at some major Kansas City area
lenders have jumped from a low of 6.5 percent to as much as 7.25
percent. On a $100,000 mortgage, borrowers could pay an additional
$50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The average sale price of a home in Johnson County, Kan., in
January 1999 was $201,339, according to the Johnson County Board of
Realtors. Assuming a $160,000 loan, the borrower would pay an extra
$85 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgage rate increase comes near the peak of the
home-buying season. Even so, real estate agents said higher rates
haven't affected sales yet. They note that rates are still near
long-term lows.
</P>
<P>
   Jodi Kaplan, a real estate agent with J.D. Reece, said she sold
two houses last weekend and put two more up for sale. None of her
customers mentioned rising interest rates, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd be concerned if they go above 8 percent,'' Kaplan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent increases amount to a few dollars a week and
shouldn't make or break a deal, Kaplan said. If the increase adds
only $25 a month to the mortgage, the cost isn't significant, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda LaMarque, an agent for Realty Executives Professional
Group, said: ``I can't say it's making a big difference for my
clients, people who are buying houses for $150,000 or more. It
might be throwing the ratios out of whack for people who are buying
houses in the $60-, $70-, $80,000 range. That extra $25 a month can
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMarque said her clients beat the rising rates anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my clients are pleasantly locked in,'' LaMarque said.
``One locked in earlier this week. Another locked in when she got
her loan application.''
</P>
<P>
   They are the lucky ones.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates are starting to eat away at the market for
homeowners looking to refinance their existing mortgages, Van Order
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main effect will be on refinancings,'' Van Order said.
``That share of the market has been falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, mortgage refinancings had been as much as 60
percent of the market, Van Order said. That share has dropped to
about half and likely will continue falling.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy McCombs, a Kansas City homeowner, said she and her
husband, Rick, refinanced the mortgage on their home after watching
rates drift down for several months.
</P>
<P>
   She locked in a no-cost, 30-year, fixed-rate mortgage on Jan. 29
at 7.125 percent. On Feb. 23, when she closed the deal, average
rates were 7.5 percent, still lower than the 8.5 percent rate on
her 10-year-old mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been watching for a few months and felt like that was
as low as they were going to go,'' McCombs said.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs said she plans to use the cash received for the equity
in the home to make repairs, including new gutters and a new roof.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wilson, co-president of Advance Mortgage Corp., a broker in
Overland Park, said the refinancing rate hasn't changed much in
three weeks. About one-third of the company's loan inquiries are
for mortgage refinancings, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wilson said interest rates at the 40 companies he monitors
have been climbing steadily for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, people call and just gasp and say, `What happened?'
'' Wilson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
