<HEADER>
A6537 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-MAYOR-KAN &LR;      03-03 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MAYOR-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Gender now isn't seen as defining element in KC mayoral race  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In 1975, Sarah Snow became the first woman in
Kansas City history to be nominated for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Then she got hit from all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Critics knocked her for being too timid. Others said Snow was
too domineering. She was ``so typically female,'' one woman
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Was Kansas City ready for a woman mayor? Evidently not: Snow
lost by a wide margin in the general election to Charles Wheeler,
then the incumbent mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 25 years later, will gender play a major role in Kansas
City's next mayoral race?
</P>
<P>
   Kay Waldo Barnes, who was nominated for mayor Tuesday by a
comfortable margin, doesn't think so. Neither does her opponent,
George Blackwood.
</P>
<P>
   If gender was a big deal back in 1975, they say, it simply isn't
today.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, women made up only 4 percent of Congress. Today, that
figure is 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, women held 10 percent of statewide elected offices.
Today, it's 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, women accounted for 8 percent of state legislature
membership across the country, compared with 22 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is considered a strong candidate for president.
Madeleine Albright is secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   So a woman mayor of Kansas City? What's the big deal, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a little of the novelty has worn off,'' said Debbie
Walsh, associate director for the Center for the American Woman and
Politics at Rutgers University. ``The world does change. People are
at a different place about this now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mayoral primary, the issue of gender never surfaced. And
in the general election, it might not either.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said Tuesday night she didn't know whether being a woman
played any role in her victory. Blackwood attributed Barnes'
victory to money, not gender.
</P>
<P>
   Few would suggest that Barnes will triumph just because she is a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think a woman just for the sake of being a
woman can win,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a California Democrat.
``I think she's got to...have the credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, women bring their own sets of advantages to
campaigns, especially now, in the wake of President Clinton's
impeachment crisis.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of 1,200 adults surveyed last month said they thought
a female president would be better than a man at ``improving
honesty and ethics in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a lot of men say, `Look, these men are messing up.
Maybe it is time to give a woman an opportunity,' '' said former
Rep. Shirley Chisholm, a Democrat who in 1972 became the first
woman to seek the presidential nomination of a major political
party.
</P>
<P>
   To a degree, the perception that women are more honest and fair
is aided by the fact that they don't hold as many top offices: They
haven't had as many opportunities to mess up.
</P>
<P>
   Women themselves suggest that their priorities as office holders
are sometimes different from those of their male predecessors.
Topeka, Kan., Mayor Joan Wagnon, for example, said she's placed
more emphasis on child-care issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an economic-development matter,'' Wagnon said. ``I
don't know that my predecessor would have taken up that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Although women have made steady gains in winning top elected
offices, the progress has been slow. Scholars blame the relatively
low number of women holding lower-level political offices.
</P>
<P>
   In the mayoral race, Barnes was helped by the fact that she had
served on the City Council and Jackson County Legislature years
ago. Janice Ellis, the race's other female contender, may have lost
points in that area. Mayor Emanuel Cleaver criticized Ellis at one
point because she had not paid her dues by serving in a lower-level
public office.
</P>
<P>
   One problem that didn't bog down Barnes' effort was
fund-raising. Women typically have more trouble than men tapping
into big donors, partly because too few women serve on major
corporate boards, said Missouri Auditor Claire McCaskill, the
former Jackson County prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes managed to overcome the problem with an aggressive,
grass-roots fund-raising plan. Blackwood, however, still managed to
outraise Barnes in the last reporting period, $141,000 to $111,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for women is that some traits favorable to men,
such as ambition and aggressiveness, are often frowned upon for
women.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill, for example, has been criticized for saying she would
like to be governor someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who said to me, `Boy, Claire, I hope
you don't run for anything else any time soon.' But I remember Kit
Bond was elected governor (in 1972) two years after he was elected
auditor. It didn't seem to slow him down any.''
</P>
<P>
   Women also face greater scrutiny when it comes to their
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Marinovich, who in 1995 became the first female mayor of
Kansas City, Kan., remembers all the unsolicited comments about her
makeup, her lipstick and her hairstyle. She knows that male
candidates would not have faced similar comments.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1975, Snow took her defeat to Wheeler in stride. She
said she was not bitter about losing or the lack of support from
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women themselves weren't ready,'' Snow said. ``They didn't
want to do it, and they didn't really know why I wanted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who she voted for on Tuesday, Snow, now 76, didn't
hesitate: Barnes. And not just because she's a woman. The former
City Council member has a good background in city government and is
a good communicator, Snow said.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted to something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just like to see a woman win,'' Snow said. ``I never made
it, and I've wanted someone else to make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
