<SLUG> BC-MET-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MET'S NEXT SEASON TO INCLUDE `GATSBY' PREMIERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 1999-2000 season of the Metropolitan Opera will
include the world premiere of John Harbison's ``Great Gatsby,'' new
productions of Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde'' and Boito's
``Mefistofele,'' and three complete cycles of Wagner's ``Ring.''
The season details were announced Wednesday by Joseph Volpe, the
general manager of the Met.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Gatsby,'' which will have its premiere on Dec. 20,
has long been in progress and is much anticipated. Harbison, the
Pulitzer Prize-winning composer on the faculty at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, has written his own libretto, adapted from
the F. Scott Fitzgerald novel, though the score also contains
Harbison's evocations of Gatsby-era popular songs with lyrics by
Murray Horwitz. Jerry Hadley will sing the title role and Dawn
Upshaw will be Daisy Buchanan, with Susan Graham as Jordan Baker,
Dwayne Croft as Nick Caraway and, in her Met debut, Lorraine Hunt
as Myrtle Wilson. James Levine, the Met's artistic director, will
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's ``Tristan und Isolde,'' last performed at the Met in
1984, will return in a new production directed by Dieter Dorn, in
his Met debut, and conducted by Levine, with Jane Eaglen and Ben
Heppner in the title roles. Samuel Ramey will sing the title role
in ``Mefistofele,'' by the overlooked opera composer Arrigo Boito,
best remembered as the librettist of Verdi's ``Otello'' and
``Falstaff.'' The opera has not been presented at the Met since the
1925-26 season. There will also be a new production by Tim Albery
of Lehar's ``Merry Widow,'' performed in English translation, with
Frederica von Stade as the widow Hanna Glawari.
</P>
<P>
   The three ``Ring'' cycles, which come in the spring of 2000,
will reunite Deborah Voigt as Sieglinde and Placido Domingo as
Siegmund, both of whom have sung these roles to acclaim at the Met.
James Morris, a heralded Wotan, will also be returning. Ms. Eaglen
will sing her first Met performances of Brunnhilde, and Stig
Anderson in his Met debut is Siegfried. There will be additional
performances of ``Die Walkure'' and ``Das Rheingold.''
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a very promising cast for Strauss'
``Rosenkavalier,'' with Renee Fleming as the Marschallin, Susan
Graham as Octavian and Heidi Grant Murphy as Sophie. Levine will
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Recent productions of operas that are returning next season
include Shostakovich's ``Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District,''
conducted by Valery Gergiev, with Catherine Malfitano in the title
role; Debussy's ``Pelleas et Melisande,'' with Ms. Upshaw and Croft
as the ill-fated couple, and Schoenberg's ``Moses und Aron.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the singers making notable first-time Met appearances in
important roles are Ms. Voigt as Aida, Ruth Anne Swenson as the
four heroines and Bryn Terfel as the four villains in Offenbach's
``Tales of Hoffmann,'' Bo Skovhus as the Count in ``Le Nozze di
Figaro,'' and Gabriela Benackova as Desdemona in Verdi's
``Otello,'' with Domingo in his signature role as the Moor.
</P>
<P>
   The season opens on Sept. 27 with the double bill of
``Cavalleria Rusticana'' and ``Pagliacci.'' Domingo will sing Tonio
in ``Pagliacci,'' marking his 18th opening-night Met performance,
breaking the record of 17 held by Enrico Caruso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
