A6544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS04-CO     03-03 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, DEMOCRATS RALLY TO PROMOTE AGENDA
 &HT;    550&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton stood with fellow Democrats on
Capitol Hill Wednesday to promote a ``Families First'' legislative
agenda designed to pressure Republican congressional leaders this
year and appeal to voters in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The rally recalled the Newt Gingrich-engineered ``Contract With
America'' gathering that propelled Republicans to a congressional
majority in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely tracking the priorities Clinton staked out in this
year's State of the Union address, the four-page legislative
platform is topped by a plan to set aside 77 percent of projected
federal budget surpluses for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for modernizing public schools, a patient's bill
of rights, targeted tax cuts, raising the minimum wage, more cops
on the beat, a crackdown on those who swindle seniors, privacy
protections and policies to promote ``liveability'' in communities.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton urged Democrats to ``put people ahead of
partisanship and common sense ahead of ideology'' in the current
congressional session, his party's congressional leaders, as well
as Vice President Al Gore, attacked Republicans for past opposition
to Clinton's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri
recalled how no Republican in the House or Senate voted in favor of
the balanced budget measure Clinton introduced in the first year of
his presidency, when the annual spending gap was approaching $300
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are currently enjoying the harvest of the seeds we planted
in 1993, when Democrats _ without a single Republican vote _ made
the difficult and courageous choice to put our long-term interests
ahead of the short-term politics,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provided all of the votes for the economic plan that is now
responsible for this historic prosperity and momentum in America,''
Gore echoed.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota took even
sharper aim at congressional Republicans, charging that the
across-the-board tax cut widely advocated in the GOP would
disproportionately favor wealthy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle noted that working families making $38,000 a year _
currently 60 percent of all families _ would save an average of
only 27 cents a day under the Republican tax cuts. ``You can't
achieve big dreams with small change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, chairman of the House Republican
Conference, responded to the Democratic rally by noting that the
GOP is ``committed to strengthening Social Security,'' improving
public schools and ``providing middle-class, working Americans with
much-needed tax relief now.''
</P>
<P>
   And House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois called the
Democratic agenda ``a throwback to a time when some believed that
more government, more taxes and more centralized control promoted a
great society.'' In contrast, he said, ``I have worked with my
colleagues in the House and Senate to devise a balanced agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   However, congressional Republicans have yet to arrive at a
consensus on how to accomplish their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, on the other hand, appear more united than at any
time since Clinton was elected in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real ... political story out of this meeting may be that
we will have to retire that famous old Will Rogers quip, 'I don't
belong to an organized political party _ I'm a Democrat',''
asserted Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Democratic political rivalries were checked at the door
as Senate and House Democrats filed into an ornate room at the
Library of Congress for their ``Families First'' event _ the first
party pep rally since the famous post-impeachment gathering on the
White House lawn last December.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is about to walk away with the party's 2000
presidential nomination, called Gephardt, his opponent in the 1988
campaign, ``a special friend'' and referred to him as ``the next
speaker of the House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   And Daschle introduced Gore as ``the president of the United
States,'' then paused before adding ``Senate.'' As vice president,
Gore presides over the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a way with a line,'' Gore told Daschle. ``Your timing
and rhythm are impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event, the first of its kind since Clinton's
acquittal in the Senate, came as first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
was appearing in New York, where there is widespread speculation
that she will run for a Senate seat next year.
</P>
<P>
   It also occurred only hours before former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky was to appear on network television to discuss her
affair with the president that led to Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
