A6545 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      03-03 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Growing economy lays to rest fiscal policy myth  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The unveiling of a century-ending federal budget
brings to mind how this century's final decade has laid to rest a
generation's worth of fiscal policy myths.
</P>
<P>
   In the long-gone era of perceived budgetary red ink as far as
the eye could see, conventional wisdom said rising federal deficits
would lift interest rates and slow economic growth. It was the
``crowding out'' theory. As Uncle Sam borrowed more, it posited,
the credit capital available for businesses to finance expansion
would become increasingly scarce and costly.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing of the sort happened, though. The interest rate trend
has been down during much of this decade. This was so even as the
deficit climbed to a record $290 billion in fiscal 1992 and stayed
above $200 billion through fiscal 1994. As the deficit moved into
surplus in 1998 for the first time in nearly 30 years, interest
rates remained on a predictably downward path.
</P>
<P>
   The experts were wrong because they didn't account for the power
of political stability. A rate-boosting credit squeeze failed to
materialize because the world remained willing to lend all U.S.
borrowers most of the credit they wanted at reasonable prices. This
willingness was largely due to America offering the safest
investment haven in the world, which also helps explain why chronic
trade deficits haven't brought the U.S. economy to grief.
</P>
<P>
   Another punctured myth is the belief that huge tax increases
would pose an insurmountable barrier to growth. This myth, too, has
been debunked largely because America is the home of the world's
most investor-friendly financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some die-hard critics of the Clinton administration claim this
economic expansion hasn't been as strong statistically in some ways
as the 1980s recovery, but they can't deny an indisputable fact:
This period of uninterrupted growth has been the longest in
peacetime history despite two substantial tax increases in the
1990s. If growth continues for another year or so, it will be the
longest expansion ever.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. economy grew at a 5.6 percent annual rate in last
year's final quarter, it was a phenomenal performance for a boom
this long in the tooth.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom was wrong because the experts failed to
fully comprehend the power of a hospitable investment climate.
Compared with Europe and Japan, for example, the U.S. stock market
is an investor's paradise. While far from perfect, the U.S. market
is probably unique in the way it protects shareholder interests.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting appeal of U.S. equity markets largely explains the
investor demand for stocks in recent years that has driven stock
prices higher than anyone thought they could go, given the
underlying economic fundamentals. As stock prices have soared,
Americans have felt wealthier, which has translated into a desire
to use their new wealth to finance a better life.
</P>
<P>
   With some two-thirds of economic growth fueled by personal
consumption, the result is a virtual circle. Rising consumption
brings economic growth, which encourages the stock investment that
drives equity prices higher and, in turn, creates aggressive
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the mix sound monetary policy that tames inflation, and
the combination becomes unbeatable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     03-03 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TAX TIME: FOR SOME, GORILLA HUNTING SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) (DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To tax and to please, no more than to love and to be wise, is
not given to men,'' wrote Edmund Burke in 1774. Nor, he might have
added, is it often given to humans to write about taxes and be
stimulating. Yet in ``The Greedy Hand: How Taxes Drive Americans
Crazy and What to Do About It,'' Amity Schlaes not only manages to
keep you wide awake, she also sets your blood to boiling.
</P>
<P>
   She does so by citing particularly egregious examples of how our
current Rube Goldberg machine of a tax code sometimes works. She
tells, for instance, of a New York City couple who lost their
29-year-old son, an investment banker, in the crash of Pan Am's
Flight 103 in Lockerbie, Scotland, and were dunned by the Internal
Revenue Service for $6 million in back taxes on the settlement the
IRS estimated they would receive, even before the amount of that
settlement was determined.
</P>
<P>
   She tells of another couple who bought a house in East Dorset,
Vt., because of the area's outstanding schools, only to learn that
the state's supreme court had ruled that the local school-financing
system was unconstitutional, that it would no longer be all right
for one school district to spend more money on its students than
another, and that henceforth local real estate money was to be sent
to the state capital so that it could be given out equitably.
</P>
<P>
   She writes that Tax Freedom Day _ which is what a
Washington-based think tank called the Tax Foundation names the day
on which the average American has paid off his total annual burden
of federal, state and local taxes _ fell in 1998 on May 10, ``the
latest day in history.''
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Schlaes is getting at with these illustrations is not
exactly subtle. She is talking about estate taxes, real-estate
taxes and social-security taxes, and the point she is making is
that the present American tax system is greedy, intrusive,
unpredictable and meddling. The Internal Revenue Service in
administering this system acts with all the restraint and subtlety
of a 500-pound gorilla on amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Ms. Schlaes details other alleged excesses of what
Thomas Paine in ``The Rights of Man'' described as ``the greedy
hand of government thrusting itself into every corner and crevice
of industry, and grasping the spoil of the multitude.'' In a
chapter called ``Your Clothes,'' she describes shopping for
tax-free apparel at the Mall of America in Minneapolis-St. Paul as
an example of the lengths to which people will go to escape sales
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Your Work,'' she argues that the present Social Security
System is ``indeed and truly a Ponzi scheme,'' or a ruse in which
money from one generation flows into the pockets of another until
there are simply not enough people to pay. In ``Your Marriage,''
she explains how two conflicting goals, ``equality for the poor''
and ``equality for women,'' have combined to produce a result
whereby married people pay higher taxes than a comparably earning
single man and woman.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Your House,'' she argues apropos of the home-mortgage
deduction that if real estate did not ``enjoy a huge advantage over
other investments, our economy would grow more efficiently
overall.'' In ``Your Baby,'' she laments how the cost and
difficulty of hiring proper child care is actually causing couples
to give up having additional children. In ``Your Success,'' she
insists that the progressive income tax does more harm than good
and fails to fulfill its stated purpose of taxing the truly rich.
In ``Your Retirement,'' she describes how the Social Security
system has the effect of idling and infantilizing older people even
as the economy demands more workers and people are living longer,
more active lives.
</P>
<P>
   How does the book propose to solve these myriad ills, which add
up to such an indictment of our tax system that by the end you are
almost ready to accept the flat tax proposed by the House majority
leader, Dick Armey? Or the single tax once dreamed up by Henry
George. Or even a system based on cowrie shells or maybe bubble
gum. Encouragingly, Ms. Schlaes, a member of The Wall Street
Journal's editorial board, concludes that ``our impasse, in fact,
contains the outline of its own solution, if only we allow
ourselves to look at it clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``our long struggle with Paine's greedy hand'' tells us,
she writes, is that ``taxes have to be ``visible,'' ``simple,''
``for revenue'' (as opposed to for the purpose of steering
behavior), and ``lower.'' She goes on: ``We don't have to load
extra taxes on the rich''; ``It's time to privatize Social
Security''; ``Local is good,'' (``The federal government cannot
solve everything''), and ``We must lock in change.'' By this last
she means that we ought to clear out the present ``underbrush,''
and ``put through lower, simpler rates that apply to all in a
consistent manner'' and that we ought to pass a constitutional
amendment ``that calls for limiting federal taxes, including Social
Security, to 25 percent of our income, or even a lower share.''
</P>
<P>
   She concludes that ``luck is on our side. Today the nation is
actually in a better position to undertake a tax reform than at any
point in living memory. . . . Today we have no deficit and no Cold
War.'' We need only look to our own history of resisting taxes for
``the path to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be any number of details about which to quarrel with
Ms. Schlaes. For instance, she fails to prove her case that all
progressive systems inevitably fail to tax the rich proportionally,
and she leaves one to suspect that the real reason the rich gain
the benefit of loopholes is not because ``progressivity'' is flawed
but simply because the rich have more power. Many will question her
larger assumptions that the welfare state has proved itself useless
and that an untrammeled free market will not create its own
systemic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by criticizing our present tax code so concretely, Ms.
Schlaes has provided a thoughtful overview of the system's many
contradictions and inequities. Even if you don't always agree with
her conclusions, she defines the debate over what we ought to do
and gets you thinking constructively about the problems she
identifies.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE GREEDY HAND'
</P>
<P>
   How Taxes Drive Americans Crazy and What to Do About It
</P>
<P>
   By Amity Schlaes
</P>
<P>
   255 pages. Random House. $22.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
