u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-HONGKONG-650&AMP;A     03-03 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HONGKONG-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY NEGOTIATING TO BUILD THEME PARK IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Confirming weeks of breathless rumors, Hong Kong and
the Walt Disney Co. said Wednesday that they were in early
negotiations about building a theme park in the former British
colony.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the second Asia-based theme park for the
entertainment company and would mark a major expansion of Disney's
dealings with China, which regained sovereignty over Hong Kong 19
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Donald Tsang, Hong Kong's financial secretary, said Disney
and the Hong Kong government had reached a ``common understanding''
about building a park in Hong Kong. He said they would now begin
``intensive negotiations'' and hoped to make a final decision by
the end of June. If a definitive agreement is reached, Sir Donald
said the first phase of a Hong Kong Disneyland could be completed
by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its parks in Orlando, Fla., and Anaheim, Calif., Disney
operates theme parks in suburban Paris and outside Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The mere whisper of Disney's interest has generated giddy
excitement in Hong Kong, which has been racked by recession and a
steep drop in tourism in the aftermath of Asia's financial crises
and the British-Chinese agreement that converted Hong Kong into a
special autonomous region of China.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Hong Kong have come to view a Disney park almost
as a pot of gold. Even as he confirmed the negotiations, Sir Donald
felt obliged to temper public expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am fully aware of, and indeed share, the public's excitement
at the prospect of seeing Mickey and his friends in Hong Kong,''
Sir Donald said in his annual budget address in the former colony.
``However, I must caution that while we have made the first
important steps, there is still much ground to cover. Much hard
negotiating lies ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney, which is based in Burbank, Calif., confirmed through a
spokesman that it was in preliminary discussions about building a
theme park resort in Hong Kong but declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Disney, Michael Eisner, had said in the latest
annual report that Disney would likely build a park in China in the
coming years, and speculation grew that Hong Kong and Shanghai were
preferred locations.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where in China a Disney park is built, the
negotiations themselves are persuasive evidence that Disney's
fortunes in the world's most populous country are improving after a
three-year chill.
</P>
<P>
   China's film market was closed to Disney movies after the
company's 1996 release of ``Kundun,'' a film about the exiled
Tibetan spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama, who is considered a
political enemy by Beijing. But in February, in an early sign of a
thaw, China approved the release of the Disney animated hit about
the Chinese heroine ``Mulan,'' which opened in theaters there last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Before Disney committed to Hong Kong, it would need to agree on
the price of the land for a theme park. Indeed, Ian Perkin, the
chief economist of the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce, said:
``I'd say the chances of this are less than 50-50. If you look at
the cost of land in Hong Kong, I'm not sure Disney is willing to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Donald said the government and the company envisioned
building the park on reclaimed land north of Lantau Island, not far
from the new Hong Kong International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airport, which is also built on reclaimed land, cost $20
billion, an amount that included the vast network of bridges,
tunnels, highways and railways that connect the airport to central
Hong Kong. Some of that infrastructure could presumably serve a new
Disneyland as well. But the cost of another enormous reclamation
project could easily reach billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   One person with knowledge of the talks between Hong Kong and
Disney said the company had initially proposed that the government
give Disney the land. No matter how much Hong Kong wants to lure
Disney, analysts said it could not accede to such a deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sir Donald said a theme park would generate thousands of new
jobs at a time when Hong Kong is suffering from record
unemployment. He said the park would also protect the territory's
status as a tourist destination in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Perkin agreed that a Disney theme park would be a potent growth
engine for Hong Kong. But because such a project would require
years of planning before construction started _ let alone the gates
opened _ he said it should not be viewed as a panacea for Hong
Kong's current problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Disney project, Sir Donald announced that the
government would build a giant industrial park for technology
companies. The $2 billion project, called Cyberport, will be
financed partly by the government and partly by the Pacific Century
Group, a real estate and technology company controlled by Richard
Li, the son of Hong Kong's most prominent tycoon, Li Ka-shing.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Donald also forecast that Hong Kong's gross domestic product
would grow five-tenths of 1 percent in 1999, after plummeting 5.1
percent last year. Perkin said even that modest goal would be hard
to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   For all the caveats, the prospect of a Disney park has been a
tonic to a city sorely in need of good news. The shares of Hong
Kong property developers have soared in recent days as the Disney
rumors percolated. Analysts said the value of real estate near the
park would rise significantly. In New York Stock Exchange trading
Wednesday, Disney shares rose 31.25 cents, to $34.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
