<HEADER>
A6549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-BALLET-REVIEW-NY     03-03 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXUBERANCE AND POWER IN A `GISELLE' MADE NEW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Spain)   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK _ The Ballet Nacional de Cuba, founded and directed by
Alicia Alonso, closed a U.S. tour with ``Giselle'' Tuesday night at
the New Jersey Performing Arts Center here. New York's loss is
Newark's gain: a new generation of young Cuban dancers led by the
vivacious Lorna Feijoo in the title role was cheered deservedly to
the rafters.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet superstars are more often than not linked to signature
ballets. Ms. Alonso, who danced with a variety of companies in the
United States from the 1930s, always has been associated with two
works. One is ``Theme and Variations,'' which George Balanchine
choreographed for her and Igor Youskevitch at American Ballet
Theater in 1947. That company honored her at a Metropolitan Opera
House Gala in 1997 on the ballet's 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The other Alonso signature is ``Giselle,'' which the Cuban
ballerina first danced on Nov. 2, 1943, with Ballet Theater. That
debut made Ms. Alonso a star, and it is that 1940 Ballet Theater
production by Anton Dolin that is the springboard for the vibrant
and dramatically detailed version Ms. Alonso staged for her company
in 1959. New Yorkers saw it in 1978 and 1979 with Ms. Alonso
triumphant as Giselle in her troupe's official U. S. debut. Yet
then as now, it was obvious that the staging was carried not only
by a star's charisma but by a solid production, strong on details
in mime and technique.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feijoo is not a copy of Ms. Alonso; her onstage persona is
less internalized, more exuberant, and her wholesome appearance,
effectively transformed from Act I to Act II into a ghostly
presence, is very different from Ms. Alonso's long-legged elegance.
The beauty of the production is that it allows for individual
interpretations within a strong framework. It is true that the mime
in Act I sometimes verged on the over-coached. But it is also clear
that without every person onstage reacting to the unfolding events,
this outstanding production would not have its special character.
</P>
<P>
   It would be healthy to throw political assumptions out the
window. Ms. Alonso, now 79, founded a small troupe in 1948 that
grew into the present company. This ``Giselle,'' as Ballet Theater
veterans said in 1978 and repeated tonight, is remarkably close to
the old Ballet Theater version. Ms. Alonso substituted a pas de dix
instead of the usual Peasant Pas de Deux. But it is not the copy of
Soviet stagings that some in the public expected in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Albrecht, the aristocrat who betrays the peasant girl Giselle,
adds virtuoso steps that were not done in 1940. Essentially, this
``Giselle'' is pre-Soviet. Unlike Ballet Theater, which now
includes steps introduced by the Soviet defectors in its company,
it omits the passage at the end when Albrecht cradles Giselle, now
a ghost, before she glides out. This was a touch from the 1944
Bolshoi version.
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Alonso's version, Giselle does a deep penche arabesque at
her grave. Albrecht presses her hand to his cheek; suddenly she is
sucked into the wings as she is pulled out. It is a tremendously
dramatic and moving moment. When Albrecht lies sobbing at the grave
(very Dolin), his grief is made real and a Romantic story of
remorse and regeneration has no truly happy end.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban ballet training recently has produced some male virtuosos:
Jose Manuel Carreno at Ballet Theater, Carlos Acosta at Houston
Ballet. In a company whose oldest dancer is now 29, the four male
soloists in the pas de dix stood out. Some were elegant and some
have an extraordinary spring to their leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Long dominated by Ms. Alonso, the Ballet Nacional traditionally
has focused on its women. Josefina Mendez, the company's ballet
mistress, has maintained a disciplined female corps. Ms. Alonso has
introduced some dancers from Spain. Myrtha, who led the corps of
wilis, or ghosts of jilted maidens, was Laura Hormigon, an immature
dancer from Spain who nonetheless has a wondrously tight bourree.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feijoo (whose sister, Lorena Feijoo, is with the Joffrey
Ballet of Chicago) embodies the strong projection and centered
dancing of the Cuban ballerinas. Her technique is powerful; she was
more a determined wili than an ethereal one. Exceptionally, she
keeps her toes always pointed, marvelously stretched and taut.
Dramatically, she understands the production's clear line between a
realistic first act and the supernatural Act II, where wilis run
head first and bent over, furies out to destroy men.
</P>
<P>
   In Act I, her impetuous peasant girl offered a controlled solo
with smooth attitude turns and astounding hops on one foot on toe
that covered the entire stage. Her mime in the mad scene, which
focused on her memories of the past and a developing breakdown (we
could see her chills) was emotionally powerful. Last but not least,
her arabesques went deeply into penche, and in the Alonso
tradition, her rapid entrechats brought down the house.
</P>
<P>
   As Albrecht, Oscar Torrado held his own, always classical in his
partnering stance. If not a virtuoso, he is an intelligent dancer.
As the seducer, he was contrasted with his woodcutter rival,
Hilarion, rugged and honest in Jose Zamorano's consistent
portrayal. Yet the only class-conscious touch was subtle: When
Albrecht's betrayal was revealed, the stage was metaphorically
divided into two groups, peasants on one side, aristocrats on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other versions, this one made a distinction between two
sets of flowers: Albrecht's roses that Giselle rejected, and white
lilies that he tore from her as tangible evidence of her ghostly
presence. From such details do superb restagings of the classic
grow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
