<HEADER>
A6559 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEADWATERS-FOREST-HNS     03-03 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADWATERS-FOREST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREST ADVOCATES CRITICIZE TREE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A landmark deal signed this week to protect
thousands of acres of redwoods, some 1,500 years old, was hailed by
politicians as a majestic step toward creating a new Yosemite along
the Northern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   But to some environmentalists and others who have watched the
wrangling over what is known as the Headwaters Forest, the $480
million federal and state deal to acquire 10,000 acres from the
Pacific Lumber Co. is flawed, overhyped and wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about the people who gave their very lives for this,
and then I started thinking about what our government was willing
to give,'' said Julia Butterfly, who has lived high up in a redwood
tree for the past 15 months in a quest to protect the forest. ``And
all they were willing to give was compromise upon compromise upon
compromise, until the very end.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the day the agreement was signed, certainly marked a
major turning point for the Headwaters. But the next five years of
the Headwaters may end up looking in many ways like the past five
years: lawsuits and logging, demonstrations and discouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are reviewing the agreement to see if it gives
Pacific Lumber loopholes to violate the Endangered Species Act. If
they find them, they say the will sue, as they have sued before.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, taxpayers spent $380 million to buy about
7,500 acres of redwood groves in Humboldt County. An additional
$100 million is expected to buy two other redwood groves in the
coming months, bringing the total acreage to 10,000 under public
preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The deal dwarfs the $63 million the federal government recently
paid Utah for almost a million acres of desert in the Grand
Staircase National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped up in the Headwaters purchase is a complicated federal
and state logging plan for 211,000 more acres Pacific Lumber is
harvesting in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The management plan forbids the company to log near streams,
curtails some road building and requires constant monitoring of
logging practices, to protect the coho salmon and other endangered
species living in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout at least five years of negotiating to acquire the
Headwaters, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., has always encouraged
environmentalists to see the forest through the trees. This deal
was not perfect, she said repeatedly, but it was the best anyone
could hope for and undoubtedly the strictest logging restrictions
imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly was the toughest negotiation I ever got myself
into,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core environmentalists pushed so hard they ended up
alienating many lawmakers they once considered allies. But
mainstream activists ended up seeing what Feinstein and others saw:
This was, after all, private property, and there were no guarantees
that a court battle would be successful.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't be certain the Endangered Species Act and
California's logging regulations would be stronger than the omnibus
agreement signed Monday with Houston-based financier Charles
Hurwitz, whose Maxxam Corp. is the parent of Pacific Lumber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neglect of the federal Endangered Species Act and state
forestry law allowed Hurwitz to hold the Headwaters for ransom,''
said Sierra Club executive director Carl Pope. ``A pattern of
strict enforcement would have prevented him and other Wall Street
raiders from using property rights arguments as an excuse to
destroy public resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Lumber has contended that under the Constitution's Fifth
Amendment, it had a right to fair compensation for its property.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists said the property rights argument was a bluff,
a device Hurwitz used to extort $480 million out of the government
to buy some trees he probably couldn't log anyway because of the
Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're allowed to do something on private property but not if
it adversely affects your neighbors,'' said Michael Passoff of the
Bay Area Coalition for Headwaters in San Francisco. ``You can't
build a porn shop next to a church and you can't sell guns from
your home next to a school.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several groups have a decade invested in the Headwaters
agreement. They promised continued demonstrations and monitoring,
just as state officials promised to step up enforcement of
environmental laws governing logging.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists worried that logging on steep slopes within
the Headwaters would erode the hills, creating more mudslides and
ruining the habitat for the endangered coho salmon. They say
loopholes in the law allow the company to log even before a
scientific assessment of the logging is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Some Stafford residents have sued Pacific Lumber over a 1997
mudslide that crashed down a clear-cut hillside and destroyed 10
houses in the Humboldt County community. The logging company has
been cited by state forestry officials for 134 violations since
1996 for things such as running heavy equipment through streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took more than a decade of litigation and protest to gain
some measure of protection for the marbled murrelet and the old
growth redwoods,'' said Cecilia Lanman, program director for the
Environmental Protection Information Center. ``It may take 10 more
years to bring about protection for our native salmon and steelhead
_ if we're not already too late.''
</P>
</TEXT>
