<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6583 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADJOE-AZR &LR;      03-03 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADJOE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRILL GURU HAS MANY IRONS IN THE FIRE  
 (ADV: INCLUDES RECIPES) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Grill guru Mad Coyote Joe Daigneault wasn't born with
a spatula in his hand, but almost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really destined to be an ironworker,'' said Daigneault
(pronounced DAY-no), charming host of ``The Sonoran Grill,'' a
weekend cooking show produced by Phoenix ABC affiliate Channel 15
(KNXV). ``When I was 13 years old and everybody else had a paper
route, I worked in a steelyard in South Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault's family was big in steel and iron. He was, too, for
a while, rising to supervisory positions on crews and contributing
to various structural landmarks around the Phoenix area, including
Terminal 4 at Sky Harbor International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your job as an ironworker foreman is to take a large group of
men and make them work like dogs,'' he said. ``I was very good at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``I hated it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a guy who got up in the morning and drank coffee and
went out to work and worked my (backside) off and pushed people
around all day long and came home tired. On the weekends, I'd just
drink beer and wait to go back at it again, and I was just dead. I
wasn't happy. I liked my wife, my wife liked me, but it was
soulless.''
</P>
<P>
   One day came a disagreement with a job superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I need some time off,' '' Daigneault said. ``He said,
`How much time off?' I said, `About 35 years.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault had been a lifelong cooking and grilling hobbyist.
(Instead of an ashtray or spice rack, he built a barbecue in
junior-high shop class. ``I went home and put some briquettes in,''
he said. ``The thing melted, but it shows I was interested.'')
</P>
<P>
   He also had been dabbling with a home-grown dry spice and
recipe-mix business. (The Mad Coyote brand name already had been
born in a beer-drinking session with some buddies.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, Daigneault was a full-timer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first month that I quit my job, I made $800,'' he said.
``The second month after I quit my job, I made $3,000, and I told
my wife, `We'll never be poor again. This is great. I've found it.'
I didn't have another $3,000 month for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mad Coyote spice-mix business has had its ups and downs over
the past decade _ currently, the company manufactures 54 culinary
products under a variety of labels, including fajitas, chili and
salsa mixes _ but Mad Coyote Joe himself has become a rising star
on local TV.
</P>
<P>
   Discovered by Channel 15 producer Paul Hallowell, Daigneault is
the centerpiece of a minor hit, which began airing slightly more
than a year ago. ``The Sonoran Grill's'' ratings have been
increasing steadily, and its performance has exceeded Channel 15's
expectations. According to Nielsen figures supplied by the station,
an average of nearly 100,000 adults saw the combined weekend
airings during the recent November sweeps ratings period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally spend the first two hours of my day every Monday
answering all the e-mail we get from the show,'' Hallowell said.
``I get stuff from 89-year-olds, kids . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Convicts,'' Daigneault added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very diverse audience from all over the state,''
Hallowell continued.
</P>
<P>
   The show's primary sponsor, AJ's Fine Foods, also is pleased. A
total of 36 episodes is ordered for this year, with expectations of
future seasons to come.
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault specializes in demystifying sophisticated recipe
ingredients _ the kind of fancy stuff you might purchase at a
high-end grocery store like, say, AJ's.
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault, who has worked in the kitchens of several Valley
restaurants and who serves as head judge and master of ceremonies
for the Xerox Southwest Salsa Challenge benefiting the Hemophilia
Association tries ``to take on things that are perceived as
complex,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just taking some ingredients and combining them. It's
just not that big of a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Daigneault's wife, Kathy, a former resort chef, sometimes
contributes to the recipe-selection process, but the show's unusual
appeal comes from its host's offbeat sense of humor and
ultracasual, regular-guy-at-the-grill approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing is, I want to be the guy down the street who drives a
cement truck, your neighbor buddy who loves to cook in his back
yard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A natural performer, Daigneault studied music and drama at
Northern Arizona University, and he occasionally gigs around town
on guitar under various names. When he's done chopping something on
the show, whatever doesn't go in the pot or on the grill tends to
get tossed over his shoulder and into the desert.
</P>
<P>
   The series actually is shot (five production hours per episode)
in the back yard of Daigneault's Cave Creek, Ariz., home, and that
setting provides the show its underlying philosophy: No matter how
out-there the recipes and ingredients might get _ octopus tacos,
say, or game hen with stuffing made from pinon nuts and fresh
roasted green chiles _ it's still a cookout. The show's gimmick
would appear to be the visual contradiction of a great big,
sometimes goofy guy dicing dainty victuals, but there's more to it
than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a television show called ``The Sonoran Grill,''
Daigneault said. ``It stars the food. It has a host. Humor is the
guest star, but only a guest star. We don't want to turn it into
the ``Saturday Night Live'' of cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   The formula seems to be working. ``Sonoran Grill'' recipes are
distributed on Channel 15's World Wide Web site _ www.knxv.com _
and in AJ's stores in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people come up to produce managers, going, `Give me
everything on this recipe card,' '' said Barbara Carrera-Holland,
media director for AJ's parent company, Bashas'. ``We get letters
all the time that say `I've never stepped foot into AJ's until I
saw this show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the legend of Mad Coyote Joe grows.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, ``people think I'm a biker, and they leave me
alone,'' he said. But should he venture out in public wearing the
ball cap and blue-denim shirt he wears on the program, ``I'll have
20 people walk up to me and say, (begin ital) `You're that guy.' ''
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   It happened recently in Lake Havasu City, Ariz., which Channel
15 reaches via translator, and to where Daigneault had traveled to
participate in a chili cook-off. As sometimes happens at such
gatherings, Daigneault found himself in a bar at the end of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trucker comes up and says, `You know, down in Missouri,
we've been watching your show for years,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm not sure we're on in Missouri.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We get it on the satellite.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pinon Nut and Fresh Roasted Green Chile
</P>
<P>
   (From Mad Coyote Joe)
</P>
<P>
   6 cups dry bread crumb cubes
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup finely chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/3 finely chopped white onion
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons poultry seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   3/4 shelled pinon nuts
</P>
<P>
   3 to 5 fresh green chiles, roasted, peeled and diced, or 1/2 cup
diced canned green chiles (fresh roasted chile has a far better
taste)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken or turkey broth
</P>
<P>
   Combine bread crumbs, parsley, onion, spices, celery, pinon nuts
and 1/2 cup green chile in a large bowl. Toss all ingredients. Add
broth slowly, stiring, and let stand until moistened. Makes 10 cups
stuffing, enough to stuff a 14-pound turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Note from Joe: You may try adding pinon nuts and green chile to
your family recipe. I would suggest you reduce the level of spice,
because of the delicate flavor of the pinon nuts. Butter is not
used in this recipe because of the natural oil in the pinon nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 183 calories, 9 g fat, 1 mg
cholesterol, 20 g carbohydrates, 2.7 g fiber, 8 g protein, 763 mg
sodium, 42 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sweet Corn Pudding
</P>
<P>
   (From Mad Coyote Joe)
</P>
<P>
   4 ears of Arizona sweet corn
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red bell pepper, sliced in thin julienne strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 poblano chile, diced into 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill and a pizza stone to approximately 350 degrees.
The grill's heat directly below the pizza stone needs to be set on
lowest heat setting.
</P>
<P>
   Remove kernels from sweet corn. In a blender, combine half the
corn with brown sugar, eggs, half-and-half, butter, paprika, nutmeg
and salt and pepper. Process for 1 to 2 minutes, then pour into a
greased 5- by 9-inch baking pan. Gently mix in the remaining corn,
red bell pepper and chile. Bake on the pizza stone until golden and
a toothpick inserted in the middle of the pudding comes out clean,
approximately 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Approximate values per serving: 200 calories, 12 g fat, 98 mg
cholesterol, 19 g carbohydrates, 2.3 g fiber, 6 g protein, 86 mg
sodium, 52 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Contact Dave Walker at dave.walker(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
