<HEADLINE>
THREE OF TEXAS OCTUPLETS GO HOME FROM HOSPITAL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Three of the seven surviving Chukwu octuplets were
given a clean bill of health and sent home from the hospital
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The discharged babies, the first of the octuplets to leave Texas
Children's Hospital here, ``had kind of done everything we needed
them to do,'' said Dr. Patti Savrick, the pediatrician who will
continue to care for them. The babies had all been removed from
respiratory support and were able to maintain their body
temperature and take food on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference at the hospital a few hours after
discharge, the parents, Nigerian-born American citizens, laughed
when asked whether they had had seven bassinets waiting for the
babies at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven everything,'' said the mother, Nkem Chukwu.
</P>
<P>
   The infants sent home are Ebuka, a girl born on Dec. 8, about
two weeks before the seven others, who was discharged weighing 4
pounds 8 ounces; her sister Echerem, 4 pounds 7 ounces, and their
brother Jioke, 5 pounds 5 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology at the hospital, said
these three had been the first to begin bottle feedings and had
consistently gained weight.
</P>
</TEXT>
