<SLUG> BC-FENZL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBARA FENZL RELISHES ROLE AS CULINARY FORCE  
 (ADV: INCLUDES RECIPES. WITH SAVOR) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Barbara Fenzl didn't grow up under the tutelage of a
mother who cooked. But she grew up with a mother who exposed her
family to wonderful foods.
</P>
<P>
   The day Mom brought home and savored a steamed artichoke is a
culinary memory that lingers in Barbara's mind.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was raising three children of her own, Barbara
was a master in the kitchen, with a sophisticated palate and a
degree from the renowned Cordon Bleu cooking school in London.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1983, she has operated her own cooking school in Phoenix,
Les Gourmettes, where she teaches three classes a week and spices
up the curriculum with guest instructors, including such globally
known chefs as Jacques Pepin, Martin Yan and Anne Willan and such
local luminaries as Vincent Guerithault and Christopher Gross.
</P>
<P>
   She was food editor of ``Southwest Passages'' magazine from
1992-1995 and food editor of ``Phoenix Home &AMP; Garden'' magazine
from 1987-1992. She is a past president of the International
Association of Culinary Professionals (IACP) and a founding member
of the Phoenix chapter of Les Dames d'Escoffier, a group of 1,900
women food, wine and hospitality experts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a resume any food lover would be content with.
</P>
<P>
   But her grandest adventure yet is just beginning. On March 9,
PBS Channel 8 (KAET), operating from Arizona State University,
launches ``Savor the Southwest,'' a cooking show hosted by Barbara
and 14 noted American chefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done so many wonderful things in my life,'' Barbara says.
``And now this show. I keep pinching myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara was the obvious choice to host the Phoenix-based series.
A 30-year Phoenix area resident, she is credited with helping
Phoenix to gain national prominence as a culinary destination.
While president of the IACP, she staked a claim for her city and
made her name among the country's top food wonks. From 1989 to
1995, she served on the IACP's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Phoenix will host the IACP's annual convention,
welcoming an all-star lineup from within the industry.
</P>
<P>
   A founder of the local chapter of the American Institute of Wine
and Food, Barbara serves on its national board of directors and is
an institute benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   She is a charter member of the Arizona Culinary Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara has worked tirelessly over the years to bring the
Phoenix area out of a small-town mentality that as recently as 15
years ago supported little more than a plethora of Mexican eateries
and the odd French restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix is small-town no more. Creative chefs make their mark
here. Even jaded Easterners applaud the Phoenix area for its
innovative cuisine, and Barbara is singled out as one who helped
steer that course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona _ how do I put this politely? _ is rather recently
arrived on the culinary scene,'' says R.W. Apple Jr., chief
correspondent for the ``New York Times,'' who recently examined
Phoenix's growth and culture in a multipart series.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara, he says, ``is generally recognized as the best person
in Arizona on these subjects. Her rise has been related to the rise
of Arizona as a place to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple credits her sophistication and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have someone around with the knowledge of
eating in Europe and Asia as an evaluator of what's taking place on
the local scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert McGrath, chef-owner of the Roaring Fork in Scottsdale and
the first chef featured on ``Savor the Southwest,'' is one of
Barbara's biggest fans. It was Barbara, he says, who wooed him to
Phoenix when she invited him to participate in an olive-oil
symposium in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   A Texan, he fell in love with the city. They've been friends and
colleagues ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gives us a conduit to a national level _ her credentials,
her energy, her name,'' McGrath says, taking precious time away
from his kitchen at the height of the dinner hour to praise his
friend. ``She's just a nice lady. She's great.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Chicago, Barbara, 53, became serious about food when
she married Terry Fenzl, now an attorney for the Phoenix law firm
of Brown and Bain. She and Terry met while students at the
University of Wisconsin at Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Although Terry's mother was a culinary whiz, cooking Austrian
favorites on special occasions, Barbara's mother had grown up in a
family with a cook who banned everyone else from the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   After Barbara and Terry were married in 1967 and moved to
Phoenix, they began traveling to Europe, where they tasted the
finest foods from celebrated chefs and learned to re-create the
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   With a bachelor's from Wisconsin and a master's from Arizona
State University, Barbara went to work as a social-studies teacher
in Phoenix. In 1971, she and Terry had their first child, and she
didn't teach again until she took a job at Rio Salado Community
College a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   By then, she and her food-savvy husband had been through several
fantasy cooking courses in such French villages as Perouges,
Annency and Eugenie-les-Bains. The latter school was run by the
legendary Michel Guerard, creator of ``cuisine minceur,'' a
reduced-calorie style of French cooking served at his signature
spa.
</P>
<P>
   While studying at the spa, the Fenzls rubbed elbows with British
lords and ladies and California winemaker Robert Mondavi, who also
were students in the intimate classroom. To the accompaniment of a
piano player flown in from Paris, the students cooked all afternoon
and ate until dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an amazing week,'' Barbara says.
</P>
<P>
   On nights off, they dined in local restaurants that served
memorable cuisine. At one, each guest received a hand-embroidered
napkin woven with that night's menu.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the number of Barbara's culinary acquaintances was
growing. She met the suave Pepin and grande dame Julia Child, who
urged her to open a cooking school.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been my mentor ever since,'' Barbara says, confirming
that Child is as charming in person as she is on television.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the early 1980s, the Valley offered a handful of
cooking classes. Barbara opened Les Gourmettes with another
teacher, Pam Wischkaemper. The two ran the school out of their
Valley homes while raising preschool children.
</P>
<P>
   When Barbara decided she needed more solid teaching credentials,
Terry took a three-month leave of absence from his law firm, and
the family rented a home for the summer in London. Barbara studied
at the Cordon Bleu while Terry minded the three kids.
</P>
<P>
   Les Gourmettes took off and now enjoys widespread popularity,
serving more than 1,200 students a year.
</P>
<P>
   The notion for a locally based cooking show began in 1994, when
Barbara published the cookbook ``Southwest the Beautiful.'' Jillian
Robinson, a producer at Channel 8, told Barbara she wanted to
develop ``a show like your book.''
</P>
<P>
   They drew up a proposal and assembled a who's-who of
Southwestern chefs. With such an esteemed cast, ``Savor'' will
enhance Phoenix's growing reputation as a tasty destination for
fine cooking and dining, Barbara believes: ``I think this is going
to do even more to put Phoenix on the culinary map.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Roasted Vegetables &QL; 
(Chuck Wiley's recipe, reprinted with permission from ``Savor the
Southwest,'' by Barbara Pool Fenzl, published by Bay Books, 1999) &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 tablespoon unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 carrots, cut into thirds
</P>
<P>
   2 parsnips, cut into thirds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 rutabaga, peeled and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   6 small onions, 2 inches in diameter, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 small Japanese eggplants, cut in half lengthwise, then in half
crosswise
</P>
<P>
   1 zucchini, cut in half lengthwise, then in thirds
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow squash, cut in half lengthwise, then in thirds
</P>
<P>
   3 portobello mushrooms, stems removed, caps cut in half
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup tomato chunks
</P>
<P>
   Heat a cast-iron skillet over charcoal briquettes or the glowing
embers of a wood fire, or preheat a heavy oven-proof skillet or
roasting pan in a 400-degree oven.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix together the butter, olive oil and balsamic
vinegar. In a large bowl, toss the carrots, parsnips, rutabaga and
onions with half of the butter-oil mixture. Season the vegetables
with salt and pepper to taste. Place the seasoned root vegetables
into the hot skillet. If cooking over a fire, cover with foil and
roast approximately 15 minutes. If cooking in an oven, do not cover
and cook approximately 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the eggplants, zucchini, yellow squash and mushrooms in a
large bowl with the rest of the butter-oil mixture. Season with
salt and pepper to taste and add to the pan with the root
vegetables. Roast, covered if over an open fire and uncovered if in
the oven, until the onions are soft, about 15 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan from the fire or the oven and stir in the thyme
and tomatoes. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 to 10 servings. Approximate values per serving: 103
calories, 3 g fat, 4 mg cholesterol, 18 g carbohydrates, 5.9 g
fiber, 3 g protein, 380 mg sodium, 27 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Margarita Shrimp Salad &QL; 
(Barb Fenzl's recipe, reprinted with permission from ``Savor the
Southwest,'' by Barbara Pool Fenzl, published by Bay Books, 1999. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shrimp and marinade:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 serrano chile, stemmed, seeded and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup tequila
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Triple Sec or Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin seed, toasted and ground, or 1 teaspoon ground
cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 pound shrimp (16 to 20 per pound), peeled, deveined and slit
open along the backs
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for frying tortillas
</P>
<P>
   4 corn tortillas, 6 inches in diameter, cut into thin julienne
strips
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, cored, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 yellow bell pepper, cored, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   6 cups torn romaine lettuce leaves, washed and thoroughly dried
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the shrimp:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the cilantro, garlic, chile, tequila, Triple Sec, lime
juice and cumin in a non-reactive bowl. Add the shrimp, turn to
coat, and refrigerate for at least 1 hour. Drain the shrimp and
reserve the marinade.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan over high heat, bring the reserved marinade
to a boil. Reduce the heat to medium and simmer until reduced by
half. Remove from the heat, transfer to a bowl, and let cool. Whisk
in the olive oil and season with salt and pepper to taste. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a barbecue grill or preheat a broiler. Grill or broil
the shrimp until just pink, about 1 minute per side. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   For the salad
</P>
<P>
   Fill a small skillet with oil to a depth of about 1 inch and
place over medium heat. When the oil is about 375 degrees, fry the
tortilla strips in batches until light brown and crisp. Drain on
paper towels. Sprinkle with chili powder while still warm.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, mix together the tomato, bell pepper and
lettuce. Toss with the marinade-oil dressing and divide among 4
large plates or shallow bowls. Top the salad with grilled shrimp
and fried tortilla strips.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings. Approximate values per serving: 463 calories,
18 g fat, 173 mg cholesterol, 32 g carbohydrates, 4 g fiber, 29 g
protein, 347 mg sodium, 41 percent calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
