<HEADLINE>
CHEFS HELP DEFINE SOUTHWEST CUISINE  
 (ADV: WITH SAVOR) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The chefs featured in ``Savor the Southwest'' and what
they will prepare, in order of their scheduled appearances:
</P>
<P>
   - Robert McGrath: fish. The chef-owner at Roaring Fork in
Scottsdale, Ariz., opens the series fishing in Oak Creek Canyon
near Sedona and makes pan-fried trout, duck breasts cured in sugar
and chile, and green chile macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   - Mary Sue Milliken and Susan Feniger: chiles. The Two Hot
Tamales of their own Food Network series own the Border Grill in
Santa Monica, Calif., and prepare chipotle corn relish, vegetarian
red-bean chile, and ancho-glazed chicken with seared chard.
</P>
<P>
   - Robert Del Grande: beef. Del Grande, Houston's Southwestern
pioneer and known for his work at Cafe Annie, Rio Ranch Texas and
Cafe Express, shows how to make coffee-roasted fillet of beef with
pasilla chile broth and gratin of Swiss chard. &QL; 
- Chuck Wiley: game and outdoor cooking. The vice president of food
and beverage for Grand Bay Hotels and Carefree Resorts, including
the Boulders in Carefree, roasts vegetables with an achiote-basted
rack of venison and Dutch-oven cornbread.
</P>
<P>
   - Donna Nordin: chocolate. The chef-owner of Cafe Terra Cotta in
Scottsdale and Tucson prepares chicken mole and chocolate tacos.
</P>
<P>
   - Janos Wilder: native seeds and heirloom plants. The chef-owner
of Janos in Tucson makes blue corn-encrusted cabrilla with rainbow
posole broth and salsa fresca.
</P>
<P>
   - Loretta Barrett Oden: stew. A Potawatomi raised in Oklahoma,
the chef-owner of the Corn Dance Cafe in Santa Fe, prepares Three
Sisters, a stew with corn dumplings, and Indian pudding.
</P>
<P>
   - Lenard Rubin: barbecue. The chef at the Scottsdale Princess
Resort's Marquesa demonstrates mango chipotle barbecue sauce,
barbecued beef short ribs, Southwestern barbecue paella and
marinated grilled chicken.
</P>
<P>
   - Stephan Pyles: fresh chiles. The chef of Star Canyon in Dallas
makes three-tomato pico, goat cheese and crab rellenos, and
chocolate diablo bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   - RoxSand Suarez Scocos: local produce. The chef-owner of
RoxSand in Phoenix prepares mesquite crepes with onion filling and
leek broth.
</P>
<P>
   - Jay McCarthy: cactus. The chef of Cazwellas in Telluride,
Colo., stuffs nopales (cactus pads) with beef machaca and makes
cactus fries, cactus shrimp and a drink he calls the Cactus Rita.
</P>
<P>
   - John Sedlar: tamales. The Southwestern pioneer, who currently
does not have a restaurant, prepares chicken and tomatillo tamales
and salmon mousse tamales.
</P>
<P>
   - Vincent Guerithault: tortillas. The chef-owner of Vincent's on
Camelback demonstrates a Southwestern omelet, seared tuna tortilla
sandwich with cilantro pesto, and a banana and raspberry tart. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
