<SLUG> BC-FISHING-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN OFFICIALS HOOK U.S. FISHING BOATS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn.: Okla.) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McALLEN, Texas _ At first, there was nothing unusual about an
early morning fishing trip to the bass-laden waters of Falcon Lake.
</P>
<P>
   After all, McAllen veterinarian Andy Baker had been fishing this
international reservoir weekly over the past 10 years since moving
his practice from Houston to the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But shortly before noon on Feb. 11, as he and his son, Brad, 31,
of the Houston area made a last cast near a rock pile not far from
the Mexican shore, something different happened.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Baker's boat was boarded by two Mexican officials asking
for his fishing license and boat permit. Baker had a valid Mexican
fishing license but didn't have it with him, and his boat permit
had expired. His son had no license.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities told Baker to follow them to shore, where
armed officials were waiting. They seized Baker's 19-foot Dynatrac
bass boat with a 150-horse power Johnson outboard motor _ purchased
new for $25,000 in 1993 _ 10 rods and reels, several tackle boxes,
life jackets, a combination Global Positioning System and sonar
unit, a $500 pair of binoculars and a new trolling motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let us take some Cokes we had iced down in the cooler,''
Andy Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Mexican shore, recent Oklahoma retirees James Battles,
62, and his wife, Laura, 58, had just been relieved of their new
Triton bass boat with a 115-hp outboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe the Mexican people and the government an apology, and a
fine, for fishing without a license,'' James Battles told the
Zapata County News. ``But I don't think I owe them a boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, it looks as if the boats may be gone for good. The
Battles finally left Zapata, Texas, on Sunday after several
unsuccessful attempts to recover their vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel the longer it goes, the less chance I have of getting
my boat,'' Andy Baker said. ``If we have to go through the legal
channels, it will take months.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who just last year towed a bass fishing rig to the
Mexican Pacific coast and frequently pilots his small plane to Baja
California to fish for marlin, said the experience has soured him
on Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 30 years, I've never had anything but good things to say,
but they've lost my tourist business for a while,'' said Baker, who
estimated he spent $4,000 in Mexico last year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. consular officials acknowledged that neither of the fishing
parties were carrying the required permits when their boats were
confiscated. But they said it's unusual for Mexican officials to
take such drastic measures to enforce the fishing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very likely these Mexican EPA guys, they just wanted a
couple of nice boats,'' said one federal official, who asked not to
be identified. ``Unfortunately along the border, oftentimes Mexican
officials are looking for an excuse to seize a vehicle. They want
it for them personally or to use as an agency vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   And even learning what the legal channels are for recovering the
boats or learning their location has proved difficult, and U.S.
officials say their Mexican counterparts have not returned calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our efforts have been fruitless,'' said David Schlaefer, chief
of American Citizen Services at the U.S. Consulate in Matamoros,
Mexico. ``We've left numerous messages, and the typical reply is
you need to get in touch with another office.''
</P>
<P>
   Schlaefer said the boats were seized by two officials of
Mexico's environmental protection agency, known as ``PROFEPA.'' The
officials were from the agency's office in San Fernando,
Tamaulipas, a town about two hours' drive south of Brownsville,
Texas. The agency's state headquarters is in the Tamaulipas capital
of Ciudad Victoria, where the anglers were told their boats would
be taken.
</P>
<P>
   But Schlaefer said his two-person consular staff in Matamoros
does not have time to drive to either city and contact the
officials in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see the penalty applied to American citizens be
more consistent with the severity of the offense,'' Schlaefer said.
``It would seem reasonable for the Mexican authorities to perhaps
levy a fine against them and allow them to pay and go on their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to seize the boats and all the equipment on the boats was
a very severe penalty for what was, after all, not a very egregious
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
