<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6606 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVOR-AZR &LR;      03-03 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE SCENES ON `SAVOR THE SOUTHWEST' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - ``It's just a little hotbed of Southwestern excitement
here, isn't it?'' chef John Sedlar said as he stood outside the
garage/prep kitchen on the set of ``Savor the Southwest'' during
filming in June in Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   In special previews next week, Arizona viewers will get to see
what went on during the 2{-week location shoot of what was
undoubtedly the most intense Southwestern food experience in recent
memory. Chefs from all over the Southwest strutted their culinary
stuff on camera for 13 episodes with host Barbara Fenzl, author and
Phoenix cooking-school owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Savor the Southwest'' is the largest production ever attempted
by Channel 8 (KAET), the Phoenix area's PBS affiliate. As of press
time, more than 80 other public-television stations, including
those in Boston, San Francisco, Chicago and Dallas, had signed up
to air the show.
</P>
<P>
   KAET produced the show with A La Carte Productions, which has
offices in Boston and San Francisco and whose crew ``lived in Julia
Child's kitchen for four years,'' as producer Geoffrey Drummond put
it. Their credits include ``Baking With Julia,'' ``In Julia's
Kitchen With Master Chefs'' and ``Julia Child &AMP; Jacques Pepin,
Cooking in Concert.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the featured chefs are from Arizona. The others are
from California, New Mexico, Texas and Colorado. Most are pioneers
who helped invent and refine Southwest cuisine since its beginnings
in the late '70s and early '80s. Most will be fresh faces to the
national audience that will see ``Savor,'' but some have television
experience, like the Two Hot Tamales, Mary Sue Milliken and Susan
Feniger of the TV Food Network. You could fill a shelf with the
cookbooks these chefs have written and plaster the walls of a
commercial kitchen with their various awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Savor'' took nearly five years from conception to airing.
KAET's Jillian Robinson had brainstorming sessions on showcases for
Southwestern culture with station manager Beth Vershure and thought
food would be an interesting window through which to view the
history, culture and lore of the region.
</P>
<P>
   She went to a party when Fenzl's ``Southwest the Beautiful''
cookbook was released in May 1994 and found her host.
</P>
<P>
   Fenzl had the same vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this dream about five years ago when I was writing the
book,'' she said. ``People said, `Oh, this is so great, this should
be a cooking show.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson added, ``Then, Barb and I were sort of attached at the
hip for several years.'' Robinson took classes at Les Gourmettes,
Fenzl's school, and Fenzl introduced her to the Southwestern chefs
teaching there.
</P>
<P>
   They put a proposal together and started the funding search.
They found their sponsoring angels for the series at the Ethel and
Kemper Marley Foundation along with KAET Program Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Once funding was secured, production of the program had to be
put out to bid, because KAET, part of Arizona State University, is
a state agency. The contract was won by A La Carte, whom Robinson
called ``the best in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The next task was to find a location, which involved scouting
dozens of homes in Paradise Valley and Scottsdale for a kitchen
with Southwestern decor and an island with a gas cooktop as well as
owners who didn't mind having their home turned into a television
studio for 2{ weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing quite worked out, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at one place in Paradise Valley at this great big
sprawling house that was quite wonderful, but I really thought I
was in Bel Air (Calif.),'' A La Carte producer Geoffrey Drummond
said. It wouldn't look Southwestern enough on TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A pro's kitchen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What finally filled the bill was the 4,000-square-foot
Pueblo-style Prescott home of Hillary Guild, whose business,
Kitchen Consultants, is a network of food professionals across the
country who work with food and equipment companies. This is Guild's
third custom home, and every one has been the site of filming. She
already had a sink, cabinetry, gas lines and heavy-duty wiring in
the garage, and when she knew her kitchen was going to be
considered, ``that of course instantly encouraged us to have the
only garage in Prescott with a working waste disposal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also put a gas cooktop into the island instead of the
smooth-top she usually prefers. When KitchenAid is one of your
clients, it's not that big of a deal to change out a cooktop.
</P>
<P>
   As production drew near, A La Carte's culinary producer, Chris
Styler, contacted all the chefs about their recipes. As the
backstage chef, Styler makes the twin dish that the on-camera chef
pulls from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Styler has one of the most intense jobs on the crew. He worked
the only day that everybody else got off. This was the first
cooking show that he worked on in which every episode featured a
different chef. Some, such as Chuck Wiley, brought everything they
needed, including napkin rings and an assistant. Most came with
little or nothing. For them, he ordered all the food, prepped it
and made the twin dishes. At the end of the day, he made the lists
and did the shopping for the next day's work.
</P>
<P>
   From the East Coast, A La Carte shipped or hand-carried almost
all the equipment needed for the shoot, from pots and pans to
cameras. Geoffrey Drummond says the jampacked three-car garage in
Connecticut where the company stores its culinary equipment looks
like a Williams-Sonoma store with three refrigerators and a stove.
Kitchen Classics in Phoenix supplied Southwestern serving dishes,
which were arrayed on tables in the hallway, site of frequent
impromptu consultations over what to use next.
</P>
<P>
   Styler and his helpers worked downstairs in the garage in a
temporary kitchen with eight burners, two ovens and two
refrigerators. The downstairs crew had to maintain quiet during the
shots and was glued to the set upstairs via intercom and TV
monitors. Specific requests from Fenzl, the chefs or director Bruce
Franchini for a serving spoon or achiote or a certain-size pot
would send Styler or assistant Pat Teel pounding up the stairs at
top speed with the needed item.
</P>
<P>
   Between shots, Styler or Teel would go pounding up the stairs
again with big trays of supplies for the next setup. Each chef did
a run-through of recipes with Styler and then another one with
Franchini and Fenzl before the cameras rolled.
</P>
<P>
   Teel, who has since moved to a job cooking at a winery in
Oregon, was a Prescott freelancer hired for the shoot. Another
Prescott-based freelancer on the set was makeup artist Clara
Taillole-Nardo, a Phoenix native who was happy to have a local job
between her frequent commutes to Hollywood, where her career
includes 20th Century Fox shows such as ``Mad About You'' and ``Two
Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place.''
</P>
<P>
   During breaks, Taillole-Nardo refreshed lipstick and re-powdered
foreheads that were starting to shine from the lights and
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did a good job on your little eyelashes,'' Mary Sue
Milliken said to Susan Feniger in the walk-throughs. The Tamales
constantly teased each other and cracked up with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Taillole-Nardo's time was spent with Fenzl in the
bedroom suite, which was converted into a dressing room. Two racks
of clothing stood under the window; the bed was covered with
Southwestern costume jewelry. As one of the pre-production chores,
Drummond and Franchini went through Fenzl's closets with her to
select outfits.
</P>
<P>
   On the first Friday of the production, Fenzl and Taillole-Nardo
did eight wardrobe and hair changes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pantyhose to the rescue &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first chef to be filmed was Vincent Guerithault, whose show
will appear last in the Channel 8 rotation. Taping was delayed
three hours because the cabinet doors, made of painted twigs,
distorted the camera image. Nothing would fix it until one of the
crew members remembered that years before he had worked on a
program in which the cameras were softened for the aging star with
pantyhose over the lenses. After frantic forays to find two dozen
pair at Wal-Mart and Target, the crew dressed the cabinet doors in
Calvin Klein No. 2 pantyhose. It worked. No more moire effect.
Vincent did his tortilla show.
</P>
<P>
   The production was painstaking, exact. Director Franchini
coached Fenzl and the chefs from the dining room, which was covered
in furniture pads to accommodate the control room. The philosophy
was ``to get in the pot,'' to show real cooking, the integrity of
the food, Drummond said. Takes were shot and re-shot, nothing was
faked.
</P>
<P>
   The crew is a big part of the aura of knowledgeable
professionalism that permeated the set. This crew knows food. At
the end of each taping, when the ``beauty shots'' of the finished
dishes were finally done, the members of the crew got to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Fenzl, who cooks and teaches as easily as she breathes, had to
learn a new set of acting skills: learning lines, timing, how to
position herself next to the chef, how to hit her marks. On one of
the first days of shooting, she had to climb a big rock spire and
fling her arms expansively.
</P>
<P>
   Fenzl opens each episode by demonstrating a cooking technique,
such as roasting chiles. The 13 techniques were edited into one
tape, which KAET plans to offer as a thank-you gift during pledge
drives. But her larger role is to be the audience's guide as she
reacts to the chefs, questions them, clarifies their terms,
mentions that Robert Del Grande has a Ph.D. in chemistry as he rubs
a mixture of coffee, cocoa and cinnamon onto a tenderloin.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the Southwest shines. And in a sense, Drummond
said, the region is the real star. Fenzl and the chefs will be
nationally known after this show is seen in different markets, but
until then the food is what is going to draw people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if the spark of the Southwest comes through the
personality of our talent,'' Drummond said. ``What we're looking to
capture through the food and people is the personality of the
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say the air is different here.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
