<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PORK04-cox     03-03 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK04-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    PORK BARREL SPENDING ROASTED
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    with PORK-List
 &HT;    moving in (w) Washington category
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although partisan rancor dominated much of Congress
last year, Democrats and Republicans had little trouble working
together in one area: spending money for home state projects.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers dipped into the ``pork barrel'' to the tune of $12
billion for 2,838 projects for local constituents, according to the
congressional ``Pig Book,'' made public Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost went down somewhat from the $13.2 billion counted
a year ago by Citizens Against Government Waste, a private watchdog
group that attempts to embarrass lawmakers who add projects through
back-room deal-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets sold as the government's money,'' the group's
president Tom Schatz said Wednesday. ``Taxpayers have to realize
it's their money.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at a gathering that featured a pot-bellied pig that
noisily chowed down on animal crackers scattered among fake dollar
bills and coins.
</P>
<P>
   Schatz said that despite the annual lampooning, the amount of
congressional pork has fluctuated only slightly since his group
began tracking it eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schatz said projects listed in the ``Pig Book'' fit one of
several criteria: they serve only a narrow or local interest, were
requested by only one chamber of Congress, were not requested by
the president, or were not competitively awarded.
</P>
<P>
   Among them:
</P>
<P>
   A water taxi service to shuttle tourists and conventioneers
between Savannah, Ga.'s entertainment district and a new
international trade center on Hutchinson Island. The $500,000
project, which had not been requested by either house or by the
White House, was added to the huge annual spending bill in an 11th
hour bargaining session.
</P>
<P>
   Vidalia onion research for Georgia costing $100,000, and
$500,000 for Texas Tech University at Lubbock to study ``stress''
in plants growing in arid regions.
</P>
<P>
   A National Center for Cool and Cold Water Aquaculture that would
study whether fish can be raised on farms and in abandoned mines in
West Virginia. Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., has captured nearly $16
million for the project since 1995, but the center has yet to be
built. Citizens Against Government Waste awarded him the ``cold
shower award'' for winning $2 million more for the project this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A new $86 million federal courthouse for Jacksonville, Fla.,
secured by Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., and Rep. Corinne Brown,
D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A new glass cockpit flight simulator for C-141 transport planes
for the Air Force Reserve at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base,
costing $1.6 million, secured by Rep. David Hobson, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors for military ``pork'' went to former Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., who was given the ``leaving with a jet plane -or
two- award'' for snaring a $112 million contract to build two
C-130J transports at Lockheed Martin's Marietta plant. The
transports had not been requested by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers defend their projects as protecting jobs and
prosperity at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water taxi project is a valid project,'' said Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga. He said it will ``ease congestion'' on the
Talmadge Bridge that links Savannah to Hutchinson Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vidalia onion is one of the most successful crops in the
first district,'' said Kingston, who argued that the funds were
``well-spent'' to keep the famous sweet onion ahead of its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   And a spokesman for Hobson argued that the flight simulator
would be a money saver, since pilots could train without the wear
and tear on planes of the fuel expense.
</P>
<P>
   As in past years, the states that won the most pork per capita
were Alaska, whose lawmakers brought in $273 per resident, and
Hawaii, which received $155 per capita.
</P>
<P>
   (For TExas only)
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers have grabbed less than some of their peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have more fiscal conservatives in Texas,'' said
David Williams, chief researcher for Citizens Against Government
Waste. The Texas pork spending totalled only $11.47 per person,
according to the group. That put Texas No. 42 in the list of per
capita ``pork'' spending among states.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Texas lured $12 million for the Dallas-Fort Worth rail
transportation project known as ``Railtran,'' $3.4 million for dam
safety at Waco Lake, and $28 million for a new courthouse at
Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courthouse is extremely old and antiquated,'' said Susan
Phalen, spokeswoman for Rep. Henry Bonilla, R-Texas. ``I don't see
how anyone visiting Laredo could think it was a pork barrel
project.''
</P>
<P>
   (end for texas only)
</P>
<P>
   (CAN END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Citizens Against Government Waste, which claims 600,000 members,
also gave a ``hopping mad'' award to Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ala., for
obtaining $250,000 for grasshopper research in his state. But that
project is tiny compared with a program that has become a pork
classic in the annual ``Pig Book.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few clicks on the Internet, and a web surfer can see U.S.
tax dollars at work with a full-collar photo display, updated
round-the-clock, of a forest of 48 antennas on a field surrounded
by snowy Alaskan peaks.
</P>
<P>
   This is the High Frequency Active Auroral Research Program
(HAARP.com), a mysterious project that is either (1) a useful
research project that bombards the ionosphere with low frequency
radio beams, (2) a secret military scheme to control the weather
(as charged by Europeans but denied by U.S. officials), or (3) a
boondoggle that has never been given an objective test by
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Energy project, which will cost $12.5
million this year, has cost at least $43 million since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
