<HEADER>
A6619 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAFIA-LEADER-HNS &LR;      03-03 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAFIA-LEADER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS OF POOR MAN'S MAFIA FOUND GUILTY IN RACKETEERING CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ As a so-called general of the Texas Mexican
Mafia, Robert ``Beaver'' Perez was by most accounts a powerful man.
</P>
<P>
   Mafia members delivered to him the 10 percent street tax
collected from drug dealers and prostitutes. Then he distributed a
share of that to imprisoned mafia members around the state.
</P>
<P>
   He even exercised his authority to give the ``green light'' _
mafia code for ordering a colleague's execution.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Perez was one of 10 Texas Mexican Mafia members
found guilty of racketeering in a federal case that accused them of
plotting 15 murders, including the execution of five people.
</P>
<P>
   But for all his influence, painstakingly illustrated in the
six-week trial, the ``general'' was in many ways just another guy
from San Antonio's poor, mostly Mexican-American west side. The
twice married father of eight was living in subsidized housing at
the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no John Gotti,'' said Blair McLeod, his
court-appointed attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the New York mob, at least, the San
Antonio-headquartered Texas Mexican Mafia is nickel-and-dime stuff.
At the time of the arrest of John Gotti's son, John Gotti Jr.,
police seized more than $300,000 in cash. At the home of Perez last
year, authorities found not even $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the Texas Mexican Mafia may help explain why this
organization might be called the poor man's mafia. The organization
is a prison gang, launched in 1984 from behind the walls of Texas
penitentiaries only to emerge in the barrios of most of the state's
major cities as its members were paroled.
</P>
<P>
   Today authorities say ``La Eme,'' as it is known on the street
for the Spanish letter M, is the largest of 10 prison gangs, with
about 1,400 members behind bars and several thousand more on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   While the East Coast mob has traditionally controlled industries
such as garbage hauling and freight moving in addition to exerting
power over politicians, the domain of the Texas Mexican Mafia is
tumble-down neighborhoods that rank among the poorest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are not sophisticated when it comes to money,''
said Bill Baumann, an assistant U.S. attorney who successfully
prosecuted the mafia in the racketeering case. ``They prey on
people in the projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cash added up. Authorities say Perez received between
$5,000 and $10,000 a week from five ``lieutenants'' charged with
collecting 10 percent, or the ``dime,'' as it is known among
members. Much of this money is believed to have gone to members in
prison, or their families.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence is scant that members of the Texas Mexican Mafia
used their money to escape the urban underclass, into which most of
them were born.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Herrera, a ``captain'' who authorities say reported to
Perez, is a high school dropout who nonetheless acquired his GED.
Authorities describe his west side home as a ``hovel.'' According
to his lawyer, Herrera was raised by an uncle and met his mother
when he was 19, only to hear her ask, ``What do you want?''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Estrada, a ``soldier'' and key government witness who
confessed with little remorse to committing six murders, finished
eighth grade without learning how to read or write and was raised
by a father who trafficked cocaine. His sister is dead from a
heroin overdose, and he has two brothers in prison.
</P>
<P>
   And Pete Carrion, another ``soldier'' and the only defendant to
take the stand, testified that he fathered the first of his six
children at age 15 and two years later became a drug dealer.
Authorities say mafia members often use drugs as well as sell them,
often frittering away their profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people with no structure in their lives,'' said Alan
Futrell, Herrera's court-appointed attorney. ``They're looking for
support or camaraderie or devotion that they can't find
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the Texas Mexican Mafia may share more with
street gangs than with organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``La Eme'' operates without the financial savvy of the
East Coast mob, it seems to be every bit as ruthless. That was
evident over the course of the San Antonio trial, in which the 10
members were charged with a racketeering conspiracy that included
15 murders since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was the worst mass murder in San Antonio history, the
execution-style killings of five people, four of them teen-agers,
during a robbery at a house on the west side. Though testimony
never made clear the reason for the slayings, it appears the mafia
members did not find what they had sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the streets of San Antonio's west side a war zone,''
said David Counts, a federal prosecutor who worked alongside
Baumann. ``Everywhere you looked, it was a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which yielded plea bargains for six members of the
organization, was the second major blow to the Mexican Mafia this
decade. In 1994, 16 mafia members were convicted, including
Heriberto ``Herb'' Huerta, the group's founder who is now being
held in a high-security federal prison in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
