<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES FOCUS ON ATTORNEY GENERAL'S DECISION IN IMMIGRANT CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several Supreme Court justices, hearing a
Guatemalan immigrant's plea that he faces persecution if deported,
said Wednesday that the federal government apparently favors
political refugees who flee American enemies over those trying to
escape from U.S. allies.
</P>
<P>
   The justices focused on the history of political assassinations
as they considered whether Attorney General Janet Reno was on firm
legal ground when she ordered the expulsion of Juan Anibal
Aguirre-Aguirre, who is wanted in Guatemala for attacking people,
burning buses and vandalizing stores.
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre-Aguirre, who sneaked into the United States in 1993,
seeks asylum based on the claim that his crimes were political acts
against an oppressive government, an argument the Justice
Department rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Solicitor General Patricia Millett, representing
the federal government, told the justices that they owe the
attorney general latitude in her decisions on whether an
immigrant's crimes were political or wholly criminal. Attorney
Nadine Wettstein, pressing Aguirre-Aguirre's case, said the
attorney general's discretion is limited and can reject claims for
asylum when the immigrants crimes were either not motivated by
politics or so egregious as to render any political motive
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia said he has difficulty accepting
Millett's argument that the attorney general has wide discretion.
In particular, Scalia said he is troubled by the notion that an
attorney general could admit assassins into the United States so
long as they killed for a political purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow those things killings to be done in this
country for a political purpose,'' Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   But Millett responded that the United States might in
extraordinary cases consider admitting someone who killed to
achieve a political goal. For example, the government might have
welcomed Germans who tried but failed to assassinate Adolf Hitler
during World War II, she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Justice David H. Souter wondered whether the United
States would protect a political dissident of a U.S. ally. ``Have
we rewarded the enemies of our side?'' Souter asked.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the specific details of Aguirre-Aguirre's case,
Millett said the issue of political assassination is irrelevant
because the Guatemalan attacked civilians, dragging them off buses
that he was about to burn and from stores he was going to
vandalize. Attacks on civilians are acts of terror, not politics,
the Justice Department attorney said, citing the April 1995
terrorist bombing of the Alfred Murrah Federal Building that killed
168 people in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Countering Millett, Wettstein said Aguirre-Aguirre did not
attack civilians but rather aimed his outrage at the buses as part
of a political statement opposing the Guatemalan government's
doubling of public transportation fares. The attorney general,
rather than focusing on the political motive and nature of
Aguirre-Aguirre's actions as she should have, concentrated only on
the illegality of his behavior in ordering him back to Guatemala,
Wettstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Immigration Appeals, a Justice Department division,
concluded that Aguirre-Aguirre's offenses were ``serious
non-political crimes'' and recommended his return to Guatemala. But
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco disagreed,
saying that the 1994 Immigration and Nationality Act requires the
attorney general to give greater consideration to the political
nature of Aguirre-Aguirre's crimes and the persecution he might
face upon his forced return to Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department then appealed to the Supreme Court,
arguing that the law gives the attorney general great deference in
granting asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, however, wondered how much deference the attorney
general is owed in cases of political assassination. For example,
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist asked whether an attorney
general could have granted asylum to communist Lee Harvey Oswald,
who assassinated President John F. Kennedy in 1963 for political
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that would be the position of the United
States,'' Millett responded.
</P>
<P>
   Using a present-day example, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor asked
whether the United States would grant asylum to someone who
attempted to assassinate Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein, with whom
the United States has had a running feud throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Millett declined to address that question, saying she was in no
position to set U.S. policy and that her answer might affect the
situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
