<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USOC ACTS TO IMPROVE BIDDING OVERSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The US Olympic Committee, moving quickly to respond
to a critical report examining its role in the Salt Lake City
payoff scandal, promised Wednesday to rein in and monitor future
Olympic bid cities.
</P>
<P>
   After a special commission chaired by US Senator George Mitchell
charged Monday that the Olympic committee failed to exercise
adequate oversight of the Salt Lake bidding and organizing
committees for the 2002 Winter Games, the USOC's executive board
adopted a reform package designed to prevent similar abuses. It
also asked the White House to designate the International Olympic
Committee as a ``public international organization'' in order to
apply the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act where bribery may be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here making excuses,'' said Olympic committee
president William Hybl. ``We accept responsibility for the change
that has to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides cracking down on the lavish lobbying and gift giving
that led to the worst scandal in modern Olympic history, the USOC
will:
</P>
<P>
   --Open an independent office to oversee bid committees, with a
full-time staffer on site;
</P>
<P>
   --Ban bidders and organizers from giving assistance funds to
foreign Olympic committees;
</P>
<P>
   --Make sure payments from its own international assistance fund
are legitimate;
</P>
<P>
   --Hold open board of directors and executive committee meetings
and publicize their minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Mitchell commission leveled its harshest criticism at
the IOC for what it said is ``an inevitably corruptive'' culture of
improper gift giving, it also found that the USOC failed in its
federal mandate to have ``exclusive responsibility'' for organizing
the Olympics in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While top Salt Lake bid officials were making improper payments
and gifts totalling nearly $1 million to two dozen IOC members, the
report said that the USOC was exercising no authority over SLOC's
day-to-day operations, had no staff members working in the Salt
Lake offices, attended virtually no board or executive committee
meetings between the 1991-95 bidding period, and made no attempt to
audit SLOC's books or records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oversight was abysmal,'' admitted Hybl, who was interim
USOC president between September 1991 and October 1992 before
starting his current term in October 1996. ``There are no excuses
and we're not making any excuses for what happened in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most embarrassing revelation amid the Salt Lake
scandal was that the USOC's own international relations director
(Alfredo LaMont, who resigned in January) was also a paid SLOC
lobbyist who funneled thousands of dollars to an IOC member from
Barbados and steered assistance funds to countries with IOC votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're embarrassed about the whole thing,'' said USOC executive
director Richard Schultz, who assumed the post a few months after
Salt Lake City was awarded the Games. ``The USOC, regardless of the
year, is responsible for this.''
</P>
<P>
   After having partnership difficulties with both the Atlanta and
Salt Lake committees, the USOC had already toughened the rules for
future bid cities before the scandal broke in December. The latest
reforms will also create a separate Office of Compliance to oversee
bidders and deal with conflict-of-interest issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be sure, because of the culture of our country,
that we have rules that are beyond reproach,'' said Schultz. ``You
are what you are perceived to be, and we want to be perceived in a
positive light.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
