<HEADER>
A6671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-HIV-BOS &LR;      03-03 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HIV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS SEEKS ACCELERATED HIV COVERAGE BY MEDICAID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts is aiming to become the first state in
the nation to expand Medicaid to cover the uninsured, working poor
almost as soon as they test HIV positive, in a major step toward
making the AIDS epidemic less deadly here.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci has proposed that $10 million of the expected
tobacco settlement go toward the first year of the expansion, to
provide comprehensive health care for up to 2,000 uninsured
individuals who test positive for the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's fiscal year 2000 budget also includes the
language that would allow the state Division of Medical Assistance
to proceed with the expansion, pending federal approval. State
officials are already in discussions with the US Health Care and
Financing Administration, which oversees the federal-state health
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be one of the most significant advances that
Massachusetts has made in terms of addressing the HIV/AIDS
epidemic,'' said Robert Greenwald, director of public policy and
legal affairs for the AIDS Action Committee of Massachusetts, which
is holding a lobby day Thursday at the Statehouse to convince
legislators to approve the governor's proposal and provide even
more funding for AIDS-related programs.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Massachusetts has seen its AIDS deaths drop by 60
percent between 1996 and 1997, largely as a result of the
availability of new AIDS drugs called protease inhibitors.
According to state public health statistics released late last
year, 242 people died from AIDS in 1997, compared with 609 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Massachusetts offers a state and federally funded
drug assistance program for HIV-infected people who meet certain
guidelines. But comprehensive Medicaid coverage is now provided
only to those who have become so sick from AIDS that they are
disabled and can no longer work.
</P>
<P>
   With the expansion of Medicaid, now known as MassHealth, that
would mean more HIV-infected people could get the comprehensive
care they need to stay as healthy as possible, and to keep working
as long as possible, said Greenwald of AIDS Action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will give early intervention and access, and hopefully it
(HIV infection) will not progress, ever, to AIDS,'' Greenwald said.
``We're excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, uninsured HIV-positive people who have
incomes up to 200 percent of the federal poverty level (about
$16,000 for a single person, $32,000 for a family of four) would
qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   In a previous expansion, Massachusetts extended coverage to
children whose family incomes are up to 200 percent of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The move would ultimately save the government money, by keeping
HIV-infected people healthier and preventing costly
hospitalizations, according to Greenwald.
</P>
<P>
   And it would allow public health officials to launch an
aggressive campaign to encourage people to get tested, since
officials will then be able to offer the Medicaid program to those
who have been reluctant to find out their HIV status because they
have no insurance coverage, Greenwald said.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS Action is also asking legislators to provide even more
public health funding than called for in Cellucci's budget: $2.6
million more for the Department of Public Health AIDS line item,
bringing it up to $54.2 million; and $5.1 million more for the
department's substance-abuse treatment line item, bringing it up to
$48.4 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
