<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERTY-CANCELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY FINANCIAL DROPS PURCHASE OF FRENCH FUNDS UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Liberty Financial Cos. Wednesday canceled its agreement
to buy the US mutual fund arm of French bank Societe Generale SA,
citing a precipitous drop in the unit's assets since the $216
million deal was announced last August.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Liberty does not have to pay any penalty for
terminating the agreement, since its contract to buy New York-based
Societe Generale Asset Management Corp. guarded against any changes
in values. Since August, the firm has seen its assets plunge around
40 percent to $2.8 billion, the victim of volatile world markets
and panicky investors who have bailed out of the firm's SoGen
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the value of the assets moves as dramatically as it did
in this case, the numbers just don't work anymore,'' said Liberty
Financial's chief executive, Kenneth R. Leibler.
</P>
<P>
   News that the transaction might be canceled first appeared in
the Globe last month.
</P>
<P>
   Leibler said Liberty had the right to walk away from the deal if
assets at Societe Generale Asset Management declined by about 30
percent or more. Liberty, a group of eight financial services firms
with $61 billion in assets under management, said Societe Generale
had agreed to call off the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Once high fliers, SoGen's six funds have stumbled, as world
markets batter the international stocks the firm focuses on under
the reins of renowned investor Jean-Marie Eveillard.
</P>
<P>
   Leibler said Liberty was still in the market to buy a global
money manager but that any deals this year were unlikely, since few
companies were for sale and overseas stocks were not doing well.
Asked if Liberty could take another look at Societe Generale's fund
arm in the future, Leibler said, ``It's kind of hard to put
toothpaste back in the tube.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Liberty, whose majority owner is Liberty Mutual
Insurance Co. of Boston, fell 1/4 to close at 21 1/2 Wednesday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0371 </DOCNO>
