<SLUG> BC-CONCENTRA-SOLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE ACQUISITION TO PAY $1.1 BILLION FOR CONCENTRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Concentra Managed Care Inc. Wednesday announced its
pending acquisition _ valued at $1.1 billion _ by Yankee
Acquisition Corp., a division of Welsh, Carson, Anderson &AMP; Stowe, a
New York investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, which is expected to be finalized in the
second quarter of this year, Welsh, Carson agreed to assume $328
million in debt held by Concentra, which manages workers
compensation cases for corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, 93 percent of the company's post-merger stock will
be converted into shares offered for $16.50 each. Welsh, Carson
will also seek an independent investor to purchase the remaining 7
percent, or 1.9 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Concentra says it will continue to operate as an independent
health-care management company under its current name and
management.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a financial buyer for the company that in taking us
private will give us the opportunity to address a few issues,''
said Joseph F. Pesce, Conentra's executive vice president and chief
executive officer, Wednesday. ``What we have had in the past year
is that we have fallen short of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston company runs the nation's largest network of
occupational health care centers, managing the practices of 278
doctors located in 156 centers in two dozen states. Concentra also
offers medical management services such as pre-employment testing
throughout the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh, Carson, a 20-year-old investment firm, currently manages
more than $7 billion in private equity capital primarily in the
health care and information services industries.
</P>
<P>
   The firm funded one of the companies that merged in the summer
of 1997 to create Concentra, and has an investment track record in
the health services industry. Last year, Welsh, Carson purchased
Centennial Healthcare Corp. of Atlanta for $290 million, a few
months after it joined forces with Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. to
buy Medcath Inc. of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement,``was very much expected,'' said Nancy
L. Weaver, who monitors Concentra for Stephens Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Concentra last year went on a Wall Street roller coaster ride,
its stock plunging more than 80 percent from a peak in January,
when more than a dozen brokerage analysts dubbed it a ``best buy.''
</P>
<P>
   By October, the company had formed a special board committee to
cut costs and hired investment bankers to sift through acquisition
offers from a number of discreet suitors. Meanwhile, Welsh, Carson
boosted its ownership of Concentra stock to 14.9 percent of the
company's shares.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver predicts Wells, Carson will increase the company's
presence in the health services industry, a strategy she says would
require capital in the short run but would be profitable down the
road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
