<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-RECYCLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE PACKAGING CITED AS WASTEFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The tiny software disc, the width of two credit cards,
arrived by mail in a Bible-sized box supported by a plastic tray
cushioned by foam _ the kind of packaging that drives recycling
activists to fits.
</P>
<P>
   Software manufacturers are among the newest offenders in
wasteful packaging, said Vivien Watts, field organizer for the
Recycling Initiative Campaign, which released its 10th annual
Wastemaker Awards Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The dubious distinction goes to manufacturers whose packaging is
difficult to recycle, excessive, contains dioxins, or doesn't
contain recycled material. Though strides are being made in
recycling, activists said, it's obviously more efficient to reduce
the amount of waste people generate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are calling on government and consumers to take actions to
reduce the packaging clog in the waste stream,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Representative Pam Resor of Acton, Mass.
announced legislation Wednesday that would ban packaging made with
polyvinyl chloride (PVC), which produces cancer-causing dioxins
when burned in trash incinerators. CVS brand carpet cleaner and
Pine Sol Lemonfresh cleaner and antibacterial spray plastic
containers include PVCs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 14 billion pounds of trash United States consumers
generate each year, 31 percent of it is packaging, Watts said. With
the increase in disposables, each American now disposes of 4.78
pounds of trash a day _ up from 2.87 pounds in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other biggest offenders named by the campaign:
</P>
<P>
   --Fig Newtons Snack Packs. Like all individually wrapped
products, these Nabisco snacks contain unnecessary plastic.
Consumers could do better buying a regular pack and transporting
them in reusable containers, Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   --EtherFast 10/100 CardBus PC Card, which comes in a 9 1/2-inch
by 6-inch by 2 1/4-inch box, filled with a hollow plastic space and
foam.
</P>
<P>
   --Ban roll-on deodorant. Unlike other brands, it comes in a box.
</P>
<P>
   --Hood opaque milk bottles. Colored plastic may shut out light,
but it also is harder to recycle.
</P>
<P>
   --Coke bottles. Labels urge consumers to recycle but the bottles
contain no recycled material.
</P>
<P>
   --Lunchables. Long the bane of recyclers, the Oscar Meyer snacks
come in segmented plastic trays covered with plastic wrap and a
cardboard shell.
</P>
<P>
   --Sunny Delight. Plastic shrink wrap covers eight individual
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   --Kool Aid Kool Bursts. The six-pack comes in shrink-wrap and
cardboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
