<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6683 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-800&AMP;A     03-03 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITY SEEN AS KEY FOR MEXICO'S RULING PARTY IN 2000 ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Hanging on a wall at the hulking downtown
headquarters of Mexico's governing party are dusty oil portraits of
nearly all the 37 politicians who have headed the party since its
founding in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Portraits are hung only after a president of the party, known as
the PRI, leaves office, and currently, there appears to be space
for only one more painting on the wall, that of the party's current
president, Mariano Palacios Alcocer. The visual suggestion left by
the gallery is that the PRI, the world's longest-ruling political
party, has a rich history but not much of a future.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for years analysts have been predicting the demise of
the Institutional Revolutionary Party, but its recent election
victories have undermined those arguments. This week, the debate
over the party's past and future dominated Mexico as President
Ernesto Zedillo and some 2,000 party stalwarts prepared to
celebrate its 70th anniversary, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For decades after its founding, the party was a tool of
successive presidents, using authoritarian methods to insure
one-party rule. Over the last 20 years, however, opposition parties
have chipped away at the PRI monopoly, and now control the Congress
and 10 of the country's 32 state capitals, including Mexico City.
Dozens of PRI leaders have defected to the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But the PRI has never lost the presidency. Polls suggest the
party can win next year's presidential elections, too, but only if
the party can avoid a damaging split. As a result, the way the
party selects its candidate in coming months is crucial, because
powerful politicians seeking the nomination could bolt the party if
they feel mistreated, several analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who has said that unlike his predecessors he will not
hand-pick his successor, is to outline rules for the candidate
selection during Thursday's celebration. The new rules will join
other recent radical changes within the party, like the decline in
influence of labor and peasant leaders and the rise of
television-oriented campaign managers.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping transformations are prompting analysts to
characterize the current period as the end of an epoch, equivalent
to the end of Spanish colonial rule here in the early 19th century
or the beginning of the 1910 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authoritarian system that ruled Mexico for 70 years is
ending,'' said Jose Antonio Crespo, a political scientist. ``The
PRI has never had internal democracy, and it's never had to
alternate presidential power with the opposition. There's no
precedent for the party in power in Mexico to cede to its
opponents. That's always provoked civil war, coup d'etat or
revolution.'' The PRI has been so dominant that to a large degree,
its history is Mexico's history. Created by President Plutarco
Elias Calles in 1929 to control provincial warlords after the
1910-1917 revolution, the party in its early years helped carry out
land reform and create the national army, central bank and public
school system. It oversaw 20 years of rapid economic growth after
World War II, and during decades when the rest of Latin America
stagnated under military rule, allowed democratic roots to take
hold here.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, however, the PRI's strength has declined. Until
the 1980s, the party consistently received 70 percent or more votes
in national elections. But according to a government analysis of
recent elections and polling data, the PRI could count on only
about 42 percent of votes if national elections were held today.
The combined votes of the two largest opposition parties would
total nearly 52 percent, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the PRI's greatest strength is the opposition's
fragmentation into two large parties of nearly equal strength. In
recent days the two parties' likely presidential candidates, Mexico
City's leftist mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, and the populist governor
of Guanajuato state, Vicente Fox, have endorsed the idea of putting
aside ideological differences to mount a single opposition
candidacy to defeat the PRI. But the legal and political obstacles
appear so great that most analysts dismissed the proposal as
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for the PRI to win in 2000 is to avoid a split in its
own ranks that could siphon off PRI votes,'' said Agustin Basave, a
former PRI deputy who has written a history of the party.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Palacios, the PRI president, said
recent victories in gubernatorial races have left party members
``with high spirits and high hopes'' for the 2000 race. He
minimized the risks of a split during the candidate selection
process over the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some individuals might leave, that happens in all parties, but
a major, significant rupture, definitely not,'' Palacios said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the PRI is, like its opponents, divided into two broad
camps, and the coming struggle between them to control the
nomination is laden with risks of a rupture. Currently in control
of the party are the technocrats, led by Zedillo and other
economists who have served their careers in the bureaucracy. The
traditionalists, often called dinosaurs, feel their grass-roots
political experience has been ignored by Zedillo, who attended
Yale, and the two previous presidents, who attended Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The dinosaurs' leader is Manuel Bartlett, a former governor who
last month announced his presidential candidacy. In the weeks
since, one PRI union leader who endorsed Bartlett has complained of
threats from PRI officials, and analysts said the government has
sought to undermine Bartlett's candidacy in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's preferred candidate appears to be Interior Minister
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only risk of a split would come if the party doesn't open
up to real democracy,'' Bartlett said in an interview Wednesday.
``If the party establishes clear rules that lead to a democratic
contest for the candidacy, then the party will be strong in 2000.
If not, there'll be problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
