<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AGENDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DEMOCRATS PUSH FAMILY   ORIENTED AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On a day when so much else was happening _ Monica
S. Lewinsky's first television interview and Hillary Rodham
Clinton's first foray into New York since declaring her interest in
a Senate race there _ President Clinton and congressional Democrats
staged a pep rally that was a counterpoint to both.
</P>
<P>
   Within the stately, ornate confines of the Library of Congress,
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore joined their party's
congressional leaders in extolling the virtues of a family oriented
Democratic agenda that focuses on preserving Social Security and
Medicare, improving public schools and access to health care, and
raising the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   As a roomfull of House and Senate Democrats and their aides
enthusiastically cheered, Clinton and the Democratic leaders
portrayed their party as unified behind its ``Families First''
agenda and brimmed with confidence that Republicans would embrace
many parts of it if for no other reason than to avoid possible
backlash in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is we are organized and we are united,'' Clinton said
to applause. ``And we are united around an agenda for America's
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The show of unity seemed designed to contrast with Republicans,
who are still hammering out the details of their own legislative
program and sifting through a crowded field of GOP presidential
hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Thomas A. Daschle introduced Gore as
``president of the United States,'' adding after a long pause,
``Senate.'' Gore embraced House Minority Leader Richard A.
Gephardt, who opted not to challenge him for the Democratic
presidential nomination, and called him a ``special friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The show of Democratic unity has flowed throughout the Lewinsky
scandal and Clinton's impeachment and trial. The ordeal not only
brought Democrats together but also inflated support for Mrs.
Clinton and led to the current drive to coax her into running for
the Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Democrats Wednesday fanned the flames of
unity, as Senator Edward M. Kennedy, who has served in the Senate
since 1962, said in an interview that he has not seen anything like
it ``in all the time that I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats agree with Clinton that 62 percent _ or $2.8 trillion
_ of the $4.9 trillion budget surplus should be preserved to shore
up Social Security and 15 percent used to extend the life of the
Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want a larger amount of the surplus _ about $200
billion more than Clinton over the next decade _ to go toward
Social Security. And Republicans have yet to agree on whether to
set aside 15 percent for Medicare, or $686 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt urged Republicans to join with Democrats in putting
``the national interest above partisanship'' to approve various
pieces of legislation. ``We want to make progress now. This month.
This year. This session. We can't afford to waste another year or
two mired in partisan wrangling and gridlock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up on the theme, Clinton said, ``I'd also like to ask
that politics stop and that the Republican majority in Congress
stand with us'' on Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   He said he welcomed Republicans' decision ``backing away from
the irresponsible across-the-board tax cut that is too costly'' and
their support for setting aside 62 percent of the budget surplus
for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask the Republican majority to join us in devoting a
portion, 15 percent, of the surplus to save Medicare,'' Clinton
said. ``They have not done that so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' agenda also includes renovating public schools,
instituting accountablity measures for schools, raising the minimum
wage, and ensuring a wider set of options for patients in health
maintenance organizations. It also provides targeted tax cuts for
child care, long-term care, and a controversial plan to establish
private retirement accounts.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois criticized the
Democratic agenda as ``unbalanced.'' ``It favors Washington
bureaucracy over local control, government budget expansion over
the family budget expansion, tax increase over tax relief,'' he
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such rhetoric, Kennedy said he believed that Republicans
and Democrats can come together on several issues, including
minimum wage, education and a patients bill of rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
