<HEADER>
A6685 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-IRP-BOS &LR;      03-03 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-IRP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMINANT PARTY STRUGGLES TO REMAIN DOMINANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Its popularity is eroding. Its leaders are widely
ridiculed as dinosaurs. Its opponents talk of uniting against it.
And its deepening internal battles mean that for the first time in
70 years, it might be in danger of losing a presidential election
next year.
</P>
<P>
   But as it prepares to mark seven decades of unbroken rule
Thursday, the Institutional Revolutionary Party, Mexico's oldest
and long-dominant political group, is trying to put a brave face on
its struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not overconfident, but we're feeling enthusiastic about
the way we've been able to change with the political climate in
Mexico,'' said Celso Humberto Delgado, who heads the party's
national political council. ``Sometimes it's painful, but this has
always been a party of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Its many critics scoff at the thought. Since its founding in
1929 as a broad-based political group in the aftermath of a bloody
revolution, the party, known by the Spanish acronym PRI, has varied
little in its near monopolistic rule, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI is a party without a democratic culture in it,'' said
Luis Javier Garrido, author of a critical history of the party.
``In 1999 we'll see some new methods. . .but the changes are only
superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI is still dominant at the ballot box. Most state
governments are controlled by PRI lawmakers and governors. And the
party has never lost a presidential election, though some say it
took fraud to protect its winning streak in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But as Mexico has opened up economically and politically, the
party's hegemony has shown signs of crumbling. Two years ago, it
lost its majority in congress in the face of gains by parties on
left and right. And in recent years it has lost crucial races for
local offices in the capital and in key states such as Nuevo Leon
and Baja California North.
</P>
<P>
   Internal eruptions _ mostly between traditionalists and
reformers _ have prompted defections of key figures, including
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the Mexico City mayor who joined the leftist
Party of the Democratic Revolution in the 1980s and is expected to
run for president next year. Last week, Cardenas urged the
opposition parties to hold a joint primary to choose a unity
candidate to run against the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   PRI leaders insist that losing some elections and the
ideological debates among factions are a normal part of a
transition toward becoming more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only campaigns we've lost have been to former PRI
members,'' Delgado added. ``We haven't lost to anyone produced by
the parties themselves. But it still concerns us that people leave
our party and win against us, and that's something we're studying
closely.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the party is recruiting younger members and promoting
grass-roots candidates who are ``more political with their neighbor
than with their boss.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was little evidence of that last week when the party
hosted a press conference with four candidates vying to run for
governor in the northern state of Coahuila. In a dreary,
smoke-filled basement at party headquarters in Mexico City, the
dour-faced rivals sat elbow to elbow at a narrow table. Each talked
about how long he had toiled for the party and offered poetic
tributes to its past. None proposed a campaign platform.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one party official boasted that having more than one
candidate seeking a nomination was itself something new.
</P>
<P>
   ``In times past there would've been one candidate and he
would've won. No questions,'' said the official, who wore a pin
bearing the party's red, white, and green logo but refused to give
his name.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, most candidates were selected by party leaders in a
closed process, and every six years the president anointed his own
successor. But in seven winning governor's races in the past two
years, the party chose its candidate in what amounted to a state
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Reformers have called for a similar process to select a
presidential candidate next year. President Ernesto Zedillo, who
won slightly more than 50 percent of the vote in 1994, says he does
not intend to name a candidate and joined those urging US-style
primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   As they mark the party's anniversary, leaders are expected to
announce Thursday how the nominee will be chosen, and perhaps drop
such longstanding restrictions as selecting only candidates who
have previously held elected office. That could open the door to a
flood of new presidential hopefuls, a prospect that worries older
members who fear that further division would bolster the
opposition. But some remain deeply skeptical that the process will
be open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they know how to elect a candidate,'' said
Sergio Aguayo Quezada, a political columnist and professor at the
Colegio de Mexico. ``It could cause a bigger rift within the
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the days of one-party rule will inevitably give way to
power-sharing among different groups, said a former Mexico City
administrator who is now a researcher at Harvard University's David
Rockefeller Center for Latin American Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is such a complicated society that you have to govern
by consensus,'' said Juan Enriquez. ``The future will have to
include coalitions. You can't have your own plan anymore and say,
`Everyone will agree with me.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1941EST &QL; 
