<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LEADERS-BOS &LR;      03-03 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LEADERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE IN KOSOVO REBEL LEADERSHIP RAISES PEACE HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When Adem Demaci, the unbending elder statesman of
ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo, stepped aside on Tuesday, he was
replaced by Hashim Thaci, a man half his age but seemingly more
open to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The shift marks a sudden generational and ideological sea change
in the murky separatist politics of Kosovo, where 90 percent of the
people in the Serbian province are ethnic Albanians. It also means,
according to western diplomats, that after months of stalemate in
Kosovo, there is hope for progress.
</P>
<P>
   Demaci spent 28 years in a Serbian jail as a political prisoner
and personifies the unyielding resistance to Serb rule that has
challenged the bigger, better-armed forces of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. Demaci resigned as political leader of the
Kosovo Liberation Army rather than preside over what he considers a
sellout of Kosovo's independence.
</P>
<P>
   For all Demaci's revolutionary rhetoric, however, it was the
29-year-old Thaci and his cadre of like-minded former student
activists who actually carried the fight to the Serbs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both men seem to belie the stereotypes of youthful
revolutionaries who embrace violent struggle and then, in the
winter of their years, become statesmen who lead the rebels to the
negotiating table. In this case, it was the young man putting out
conciliatory signals while the old man continued to rattle sabres
that others were carrying.
</P>
<P>
   After learning of the change in leadership, Christopher Hill,
the US envoy in Kosovo, said he was more optimistic than ever that
the Albanians will sign the settlement they had agreed to in
principle before leaving peace talks near Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
   Knut Vollebaek, the Norwegian foreign minister and chairman of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which has
1,300 observers in Kosovo, is similarly encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   The ascension of Thaci to the most senior political position in
the Kosovo Liberation Army leads many US diplomats to believe that
the ethnic Albanians will keep their promise to return to France on
March 15 and sign an agreement that would restore autonomy to
Kosovo but keep it within Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   To Demaci, a Marxist, fighting for independence is a
non-negotiable principle. Thaci is a college-educated idealist who
took up arms after coming of age just as Kosovar Albanians were
stripped of their autonomy in 1989 and relegated to second-class
citizenship, but he is described as a pragmatist.
</P>
<P>
   Dukagjin Gorani, an ethnic Albanian journalist who is close to
the KLA leadership, said Thaci emerged as the key figure in the
16-member Albanian delegation at the peace talks. Gorani credits
Thaci with helping unify a disparate delegation that included those
like him, who believe the Serbs will only listen to force, and
Ibrahim Rugova, a 53-year-old Sorbonne-educated professor and
pacifist who leads ethnic Albanian moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Like other KLA commanders, Thaci has a nom de guerre,
``Commander Snake.'' Along with his friend, Suleiman ``Commander
Sultan'' Selimi, the KLA's overall commander, he helped mold a
ragtag collection of rebels into a formidable insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials say the a key difference between him and Demaci
is that Thaci is said to recognize his forces' limits in fighting
the militarily superior Serbs. As one western diplomat complained,
Demaci was too ``willing to fight to the last drop of everyone
else's blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Thaci is seen as someone who tasted battle and found it bitter.
If some KLA leaders see the suffering of ethnic Albanian civilians
as the price that must be paid for independence, Thaci is said to
have been chastened by the Serb offensive that has cost some 2,000
civilian lives and produced 300,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as one US official put it, describing Thaci as a dove
would be wrong, as would be suggesting that Thaci has dissension
among his compatriots under control.
</P>
<P>
   It was Thaci who said he could not sign the agreement without
first consulting with others in Kosovo. But as Hill and other
diplomats point out, Thaci took that line after he had briefly left
the talks to confer with Demaci, who refused to take part and calls
it treachery to consider a deal that does not guarantee a
referendum on independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of sounding out other KLA leaders, Thaci and the
rest of the leadership are making more conciliatory sounds.
Demaci's sudden resignation convinced many western diplomats that,
unless something unforseen occurs, _ always a possibility _ the
rebels will back the compromise settlement.
</P>
<P>
   That would put pressure on Milosevic to accept the 30,000 NATO
troops that the western allies say are needed to police a
settlement. If Milosevic refuses, he faces possible NATO air
strikes, which weren't going to happen if the ethnic Albanians also
turned down the deal.
</P>
<P>
   A major sticking point remains disarming the KLA. But sources
say Thaci and others are arguing that the ethnic Albanians have
nothing to lose by trying to box in Milosevic with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to ensure the Albanians will sign, US officials
hope to bring them to Washington before March 15. The White House
will not treat Thaci like a terrorist, as the Serbs do, but as a
fledgling democrat, someone who could get the ethnic Albanians to
put aside their weapons _ and in the process deliver a foreign
policy coup to the Clinton administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
