<HEADLINE>
RJ REYNOLDS' `NO BULL' CIGARETTE ADVERTISING CAMPAIGN TO GET A
DISCLAIMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1997, RJ Reynolds Tobacco Co. settled on ``No
bull'' as an advertising slogan for its Winston cigarettes, which
it said were 100 percent tobacco with no additives.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission, however, detected at least a
little confusion among consumers and announced Wednesday that the
company, a unit of RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp., would start
including disclaimers with its Winston advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The disclaimers, an RJR spokeswoman said, will read, ``No
additives in our tobacco does not mean a safer cigarette.''
Questions about how consumers interpreted the company's advertising
arose after complaints from anti-smoking groups in 1997. The
commission conducted its own research and determined that people
could be confused by the advertising, said Jodie Bernstein,
director of the agency's Bureau of Consumer Protection.
</P>
<P>
   The RJR spokeswoman, Carole Crosslin, said in a statement that
the company had never tried to imply that Winston cigarettes
carried lower risks of smoking-related health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with the FTC's premise, and our own research
demonstrated that smokers do not interpret the phrases to mean that
Winston is safe or safer than other cigarettes,'' she said. ``RJR
has publicly and consistently stated that we do not believe the
risks associated with smoking are reduced due to the lack of
additives, and we have never communicated otherwise to smokers.''
Additives used in cigarettes include flavorings like licorice,
menthol and sugar, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The order will go into effect in May after a comment period, Ms.
Bernstein said. Print ads for Winston that are still running will
have to include the disclaimer, although individual packages of
cigarettes will not, Ms. Crosslin said.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes at a time when sales of Winston cigarettes have
risen slightly after the repositioning of the brand 18 months ago.
Winston's market share is 4.93 percent, Ms. Crosslin said, up from
4.86 percent when the ``No bull'' campaign began. Sales of
cigarettes overall have been falling steadily, both as a result of
price increases imposed by the companies and from anti-smoking
efforts at the state and federal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This indicates that the federal government is becoming more
concerned about the safety perceptions of tobacco consumption by
the American public,'' said Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst for
Salomon Smith Barney. ``The FTC is looking to make sure consumers
don't mistake the word `natural' for `healthy.''' Across the board,
consumer-products companies use words like ``low-fat'' and
``natural,'' he said, to get an extra promotional lift.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
