</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMATE-BILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BILL WOULD REWARD COMPANIES THAT CURTAIL EMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid a new report that the 1990s have been the hottest decade in
1,000 years, Congress appears to be warming toward legislation
aimed at reducing emissions of chemicals that many scientists say
are causing the Earth's temperature to rise.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators, including conservatives who
often oppose environmental initiatives, plans to unveil a bill
Thursday that would reward companies for taking steps to reduce
carbon dioxide emissions now, rather than waiting for an
international treaty on global warming to take effect in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which would give businesses potentially valuable
credits in exchange for cutting pollution, still faces tough
challenges, including a skeptical House of Representatives and some
environmentalists who fear that the proposal would result in the
increased us of nuclear power because it causes no carbon dioxide
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   But several observers say the bill, written by Senator John H.
Chafee, a Rhode Island Republican, and cosponsored by nine others,
could bestir a Congress that has been largely hostile to efforts to
slow the two-century increase in the Earth's carbon dioxide levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing bipartisan momentum develop for an idea that
makes sense for the environment and makes sense for industry as
well,'' said Fred Krupp, executive director of the Environmental
Defense Fund of New York, one of the nation's biggest environmental
groups. ``This stands a good chance of passing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, chairman of the Senate Environment and Public Works
Committee, said he hopes the bill encourages companies to be
creative in trying to reverse the United State's steadily rising
emissions of carbon dioxide and other heat-trapping gases, rather
than waiting for an international treaty called the Kyoto Protocol
to order them to take action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we just sit around and wait another nine years before we do
anything?'' Chafee asked. ``Whether you are for or against the
Kyoto Protocol, the US should do things now to facilitate immediate
environmental gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new study suggests that the 1990s have been the
warmest decade at least since the Norman Conquest of England in
1066. What's more, the researchers say that 1998 was the hottest
year of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Using a combination of ancient tree rings and ice drilled from
glaciers, Raymond Bradley and Michael Mann of the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, along with a University of Arizona
scientist, found that the planet is even warmer than during the
so-called Medievel Warm Period when Europeans complained about the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can't quite pin things down as well'' further back in
time, admitted Mann, ``but our results do reveal that . . .
temperatures in the latter 20th century have been exceptionally
warm compared to the preceding 900 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Their paper in the journal Geophysical Research Letters, joins a
growing body of research showing that the 1990s have been
record-hot, capped by 1998, when the long Texas drought and Florida
wildfires made headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But climate change remains one of the most contentious issues in
environmental politics, in part because it is so complex. Skeptical
scientists, such as Thomas Gale Moore of Stanford University, doubt
the temperature has risen abnormally, and they are even more
skeptical that human actions such as burning coal and oil have
caused it.
</P>
<P>
   The climate debate has sharply divided President Clinton from
the Republican-controlled Congress. In 1997, Clinton endorsed the
Kyoto Protocol, which commits the United States to reduce
heat-trapping gases beginning in 2008, but Senate leaders have
vowed not to ratify the deal, arguing it would hurt the economy.
</P>
<P>
   While the two sides wrangled, Chafee, along with Senators Joe
Lieberman of Connecticut and Connie Mack of Florida, drafted a bill
late last year to encourage American companies to act now. The fact
that Mack, who received a zero rating from the environmental League
of Conservation Voters, immediately drew attention to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Their bill would allow companies to cut emissions now _ for
instance, by converting from coal to natural gas power _ and claim
credit for the savings under whatever rules the United States later
adopts to fight global warming. Those credits, measured in tons of
avoided emissions, could be subtracted from the company's total
emissions to meet the rules, or sold to other firms that need them.
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists fear that the bill may be too loose,
giving companies credit for anything that reduces carbon dioxide
even if it causes new problems. Replacing a coal-burning plant with
a nuclear plant would reduce carbon dioxide emissions, they note,
but would increase nuclear waste. The bill would also give credit
for shutting down factories, they add.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for a Congress that only last year was considering a
measure to prevent federal officials from talking about global
warming, other environmentalists see Chafee's initiative as
progress. And, with five Democratic and five Republican cosponsors,
including James Jeffords of Vermont and Susan Collins of Maine,
they say it has a political future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
