<HEADLINE>
10 TEXAS MOBSTERS CONVICTED OR RACKETEERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARO ROBBINS and BILL HENDRICKS  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In a sweeping government victory, the San Antonio
head of the Mexican mafia and nine of his soldiers were convicted
Wednesday of racketeering charges.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 are likely facing life behind bars, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Mafia leader Robert ``Beaver'' Perez stood statuelike as U.S.
District Judge Edward C. Prado read his verdicts: guilty of
racketeering, guilty of conspiring to racketeer.
</P>
<P>
   A chorus of 18 more guilty verdicts followed, two for each
defendant. A hand-clap from somewhere in the courtroom punctuated
the verdict for Jesse ``Chango'' Gomez, the defendant accused of
being the main triggerman in the notorious 1997 shotgun slayings of
five people in a San Antonio home.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of soft weeping gradually emerged from corners in the
courtroom. But the defendants' expressions remained blank except
for a wink and grin from mafia lieutenant Louis ``Big Lou''
Morales, who was described during the trial as having laughed about
strangling a former gang member.
</P>
<P>
   Most, if not all, gang members likely face mandatory life
imprisonment once sentencing dates are set, defense lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   The racketeering law carries a maximum penalty of roughly 25
years, but because the gang is accused of killing 15 people,
several defense attorneys have said that barring appeals, their
clients would likely die in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Bill Baumann, the lead prosecutor in a
six-week trial that included some seven-day work-weeks and
sleepless nights, lowered his head into his hands as verdict after
verdict turned into a government victory.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the heavily guarded courtroom Wednesday, Baumann said
the case dismantled the prison-bred gang's local leadership. As new
leaders emerge, he said, law enforcement officers will remain
vigilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to eliminate them, but we're going to restrain
them,'' Baumann said. ``We need to keep a foot on the throat or
they'll be killing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 40, faces murder charges in state court. He is accused of
ordering six slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Several defense lawyers indicated they would appeal the federal
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Ed Camara said his client, 24-year-old Michael Perez, was
convicted simply because his uncle is Robert Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got steamrolled with the other defendants,'' Camara
said, adding, ``It wasn't justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts brought the total number of racketeering
convictions on this case to 16. Six pleaded guilty before the trial
began, accepting plea bargains that are likely to put them behind
bars for between 12 to 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the trial, prosecutors relied on the testimony
of former mafia members, a few of whom went to the government when
they feared they would be killed by other mob members.
</P>
<P>
   The massive trial, with more than 150 witnesses and almost 20
crates of evidence, pulled back the covers on San Antonio's
criminal culture.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony attracted, among others, a tattooed minister who
came, he said, offering his faith to anyone who would receive it.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal judges also left their benches to join
observers in the wooden pews in Prado's courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
