<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-HOSPITAL-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST THREE OF TEXAS OCTUPLETS `ARE NOW HOME' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After more than two months in the hospital, the first
three of the seven surviving Chukwu octuplets went home Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ebuka, the firstborn, Echrem, the third child born, and Jioke,
the seventh child to be delivered, left Texas Children's Hospital
about 10 a.m. CST and were driven to their house in southwest
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a full-time job now,'' joked Nkem Chukwu, the mother of
the children, at a Wednesday afternoon news conference at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They opened their eyes when they got there signifying, `We are
now home','' said their father, Iyke Louis Udobi.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors expected the first children to leave the hospital in
late March or early April, but they progressed better than expected
and were released ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of their release, Jioke weighed 5 pounds, 5 ounces,
Echerem weighed 4 pounds, 7 ounces, and Ebuka was 4 pounds, 8
ounces.
</P>
<P>
   There were several medical milestones the children had to meet
before being released from the hospital, said their pediatrician,
Dr. Patti Savrik.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were maintaining their temperatures in open cribs,''
Savrik said. ``They were taking all their nutrition through a
bottle or by breast feeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that figured into their time of release included
the ability to breathe without the help of any respiratory
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are ready to go. They're good babies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Savrik said another baby might be going home in 10 days to two
weeks and that the other three may remain in the hospital for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard right now to predict exactly how these babies are
going to come along because we are dealing with different issues
with different babies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The baby who will probably be going home next is Chima, a girl,
who is in serious condition in the Level II nursery, while the
others, Chidi, Gorom and Ikem, remain in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Ikem, who is the smaller of the boys, had some abdominal surgery
to repair an intestinal perforation Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same type of surgery that was done on Gorom in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the seven children appeared relaxed and happy to
have their first three children home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was elated. We were dancing,'' said Udobi.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the babies, Nkem Chukwu, said there was quite a
celebration when the infants were brought into the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all dancing and rejoicing. My mother was kind of
screaming and praising the lord,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The home was decorated with a ``Welcome'' sign and balloons, and
relatives, neighbors and the family minister were on hand to greet
them, Udobi said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said they still are working out the details of how
they are going to care for the three babies and then eventually all
seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the dust settles down we will be able to tell. Right now
we have my mother-in-law there and some church members and
neighbors also,'' said the father.
</P>
<P>
   Savrik said her experience with multiple birth families has
shown that it takes several days with the children at home before
parents have a good idea of how much help they will need.
</P>
<P>
   Udobi thanked people who had donated services and money to the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll need a bigger van for sure and a bigger house. Where we
live now is not big enough to accommodate and give them freedom,''
he said of the couple's four-bedroom home.
</P>
<P>
   Udobi, a respiratory therapist, said the couple have still not
taken any photographs of the children and that they do not plan to
show them to the public until ``due time.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said they have not agreed to any commercial offers or
endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preoccupation is for the health of these kids and their
coming home. Three are home now and we are expecting four more.
When we get to that bridge we will cross it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, who was treated with fertility drugs, delivered Ebuka
naturally Dec. 8 and the others by Caesarean section Dec. 20. The
smallest baby died a week later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
