<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELAXED NORMAN READY FOR FRIENDLY DORAL COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Greg Norman may have missed the cut in the tournament
that bears his name in his Australian homeland a little over a
month ago, but he arrived in South Florida fit and ready to go for
the $3 million Doral-Ryder Open, which begins Thursday on a course
where he has won three times.
</P>
<P>
   This is a time of transition for Norman, and the PGA Tour as
well. Norman spent eight months recuperating from shoulder surgery
following the Masters a year ago, and at 44 realizes time isn't his
best friend in terms of his future. ``I have zero pressure,'' he
said Wednesday. ``To me I can stop now and everything I have done
in the game of golf has been for the good of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's perhaps no more than coincidence that Norman returned for
last week's World Match Play Championships in San Diego, the
inaugural event of the World Golf Championships, organized chiefly
by PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem. Norman advanced to the second
round of the event, which featured an unprecedented purse of $5
million. Other events of the World Golf Championships are the NEC
Invitational (Aug. 26-29) in Akron, Ohio, and the American Express
Championship (Nov. 4-7) in Valderrama on the southern coast of
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The World Championship concept originally was proposed by
Norman, and Finchem shot it down. Now many of the game's top
players are reshaping their schedules around the new events, and a
fourth will be added next year in South Africa. The game's four
major championships still are the signature events, but a
tournament like Doral is hurt this year because six of the top
seven players in the world including, Tiger Woods and David Duval,
are skipping it to rest up.
</P>
<P>
   Even Norman endorsed the match play event at La Costa in
Carlsbad, Calif., that saw Jeff Maggert defeat Andrew Magee in the
championship match that went 38 holes. ``I think from the players'
perspective, we all enjoyed the format,'' said Norman. ``We knew
the format would be a success, because the players like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The television ratings were high, and it goes to show, you
don't need the name players in a final to stir up the interest of
the public and the television viewers. I think that was just a good
reflection on the overall quality of the golf tournament. I
definitely would keep the tournament on my schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The will to excel again still burns within, but Norman said he
realized time wasn't on his side in a career that has been more
memorable for lost opportunities than his only two major wins in
the British Open. ``I have to rehab every day,'' he said. ``The
surgery was a complete success, but the surgery is the easiest
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part starts when you have to start your rehab and
continue going basically for the rest of your life as long as you
want to play the game. I have always got to have somebody there as
long as I am playing. It's a good two hours a day in the morning
and evening. That isn't including working out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I made the decision, I knew it was going to help my
career. I knew I wanted to play. Before I had the surgery, I had no
desire to go out and hit golf balls because I was in so much pain.
If it was a cool, wet day, I wouldn't even go out there. It all
gave me an unfiltered approach toward my game and my life because I
had more time to sit back and become reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play again. I love being out there. I think that is
what I missed the most. I didn't miss the game, but I missed being
out there on the golf course playing at the competitive level. I
don't want to be out here if I don't think I can compete. I don't
want to take up the space when somebody who is 20 or 21 could be
out here playing. It's in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman pointed to his heart, aware that his left shoulder is
strong and the game he played growing up on the Queensland coast
still has a fascination and an appeal. ``Frustration may never set
in,'' he said. ``It's difficult to say. I know my doctor only wants
me to play no more than two tournaments a month.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are reports that Tiger Woods and his caddie, Mike
``Fluff'' Cowan, may be parting company. Woods has already
dismissed his Maine agent, Hughes Norton. Cowan, also of Maine,
didn't tote the bag when Woods won the Buick Invitational in San
Diego or during the match play event. Cowan was replaced by Bryon
Bell, a longtime friend of Woods. Woods said Bell needed some money
to defray medical school expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Rita, a native of Glastonbury, Conn., may be next in line.
Rita caddied for Curtis Strange when Strange won the US Open in
1988 at The Country Club and in 1989 at Oak Hill and has been
working for Scott Hoch recently. ``We're week to week,'' said Hoch
of his arrangement with Rita.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? I wouldn't stand in his way if he had a chance to
go with Tiger,'' said Cowan, who worked for Peter Jacobsen for the
better part of 18 years before getting a call from Woods. Cowan
worked as an assistant professional at Martindale CC in Auburn,
Maine, and was raised in Fairfield, Maine. ``Who caddies for Woods
two weeks up the road at Bay Hill in Orlando should supply the
answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
