<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TJX-EARNS-BOS &LR;      03-03 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TJX-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TJX COS. FOURTH TOPS PREDICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A strong year for the TJX Cos. is about as commonplace as Roger
Clemens winning another Cy Young Award or the New York Yankees
winning another World Series.
</P>
<P>
   So at a time when many retailers are doing well, it was hardly a
surprise when the Framingham, Mass. operator of such offprice
chains as T.J. Maxx and Marshalls announced Wednesday that it
enjoyed record sales and earnings for the fiscal year that ended
Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth-quarter, profits jumped a better-than-expected 29
percent to $126.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``1998 was a banner year for the TJX Cos.,'' said Bernard
Cammarata, TJX's president and chief executive, who added, ``We
outpaced our objectives in every quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The results pushed TJX shares to a 52-week high of 32 11/16 on
the New York Stock Exchange. The stock then dipped a bit to close
at 31 15/16, up 1 1/16 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, fourth-quarter sales seemed disappointing,
rising less than 2 percent to $2.28 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But last year's fourth quarter contained an extra week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made TJX's performance this quarter all the more
impressive,'' said Sally H. Wallick, an analyst with Legg Mason
Wood Walker.
</P>
<P>
   When year-to-year comparisons were made on a 13-week basis,
rather than on the basis of a 14-week quarter versus a 13-week
quarter, sales were up 9 percent, and sales at stores open for at
least a year were up 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the full fiscal year, sales were $7.9 billion, up 9 percent
from the comparable 52-week period. Net income was $424.2 million,
compared with $304.8 million in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining some of TJX's success, Cammarata said: ``We did an
excellent job of managing inventories. We remained very fluid in
our inventory position, which enabled us to offer a constant flow
of fresh and exciting merchandise throughout the year.''
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 1,100 stores, T.J. Maxx and Marshalls provide TJX
with the bulk of its revenues and profits. Keeping the identities
of the two chains separate and distinctive in the minds of
consumers is crucial for success, Cammarata said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the strategy has been so successful that the
opportunity for expanding the two chains in the United States may
be greater than previously thought, TJX told analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chains in Canada and the United Kingdom, Winners
Apparel Ltd. and T.K. Maxx, also turned in strong performances, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   HomeGoods, which specializes in home furnishings, also ``made
significant strides'' last year, TJX said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, TJX debuted a new concept called A.J. Wright, a chain
aimed at more moderate-income customers than those who shop T.J.
Maxx or Marshalls.
</P>
<P>
   The company opened six A.J. Wright stores last year and expects
to ``more than double its store base in 1999,'' TJX said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
