with Democrats on Capitol Hill to emphasize their post-impeachment
agenda. The Republicans will counter with an anti-tax rally as both
parties adopt a campaign footing. By Alison Mitchell. (Scheduled to
move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., America's
last big private investment bank _ barring a repeat of the stock
market slump that undid its carefully laid plans last fall _ will
go public by early summer. The partners who own the firm will not
vote formally on the share offering until this weekend, but little
opposition is expected. By Joseph Kahn. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SPRINGFIELD (Undated) _ Dusty Springfield, the smoky-voiced
English torch singer whose interpretations of pop ballads were
suffused with a heartbroken wistfulness, died on Tuesday at her
home in Henley-on-Thames, near Oxford, west of London. She was 59.
The cause was breast cancer. By Stephen Holden. (The obit has moved
in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
