<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-USOC-REACT04-COX     03-03 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-REACT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USOC vows change in answer to report
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to move beyond the gift scandal enveloping
the international Olympic movement, U.S. Olympic officials pledged
Wednesday to strengthen internal controls and ``return the Games
and the attention to the athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to find the flaws, correct the mistakes and to
create a system that will ensure that these mistakes do not occur
again,'' said Bill Hybl, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Hybl and other officials delivered their formal response to a
report issued Monday that criticized the USOC for giving virtually
no oversight to the bidding practices of Salt Lake City, host of
the 2002 Winter Games, and other American cities that sought to
become Olympic hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized the International Olympic Committee
for creating a culture in which lavish gift-giving to IOC members
flourished with little accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to one recommendation in the report, U.S. Olympic
officials said they would lobby the IOC and President Clinton to
have the IOC named a ``public international organization,'' making
the IOC subject to federal bribery statutes. USOC officials
conceded, however, that such a determination from Clinton would
mean little unless other countries adopted similar measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't guarantee what other countries will do,'' USOC
executive director Dick Schultz said. ``All we can try to do is
provide a model that we hope other countries will take a look at.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC is a private entity currently beyond the jurisdiction of
bribery statutes as defined by the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act,
which prohibits U.S. business people from giving foreign government
officials anything of value to influence them.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said the president has not made
a decision on the USOC's recommendation. Clinton could make the
change by executive order.
</P>
<P>
   In a closed meeting Tuesday, the USOC agreed to draft the letter
to Clinton and adopt a series of other proposals dealing with
host-city bidding practices. Officials said they also support
recommendations in Monday's report on changes within the IOC, such
as limiting terms for members and altering the election process.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they are anxious to learn what reforms, if any,
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch and other officials will
propose at IOC meetings in two weeks in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are encouraged by what President Samaranch has said ...
that they are taking a very careful look at their structure and
their accountability,'' Hybl said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hybl declined to call for Samaranch's resignation. ``It
seems to me that the system really needs to change,'' he said,
``because, if the system doesn't change, the individuals involved
won't make a great deal of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials also said they would ban American bid cities from
operating accounts designed to assist athletes or Olympic efforts
in other countries. The tactic was used by Atlanta officials, who
suggested the possibility of a training camp for African nations
during the bid process and successfully pitched the idea to the
city of LaGrange.
</P>
<P>
   The oversight commission's report released Monday found that
Salt Lake City bid officials gave at least $4 million to IOC
members since 1989 for travel, skiing, scholarships and shopping
sprees, much of it funneled through an account set up to provide
financial assistance to athletes. The account had no oversight and
didn't follow established procedures for awarding the money.
</P>
<P>
   The report also concluded that the USOC dispensed at least
$40,000 to Sudanese athletes at the request of Salt Lake officials
through the USOC's own international assistance program. Several
USOC e-mail messages referred to the payments as ``a payback for
(Salt Lake City) votes.''
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials said they will not discontinue their own
international assistance program, but they pledged to do a better
job of overseeing disbursement of funds.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the USOC official who oversaw the international
assistance, Alfredo LeMont, resigned. Two other high-ranking USOC
officials involved in the assistance fund _ Tom Wilkinson, USOC's
assistant executive director, and Jim Page, USOC's deputy executive
director for programs _ will not be disciplined, even though they
authored messages that discussed the use of USOC's
international-assistance fund in relation to IOC votes for Salt
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at that very, very carefully,'' Schultz said, ``and,
while the e-mail conversations were inappropriate, neither us or
our general counsel found any indication that there was any type of
conspiracy there to get votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Separate from the bid commission's recommendations, the USOC
vowed to increase the representation of athletes and minorities on
its boards and in its executive positions, and to hold open
meetings and publish minutes of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   USOC staff no longer will be allowed to visit bid cities at the
expense of those cities, and any payments or gifts to USOC staff
must be turned over to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   To highlight the USOC's renewed commitment to athletes, Olympic
swimming gold medalist John Naber and track gold medalist Jackie
Joyner-Kersee were invited to join Wednesday's news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee said she is worried about the scandal's impact on
corporate sponsors, who provide much of the financial assistance to
athletes in training. Naber said the scandal had diverted media
attention from the stories about young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that after the dust settles, (we) will once again turn
our attention to where it belongs,'' Naber said. ``It belongs on
the hopes and dreams of the young athletes trying to represent our
country well in the greatest sporting competition in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   USOC POLICY CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibit U.S. bid cities and organizing committees from
establishing assistance funds for other countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strictly apply its criteria for providing grants from its
International Assistance Fund.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish an Office of Compliance to oversee U.S. bid cities
and conflict-of-interest issues.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strengthen its bid and candidate cities' contracts and bid
procedures manual, while putting a full-time staffer in candidate
cities during their bid.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attempt to get the IOC designated as a ``public international
organization'' to make it subject to the Foreign Corrupt Practices
Act.
</P>
<P>
   _ Open board of directors and executive committee meetings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seek increased athlete participation and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
