u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-NYT &LR;      03-03 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA ANNOUNCES JUNE DATE FOR SOUTH AFRICAN ELECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ After months of wrangling over how
to conduct the second post-apartheid elections in South Africa,
President Nelson Mandela announced Wednesday that the voting would
be on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela had earlier said he wanted the general elections held
around May 17 to May 28. But Wednesday he said that after
consulting with election officials, he decided to give the
elections commission an extra week to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   To widespread laughter, Mandela, who made his announcement in
Parliament, paused on the verge of saying the date, teasing the
legislators who had been awaiting his decision. He took off his
glasses. He drank a glass of water. Finally he said June 2. The
legislators applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials say they hope that the announcement of the
date will prompt many citizens to register to vote this weekend in
the election commission's third and final registration drive.
</P>
<P>
   So far, South Africans appear to far less interested in voting
than they were in 1994, when nonwhites were allowed to vote for the
first time. That year more than 85 percent of the eligible voters
cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Now fewer than 60 percent have registered. Part of the problem
may be that they do not have the documentation to register. The
government and opposition parties have been locked in a battle over
a decision to allow only citizens with a new ``bar coded''
identification document to register.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said up to five million of the 25 million voters
did not have such documents. Some are blacks in rural areas who
have never had any documents. But many of those who have not yet
received the bar-coded documents are whites who have failed to
update their papers.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks moved far more quickly to obtain documents, because the
apartheid-era documents were so demeaning to them.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties have accused the government of using the
identification rule to gain an advantage in the election. Officials
called such accusations preposterous, saying they simply want an
accurate roll.
</P>
<P>
   Two largely white-supported parties, the small liberal
Democratic Party and the party that instituted apartheid, now
called the New National Party, took the government to court to
relax the registration rules. Last week, the New National Party
suit lost in a lower court. The judge ruled that there had been
plenty of time for citizens to obtain the new papers. The decision
is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party announced Wednesday that it would postpone
its suit until after the registration drive had ended to see how
many citizens had registered.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are not the only protest against the handling of the
elections. Last month, the head of the elections commission, Judge
Johann Kriegler, quit in protest over what he called government
interference in the panel's independence. One sore point was a lack
of financing that he said had reduced the commission staff to
supplicants. The agency has since been given an increase in
appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution does not actually allow Mandela to fix the date
of the elections officially until April 30, when Parliament
adjourns. But a constitutional amendment to remedy this problem is
widely expected to pass on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the vote, the party that wins the Parliamentary majority
chooses the president. The winner is widely expected to be the
African National Congress, and the next president Thabo Mbeki,
Mandela's deputy president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 1953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-USOC-REACT04-COX     03-03 1123
