<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6712 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAND-IN-BERLIN-THEATE     03-03 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAND-IN-BERLIN-THEATER-ART-$ADV07-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRED IN BROOKLYN FOR A BROADWAY RUN  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7)
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
Anne Midgette writes frequently on international art, music and
theater. 
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Broadway is new territory for Susan Feldman. Not that
she works far away: she is the director of the well-known Arts at
St. Ann's program in Brooklyn Heights. Nor is she a stranger to
music theater.
</P>
<P>
   She has co-commissioned and produced a range of work since 1980,
including ``Songs for 'Drella,'' Lou Reed and John Cale's piece
about Andy Warhol.
</P>
<P>
   But Arts at St. Ann's, at the Church of St. Ann and the Holy
Trinity, is more commonly associated with the Brooklyn Academy of
Music than with Broadway, and Ms. Feldman is thought of more as a
producer of other people's work than as the creator of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, after a long incubation period, she has conceived,
written and co-directed her first Broadway show. Entitled ``Band in
Berlin,'' it opens Sunday night at the Helen Hayes Theater, the
product of a close collaboration among Ms. Feldman; the bass Wilbur
Pauley, the show's music director, and the Broadway choreographer
Patricia Birch, who is also a co-director. The project took shape
at Arts at St. Ann's and the American Music Theater Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she thought in 1992, when an earlier version of the
work first opened at St. Ann's, that it would be a Broadway show,
Ms. Feldman laughed. ``I'm still not sure it is a Broadway show,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the production team has trouble describing the collage of
film, slides, puppets and live singers that constitutes ``Band in
Berlin.'' The story follows the Comedian Harmonists, a singing
group that attained Beatles-like popularity in Germany before the
Nazis banned it in 1935 because three of its six members were
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the show's narrative is contained in a film, portions of
which are projected on a large screen at the rear of the stage, in
which an actor, Herbert Rubens, portrays the elderly Roman
Cycowski, the last surviving member of the Comedian Harmonists.
Cycowski died in November at the age of 97, and the show is
dedicated to him.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying this pseudo-documentary, as well as photomontages
of Germany under Hitler, a live singing group performs the
Harmonists' intricate original arrangements of folk and popular
songs. These are sung in French, English and German and include
``Stormy Weather,'' ``Tea for Two,'' ``Creole Love Call'' and ``Auf
Wiederseh'n, My Dear.''
</P>
<P>
   The singers are also not the Broadway norm. Hudson Shad, the
vocal ensemble that portrays the Harmonists in the show, is made up
of five opera and oratorio singers and a pianist, Robert Wolinsky,
better known in some circles as the harpsichordist for the Chamber
Orchestra of St. Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   This amalgam may be unusual for Broadway, but it is typical of
the two organizations involved with the show: Arts at St. Ann's and
the American Music Theater Festival in Philadelphia, where ``Band
in Berlin'' reached its final form in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Both the arts program and the music theater festival have
explored different aspects of theatrical and musical collaboration,
from the operatic (``Malcolm X'' and ``Tania'' by Anthony Davis) to
the offbeat (``1,000 Airplanes on the Roof'' by Philip Glass), with
the hope that the works they nurture will have extended lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our projects are developed to go on to other places,''
Ms. Feldman said. But those places are usually the Brooklyn
Academy, New York City Opera or the Old Globe Theater in San Diego
rather than a Broadway house.
</P>
<P>
   Arts at St. Ann's was established in 1980 with an eye to the
past: to draw attention to a venerable landmark, one of the oldest
churches in Brooklyn, and to create a public use for the building.
But the program has proved an eminently forward-looking starting
point for some significant works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different institutions are equipped to take on projects at
different stages of development,'' Ms. Feldman said. ``We're good
for the beginning. BAM, for example, can't do the kind of
development and workshop we do; they're not set up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Academy has therefore undertaken several
co-productions with Arts at St. Ann's: ``Songs for 'Drella,''
``Frida,'' the opera about the Mexican artist Frida Kahlo, which
went on to the Houston Grand Opera, among other places, and the
forthcoming ``Falling and Waving,'' a digital opera by Ronald Jones
and David Lang that opens on March 25 at St. Ann's.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Feldman, the $1.4 million version of ``Band in Berlin''
on Broadway is ``a culmination of everything I've done at St.
Ann's.'' The show got off the ground when Pauley, an opera singer
and longtime St. Ann's artist, put together a male vocal quartet
for a 1990 St. Ann's production of Bertolt Brecht and Kurt Weill's
``Seven Deadly Sins,'' with Marianne Faithfull.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing them perform, a friend of Ms. Feldman's, Jonathan Cott,
a music writer, suggested they sing the music of the Comedian
Harmonists. That was the start of Hudson Shad.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feldman had no idea who the Comedian Harmonists were. Cott
provided her with tapes, took her to the highly regarded
documentary on the group by the German filmmaker Eberhard Fechner,
``The Comedian Harmonists: Six Life Stories,'' and ultimately
brought her to California to interview Cycowski. ``His voice was
amazing,'' Ms. Feldman said, as she described hearing the baritone,
a cantor for more than 40 years, sing the morning temple service at
the age of 91: ``Afterward, I said, `Roman, that was incredible.'
And he said, `Ah, I'm never warmed up in the morning.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Before she met Cycowski, Ms. Feldman said, she had equated
Germany with the Holocaust. ``But I realized,'' she added, ``that
there was a whole world before Hitler still in Roman's mind. I felt
like I was given this legacy, this story to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   If St. Ann's is a place where new ideas are born, the American
Music Theater Festival is where they grow up. Founded in 1984, the
festival presents ``theater that sings,'' a definition that
embraces ``Atlas'' by Meredith Monk and ``Strike Up the Band'' by
George and Ira Gershwin, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The music theater festival _ still headed by one of its
founders, Marjorie Samoff, the producing director _ has an
impressive track record: 32 of its more than 70 productions have
gone on to other cities, and 16 of them have been recorded as
professional cast albums. Two have even made it to Broadway:
``Gospel at Colonus,'' which achieved renown if not a long run, and
``Dangerous Games,'' with music by Astor Piazzolla, which did not
do well with New York critics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the festival has shown it can spot Broadway potential:
the director Julie Taymor and the choreographer Garth Fagan both
worked there, separately, in 1986, long before they collaborated on
``The Lion King'' musical.
</P>
<P>
   Arts at St. Ann's and the American Music Theater Festival are
linked, Ms. Samoff said, by ``a long artistic and personal
friendship.'' The artistic part has included three co-productions,
one of which is ``Band in Berlin.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the show got to Philadelphia, it had had a run in
1994 at the Geva Theater in Rochester, been broadcast on public
radio, and evolved considerably from its original incarnation. It
had also sat fallow for four years as Ms. Feldman and Ms. Birch
tried to figure out what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual cast for ``Band in Berlin'' also proved a liability.
``Those classical singers all book two years in advance,'' Ms.
Birch said. ``Every time we got a nibble from a theater, one of the
guys would be unable to get out of his contract.'' In addition to
Pauley, the singers are Mark Bleeke, Timothy Leigh Evans, Hugo
Munday and Peter Becker.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't only opera that kept the performers busy. Hudson Shad
has become an ensemble in its own right. The group's first visit to
Germany in 1995 proved so popular that it has continued to tour
there and in the United States. On the most recent visit last
month, a sellout crowd at Komische Oper in Berlin gave the group a
five-minute standing ovation. Hudson Shad has released two CDs and
a third is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   When the ensemble did manage to get together for the run of
``Band in Berlin'' at the American Music Theater Festival last
March, the show was a success. But without a permanent theater of
its own, the festival was stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Booking various theaters around the city for individual
productions, the festival was unable to extend a run if a show
proved to be a hit. ``When we had a success, we had no way to
develop it,'' Ms. Samoff said. ``The theater we were in for `Band
in Berlin' was about to be demolished.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the music theater festival is changing both its name and
its site. The new Prince Music Theater, a converted movie theater
in downtown Philadelphia, opens on March 22. With three performance
spaces, including a black box and a theater with 450 seats, the
house will allow Ms. Samoff the freedom to develop work at her own
pace _ in the spirit of the building's namesake, the director
Harold Prince, who is a board member of the American Music Theater
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The first staged work in the new theater will be ``Floyd
Collins.'' The musical by Adam Guettel and Tina Landau, about a
1925 Kentucky cave disaster, was seen at Playwrights Horizons in
New York in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The show first opened in Philadelphia in 1994; an original-cast
recording came out in 1997. Currently at the Old Globe Theater in
San Diego, the show's latest incarnation will go on from its April
run at the Prince Music Theater to the Goodman Theater in Chicago.
The hope is that it will eventually get to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Band in Berlin'' itself was in a race to Broadway with
``Harmony,'' another musical about the Comedian Harmonists that has
an original score by Barry Manilow. ``Harmony'' opened at the La
Jolla Playhouse in California in 1997, but after lukewarm reviews
it was decided to continue working on it.
</P>
<P>
   The show is expected to open on Broadway by 2000. (The German
sextet is also the subject of a Miramax feature film, ``The
Harmonists,'' opening in the United States on Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Harmony,'' ``Band in Berlin'' is not necessarily aiming
at a mainstream audience. And Broadway success is not the ultimate
artistic goal of either Arts at St. Ann's or the Prince Music
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal with any show,'' Ms. Samoff said, ``is to give it the
longest possible life and the widest audience compatible with what
it is: an opera house, or a tiny Off Off Off Off Broadway theater.
I'm just as thrilled and proud that `Frida,' a co-production with
Arts at St. Ann's, went to the Houston opera company, a small
theater in Vermont and to BAM. It was the life `Frida' needed to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the life of ``Band in Berlin'' includes a long Broadway
run remains to be seen. Caught in the middle of a rehearsal week,
Pauley seemed thoughtful. ```Ariadne auf Naxos,''' he said, ``was
easier than this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
