<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRINGTON-OBIT04-COX     03-03 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRINGTON-OBIT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longtime minister at Peachtree Presbyterian dies
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. W. Frank Harrington, longtime pastor of
Atlanta's Peachtree Presbyterian Church, the country's largest
mainline Presbyterian congregation, died Wednesday at Emory
University Hospital of complications from acute respiratory
distress syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, 63, of Atlanta was admitted to Emory University
Hospital on Jan. 16. He died at 10:30 a.m. Wednesday, and his
family was with him.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service will be at 4 p.m. Sunday at Peachtree
Presbyterian Church. Visitation is 4-8 p.m. Friday at H.M.
Patterson &AMP; Son, Spring Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1971 when his Peachtree pastorate began, Harrington
increased the church's membership fivefold and its annual budget
from $306,000 to $9.4 million, according to church records. He
baptized more than 3,000 infants and about 1,000 adults and
performed nearly 1,000 weddings. And, while garnering many titles
and honors, he built a legacy of ministry to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Harrington was one of the giants of the Presbyterian
Church,'' said the Rev. Edwin Albright, executive presbyter of the
Presbytery of Greater Atlanta, made up of 109 churches in most of
metro Atlanta. ``He was known from coast to coast as a great
preacher, great leader and a person of great inspiration. He is a
great loss to the church.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank is obviously one of the great saints of the church,''
said the Rev. Clifton Kirkpatrick, stated clerk of the 2.6-million
member, Louisville-based Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.). ``He has
done remarkable ministry at Peachtree and shared the same good news
throughout the church. He is going to be greatly missed.''
</P>
<P>
   William Franklin Harrington was born May 13, 1935, the son of a
farmer in the Lowcountry of South Carolina. He graduated from
Presbyterian College in Clinton, S.C., and from Columbia
Theological Seminary in Decatur.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was ordained to the ministry in July 1961 and served
as minister of First Presbyterian Church in Hinesville and Fairview
Presbyterian Church in North Augusta, S.C., before taking the
pulpit of Peachtree in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the church rolls grew from about 2,400
members to about 11,882. The growth was largely built on ministries
to single adults and young families.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the church's massive building programs to accommodate
its swelling membership _ including a current $20 million expansion
_ Harrington sometimes joked that neighbors thought of him as ``a
developer in a clerical collar.''
</P>
<P>
   At an interview in 1995 when the church was celebrating its 75th
anniversary, Harrington told writer H.M. Cauley, ``I walk out each
Sunday morning before preaching and think, `Thank God, they came
one more time.' But it's never particularly been my dream to have a
church that was just big. What I did want was a church with a big
heart and a community where people felt cared for and loved. And
when people experience that, they tell others about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was a visible leader in Atlanta's religious
community. A few days before he entered the hospital, he gave the
invocation at the inauguration of Gov. Roy Barnes and Lt. Gov. Mark
Taylor. Harrington, whose church Taylor attends in Atlanta, was
minister to Guy Millner, Barnes' unsuccessful opponent.
</P>
<P>
   In a less pleasant time in the spotlight, Harrington presided
over an Atlanta memorial service for JonBenet Ramsey, the child
beauty queen murdered in her Boulder, Colo., home on Dec. 26, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He told mourners at Peachtree Presbyterian not to focus on why
someone would kill the Atlanta-born Little Miss Colorado, but to
remember ``a bright, happy child whose beauty lighted up her
parents' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was co-chairman, with the Rev. Cameron Alexander of
Antioch North Baptist Church, of Atlanta's most recent Billy Graham
crusade in 1994. Graham visited Harrington's church while he was in
town.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington served as chairman of the boards of Westminster
Schools and Presbyterian College and on the boards of trustees at
Oglethorpe University, Queens College in Charlotte, N.C., and
Columbia Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Oldenburg, president of Columbia Theological Seminary
and moderator of the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.), called
Harrington ``an effective preacher, a caring pastor and an able
administrator.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have cherished his friendship and admired his leadership at
Peachtree Church and throughout our denomination,'' said Oldenburg.
``No one has given more support to Columbia Seminary and its
president than Frank Harrington.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Harrington's leadership, Peachtree Presbyterian Church
established the Peachtree Chair in Evangelism and Church Growth at
Columbia, and provided funds to build the school's Harrington
Center for Continuing Education and Church Growth.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was a candidate for moderator _ the top elected
office of the denomination _ in 1993, but finished a close second
to the Rev. John M. Fife of Tucson, Ariz. He was known throughout
the denomination as ``an ardent advocate for New Church
Development, for evangelism and for church growth,'' Oldenburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Harrington's leadership, Peachtree Presbyterian gave
``hundreds of thousands of dollars'' to the development of new
churches in metro Atlanta and in other smaller, struggling areas
around the country, said Albright. Within just the last 10 years,
Peachtree contributed to the construction of eight new Presbyterian
churches in metro Atlanta, according to Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington also pushed his church to great involvement with
Habitat for Humanity and was on the board of directors of the
nonprofit organization. Peachtree Presbyterian this month is
completing its 79th Habitat house, more than any other church in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Habitat is only one of many ministries supported by the church.
Some 40 percent of its budget goes to agencies such as the Atlanta
Food Bank, Atlanta Day Shelter for Women and Children and North
Atlanta Senior Services.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington was the author of three books, drawing on his studies
and his experience, including successful battles with cancer and
heart problems. His most recent, ``First Comes Faith,'' was
published last year by Westminster John Knox Press.
</P>
<P>
   In the pulpit, he was known for warm, folksy sermons illustrated
with anecdotes from his own life. ``I've never preached a sermon I
didn't need to hear myself,'' he once told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   He was acutely aware of the need to nourish his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father once said to me, `It's a great temptation for
preachers to preach more faith than they have,''' he said in 1997.
``I've never forgotten that. Pastors have to constantly make time
for replenishing the springs of their own inner life.''
</P>
<P>
   He read the Bible daily, ``not as a sermon sourcebook but as the
word of God,'' and prayed regularly for anyone who had requested
that he do so.
</P>
<P>
   He also realized that he was the subject of other people's
petitions to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in one place for a long time and that's a great
blessing,'' he said in 1997. ``You become aware that because of
your own journey among people, you're the beneficiary of many
prayers. I feel very comforted by that knowledge. It's been a great
journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Sara Harrington; two daughters,
Victoria Franch of Atlanta and Susan Potter of Shelburne Falls,
Mass.; and three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
