<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6715 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANANA-DISPUTE-BOS &LR;      03-03 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANANA-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US, EUROPE LOCKED IN BANANA DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Great nations have been known to skirmish over
land, human rights and lesser causes, such as the right to sell
opium. But over bananas?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a dispute over the fruit prompted the Clinton
administration to announce heavy penalties on a range of imported
European products, which could double the price of Parma ham from
Italy, feta cheese from Greece, Louis Vuitton handbags from France
and 12 other items _ or remove them from store shelves altogether.
</P>
<P>
   While only a tiny fraction of US trade with Europe is affected,
analysts warned that the fight could escalate into a broader war
that tests the ability of a young international body _ the
5-year-old World Trade Organization _ to keep the peace in trade
disputes. ``We're on a dangerous road here that both sides seem to
have embarked on casually,'' said Jeffrey Schott, a trade
specialist at the Institute for International Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the United States nor Europe is a big producer of
bananas, and neither has many jobs tied to the banana trade. And
yet for six years, the banana war has been a preoccupation of top
trade officials.
</P>
<P>
   US officials say the European Union favors bananas from its
former colonies in the Caribbean and Africa, such as Martinique,
the Ivory Coast and Jamaica. They say this cuts into imports from
Latin America, where US distributors operate. An arbitration panel
at the World Trade Organization has ruled in favor of the US
several times.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans answer that they have changed their import
policies to comply with WTO rulings. They say the Clinton
administration is merely pushing for even more advantages for
politically connected US companies, such as Chiquita Brands
International Inc. and Dole Food Co., which grow bananas in Latin
America. Carl H. Lindner, the head of Chiquita, is a major donor to
both Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans also put a humanitarian cast on their import
rules, saying that their former colonies are far more dependent on
the banana trade than are the larger nations where Dole and
Chiquita operate. ``Our policy helps these countries subsist,''
said Ella Krucoff, a European Union spokeswoman in Washington.
``Their whole economies are dependent on banana exports.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she said, 75 percent of European Union banana imports
come from Latin America. That means the United States is
complaining about rules favoring a mere 25 percent of the imports.
</P>
<P>
   Trade analysts say that bananas are not at the heart of the
case. The real dispute, they say, is the World Trade Organization
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO was created in 1995 during massive negotiations over new
trade rules among 123 nations. It was given powers to hear trade
disputes and to issue binding rulings. Until then, parties in a
trade case could block an arbitrator's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   More than 140 disputes have been submitted to the WTO, which has
ruled on at least 17 of them. (Many of the other disputes have been
settled or withrawn.) But US officials say the banana dispute is
the first one in which a losing party has refused to abide by the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gotten far beyond bananas,'' said Schott, who
recently wrote a study of the WTO. ``This case calls into question
the credibility of the dispute settlement mechanism of the WTO. If
that mechanism is questioned, you could begin an unraveling of the
politcal commitment to the trading system.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate opportunity for conflict could arise, as the European
Union faces a May deadline for adhering to a WTO ruling that it
open its borders to more US beef, Schott said.
</P>
<P>
   But I.M. (Mac) Destler, a trade scholar with the University of
Maryland, said he believed the tariffs announced Wednesday would
provide the political pressure needed to settle the dispute, rather
than escalate it.
</P>
<P>
   Destler said the WTO has often ruled in favor of the United
States. But it has forced the United States to change its import
rules at least once, after a complaint that American standards
unfairly kept Venezuelan gasoline out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the banana dispute, WTO panels ruled for the United States in
1997 and 1998. On Tuesday, the trade group was due to announce the
dollar amount of penalties the US could levy on Euoropean goods.
Instead, it asked for more time and more information to make its
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the US Trade Representative announced 100 percent
duties on selected European products, though US officials also said
they would adjust the duty according to how the WTO panel
ultimately rules. In the meantime, importers will have to post a
bond when they move products into the United States to cover the
eventual cost of the tariff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measures we are taking today ensure that when the
arbitrators reach their final decision, we will be in the same
position as if they had rendered their final decision Wednesday,''
said Peter Scher, special US trade negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Leon Brittan, the European Union's top negotiator, said the
US action was ``unacceptable and unlawful'' because the WTO had not
sanctioned it. ``Just at the time when we should both be working
toward a settlement, the United States is fanning the flames of
this dispute,'' he said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Because importers must post bonds, prices will rise immediately
on some of the targeted items, especially foods that move quickly
from ship to shelf, said Erik Autor, international trade counsel
for the National Retail Federation. Consumers will not see price
increases for several months on other products, such as linens or
sweaters, because stores restock them slowly, or because they are
currently out of season.
</P>
<P>
   But if the tariffs truly remain in effect, it is even more
likely that Europeans will not ship these products to the United
States at all, Autor said. At twice their current prices, they
could not compete against similar American products.
</P>
<P>
   US trade officials carefully chose which products faced a
tariff. Pointing blame for the dispute at France, they chose a
certain type of plastic handbag produced there. Italy was hit with
tariffs on ham and on cheese, Cashmere sweaters and sweet biscuits
were chosen to hurt the United Kingdom. US officials said they only
chose items that are also made in the United States or in
non-European Union nations, an effort to protect US consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Products from Denmark and Holland were excluded, because US
officials felt those nations had lobbied against the European
banana policy.
</P>
<P>
   The total value of products targeted is $500 million, which US
officials said is roughly equal to what US banana distributors lost
in 1998 because of European import policies.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tiny fraction of the $160 billion in products that the
United States imports annually from European Union nations. But
because the new duties are aimed at particular items, certain
producers will feel pain and presumably bring political pressure on
European leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dramatic if not ironic element to this is that the
industries affected have nothing to do with bananas,'' said
Krucoff, the European Union spokeswoman. ``Innocent parties are
always affected in trade war. It's very sad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
