<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6721 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-SHAKESPEARE-$A     03-03 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-SHAKESPEARE-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING THE HARD SELL TO GRAB THE GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England , Italy, Brazil) (For Release Sunday, March 7) 
(DW) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Six months ago, Steven Spielberg's ``Saving
Private Ryan'' virtually was anointed by Hollywood as the winner of
the Academy Award. How could the 5,500 members of the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences vote against one of the most
acclaimed films of Spielberg's career, a searing and patriotic
drama about World War II soldiers, a movie that unexpectedly turned
into a huge box office hit for its studios, Dreamworks and
Paramount?
</P>
<P>
   Then along came the Weinstein brothers, Harvey and Bob. The
co-chairmen of Miramax, the Disney-owned company, the Weinsteins
have proved more successful than any company or studio in town at
gathering Academy Award nominations. In every awards year since
1992, Miramax has been represented in the best picture category
with such movies as ``Pulp Fiction,'' ``The Crying Game'' and ``The
English Patient,'' which won the prize in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This year Miramax led all distributors with 23 nominations _
including 13 for the comedy ``Shakespeare in Love'' and seven for
``Life is Beautiful'' (a record for a foreign-language film), a
tragicomedy about a clownish man who struggles to shield his son
from the horrors of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the nominations for the 71st annual Academy Awards
were announced on Feb. 9, the Miramax juggernaut was at work,
spinning journalists and spending lavishly on trade paper
advertisements promoting the films, notably ``Shakespeare in
Love.'' The nominations cemented the belief that ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' a charming romantic comedy, directed by John Madden and
starring Gwyneth Paltrow and Joseph Fiennes, had emerged as the
rival to ``Saving Private Ryan'' for the best picture award. The
awards will be given, for the first time ever on a Sunday evening,
on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   The other best picture candidates are ``Elizabeth,'' ``The Thin
Red Line'' and ``Life is Beautiful'' _ and there is every
possibility that one of these three dark horses could slip in
because of the intense rivalry between the two front-runners, who
could split the votes of Academy members.
</P>
<P>
   This rivalry is unusually intense. Miramax has not only hired a
slew of publicists to pitch newspaper and television stories about
``Shakespeare in Love'' and ``Life is Beautiful''; it is also
outspending every other company with splashy ads and promotion for
the two films in Variety and the Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax went so far as to issue a press release saying that
``Miramax Films is proud to announce that The Vatican has named
`Life is Beautiful' number three on its list of films it regards as
suitable for viewing by the faithful.'' (The first two are
``Schindler's List'' and ``The Gospel According to St. Matthew'').
Miramax went on to say that the list is known as ``the Pope's
Oscars.'' The implication was that the Pope is supporting ``Life is
Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' with 11 Oscar
nominations, seems to remain the the one to beat as best picture.
``You have to think of the age of the Academy _ they're older, they
like to vote for important films, not comedies,'' said Marvin
Antonowsky, a veteran former studio marketing executive. `` `Ryan'
is an epic; it's patriotic. How do you walk away from that?''
</P>
<P>
   Some Academy members will walk away from the Spielberg film out
of either resentment or jealousy; the director, who already has won
an Oscar for ``Schindler's List,'' is the most successful in film
history.
</P>
<P>
   As to the other nominations the directing category seems to be
heavily in favor of Spielberg over Roberto Benigni for ``Life is
Beautiful,'' John Madden for ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Terrence
Malick for ``The Thin Red Line'' and Peter Weir for ``The Truman
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The betting on the best actor category is leaning towards Ian
McKellen for his role as the gay Hollywood film director James
Whale in Bill Condon's ``Gods and Monsters.'' The runner-up seems
to be Nick Nolte, for his brutal performance as a man on the edge
in Paul Schrader's ``Affliction.'' The other candidates are Tom
Hanks for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' who has won two Oscars, Edward
Norton for ``American History X'' (a dark horse) and Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   Like political candidates, some of the actors are engaged in
nothing short of a campaign to win votes. Ian McKellen flew into
New York last Monday from Leeds, England, where he's appearing at a
repertory theater. (Not-so-coincidentally, ballots went out last
Tuesday, and the voting deadline is March 16).
</P>
<P>
   McKellen swung into action, with appearances set up by his
handlers on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' ``The Late Show,'' with
David Letterman, Charlie Rose, ``The Daily Show'' on Comedy Central
and several Academy Award specials. Benigni hit the publicity
jackpot, showing up on ``60 Minutes'' last Sunday and ``The Rosie
O'Donnell Show'' as well as being featured on NBC's ``Nightly News
with Tom Brokaw.'' These actors seem to be relishing this rare
moment in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the spectrum is Edward Norton. He issued
a statement expressing delight with his nomination on the day it
was announced but has since refused to appear on television shows
or speak to journalists. As to best actress, the two chief
contenders are the Australian actress Cate Blanchett for
``Elizabeth'' and the Brazilian actress Fernanda Montenegro for
``Central Station.'' (Ms. Montenegro was flown from Brazil for a
Hollywood blitz of her own just before the Oscar ballots went out.)
The others nominated are Gwyneth Paltrow (``Shakespeare in Love''),
Meryl Streep (``One True Thing'') and the British actress Emily
Watson (``Hilary and Jackie'').
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Dreamworks and other rivals to the Miramax Oscar
machine are dismayed and angry at what they view as a campaign to
oversell ``Shakespeare in Love'' and to raise doubts about ``Saving
Private Ryan'' _ something Miramax denies. (The negative campaign
on ``Ryan'' asserts that after its brutal opening sequence, the
bloodbath at Omaha Beach, the movie turns into a more conventional
World War II drama).
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Weinstein, the co-chairman of Miramax, said the five
nominated films were the best he had seen in years. As to the
Miramax efforts on behalf of ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Weinstein
said: ``It's the same kind of Academy campaign we've always run. I
don't know how to do it differently. There's not that much to do,
to be honest.'' He said ads are purchased and efforts are made to
insure that Academy voters see the movie at least once, maybe
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein pointed out that in the last 14 out of 15 years, the
best picture award has gone to the film with the most nominations _
and ``Shakespeare in Love' has 13 nominations, two more than the
Spielberg epic.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing with `Shakespeare' is that people in the industry
feel it's about them, it's a movie that celebrates writers, actors
and financiers, it's a movie that celebrates what we all do,''
added Weinstein. ``It really resonates.''
</P>
<P>
   But what resonates at Dreamworks is the sense that Miramax is in
overdrive with its plethora of publicists and a seemingly open
checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
