<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6722 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HILLARY-BOS &LR;      03-03 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY TALKS _ BUT AVOIDS HINT ABOUT SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is the Democratic pipe dream _ Hillary Rodham Clinton
for Senate _ going up in smoke, just as the fantasy candidate
herself is getting serious?
</P>
<P>
   The first lady delivered an eagerly awaited address here
Wednesday that _ while stopping well short of declaring a run _
amounted to a preview of a campaign stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, just hours earlier, a statewide survey, released by the
Marist Institute for Public Opinion, showed Mrs. Clinton in a
statistical dead-heat with her most likely Republican opponent, New
York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago, the Marist poll showed Mrs. Clinton leading
Giuliani, 49-38. Wednesday, however, her edge had been cut to 49-45
_ within the poll's 4 percent margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Miringoff, the institute's director, said in a phone
interview that many voters who were uncertain two weeks ago _
especially among those who live upstate _ have since moved into
Giuliani's column.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial balloon came back to earth a little bit,'' Miringoff
said. ``She needs to make a transition between celebrity Clinton
and candidate Clinton,'' meaning she will have to start showing up
here a lot more, speaking out on New York issues from a New York
angle. ``No fly-by campaigns here,'' the pollster said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's 35-minute speech at the Plaza Hotel _ before a
sold-out, $150-a-head luncheon of the Democratic National
Committee's Women's Leadership Conference _ could mark the
beginning of that transition.
</P>
<P>
   She started it with a tease. ``I'm told there are some who
thought I might have an announcement to make,'' she said to
laughter. She paused, then said quietly, ``But I don't.'' Many
moaned. ``But,'' she added, ``I do have a lot on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady made it clear that the stresses of this past
scandal-riven year in Washington will not drive her out of some
sort of political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics, in good times and bad times, is the lifeblood of a
democracy,'' she said, reciting specific cases of people she had
met _ many of them during trips to New York _ who have been helped
by policies crafted by her husband's administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot drop out of the political process and leave the
arena to those with very specific agendas,'' she added, leaving it
provocatively ambiguous whether she was talking about her own
situation or merely urging her audience to stay politically
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting some people who want out of politics because they
``don't like the negativity,'' Mrs. Clinton remarked, to
sympathetic laughter, ``I can certainly understand why someone
would feel that way.'' But, she went on, ``somebody's going to make
the decisions'' about a variety of issues _ and ``these are not
decisions we should leave to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues she cited encompassed a whole range of social issues
that President Clinton has laid on the table _ money for more
teachers, a patients' bill of rights, saving Social Security and
Medicare, increasing the minimum wage, the 1992 economics bill that
raised taxes to lower the deficit, and the 1994 crime bill that put
more police on the streets and imposed tighter regulations on
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   If she does run for the Senate, she seemed to be hinting, her
platform would amount to a continuation of Bill Clinton's agenda _
a popular position here.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Charles Schumer, who was greatly helped by the first
lady's campaigning in his own successful election last fall, spoke
before Mrs. Clinton, and warned the crowd not to get too excited by
a possible Senate run by her.
</P>
<P>
   ``One needs to make that decision in a deliberative way, and in
an unfrenzied atmosphere,'' Schumer said. ``So I say to the first
lady, take a little time, think this one through.'' However, he
added, to wild applause, that if she did decide to run, ``you will
be one of the finest senators New York will ever have.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 900 Democrats in the audience _ almost all of them
women _ left the event at the Plaza in a buzz of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few men, Peter Vallone, speaker of the New York City
Council, nodded when asked if he thought the speech suggested the
first lady would run for the Senate seat being vacated next year by
Daniel Patrick Moynihan. ``I think she's setting the stage,''
Vallone said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton met with several local leaders, including Vallone,
later in the day, and had dinner at the home of financier Roger
Altman, a well-known Democratic donor.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the first lady spoke at a middle school in
Queens that has been cited as a model in a new federal report on
arts education. Ironically, that school's arts program was
replenished by a two-year $75 million citywide boost in arts
funding ordered by Giuliani. Among the speakers who preceded Mrs.
Clinton at the auditorium's podium was a mayoral aide who, politely
but pointedly, made that clear.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, Giuliani himself, when asked about the first
lady's impending speech at the school, said a bit facetiously that
he would be happy to hear her praise his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wednesday, as if to signal that the race is on, Mrs.
Clinton singled out, as responsible for the school's success, the
Annenberg Foundation, the National Endowment for the Arts, and the
New York State government _ but said nothing about City Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
