<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NURSES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES RULE SCHOOLS MUST PROVIDE NURSES FOR DISABLED STUDENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that federal law
requires school boards to pay nurses to provide classroom care for
disabled students whose health must be monitored constantly.
</P>
<P>
   However, the court said the Individuals with Disabilities
Education Act does not require schools to provide doctors for
severely disabled students who require the continuous care of a
physician.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's ruling that the law includes nursing care was
criticized by the National School Boards Association, which said
the expense of providing nurses will further strain financially
strapped schools. But the Clinton administration and advocates for
the disabled hailed the decision as a giant step in their effort to
ensure that disabled children receive the same level of education
as their able-bodied peers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the IDEA, schools must provide disabled children ``a free
appropriate public education and related services designed to meet
their unique needs.'' But the law does not require schools to
assist students whose disabilities are so severe that they require
``medical services.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 7-2 decision, the high court said the medical-services
exception refers to care that only a doctor can provide. Students
whose needs can be adequately addressed by a nurse are entitled
under the law to receive nursing care in the classroom, the court
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The school boards association said the decision will cost public
schools more than $500 million annually, as it now must provide
continuous nursing care to the approximately 17,000 children
nationwide who depend on the medical assistance while in class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worry that school districts will endure a great strain
because of today's decision,'' said Anne Bryant, the association's
executive director. ``It takes the focus of schools away from being
educators and into being medical-service providers. Furthermore,
schools must now assume responsibility for serious life-threatening
conditions, which could lead to greater legal liability.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials in several Texas school districts said Wednesday
they do not believe the ruling will have a major impact since their
districts already provide nursing services to physically disabled
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a court case comes about with a ruling, that is
certainly used to look at all other individual cases,'' said Dana
Riley, a special education administrator in the Spring Branch
district in the Houston area. ``But with special education, we have
to look at every child on a child-by-child basis to determine their
needs and in what ways we can provide services.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Edens, a Houston advocate for special education students,
said that case law has long been clear that schools must provide
special education children with necessary personnel to be
successful in the classroom. However, he said, the ruling will
likely have an impact ``in that it gives extra teeth'' to the law.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Education Secretary Judith Heumann said the
court's ruling ``is a very important decision for ... all of
America's disabled children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe disabled students ... should receive the services
necessary to ensure access to an appropriate education. That's what
the law guarantees, and now the courts have made that clear,'' said
Heumann, who is in charge of the department's special education and
rehabilitative services division.
</P>
<P>
   The high court decision marked a win for a quadriplegic
high-school student in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, who took the local
school board to court to force it to pay for the continuous health
monitoring he needs. The student, identified in court papers as
Garret F., has normal mental capacity, can speak and uses a
puff-and-sip straw to control his wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   But Garret requires constant attention for a variety of health
needs, including regular bladder catheterization; suctioning of his
breathing tube; changing his sitting position; and monitoring his
respiration and blood pressure. Garret suffered his life-altering
injury in 1987 when the then-4-year-old was thrown from a
motorcycle after the blanket he was holding got snarled in the
vehicle's drive mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   The jolt jerked Garret's head, severing his spine.
</P>
<P>
   In the litigation over whether the school district should pay
for his care in the classroom, the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals agreed with Garret that the nursing assistance he needs
does not qualify as a ``medical service'' under the law. The Cedar
Rapids Community School District _ which pays about $20,000 per
school year for Garret's care _ appealed to the Supreme Court,
arguing that nurses, like doctors, provide critical, continuous
medical services and are expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court, agreeing with the 8th Circuit, said the
law's exception for medical services is strictly limited to
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuous services may be more costly and may require
additional school personnel, but they are not thereby more
`medical,''' Justice John Paul Stevens wrote for the court.
``Whatever its imperfections, a rule that limits the
medical-service exemption to physician services is unquestionably a
reasonable and generally workable interpretation of the statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting Justices Clarence Thomas and Anthony M. Kennedy
assailed the court for its narrow definition of the law, saying
that school boards should not have to pay for nursing because the
``medical services'' a nurse provides are indistinguishable from
those a doctor performs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not typically think that `automotive services' are
limited to those provided by a mechanic, for example,'' Thomas
wrote in a dissenting opinion Kennedy joined. ``Rather, anything
done to repair or service a car, no matter who does the work, is
thought to fall into that category.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
