<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-SHAKESPEARE-$A     03-03 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-SHAKESPEARE-$ADV07-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES.: open checkbook.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Press, the marketing chief at Dreamworks who has organized
the Oscar campaign for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' said tartly, ``I'm
running a competitive and respectful campaign.'' With a laugh, she
said, ``My legs are hurting from being on the high road.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the long-time front-runner with ``Saving Private Ryan,''
she said, was not an enviable position. ``When people said it was a
shoo-in for `Ryan,' that's the worst thing that can happen, because
it allows room for an underdog,'' said Ms. Press. ``I cringed every
time someone said it. Shoo-ins exist to be toppled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Press acknowledged that `` `Shakespeare in Love' may have an
advantage in being in current release, making it fresher in the
minds of Academy voters. She added: ``But it is my understanding
that the Academy Award for best picture is supposed to go to the
outstanding achievement in motion picture _ not the most enjoyable
in current release or the easiest to watch twice on tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly Laura Ziskin, president of Fox 2000, whose studio,
20th Century Fox, released ``The Thin Red Line,'' Terrence Malick's
meditation on war, said: ``Actually, you get numbed by all the
hype. I kind of turn off at some point. Remind me once or twice
about a film and that's fine. Twenty times, it's overkill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting question for the Academy is how much of the
best picture award is about box office and ads, and how much of it
is giving an award for artistic achievement,'' Ms. Ziskin said,
clearly pushing hard for the Malick film, which won seven
nominations and which earned about $37 million domestically.
``Saving Private Ryan'' has made more than $203 million at the
domestic box office.
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Urman, co-president of Lions Gate Films Releasing,
whose films ``Gods and Monsters,'' and ``Affliction'' earned five
Academy nominations, said he was simply dazzled at the Miramax
approach. ``If we had gone to school anywhere to learn the dark
magic and vodoo of Academy campaigning, we all went to Miramax
University,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have made a science and art of Academy campaigning, which
in the past had to do with spending a ton of money,'' said Urman, a
former studio publicist. ``They have customized their campaigns,
film by film, nomination by nomination. They strategize about it;
they add people to their staff just for the awards season. They
don't miss a trick. And there is not a distributor today who plays
the Oscar game who doesn't study what Miramax has done.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Urman's company, a New York-based operation that
he runs with Tom Ortenberg, is the Cinderella candidate of the
Oscar campaign. Their nominations for ``Gods and Monsters'' include
best actor for McKellen, supporting actress for Lynn Redgrave and
adapted screenplay for Bill Condon. The two nominations for
``Affliction'' are for Nolte, as best actor, and James Coburn, as
supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   Urman's company has spent a relatively small amount _ $250,000
each _ to promote the Oscar chances of ``Gods and Monsters'' and
``Affliction.'' By contrast, studios may spend about $4 million for
an overall Academy Award effort, before and after the nominations.
Miramax, by the estimates of rival studio executives, probably will
spend as much as $10 million to promote ``Shakespeare in Love's''
Oscar push, which includes double-page ads in newspapers like The
New York Times and The Los Angeles Times. ``If the campaigns were
just about money and clout, we wouldn't have been nominated at
all,'' Urman said.
</P>
<P>
   For a small company like Lions Gate, the current Oscar season
can be costly. ``One of our greatest expenses has been to receive
the accolades,'' said Urman. ``We have to take out congratulatory
ads in the trade papers. You're frequently required to buy all
sorts of expensive tables and tickets to events in which you're
being honored. You're flying people from one city to another to
receive the awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're nominated for the Golden Globes, you're talking
Concordes and hotel rooms and limousines and tables at great
costs,'' he said. ``So much money goes to showing up and being
proud.'' Urman laughed. ``My wife just bought a fancy dress for the
Oscars,'' he said. ``I'm not complaining. These are the problems
you want.''
</P>
</TEXT>
