<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPSIDED LOSS SHOWS HOW FAR BOSTON COLLEGE HAS TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The end came with neither a bang nor a whimper, but
with a buzzer, which officially concluded not only Boston College's
96-55 loss to Syracuse in Wednesday's opening round Big East
tournament game, but the Eagles' season as well.
</P>
<P>
   For historical purposes only, the loss was the most lopsided in
Big East tournament history, but also gave the Eagles' 21 losses,
the most in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The hard facts will record 6-21, 3-15 in the Big East. Not
pretty numbers. And no one at BC is minimizing how difficult it was
to go through such a season.
</P>
<P>
   But there were few hung heads around the BC locker room
Wednesday at Madison Square Garden. ``We survived,'' said associate
head coach Tim O'Shea with a smile and a shake of his head.
</P>
<P>
   And they did it with their heads held up, the one-sided nature
of the Eagles' loss to Syracuse not withstanding.
</P>
<P>
   That characteristic might have been missing Wednesday, but it
was evident in the latter part of a season that began with people
predicting an 0-fer for the Big East season and, after a
last-second loss to Harvard at home in December, there was even
talk of a total blank for the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (the Harvard game) to me was the low point,'' said BC
athletic director Gene DeFilippo, while watching the Eagles' last
futile effort. ``I felt so bad for (coach) Al (Skinner)and for the
players. I cried coming home that night. I thought that was a game
we were supposed to win. And when we didn't do it, I was wondering
if we were ever going to win a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' did sporadically. All six of their wins had to be
called upsets. But they were also showing more signs of a life than
most people would expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't profess to know as much basketball as Al,'' said
DeFilippo. ``But I know I saw two things. I saw a team that was
playing hard and listening to what Al was saying. And that told me
good things were going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you. I'm not happy with what happened.
This hasn't been an easy season. But I've been at places where
programs are rebuilt and you have to be patient. I really think
we're going to get the job here.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Skinner, who just finished the second season of a seven
year contract that he might need all of to get BC basketball back
to the elite status it was approaching two years ago before the
program self destructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, not disheartened,'' said Skinner Wednesday,
walking back through the bowels of the Garden after his final press
conference of the season. ``But what I see encourages me. There
were lots of people out there who didn't give us a chance to win a
game at the start of the season. And the way we were playing they
might have been right.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude the whole year was that we weren't capaple of
beating a lot of teams unless we did a lot of things right. And
most of the season we didn't. But in early January, I started to
see things. I saw an attitude change. We started to get better. We
won three league games. We had a pretty good chance to win a couple
more (Pittsburgh, Georgetown).''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner dismissed Wednesday the way his players did on the
court. Syracuse was a bad matchup for the Eagles and they finished
the game the way they started, lacking any kind of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Skinner stood in the middle of a barren locker
room and told his team two things. That Wednesday's game was not
indicative of the kind of team they were and that next year, if
they wanted to work at it, would be better. Much better.
</P>
<P>
   The optimists out there agree. Next season will bring highly
regarded point guard Troy Bell from Minneapolis and a 6-10 big man
named Andrew Dudley from Bristol, Pa. It will also bring scoring
guard-small forward Xavier Singletary, who is sat out the season
after transferring from Howard.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly it will bring a new attitude of optimism that
has only barely begun to blossom.
</P>
<P>
   When Skinner and his staff arrived two years ago from Rhode
Island, BC basketball was a toxic wasteland, decimated by all the
nonsense involved in the Jim O'Brien/recruiting controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Players left, lines of communications were destroyed. The flow
of talent, which had taken so long to establish, had stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Now, much of that negativity has been washed away. There is
still no cause for celebration in the BC basketball offices.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shea and asisstant basketball coach Billy Coen will hit the
the recruiting road starting Thursday
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to remember,'' said Skinner,``is that this is a
marathon, not a sprint. We're in this for the long haul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
