<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLAND04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student survives Hutu attack Uganda
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Several months before University of Chicago
anthropology student Elizabeth Garland left for Uganda, she had
doubts about making the trip because of violence in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Garland, 29, daughter of Miami University President James
Garland, escaped harm Monday by hiding in her tent when Rwandan
Hutu attacked her campsite in southwest Uganda. Four park employees
were killed at the site and eight tourists kidnapped and murdered
in the nearby jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``She worried about (traveling there); her advisers worried
about it,'' said Anne Chien, the administrator for graduate student
affairs in the anthropology department at the University of
Chicago, where Garland is a doctoral student.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, four tourists were attacked by Hutu rebels in a
national park in Congo, near where Garland was planning to go to
study the effects of tourism on impoverished African villages.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before, Garland had lined up funding for the trip
through grants, including a Fulbright Scholarship, but put her
plans on hold after news of the attack in Congo, Chien said.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, after discussions with her advisers at the
University of Chicago and others, she decided to go. Fulbright
officials did not pull back its funding, as they have done in the
past when students wish to study in dangerous parts of the world,
Chien said. And the Ugandan national park she would be living in
was considered ``more secure'' than other areas, Chien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone finally came to the conclusion that it was relatively
safe,'' Chien said.
</P>
<P>
   So in early December, Garland left for the Ugandan capital of
Kampala, where she spent the first two months looking through
archives. In February, she set up camp in the village of Buhama on
the edge of the Bwindi Impenetrable Forest, a national park in
southwest Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Monday's massacre, Garland had sent an e-mail
message to her advisers telling them things were going well, Chien
said. She was building a house and getting settled.
</P>
<P>
   When the rebels attacked the village early Monday morning,
Garland stayed in her tent, which was hidden by bushes, according
to her father. The rebels didn't discover her and she managed to
escape the village unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   She is in Kampala now, according to Chien, and has no immediate
plans to return to the United States. She will however move to a
new location. It was unclear how long she is scheduled to stay in
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Chien said she got word that Garland was OK before she learned
what had happened. She immediately sent an e-mail message to
department faculty and then students.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Vogt, a classmate of Garland's, said she couldn't bear to
think of the horror Garland experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the news and I just felt so horrible,'' Vogt said.
``Just her sitting in the tent fearing for her life. Can you
imagine that? It's so horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogt described Garland as ``very positive and happy'' and said
she wasn't surprised her classmate wanted to stay on and complete
her studies in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a strong person with a lot of positive energy,'' Vogt
said. ``She's going to have a great project.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
