<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEMS-ART-700&AMP;     03-03 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEMS-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RALLY BEHIND CLINTON TO PUSH POST-IMPEACHMENT AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CONGRESS-EDUC) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under a campaign-style blue banner, President
Clinton rallied Wednesday with congressional Democrats to show
party unity on a legislative agenda that would reserve more than
three-quarters of federal budget surpluses for Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Vice President Al Gore received standing ovations
from Democrats who protected the president from impeachment but
wanted to censure him for ``shameful, reckless and indefensible''
behavior. Gore and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
who recently gave up plans to challenge Gore for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 2000, even hugged.
</P>
<P>
   With impeachment over, Democrats and Republicans have quickly
become enmeshed in battles over issues like education and how to
apportion surpluses for tax cutting, spending and the long-term
solvency of Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to inoculate themselves against a Democratic assault on
the issue of Social Security, the Republican leaders of Congress
have been working this week to assemble a budget plan that would
segregate Social Security trust funds from the rest of the federal
budget so the money could only be used for the popular retirement
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Wednesday praised Republicans for agreeing to reserve
billions of dollars for Social Security, but said that another 15
percent of the surplus should be put aside for Medicare. This is a
stand that the Democrats hope will allow them to frame the
Republican tax-cutting plans as a raid on the federal health care
program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still strong differences in our approach,'' the
president said in an ornate room in the Library of Congress, ``and
we must resolve them in a way that benefits the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a frieze of ancient warriors carrying back their dead,
Clinton spoke of the Democratic origins of the Great Society
programs for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do these things _ saving Social Security, saving
Medicare, empowering more Americans to save for their own
retirement,'' he said, ``we will fulfill our historic challenge to
meet the difficulties and the opportunities of the aging of America
in a way that provides a stronger economy and more stable families
for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans countered with their own tax-cutting rally led
by House Majority Leader Dick Armey. The crowd shouted
``Cha-Ching'' _ to imitate the sound of an IRS cash register _ as
the Texas Republican recited all the different ways that a family
is taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., called the surplus the ``overcharge''
and said that with tax cuts, a family could save money ``for a new
home, or money for ballet lessons for your daughter or shots for
the new puppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said that Republicans had agreed with Clinton to set aside
62 percent of projected budget surpluses to fix Social Security,
making the real debate over whether to use the remainder of the
surplus to cut taxes or increase government spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the choice is seen that way,'' Armey said, ``the American
people overwhelmingly come out on the side of cutting taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Republicans feuding among themselves over which taxes
to cut, Armey and his fellow Republicans did not showcase any
particular tax cut. Instead they announced plans for town hall
meetings around the nation to promote tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   At the Democratic rally, Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle of
South Dakota said that one Republican proposal, for a 10 percent
tax cut, would give people who earn $800,000 an annual tax
reduction of $20,000 while families who earn $38,000 or less would
save 27 cents a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe America's families deserve better than 27 cents a
day,'' he said and moved on to highlight other Democratic agenda
items for education and to control health maintenance
organizations. ``They deserve good schools for their children. If
they are sick, they deserve whatever treatment their doctor says
they need.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats Wednesday also called for raising the minimum
wage, putting 50,000 more police on the streets, and for tax
credits devoted to retirement savings, child care and long-term
health care.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The competing rallies showed that for all the talk of
bipartisanship in the wake of impeachment, both parties are on a
campaign footing _ not a good sign for legislative achievement. It
was also a telling sign of the mood of Democrats on Capitol Hill
that the most enthusiastic and spontaneous applause came not for
Clinton or Gore, but when Daschle introduced Gephardt as ``the next
speaker of the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt urged Democrats to work with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be judged by our progress, our action, our
accomplishment, he said, ``not by our words.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Democrats made clear that they would be happy to
bludgeon the Republicans if they block the Democratic agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they reject all of it, they provide the foundation for the
2000 elections,'' said Sen. Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey,
chairman of the Senate Democratic campaign effort.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island, who is heading
campaign efforts in the House, said, ``We are going to have to
continue to identify Republicans as the party that has put off the
important business of this country for the past year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
