<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-AGENDA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON JOINS DEMOCRATS IN SUPPORTING `FAMILIES FIRST' PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton joined with Democratic lawmakers
Wednesday in unveiling an ambitious legislative agenda for the
106th Congress, but a Congressional Budget Office report said some
of the proposals would break spending limits set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton and the Democrats said they remain
``united'' behind their ``Families First'' plan to preserve Social
Security by tapping in to the budget surplus, to modernize public
schools, assure access to quality health-care services and provide
targeted tax cuts to help families save for retirement, care for
their children and older relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At a pep rally at the Library of Congress, Clinton told the
lawmakers that the party's agenda, which is basically built around
his 1999 budget proposal and issues the Democrats have long
supported, would ``bring opportunity to every American'' by
building on the economic progress of the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is working again,'' Clinton said, borrowing a line
from Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. ``The question is,
what shall we do? And we're here to say that as proud as we are of
the record of the last six years, this is not a time to boast about
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehashing some of the proposals he laid out in his January State
of the Union address, Clinton issued a long wish list of spending
priorities coupled with limited, specifically targeted tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Extending the life of the Social Security and Medicare programs
is at the top of both parties' agendas this year. Clinton and the
Democrats would like to devote at least 62 percent of the budget
surpluses over the next 10 to 15 years _ an estimated $2.8 trillion
_ to help guarantee the soundness of Social Security for at least
the next 55 years. They also want to take at least 15 percent of
the surpluses _ some $686 billion _ to keep the Medicare program
solvent.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans agree with the idea of setting aside up to 62
percent of the surpluses for Social Security, but have not yet
signed on to the proposal that surplus money also be used to shore
up the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton rallied with his Democratic colleagues, Congress's
chief budget analyst was warning the Senate Budget Committee that
the president's 2000 budget proposal could bust next year's
spending caps by some $30 billion, primarily because of increases
he wants in education, defense, health care and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contends that increased cigarette taxes and other
revenues would be more than enough to pay for the spending
increases. But Dan Crippen, director of the nonpartisan CBO, said
the revenues could not be counted as offsets under current budget
law.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO also criticized Republican spending plans, including one
that would increase education funding by up to 40 percent and raise
defense spending by billions more than even the Pentagon has
sought.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO has also questioned both the Democratic and Republican
proposals to use the biggest chunk of projected surpluses to help
preserve the Social Security program. Crippen noted Wednesday that
the plan could leave both sides short of the money they need to pay
for the big tax cuts and spending increases they are promising.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security was a big topic elsewhere on Capitol Hill
Wednesday. The administration defended its proposal to a House Ways
and Means subcommittee, particularly a controversial element that
would have the federal government invest part of the retirement
funds in the private market.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
answered criticism that such large-scale government investment
would be susceptible to political meddling that could interfere
with the investments' performance. Summers said the administration
envisioned setting up an independent board, insulated from
political pressure, to make investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic rally unfolded as congressional Republicans were
trying to hammer together their own legislative priorities for this
year. Like the Democrats, they hope to focus their efforts on
Social Security, education defense increases and tax cuts. But they
still have significant disagreements among themselves about how to
achieve those goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic event was designed to show the party is united
behind one agenda, unlike the GOP at the moment. Rep. Gene Green,
D-Texas, said that despite Clinton's troubles, he and other
Democratic lawmakers were ``proud'' to stand with him behind a plan
that Green says will address ``real problems affecting Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is intended to help our families prepare for retirement,
educate their children and raise them in a safe neighborhoods, and
have access to quality, affordable health care,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
