<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-COP-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TIMONEY TOUTS CITY'S COMPUTER CRIME SYSTEM AS NATIONAL
MODEL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, March 3, -- Philadelphia Police Commissioner John
Timoney urged a congressional panel to set up a nationwide
computerized crime mapping and tracking system modeled after his
department's program.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said Wednesday that if police departments all over the
country had the same technology, it would help departments share
data, and coordinate their actions in solving regional crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchange of information between departments becomes a
laborious and expensive undertaking that is only worth doing in
exceptional circumstances,'' Timoney said. ``If all these
departments shared data, the transfer of crime information
electronically would require nothing more than the press of a
button.''
</P>
<P>
   Timoney, who testified at a House Committee on Government Reform
hearing examining how local officials find solutions to problems
that are common to many cities, said there should be national
technology standards for police departments.
</P>
<P>
   Before setting up the Philadelphia police department's
``COMPSTAT,'' program, Timoney had served in the top ranks of New
York City's police department, when it was the first to use the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enabling police departments around the country to share data
... is too important a goal to be left to voluntary action at the
local level,'' Timoney said.
</P>
<P>
   COMPSTAT tracks crime statistics including the locations of
burglaries or stolen cars, and maps them out to help officers spot
trends.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia department uses the program at weekly meetings,
when commanders in each district discuss with top officers the
crimes they are working on, Timoney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps involve the higher-ups like myself with officers as
they plan strategies and solve crimes,'' Timoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said police departments in Bucks, Montgomery, Chester
and Delaware counties will be working with him to set up their own
programs, which would help officers solve crime in the Greater
Philadelphia area.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the panel were Mayor Rudy Giuliani who spoke about how
New York City lowered its crime rate, and Harry Shorstein, the
state attorney from Jacksonville, Florida, who touted his city's
crackdown on juvenile crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
