A6741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON04-COX     03-03 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hezbollah turns to PR to fight off terroristic image
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT _ As we ambled around a mountain village in south
Lebanon, our Lebanese translator attempted a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to an Israeli encampment on a hill nearby, he suggested
that the two journalists in our little group take the lead.
Otherwise, he quipped, the Israelis might spot our Hezbollah guide
and open fire.
</P>
<P>
   But our guide, Samir Alami, hardly looked like a target in a
guerrilla war. Clean-cut in his slacks and sweater, he was the
best-dressed of our bunch. And, he was working his cellular
telephone as any good PR man does.
</P>
<P>
   He works in the Hezbollah press office, and he is trying to
spruce up the Party of God's image in the west.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after Hezbollah killed seven Israelis, including a
brigadier general, their press machine was in high gear. They
displayed captured Israeli equipment, held news conferences and
released battlefield video.
</P>
<P>
   That was no surprise. Traveling in Lebanon, I found a Hezbollah
that has gone from kidnapping journalists to simply ``spinning''
them.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah was born in 1982, when Israel invaded Lebanon and took
over the 9-mile strip of that neighboring country's southern border
that it still occupies today. It was a radical offshoot of Amal, a
Shiite Muslim movement. And Iranian financing has kept it going
strong and constantly updating its warfare.
</P>
<P>
   It's a group on the hinge of world opinion. The Israelis and the
United States consider the guerrillas terrorists, but the United
Nations calls them by the more neutral name, ``resistance'' forces.
In Lebanon, Hezbollah's fighters are considered heroes.
</P>
<P>
   But Hezbollah is not only a militant organization. It also does
charity work. It operates nine schools, three hospitals and 13
dental clinics. It provides drinking water to Beirut slums and
rebuilds roads and houses destroyed in fighting in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Hezbollah collection boxes, painted like the Dome of the
Rock mosque in Jerusalem, stand outside many stores in downtown
Beirut, Lebanon's capital city. In Baalbek, a tourist town where
Hezbollah dominates, shops sell desktop Hezbollah flags. Several
party members serve in Lebanon's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   When I arranged a trip to south Lebanon, the confirmation came
as I sat in a dingy Beirut office with a Hezbollah sheikh, who was
sporting a burgundy blazer and tasseled loafers. He copied my
passport and asked about the circulation of newspapers I write for.
</P>
<P>
   He also gave me glossy propaganda pamphlets. One showed e-mail
messages to Hezbollah's Internet home page.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of days later, a guide met me at a specified cafe. He
eventually took me to an unmarked office above a perfume shop in
the port city of Tyre. It's one of the safe houses Hezbollah
maintains for meeting outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the Americans will stop hating us,'' said Sheik Nabil
Kaouk, Hezbollah's leader for southern Lebanon. ``We are dying from
American weapons (used by Israelis) and they don't feel guilty
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaouk, a tall 35-year-old, cuts an elegant figure in the brown
cape and turban-like headgear of Shiite Muslim clerics. He spoke
politely while aides served strawberry juice.
</P>
<P>
   We covered politics and Hezbollah history. When questioned about
his family, Kaouk talked about a son who was getting married. But
then _ because he is an occasional target of Israeli assassination
attempts _ he got edgy and said we should not be discussing his
family.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked him why Hezbollah now meets with journalists rather
than kidnapping them, Kaouk denied that Hezbollah staged
kidnappings. Those denials are widely refuted by experts.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaouk said that just shows how Israel's supporters have
tarnished Hezbollah's reputation around the world. He asked me to
write what I had seen and added, ``Thank you for coming here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
