<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-BANANA-2TAKES-N     03-03 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-BANANA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IMPOSES TARIFFS ON EUROPEAN GOODS; A BAN ON THE CONCORDE
THREATENED 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: This story was budgeted earlier as BANANA-TRADE) 
(fe) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States escalated two politically
contentious trade disputes with Europe on Wednesday, imposing 100
percent tariffs on $520 million in European products and
threatening to ban Europe's supersonic pride, the Concorde, from
landing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The tariffs imposed by the Clinton administration essentially
double the price of such goods as Louis Vuitton handbags, Parma
hams, pecorino cheese and Scottish cashmere sweaters. They are part
of a six-year battle over trade in bananas.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to ban the Concorde was in a bill passed
overwhelmingly on Wednesday in the House of Representatives. It is
in retaliation for a European ruling that would ban many older
American airplanes from landing in Europe. American officials
contend Europe's restriction is intended to promote the sale of new
engines and aircraft made by European manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But both battles are really about the serious tensions that have
erupted between the United States and a Europe newly unified by a
common currency. On both continents, politicians are feeling the
heat from slowing exports and fear a slowdown in economic growth
later this year. And, increasingly, Washington and the European
Union have found themselves unable to resolve seemingly ordinary
economic disputes, with each accusing the other of defying the
World Trade Organization, the four-year-old court of international
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The trade court has stepped in to arbitrate the banana dispute
and has become the battleground for other politically sensitive
issues, including Europe's ban on imported beef from cattle raised
with hormones.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments have resulted in some of the nastiest
trans-Atlantic bickering in years. Wednesday afternoon, American
officials said they hoped that the imposition of the 100 percent
tariffs on European luxury goods _ with the notable exception of
wine and Mercedes Benz cars _ would ``freeze trade'' in those items
and compel the Europeans to negotiate. In response, Europe's top
trade official, Sir Leon Brittan, called the U.S. action
``unacceptable and unlawful.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the arguments particularly strange is the fact that
the underlying dispute seems relatively trivial. ``It's hard to
believe,'' one American official mused on Wednesday, ``that we got
to this by arguing over bananas.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade fights with Europe have become a major issue at the
White House, with President Clinton becoming directly involved in
some of the negotiations, most recently with President Jacques
Chirac of France. But the economic impact is relatively modest: The
United States imported $176.3 billion in goods from nations in the
European Union last year, meaning that Wednesday's sanctions apply
to one-quarter of 1 percent of goods imported from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But in trade, as in politics, symbolism counts for more than
statistics. And the symbolism of Wednesday's actions are clear: the
United States is showing that it intends to retaliate if it
believes Europe is manipulating trade rules to keep out
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The airplane battle, like the beef-hormone dispute, is a prime
example of how one continent's environmental and health regulations
are another continent's trade barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The European Parliament recently passed legislation banning the
takeoff or landing of older airplanes even if their engines have
been retrofitted with devices called ``hush kits'' that cut down on
airplane noise. European officials say that even planes equipped
with the hush kits _ which are also required here to bring older
planes into compliance with international noise-reduction standards
_ make more noise than newer planes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Oberstar, D-Minn., who sponsored the measure to ban
the Concorde flights, calls the rule ``a thinly veiled attempt to
give a competitive advantage'' to the European aircraft consortium,
Airbus Industries, and European engine makers that would benefit if
airlines are forced to buy new engines.
</P>
<P>
   If the ban were actually carried out by the transport ministers
of the European nations, it would drastically lower the value of
about 1,000 planes now in operation. Newer planes, equipped with
quieter engines, are unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   The full House approved the ban on Concorde by a voice vote on
Wednesday, after several members noted that the supersonic plane
violates American noise limitations and flies because of a waiver
of those rules. There are only 12 Concorde aircraft now flying, and
the only aircraft that come into the United States operate between
Kennedy International Airport and London and Paris. They are flown
by British Airways and Air France; both airlines called on
Wednesday for the United States and Europe to settle their
differences at the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   That may yet happen. But clearly the House action was intended
to give the Clinton administration more leverage in its talks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The banana dispute is deeply steeped in American politics. While
the government is acting on behalf of the Dole Food Co. and
Chiquita Brands International, neither company grows or picks
bananas in the United States. Almost all of their bananas are grown
in Ecuador, Guatemala, Honduras, El Salvador and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   Europe has imposed an enormously complex ``banana regime'' that
places quotas on the import of Latin American bananas, to benefit
former European colonies, many in the Caribbean. The WTO has struck
down the quota system several times. In each case, American
officials charge, Europe has made minor modifications to the rules
that essentially kept the trade barrier in place and insisted that
if the United States was unhappy it should litigate the issue all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   So in December the administration warned it was preparing to
retaliate, publishing a list of goods whose wholesale price would
be doubled. It includes Louis Vuitton handbags and pecorino, a
hard, sharp Italian cheese, ``in original loaves, not suitable for
grating.'' European-made cotton bed linens are subject to the huge
tariffs, along with cashmere ``sweaters, pullovers, sweat shirts,
waistcoats and similar articles.''
</P>
<P>
   Europe insists that the administration is acting on behalf of
Carl Lindner, who controls Chiquita and has close connections to
both political parties. And they note that few if any American jobs
are at stake in the banana trade. Earlier this week the WTO said it
needed more time to determine whether the United States threat of
$500 million in sanctions was proportionate to the injury Europe
was causing with its quota system.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States did not wait and insisted that the Customs
Service apply the sanctions on Wednesday with the understanding
that the tariffs will be lowered retroactively if the WTO reduces
the amount. Ambassador Peter Scher, who heads up agricultural talks
for the U.S. trade representative's office, said that the ``real
issue is whether Europe is prepared to obey the WTO's rulings.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It is becoming more and more difficult for the
commission to solve problems. We are very close to losing support
for the WTO as a viable means to solve trade problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Brittan said in a statement that the United States ``has today
decided to defy the WTO system by introducing a form of sanctions
which has no WTO authorization whatsoever. The U.S. action is a
measure designed to have an immediate effect on European exports.
The arbitrators yesterday made it clear that they were in no way
authorizing such action, by stating expressly that they were not
ready for the moment to take a decision on the American request.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
