<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MEXICO'S RULING PARTY TURNS 70, MANY WONDER IF IT'S SHORT OF
TIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL RILEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The 70th birthday this week of Mexico's
long-ruling party won't be its last, nor is it likely to be
remembered as one of its best.
</P>
<P>
   As it celebrates its birthday Thursday, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI _ the political force that has ruled
Mexico's federal government continually since just after the
Mexican Revolution _ is facing a tumultuous present and an
uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   It's now rife with infighting and internal splits, movements to
push the party forward and movements to return it to its more
glorious past. Depending on who is talking, these forces may either
rip the party apart or provide the creative impetus necessary to
take it into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, the 70th anniversary is a heavyweight. The PRI is
painted as exhausted, incapable of change,'' said Sergio Martinez,
director of the Colosio Foundation, the party's think tank. ``We
have to stress the historical balance of the party's achievements,
the positive electoral results of 1998, and show we're ready for
the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The 70th anniversary is special because it comes in what must
certainly rank as one of the most important years in the PRI's
political life.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the party will select a candidate for the
presidential race in 2000, the first in which it has a real chance
of losing. It will also be the first time in memory when the
party's candidate won't be chosen personally by the sitting
president.
</P>
<P>
   That combination of uncertainty both inside the party and out
has opened rifts that long lay underneath the PRI's public show of
unity.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to changes in electoral laws in the early 1990s, the party
sat atop a virtual political monopoly, compared by some analysts to
the dominance enjoyed by the Communist Party in its heyday in the
Soviet Union. Under the PRI's big tent, just about every important
sector, and every ideological stripe, were included: peasants and
students, businessmen and unions, leftists, rightists and
centrists.
</P>
<P>
   That grip eased when the political system opened through a
series of reforms that the PRI itself enacted under former
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari and the current president,
Ernesto Zedillo. In 1982, the party held 91 percent of all elected
posts in the country from the presidency down to local mayors. That
fell to 62 percent by 1994 and 54 percent by 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The search for a more distinct political profile has antagonized
the divide between party traditionalists _ known in Mexico as the
dinosaurs _ and the technocrats, the outward-looking, mostly
foreign-trained bureaucrats who now control the party's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now, they've needed each other,'' said Federico
Esteves, a political scientist in Mexico City. ``The technocrats
know how to run the economy, and the dinosaurs know how to win
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have always been tensions. Now, they've just become more
open.''
</P>
<P>
   While the party has yet to decide the actual process for
choosing a candidate, the two factions are already lining up behind
the men most likely to carry their banners. And the possibility
looms of a nasty, factional fight erupting in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of whether the fight within the PRI could
conceivably turn into the worst possible scenario for them _ that
is, break the party apart if the losers leave _ is the heart of a
debate that's been going on within the party over the last few
months,'' Esteves said.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Bartlett has emerged as the old guard's candidate of
choice. One of Mexico's most seasoned politicians, Bartlett is both
eloquent and soft-spoken. He was also identified by two witnesses
testifying in a U.S. court as present during the torture and murder
of Enrique ``Kiki'' Camarena, a U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency
officer killed in Mexico in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett has repeatedly denied the charge, and can point to
letters from three former U.S. ambassadors to Mexico that attest to
his character. But as Mexico's interior minister from 1983 to 1988,
he was responsible for the country's now-defunct secret police that
U.S. law enforcers said worked hand in glove with drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   While many Mexicans see Bartlett as a reminder of the PRI's dark
past, others see him as the politician most capable of restoring
the party's greatness. He stresses the party's successes in leading
Mexico into the modern age, and says the PRI needs to return to its
populist roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that governments are for politicians, not for
specialists,`` Bartlett has said. ``This is at the core of the
discussion in Mexico now: Who is going to be the next president? I
say we need a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   The party's technocrats are closing ranks behind Mexico's
current Interior Minister, Francisco Labastida, who is said to be
Zedillo's favorite. Like Zedillo and Salinas before him, Labastida
is a university-trained economist.
</P>
<P>
   Although less charismatic than Bartlett, he has the advantage of
being backed by the party leadership. ``Labastida has fairly good
regional support and the backing of the president,'' Esteves said.
``He's already the front-runner,'' even before officially
announcing his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts are speculating that the party may use the
anniversary to announce the method of choosing its presidential
candidate. The options under debate range from convening a
nominating convention of party stalwarts to holding a national
primary open to all candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential for a messy year, nobody is counting the
PRI out. Even suffering through a sagging economy and a series of
scandals, the party can rely on an enormous organizational base. It
won seven of 10 state governorships in elections last year and
consistently leads both main opposition parties in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRI still has a strong plurality increasingly based on the
votes of the poor and the uneducated,'' said Carlos Elizondo, a
writer and political analyst. ``The worst off of all still live in
the old Mexico, in terms of access to information.''
</P>
<P>
   In what many interpret as an unexpected birthday present, the
main opposition parties _ the left-of-center Democratic Revolution
Party, or PRD, and its right-of-center rival, the National Action
Party, or PAN _ announced earlier this week that they would
consider a proposal to offer a joint presidential candidate in the
2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   While it carries potential dangers for the PRI, the proposal
nonetheless suggests that the party's two major opponents believe
they can't unseat it alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' Elizondo said, ``the two opposition parties are
much less optimistic. They are starting to realize that the PRI
could actually win.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
