<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAY-TV-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST LIKE HOMEMADE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By DEREK REVERON 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Latin America's pay television has traditionally thrived on U.S.
movies, sports, cartoons and a lot of reruns. Viewers were
perenially Perdido en el Espacio (Lost in Space) or visiting Los
Picapiedra (The Flintstones) and Los Locos Adams (The Adam's
Family). Now, however, a cadre of Miami-based pay television
networks are transmitting a growing volume and variety of original
programming to boost ratings in the region.
 &HT;    Over the last six years or so, more than 30 networks have opened
Latin American operations in the Miami area. They have staked a
claim in the region's fledgling, but promising, cable television
market and, in doing so, have stepped up efforts to produce shows
that reflect Latin cultures and tastes.
 &HT;    Pay television _ delivered by cable or satellite _ reaches about
a tenth of Latin American's more than 150 million households.
However, the industry is growing fast, with the number of
subscribers forecast to reach 38 million over the next five years,
according to the Strategis research group. Currently, Argentina and
Mexico are the region's largest cable markets, but Brazil is coming
on fast.
 &HT;    Brazil has been passing laws to allow the expansion of its cable
system and U.S. pay TV channels are cranking out Portuguese feeds
to the nation. ``Sooner or later, Brazil will become the biggest
cable market in Latin America, if the economy keeps holding and
there are no major setbacks,'' says Luis Peraza, senior vice
president of programming and production for U.S.-based Cisneros
Television Group. CTG, a major player in Latin America, is a
subsidiary of the Cisneros Group of Companies, a privately held
Venezuelan conglomerate.
 &HT;    Cable companies are flocking to Miami because it is located near
Latin America and has a large pool of Spanish-speaking talent. More
importantly, the city has a fast-growing cable industry
infrastructure aimed at Latin America. There are an increasing
number of casting outfits, production facilities, media buyers and
broadcasting companies.
 &HT;    In the early 1990s, the Latin American cable industry barely
existed. Now, programmers in the Miami area alone account for more
than US$600 million in annual revenues, according to Miami-Dade
County officials. GlobeCast North America, a provider of satellite
services, reflects the growth. In l997, the company distributed 17
cable networks to Latin America. By the end of l998, it had nearly
doubled its customer base. The company, a subsidiary of
telecommunications giant France Telecom, is investing $18 million
over the next three years to expand operations and recently bought
an 85,000 square foot building and six acres of land that will more
than double its operations.
 &HT;    U.S-based TransAmerica Media Group, which buys advertising space
in Spanish-language media, says its revenues from Latin American
billing doubles annually thanks in part to the region's exploding
cable TV industry. ``Miami is where deals are put together,'' says
Trans-America Chief Executive Officer Jose del Cueto. ``The cable
operators are here. The signal providers are here, and hundreds of
companies who are potential cable advertisers are here.''
 &HT;    Programming cornucopia. U.S. pay TV networks have only just
begun their mission of filling Latin America with the kind of
programming variety that exists in the United States. ``There's
more niche marketing and targeting of audience segments going on
now [in Latin America,'' says Robert Behar, chief executive of
GlobeCast North America. ``You now have specialty channels, music
channels, sports channels, racing channels, movie channels,
documentaries, travel and news. It's evolving almost the way the
U.S. market did.''
 &HT;    Cable companies hope to attract viewers partly by appealing to
cultural sensibilities. U.S. cable executives say that Latin
Americans clamor for more programming that reflects their reality.
``In Mexico, cable operators and distributors say we don't transmit
enough Mexican product. In Argentina and Chile they say the same
thing,'' says Yolanda Ramirez Foster, vice president of programming
at GEMS International Television.
 &HT;    GEMS, which targets Latin women, is increasing its original
programming by about 10 percent this year. Consulte a Su Doctor, a
new call-in medical show, will feature medical professionals from
varying Latin American backgrounds.
 &HT;    Venezuelan-owned CTG plans to expand the number of its channels
from eight to 11 over the next year. The company currently produces
about 5 percent of its own programs, but expects to increase that
substantially as well. CTG is developing original novelas (soap
operas), sitcoms and drama series, the bulk of which it will
produce in Miami. The company also will create shows for its joint
venture with Playboy that will feature talent from across the
region.
 &HT;    Discovery Networks Latin America/Iberia says that 1999 will be
its most aggressive year yet for original programming, which
currently accounts for about one tenth of all shows. The U.S.
broadcaster will produce its first hour-long documentaries
specifically for Latin America. Some of Discovery's new hour-long
shows will explore Mexican colonial history, mark the 500th
anniversary of the discovery of Brazil, and discuss how Latin
Americans are fighting the Year 2000 computer problem. Additional
shows will feature Latin American architecture, famous houses and
their current and former occupants. Other networks are following
suit. The host of cable companies aggressively targeting the region
includes MTV, Sony TV, HBO, Nickelodeon, USA Network, the Weather
Channel, the Travel Channel, music video station HTV and QVC
shopping network.
 &HT;    Limits to local. There is a limit to how much original,
culturally sensitive programming cable operators can afford to
provide due to high production and broadcast costs. That's why
companies try to strike a balance between targeting Latin America
as a region and appealing to certain countries, notably the biggest
cable markets of Argentina and Mexico. They also try to split costs
between the region and the U.S. Hispanic market. GEMS, for
instance, has four feeds: Argentina, Mexico, the rest of Latin
America and the United States. The station plans to launch a
Portuguese-language feed to Brazil this year. Every day, each
region receives the same blocks of programming, but GEMS varies the
content within each daily block. Menu del Dia, a cooking show,
might feature Argentine cuisine one day and Colombian food the next
day. Consulte a Su Doctor might have a Peruvian pediatrician and a
Mexican gynecologist on back-to-back days. Perspectivas, a talk
show produced in Los Angeles, features regional variety every day,
since its three hosts are from Argentina, Mexico and Spain,
respectively. ``We aim to give our shows an international feel,''
says Ramirez Foster. ``We take that approach, as opposed to having
30 feeds to satisfy everybody in Latin America. We focus on the
things that women have in common, like fashion, home improvement
and issues important to them, such as health.''
 &HT;    Historical and cultural cable channels perhaps feel the greatest
urgency to produce programs that reflect Latin America. ``We try
very hard to take into account our audiences' sensitivities,'' says
Rick Rodriguez, vice president of programming for Discovery
Networks Latin America/Iberia. ``Neutral Spanish doesn't work for
these programs.'' When Discovery carried live coverage of the
Titanic shipwreck dive, simultaneous Spanish and Portuguese
translators kept up with the show's English-speaking host the best
they could. But for rebroadcasts of the special, Discovery dubbed
more thoughtful translations in a number of Latin American
dialects.
 &HT;    Sometimes shows based on one aspect of a specific Latin American
culture have regional appeal. Take, for instance, Cisneros
Television Group's version of the animated series Dr. Katz series.
 &HT;    In the Comedy Central channel's English-language version, Dr.
Katz is a New York psychiatrist who treats famous U.S. patients. On
CTG, he is an Argentine psychiatrist who treats Latin American
celebrities; one, for instance, is a Venezuelan Miss Universe.
CTG's Dr. Katz is a humorous takeoff on the stereotype throughout
Latin America that Argentines have a fascination with
psychotherapy, says CTG's Peraza.
 &HT;    Playing on stereotypes doesn't always work. With South Park, an
irreverent animated spoof of growing up somewhere in the U.S.
Rockies, CTG first experimented with using Mexican expressions and
slang. Executives later decided that approach wouldn't help the
show's edgy sarcasm to appeal across Latin America. CTG settled on
neutral Spanish accents to help Latin Americans perceive the show
as a peculiarly kooky U.S. take on childhood.
 &HT;    While cable programmers believe that culturally sensitive
programming will draw more subscribers, they aren't absolutely
sure. Latin America has a formal, standardized ratings system for
pay TV, but audiences measured are so small that it is hard to
judge the true impact of programming. ``We still haven't seen a
correlation in terms of ratings, but they are so immature in this
market that you can't draw much information from them,'' notes
Rodriguez. ``But from what I see in terms of press coverage,
additional advertising and anecdotal feedback about these shows,
they tend to have the viewers' interest.''
 &HT;     
