c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNKIND CUT
</P>
<P>
   The medical benefits of circumcision are not compelling enough
to warrant recommending it as a routine procedure for newborn baby
boys, the American Academy of Pediatrics concludes in a new policy
statement released this week.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors say parents should discuss the risks and benefits of
circumcision with their pediatrician and then make an informed
decision about what is in the best interest of their child.
</P>
<P>
   And, they say, if parents decide to circumcise their infant, it
is essential that pain relief be provided. The surgery is often
done without anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   The AAP's task force on circumcision reviewed 40 years of
medical research on the benefits and risks before deciding that the
benefits are not significant enough to make it routine, according
to the policy statement, published in this month's edition of
``Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER HEALTHY
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, butternut squash, lean beef and spinach may not be your
child's idea of a super meal, but researchers at the University of
Texas Southwestern Medical School in Dallas say the supernutrients
found in those foods provide a great foundation for pediatric good
health.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin A, iron, omega-3 fatty acids and folic acid are
essential nutrients for growing children, says Dr. Robert Squires
Jr., associate professor of pediatrics at Southwestern.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends that parents seek out foods high in those
nutrients and consider new ways to make them more appetizing to
children.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a child who turns up his nose at a bowl of spinach
might love spinach pizza.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
