A6771 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MILAN04-COX     03-03 0326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MILAN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ever-elegant Armani draws a bead on the slit, the sheer
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Some designers have muddled outlooks on the
future of fashion. Giorgio Armani's views on century's-end
dressing, however, are crystal clear.
</P>
<P>
   For the finale of his fall/winter collection, Armani showed the
sort of evening gow ns that should cause jaws to drop harder than
Times Square's apple or Underground Atlanta's peach come New Year's
Eve. All were super-sheer numbers with crystal beading in strategic
places to keep the models from appearing nude.
</P>
<P>
   There was no vulgarity to the look, just masterful manipulation
of fabric and the human form. The eye-catching blue and green
beading _ in stripes, plaids, chevrons and florals _ served as
delicious distractions from the skin just beneath.
</P>
<P>
   And if the pre-millenial hoopla running rampant through the
industry distracted Armani while assembling this collection, it
hardly showed. Understated elegance remains his trademark, even
when he plugs into such trends as the ubiquitous ``utility'' bag
with the vengance of someone who's banking on an upsurge in
accessories sales come fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Armani look has evolved dramatically: in contrast to the
broad-shouldered, tight-waisted, full-legged drape of old, his
latest collection featured: jackets that fit snug on the shoulders
and were cropped at the waist; flat-front pants cut with just
enough room to walk breezily; and semi-sheer knit sweaters and
tanks used in place of blouses.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the jackets were collarless and wrapped asymetrically
around the torso. Most of Armani's skirt were wrap-style as well,
with daringly high slits up the front, back and sides. His models
were shod in flat, molded-sole shoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
