A6779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EDUCATION-ANALYSIS     03-03 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EDUCATION-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE SPIN, SHORTCOMINGS IN LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After a weeklong stalemate, it all worked out in the
end.
</P>
<P>
   That's the political polish Gov. Cellucci is applying to the
three-corner compromise that broke an impasse over selecting a new
commissioner of education.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrangement Cellucci approved Wednesday not only marks a
defeat for him, it also highlights the shortcomings of an
administration that has repeatedly been caught off guard on
education, an issue Cellucci calls one of his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, floated Tuesday and approved Wednesday, saw John
Silber resign as chairman of the Board of Education, thereby making
way for James Peyser, Cellucci's candidate for commissioner, to
become board chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Political face saved, Cellucci will now bow to the inevitable,
letting the board award the commissioner's job to David Driscoll,
the interim commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guy is going to be chairman. He is going to be the boss of
the commissioner,'' Cellucci said. ``I think it is a good result. .
. . It enables us to move education reform forward. That is the
result I have been focused on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a post crucial to Cellucci's success as governor, the
board will now install a man whom the governor views as too much a
creature of the state's education establishment to reform it.
</P>
<P>
   As Cellucci aides see it, voters will likely hold the governor
accountable if their children don't fare well when student tests
begin to count in upcoming years.
</P>
<P>
   During the standoff last week, one aide drew a comparison to
Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino, who has also made improving
education a top priority. ``If we're going to be held accountable,
we need our own person as commissioner,'' said the aide.
</P>
<P>
   But as John Silber is fond of saying, if wishes were horses,
beggars would ride.
</P>
<P>
   For all his efforts, Cellucci couldn't sway the two votes
necessary to secure the commissioner's job for Peyser. And when he
demanded that Roberta Schaefer and Abigail Thernstrom resign if
they wouldn't support Peyser, the two flatly refused, according to
sources familiar with the Monday meeting exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Several sources say Cellucci learned only belatedly that he
didn't have the votes for Peyser.
</P>
<P>
   As early as the Feb. 6 round of interviews with candidates for
the job, it had become obvious to observers that a majority of the
board had coalesced around Driscoll. Still, several sources say the
administration didn't wake up to that reality until the afternoon
of Feb. 22, the day before the board was scheduled to vote on a new
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   That's the third time in nine months that Cellucci has been
caught off guard by important education developments. The first
time was last summer, when the Board of Education voted to lower
the passing standard for those taking the state's new
teacher-certification test. Cellucci had to make a personal
appearance at the board to get that vote reversed, staving off what
might have been a campaign catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago the University of Massachusetts Board of Trustees
raised tuition, despite the governor's expressed desire that it be
lowered. Once again, Cellucci was put in the position of cajoling _
indeed, even threatening _ his own appointees to reverse an
unpopular decision. He prevailed, but only after days of headlines
that portrayed an administration at odds with itself.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor didn't prevail last week. That means Cellucci
will be left to nudge education reform along, using like-minded
appointees on a board he no longer controls to ride herd on a
commissioner of whom he's been publicly skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be my responsibility to make sure there is a real
partnership between the governor and the administration and the
board, and that there aren't any surprises,'' Peyser said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's embarrassment, one thing most everyone can
agree on is that Cellucci sorely needs someone to play that role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
