<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allied Holdings to open unit in Mexico
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Allied Holdings, the biggest car-hauling company in
the United States and Canada, said it will set up a logistics
subsidiary in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur-based Allied Holdings said Wednesday the new unit, Axis
Logistica, will be part of its existing Axis Group subsidiary and
will be based in Guadelajara.
</P>
<P>
   Axis Logistica will arrange third-party transport of automobiles
when needed and provide export and import processing services and
customization work, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Holdings' car-hauling business in Mexico is limited by
trade agreements. But many of its customers have operations there.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fleming, vice president of business development for Axis
Group, said the company ``is being drawn to Mexico because of
customer requirements and the need to have a company to spearhead
our efforts to meet them.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied Holdings last year absorbed Ryder's Automotive Carrier
Group and saw its annual revenues grow to $1.03 billion, up from
$581.5 million in 1997. Profit was $8.5 million vs. $2.4 million.
Shares in Allied Holdings were unchanged Wednesday at $11.93 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
