<HEADER>
A6783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZMAGS04-COX     03-03 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michael Jordan ads brought big returns
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Chicago Bulls wasn't the only bull market
superstar Michael Jordan was responsible for creating. He did a
pretty spectacular job for Wall Street, too.
</P>
<P>
   Worth (March) calculated the total return of five companies
whose brands Jordan endorsed vs. their five top competitors from
Jan. 1, 1996, to Jan. 13, 1999, when he retired from pro
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The total return of endorsed companies was 101.7 percent vs.
31.9 percent for non-endorsed competitors, Worth says.
</P>
<P>
   Just an accident? Not at all, sports marketer Brandon Steiner
tells Worth. MCI Worldcom stock soared 314 percent to rival AT&AMP;T's
68 percent in the three-year period, thanks to Jordan's MCI
long-distance phone commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's other endorsements cited in the analysis are Quaker
Oats (Gatorade), Nike, Sara Lee (Hanes), and Rayovac. The other top
competitors of these companies are Coca-Cola (PowerAde), Reebok,
Fruit of the Loom and Gillette (Duracell).
</P>
<P>
   MAKE IT SIMPLE, STUPID
</P>
<P>
   Never mind those complex PCs with their spreadsheets and serial
windows. Most people want a simple gizmo that does the basics: fax,
Web surf and phone, with maybe some TV or music, says Business Week
(March 8).
</P>
<P>
   With that type of consumer demand in mind, manufacturers of
personal computers have a host of new products in their pipelines,
including digital picture frames that display as many as 50 photos
_ even a cell phone that automatically locates the nearest greasy
spoon restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   WHICH MARKET IS YOURS?
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports (March) points out there is no such thing as
the stock market. There are various markets, depending on how they
are defined.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P-500 stock index rose 27 percent last year, for example,
but more than 370 mutual funds posted no better than single-digit
gains and another 668 lost money.
</P>
<P>
   This makes fund picking all the more important, says the
magazine, since ``all of the elements that made the past year so
unsettling are still in place this year.''
</P>
<P>
   CLICHES FOR THE MILLENNIUM
</P>
<P>
   The 21st century will solve two big problems, according to
Fortune (March 15).
</P>
<P>
   One is the Y2K computer software dilemma, of course. The other
is the lack of a phrase to replace the cliche ``as we approach the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   This is no small problem because, being a cliche, the phrase of
choice will be used repeatedly by pundits, politicians and press.
The phrase appeared in 277 news reports in 1998 alone, and is
destined to top that by a wide margin in 1999, says Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   In just the first two weeks, the phrase appeared in 1,335 news
stories _ including 275 articles that were about President Clinton
or quoted him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
