A6784 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHECKFREE04-COX     03-03 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECKFREE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intuit sues CheckFree in spite of 20% stake
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Intuit, the Silicon Valley-based maker of personal
finance software, has sued Norcross-based CheckFree, a company in
which Intuit owns a 20 percent stake, alleging CheckFree is not
complying with the terms of an April 1998 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountain View, Calif., company seeks an injunction and
unspecified damages. Neither company would outline the areas of
disagreement late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree spokeswoman Laurinda Wilson said no one at CheckFree
has seen a copy of the lawsuit and therefore could not comment.
Intuit declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree's stock dropped 8.7 percent on news of the lawsuit,
closing at $35.50, down $3.37 1/2. With its 20 percent stake in
CheckFree, Intuit took a $33.8 million paper loss Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the agreement in question, CheckFree said it would provide
electronic bill paying and bill presenting for users of Intuit's
Quicken software and for visitors to http://www.quicken.com.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, Intuit alleges CheckFree agreed to offer those
services to Intuit customers and ``not to offer Web-based bill
presentment products of its own in certain distribution channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Intuit officials, who filed the suit in the Superior Court of
Santa Clara County, Calif., Wednesday, would not say which
distribution channels it referred to in its lawsuit. But CheckFree
announced in January that it had signed a contract with a
high-traffic Internet portal. The agreement would let the portal
offer its visitors the ability to get and pay their bills online.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree has not announced who the portal is, but Avivah Litan,
an analyst with the Gartner Group, said it was Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   Gary Craft, an analyst who covers CheckFree for BancBoston
Roberston Stephens, said the suit is a reflection of CheckFree's
important role in bill presentment and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intuit is shooting themselves in the foot,'' Craft said.
``Intuit is really trying to prevent the competition from getting a
leg up in bill presentment and they're using CheckFree. Apparently
they care less about their CheckFree shares than about their
leadership position in bill presentment.''
</P>
<P>
   Intuit makes and sells two popular software products, Quicken
and TurboTax, which let people handle their finances and taxes
using a PC. CheckFree processes electronic payments. The company,
based on East Jones Bridge Road, also leads a handful of companies
trying to make the Web the place where people get and pay their
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
