A6785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEARCH-TRIANGLE04-C     03-03 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-TRIANGLE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impact study confirmation for Research Triangle Park
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. _ In its 40 years, the Research
Triangle Park has attracted tens of thousands of jobs to North
Carolina like bugs to a high-tech light bulb, a study released
Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for the 6,900-acre park between Raleigh, Durham
and Chapel Hill, it's unlikely that companies employing an
estimated 48,500 people would have started operations in central
North Carolina, according to the economic impact study commissioned
the park's developer.
</P>
<P>
   Recognized for years as one of the South's leading technology
hubs, the Research Triangle Park is touting the study's findings as
further proof that it deserves ranking with Silicon Valley and
Boston's Route 128 corridor as one of the nation's top science and
technology centers.
</P>
<P>
   The study by Silver Spring, Md.-based consulting firm Hammer,
Siler, George Associates largely ignored the Research Triangle's
problems, such as worsening traffic caused by the region's rapid
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1958 at the urging of Gov. Luther Hodges and
other North Carolina leaders seeking to end the state's dependence
on textiles, tobacco and furniture, the park has emerged as a model
of government, academic and private-sector cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that nearly 90 percent of the park's tenants
have formal or informal relationships with regional universities,
including Duke University in Durham, the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill and North Carolina State University in
Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   In counties surrounding the park, companies have invested more
than $300 million in technology-related manufacturing plants in the
1990s, the study said. The park also has spurred the start-up of
more than 200 technology companies since 1970, representing more
than 13,900 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accelerated economy of the state is directly attributable
to the Research Triangle Park,'' said retired University of North
Carolina President William Friday, one of numerous state officials
who participated in the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many large businesses and small, both in the park and
elsewhere, are in the state because of the Research Triangle Park
...''
</P>
<P>
   The Research Triangle Foundation, the park's developer, released
the report at a symposium celebrating the park's 40th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, officials of firms representing 84 percent of the
park's employees were asked to judge whether their companies were
likely, unlikely or very unlikely to have located in the region if
the park were not in existence.
</P>
<P>
   Firms representing 97 percent of the employees responded
unlikely or very unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that all of the park's tenants share that view, the
study said more than 38,800 regular employees and more than 9,700
contract employees ``would not be in the region if not for the
park.''
</P>
<P>
   The study estimated that more than 25,000 other people work in
technology-related office parks near the Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER FINDINGS:
</P>
<P>
   _ The park has 98 tenants, including research companies and
government labs, which employ 39,500 people on a regular, full-time
basis and another 10,000 under contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average pay per employee is $54,145 a year, resulting in
total park payroll of $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 45 percent of the employees in the park are
scientists or engineers, followed by managers and administrators,
skilled technicians and clerical workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Approximately 2.5 million square feet of space is under
construction and 15.4 million square feet is already occupied by
offices and labs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
