<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-EDUCATION-BOS &LR;      03-03 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS UNION HITS EDUCATION CHAIRMAN CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Governor Paul Cellucci's choice to replace John R.
Silber as education chairman came under heavy fire from the state's
largest teachers union Wednesday, evidence that while the acrimony
surrounding Silber may abate, the battle over the course of
education reform will continue.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Silber offered to quit to end a deadlock over
selection of a new education commissioner, Cellucci accepted and
said he will appoint James Peyser to replace Silber. Cellucci added
he will support David Driscoll as the next commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci dismissed suggestions that the deal marked a serious
political setback for him because he wanted Peyser, not Driscoll,
in the commissioner's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man I wanted is now the chair of the commission,''
Cellucci told reporters. ``He is a change agent... and he is the
boss of the man who did get the job.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Cellucci put the best face on the deal, the state's
largest teachers union immediately took aim at Peyser, 42,
executive director of the Pioneer Institute, a conservative think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gorrie, president of the Massachusetts Teachers
Assocation, said his union had serious concerns about Peyser
because of his advocacy of vouchers and privatization that the
union claims would damage public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon his past philosophies and current philosophies, he
tends to lean toward toward privatization, vouchers, and those
things which would be detrimental to public education,'' Gorrie
said.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Peyser: ``I am an optimist by nature. Until it doesn't
work out, I am prepared to try.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the board of education, an unpaid post, is
appointed by the governor and oversees the nine-member board as it
sets statewide education policy and regulations. The commissioner,
a full-time post selected by the board, implements them.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll, 55, currently the interim commissioner, praised the
compromise that will allow him to keep his post on a permanent
basis. He disputed suggestions _ offered previously by Cellucci and
Silber _ that he is too tied into the education establishment to
push an overhaul of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and I are both change agents and I am willing to work with
him in making them,'' Driscoll said, referring to Peyser. ``I just
believe change has to be made in a way that is understandable to
the field and it has to be done after a good discussion. But we do
need to make dramatic changes in the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cellucci praised Silber, whose confrontational style
had created acrimony and tension on the board even as he shared the
governor's push to reform the state education system. ``I have only
come here to praise Dr. Silber,'' the governor said, adding his
resignation was a ``remarkable'' act. ``It's not something we often
see in public life.''
</P>
<P>
   The board had been at impasse since last week when Driscoll
received five of the necessary six votes to become commissioner,
while Peyser got four votes. Top Cellucci aides believed the
controversial Boston University chancellor had so alienated several
administraton-appointed board members that the governor stood no
chance of getting Peyser the post.
</P>
<P>
   Silber said he felt obligated to resign because it became clear
it was the only way to break the impasse. He also brushed aside
suggestions that his brusque style of leadership had led to the
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a neat way to make it look like I was the problem,''
Silber said. Then referring to his nemeses on the board, Abigail
Thernstrom and Roberta Schafer, he said, ``They were the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Silber said Cellucci had told him he did not want his
resignation, but wanted the two women to resign. But because they
would not, Silber said he felt obligated to remove himself.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the compromise that reconfigured the board and
elected a new commissioner will restore calm to the debate over the
state's education agenda is not clear. Peyser, while saying he
would try to work with the unions and the education establishment,
adopted a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the union leadership has had some negative things to
say about me from time to time, but I am operating on the
assumption that they have a good faith interest in improving
student achievement and given that, we have something to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he faulted the union leadership for its fierce opposition
to charter schools _ publicly funded schools that operate with
considerable autonomy from the regular school system _ which the
Pioneer Institute has advocated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have made, at a minimum, some tactical mistakes
in opposing things like charter schools,'' he said. ``Among other
things, charter schools provide career opportunities for teachers.
That should be something the teachers endorse, but I am not
expecting miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   On another issue that has aroused the ire of the teachers
unions, Peyser said he remains an advocate of vouchers _ using
public money to let students attend private schools _ but noted
that issue would require constitutional change before vouchers
could be legal in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Peyser said vouchers ``are not going to be my leading
priority by any stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorrie made it clear that the MTA strongly favored Driscoll,
saying the educator understands the needs of the state's public
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``To characterize him as someone who is not a strong change
agent is... incorrect. He has the experience, the expertise, and
the energy to lead the educational force,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if both the union leadership and Peyser seemed tentative,
Thernstrom, who supported Driscoll for commissioner, said she
thought the new arrangement would work well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues that upset teachers about Jim Peyser are not Board
of Education issues, they are legislative issues,'' she said,
citing both vouchers and Cellucci's proposal to test veteran
teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
