u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      03-03 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ HEADED FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Pending the passage of a routine physical
that has nothing to do with his surgically repaired right shoulder,
pitcher Ramon Martinez will officially become a member of the Red
Sox early next week and be reunited with his younger brother Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Red Sox have suggested it may be July before he is
ready to pitch, Ramon Martinez says it could be much sooner,
perhaps as early as May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be sometime around May, the way everything is
going,'' Martinez said Wednesday from his home in Santo Domingo,
where he was working out after throwing off a mound for the first
time since his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty soon, I'll be throwing batting practice. Everything is
going well. I don't want to rush it, but I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox and Martinez, according to sources, have agreed to a
two-year contract, with an option for a third year, that is laden
with performance incentives based largely on innings pitched and
games started. Further details of the deal have not been disclosed,
but officials with other clubs have said Red Sox general manager
Dan Duquette was able to complete the deal by guaranteeing millions
to the righthander who turns 31 March 22. One source said the deal
included close to $8 million in guaranteed money, but neither side
would confirm numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is expected to arrive here Sunday night and undergo a
physical soon thereafter. He said he wanted to speak with Duquette
about where he will continue his rehabilitation, but he would
prefer to return to the Dominican Republic, where he has been
working with the same pitching coach, Eleodoro Arias, he has known
since signing with the Los Angeles Dodgers in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dan wants me to stay, I'll stay,'' Martinez said, ``but
maybe I could work out something where I would go home, then come
back here every two weeks. It's up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he had not yet spoken to his younger brother, but
intended to call him Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's healthy, he can help out a lot,'' Pedro Martinez said.
``To me, it's a great move. I feel happy my brother will be here,
and my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez became a free agent after the Dodgers, for whom
he had won 126 games in 11 seasons, did not exercise the $5.6
million option the team held for the 1999 season. Those
knowledgeable about his deal with the Red Sox say Martinez could
earn significantly more than that next year.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez underwent surgery on his shoulder last June 30 to
repair a hole in his rotator cuff and clean out some cartilage in
his shoulder. Unlike similar procedures, which are done with an
arthroscope, a much less invasive procedure, Martinez had an ``open
cuff'' operation, which involved the use of a scalpel to repair the
hole.
</P>
<P>
   But Duquette, no doubt encouraged by the successful comeback of
Bret Saberhagen from radical shoulder reconstruction, was willing
to take a risk and guarantee Martinez a much better deal than he
would have received from LA.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers made an attempt this winter to re-sign him, offering
him an incentive-laded contract worth about $6 million this season,
but according to Martinez, less than $1 million was guaranteed. He
would have received bonuses for being placed on the big-league
roster, innings pitched, starts, and victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to miss Ramon as an organization and as people
because Ramon represents everything that's good about the
Dodgers,'' Los Angeles general manager Kevin Malone told reporters
Wednesday at the team's training facility in Vero Beach, Fla.
``We're very happy for him, happy that he felt comfortable he could
make this decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt we were willing to assume a lot of the risk, but
we felt we couldn't assume all of the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pedro Martinez lashed out at the Dodgers earlier this week
for the way they approached his brother, Ramon was more measured in
his words, saying he was ``a little bit disappointed.'' He said
that while the Dodgers had watched him throw when he was in LA at
the end of January, they have not seen him since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I decided to become a free agent, they didn't make any
offer until a week ago,'' Ramon Martinez said. ``It was like they
were not interested in me. (The offer) they made was something just
to make an offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he was throwing 88 miles an hour off a flat
surface earlier this week and believed he threw nearly as hard
Wednesday, even though his physical therapist had advised he back
off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinez brothers played together in Los Angeles for the
1992 and '93 seasons until Pedro was traded to the Montreal Expos.
At that time, Ramon was considered the ace of the Dodgers staff,
though he had his worst two seasons professionally, going 8-11 and
10-12 after having won 37 games the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez, meanwhile, was used almost exclusively in relief
by the Dodgers. If Ramon is successful in his comeback, he would be
in the same rotation as his brother for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, who is 3 years and 7 months older than Pedro, is
very much the same type of pitcher, according to his younger
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same, except I throw a curveball and he throws a
slider,'' Pedro Martinez said. ``Same velocity, same changeup. His
fastball moves more than mine.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen, of course, how Martinez's velocity will
be affected by the surgery. But if healthy, his presence in the Sox
rotation would give the club two Cy Young Award winners (Pedro
Martinez and Saberhagen twice), a World Series MVP (Saberhagen) and
two 20-game winners (Ramon Martinez and Saberhagen twice). Ramon
Martinez and Saberhagen both have thrown no-hitters, and Pedro
Martinez pitched nine perfect innings before giving up a hit in the
10th in San Diego. Ramon Martinez also has struck out 18 batters in
a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy because now we're going to play together
again,'' Ramon Martinez said. ``I'm glad we have a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But while they may be similar pitchers, Pedro Martinez warns not
to expect the same person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very aggressive,'' Pedro Martinez said. ``Ramon is a
cold-blooded man, very quiet on the mound. I'm not. I'm moody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon, he'll say hello, how are you, and give you an interview
if you ask him. But he's like, `I'm not going to be a brat like
Pedro.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, in other words, would not be caught dead wearing
a Yoda mask in the dugout, as his younger brother did last season.
``I don't think he would have allowed me to do that if he had been
here,'' Pedro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
