   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-NY (New York) _ In a speech that many Democrats view
as a strong indication that Hillary Rodham Clinton will run for the
Senate from New York, the first lady proclaims her commitment to
government and politics before some of her most passionate
supporters, New York Democratic women, in a packed and enthusiastic
ballroom of the Plaza Hotel. By Elisabeth Bumiller. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABLED (Washington) _ Students with disabilities who
require special care during the school day are entitled to that
care at public expense, the Supreme Court rules, as long as the
services can be provided by someone other than a doctor. The 7-2
decision upholds lower court rulings that required an Iowa school
district to provide a trained aide to monitor the needs of a
quadriplegic boy who was dependent on a ventilator. By Linda
Greenhouse. (The story has moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo reefer to inside story: LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW
(Washington) _ Finally free to seek self-justification and personal
profit, Monica Lewinsky opens a double-fronted campaign. By TV
interview and book publication, she sought to frame a different,
more sympathetic image of herself as a venturesome romantic who
meant well but became ensnared in the criminal investigation of the
president's misbehavior. By Francis X. Clines and Frank Bruni.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebar: LEWINSKY-MEDIA by television critic Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   GERIATRIC-CARE (Newport Beach, Calif.) _ Geriatric care
managers: an occupation born in response to the nation's rapidly
aging population and the health care system's complexity. Part
counselors and part social workers, they help manage the health
care, living arrangements and other affairs of their elderly
clients. They perform a role once filled by families _ not only
because families have become so scattered and care has become more
complicated, but also because outsiders are listened to, while
children often are not. By Sara Rimer. (The story has moved in
``a'' news file.) With photo. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ The past, present and future of
PRI, the governing party, is at the center of a tremendous debate
here this week, as President Ernesto Zedillo and some 2,000 party
stalwarts prepare to celebrate the party's 70th anniversary. By Sam
Dillon. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEMS (Washington) _ Under a campaign-style blue banner,
President Clinton rallies with congressional Democrats to show
party unity on a legislative agenda that would reserve more than
three-quarters of federal budget surpluses for Social Security and
Medicare. By Alison Mitchell. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., America's
last big private investment bank, will go public by early summer _
barring a repeat of the stock market slump that undid its carefully
laid plans last fall. The partners who own the firm will not vote
formally on the share offering until this weekend, but little
opposition is expected. By Joseph Kahn. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-CHIP-DRAWINGS (Undated) _ Drawings found on silicon chips:
Waldo lurks in the processor. By Bruce Headlam. (The story has
moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-SPRINGFIELD (Undated) _ Dusty Springfield, the smoky-voiced
English torch singer whose interpretations of pop ballads were
suffused with a heartbroken wistfulness, died Tuesday at her home
in Henley-on-Thames, near Oxford, west of London. She was 59. The
cause was breast cancer. By Stephen Holden. (The obit has moved in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
