<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC--TEX     03-03 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking Down Barriers''
</P>
<P>
   By Dwight Perry
</P>
<P>
   Baker Books, $12.99
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gospel in Black &AMP; White''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Dennis L. Okholm
</P>
<P>
   InterVarsity Press, $15.99
</P>
<P>
   There are times in every life when ``Just shut up and listen''
is good advice. For the lighter-skinned among us, the time spent
reading ``Breaking Down Barriers'' and ``The Gospel in Black &AMP;
White'' may be one such occasion. Not that the authors would phrase
it anywhere near that bluntly, and not that one needs to agree with
all their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The subtitle of Dwight Perry's book is ``A Black Evangelical
Explains the Black Church,'' and the Moody Bible Institute
professor does just that. ``Breaking Down Barriers'' scans
African-American history, black denominations and ministries, music
and preaching styles, and the civil rights era. One area that may
spark discussion: Perry's definitions of ``racism'' and
``institutional racism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking Down Barriers'' is an easy-to-read primer for those
who are unacquainted with black spirituality and its history. ``The
Gospel in Black &AMP; White'' is noticeably different in tone; as a
series of essays originally presented at a 1996 Wheaton College
theology conference, it has a more academic flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Editor Dennis L. Okholm presents the work of 10 writers, among
them Pamela Baker Powell, a white minister at a small black
congregation in Lubbock, Texas. The topics range from how the
concept of the Trinity should encourage racial reconciliation to
how dispensational premillennialism can impede it (something
certain to raise many evangelical eyebrows). The styles include
Eugene Rivers' fiery ``The Responsibility of Evangelical
Intellectuals in the Age of White Supremacy'' and Vincent Bacote's
straightforward ``Theological Method in Black &AMP; White: Does Race
Matter at All?''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part,'' Craig S. Keener says, ``white
evangelicals have not listened to the perspectives of black church
leaders on issues that often affect the black church directly. Is
the coercive power of a voting majority that ignores minority
concerns less oppressive in principle than slaveholders who imposed
their will on slaves?''
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that both ways, but listening to these authors
is definitely educational.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by ALAN COCHRUM
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
