<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-EDUC-580&AMP;ADD     03-03 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-EDUC-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TAKES PARTISAN TURN ON EDUCATION LEGISLATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Tenn., Conn., Vt., Minn.)   (Eds: See also CLINTON-DEMS)  
 (rk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ Eager to show that education is foremost on their
minds, Senate Democrats and Republicans began a debate on federal
education policy Wednesday that they hope will resonate with voters
weary of impeachment and partisan warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, intending to
diminish negative reviews on the Republicans' handling of the
impeachment trial, made it a point to bring Wednesday's education
bill to the floor as one of his first orders of business.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has little real opposition, would give schools
more flexibility over $10 billion in federal aid by permitting
states to waive certain federal requirements. The pilot program is
already in effect in 12 states and would be expanded to all 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe parents, teachers and local education officials know
best what's needed locally, and this bill gives them the ability to
meet their area's individual needs,'' said Sen. Bill Frist,
R-Tenn., who co-sponsored the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But, to the Republicans' chagrin, Democrats turned the Senate's
consideration of the relatively uncontroversial ``Ed-Flex'' bill
Wednesday into a lengthier debate showcasing one of their prized
proposals, a plan to reduce class sizes by hiring 100,000 teachers,
which they will propose as an amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are important issues to people across the country,''
Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., said from the floor. ``How many
teachers are in the room? How well educated are they?''
</P>
<P>
   With a close eye on the 2000 political campaign, Republicans and
Democrats in Congress are already jockeying to seize the education
issue as their own; Democrats have traditionally won that argument
by emphasizing public school dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, though, are anxious to make up lost ground on
education and soften negative public reviews of their impeachment
performance by making education an immediate priority.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete V. Domenici, the Republican chairman of the Budget
Committee, is considering a 40 percent increase in the federal
education budget over the next five years, a major turnabout from
four years ago when Republicans sought to abolish the Department of
Education. Federal dollars now make up about 6 percent of the money
spent on elementary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Domenici and other Republicans are not likely to drop
their desire to reduce the role of the federal government in
education by giving school districts greater local control,
especially through block grants. And they will continue to pursue
ways to funnel taxpayer money to private and parochial schools or
allow parents to use tax savings for tuition, if they choose, an
idea widely reviled by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans also know they must compromise to get important
education legislation passed this year, especially in the House,
where they hold a slim six-vote margin.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ``Ed-Flex'' bill, sponsored by Frist and Ron Wyden,
D-Ore, is widely supported by lawmakers in both parties, all 50
governors and, with certain caveats, President Clinton. A House
committee voted out a nearly identical bill Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By allowing states to waive certain requirements, the
legislation would loosen restrictions on how $10 billion in federal
money, most of it designated for poor children, can be spent, so
long as schools show improvement. Federal money earmarked for
specific programs, under the new measure, could be spent for other
purposes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It would be a gross overstatement to suggest that this bill
will revolutionize education,'' said Sen. James M. Jeffords, R-Vt.,
the chairman of the committee on health, education and labor, who
called it a ``sensible step'' in stretching federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The senators said the bill would hold school districts
responsible for improving academic performance, a major concern of
Democrats. Late Tuesday night, the Senate approved one Democratic
amendment aimed at beefing up accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also argued they would prefer to await the results of
a study on the pilot program, due out later this year, before
voting to expand it. Last year, the General Accounting Office gave
the program mixed reviews, concluding it was modestly successful
overall. And Democrats expressed concern about whether poor
children would be shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have they used this ``Ed-Flex'' to improve the opportunity for
poor children?'' asked Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. ``We don't
know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-AIRWAR-NYT &LR;      03-03 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-AIRWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND BRITAIN COME UNDER PRESSURE TO END AIR WAR OVER IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Turkey on Wednesday criticized the air war over
Iraq and declared that the American strike that disrupted a
pipeline to Turkey this week was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, China told a closed session of the
Security Council that all bombardments over Iraq must end,
according to diplomats. And over the weekend, the Arab League
reversed its policy enunciated in January and called on the United
States and Britain to stop the bombing immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Flow from the pipeline resumed on Wednesday, the United Nations
said. But with the souring of the international mood, it was no
accident that the skies over Iraq were quiet on Wednesday, one
allied diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   While many of those countries, as well as France and Russia,
have raised sharp questions about the air war, they seem to have
become more outspoken in their criticism since the American bombing
of a communications station for the Kirkuk to Ceyhan pipeline on
Sunday. That pipeline carries oil to the Mediterranean coast of
Turkey, where it is then sold as part of the United Nations oil for
food program for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is a close ally of the United States and lets American
planes carry out raids from bases in Turkey. But the Pentagon said
that the furor would not lead to any changes in its rules of
engagement that were widened at the end of January to allow
American pilots to hit anything that threatened their ability to
patrol the no-flight zones in northern and southern Iraq. The
United States created those zones after the Persian Gulf war ended
in 1991 to protect the Kurds and Shiite Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   President Saddam Hussein of Iraq began challenging British and
American jets patrolling those zones in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our view that nothing has changed except that Saddam
Hussein has repeatedly been challenging our enforcement of the
no-flight zone,'' said James Foley, deputy State Department
spokesman. ``We targeted these facilities because we believe that
they serve a function in the operation of Iraq's air defense
system.''
</P>
<P>
   While Britain remains a solid ally in patrolling the zones,
Prime Minister Tony Blair on Wednesday did call the bombing that
disrupted the pipeline a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But Foley said the United States does not intentionally target
the pipeline and other systems associated with the oil for food
program.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Security Council was given the damage
assessment done by the United Nations independent inspection agents
who visited the pipeline station on Monday. The damages temporarily
disrupted the pipeline from Kirkuk to Ceyhan that carries half the
oil Iraq is permitted to export under the oil for food program.
</P>
<P>
   British and American officials say that Saddam has been moving
antiaircraft artillery pieces and surface-to-air missiles near
population centers, antiquities and other sensitive locations,
making it difficult for pilots to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saddam is playing games and becoming more sophisticated at how
to play these angles,'' said a Pentagon official. ``That repeater
station was relaying radar data for the Iraqi air-defense system
and the strike against it was done in pure self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arab League on Sunday called for an immediate halt of the
allied bombing because of ``great disquiet'' over the ``loss of
life, destruction of infrastructure and an increase in tension in
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese request for a halt in the bombing was made at a
private session at the United Nations. Diplomats said that Russia
and other member countries agreed with China, citing humanitarian
grounds.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One allied diplomat said on Wednesday: ``There has been a
pile-on effect these last few days. There has to be a balance
between protecting pilots and not falling into one of Saddam's
traps. But given the number of bombs dropped over the last five
days, it's surprising things have gone bad only once.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
