<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRTY-CAR-FACTORIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP REPORTS NO LINK BETWEEN FUEL-EFFICIENT CARS AND NONPOLLUTING
FACTORIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Ill.)   (rk) 
 By   CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For environmentalists in the market for a new car,
the choice is not an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Council on Economic Priorities, an
environmental group based in New York, car buyers face a
rock-and-a-hard-place choice: They can buy cars that were made in
nonpolluting plants or cars that run clean themselves, but they
cannot do both.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released Wednesday, the council lauds the fuel
efficiency, and thus environmental cleanliness, of the Honda Civic
and Mitsubishi Mirage. But it criticizes Honda &UR;  &LR; of America
Manufacturing and Mitsubishi Motor &UR;  &LR; Manufacturing of America for
the high levels of pollutants spewing out of the Ohio and Illinois
plants where the cars are made.
</P>
<P>
   It cites the Chrysler Jeep Grand Cherokee as a gas guzzler, even
when compared with other sport utility vehicles. But it praises the
Toledo plant where the Cherokee is made as one of the cleanest
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the most polluting cars are made at the
least-polluting facilities, while the clean cars are coming out of
dirty plants,'' said Romi Chin Gottfrid, an environmental research
associate at the council.
</P>
<P>
   None of the plants mentioned in the study are flagrant violators
of state or federal environmental regulations. A spokeswoman for
the Environmental Protection Agency, while acknowledging the
``irony that sometimes clean products come from dirty facilities,''
indicated that the agency was not particularly incensed by the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gottfrid responded, ``Regulators should be holding these
companies to a higher standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, none of the companies are apologizing. ``We've
taken proactive action to minimize environmental impact,'' said a
Mitsubishi spokeswoman, who added that ``the council's data is
incomplete.'' Ron Lietzke, a spokesman for Honda of America, said
that Honda's four Ohio plants were recently certified as
environmentally sound by the International Organization for
Standardization in Geneva. ``We have continuous, active efforts
going to reduce our emissions, waste and use of natural
resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler &UR;  &LR; AG, which makes the Jeep Grand Cherokee,
meanwhile, is focusing on the praise. ``We're very pleased that our
employees' efforts to address environmental performance have been
recognized,'' said Sonja Bultynck, an environmental spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   And about that nagging fuel efficiency problem? ``Well, the 1999
Cherokee is 7 percent more fuel efficient than the 1998 model,''
she said.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
