A6815 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     03-03 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS SERVED UP AT THE COOKING TABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some time ago, while watching an episode of ``Family Matters,''
my daughters witnessed Steve Urkel making a fool of himself once
again trying to win the affection of his love interest, this time
taking the girl to dinner at a Japanese restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lovely little story, but what held my daughters'
attention was the dreaded cooking table. And they couldn't seem to
forget it.
</P>
<P>
   For months, they nagged me to take them to a restaurant ``where
they cook the food at your table.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday night, on Asha's eighth birthday, I was obliged to
make that happen, partly because I enjoy watching them partake of
new experiences _ and partly due to guilt.
</P>
<P>
   You see, I'd told a colleague that I was trying desperately to
put together one more double birthday party to try to cut down on
expenses. But it wasn't just the expense. I have yet to sponsor one
of these ventures when the noise level wasn't so, well ...
overwhelming, the movement not so constant.
</P>
<P>
   I'm over 40. It makes me crazy.
</P>
<P>
   But my colleague said to me, ``Poor kids are going to grow up
dysfunctional because they've never had their very own birthday
party.''
</P>
<P>
   I smiled, trying to receive her comment in the spirit in which
it was delivered, but the knife had already pierced my flesh, or my
heart.
</P>
<P>
   I explained to her that their father and I make a point of
acknowledging each of their birthdays but that because they are so
close together, we have one BIG celebration.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, on Asha's birthday, Jimmy prepared pancakes, her
favorite, with eight candles on top. And all of us _ Jimmy, Jamila
and I _ sang ``Happy Birthday'' to the tune of Stevie Wonder's
``Happy Birthday,'' sans the Martin Luther King Jr. lyrics, of
course. Then they ate, and Asha opened one of her gifts. We will do
the same thing Thursday, Jamila's 10th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Back to that first excursion to the Japanese cooking table.
</P>
<P>
   Five us _ we invited my niece, Jasmine _ arrived at the
restaurant around 6:30 p.m. It took us 30 minutes to decide what to
eat. Jamila and Jasmine wanted shrimp, Asha and I took the chicken
and Jimmy, the unhealthful red meat. I know better than to say
``cow.'' I can't afford the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about nothing until the cook showed up with platters
of meat and vegetables, and the show began. Soup came first. I
drank mine. Jamila sipped a little. The others sniffed, frowned and
replaced the bowls on the table. The same thing happened with the
salad, and the eggplant, and the bean sprouts, and the grilled
onions and green peppers.
</P>
<P>
   I hate to see food go to waste, money go down the drain. I was
disgusted with their unwillingness to try the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   They ate their meat and bowls of ice cream. We went home. They
were hungry. I was stuffed.
</P>
<P>
   As I thought about it later, I wondered which of those
experiences is more likely to render my daughters dysfunctional
adults: having one BIG birthday celebration, or having me give in
to their every whim.
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting on the latter.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
