<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-VS-PEROT04-COX     03-03 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VS-PEROT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perot run could stir feud with Bushes
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Leaders in Ross Perot's Reform Party said
Wednesday they hope their party's godfather makes a third run for
president, a move that could lead to a revival of one of the better
political family feuds of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In private, the Bush family still blames Perot's third-party
candidacy in 1992 for the ouster of President George Bush. In
public, Barbara Bush has been highly critical of Perot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What an amazing, insensitive man!'' the mother of Gov. George
W. Bush, a front-runner for the GOP presidential nomination in
2000, wrote of Perot in her 1994 memoir.
</P>
<P>
   At the Reform Party's national headquarters in Dallas, where the
phones are still answered with an earnest ``Perot '96,'' Chairman
Russell Verney said Wednesday he ``absolutely'' wants Perot to run
again next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a decision he will have to make,'' Verney said. ``He
has given no indication one way or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot did not respond to a written request for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Verney would offer no opinion on George W. Bush's probable
presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even thought about him. We are looking at people
outside the Republican and Democratic parties,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeanne Droogs of Fort Worth, the Reform Party's state
chairwoman, has thought about Bush and doesn't think much of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has really dumped on us,'' she said. ``He is going to spend
the rest of his time going out while he is supposed to be our
governor, and leaving us in the lurch. This is very immature in my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said being governor will be his priority through the
end of the legislative session on May 31. Droogs said she is not
impressed with Bush's performance as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean this to be insulting to him, but I don't know
what he has accomplished,'' she said. ``Please do not think I'm
doing this out of any animosity. I'm looking from an analytical
viewpoint. He is a popular man because he does have charm.
President Clinton has charm.''
</P>
<P>
   Droogs indicated that Perot is her top choice for the Reform
Party nomination in 2000 unless she comes across ``somebody
better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Mr. Perot's sake, I would prefer someone of his caliber
coming forward,'' she said. ``If I don't see anyone better, why
should I support them?''
</P>
<P>
   Perot has been mum on whether he is interested in another
presidential race. Last November, he said he would not run next
year if Clinton resigned. Perot organized a petition drive urging
Clinton to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Though Reform Party officials cite studies showing Perot drew
equally from Clinton and Bush in 1992, Bush family members still
think Perot's candidacy took a more severe toll on the
then-president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when Clinton won with 43 percent of the popular vote to
37 percent for the elder Bush, Perot ran third with 19 percent, but
got no electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Perot pulled only 8 percent of the popular vote when
Clinton trounced Republican Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bush-Perot relationship has been a rocky one, the
Texas governor has a new friend in Perot's party. The younger Bush
shared the spotlight with Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, the Reform
Party's only statewide elected official, at the National Governors
Association meeting in Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bonded with The Body,'' Bush said joking about the former
pro wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Though his party's new star, Ventura has said he would complete
his four-year gubernatorial term and not run for president next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
