<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA LEWINSKY TELLS HER SIDE OF THE STORY, IN PRINT AND ON
TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also LEWINSKY-MEDIA) 
(fe) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES and FRANK BRUNI 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finally free to seek self-justification and
personal profit, Monica Lewinsky opened a double-fronted campaign
on Wednesday to explain the sexual affair that triggered the
impeachment of President Clinton and put the nation through a
harrowing year of scandal tracking.
</P>
<P>
   By television interview and book publication, the former White
House intern sought to frame a different, more sympathetic image of
herself as a venturesome romantic who meant well but became
ensnared in the criminal investigation of the president's
misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a pawn used to get the president,'' she said in the
book, ``Monica's Story'' (St. Martin's Press), written by Andrew
Morton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's sorry he got caught,'' Ms. Lewinsky said of the
president in the ABC-TV interview. But, ever hesitating to fully
renounce him, she added that ``when I think of the person I thought
Bill Clinton was, he had genuine remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview, with Barbara Walters on ``20-20,'' was one of the
first interrogations conducted without benefit of sworn oath by the
25-year-old California woman since she was confronted by
prosecutors 13 months ago. Her revelations caused a presidential
crisis in which Clinton finally was acquitted by the Senate last
month of perjury and obstruction of justice charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't dream of asking Chelsea and Mrs. Clinton to forgive
me, but I would ask them to know that I am very sorry for what
happened and for what they've been through,'' Ms. Lewinsky told
Walters in the first of a series of worldwide television and
magazine interviews that, in conjunction with her book, are
expected to garner multimillions of dollars, by the estimates of
her sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, for which ABC increased its commercial rates
for sponsors more than fourfold, Ms. Lewinsky could not discuss her
seven-month struggle to avoid prosecution in exchange for
testifying about the sexual affair. This stricture was made part of
her immunity deal by Kenneth W. Starr, the independent counsel who
investigated the president and recommended impeachment. The Justice
Department now is considering an investigation of the fairness of
Starr's methods _ whether he misled Ms. Lewinsky and the Justice
Department in claiming jurisdiction to branch into the president's
private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's book had no such stricture, however, and it
accuses Starr of ``a level of zealous malevolence.'' It endorses
Hillary Rodham Clinton's denouncement of Starr as a ``politically
motivated prosecutor,'' part of the ``vast right-wing conspiracy''
Mrs. Clinton has alleged.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are sentiments with which Monica, in the front line of
the war, entirely agrees,'' Morton writes.
</P>
<P>
   The account that the book gives of her relationship with the
president dovetails almost precisely with the one given by the
Starr report, although there are a few new details.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking is Ms. Lewinsky's revelation that during a lull in
the affair, she briefly dated a Pentagon employee, became pregnant
and had an abortion, which plunged her into depression and, at her
mother's urgings, sent her into psychotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   But what the Starr report obviously did not cover, and the book
explores in bracing and precise detail, is Ms. Lewinsky's treatment
by Starr, his deputies and investigators _ and the feelings she now
holds toward the independent counsel, a man who could still subject
to her criminal prosecution under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ```During his investigation,'' the book declares, ``Kenneth
Starr had not once met Monica Lewinsky, and yet she felt that he
had defiled and molested her _ not physically, but by using his
legal and constitutional power to strip away every last vestige of
her dignity and her humanity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
