<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BC-SYRACUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG BC TEAM TROUNCED BY SYRACUSE, 96-55 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It went down as the worst conference loss of the
worst season in the annals of Boston College basketball. And while
BC's 96-55 loss Wednesday in the first round of the Big East
tournmanent at Madison Square Garden was the kind of blowout
everyone initially feared would occur on a nightly basis for BC's
young and inexperienced squad, it only proved to be the case
against one conference team this year: The Syracuse Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite preseason prognostications that pegged them to finish
last in the league _ and maybe even as the worst team ever in
conference history _ the Eagles gave an honest acquittal of
themselves by playing all year with extraordinary heart,
scrappiness and fierce determination. Until, that is, the No. 13
seed Eagles (6-21) simply expired with a futile gasp in Wednesday's
41-point loss to the fourth-seeded Orangemen (20-10) that ranked as
the biggest rout in the history of the conference tourney.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the face of that, BC coach Al Skinner saw some
semblance of improvement in his team that all began after a
demoralizing 62-61 nonconference loss to Harvard Nov. 21. ``We went
from being a terrible team after that game, to being just a bad
team,'' Skinner said.
</P>
<P>
   BC's devastating loss to Syracuse was its worst since a 61-point
thrashing against Marshall, 130-69, in the 1955-56 season. It also
matched Providence College's 41-point setback to Georgetown, 85-44,
in 1985 as the league's most lopsided game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what I told the players after the loss this
afternoon is that, unfortunately, this game is not really
reflective on how we performed the last couple months of the
season,'' said Skinner, whose 1998-99 team wound up losing more
games than any other in BC history, but still managed to string
together three consecutive conference home victories over Notre
Dame, Seton Hall and West Virginia. ``So, it's very disappointing
from that standpoint that we really didn't show the way we've
played the last month. I think that's what hurts the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syracuse has played extremely well against us,'' he added.
``They have every time we've played against them and we knew that
we were going to be in for a long afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Eagles were unable to find a solution for the
problematic Etan Thomas, Syracuse's 6-foot-8-inch swatmeister who
was voted the conference's Defensive Player of the Year. Thomas who
led the Orangemen with 19 points on 8-for-13 shooting and helped
Syracuse dominate the boards, 52-23, by grabbing 9 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   In Syracuse's three convincing victories over BC this season _
all by a combined margin of 97 points _ Thomas scored 58 points,
grabbed 23 rebounds and blocked 9 shots in 65 minutes of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are just matchups with certain teams and Boston
College has just had trouble with us inside this year,'' said
Syracuse coach Jim Boeheim, whose team established a tourney record
not only for scoring margin (erasing the 33-point romp, 103-70, the
Orangemen suffered in the 1993 tourney final against Seton Hall)
but also for rebounding margin, surpassing its own mark (28, 54-26)
set against BC in 1986. ``With Etan Thomas, they really have nobody
that can stay with him. I thought today we came out focused. We did
a good job of getting the ball. Our defense was good and we didn't
let them get any open shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're just bigger and strong than them.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident by the way Syracuse went opened the game
with a 12-0 run, before allowing BC to get on the board on Michael
Cotton's 3-pointer with 16:48 to go. By the 8:27 mark, Syracuse
controlled a 25-8 lead. At that juncture, Jason Hart, who had 11 of
his 15 total points, and Thomas, who had 9,each had outscored the
Eagles, single-handedly. By halftime, the Orangemen led by 29,
47-18.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Eagles came out and scored 15 points in the first
4:43, they didn't surpass Syracuse's first-half total until 6:47
remained in the game when Willie Deane, who led BC with 14 points
off the bench, hit a 3-pointer. By then, Syracuse controlled a
whopping 37-point lead, 83-46, that wound up growing to 41 by
game's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give them credit for the exceptional game that
they played,'' Skinner said, saluting the Orangemen. ``But the good
thing is that, you know, all my guys are going to be coming back.
We're gong to be spending some time trying to improve ourselves.
But, like I said, the most disappointing thing is that this game
was not reflective on how we've played in the league this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
