<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-2N     03-03 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: her humanity.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In August of last year, when Ms. Lewinsky was still in the midst
of detailing her relationship with the president, Starr wanted to
videotape the session, held away from the grand jury, during which
Ms. Lewinsky recited all of her sexual encounters with the
president, the book reports. ``It would have been the complete and
utter destruction of my soul,'' Ms. Lewinsky tells Morton.
</P>
<P>
   But her lawyers quashed the idea, and Ms. Lewinsky instead
shared the information in a private interview with two female
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ms. Lewinsky tells Morton that the release of the Starr
report, with its exacting sexual details, devastated her. ``I just
felt that the world looked at me as a whore,'' she tells him.
</P>
<P>
   She concludes that Starr cared not a whit about his impact on
her or her family's lives. Her first bitter sense of being his
``pawn'' came on the day when she was detained by Starr's
investigators for more than 10 hours in a hotel in nearby Virginia,
lured there by her erstwhile friend, Linda Tripp, and the book
provides fresh details about the experience.
</P>
<P>
   After Mrs. Tripp handed her over to Starr's investigators ``like
a latter-day Judas,'' the book says, Ms. Lewinsky reeled with
terror and despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if my stomach had been cut open and someone had
poured acid into my wound,'' Ms. Lewinsky tells Morton. She further
says that she looked at Ms. Tripp and ``wanted to hurt her. I felt
like an animal wanting to claw at her skin.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the book, when Ms. Lewinsky was finally allowed a
brief call to her mother, who had been paging her, an FBI agent sat
by her, his finger hovering above the phone, ready to sever the
connection if Ms. Lewinsky revealed where she was and what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   The book asserts that even as Ms. Lewinsky was being threatened
with decades of prison time if she did not cooperate and even as an
investigator was flashing her the handcuffs beneath his jacket, she
strived to warn the president about what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, when she was allowed to go into a bathroom in the
mall near the hotel, she contemplated giving Betty Currie's number
and a set of instructions to a young mother changing her baby's
diapers, but decided against it. Days later, she was still trying
unsuccessfully to get word to Ms. Currie.
</P>
<P>
   The book portrays her _ obviously, in a flattering fashion _ as
a loyal, steadfast protector of the president, who had to rebuff
some of the tactics suggested by one of her initial lawyers,
William H. Ginsburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the car,'' Morton writes, ``he announced that he was going
to state publicly that the president had sexually harassed Monica
and that he was nothing more than a child molester.'' Monica
forbade it and pleaded to be committed to a psychiatric hospital as
a way out of the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   The interview and book gave Ms. Lewinsky, the face that launched
a thousand pundits, a long-awaited and oft-delayed opportunity to
vent some opinions of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Her assessments of Starr, Tripp and even Ginsburg, her lawyer
for several months after she was first approached by Starr's
deputies, are withering; her contempt for these players in her
personal melodrama is untempered and undisguised.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in many respects, ``Monica's Story,'' although written
by Morton in the third person, represents Ms. Lewinsky's attempt to
get even with the people who did her wrong, at least in her
generously lashed eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tripp is treated most harshly, and most snidely, making her
entrance into the narrative of ``Monica's Story'' as a ``lumpy
figure'' draped in a ``dun-brown business suit.'' The book says
that at one point, after being successfully coached through a diet
by Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Tripp could finally avail herself of some of
the larger dresses in what Ms. Lewinsky, whose own weight
fluctuated wildly, dubbed her ``fat closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg is portrayed as a glutton for attention who relished
hobnobbing with the media elite, spoke recklessly, sowed suspicion
and ill will among members of the Lewinsky family as a method for
controlling them and exaggerated his closeness with them.
</P>
<P>
   In the TV interview, Ms. Lewinsky said the ``most difficult''
and pointed question she faced in the long ordeal came from a grand
juror who asked why she has had affairs with married men. ``I know
I will never have an affair with a married man again,'' she
insisted. ``What I've come to see is that that happened because I
didn't have enough feelings of self worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters asked about Ms. Lewinsky's gambit in suddenly flashing
her thong underwear at the president. ``Where do you get that nerve
for that?'' she asked as Ms. Lewinsky laughed and described it as a
``small, subtle, flirtatious gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dance,'' she said. ``I think it was saying, I'm
interested, too. I'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky said her mother sought to break off the
relationship but she stubbornly resisted. ``From the time I was 2
years old,'' she smilingly recounted, ``one of my first phrases was
_ with my hands on my hips: `You are not the boss of me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Confirming she sometimes screamed at Clinton in frustration, she
explained, ``I didn't see him as the president of the United
States. I saw him as a man. And that was how I treated him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My breath was taken away,'' she said of her first sighting of
the president at a routine White House arrival ceremony. ``It was
this man who was full of energy and sensuality and
attractiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the president reacted when she inquired if the affair
was merely sexual, Ms. Lewinsky responded, ``He started to, uh,
tear up and told me that he never wanted me to think that.'' He
said the president, when told of her love, declared, ``That means a
lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the president gave her hope he might some day
marry her, Ms. Lewinsky firmly responded, ``He did. He said, `Well,
I might be alone in three years.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She described White House officials who finally transferred her
away from the president to the Pentagon as ``the meanies.'' ``I
don't think that my relationship hurt the job he was doing,'' she
maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I have warm feelings, sometimes I'm proud of him
still, and sometimes I hate his guts,'' she told Walters. ``And,
um, he makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the book, Ms. Lewinsky cried when she signed an
immunity deal to testify about her affair because she did not want
to hurt the president. But her feelings subsequently grew more
complicated and there were times she resented Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered how I could have ever cared about this man,'' Ms.
Lewinsky tells Morton. ``He was so self-righteous and
self-centered.''
</P>
<P>
   The book endeavors, in some fashion, to provide a psychological
deconstruction of Ms. Lewinsky and how she fell into an affair with
the president. As a child, it recounts, she sometimes wore a
T-shirt that said ``Daddy's Little Girl'' but was estranged from
her father after he and her mother divorced.
</P>
<P>
   The book's leitmotifs seem to be crying and dieting. Ms.
Lewinsky sheds tears just about every four paragraphs and filters
every episode through her weight at the moment. She even recalls
that the first time the president removed his shirt in front of
her, he sucked in his stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will you tell your children, when you have them?'' she
was asked at the end of the television interview. To which she
replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy made a big mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
