<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-975     03-03 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-975&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY'S VISIT TO NEW YORK HAS THE LOOK OF A CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)   (ART ADV: Photo of Hillary Clinton in New York City is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase
by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a speech that many Democrats viewed as a strong
indication that Hillary Rodham Clinton would run for the Senate
from New York, the first lady Wednesday proclaimed her commitment
to government and politics before some of her most passionate
supporters, New York Democratic women, in a packed and enthusiastic
ballroom of the Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot drop out of the political process and leave the
arena to those with very specific agendas,'' Mrs. Clinton said in
remarks so rich with double meaning that some women wondered if the
first lady was referring to them, to herself or to both.
</P>
<P>
   She added that ``you can say all you want about the flaws of our
political system, but when it comes right down to it, somebody is
going to make the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Clinton started her day in New York as a
traditional first lady with a visit to a Queens school and a speech
about the importance of arts education, by the time she arrived at
the Plaza she seemed transformed into a potential Senate candidate
at an exuberant political rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think it's time for a woman to represent New York in
the United States Senate?'' said Sen. Charles E. Schumer to cheers
as he introduced Mrs. Clinton to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mrs. Clinton's first visit to New York since announcing
two weeks ago that she was giving ``careful thought'' to a Senate
run in the state. She addressed the issue almost immediately when
she came to the podium. ``There was talk I might have an
announcement to make,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``I do not.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton seemed to tease the crowd, a Democratic Party
fund-raising group called the Women's Leadership Forum, as she
spoke about a woman's responsibility to participate in politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot say `I won't be involved in politics because I don't
like all of the negativity, I don't like all of the ads on
television,''' Mrs. Clinton said. She added to laughter that ``I
can certainly understand why someone might feel that way, but it is
not a feeling that you should act on.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Judith Hope, chairwoman of the New York state
Democratic party and one of the most ardent supporters of a Hillary
Clinton candidacy, said in an interview that Mrs. Clinton was
``publicly sharing her thought process with us'' as she considers a
Senate run.
</P>
<P>
   City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, one of the few men to attend
the lunch, went so far as to call Mrs. Clinton's speech ``very
close to an open declaration'' of candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   But some women at the lunch for 900, who paid from $150 to
$10,000 per ticket, described the speech as nothing more than
``classic Hillary'' in its advocacy for women and children and its
view of politics as a higher calling. Some of it, in fact, was
recycled material from a speech Mrs. Clinton made at the 150th
anniversary of the first women's convention in Seneca Falls last
summer. At the Plaza, Mrs. Clinton spoke about what she considers
the obligations of this generation of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like those women in Seneca Falls, we are standing in for
countless other women who cannot be here, who couldn't afford the
ticket, wouldn't think they had anything to wear, or anything to
contribute, who wouldn't see themselves as a political person at
all,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``One of our great challenges in the next
years is to make sure that our society doesn't split apart along
income lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made no reference to her potential opponent, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who in a reversal of geography spent Wednesday in
Washington testifying about crime reduction and cutting welfare
roles before a congressional committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference after his testimony, Giuliani said that
Mrs. Clinton is ``acting like a Senatorial candidate, I'm acting
like a Mayor. That's not a bad comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mrs. Clinton nor Giuliani have announced plans to run
for the Senate seat to be vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Giuliani from pointing to a poll released
Wednesday by the Marist Institute for Public Opinion that showed
Mrs. Clinton in a statistical tie in a hypothetical race with the
mayor, 50 percent for Mrs. Clinton and 46 percent for the
mayor. &UR;  &LR; The poll was taken among New York registered voters and
showed a drop in her support in a Marist poll of two weeks ago,
when she was ahead, 49 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at today's Marist and see if she's crowned the
winner,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added that Mrs. Clinton's ``celebrity status is helping
her a great deal'' but ``when she becomes a candidate'' and ``maybe
even faster, it's coming down to more and more questions in the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean she wouldn't be a strong candidate,'' he
added. ``But so will the Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani predicted a very close ``two to three point election.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's visit to New York, which coincided with ABC's
highly publicized ``20/20'' interview with Monica S. Lewinsky, drew
enormous media attention, rivaling that of a presidential visit.
There were 25 video cameras from the networks and foreign, local
and cable channels positioned in the auditorium of the Adrien Block
Intermediate School 25 in Flushing, Queens, where Mrs. Clinton did
nothing more political than release a national report about the
benefits of arts education.
</P>
<P>
   In the early evening, Mrs. Clinton stopped at the Manhattan home
of Lynn Forester, a longtime Democratic supporter and an owner of a
wireless communications company.
</P>
<P>
   Later she went to a dinner at the home of Jurate Kazickas and
Roger C. Altman, an investment banker who was President Clinton's
Deputy Treasury Secretary and whose firm bought The National
Enquirer and Star magazine two weeks ago. The dinner was described
as a gathering of 15 people, not a fund-raising event, that was to
include business executives and leaders of nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and supporters who have talked to Mrs. Clinton in recent
days said she has not decided whether she will run, but that she is
continuing her methodical research into the race. They described
her in recent days as excited about the idea of serving in the
Senate both because of her idealism about government and the
enticement of at last having a political career independent of her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., said he had spoken to Mrs. Clinton
for 20 minutes on the phone Tuesday night, and that the first lady
``asked me what I thought, if people really would welcome somebody
who wasn't a born and bred New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   After her remarks at the school, Mrs. Clinton was surrounded by
well-wishers and a mob of reporters, who were kept at a distance by
the Secret Service. Mrs. Clinton's staff said the first lady would
answer no questions from the press.
</P>
<P>
   The Plaza Hotel was even more crowded. Guests at the lunch,
which raised $500,000 for the Democratic National Committee and
sold out two weeks ago, were split into two _ one group in the
ballroom where Mrs. Clinton spoke, and another in separate room to
watch Mrs. Clinton on a television screen.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many citizens of New York who had opinions about the
first lady's visit Wednesday was Cathy Arevalo, 14, a ninth grader
at P.S. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a campaign appearance,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
