<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGIS-RYLANDERREVIEW04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas comptroller's plan would save state $1.2 billion
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With less than 10 days left for legislators to
file proposed legislation, Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander on
Wednesday unveiled 199 ideas for saving more than $1.2 billion in
state money and operating government more efficiently. The single
largest proposal, worth $652.5 million, would be to sell state
bonds and use the proceeds to pay for infrastructure along the
border. The bonds would be paid off with federal highway dollars
expected to trickle in over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander also suggests teacher bonuses, tax incentives for Texas
businesses and housing vouchers for older Texans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report has a lot of options for Texas,'' Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Texas Performance Review normally comes out before
lawmakers begin their biennial session. This year, outgoing
Comptroller John Sharp, a Democrat, declined to release the report.
Rylander, a Republican, declined to put her name on it before
taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, a staff report that proposed savings of $626.4
million was released without support from either comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   When she took office, Rylander and her staff combed through that
report, deleting some recommendations and adding others. ``What
I've done is to combine some new ideas with some good old ideas and
some revised ideas,'' Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander, who took office earlier this year, acknowledged that
time is running short to get many of the proposals into shape for
legislative action. But she added that legislators already are
considering many of the ideas. Others might be accomplished without
legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is when the real work starts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As the staff report recommended, Rylander says the state payroll
should be trimmed by 3,039 full-time positions, all of which would
come from the Department of Human Services, which currently has
about 15,500 employees. Statewide, there are more than 220,000
employees working for Texas. According to the report, the number of
welfare cases has steadily declined in the past few years, but the
number or employees at DHS hasn't fallen proportionately.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Performance Review began in 1991 when lawmakers were
facing tough economic times. To stave off the need for more tax
dollars, lawmakers asked Sharp to come up with ways to trim
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, lawmakers have used the report during good and bad
times to keep tabs on government spending. Each report has had a
unique title, including the first,''Breaking the Mold: New Ways to
Govern Texas,'' and this year's ``Challenging the Status Quo:
Toward Smaller, Smarter Government.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
