<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-SCHOOL-WARES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTUCE CONSIDER SOME PEACHY SUNDAY SCHOOL FARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It was hardly a revelation to Wayne Geer when
his toddler son, Samuel, named Larry the Cucumber as his favorite
biblical character.
</P>
<P>
   Geer is youth minister at Christian Life Assembly in Carrollton,
Texas, and is well aware of the popularity of the evangelistic
VeggieTales characters.
</P>
<P>
   The Geers were among representatives of 28 churches who
congregated at the Living Vine Family Christian Store last week for
a vacation Bible school workshop, an event at which publishers of
Christian materials trotted out their latest wares with dazzle and
devotion.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop was a kind of God trade show, complete with soft
sell and hard numbers, video presentations and stuffed-animal
characters, costumes and colorful booth decorations, all wrapped up
with a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, if you don't have a catchy theme in the VBS universe,
then you are a really small voice crying in the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   But, isn't it a stretch to use something as secular as a
medieval castle motif to introduce Jesus?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole world is theme-y,'' said T.J. Thurman, a children's
minister with Metroplex Chapel in Euless. ``You go to a restaurant,
it's got a theme. That goes back to the X-Generation-type
philosophy: `If it's not fun, I don't want to do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Churches should look for vacation Bible school themes that won't
become dated and that can be adapted to Sunday school or Wednesday
Bible study use, Thurman said. And, a good VBS plan can be used in
a daytime or an evening setting, because 50 percent of all Bible
schools are held at night.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Darrow of Plano, Texas, is typical of the publisher's
representatives who were on hand. A full-time educational director
at Preston Meadow Lutheran Church, she hawks Standard Publishing's
VBS program as a sideline. She works six or seven big showcases per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow had set up a radio station booth to tout a Station WSFJ
(We Shine For Jesus) theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want flexibility, age-appropriate crafts and activities,
and something that's easy to teach for novices,'' she said of the
typical VBS shopper.
</P>
<P>
   It's the appeal of drawing in a new, young flock that motivates
many VBS coordinators, some of the representatives said. ``Many
times, families who don't go to church will let their children come
to vacation Bible school, where they hear the message of Jesus
Christ for the first time,'' Darrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Thurman touted the cost-effectiveness of Gospel Light's Son
Castle Faire box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use a lot of recyclable material for crafts,'' he said.
``We're kind of known as the king of toilet paper rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's VBS Superbox, with enough materials for 35 to 50
children, runs $129.95, complete with sheet music, videos,
reproducible handouts and a cardboard puppet stage.
</P>
<P>
   Other VBS boxes range from about $50 to $150 and more.
</P>
<P>
   The most elaborate plan was ``The Ultimate Adventure With
Jesus,'' a $159.99 box with a five-destination, extreme-sports
theme of rock climbing, wind surfing, mountain biking, white-water
rafting and snowshoeing.
</P>
<P>
   The box contains director and leader guides for pre-school and
youth levels, adventure destination booklets illustrated with
gorgeous scenery from around the world, promotional posters, mural
art transparencies, a reproducible music CD, scripts for skits, and
even optional Ultimate Adventure-themed Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   Geer and his wife, Jamie, scouting out their first VBS program
for the 100 or so children in their ministry, were not that
concerned about cost-effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're mostly looking for something we're going to enjoy
themewise and productionwise, so we're watching them all to
decide,'' Gree said. Like many participants, though, the Geers
found that VeggieTales' ``Veggie Town Values: Building Citizens for
God's Community'' had the advantage of familiarity.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Geer had been down a similar road on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago, she came up with her own character when we
were at an inner-city church in another part of the country,''
Wayne Geer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was Gretchen, the Grape.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
