<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. IMPOSES TARIFFS AND VOWS TO BAN CONCORDE
</P>
<P>
   The United States escalated two politically contentious trade
disputes with Europe, imposing 100 percent tariffs on $520 million
in European products and threatening to ban Europe's supersonic
pride, the Concorde, from landing in the United States. The tariffs
imposed by the Clinton administration on goods such as Louis
Vuitton handbags, Parma ham, pecorino cheese and Scottish cashmere
sweaters, which essentially doubles their price, are part of a
six-year battle over trade in bananas.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS PUNISH JONES APPAREL
</P>
<P>
   The stock of Jones Apparel Group declined 12.2 percent as the
market frowned on the company's planned acquisition of Nine West
Group, the shoe retailer and manufacturer. Nine West has had some
problems, including a slowdown in sales and an inquiry by the
Federal Trade Commission into price-fixing allegations. Shares of
Jones Apparel fell $3.1875, to $22.75.
</P>
<P>
   GM SALES START TO REBOUND
</P>
<P>
   General Motors reported higher February sales and appears to be
rebounding from last summer's strike and joining its rivals in the
robust auto market.
</P>
<P>
   LINUX GETS A FRIENDLY FACE
</P>
<P>
   The free software movement took a big step toward a direct
confrontation with Microsoft by introducing software that gives the
Linux operating system the ease-of-use found on Windows and
Macintosh computers.
</P>
<P>
   KMART PROFIT BEATS EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Kmart, the No.2 discount retailer in the United States behind
Wal-Mart, said its fourth-quarter profit beat forecasts as it sold
more clothing and home goods.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY DISCUSSING HONG KONG PARK
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong and Walt Disney said that they were in early talks
about building a theme park in the Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED; BOND YIELDS RISE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed after slumping technology shares rallied in
the final hour, pulling the major market gauges up with them. The
Dow Jones industrials fell 21.73 points, to 9,275.88. Nasdaq ended
up 6.17 points, to 2,265.20, and the S.&AMP;P. 500 rose 2.20 points, to
1,227.70. In the bond market, the price of the 30-year Treasury
fell as its yield rose to 5.69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND LEAVES RATES UNCHANGED
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England brought five months of monetary easing to an
end, deciding to leave its key short-term rate unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
