<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPORT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congress to take on tobacco allocations
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State Rep. Dianne Delisi, who will lead a House
Appropriations subcommittee charged with determining how the
state's first tobacco settlement payments will be spent, said
Wednesday that Congress will begin to consider the issue today of
how much Texas may get to keep of its $17.3 billion recovery. That
decision will determine the scope of her subcommittee's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to do is give as much structure as we can,''
said Delisi (R-Temple).
</P>
<P>
   A total of $1.7 billion could be available over the next two
years from tobacco proceeds. That money will be set aside from
other state spending plans under an agreement between former
Attorney General Dan Morales and key budget-writing lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   FATHERS COULD BE LIABLE SOONER
</P>
<P>
   Houston state Rep. Fred Bosse has filed the first of several
bills expected to deal with Sunset Advisory Commission
recommendations for Texas' beleaguered child-support enforcement
program.
</P>
<P>
   Bosse, a Democrat, incorporates a version of various proposals
to streamline the process by which fathers of children born to
unwed mothers can be identified and ordered to pay support. In his
bill, Bosse would have a man's signature on a birth certificate or
on a declaration given at the hospital as proof sufficient to allow
a temporary child support order to be issued without a judge's
involvement. Paternity itself could still be contested in court,
but a mother supposedly could get support faster than under
existing law.WILLIAMSON MAY GET NEW COURT
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County would get a third county court-at-law under a
bill heard by a Senate committee Wednesday. A separate bill up for
committee consideration next week would create a new district court
for a county that has nearly doubled in population since the last
new court started in 1991.DEREGULATION PLAN NEARS SENATE
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Sibley (R-Waco) announced Wednesday that he expects
to bring his massive electric utility deregulation bill to the full
Senate in two weeks, on March 17, and to vote it out of his Special
Senate Committee on Electric Utility Restructuring on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the complexity of the issue, the Senate agreed, at
Sibley's request, to take the unusual step of requiring that all
amendments to the bill be filed with the secretary of the Senate at
least 48 hours before the Senate takes up the bill. Normally,
amendments can be offered at any time before the Senate votes on a
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley said the bill is ``150 pages right now and rising'' and
he expects it to be close to 200 pages by the time it reaches the
full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL EXPULSION PLAN PASSES
</P>
<P>
   Local school districts would get the right to expel students who
assault school district employees or volunteers under a bill
approved by the Texas Senate on a 31-0 vote Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, author of the bill, said students
guilty of assault cannot under current law be expelled. Students
who assault others at school must be placed in an alternative
education program.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' bill originally would apply only to assaults that
occurred on school district property or at school-related events.
But Sen. Chris Harris, R-Arlington, won approval of an amendment to
allow a student to be expelled for an assault against a school
district employee or volunteers anywhere if it were retaliation for
a school-related matter.
</P>
<P>
   SUIT ALLEGES TXDOT USED QUOTAS
</P>
<P>
   A Houston contractor has filed a lawsuit against the Texas
Department of Transportation for allegedly using racial quotas to
award contracts. Robert Kossman, the plaintiff in the lawsuit, said
his erosion control firm lost business under such practices to
minority-owned businesses even when his firm submitted the low bid.
</P>
<P>
   Kossman, who is white, is asking a federal district judge to
declare the program unconstitutional. His lawsuit is being handled
by the Campaign for a Color-Blind America, Legal Defense and
Educational Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes as TXDOT is transitioning to new federal
guidelines, which allow economically-disadvantaged businesses _
including those owned by whites _ to qualify for the disadvantaged
business program.
</P>
<P>
   The Campaign for a Color-Blind America was founded by Edward
Blum, who led a ballot-initiative in 1997 to eliminate the City of
Houston's affirmative action contracting and employment program.
Voters defeated the measure, but a court fight continues.
</P>
<P>
   UNCERTIFIED TEACHERS IDENTIFIED
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dawnna Dukes said Wednesday that parents have a right to
know when their children are in classrooms taught by teachers who
are not certified or who are improperly certified. She has filed
House Bill 618, which would require schools to notify parents
within 30 days if an uncertified teacher is still in the classroom
or teaching the course.
</P>
<P>
   Shortages of certified teachers have led to many subjects being
taught by underqualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, 62 percent of teachers in bilingual classes were
not certified in that subject in the 1997-98 school year and more
than a quarter _ 27 percent _ of math teachers were improperly
certified.
</P>
<P>
   COMMITTEE OKS BUSH APPOINTEES
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Nominations Committee on Wednesday approved Gov.
George W. Bush's selection of six Texans to the embattled Board of
Pardons and Paroles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush last month replaced a third of the board in the largest
replacement sweep in years. The 18-member panel has faced harsh
criticism for the secrecy in which it considers clemency for death
row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Approved by the Nominations Committee were Paddy Lann Burwell,
of DeWitt County; LaFayette Collins, of Round Rock; Linda Garcia,
of La Porte; James Paul Kiel Jr., of Tyler; Filiberto ``Bert''
Reyna, of Waco; and Lucinda ``Cindy'' Simons, of Hereford.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
