u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKS-DISPUTE-ECONSCE     03-03 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-DISPUTE-ECONSCENE-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE BETWEEN RUBIN, GREENSPAN COULD SCUTTLE MODERNIZATION OF
BANKING RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ A continuing spat between Treasury Secretary Robert E.
Rubin and Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, over
modernizing bank regulations threatens to bury legislation that
comes before House and Senate committees Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They agree that laws from the 1930s and 1950s that keep banks
out of the securities and insurance markets should be scrapped. But
they disagree how banks should be structured to handle their new
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, with the support of most economists, looks like he will
get most of what he wants from the House. Greenspan, drawing
powerful support from past and present Fed officials, may win in
the Senate. Indeed, the administration Wednesday threatened to veto
the proposal by Phil Gramm, chairman of the Senate banking
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is that Congress will be deadlocked, forcing the
economy to operate under Depression-era rules for at least a few
more years.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's laws prohibit commercial banks from underwriting
insurance and securities or engaging in most commercial activities.
Nearly everyone agrees that most of these prohibitions should be
scrapped. The idea is that banks could be allowed to offer
customers a single, convenient and low-cost place to bank, invest
and buy insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan would require banks to affiliate with securities and
insurance firms under the joint ownership of a bank holding
company. He would not allow banks to provide financial services
directly or through wholly owned subsidiaries. Under the Greenspan
plan, bank holding companies would rule the market. By the way,
Greenspan's Fed regulates bank holding companies.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin would allow banks to avoid the complicated and costly
burden of setting up holding companies and instead create wholly
owned, but separately incorporated, subsidiaries. In this
arrangement, banks could become financial giants. By the way,
Rubin's Treasury regulates banks.
</P>
<P>
   To almost anyone outside the Beltway, the distinction between
affiliates and subsidiaries appears arcane. Suspicions are
heightened by the strong aroma of a turf war. But there is more to
this dispute than petty jealously.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed points out that subsidiaries are dangerous because their
losses would directly eat into the financial reserves of the parent
bank. That leaves the bank financially vulnerable. The Fed worries
that transfers between parent banks and their subsidiaries could
grow excessively large because the money would still be owned by
the bank and would not, therefore, spook creditors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed is hard pressed to point to independent economists
who share its fears. George Benston of Emory University says that
the Rubin plan _ and the bipartisan bill proposed by James Leach
and John LaFalce, the chairman and ranking minority member,
respectively, of the House banking committee that embraces many of
Rubin's demands _ ``gives Greenspan all the protections that he
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, banks could offer securities underwriting
through a subsidiary. But participating banks would be required to
hold an extra layer of capital reserves. And none of the dollars
that the bank invests in its subsidiary could be counted toward its
capital requirement. In other words, if the subsidiary went
bankrupt and the parent bank lost its entire investment, the bank
would still be left with more capital than is normally required.
Second, the amount of money that the bank would be allowed to send
to its subsidiary would be limited to the amount the bank would be
allowed to send to an affiliate of a holding company.
</P>
<P>
   Benston's point, like Rubin's, is that affiliates and
subsidiaries are largely equivalent under the House proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan makes a second criticism of the House plan. Banks,
he points out, can borrow money more cheaply than other firms
because of various government-provided favors. The government
insures money deposited by the bank's customers. The government
provides loans to banks in times of distress. And the government
guarantees the system that provides for rapid processing of
deposits and payments. Greenspan worries that banks will pass the
financial benefit of these implicit federal subsidies to their
subsidiaries, thereby distorting competition in the market for
financial services.
</P>
<P>
   But Benston dismisses these arguments, as well. ``The subsidy
Greenspan points to may not exist, but it is almost surely small.
Along with the federal insurance come layers of expensive
regulations. Besides, the benefit of the subsidy, if it exists, can
be passed along to affiliates about as easily as subsidiaries. And,
banks have little incentive to pass along subsidies to affiliates
or subsidiaries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Fed appears to fear that securities underwriting and other
financial services are so inherently nuclear that they can blow
open holes in the parent bank's capital before regulators have time
to react. But, Benston points out, ``Derivatives can blow up faster
than stock and bond purchases. Underwriting poses no special
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is another argument that may explain the Fed's animus
toward subsidiaries. If banks prefer Rubin's model to the Fed's,
bank holding companies will shrivel, leaving the Fed little to
regulate. Over time, Fed officials fear, their regulatory expertise
will also shrivel. Fed officials believe regulatory expertise is
integral to the Fed's ability to do its other job: setting monetary
policy.
</P>
<P>
   There are other contentious issues, including Gramm's threat to
undermine the rules that compel banks to lend in poor
neighborhoods. But the major dispute is over bank structure. It
might seem obvious that the impact on the economy of Depression-era
bank rules is large. But the presumption may well be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have chipped away at the regulatory shackles, finding
loopholes by which to approve, for example, a merger that brought
Citibank and Salomon Smith Barney together. A legislative fix may
not be all that important. Leach says his bill will deliver a
``psychological boost'' to the financial services sector,
especially to firms serving midsize business. Perhaps. But Leach
cites testimony that the economywide benefits might be only a few
billion dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always good reason to throw out silly rules,''
Benston said, ``but don't expect bank reform to pack much of a
wallop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2126EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
