<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOLS CHIEF DRAWS A LINE OVER SCHOOL VOUCHERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Calif.)  (nk) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Drawing an ideological line over an emotional issue
in public education, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has warned Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani that he will resign if the administration pushes
through an experimental voucher program to spend tax dollars for
children to attend private schools, a person close to the
chancellor said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That message, which the person _ speaking on the condition of
anonymity _ said was unequivocal, threatens a relationship between
Giuliani and Crew that by many accounts has been both productive
and congenial. After a nationwide search, Crew was hired in October
1995 with Giuliani's blessing to replace Ramon C. Cortines, who had
been pressured by the mayor to resign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chancellor has been clear with his board, with the mayor
and with his staff that on principle he could never support
vouchers in the New York City public school system,'' the person
said. ``He feels that it is the beginning of the end of public
education, period, if you start funneling taxpayer dollars into
private education.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate between the mayor and the chancellor over school
vouchers was waged through surrogates Wednesday, in part because
both were out of town _ Giuliani in Washington, Crew in California.
But both administration and school officials acknowledged that the
conflict was intensifying and said that the two men had at least
two telephone conversations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made the issue a central theme of his State of the
City address in January by announcing that he hoped to establish a
pilot voucher program in one of the city's 32 community school
districts. To that end, his aides have been lobbying the school
board's seven board members to support his proposal. Three members
are said to be against the plan and three, including his two
appointees, are in favor; that has placed enormous pressure on the
one undecided member, Terri Thomson, who represents Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Given comments made Wednesday night by Joseph J. Lhota, the
deputy mayor for operations, the administration appears to have no
intention of relenting in pursuing its goal to have some form of a
voucher program in the city's school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good relationship with the chancellor,'' Lhota said.
``As with other new issues, the chancellor somewhat overreacts at
first _ he did with charter schools, he did with school safety. I
know the chancellor always holds the schoolchildren more important
than the system itself. He came around on both those issues, and at
the end of the day, reason will prevail on the issue of vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chiara Coletti, the public affairs director for the school
board, immediately took issue with Lhota's comments. She said that
Crew has never been opposed to charter schools _ tax-financed
public schools that are not controlled by local school boards _ but
rather to one legislative proposal. On the matter of school safety,
she said, ``the mayor and the chancellor negotiated a signed
compromise'' in allowing the Police Department to oversee security
in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just no comparison here,'' Ms. Coletti said. ``On the
issue of vouchers, within the public school system the chancellor
is unequivocal in his opposition, despite his respect for and
friendship with the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday night, neither official seemed prepared to back
down. Giuliani, who is in the midst of considering his political
future, has adopted the national Republican Party's enthusiasm for
school vouchers. On Sunday, while delivering a speech in Miami, for
example, he called it ``the most important thing that has to be
done with education in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has said that he hoped to mirror a program in
Milwaukee that uses tax dollars to pay the private school tuition
of children from low-income families. Among the restrictions of
that program _ whose constitutionality so far has been upheld by
the Wisconsin courts _ is one prohibiting the schools from having
the students participate in religious activities.
</P>
<P>
   In setting aside $12 million in his budget plan to entice school
districts to participate, Giuliani has defended his proposal as an
experiment that would create competition and therefore force the
public school system to improve. The mayor has also argued that
poor families should have the same choice in selecting schools for
their children as more affluent families have.
</P>
<P>
   But Crew expressed opposition to the mayor's proposal just hours
after Giuliani unveiled it in January. The argument that Crew makes
is simple: Public money should not be used to pay for private
education _ particularly when the city's public school system is
underfinanced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very clear on this position'' in his discussions
with the mayor and his aides, said the person close to Crew.
``Basically, you're taking the money and energy out for a very,
very few.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
