</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With Williams at leadoff, Cox begins lineup testing
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ The tinkering officially has begun.
While manager Bobby Cox is in no way setting a lineup this early,
some of the things he'll be thinking about this spring become more
evident with his announcement of the starting lineup for the
Braves' exhibition against Georgia Tech today.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup: 1) Gerald Williams in left; 2) Bret Boone at second;
3) Chipper Jones at third; 4) Brian Jordan in right; 5) Ryan Klesko
at first; 6) Andruw Jones in center; 7) Ozzie Guillen at shortstop;
8) Mike Mahoney at catcher; and (9) Jason Marquis on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was used in the No. 2 hole most during last season but
led off eight times. Jordan, as expected, will take some turns in
the cleanup spot. Cox will take a look at Boone, who batted fifth
and sixth most of last year for the Reds, in the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   But that's that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was serious about messing with the lineup, hitting guys in
different areas and setting on a lineup the last week or 10 days
(of spring training),'' Cox said. ``Right now, it's a matter of
getting guys at-bats and getting them out of the game. I might hit
Brian Jordan leadoff just to get him two at-bats and get him out of
some games.''
</P>
<P>
   WORKOUTS END
</P>
<P>
   The Braves begin their exhibition season today against Georgia
Tech. Rain Wednesday morning forced the Braves inside for much of
their workout. They did not get to work on cutoffs and relay
throws, so they will practice that before the Tech game today.
Earlier this week, the Braves worked on bunt plays and pickoff
throws.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is known for having relatively short workouts in spring
training _ several hours at the longest _ which undoubtedly is
popular with the players.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who came from Tony La Russa's more rigorous St. Louis
camp, appreciates the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, compared to the Cardinals camp, is a breeze,'' Jordan
said. ``I like it because it shows how much Bobby Cox trusts you as
a player. He knows you know what you need to do to get ready. That
also prevents injury.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS AND THAT
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss is believed to have strep throat and was
not in camp for the second day in a row. Trainer Dave Pursley said
the Braves didn't actually take a strep culture, but began treating
him for it because he had all the symptoms. ... Minor-league third
baseman Wes Helms has been having pain in his throwing shoulder and
was scheduled to have it checked out with an MRI on Wednesday. ``I
think it took its toll from sliding and stuff,'' Helms said. ``I
felt a twinge. I don't think it's too serious.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
