<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-PREVIEW04     03-03 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PREVIEW04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dodgers consider spring break
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Branch Rickey schemed here. Jackie Robinson
trained here. Don Drysdale and Sandy Koufax staged their twin
holdout here. Jay Johnstone tied Tommy Lasorda's hotel door knob to
a palm tree here. Roy Campanella rolled his wheelchair through
here. Above all, the Dodgers remain here, staging their 51st spring
camp, the blue ghosts just as touchable as Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dodgertown has a way of affecting you,'' said Kevin Malone,
the Dodgers' new general manager. ``It's all about baseball. It's
special. It's almost sacred ground.''
</P>
<P>
   So then, why would the Dodgers leave?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's what they call progress or something,'' first
baseman Eric Karros said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers, a franchise transforming into something
different before our very eyes, continue to negotiate with the city
of Vero Beach and Indian River County over ownership of the
460-acre Dodgertown complex. With the club holding a sweet offer
from the Yavapi Indian tribe in Arizona for a new $30 million
training complex to be built at the Fort McDowell reservation
outside Scottsdale, the Dodgers are waiting for the local
authorities here to buy back Dodgertown _ approximate price: $8
million _ renovate the place and then beat the Yavapis at the
bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers say they don't want to leave. The Arizona deal, with
a proposed $1 a year lease, makes it crazy for the Dodgers to stay.
No other team owns its own spring complex anymore, nor pays local
taxes, nor pays all operating costs. Even so, a decision to move,
seemingly unavoidable, would be another vile mark against Fox's new
ownership of one of American's sports most storied organizations.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Dodgers remained the only West Coast team
training in Florida in part because the O'Malley family still felt
guilty about fleeing Brooklyn and wanted to keep a presence in the
East. Since Rupert Murdoch's acquisition, the club has decided to
cram more luxury suites into Dodger Stadium, has messed with
uniform design and now seeks a way out of Dodgertown. The loyalists
have gone from blue to bright red.
</P>
<P>
   ``They live in the past,'' Malone said, ``and so they want us to
stay in the past, too.''
</P>
<P>
   With new complexes sprouting almost annually, Dodgertown remains
as 1950s cool as Dean Martin's cocktail, not as grand as the new
places but twice as great. History blends with proximity to provide
the finest taste of the Grapefruit League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people come out here and feel a part of the atmosphere,''
said broadcaster Rick Monday, who felt like he had moved to ``the
Disneyland of baseball'' when the Dodgers signed him in 1977.
``They can hear the players mumbling as they're running sprints.
They can see the sweat. This has been a wonderful place over the
years for baseball to transfer to another generation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Arizona facility makes too much sense to a bottom-line
corporation. The Dodgers could train on its six fields next spring,
would assume no construction costs of a new stadium to be ready for
2001 and would split all parking, ticket and concession revenues.
Although the Dodgers generate an estimated $20 million to the Vero
Beach economy, the town in return can offer little beyond an
improved rent rate, a spruced-up stadium and the small-town appeal,
which still carries weight around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more partial to raccoons and water moccasins than I am to
gila monsters and cactus,'' incoming manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Detroit Tigers, training at Lakeland, Fla., since 1934,
and the Philadelphia Phillies, training in Clearwater since 1947,
have held the same winter homes longer. The Dodgers' decision is
not expected until late March.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a fans' standpoint,'' Karros said, ``I can see where this
is a very appealing place, and I'm sure a lot of fans will be
really upset. But from a players' standpoint, there are definitely
a few things this place lacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, history isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
