<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BERKOW-COLUMN-ART     03-03 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BERKOW-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LEVANE MADE MUSIC OF HIS OWN ON THE BASKETBALL
COURT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Antonio Levane immigrated to America from Naples
early in this century, he was 10 years old. To help out his family,
he played a mandolin for pennies on the streets of Brooklyn. He
went on to play the double bass in renowned orchestras, such as at
the Metropolitan Opera House, and for such classical luminaries as
Caruso and Toscanini.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Antonio Levane wanted his six children to play
musical instruments. But some of his children, particularly the one
that the nation would come to know as Fuzzy, had other notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop first tried to teach me the cello,'' Levane said recently,
``and I'd practice for an hour or so _ I did learn some notes _ and
then duck out to play ball. But Pop was determined. He thought I'd
respond to a more modern instrument and tried to teach me the
saxophone. Same result. All the time my sisters were playing
instruments, and Lucille even became a concert pianist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew Levane _ the nickname Fuzzy, which derived from Cuzzy
or ``cousin,'' was bestowed by neighborhood pals _ was a flop as a
symphonist. When Fuzzy departed the family's third-floor apartment
in Flatbush, he headed mainly to basketball courts, especially St.
Brendan's parish gymnasium, with a ceiling so low that by necessity
he developed a two-handed, over-the-head line-drive set shot. Fuzzy
mastered the shot in the way his father embraced Puccini.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father,'' Levane recalled, ``used to tell me, in his broken
English, `Andrew, if you don't learn something, you gonna be a bum.
Stop with the ball!''
</P>
<P>
   But Fuzzy had a mind of his own, and an uncommon skill with the
ball. He grew to 6 feet 2 inches, which appeared extraordinary when
he stood next to his father, who was 5 feet tall. (Fuzzy's mother
was 5-7. ``In those days,'' Levane said, ``marriages were arranged.
I had an uncle 4-11 and his wife was 5-8.'')
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, as the star center of the undefeated city championship
James Madison High School team, Fuzzy was named the outstanding
prep player in New York City. He went to St. John's University and
in his senior year, 1943, led the team to the National Invitation
Tournament championship _ the NIT, not the NCAA, was then the
premier college post-season tournament in the nation. He won the
Haggerty Award as the best college player in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   After two years in the Army during World War II, he joined the
Rochester Royals in 1945 in the new National Basketball League
(soon to be the NBA). He was the starting forward on the league's
first championship team, and it was the start of a six-year N.B.A.
playing career. He then became a coach, first with the Milwaukee
Hawks, and then in New York, leading the Knicks to the playoffs in
1958-59.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the 1959-60 season began, he was fired. ``All I
know,'' Levane said, ``is that Wilt Chamberlain came into the
league, and I went out.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he remains in the league, and with the Knicks, as a
scout, primarily looking at Continental Basketball Association
players. He recommended, among others, a big, strong rebounder who
could dribble. His name was Anthony Mason.
</P>
<P>
   The white-haired Levane, now 78, will be honored at Madison
Square Garden on March 14 at halftime of the Public Schools
Athletic League basketball finals, whose playoffs are now getting
under way. It was 60 years ago that the dark-haired Levane led
James Madison to the title in the old Madison Square Garden.
``Playing there was as big a thrill as I've ever had,'' Levane
said.
</P>
<P>
   The team was called the Wonder Five because it won 39 straight
games. It dominated Jamaica in the final, 44-32, and all five of
its starters went on to play in the pros _ Stanley Waxman; Larry
Baxter; the Rader twins, Lennie and Howie, and Levane _ as well as
the sixth man, Freddie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``On its record,'' Levane said, ``we had to be the best high
school team ever.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his recognition at halftime, Levane said: ``People are
going to say, `What's that old guy doing out there?' And I can't
blame 'em. It's been a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Levane laughed. He is a man with an easy manner, and laughter is
an essential part of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father eventually took to basketball,'' Levane said.
``Especially after St. John's gave me a scholarship when I was a
junior in high school. It was the Depression, he was out of work,
and they paid our rent, $30 a month. And when I played ball for St.
John's my dad came to all the games. And you could hear him
cheering in the stands: `Let's-a-go, St. John's, let's-a-go!'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
