<SLUG> BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE JURY WEIGHS FATE OF JET PILOT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ A jury of eight Marine officers began
deliberating Wednesday afternoon whether a pilot whose plane struck
ski-lift cables in the Italian Alps 13 months ago was guilty of a
crime, or whether the incident that killed all 20 people in a
gondola was simply an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, the pilot of the EA-6B Prowler, faces a
sentence of 200 years in prison for involuntary manslaughter if the
jury concludes that he was ``culpably negligent,'' which the judge
defined as acting with ``a gross, reckless, wanton or deliberate
disregard for the foreseeable results to others.''
</P>
<P>
   He could be convicted of a lesser crime, negligent homicide, if
the jury concludes his negligence was simple rather than culpable.
He also faces charges of dereliction of duty, failure to plan the
flight properly, destroying government property and destroying
private property.
</P>
<P>
   But he could be acquitted of all charges if the jury concludes,
as his lawyer argued Wednesday, that the incident was ``an accident
waiting to happen'' because the ski lift did not appear on charts
available to the jet's crew, among other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not acquit Captain Ashby because he's a fellow Marine
officer,'' the lawyer, Frank Spinner, said in closing arguments
this morning. ``Do not convict Captain Ashby because 20 people
died.''
</P>
<P>
   But the chief prosecutor, Maj. Daniel Daugherty, said, ``He put
himself in a situation he couldn't get out of, at maximum speed and
minimum height.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane's target altitude was 1,000 feet above the ground, but
it struck the cables at about 360 feet. The plane was at maximum
thrust at the time, said Daugherty, so ``there's nothing left in
that aircraft to give; he is on a rocket sled going right through
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial has run through hours of complicated detail about
various flaws that led up to the accident. In addition to the fact
that the cable was not on American charts, a crucial argument for
the defense is that the radar altimeter, which measures distance
above the ground, may not have worked because of the way the plane
was banking sharply, pointing its belly at distant mountains
instead of the nearby ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 1,000-foot rule is now etched in the blood of 20
civilians,'' Daugherty told the jurors. ``There is no good reason
to be down that low, no good reason to be maneuvering with that
population right there, all those houses, all those people, all
that humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   He maintained that the accident occurred because instead of
following the rules, Ashby was ``down where he wants to be, making
the decisions he wants to make, flying the aircraft the way he
wants to fly it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spinner argued that Ashby had no reason to skirt the rules.
Among other factors, Spinner said, Ashby was at the end of a
six-month deployment in Aviano, Italy, a few days from rotating
back to his home base at Cherry Point, N.C., a few miles from here,
and had been selected to switch to flying F-18's, a higher-status
job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
