<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     03-03 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HARD WORK TRANSFORMS A PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You don't see Leonard Hamilton relax that often. On
the sidelines, during practices, watching film, Hamilton, the coach
of the University of Miami's surging basketball team, moves with a
never-ending sense of urgency. He lives in a world where the
mission is never complete, the deed never done.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton smiled Tuesday and perhaps briefly allowed himself
to absorb the moment. This was at the announcement of the Big East
Conference's individual honors. Hamilton's Miami Hurricane program
received three awards: Johnny Hemsley was voted the most improved
player; Tim James shared most valuable player with Richard Hamilton
of Connecticut, and Leonard Hamilton, in his ninth season, was
voted the league's coach of the year for the second time in three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't what made him smile. Etan Thomas, the Syracuse
junior center, did. As Thomas accepted his defensive player of the
year award, he hesitated and looked over at James. ``I know this is
unusual,'' he said ``but I'd like to congratulate Tim James. He's
really someone I look up to and respect. The thing I really admire
about him is he's understated and humble. So, my hat's off to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' impromptu tribute spoke volumes about James and
illuminated a Miami program that has come from extinction to having
a defining presence at a cozy private school that has searched for
an alternative to the bruising national reputation of its football
team.
</P>
<P>
   What it has is Hamilton, a 50-year-old coaching alchemist who
has taken the best elements of his most ferocious Big East rivals,
combined them and produced a formula that has become daunting: a
cup of Georgetown's unyielding toughness, a tablespoon of
Syracuse's elan, a pinch of Connecticut's precision and a heavy
dose of the sleeves-rolled-up, dusk-to-dawn hard work Hamilton
learned growing up in Gastonia, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Miami finished second in the Big East with a school-record 15
conference victories and, at 21-5, had 20 victories for the first
time in a season since 1965. The Hurricanes, at No. 9, enjoy their
highest ranking since 1965, the last year they were ranked. Last
month Miami handed Connecticut a stunning defeat in Storrs.
Thursday it is the second-seeded team in a Big East tournament
quarterfinal against the winner of Wednesday night's
Georgetown-Providence game. ``We're a team that's trying to build a
tradition,'' he said. ``Once we get there, I hope we'll stay
there.''
</P>
<P>
   A slide is unlikely. Hamilton's upbringing won't let him stop.
He was formed by the discipline of parents who sometimes gave him
whippings in front of friends; his father woke Hamilton and his
brothers at midnight to make them cut the grass they had neglected.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's basketball tradition fits in a thimble. The 1959-60 team
earned its first NCAA tournament berth. Rick Barry played there
from 1962 to 1965. In 1971, Miami dropped the sport. Even when
Miami brought basketball back as an independent in 1985, the
program, with no arena, had to schedule around everything from the
circus to conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no arena, no conference affiliation and no program for
14 years _ that was the most attractive part of the job for me,''
Hamilton said. ``So many coaches look for a job where the streets
are already paved with gold. That's easy. I've always been
motivated by challenges: this was a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton attended junior college, then transferred to
Tennessee-Martin on a basketball scholarship. After graduation he
took a coaching job at Austin Peay, where he was a graduate
assistant, newly married with a son and working on his master's
degree. Hamilton ordered his younger brother, who was struggling
with high school academics, to leave Gastonia and move in, adopting
him. After his brother left for college, Hamilton ordered his next
youngest brother to move in, then, after he advanced to the
University of Kentucky, his sister and then his nephew. He adopted
each one.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton deals in hard work and transformation. He remembers
riding on the back of buses, getting food from the rear of
segregated restaurants. He was the first black assistant at
Kentucky, where he spent 12 years, then the head coach at Oklahoma
State, where he spent four seasons, and now is rebuilding at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I've ever said in my life is `Why not?''' he said. `` `Why
not me,' or `Why not us?'''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's success is about strategy and guile but also about
fundamental issues of discipline, persistence, toughness and
restraint. The Hurricanes were 0-18 in the Big East in 1993-94, and
now they're breathing down the necks of the contenders. Etan Thomas
picked up on a subtlety Tuesday, and Leonard Hamilton smiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
