<P>
   (NYT26) LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. -- March 03, 1999 -- LEISURE-WORLD,
3-03 -- Residents of the Leisure World retirement community play
lawn bowling recently. The residents on Tuesday voted to transform
their gated patch of what they call ``God's country'' into
California's newest city. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- NY-DOG-CONTROL, 3-03 --
Judith Schwarz protests getting a ticket from a mounted park ranger
on Wednesday in Riverside Park. Schwarz was cited for not having
her dogs on a leash. Police and park rangers have begun to enforce
leash laws in the city's parks. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW DELHI, India -- March 03, 1999 -- INDIA-AUTOS, 3-03
-- Ambassadors, produced by Hindustan Motors Ltd., roll off the
assembly line recently. Until the early 1980s, almost every car
sold in India was an Ambassador. Near-monopoly conditions led to
lingering corporate somnolence. Now, with India's economy more open
and foreign automakers joining up with local partners, the
Ambassador is in a fight for its survival. (Barry Bearak/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- NY-DOG-CONTROL, 3-03 --
Judith Schwarz protests getting a ticket from a mounted park ranger
on Wednesday in Riverside Park. Schwarz was cited for not having
her dogs on a leash. Police and park rangers have begun to enforce
leash laws in the city's parks. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CORONA DEL MAR, Calif. -- March 03, 1999 --
GERIATRIC-CARE-3, 3-03 -- Dr. Deborah Newquist, right, walks with
her client Clarence Maverhan near his home. Newquist, whose
doctorate is in medical anthropology, is a geriatric care manager,
an occupation that did not exist when she received her master's
degree in social work 24 years ago. The field was born in response
to the nation's rapidly aging population, the health care system's
complexity and, in many cases, the frustration of those who cared
for elderly relatives and decided to help others in a similar
situation. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- March 03, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 3-03
-- Before applying any finish, it is essential to carefully sand
the wood to remove all scratches and create a smooth surface. Start
with a medium-grit paper aluminum oxide paper, then progress to
finer grits before smoothing with a 180-grit paper (Some stains
require sanding with even finer grits. Read the label on the
product for recommendations.). Always sand with the grain. (Edward
R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-NY-3, 3-03 --
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton waves to supporters as Sen. Chuck
Schumer, D-N.Y., looks on at right during a fund-raising event at
the Plaza Hotel on Wednesday. Mrs. Clinton's trip to New York comes
amid increasing speculation about a possible run for the Senate
seat of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who is
retiring. Mrs. Clinton had made several trips to New York during
Schumer's campaign last year. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HOUSTON -- March 03, 1999 -- SUB-OCTUPLETS, 3-03 -- Dr.
Patti Savrik, right, looks on as Nkem Chukwu, left, and Ikye Louis
Udobi, parents of the Houston octuplets, as they talk to reporters
on Wednesday. Three of their children finally came home after
spending the first few months of their lives in the hospital. The
parents brought home daughters Ebuka and Echerem and son Jioke, who
have been among the largest and healthiest since their births last
December. (Kevin Fujii/Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) VELIKA HOCA, Yugoslavia -- March 03, 1999 -- KOSOVO-2,
3-03 -- Family members comfort Daniela Savalic, 14, center, the
daughter of Dobrivoje Savalic, during funeral services on
Wednesday. Savalic, a Serb civilian, was cutting wood when he was
kidnapped and beaten to death allegedly by members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army. While Serbian forces and guerrillas of the K.L.A.
are engaged in a series of clashes around Yugoslavia's Kosovo
province, there is a more hidden war where people disappear, or are
killed stealthily, often at night and often close to home. (Alan
Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) VELIKA HOCA, Yugoslavia -- March 03, 1999 -- KOSOVO,
3-03 -- The body of Dobrivoje Savalic, 42, lies next to his grave
before burial on Wednesday. Savalic, a Serb civilian, was cutting
wood when he was kidnapped and beaten to death allegedly by members
of the Kosovo Liberation Army. While Serbian forces and guerrillas
of the K.L.A. are engaged in a series of clashes around
Yugoslavia's Kosovo province, there is a more hidden war where
people disappear, or are killed stealthily, often at night and
often close to home. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
