agenda. Clinton is flanked by House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, left, and his counterpart in the Senate, Tom Daschle.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-4, 3-03 --
Frida Kahlo's blue studio near Mexico City. Kahlo's family home was
expanded when her husband, painter Diego Rivera, added the studio
for her. Given Rivera's emotional past, crowded with liaisons,
separate studios for the two painters amounted to spatial wisdom.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- March 03, 1999 -- CIR-GAME-SHARK, 3-03 -- The
Game Shark, for Nintendo 64 video games, contains hundreds of cheat
codes. Interact has sold two million pieces of the plastic and
silicon that plug into the back of a Sony Playstation or the
cartridge slot of a Nintendo 64 to give the player invincibility,
extra weapons, superpowers and access to hidden areas and bonus
levels. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MEDFORD, Mass. -- March 03, 1999 -- VENTURE-TALENT-BOS,
3-03 -- Rina Spence, interim chief executive of Consensus
Pharmaceuticals Inc., a start-up biotechnology company, sits near
Jack Lai, working at a peptide synthesizer. Spence began her
working life as a junior high school teacher, ran a health
management organization, was president and chief executive for 10
years at a big suburban hospital, and then turned entrepreneur,
opening a chain of women's health clinics. More than just a
personal odyssey, Spence's current transition is emblematic of
major changes occurring in how key jobs are being filled at many of
the promising young companies that get their initial bankroll from
venture capital funds. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- March 03, 1999 -- SOUL-TRAINING-BOS, 3-03 --
Ray Barrieau looks at his portrait of his 16-year old son Jonathan
who was killed in car accident a year ago. Barrieau is part of a
group of 130 people attending a three-and-a-half day forum of
intense self-examination hoping that it will help them smooth out
cracks in their relationships with families, friends and
co-workers. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-NY-2, 3-03 --
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton during a visit to a school in the
borough of Queens on Wednesday. Mrs. Clinton's visit to New York
came amid increasing speculation about her possible run for the
Senate seat of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who
