<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- SUPER-BRIGHT-HEADLIGHTS,
3-03 -- Cars stopped at an intersection demonstrate the difference
between standard headlights, right, and those using new High
Intensity Discharge (HID) technology. The new lights emit a broad
field of intensely clear light closely approximating the spectrum
of daylight. Darkness is banished as the car drives forward into
its own private pocket of renewable daylight. (Thomas Dallal/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-3, 3-03 --
Frida Kahlo's work space in the blue studio near Mexico City. A
portrait of the artist is at right. Kahlo's family home was
expanded when her husband, painter Diego Rivera, added the studio
for her. Given Rivera's emotional past, crowded with liaisons,
separate studios for the two painters amounted to spatial wisdom.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-2, 3-03 --
Diego Rivera's 1932 studio with his portrait of Dolores Del Rio.
Rivera's life was a legend wrapped in scandal surrounded by myth
that played against the backdrop of Technicolor buildings as if he
was a figure walking through one of his own heroic canvases.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-1, 3-03 --
Diego Rivera's red studio brought modernism to Mexico City.
Rivera's life was a legend wrapped in scandal surrounded by myth
that played against the backdrop of Technicolor buildings as if he
was a figure walking through one of his own heroic canvases.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) RED HOOK, N.Y. -- March 03, 1999 -- PET-ALLERGY, 3-03 --
Hemingway, left, and Wolfie, pose next to a selection of air
purifiers. Healthcare professionals will usually recommend getting
rid of a pet if its owners show signs of any allergic reaction to
the animal. However air cleaners can provide relief and allow the
owner and pet to co-exist. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DENVER -- March 03, 1999 -- CIR-NEIGHBORHOOD-SITES, 3-03
-- Dan du Bois, executive director of the Lower Downtown District,
Inc. and supporter of Denver's Neighborhood Link Program, sits on a
street in the historic Highlands neighborhood in January. The
Neighborhood Link program provides web sites for neighborhood
associations to post news about their communities. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NORWALK, Conn. -- March 03, 1999 -- CIR-USED-COMPUTERS,
3-03 -- Benno Schapira, of Computer Renaissance, at his store which
sells used computers and hardware. Computer Renaissance is a
franchise operation that buys and sells new and used computers from
240 stores in the United States and Canada. Eighty of them were
added in 1998 and another 80 are expected in 1999. (Janet
Durrands/New York Times Photo)
</P>
