</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- March 03, 1999 -- GREENSPAN-SOCSEC, 3-03
-- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan testifies before the
House Commerce Sub-committee about reforming the Social Security
system on Wednesday. If budget surpluses now are going to help pay
for Social Security in the future, the key issue confronting
Congress is how to make sure the extra money is somehow saved,
Greenspan said. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- March 03, 1999 -- CLINTON-DEMS, 3-03 --
President Clinton is applauded during a rally at the Library of
Congress attended by Democrats on Capitol Hill on Wednesday. The
unity rally was held to emphasize the Democrats post-impeachment
agenda. Clinton is flanked by House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, left, and his counterpart in the Senate, Tom Daschle.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-4, 3-03 --
Frida Kahlo's blue studio near Mexico City. Kahlo's family home was
expanded when her husband, painter Diego Rivera, added the studio
for her. Given Rivera's emotional past, crowded with liaisons,
separate studios for the two painters amounted to spatial wisdom.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- March 03, 1999 -- CIR-GAME-SHARK, 3-03 -- The
Game Shark, for Nintendo 64 video games, contains hundreds of cheat
codes. Interact has sold two million pieces of the plastic and
silicon that plug into the back of a Sony Playstation or the
cartridge slot of a Nintendo 64 to give the player invincibility,
extra weapons, superpowers and access to hidden areas and bonus
levels. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MEDFORD, Mass. -- March 03, 1999 -- VENTURE-TALENT-BOS,
3-03 -- Rina Spence, interim chief executive of Consensus
Pharmaceuticals Inc., a start-up biotechnology company, sits near
Jack Lai, working at a peptide synthesizer. Spence began her
working life as a junior high school teacher, ran a health
management organization, was president and chief executive for 10
years at a big suburban hospital, and then turned entrepreneur,
opening a chain of women's health clinics. More than just a
personal odyssey, Spence's current transition is emblematic of
major changes occurring in how key jobs are being filled at many of
the promising young companies that get their initial bankroll from
venture capital funds. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- March 03, 1999 -- SOUL-TRAINING-BOS, 3-03 --
Ray Barrieau looks at his portrait of his 16-year old son Jonathan
who was killed in car accident a year ago. Barrieau is part of a
group of 130 people attending a three-and-a-half day forum of
intense self-examination hoping that it will help them smooth out
cracks in their relationships with families, friends and
co-workers. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-NY-2, 3-03 --
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton during a visit to a school in the
borough of Queens on Wednesday. Mrs. Clinton's visit to New York
came amid increasing speculation about her possible run for the
Senate seat of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who
is retiring. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-NY, 3-03 --
Flanked by students, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton looks at
artwork during a visit to a school in the borough of Queens on
Wednesday. Mrs. Clinton's visit to New York came amid increasing
speculation about her possible run for the Senate seat of Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who is retiring. (Fred
R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- SUPER-BRIGHT-HEADLIGHTS,
3-03 -- Cars stopped at an intersection demonstrate the difference
between standard headlights, right, and those using new High
Intensity Discharge (HID) technology. The new lights emit a broad
field of intensely clear light closely approximating the spectrum
of daylight. Darkness is banished as the car drives forward into
its own private pocket of renewable daylight. (Thomas Dallal/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-3, 3-03 --
Frida Kahlo's work space in the blue studio near Mexico City. A
portrait of the artist is at right. Kahlo's family home was
expanded when her husband, painter Diego Rivera, added the studio
for her. Given Rivera's emotional past, crowded with liaisons,
separate studios for the two painters amounted to spatial wisdom.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-2, 3-03 --
Diego Rivera's 1932 studio with his portrait of Dolores Del Rio.
Rivera's life was a legend wrapped in scandal surrounded by myth
that played against the backdrop of Technicolor buildings as if he
was a figure walking through one of his own heroic canvases.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MEXICO CITY -- March 03, 1999 -- DIEGO-RIVERA-1, 3-03 --
Diego Rivera's red studio brought modernism to Mexico City.
Rivera's life was a legend wrapped in scandal surrounded by myth
that played against the backdrop of Technicolor buildings as if he
was a figure walking through one of his own heroic canvases.
(Sergio Dorantes/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) RED HOOK, N.Y. -- March 03, 1999 -- PET-ALLERGY, 3-03 --
Hemingway, left, and Wolfie, pose next to a selection of air
purifiers. Healthcare professionals will usually recommend getting
rid of a pet if its owners show signs of any allergic reaction to
the animal. However air cleaners can provide relief and allow the
owner and pet to co-exist. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DENVER -- March 03, 1999 -- CIR-NEIGHBORHOOD-SITES, 3-03
-- Dan du Bois, executive director of the Lower Downtown District,
Inc. and supporter of Denver's Neighborhood Link Program, sits on a
street in the historic Highlands neighborhood in January. The
Neighborhood Link program provides web sites for neighborhood
associations to post news about their communities. (Kevin
Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NORWALK, Conn. -- March 03, 1999 -- CIR-USED-COMPUTERS,
3-03 -- Benno Schapira, of Computer Renaissance, at his store which
sells used computers and hardware. Computer Renaissance is a
franchise operation that buys and sells new and used computers from
240 stores in the United States and Canada. Eighty of them were
added in 1998 and another 80 are expected in 1999. (Janet
Durrands/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
