</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SEC-PREVIEW04-COX     03-03 1797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SEC-PREVIEW04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auburn, Florida building powers
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Outside Humphrey Coliseum, Starkville, Miss., loomed
like the end of the world, even more than usual. Thunder roared.
The heavens burst, and rain gusted across the Mississippi State
campus. Lightning crackled and lit the landscape like
hell-or-come-high-water noon. Yet the most otherworldly phenomenon
was happening inside The Hump.
</P>
<P>
   In a hallway outside the visitors' locker room, a splendid point
guard named Doc Robinson was autographing a poster and T-shirt
heralding the 1999 SEC regular-season champions. Ladies and
gentlemen, your _ Auburn Tigers? What in the name of Babe McCarthy
is going on here?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of our goals to come in and win the (SEC) West,''
Robinson said Saturday after Auburn punctuated the most remarkable
regular season in school history with its 26th win, surviving State
76-73. ``Now that we've won both the West and the regular season,
we want to move on to bigger and better things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win the SEC Tournament, and we want to make a real
strong statement in the NCAA Tournament,'' said Scott Pohlman,
Auburn's skinny sophomore shooting guard from Roswell. ``The sky's
the limit for this team. It's been a dream of mine forever to go to
the Final Four. I think we have a team that can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pohlman is neither alone nor a loon. As the SEC Tournament opens
today in the Georgia Dome, the consensus favorite isn't perennial
pick Kentucky, but Auburn. Since the Tigers last danced in the NCAA
Tournament in 1988, every other SEC team has been to the NCAA's at
least twice. Now Auburn arrives with a 26-2 record, a No. 4
national ranking and a likely No. 1 seed in an NCAA regional in its
hip pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can do it at South Alabama, you can do it anywhere,''
said Tigers coach Cliff Ellis, who wrought similar miracles in
Mobile and later Clemson before coming to Auburn in 1994. ``That's
South Alabama, with no _ nada _ tradition. And Clemson was the
doormat of the ACC.''
</P>
<P>
   And Auburn basketball was an after-football afterthought at a
football-mad school in a pigskin-crazed conference. Look now. Ellis
has made hoops matter in the land of King Football. He, too, is not
alone. The SEC East titleist? Tennessee, which dethroned Kentucky
on Sunday for its first championship since 1982 and its first
season sweep of the 'Cats since '79. And if Florida hadn't stumbled
in overtime at Vanderbilt on Saturday, Kentucky would have finished
third in the SEC East behind Billy Donovan's kids from Steve
Spurrier's school.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that one-point loss, Florida (19-7, 10-6 SEC) is the
second-most improved team in the SEC. The Gators were 14-15 last
year, 6-10 in the SEC. Auburn, of course, made a quantum leap of
Chris Porter proportions: from 16-14 (7-9) to 26-2 (14-2) and the
school's only SEC title since 1960. ``It's a league that, because
of its football success, has a chance to be successful in
anything,'' Florida The trick, though, is sustaining it.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn went to five NCAA tournaments in a row, 1984-88, but
never before and not since. Florida reached its first Final Four in
1994 and returned to the NCAA Tournament in '95. But the Gators
then suffered three losing seasons in a row and have experienced
what Donovan and Foley call ``pockets of success.'' Until Norm
Sloan took Florida to three consecutive NCAA tourneys, 1987-89, and
won the school's lone SEC title in 1989, the Gators had never made
the national tournament. Foley did what Auburn did: hired the right
man for the job. Ellis, now 53 and 20 years older than Donovan, was
48 when Auburn hired him. The school initially wanted a young Duke
assistant named Mike Brey. When Brey went to Delaware, Auburn
turned to Ellis, with his sweater vests and a penchant for
developing big men and singing beach music. Ellis first recorded
while a student at Florida State, as the lead singer for a group
called ''The Villagers.'' He later sang with Roy Orbison, Charlie
Rich, Delbert McClinton and Etta James and cut two CDs while
coaching at Clemson, where he won the school's lone ACC
regular-season title in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Until this season, the only Big Dance at Auburn was the shag
Ellis loves so dearly. But Ellis has been implementing the
five-year plan that came to fruition at South Alabama and Clemson.
Auburn's football heritage never daunted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can cut a record at 17,'' Ellis said, ``write a book at
29 (on basketball coaching), go from junior high to Cumberland
College, you never doubt yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The zone press featured in the book helps Auburn wear down
opponents and features Porter frenetically guarding the inbounds
passer. Porter is the 6-foot-7 junior power forward who couldn't
qualify for Auburn out of high school, attended Chipola Junior
College in Marianna, Fla., and now is the SEC Player of the Year.
But it's Robinson, the son of Selma whose signing Ellis calls the
key to Auburn's success, who is largely responsible for Auburn's
SEC-best turnover margin of plus 7.5. ``If there's a better college
point guard ...,'' Ellis says about Robinson, ``he's the college
point guard.'' The result: a 17-0 start before a 72-62 loss at
Kentucky, where three Tigers played with the flu, most notably
Robinson, and eight more wins before a 104-88 loss at Arkansas on
Senior Night. That dropped Auburn from No. 2 _ its highest ranking
since reaching No. 2 for a week in 1959 _ to No. 4. Auburn has
embraced these Tigers with such fervor that home games sell out and
afterwards fans roll Toomer's Corner with toilet paper. Just like
after football games. ``This sounds cheesy and corny, but watching
them, they motivate me,'' said Amy Bryant, an Auburn senior. ``With
all the, you know, stuff that's been going on with the athletic
department, I think the basketball team has shown how we can rise
above the bad situations with (football). The basketball team is a
good metaphor for what this university is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gainesville, meanwhile, that basketball team also is proving
that basketball can co-exist with football. Not that Donovan ever
doubted that, or himself. ``The one thing about the University of
Florida is people love the Gators,'' he said. ``All the sports here
have competed on a national level. I'm not coming in here with the
attitude I'm going to make this a basketball school. It's a
national sports school.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also Billy the Kid's school, at least to basketball
recruits. ``Recruiting's the name of the game here,'' Foley said.
``And the key component there is Billy.''
</P>
<P>
   That was quickly apparent to Foley when he interviewed Donovan
immediately after Kruger bolted for Champaign in March '96. Donovan
had just completed his second successful season at Marshall,
employing the same run-and-gun-the-three, full-pressure style he
had learned under Rick Pitino as the star of Providence's unlikely
1987 Final Four team and then had coached while an assistant to
Pitino at Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick told me (that), of all the people he'd coached and had
coached with him, Billy knew his style of play best,'' Foley said,
``because he'd played and coached in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley also was taken by Donovan's personality, youthful
exuberance and straightforwardness. ``I felt comfortable with him,
and I thought parents and recruits would feel comfortable with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was mutual. ``I trusted Jeremy,'' Donovan said. ``I
was talking to a straight-shooter. ... The big thing here was the
lack of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   That was symbolized by the O-Dome _ O'Connell Center, the
12,000-seat, Teflon-roof dome that was rarely filled and seldom
daunting for opponents. ``When I first got this job, people told
me, 'You've gotta get a new building.' I think this building has
been pretty good to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That building was deafening the night of Feb. 4, soliciting this
critique from Kentucky coach Tubby Smith after Florida's 75-68
upset: ``We've never played in a tougher arena.'' Indeed,
basketball has become a game of hoarse in the O-Dome, where the
Gators were 14-1 this season and where Florida fans are now as
vocal, and vulgar, as their football counterparts. The reason is
three-fold: three-pointers galore, including 17 in last week's
89-61 annihilation of South Carolina; the kids who fire 'em up; and
Donovan, whose slicked-back black hair renders him Eddie Munster
reincarnate. And Eddie Munster, who knows he's recruiting
teenagers, not traditionalists, is creating a monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key is recruiting,'' Donovan said. ``You want to
put up borders around the state.'' Unlike Kruger, who was crushed
when Vince Carter of Daytona Beach chose North Carolina over
Florida, Donovan has managed to keep much homegrown talent at home.
First, sophomore forwards Brent Wright and Major Parker. Then, this
year's celebrated freshman class that includes three Floridians:
center Udonis Haslem, shooting guard LaDarius Halton and Teddy
Dupay, who alternates at point guard and is the poster boy for
Donovan's in-state allure. Dupay committed to Florida after his
sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good reputation in the state, so if I committed maybe
(other Floridians) would come,'' said Dupay, who loved Donovan's
style of play. ``Being (that it was) a football school, it took
some guts. I broke the ice. Other players didn't have to do that. I
did it for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Donovan to achieve his goal _ ``to win a national
championship'' _- he also has to venture afar. ``You've got to get
some guys that are strong enough to leave their home state and not
feel any pressure about doing it,'' he said. He first found one in
6-8 swingman Mike Miller, the McDonald's All-American from South
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's aggressive recruiting of Miller caused Kansas coach
Roy Williams to complain _unsuccessfully _ to the NCAA. Now Donovan
has signed West Virginia guard Brett Nelson, the state's best
prospect since Jerry West; and Matt Bonner, a coveted 6-9 forward
from New Hampshire. Their recruitment prompted South Carolina coach
Eddie Fogler to complain _ unsuccessfully _ to the SEC and led to
an ugly, preseason feud in which Fogler questioned Donovan's
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem was I never got a phone call from either
coach,'' Donovan said. ``That definitely bothered me. The NCAA's
looked into it. The SEC's looked into it. Nothing came out. We
didn't do anything (illegal).'' Just as Auburn has done, the Gators
have spawned a cultural revolution in a stronghold of King
Football. ``The fans have really responded,'' Foley said. ``And if
Billy can deliver the kind of product he can, that culture will
change. Hopefully, forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
