<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Web Makes It Easy to Get Tax Software, Send Forms to IRS  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
You can shop on the Internet, chat on the Internet, get your news
on the Internet, even apply for a job on the Internet. So it stands
to reason that you also can use the Internet at tax time.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you need an obscure IRS form or complete tax preparation
software, it can be downloaded from the Web to your personal
computer. And you can even do your taxes right on the Internet,
without any packaged software at all.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, whether you prepare your taxes using commercial
software or a Web-based program, you can file your return
electronically _ a move that can halve the time it takes to get a
refund.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the IRS is pushing heavily for people to file
their taxes electronically. It helps the agency cut costs and
reduces the number of errors made in processing returns.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good bet, though, that taxpayers are more motivated by
the prospect of a quick refund than by making life easier for the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, according to the IRS, 24.6 million taxpayers filed
electronically. The majority went to professional tax preparers who
created and filed returns for them.
</P>
<P>
   But an increasing number of individuals are taking tax matters
into their own hands. Some 8 million taxpayers last year used their
computers to prepare and file their taxes, and the number is
expected to rise substantially this year.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of electronic filing suggests that consumers
aren't worried about possible security dangers involved in sending
sensitive tax information across cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing electronic filing go up every year because it's
getting easier and less costly,'' said Gina Rodriquez, an editor
with Spidell Publishing, which publishes a newsletter for
California tax professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there may be reason for concern, especially since you
can't electronically file directly to the IRS. Instead, you must
send your return to a third-party ``transmitter,'' who then sends
it into the IRS computer system. Leading transmitters include
Intuit, the maker of TurboTax software, and Nelco, which processes
returns for Kiplinger TaxCut and many professional tax preparers.
</P>
<P>
   The reason the IRS can't accept returns directly is that its
computers aren't capable of guaranteeing security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with a 1960s computer system that still uses
tape drives,'' said IRS spokesman Larry Wright. ``Third-party
transmitters are equipped to handle security, and the IRS isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little threat to information as it's being sent over
the Internet, because it's scrambled prior to transmission with a
state-of-the-art encryption code. It's when a return is sitting in
a transmitter's computer that it's at the highest risk of being
hacked. And it can sit there for up to three years to satisfy
government record-keeping regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more steps you have between the consumer and the IRS, the
more likelihood you have for vulnerabilities,'' says Internet
privacy expert Ira Winkler.
</P>
<P>
   Security aside, the Internet really takes the pain out of
dealing with Uncle Sam in several ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Tax software: &LR;  Basic versions of TurboTax and TaxCut, the
leading tax preparation programs, can be purchased and downloaded
online. TaxCut is available for $19.95 at  &LR; www.taxcut.com. &LR; 
TurboTax, at $29.95, can be downloaded from  &LR; www.turbotax.com. &LR; 
Those versions are for federal returns. State versions also can be
downloaded for an extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   The programs also are available in CD form at retail stores. And
you can buy deluxe multimedia versions of the federal programs that
boast extra help with tax planning.
</P>
<P>
   TaxCut and TurboTax offer similar features. They both walk you
through an interview to determine your tax status, number of
dependents, etc., and they both calculate your taxes as you enter
financial information. In addition, you can override the automatic
controls and fill in forms directly.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs produce crisp, clean printouts that can be mailed
directly to the IRS. Or you can file electronically, either over
the Internet or by taking your completed return on a disk to a
professional tax preparer. Filing electronically typically costs
around $10 if you do it yourself, and more if you go to someone
else. TaxCut is offering a rebate to cover its $9.95 online filing
fee.
</P>
<P>
   This year TaxCut may be a better value than TurboTax. Not only
is it less expensive, but if you buy the deluxe version, you can
download the software for your state return for free. With
TurboTax, you have to buy the state program in addition to the
federal program.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Web-based programs:  &LR; The Web-based version of TurboTax, which
you'll find at  &LR; www.webturbotax.com,  &LR; is the leading
tax-preparation site online. It gives you most of the features of
the TurboTax CD program, without the hassle of having to install
any software.
</P>
<P>
   WebTurboTax's major competitor is SecureTax.com from Universal
Tax Systems &LR;  (www.securetax.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Both WebTurboTax and SecureTax.com let you try before you buy.
That means you can create your return for free _ you only pay if
you decide to print or electronically file it. WebTurboTax charges
$19.95 for a regular 1040, while SecureTax charges $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Free filing:  &LR; If your adjusted gross income is under $20,000 a
year, you can use the Web version of TurboTax for free (including
filing). Similarly, TaxCut , which doesn't have a full-fledged
Web-based program, offers a 1040EZ form on its Web site that's free
to anyone who qualifies to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Free tax information and advice is plentiful on the Net. The IRS
maintains an extensive Web site  &LR; (www.irs.gov),  &LR; which includes all
forms, regulations and publications for the current tax year.
Materials can be downloaded for free, although you'll probably need
Adobe's Acrobat Reader software to view and print them. (You can
download that program at no charge from Adobe at  &LR; www.adobe.com &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Other good destinations for tax information include Yahoo's Tax
Center ( &LR; biz.yahoo.com/taxes &LR; ), and the tax planning area in
America Online's Personal Finance channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
