 Column: Ins, Outs of ADSL Technology  &HT;       
 By David Einstein  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Lately, I have been hearing quite a bit about ADSL for
high-speed Internet access. I am in the market for a new computer
and would like it to be able to use ADSL. Are there any special
hardware requirements? Also, how does one go about getting ADSL and
what does it cost?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  ADSL _ short for asymmetrical digital subscriber line
_ is a technology that lets you access the Internet at speeds at
least 50 times greater than you get with a 28.8 Kbps modem. It's
always on, so you don't have to dial each time you want to surf the
Web. And you can use the phone at the same time you're online. ADSL
currently is available from local phone companies in many
communities across the country, including most areas of California.
</P>
<P>
   Any new PC is capable of using ADSL, but you will need some
extra equipment, to wit: an ADSL modem, a network card to connect
the modem to the PC and a device called a splitter that connects
the modem to your telephone line. The easiest way to get this stuff
is to buy it from the phone firm that provides the ADSL service.
Pacific Bell, for instance, offers installation plus hardware for
under $200.
</P>
<P>
   As for the service itself, Pac Bell recently lowered the price
of ADSL with Internet access to $49 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Color Me Confused
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you explain in easy-to-understand language the difference
between 16 color, 256 color, 16-bit color and 24-bit color? These
are all options for my Windows video display. I'm currently using
256 color. Would one of the other settings be better?
</P>
<P>
   A: The number of colors displayed on your monitor depends on the
number of bits used to represent each pixel. A bit is the smallest
piece of data used by a computer. A pixel (a contraction of
``picture element'') is the smallest element on a video-display
screen.
</P>
<P>
   The more bits used to represent a pixel, the more colors can be
generated. The standard these days is 256 color, which uses eight
bits. If you go to 16-bit color, also known as High Color, you'll
have 65,536 colors. And 24-bit color, also known as True Color,
gives you up to 16.8 million hues. Why anyone would need that many
is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   How many colors you can display depends on a number of factors,
including your monitor, the amount of video memory in your PC and
the screen resolution you're using. If you want more colors, you
may have to settle for lower resolution, and vice versa. To get
16.8 million colors at a high resolution like 1,024 by 768 pixels,
you'd need 4 megabytes of video memory. But even if you only have 1
Mbyte, you can have a sharp picture by choosing High Color and 800
by 600 resolution.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail From Abroad
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm going to Greece and Italy for five months, and I need to
be able to send and receive e-mail from my laptop while I'm abroad.
I also need to be able to connect to my e-mail account with my
employers. What are the options?
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of COMPUTE0 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  A: Here's what I'd do if were lucky enough to spend a few months
near the Mediterranean. As soon as I got settled in, I'd get an
Internet account from a local access provider. Then, I'd create a
free e-mail account for myself using Hotmail  &LR; (www.hotmail.com)  &LR; or
any of the big portals _ Yahoo, Excite, Infoseek, etc. _ all of
which offer it. I'd then configure my free e-mail so that I could
check my office mail. (To do that, you must know the name of your
company's incoming mail server, plus your log-on ID and password.)
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of other options, both of which are too
expensive to warrant much consideration. One is international
roaming, which your current Internet service provider may offer. It
lets you sign onto your Internet account using the phone number of
a local ISP in a foreign country. But it costs extra _ around 10
cents a minute. Roaming really is good only for business travelers
who are constantly hopping around.
</P>
<P>
   The other alternative is to get an America Online account (if
you don't already have one) before you leave the States and dial
into your account through a local AOL number in Greece or Italy.
But this also will cost you 10 cents a minute, on top of your
regular AOL rate. Like roaming, this solution is best for visiting
a foreign country, not living in it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Everyone knows that Windows comes with a simple calculator. But it
also can be a scientific calculator capable of solving complex math
problems. To access it, go to
Start/Programs/Accessories/Calculator. In the calculator's View
menu, choose Scientific.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
