<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Microsoft to Unveil Strategy to Best Rivals in E-Commerce  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Microsoft Corp. has been an also-ran in the fast-growing field of
electronic commerce, but the company's top two executives, Chairman
Bill Gates and President Steve Ballmer are coming to town today to
try to leapfrog the competition.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning briefing at the Argent Hotel for analysts and
reporters, Gates and Ballmer will unveil Microsoft's new
``electronic commerce strategy'' to help companies do business on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the Redmond, Wash., software giant expect
the strategy to include a new plan to offer tools and services to
help small businesses set up e-commerce sites on the Web through
Microsoft's MSN.com ``portal'' site, which was originally intended
as a consumer-oriented site competing with the likes of America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is also expected to announce e-commerce alliances with
companies like MasterCard International and to highlight business
services that will come with the new Windows 2000 operating system
upgrade to Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Microsoft wasn't going to break new ground but was
rather repackaging itself for the expanding world of Internet
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   It's a huge market: E-commerce sales are expected to hit $133
billion in 2000 and $202 billion in 2001, according to Zona
Research of Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has uncharacteristically been slow to articulate and
develop a cohesive strategy on how it's going to play in the
e-commerce space,'' said Dwight Davis, an analyst who tracks
Microsoft for Summit Strategies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft would only say that Gates and Ballmer will brief
analysts and reporters about the company's new strategy, ``new
technologies and initiatives'' and Gates' ``vision for the future
of the digital marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM has been more successful in marketing its image as a company
that provides business-to-consumer services, said Jack Staff, chief
economist for Zona Research, which was briefed on Microsoft's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MICROSOF () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Microsoft offered similar services through its consumer and
server software but has not done a good job making that known to
businesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web services aimed toward small- and medium-size businesses
will be another attempt to ``make Microsoft more visible as an
e-commerce power,'' said Rob Enderle, analyst at Giga Information
Group in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of MICROSOF () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
