<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETBILL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bill to Build the Internet Focuses on Speed, Spam  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
A sweeping bill to accelerate Internet growth without regulating
the fledgling market is expected to be introduced in Congress this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan legislation would encourage large-scale
availability of high-speed Internet connections for consumers,
place a lid on spam and require the use of ``digital signatures''
for all online commercial transactions. It also may place strict
limits on how Web vendors collect personal information from their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a regulatory measure. It is a a measure to foster
Internet development,'' said Representative Rick Boucher, D-Va.,
who is co-chairman of the House Internet Caucus and co-author of
the bill with Representative Bob Goodlatte, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   The far-ranging bill addresses several hot-button issues for the
Internet, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Bandwidth. &LR;  The cornerstone of the bill would push for
deployment of blur-fast broadband networks to Internet service
providers and, consequently, to consumers, businesses and
educational institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Internet to achieve its potential as a multimedia
platform for voice, video and data, the connection speeds have to
increase,'' Boucher said. ``Unfortunately, most people still rely
on dial-up modems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bandwidth is a topic of fierce debate in the Internet industry,
where America Online and Yahoo are lobbying cable companies to sell
room on their broadband networks _ which are up to 100 times faster
than standard telephone-line connections _ to ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission indicated this year that
it won't require cable operators to share high-speed Internet
access with competitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Spam.  &LR; Based loosely on a new California law that levies daily
fines of up to $25,000 against junk e-mailers, the
Boucher-Goodlatte bill would establish the first national law to
curb unsolicited commercial e-mail. Internet users have
consistently listed spam as one of their biggest headaches, yet
only a handful of states have bills outlawing the marketing
practice.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Digital signatures.  &LR; This virtual verification system makes it
nearly impossible for individuals to pose as someone else while
making a purchase via the Internet. The added layer of privacy is
likely to assuage the fears of consumers who have doubts about the
security of online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most of the Internet community will examine this and
agree it is an important step for federal policy,'' said Boucher,
who has discussed details of the bill with Internet service
providers, telephone and cable companies, telecommunications
suppliers and consumer organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those companies like what they have heard so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boucher and Goodlatte are friends of the Net,'' said Jill
Lesser, director of domestic public policy at AOL in Dulles, Va.
``They understand the importance of the industry self-policing
itself and, hopefully, will strike the right balance between
regulation and legislation that either prohibits online abuses like
spam or encourages the wide use of broadband services.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some _ like Alex Fowler, director of public affairs at
the Electronic Frontier Foundation in San Francisco _ are skeptical
about how the bill can satisfy the wishes of so many competing
companies in the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative marks a major shift for the 100-member Internet
Caucus, which was formed in 1996 at the height of debate over the
anti-cyberporn Communications Decency Act but has operated almost
exclusively as an ad hoc group where Senate and House members
discuss high-tech issues.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher _ who co-founded the caucus with Senator Conrad Burns,
R-Mt., Senator Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., and former Representative Rick
White, R-Wash. _ predicted that it will become a leading source of
Internet legislation on Capitol Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
