<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTGOMERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Montgomery Sales Up 80% in January  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Despite the loss of key personnel and speculation that its business
was eroding, NationsBanc Montgomery Securities' revenue in January
soared 80 percent above the previous year's level, according to
people close to the San Francisco investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, a unit of North Carolina's BankAmerica, booked
income of approximately $75 million during the month, with
brokerage revenue rocketing 146 percent and investment banking
income edging up 1 percent, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   For the three months ended in December, Montgomery's revenue
fell 13 percent from the year before to a little over $175 million.
The drop reflected the stock market meltdown in October, which
brought capital-raising activity nearly to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, for the four months ended in January, Montgomery's
revenue rose 3 percent to a little over $250 million, with
brokerage income up 89 percent and investment banking income down
38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The firm doesn't release specific revenue figures, but a
spokeswoman confirmed the general accuracy of the information.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Montgomery chief executive Thomas Weisel quit
the firm he helped found nearly three decades before in a dispute
with the parent company, then known as NationsBank, over control of
key business lines.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 employees, including several senior partners, joined
him in starting a new investment bank, prompting speculation that
Montgomery's business had been crippled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery is doing much better than expected,'' said Michael
Flanagan, an independent securities industry analyst based in the
Philadelphia area. ``The numbers don't suggest the diminution of
franchise value.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said Montgomery's brokerage operations, buying and
selling securities for institutional investors, is going
gangbusters, reflecting recent sharp gains in stock market volume.
Meanwhile, its business of raising capital and providing merger
advice to corporations is just holding its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've maintained market share in all key products,''
Montgomery chief executive Lewis Coleman said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONTGOME () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The firm's ability to hold its investment banking practice
together is due in part to business it has won from BankAmerica
clients. For example, last month, it helped manage the $300 million
public stock offering of San Francisco's Del Monte Foods.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals said Montgomery has lost business in such traditional
areas of strength as technology and health care because of the
resignations of senior investment bankers and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery is fighting to recoup traditional business by
recruiting high-profile staff members. On Tuesday, it announced it
had hired Deutsche Bank Securities star Internet analyst Alan
Braverman, filling a vacuum left by the defection of David
Readerman to Weisel's new firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
