r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      03-03 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Column: Cnet Tiptoes Into E-Commerce, But Can It Avoid
Amazonian  Mistakes?  By Dan Fost  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Memo to Cnet: Step carefully into e-commerce. It's a minefield for
a media company.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Amazon.com, which was roasted for putting its book
reviews up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Amazon is primarily an online store, so its ``ethical
lapse'' is forgivable, or at least understandable.
</P>
<P>
   But Cnet holds itself up as a &UR;  &LR; media company providing news and
reviews, even as it aggressively adds e-commerce elements. Cnet
actively posts links to sites selling products that Cnet reviews,
taking a commission on each referral (but not the actual sale).
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cnet ponied up $5.8 million for AuctionGate
Interactive, sort of a small-scale eBay for consumer-to-consumer
auctions of computer products. And in February, Cnet paid $12.1
million for NetVentures, an e-commerce software firm. Last year,
Cnet launched its own e-commerce site, Shopper.com, and it also
owns 16 percent of e-tailer BuyDirect.com.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of toes dipping into the e-commerce waters. How can
a company high on its first profitable year resist the urge to
Amazon-ize?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a media company, we've been, from day one, very aware of
... what the church and state line is,'' said Matthew Barzun, 28,
senior vice president of Cnet Online. (How can a 28-year-old be
senior anything? Easy _ Barzun was the company's third employee
five years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Barzun conceded that the line between church (editorial) and
state (advertising/e-commerce) is thin in the online world, but he
asserted that ``it's a bright shining line. You cannot buy
editorial influence.''
</P>
<P>
   That's important because as e-commerce grows, it threatens to
overtake advertising as the Web's main economic engine. Cnet draws
most of its revenue by selling ads on its site, but most Internet
companies now seek their bread-and-butter through direct online
sales to consumers or other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Cnet is not immune to the siren song of e-commerce. ``I doubt
Cnet could sustain its stock price based on advertising revenues
alone,'' said Barry Parr, an analyst with IDC (and a former Cnet
executive).
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MEDIA04 (98635 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Cnet's new front page, launched Monday, steers readers of its
high-tech reviews to links to purchase the gadgets and gizmos. From
Cnet.com, a user can click to see reviews of digital cameras and
then click on ``latest prices'' for the Kodak DC 200. That leads to
a chart with links to 21 online retailers. The first three on the
list _ NECX, HardwareStreet.com and Egghead.com _ have little
colored ads, and the next two, Virtual World and Computers4Sure,
are in bold. Ads for the rest, presumably companies that didn't pay
extra, are in a regular typeface.
</P>
<P>
   Gasp! That sounds like priority listings! But is it a conflict
of Amazonian proportions?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a media company, all you do is stand between buyers and
sellers,'' Barzun said. ``It doesn't mean that to say where to buy
something is dirty. That's what people want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the chart can be sorted by price, so the paying
advertisers could land much lower on the list.
</P>
<P>
   When Amazon.com's review policy was discovered, it landed on the
front page of newspapers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   If Cnet betrays its trust, you'll hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAN'T STOP THE PRESSES &LR; : When mistakes happen, online media
have an edge over publications printed on dead trees: They can wipe
the story out of existence.
</P>
<P>
   Or can they? Even though Cnet's News.com pulled an inaccurate
story within an hour of its posting last week, someone else had
already snagged the story _ and posted it on his own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened: First, News.com reported on a dispute
between Apple Computer and a Canadian teenager who had registered
the domain name  &LR; www.appleimac.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Then in a follow-up piece, the site erroneously reported that
Apple apparently had registered the domain name  &LR; www.traya.net &LR;  _ a
name similar to the teen's tiny consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Apple, which had declined comment on the follow-up story,
had not registered  &LR; www.traya.net &LR; . Instead, it was Ben Reser, a
21-year-old software author in Issaquah, Wash. Reser, who had
followed news of the teenager's dispute with Apple, said he was
only joking when he registered the domain name with Network
Solutions, falsely claiming that he was a representative of Apple
Computer.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MEDIA04 (98635 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  News.com fell for the joke. Then it acted responsibly, yanked the
erroneous story and posted a correction on its front page.
</P>
<P>
   End of story _ except that Reser had already made a copy and
posted it at  &LR; www.traya.net &LR; . He accused Cnet of erasing the error
the way Soviet bureaucrats rewrote history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once they publish something, it should stay. It makes
them responsible for what they publish,'' Reser said.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail, Beth Lipton, an editor at News.com, wrote, ``We
removed the story because it was written on a premise that turned
out to be false. For Apple's sake and to avoid confusion, we did
not want to perpetuate the mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ICONOCAST &LR; : With five employees and 36,000 subscribers to
his free e-mail newsletter, Iconocast, serial entrepreneur Michael
Tchong launches his fourth startup with an invitation-only South of
Market party tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Tchong, whose most notable achievement was the founding of the
late, lamented MacWeek, says his new venture, also called
Iconocast, will offer contrarian thinking on the links between
advertising and Web publishing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  He won't say what the new venture will be, exactly; he's
saving that for tonight. But you can bet its home will be in
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOURNALISM PAYS &LR; : Journalism is not a career that typically
pays big bucks, but James Cramer is not a typical journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Cramer, the hedge fund guru who is a co-founder and columnist at
TheStreet.com, will earn $250,000 a year in salary, according to
TheStreet's filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't even count his 400,000 stock options, which should
dwarf the salary.
</P>
<P>
   Time for all ink-stained wretches to ask for a raise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Media Bytes will appear every Thursday in The San Francisco
Chronicle. Send buzz, dirt, tips and comments to fostd(AT
SIGN)sfgate.com, call (415) 777-6004 or fax (415) 543-2482. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
