<SLUG> BC-LEISURE-WORLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEISURE WORLD BECOMES CALIFORNIA'S NEWEST CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. _ The residents of the Leisure World
retirement community here voted on Tuesday to transform their gated
patch of ``God's country'' into California's newest city, with
surely one of its oldest populations.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the 18,000 residents of the city, to be
called Laguna Woods, is 77. Laguna Woods, encompassing the
retirement community and some surrounding businesses, will be one
of the few towns in the United States where more than 90 percent of
the population is over 55.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the election tells us something about what local
government will look like in the 21st century,'' said Mark
Baldassare, a professor of urban and regional planning at the
University of California at Irvine. ``Leisure World gives us a view
into the future of California. As the state ages and more and more
of the population is 65 and older, government will increasingly be
influenced by older voters, and older voters will increasingly be
elected to office.''
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's election, which followed a state certification
process that took more than a year, Leisure World not only opted to
become a city but also chose a five-member City Council that was
sworn in Wednesday and will now get down to work on tasks like
selecting a mayor and hiring a city manager.
</P>
<P>
   One of those elected was Victor Kay, a 79-year-old retired
accountant who grew up in New York City. Kay said he was excited
about his new city, although he regretted that his wife of nearly
40 years was not alive to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we moved here 12 years ago, my wife called this an
Eden,'' Kay said. ``She said she came here to die, and that's what
she did in 1993. She loved it here, and so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Leisure World has been part of an unincorporated area
of Orange County _ the mailing address is Laguna Hills _ and the
county has administered most services. Now the brand-new City
Council will itself have to tend to contracting for police and fire
services.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said he had nonetheless supported cityhood, partly in the
name of local control and the chance to keep more tax dollars in
the area. But a bigger reason was to give Leisure World's residents
greater say in the heated battle to stop a proposed commercial
airport on the site of the 4,700-acre El Toro Marine Corps Air
Station, which will soon be closed. Now, Kay said, Laguna Woods
will be able to join seven other cities in a united front against
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the vote,'' he said, ``we didn't really have a voice.''
</P>
<P>
   But while opposition to the airport and its accompanying noise
is widespread among the people of Leisure World, there was also
significant opposition to becoming a city. Critics of the idea,
arguing that Leisure World had been running smoothly for 35 years,
saw no need for a change, and worried that the costs of running a
city would increase taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't need it,'' said Harold Woods, who has lived at
Leisure World since retiring nine years ago from his job as a union
official in Los Angeles. ``Now we're going to have five City
Council people, and that's just another layer of government.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Tuesday was close. The polls closed at 8 p.m., and
90 minutes later the count was dead even. ``If cityhood failed, it
would have been because of a bunch of old fogies,'' Gloria
Marienthal, 73, said Wednesday before getting into a pool to work
out with her synchronized swimming team. ``Many people are just
simply afraid of change.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 10:30 p.m., Mrs. Marienthal felt like celebrating. With
all 32 precincts counted, 51.7 percent of the 10,000 or so voters
were in favor of incorporation, and 48.3 percent were opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Laguna Woods will become a city on March 24, with nearly all its
residents living behind the gates of Leisure World, which will
retain its name. But the city itself will not be gated. About 60
businesses that make up the bulk of the new city's tax base, from
fast-food restaurants to a home repair warehouse store, lie outside
the gates.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, there are swimming pools, tennis courts, riding stables
and comfortable homes that rest on rolling green hills and range in
price from $60,000 to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful place to live,'' Mrs. Marienthal said. ``This
is God's country. And I want to keep it that way. That's why I
voted for change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
