<SLUG> BC-EBAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 You Still Can Buy Weapons On eBay  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Despite its recent ban on firearms sales, online auctioneer eBay
yesterday had a missile, a bazooka, a rocket launcher and other
military weapons up for bid.
</P>
<P>
   The auctions raise the question of how much control, if any,
eBay has over its site.
</P>
<P>
   On February 19, the San Jose auctioneer announced that it would
no longer allow the sale of guns or ammunition. The company said it
would no longer take such listings starting February 26, and that
all existing auctions for firearms must be complete by March 5.
</P>
<P>
   However, an auction for a ``live new military tear gas grenade
... that will stop anything that breathes'' began Sunday. (High bid
last night, $202.)
</P>
<P>
   And an auction for a World War II bazooka rocket launcher
started Tuesday. (Current high bid, $175).
</P>
<P>
   Both auctions are advertised to end on Sunday, after tomorrow's
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   When told about the auctions by The Chronicle yesterday, an eBay
spokesman said his company ``will take them down immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The items listed are ``solely the responsibility of the
lister,'' said eBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that eBay, the leading online auction house, has no
prior notice or control over what individuals put up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, eBay has relied on its users to police its site
and notify eBay when they spot contraband.
</P>
<P>
   Also up for sale yesterday: a ``Classic Nike Ajax surface-to-air
guided missile'' that is 32 feet long and weighs about a ton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great yard ornament,'' the sellers advertises. ``Beats the
pink flamingos any day.''
</P>
<P>
   This auction has welcomed more than 8,000 visitors, but only
three bidders, including one who has offered $2,400 for the
missile.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of these items are advertised as disarmed,
firearms experts said weapons that have been deactivated or
dismantled can often be rearmed or reconfigured so they will fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just astounding to me,'' said Representative Anna
Eshoo, D-Atherton, when she saw the missile and bazooka for sale on
the Web site. ``It takes your breath away.''
</P>
<P>
   Eshoo said she is no expert on weaponry, but she was concerned
that some of the items advertised might be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the responsibility of the DOD (Department of Defense),
FBI (Federal Bureau of Investigation) and ATF (Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms) to be on this,'' she said. ``I'm going to get
on them (these agencies).''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers aren't supposed to own most military weapons in the
first place, according to a spokesman for the Department of
Defense. Although restrictions were looser during World War II and
soldiers may have carried guns home with them, sales of military
surplus have been strictly controlled since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never sell these things to private citizens. Either
somebody stole them or brought them back from overseas or just
found them and kept them,'' said DOD spokesman Glenn Flood. ``The
Department of Defense does not sell items like that to individual
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dodd, founder of auctionwatch.com, who spotted the bazooka
for sale, said he was surprised to see the weapon because of eBay's
recent and well-publicized firearms ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all boils down to whether eBay is going to take
responsibility for the auctions that occur on its site.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, eBay disclosed that it is being investigated by a
federal agency for sales that occurred on its Web site. Published
reports have said the probe involves the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms, but neither eBay nor the ATF would comment
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, government authorities in New York City,
Pennsylvania, Florida and Oklahoma have investigated alleged fraud
by buyers and sellers on eBay. In some cases sellers have
advertised items falsely or failed to deliver paid-for merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of EBAY04 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
