<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HMOS-NONPROFIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE OFFICIAL TO CHALLENGE HMOS' NONPROFIT STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Responding to a growing outcry from elderly HMO
subscribers who can't afford to pay for prescription drugs,
Massachusetts Secretary of State William F. Galvin said Wednesday
he will challenge the right of Massachusetts health maintenance
organizations to keep their tax-exempt, non-profit status.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said in an interview the HMOs' decision last year to
terminate 50,000 elderly Medicare subscribers' unlimited
pharmaceutical benefits was ``the flag that suggested to me they
are not existing as a nonprofit might for the benefit of its
members.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to behave like businesses, perhaps they
should be treated as businesses,'' said Galvin, whose office
registers corporations. ``They have made the decision that they
want to behave more like for-profits, and the prescription drug
issue is just one example.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin, state legislators, and advocates for the elderly said
they have been flooded recently with calls from desperate elders
who are reaching the limits of the substitute drug benefits the
HMOs provided. ``We're being deluged,'' said Rep. Harriette
Chandler, a Worcester Democrat who cochairs the Joint Health Care
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The key problem is that some elders have catastrophic drug costs
that are no longer covered by any program. The average outpatient
drug cost for the 21,382 Medicare recipients enrolled in Harvard
Pilgrim's First Seniority plan last year was $1,153, according to
an article published in the current New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   However, 10 percent of the First Seniority enrollees had average
medication costs of $3,953. Various studies have shown that capping
drug coverage ends up costing far more in avoidable hospital and
nursing home stays, noted Stephen B. Soumerai and Dennis
Ross-Degnan, two Harvard Pilgrim researchers who wrote the article.
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of tradeoff that Kathy McFarland is currently
weighing. McFarland, a 67-year-old woman who lives with her
diabetic 76-year-old husband in subsidized housing in Marlborough,
has stopped taking an antibiotic for a urinary tract infection
because ``it's not life-threatening.'' She may decide to stop
taking her costly osteoporosis medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I fall and break my hip, I'm not going to die from
osteoporosis,'' McFarland said. ``But I have to take my heart
medication. My husband has to take his diabetes medication and he
has to take his medication for an esophagus condition. And compared
to us, there are people who are really bad off.''
</P>
<P>
   One Central Massachusetts woman reportedly threatened suicide
because she couldn't get needed medications. ``An HMO
representative, who finds it very difficult to keep saying `no, no,
no,' told me he had to keep this woman on the phone until he could
get suicide intervention,'' said Janice Long of the Marlborough
Council on Elder Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Long told of a couple on Medicare who have prescription drug
costs of $2,146.61 per quarter-year, far beyond the $200 per
quarter that the First Seniority program now allows. They do not
qualify for a ``transitional aid'' program that HMOs have made
available to pay drug costs beyond that because their income is
$28,000, above the $21,700 eligibility limit for a married couple
under the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gentleman was in my office the other day and he was all
swollen because he had stopped taking his blood pressure
medication,'' Long said. ``He said, `I'll give my drug allowance to
my wife to keep her alive.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation has just about exploded,'' Galvin said of the
calls to his office in response to a consumer fact sheet on
Medicare HMO drug coverage published by his office. ``I don't think
it's an exaggeration to say the situation has become
life-threatening for many people.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state's decision stunned HMO representatives.
``We have not been notified, which we find to be amazing, given the
importance of this discussion,'' said Patti Embry-Tautenhan of
Harvard Pilgrim, the state's largest HMO. Tufts Health Plan and
Fallon Health Plan, the state's other large non-profit HMOs,
declined to comment or did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Blue Cross-Blue Shield operates under a unique
statute that grants it non-profit status. But Galvin claims the
Massachusetts statute that governs HMOs does not necessarily
entitle any of them to claim non-profit, tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said he will call a hearing in the next few weeks at
which Massachusetts HMOs can argue to retain their non-profit
status. Calling himself the ``chief corporate law enforcement
officer,'' he said the secretary of state has the legal authority
to determine if corporations can be registered as nonprofit.
</P>
<P>
   If Galvin remains unpersuaded by the HMOs' arguments, he said he
will ask Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly to bring an action in
Superior Court ``to restrain them from conducting business not
authorized by the commonwealth, which would force them to
reorganize.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observers said that, whatever the legal basis of Galvin's
challenge, Massachusetts HMOs are in a politically precarious state
because of public reaction to the elder drug benefit decision on
top of more general disaffection with managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the HMOs are very vulnerable to this kind of
question,'' said Geoff Wilkinson, executive director of
Massachusetts Senior Action Council, an advocacy group that is
leading consumer groups' efforts to pass remedial legislation.
``There's a lot of public anguish and outrage at what they've done
and what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts HMOs had been required by a nationally unique
state law to provide an unlimited prescription drug benefit to
Medicare beneficiaries. But Federal District Court Judge Richard H.
Stearns ruled last October that federal Medicare law, which does
not require such coverage, trumped the Bay State law.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently Massachusetts HMOs decided not to extend the
unlimited drug program voluntarily, as a chorus of state officials
and consumer groups had pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs replaced the popular unlimited-drug benefit with a
no-premium program of coverage capped at $125 to $200 per quarter,
depending on the health plan. Elders with incomes below $16,000 for
an individual and $21,700 for a couple qualify for additional
coverage, but they must first spend $300 per quarter and pay out of
their own pockets for prescription drugs and get reimbursed later _
a requirement that advocates say puts medication out of reach for
such low-income elders.
</P>
<P>
   Early reaction to the gauntlet flung by Galvin was decidedly
mixed, even among those critical of HMOs. ``They're painting the
HMOs as the bad guys, and I'm not sure I agree with that, even
though I'm not their greatest friend,'' said one legislator,
requesting anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, the Health Care Committee co-chairwoman, said: ``I
think it will be an interesting debate, but I don't think it's
going to solve the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bullen, the state's commissioner of medical assistance
defended Massachusetts' non-profit HMOs. ``I think we should think
twice before we go after them on this issue,'' Bullen said.
``Certainly there is a difference between our not-for-profit HMOs
and the national for-profits, with their quarterly reports and
their stockholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullen also took issue with Galvin's statement that the
situation of elders' prescription drug coverage amounts to a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see an immediate crisis,'' Bullen said.
</P>
<P>
   Most elders' medication needs can be met, he said, by the $500
to $800 yearly benefit HMOs are currently offering for free, plus
an additional $1,000 out of their own pockets that elders used to
pay for the now-defunct unlimited drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real question becomes how do we make a catastrophic drug
benefit available for those with quite expensive drug needs,''
Bullen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
