<HEADER>
A6903 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     03-03 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUBBLE, BUBBLE, SELECTION TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In recent weeks, Pac-10 coaches and officials have
proclaimed the league worthy of five NCAA Tournament bids. ``Either
Cal or Oregon should make it, because the league deserves five
bids,'' they say. Or: ``If the Big Ten is getting seven, we deserve
at least five.''
</P>
<P>
   Phooey.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 deserves nothing, just like the Big Ten and ACC and
Southeastern Conference deserve nothing. The Pac-10's stellar
performance in recent NCAA Tournaments _ national titles in 1995
and 97, four Sweet 16 participants in '97 and '98 _ has no bearing
on its potential at-large bids this year.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Committee, which picks,
seeds and places the 64 teams, has two goals: to pick the best
field and balance the four regions.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime Saturday night or Sunday morning _ after seeding and
placing the conference champs like Stanford and obvious at-large
entries like Arizona and UCLA _ the selection committee will
evaluate the so-called ``bubble teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington probably has secured a bid despite two losses in Los
Angeles, but Oregon and Cal are in tenuous positions. They'll be
compared to other bubble teams, like Minnesota, Nebraska and
Rutgers, and current credentials _ not past performance _ are the
only criteria: power ratings, good wins, bad losses, strong
finishes. On Selection Sunday, everything is earned.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Oregon has better power ratings, while Cal has better
wins (North Carolina, Arizona, UCLA). Both teams are 7-9 in
conference and probably need to finish 9-9 for an at-large berth.
They meet Saturday in Eugene, with space on the dance floor at
stake.
</P>
<P>
   How will the field look? Nineteen conferences will get one bid:
America East, Big Sky, Big South (Winthrop), Big West, Colonial
(George Mason), Ivy (Penn), Metro Atlantic (Siena), Mid-Continent
(Valparaiso), Mid-Eastern Athletic, Midwestern Collegiate
(Detroit), Northeast (Mt. St. Mary's), Ohio Valley (Murray State),
Patriot, Southern (Charleston), Southland (Texas-San Antonio),
Southwestern Athletic, Sun Belt (Arkansas State), Trans-America
(Samford) and West Coast (Gonzaga).
</P>
<P>
   The 45 remaining slots will be divided among the power
conferences and several middle-tier leagues, like the Missouri
Valley and Mid-American, that might get multiple bids.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Coast: The nation's best conference has one team for
the ages (Duke), one team for today (Maryland), one team for
tomorrow (baby-faced North Carolina), and a bunch of mush.
Brilliant at the top, mediocre in the middle, bad at the bottom,
the ACC gets three bids unless N.C. State or Wake Forest win two in
the league tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic-10: With that suffocating zone, Temple once again tops
the list of ``teams you don't want to play in the first weekend.''
Otherwise, there's not much to fear here. Xavier and George
Washington will get at-large spots, while Jim Harrick and Rhode
Island must win the A-10 tourney.
</P>
<P>
   Big East: Connecticut, Miami and St. John's will be high seeds
regardless of league-tournament results. Villanova's in, but
Rutgers _ yes, Rutgers _ needs a tourney win to secure an at-large
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten: The possibility of eight entries collapsed with
Northwestern, leaving the Big Ten with seven bids and a bunch of
first-round losses. There is no greatness here, just ubiquitous
mediocrity. Wisconsin, Purdue and Minnesota have played poorly of
late, but their lofty power ratings _ generated by the conference's
overall power rating _ indicate they'll dance anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12: The poor man's Big Ten, bland as can be, yet watch for
the Big 12 to get five or six bids. Oklahoma, Kansas, Texas,
Oklahoma State and Missouri are in. Let's hope Nebraska is not.
Next.
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA: Two locks (Cincinnati, Louisville), one probable
(DePaul) and one bubble (UNC-Charlotte). C-USA could have had a
fifth entry, except Alabama-Birmingham imploded in February. At
least there's some spice here, with DePaul's wondrous freshmen,
Cincinnati's strongmen and Louisville's great escape from
postseason probation.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-American: This league is dominated by Captain Consonant,
Miami-Ohio's Wally Szczerbiak, but Kent should get an at-large bid.
Combined, they'll win at least one game in the tournament, perhaps
two.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Valley: The rise of the mid majors continues here, with
Evansville and Southwest Missouri State joining tourney champ
Creighton in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10: If Auburn or Michigan State lose in their conference
tournaments, Stanford might return to a No. 1 seed. A fourth seed
might be on the line Saturday in Tucson when Arizona and UCLA
clash, with the loser getting a No. 5. Washington has slipped to an
eight or nine after its dreadful showing in L.A. And give Cal a
bid: Its seniors will be the difference on the Oregon Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern: If you could attend one conference tournament,
this would be it: Arkansas, Florida and Tennessee have proven they
can beat the heavyweights. Auburn has a No. 1 seed at stake.
Mississippi is in, but Mississippi State has faltered and needs two
tourney wins. Watch for Kentucky to play its first-round games in
New Orleans (Midwest Region) because ticket sales are slow.
</P>
<P>
   Western Athletic: Reputation and glib coaches mask the truth:
This is a one-team league (Utah), no better than the Mid-American
Conference. Texas Christian played its way out of the NCAAs with a
horrible loss to BYU on Tuesday night. Fresno State blew its chance
when it lost at home to Utah. And let's hope the NCAA has more
sense than those inept Associated Press voters who keep putting New
Mexico in the top 25. The only thing the No. 89 (Sagarin) Lobos
deserve is to spend next weekend at home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
