<HEADER>
A6904 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TABLE-SETTINGS-TEX     03-03 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TABLE-SETTINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO WILD FOR PRIDE OF PLACE SETTINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JUNE NAYLOR RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tree frogs on the dinner table? Crouton-size diamonds scattered
across a salad plate? Why not? Set an outrageous table, and your
dinner guests will remember the evening forever.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with such strategy, the legion of designers who
participated in the recent sixth annual Fort Worth Design
Inspirations turned three rooms at Shady Oaks Country Club into a
55-table showplace.
</P>
<P>
   No concept was over-the-top. No idea was considered too
outlandish. Take ``Frog Frenzy,'' the table fashioned by Fort Worth
designers Holly Lydick and Monique McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   Their jungle-ish creation offered a towering centerpiece with
stalks of fresh, green reeds reaching nearly 3 feet high with
asparaguslike tops. On intermittent plates were pairs of tiny live,
chirping tree frogs beneath bronze-colored dome screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veranda'' was the name given to the table crafted by Molly
Moon Ogden Interior Design. Around a rambling, hodgepodge
arrangement of fine leather volumes and polished, dark wood boxes _
providing the feel of a richly hued study _ were formal place
settings. Each contained a stack of delicate, floral-patterned
china, an extensive arrangement of antique silver flatware and a
mix of crystal stemware and shining pewter goblets.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy K. Taylor, a designer for Pacetti de Medici Precious
Jewels of Dallas, called her table ``Playing Dress Up.'' Four
pieces of crystal stemware graced each setting, as did antique
Tiffany flatware bearing a fancy Audubon design. A tumble of a
dozen or so faux diamonds as big as dimes and quarters flowed
across each plate.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as centerpiece was a 2-foot-by-3-foot stick-figure
mannequin, wrapped in black tulle and draped in about a million
dollars' worth of shimmering bracelets and necklaces. (Not that
this is recommended at home, unless you don't mind an armed guard
standing duty while you entertain _ as this jeweler did at Design
Inspirations.)
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL MATTERS
</P>
<P>
   It's an overused film gimmick: the rube who breaks into a sweat
looking at all the forks at his place setting. Flatware shouldn't
be a threat, especially because you need plenty of it to live in a
civilized fashion.
</P>
<P>
   CHOOSING IT:
</P>
<P>
   Flatware and silverware mean essentially the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   When selecting your pattern or style of sterling or silverplate,
be sure it's something you'll love for years and years. Sterling is
what becomes heirloom and has better endurance than silverplate.
</P>
<P>
   Stainless is the most affordable choice; 18/8 is the quality you
need, meaning it has 18 percent chrome and 8 percent nickel.
</P>
<P>
   You'll want a look that blends with or complements your china
and crystal.
</P>
<P>
   The basic setting includes salad and dinner forks, dinner knife
and teaspoon. The next additions are tablespoon, butter/pastry
knife and tall drink (also called iced tea) spoon, followed by
demitasse spoon and appetizer fork for a more formal setting.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the serving pieces: cake server, gravy ladle,
serving fork, pierced spoon, salad servers, sugar spoon and various
serving spoons.
</P>
<P>
   USING IT
</P>
<P>
   If you received all that marvelous flatware for wedding gifts
(or were blessed with an inheritance), you need to quit being
intimidated by it. The surest way to do that is to plan a lovely
dinner, invite people whose company you really enjoy, and put that
beautiful silverware to use.
</P>
<P>
   Forks go on the left, knives and spoons on the right. Work from
the outside in, in the order they will be used. Shrimp forks will
be used before salad forks, which are used before dinner forks, and
a butter knife will be used before a dinner knife. Get it?
</P>
<P>
   Each place gets its own butter knife, and a master butter knife
is used, as well. Guests use the master butter knife as it is
passed with the butter, then their own knives when buttering their
own bread.
</P>
<P>
   Center the dessert forks or spoons above the dinner plates so
they won't be used until later and won't be confused with the other
utensils.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the cutting edge of the knife toward the plate. Don't
question this, just do it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
