A6906 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     03-03 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACHES DESERVING OF COMBAT PAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Discontent is spreading like a virus. At this rate
it won't be long before the blue flu replaces groin pulls or
concussions as the pox of professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   From North Carolina to Southern California the duped, the
defenseless and the down-and-out are sick, they're leery, they're
growing weary of their lot.
</P>
<P>
   In Charlotte, Dave Cowens calls himself underappreciated and
underpaid. ``I don't need millions and millions of dollars,'' he
says. ``I just want to be paid fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Blackhawks general manager Bob Murray fires Dirk
Graham less than one season into his first head-coaching stint,
then says, ``We set him up to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Jimmy Johnson is riled by the firing in one day of
five of his NFL head-coaching peers. ``It's a shame,'' he says,
``when coaches' jobs are dependent on injuries, skyboxes, people in
the stands and officiating calls. It doesn't give me a good feeling
about our profession.''
</P>
<P>
   In L.A., Del Harris loses his job despite drawing the Lakers
ever near to NBA championship contenders each of his first four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, Kurt Rambis, doesn't need his old, thick,
black-rimmed glasses to see the writing between the lines of his
contract. ``I'm the next Laker coach to be fired,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The way things are now, a player can get caught buying drugs in
the shadows of Disneyland and, backed by his union, keep his job
through at least the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A coach, on the other hand, can't even buy time if his team is
decimated by injuries or wallowing in youth.
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's as inevitable as the next pink slip; one day
coaches of professional sports teams will rise like a Ruslan Salei
slapshot, a Roger Clemens fastball, a Rex Chapman 3-pointer.
They're going to get ornery as Bill Romanowski and spit at the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, bless their stingy, idiosyncratic, insensitive
souls, won't know what's hit them when the coaches band together to
form The Instructional Workers' Union.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine having to dig to the root of a team's failings instead
of simply sawing off the weakest branch.
</P>
<P>
   Consider not being able to fire a coach simply because he can't
fashion a champion out of chintz. Or because he's prone to
long-winded lectures that settle in his players' ears like wax. Or
because he's just not hip or (fill in the blank) enough.
</P>
<P>
   If physicians are finding unions to be the right prescription
for workplace indignities, why not coaches? Just as managed care
has a lot of doctors questioning their calling, coaches at the pro
level find themselves grappling with issues of autonomy and dignity
and diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   No one is immune.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Robinson has won five Stanley Cup rings as a player and a
sixth as an assistant coach. Still, he definitely could use a shot
in the arm about right now. His Kings have lost 248 man-games to
injury _ compared to 89 at this time last season _ and are fighting
to stave off a premature death.
</P>
<P>
   They entered Wednesday's game against the Ducks at the Pond five
points out of the eighth and final playoff spot. Some days Robinson
has reason to wonder whom exactly his players are battling,
seventh-place Edmonton, eighth-place San Jose, ninth-place Calgary
or themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One King recently suggested there are people in the room who
have tuned Robinson out. Say this about the Lakers' Kobe Bryant; he
at least had the good grace to wait until after Harris was fired to
admit as much.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, in his fourth year with the Kings, recognizes when
players ``aren't looking at you, they're looking through you.'' The
day he feels like Casper the Ghost in front of his players is the
day he'll slip out the back door and get on with the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I felt my message wasn't getting across,'' Robinson said,
``I'm a strong enough person to say they don't appreciate what I'm
doing anymore. I have too much respect for (general manager) Dave
Taylor and (president) Tim Leiweke and (owners) Philip Anschutz and
Ed Roski just to stick around.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson realizes there's a reason he currently has the
third-longest coaching tenure in the NHL, behind Scotty Bowman (six
seasons in Detroit) and Ron Low (five seasons in Edmonton).
</P>
<P>
   ``In hockey there's only so many ways you can teach, only so
many drills you can do,'' Robinson said. ``When some guy's
constantly saying the same things it becomes very, very repetitive.
Players do turn you off after a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the best coaching aid is to have someone, maybe
three or four guys, lead from within. You can get more done from
peer pressure than from the coach barking every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers didn't have the leadership in the locker room to save
Harris' voice or his job. Robinson will find out in the next 20
games whether or not he has any co-pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were flying high after making the playoffs last year.
This year, with so many key players in a holding pattern because of
injuries, the front office has gotten a truer reading of the team's
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of guys who had career years in 1997-98 lost their way at
the first jolt of heavy turbulence this season. To Yanic Perreault,
Craig Johnson, Vladimir Tsyplakov, et al: Mayday! Mayday!
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someday there'll be a safe harbor for Robinson. But for
now, the distress he feels is his alone to bear. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEILLOR-BOPS-VENTURA-     03-03 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEILLOR-BOPS-VENTURA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRISON KEILLOR PUMMELS JESSE VENTURA WITH LOW BLOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is a point in some books when satire gives way to outright
meanness. Maybe, like the Supreme Court justice trying to define
pornography, readers can't quite explain why they know something.
They just do.
</P>
<P>
   Which means readers will recognize that ``Me: By Jimmy (Big Boy)
Valente,'' Garrison Keillor's supposed ``just having a little fun''
mock-book about Jesse Ventura, the pro-wrestler-turned-governor of
Keillor's beloved home state of Minnesota, is, frankly, nasty.
Maybe Keillor didn't intend it that way. Maybe he thought that he
and Gov. Jesse could laugh about it later over a few dozen mugs of
beer.
</P>
<P>
   Nah.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of ``Me,'' like that of most exercises in negative
innuendo, is deceptively simple. Former wrestler Jimmy (Big Boy)
Valente has been elected governor of Minnesota. Eager to cash in on
his political success, he negotiates a book contract that includes
the whiny services of ghost writer Garrison Keillor. Much of the
book consists of Jimmy insulting Keillor, all the while spinning
ever-wilder yarns about his childhood, military experiences and
wrestling career, in which he pretended to fight other behemoths
for the entertainment of intellectually challenged wrestling fans.
</P>
<P>
   The real-life Keillor does some fictional stretching meant,
perhaps, to be lighthearted. Ventura's service in the Navy SEALS is
transformed into Jimmy's leadership of the top-secret WALRUSES
(Water Air Land Rising Up Suddenly). In Vietnam, Jimmy befriends a
turncoat Viet Cong with whom he eventually ends up on the Alaskan
wrestling circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Keillor mostly confines himself to one-liners (the
Walruses, for instance, are taught ``how to avoid venereal disease
by using raspberry jam and sauerkraut juice''). These offer the
author the advantage of creating certain visual images without
having to explain anything further. Writers do this kind of thing
when they really have nothing to say but want to get enough words
into print to fill up a book.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Keillor exactly extends himself in that direction,
either. The miniature ``Me'' clocks in at 152 pages, and most of
those pages are filled as much with cartoonish illustrations as
printed paragraphs.
</P>
<P>
   Keillor didn't have to wonder long whether Jesse Ventura would
like ``Me.'' The Grappling Governor wondered publicly if he could
sue, arguing that Keillor's book infringed on the ring character
Ventura had created. Learning that he couldn't _ governors are
classified as public figures, fair game for any writer who wants to
take a cheap shot _ Ventura grumbled and went back to working on
his own book, which industry scuttlebutt has coming out next year,
although no contract has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, let's ask ourselves a few basic questions about
``Me.''
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Does it humorously point out any truths about modern
American politics?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Does it offer any sense of affection for its real-life
subject?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope, again.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Is it at least fun to read?''
</P>
<P>
   Odd thing, that; with ``Me,'' Keillor proves it is possible to
spend 45 minutes reading a very short book cover-to-cover and still
end up thinking you wasted too much of your life in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
