</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTEL-REORGANIZE-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TOP EXECUTIVES LEAVING MATTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two top executives, including the chief operating
officer, are leaving Mattel Inc. as part of a sweeping management
reorganization announced Wednesday by the struggling toy maker.
</P>
<P>
   The company's second-ranking executive post _ that of chief
operating officer, which is now held by Bruce Stein _ will be
eliminated. Instead, the company said it would have five
business-products units headed by presidents who will report
directly to Jill Barad, Mattel's chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The other executive leaving is Gary Baughman, president of the
company's Fisher-Price subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel, the world's largest toy maker, based in El Segundo,
Calif., near Los Angeles, is trying to retool itself as a broader
children's products concern. The reorganization comes as Mattel
tries to recover from a series of disappointing earnings reports
and a decline in sales in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While a big part of the problem stemmed from cutbacks in
inventory by Toys ``R'' Us and other retailers, some analysts said
that Barbie, the 40-year-old core product, is showing signs of age.
Mattel's wholesale shipments of the doll were down 14 percent last
year, although the company says that retail sales increased.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel is in the process of buying Learning Co., a software
manufacturer, for $3.8 billion, a transaction that would make
Mattel the second-largest consumer software company behind
Microsoft. It is also broadening its distribution beyond stores to
catalogs and the Internet, helped by the acquisition last year of
Pleasant Co., a mail-order doll business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the process of transforming Mattel from a
traditional toy company with four core brands to a children's
products company,'' Ms. Barad said in a statement explaining the
reason for the management changes. The new structure, she said,
would have fewer layers of management and allow for faster
decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   ``The departure of Bruce and Gary is most painful for me, as I
have great respect for both of these men,'' Ms. Barad's statement
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Stein, a seasoned toy-industry strategist, was
greeted warily by investors. Mattel's shares, which have been
tumbling, fell 75 cents Wednesday, to $24.75, well below their
12-month high above $46.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Stein, 44, said that ``at this point in my
career, I felt I needed a new challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said Stein could be taking the blame for Mattel's
recent problems, including the earnings disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested that he was leaving because of disputes with
Ms. Barad, whose assertive management style is said to have
contributed to the departures of several other high-level
executives in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barad takes great interest in product planning and
marketing, even though those activities were officially Stein's
province.
</P>
<P>
   It was she who spearheaded the acquisition of Learning Co., said
Michael Perik, the software company's chief executive, who said he
had never even met Stein. Perik said the acquisition was still on
track and would not be affected by the changes at Mattel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Stein was recruited by Ms. Barad in 1996 to help bolster the
boys' toy business at Mattel, a company that has traditionally been
strongest in girls' toys. He earned credit for integrating Tyco
Toys, which was purchased in 1997, but under his watch, Mattel lost
out to Hasbro in the battle over the license for Star Wars toys.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who is also resigning from Mattel's board, has been both
friend and rival to Ms. Barad for two decades. In the early 1980s,
he was in charge of the Mattel account at the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather
advertising agency. He joined Mattel in 1985 and ran boys' toys
when Ms. Barad was in charge of girls' toys. It was her success in
building the Barbie line that led to her being named chief
executive in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, in the meantime, left Mattel and became head of the
Kenner Products subsidiary of Hasbro, where he introduced hit
products based on such movies as ``Batman'' and ``Jurassic Park.''
He became president and chief operating officer of Marvel
Entertainment Group in 1994 but left after four months. He was then
a consultant to Dreamworks SKG, the film studio, and president of a
Sony Corp. division in charge of the American marketing of the
Playstation video game.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman, 52, came to Mattel as part of the company's 1997
merger with Tyco Toys. Mattel took a $27 million charge against
1998 earnings to cover a recall of the Fisher-Price Power Wheels
cars, which were catching on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fisher-Price remains the company's best known brand name
for the preschool market. So in the reorganization announced
Wednesday, all preschool toys will be sold under the Fisher-Price
brand. The expanded Fisher-Price division will now be headed by
Neil Friedman, who had been president of the Tyco Preschool
division.
</P>
<P>
   The other four units created by the reorganization are
Boys/Entertainment, to be run by Matt Bousquette, which includes
various toy cars as well as toys based on Disney and Nickelodeon
characters; Girls/Barbie, to be headed by Adrienne Fontanella;
Mattel Media, which will include software and the interactive toys
made in partnership with Intel Corp., to be be run by David Haddad,
and Pleasant Co., which will continue to be run by its founder,
Pleasant Rowland, who will also help with direct sales of other
Mattel products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
