</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHATCOM-RESULTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHATCOM ALMOST BROKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the latest in a series of grim financial
statements, ChatCom Inc. officials say the company faces bankruptcy
unless it can quickly come up with some cash.
</P>
<P>
   Third-quarter sales were down 61 percent from a year ago and the
company, which makes computer network servers, lost more than
$600,000 on sales of $594,000.
</P>
<P>
   ChatCom has developed what its officials say is an innovative
new computer server, called BriteStar, that can readily connect
machines operating on different software platforms with one
another. But the company has been unable to finish the work and get
BriteStar into production because revenue has been dwindling along
with sales of its other products.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to find business partners willing to shoulder some of
the financial burden have been unsuccessful, as have attempts to
find a buyer for ChatCom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company anticipates that it will be forced to seek relief
in the bankruptcy courts this month if it is unable to immediately
secure short-term financing,'' ChatCom officials said Wednesday in
a joint statement filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   E. Carey Walters, the chief executive brought in last year to
try to sell ChatCom, said he has downsized the staff from about 50
employees to 21 in an attempt to cut costs. ChatCom also moved to
smaller offices when its lease expired last fall.
</P>
<P>
   But without a cash infusion soon, Walters said, the firm will
have to turn to bankruptcy court. And still more money will be
needed to market BriteStar, the one jewel in the company's crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could basically ship (BriteStar) in 90 to 100 days,''
Walters said. ``We have a prototype which we're reworking. ... We
just need some fuel to get it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ChatCom shares closed down 1.3 cents, or 17.33 percent, to 6.25
cents on volume of 500 shares traded Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
