<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-TRENDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYING WITH THE NEXT BIG THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KELLY DeGARMO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Furby, we hardly knew ye. And now we're on the hunt again,
looking for the hottest, newest, most sensational toy. At New
York's American International Toy Fair, we joined toy buyers on the
quest to uncover this year's
stand-in-line-and-then-shell-out-the-cash toy wonder. We previewed
thousands of toys, many of them mechanical prototypes. Whattaya
want for 1999? Here are our top three picks.
</P>
<P>
   CHAT PALS
</P>
<P>
   Using cutting-edge technology (and, of course, lotsa batteries),
Winnie the Pooh and Tigger (too) come to life as never before. Kids
activate the plush toy by squeezing its paw. The Chat Pal responds
by telling jokes, playing games, asking questions and singing
songs. Thanks to a combination of microphone and radio-frequency
technology, the Silly Old Bear and his friend ``hear'' your child's
patter and turn their little fuzzy heads in response. Rumor has it
that Piglet will be the next character in the line, which is
expected to expand next year.
</P>
<P>
   For ages 4 and up. Mattel, $40. Available in October.
</P>
<P>
   CD-ROM PLAY SETS
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the popularity of last year's Tonka and Star Wars
Playsets, Hasbro is adding four kinds of CD-ROM play sets this
fall. The plastic play sets strap onto most standard computer
keyboards to combine hands-on play with the effects of multimedia
software.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the most curious is the Easy-Bake Oven play set.
Little bakers create virtual cakes and cookies with the help of the
play set's toy appliances, including a mixer, measuring cup,
rolling pin, cookie cutter and more. Kids learn to follow a recipe
without making a mess. Of course, no mess also means none of those
odd-tasting little treats loved by those of us raised with the
old-school Easy-Bake.
</P>
<P>
   Look also for the Playskool Store play set, featuring a cash
register, virtual cash (couldn't we all use some?) and other store
items, and for the Nerf Jr. play sets, which use a new light-pen
technology. A hand-held interactive toy connects to the PC's
gameport to simulate an arcade experience.
</P>
<P>
   Age 3 and up. Hasbro Interactive, $30-$40. Compatible with
Windows 95/98. Available this fall.
</P>
<P>
   TECH DECK FINGERBOARDS
</P>
<P>
   Created by a 12-year-old California boy (and already at the
fingertips of all of the cool kids in Manhattan Beach),
fingerboards are miniature skateboards, complete with real grip
tape, adjustable trucks, axle nuts and replaceable wheels. In a
word, fingerboards rock. Easy to pocket, the miniature boards can
be manipulated with fingers on a desktop, driveway, tray table or
anywhere else. Kids can buy or make their own accessories, such as
a half pipe. The boards are relatively cheap (in the ballpark of
the dusty old Beanie Babies), which means that kids will probably
want to trade and collect them.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 8 and up. XConcepts, $6. Available now.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Furby? The interactive plush Pooh Chat Pals are
expected to be one of this year's top Christmas toys. Look, Mom, no
mess! With the Easy-Bake Oven CD-ROM play set, kids create virtual
treats.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
