r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-VALENZUELA-LADN     03-03 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VALENZUELA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENZUELA'S ARREST `A SHAME'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ News of Pat Valenzuela's arrest on suspicion of armed
robbery left the jockey's old Santa Anita friends surprised _
though hardly shocked _ and nostalgic for the days before drugs
dimmed the teen-age star.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a shame for such a talent to fall so far,'' said trainer
Ted West, for whom Valenzuela rode Interco to victory in the 1984
Santa Anita Handicap. ``Pat was a natural. Horses just ran for him.
He was one of the top five riders in the country when he was riding
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he threw it all away.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, 36, who won the Santa Anita Handicap aboard Sir
Beaufort in 1993, probably will be in the Los Angeles men's central
jail when the historic race is run Saturday. He was held on $75,000
bail Wednesday after being arrested Friday and identified by a taxi
driver as the man who robbed him at gunpoint of $150 two days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela pleaded not guilty in a court appearance Tuesday. A
March 15 preliminary hearing is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   According to Deputy District Attorney Leonard J. Torrealba, the
cab driver said he was picking up a passenger Friday at a Rosemead
bar called Spike's, in the area where the crime occurred, when he
spotted Valenzuela wearing the same jacket and hat as the robber.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did what they say he did, that's the drugs,'' said
trainer Bob Baffert, who called Valenzuela so personable, ``he was
his own best agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, born in Colorado to a family of jockeys and
trainers, recorded his first victory at 16 and won the 1980 Santa
Anita Derby aboard Codex at 17. After his first bout with cocaine
addiction, he won the 1989 Kentucky Derby aboard Sunday Silence,
and promoted the ``Just Say No'' campaign in a post-race press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   But his career was to be marked by his drug problems as much as
his accomplishments _ six Breeders' Cup victories, six winners in a
day at Santa Anita in 1988, riding titles at all three major
Southern California tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Drug-related absences led to suspensions as long as nine months,
and then an arrest on spousal-abuse charges in 1997 prompted
California racing officials to ban him indefinitely. Valenzuela
hasn't competed since October 1997 at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit rock bottom three times,'' said jockey Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Divorced three times, he has been living in El Monte, apart from
his four children.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela's charisma earned him live mounts in each of his
comebacks. And racetrack associates said Wednesday they'd heard he
planned to seek yet another chance.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also rumblings that Valenzuela, who once signed a
$1 million contract to ride for owner Allen Paulson, had sold his
Kentucky Derby trophy and other mementos, and was asking former
rivals for loans.
</P>
<P>
   Don Murray, director of a racetrack support program for
substance abusers, said he last spoke with Valenzuela when the
jockey phoned in January, ``asking how other people were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's got a great heart,'' Murray said. ``He's just got a
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
