<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE IN ALABAMA IS DISSOLVING IN TUG OF WAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., S.C., Texas, N.C., Va., Tenn.)   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Alabama Legislature dissolved into chaos and
paralysis this week as the state's newly elected lieutenant
governor, a Republican, used a quick gavel on Tuesday to snatch
power from the Democratic majority in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The coup in Montgomery incited such ear-splitting animus on the
Senate floor that a 5-year-old visitor was reduced to tears. It led
a Democratic leader to call the lieutenant governor, Steve Windom,
``a madman'' and to talk of impeaching him before the close of his
first day as presiding officer of the Senate. In protest, the
Democratic majority boycotted Wednesday's session, which adjourned
for want of a quorum, and then filed a lawsuit against Windom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been different,'' said McDowell Lee, who has watched all
manner of political wrangling during his 36 years as secretary of
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The discord in Alabama reflects the growing pains of two-party
politics in southern legislatures, which until recently have been
Democratic preserves where Republicans could only carp from the
backbenches. But Republicans now control at least one legislative
chamber in Florida, South Carolina, Texas and Virginia and they are
close enough in North Carolina, Tennessee and Alabama to wield
significant influence.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, Democrats hold a 23-to-12 margin in the Senate. But
five Democrats elected with heavy support from business interests
have allied with the Republicans, giving the Democrats an actual
majority of only 18 to 17. In addition, Alabama voters elected
Windom last November as the first Republican lieutenant governor
this century.
</P>
<P>
   The state Constitution gives the lieutenant governor the
authority to preside over the Senate and to break ties. In decades
of Democratic control, senators have enacted rules that also gave
the lieutenant governor substantial power to make committee
assignments, appoint committee chairs, and direct the flow of
legislation. But in January, before Windom took office, the newly
elected Senate met in an organizational session and the Democratic
majority adopted new rules that stripped the lieutenant governor of
those powers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that authority was then vested in the president pro tem,
who happens to be a Democrat. The rules changes were supported by
Don Siegelman, a Democrat who was lieutenant governor but was sworn
in as governor six days later.
</P>
<P>
   Windom made it clear in an interview Wednesday that he was
outraged by the rules changes. Several of his allies cast the
dispute as an effort by trial lawyers to maintain their traditional
influence in the Senate after the election of a lieutenant governor
who strongly supports tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   Windom said that he had been left ``little choice but to take
action and restore democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   So shortly after he called the Senate into session for the first
time on Tuesday, one of his Democratic allies proposed rules to
restore the lieutenant governor's power. Windom declined to allow a
debate or to recognize his opponents and then quickly called for a
voice vote. As the Senate floor broke into pandemonium, Windom
declared that the measure had passed and then gaveled the session
into adjournment.
</P>
<P>
   How did Windom know the new rules had gained a majority?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I heard,'' he said. ``You obviously do it on what
the chair hears and sees and I heard a majority. The prevailing
side voted loudest.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he simply had followed the procedure set by
Siegelman and his supporters in the organizational session and that
he was ``not going to let the governor destroy a constitutional
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders were stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never dreamed that a madman would just begin gaveling
through laws by himself with 18 of us voting no,'' said Sen. Lowell
Barron, a Democrat and the president pro tem. ``I reckon he's like
the rest of the Republicans. He wants to shut down the state
government like Newt did with the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron said his Democratic coalition would continue to boycott
Senate sessions this week. But each day that the Senate fails to
gain a quorum counts against the maximum of 30 working days that
the Legislature can meet this year. Before long, the impasse could
threaten the timely passage of the state budget and consideration
of Siegelman's first-year agenda, including his call for a
referendum on a state lottery to benefit education.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen Democratic senators filed a lawsuit Wednesday asking a
judge to invalidate the rules enacted on Tuesday. A hearing is set
for Monday in Circuit Court in Montgomery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
