<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-FOREST-ART-440&AMP;     03-03 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-FOREST-ART-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL PROTECTS MAINE WOODS FROM DEVELOPMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: N.Y., N.H., Vt.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Great swaths of the Maine woods with a combined land
area bigger than Rhode Island would be protected forever from
development under a $28 million plan announced Wednesday and
thought to encompass more territory than any other such deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Angus King of Maine said in Augusta that the plan would
include more than 2,000 miles of shoreline on streams and rivers,
more than 85 lakes or ponds, and nesting areas for bald eagles and
peregrine falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the biggest day for Maine out-of-doors since
Gov. Baxter first saw Mount Katahdin,'' King said, referring to the
1920s governor, Percival Baxter, who personally bought and donated
Baxter State Park, a widely beloved wilderness area crowned by
Mount Katahdin in northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, a family of longtime Maine landowners, the
Pingrees, would provide a conservation easement on the land by
selling the development rights on 754,673 acres to a private
nonprofit group, the New England Forestry Foundation. The family
can continue limited industrial logging and the public will still
have recreational access, although there are no plans to transform
the land into a park.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old foundation, which promotes sustainable forestry,
is still raising the money for the purchase, and has two years to
amass it.
</P>
<P>
   King, who announced the agreement, said it was probably the
largest conservation easement deal on private forest land.
</P>
<P>
   On a roll of recent victories in their efforts to preserve
Northeastern forest land, environmentalists praised the Pingree
agreement as a significant step toward saving more of the Northern
Forest, the 26 million acres of woods from Maine to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the soul-satisfying sound of another big piece of the
Northern Forest puzzle clicking into place,'' said Bob Perschel,
chairman of the Northern Forest Alliance, a coalition of 35 groups.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came at a moment of exceptionally hot debate over what
Maine should do about its 17 million acres of woods, a discussion
prompted by land sales last year of giant paper company holdings
that amounted to about 15 percent of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists scored their most recent Maine triumph in
mid-December, when the Nature Conservancy, an international group,
announced that it would pay $35 million to buy 185,000 acres of
International Paper Co. land in northern Maine. Not far away, a
week earlier, conservationists cheered an even bigger landmark
preservation purchase: 300,000 acres of forest land in New York,
Vermont and New Hampshire from the Champion International paper
company for $76 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But at the same time, Maine environmentalists have complained
loudly that the state is not prepared to protect more of the
millions of acres coming up for sale as global economic forces lead
paper companies to shift their assets. They called for the state to
find the money and the will to buy more land to protect it, and
warned that at least one big land purchaser was known for
sub-dividing and building on wilderness parcels.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where love for the forest gets as prosaic as moose
meat in the freezer and as poetic as Henry David Thoreau's paeans
to the Maine Woods, the heightened discussion has been enough to
move the state legislature to put the issue on the front burner in
its current session.
</P>
<P>
   It is considering a variety of proposals, including one from
King for a $50-million bond issue for land purchases and ranging to
more than $100 million. Any such bond issue would have to come
before voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders say there seems to be enough consensus that
at least a $50-million bond issue has a good chance of passing. In
public debate, however, contention remains on issues ranging from
just how much land should be bought to whether it should remain
working forest or be protected from logging. But today's
announcement seemed to please virtually all camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a win-win,'' said Abby Holman, executive director of the
Maine Forest Products Council, a trade association for the wood and
paper industry. ``You're actually able to provide for a
conservation easement and reduce the threat of development in
pristine areas, and secure the future of the timber industry.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the forest spectrum, Jonathan Carter,
executive director of the Forest Ecology Network and an advocate of
maximizing wilderness areas, also praised the deal as a great step,
though he added, ``It's important that we realize that conservation
easements are not wilderness restoration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Carter said, ``Now we've got it out of
development's hands, we can now move forward and create a
wilderness park.''
</P>
<P>
   That _ creation of a wilderness park _ was the kind of total
stop to logging achieved this week by defenders of Headwaters, the
old-growth redwood forest owned by a lumber company in Northern
California. But in the East, where most forests are privately
owned, unlike their publicly owned Western counterparts, just
reducing logging and stopping development can seem to
environmentalists like progress.
</P>
<P>
   Injecting a note of skepticism into all the celebration, Carter
pointed out that the Pingrees, who are known as the most
environmentally punctilious of Maine's large landowners, would
receive $30 million for abstaining from developing land that they
may have had no intention of developing anyway. ``If you can
continue to do what you've always done and someone will give you
$30 million, who will say no?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   But King countered that the Pingrees, who are now in their
seventh generation of holding land first assembled in 1840, were
showing unusual vision in putting a permanent ban on developing
their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is forever,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
