</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USOC MOVES TO CLEAN UP THE MISTAKES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; _ U.S. Olympic Committee officials acknowledged
Wednesday that the committee's oversight of Salt Lake City's
scandal-ridden bid for the 2002 Winter Games was ``abysmal'' and
vowed to strictly monitor the host-city selection process in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure our rules go beyond reproach,'' Dick
Schultz, the USOC's executive director, said at a news conference.
``We're embarrassed by the whole thing. But we can't be defensive.
We have to assume responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   USOC officials were responding to a report released Tuesday by
an independent USOC commission that accused the International
Olympic Committee of fostering a ``culture of improper
gift-giving'' that Salt Lake City bid officials continued in their
effort to win the Games. The commission, chaired by the former Sen.
George Mitchell, made four recommendations for reform to the USOC,
and Wednesday the USOC executive committee adopted all of them, a
move that seemed to be daring the IOC into making dramatic change.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also suggested that the White House be asked for
help in curbing the excesses in the bidding process, and Bill Hybl,
the USOC president, sent a letter Wednesday to President Clinton
asking him to designate the IOC a ``public international
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   That would make illicit gifts to IOC members by the U.S. bid and
organizing committees punishable under the Foreign Corrupt
Practices Act.
</P>
<P>
   According to investigations by the IOC and a Salt Lake
Organizing Committee ethics panel, Salt Lake City's top officials
engaged in an aggressive program of cash payments and gift-giving _
totaling more than $1 million _ to IOC members and their families.
Nine IOC officials have either resigned or been expelled, and as
many as 20 other remain under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hybl did not criticize the IOC, or describe what pressure, if
any, the USOC could exert on the IOC to enact serious reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to find the flaws, correct the mistakes, and to
create a system that will ensure these mistakes do not occur
again,'' Hybl said, speaking generally.
</P>
<P>
   But privately, USOC officials endorsed possible congressional
action against the IOC _ including stripping it of its tax-free
status in the United States _ if the IOC does not demonstrate a
stern resolve for significant reform at a special session scheduled
for March 17-18 at its headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the IOC acts cavalierly we'll make it clear in hearings
what they will face,'' said Mark Buse, staff director of the Senate
Commerce Committee, which is to hold a hearing April 14. ``We want
them to understand that Senators McCain and Stevens are serious.''
</P>
<P>
   John McCain, R-Ariz., is the committee chairman; Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, wrote the Amateur Sports Act.
</P>
<P>
   The law, said Buse, could be redrawn to make the IOC pay taxes
on global sponsorships and television deals paid by U.S. companies.
Buse said the law could also be changed to put control of that
money in the hands of the USOC, which now receives 10 percent of
the money from U.S. Olympic television rights. NBC is committed to
pay the IOC $3.5 billion for the Olympics from 2000 to 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move could dramatically alter the balance of Olympic
power because nearly all IOC sponsors are based in the United
States, and NBC's rights fees dwarf any other country's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd rather avoid ultra-dramatic steps,'' Buse said. ``So we'd
hope that the IOC bows to public pressure and the pressure by the
USOC to reform their rules.''
</P>
<P>
   In adopting the other recommended reforms, the USOC said it
would open an independent office of bid compliance; bar bid cities
and organizing committees from offering assistance to IOC members
or international organizations, and prohibit those cities from
making grants to IOC member countries from the USOC's international
fund.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC will also make public all meetings, except for
executive sessions; require board of directors and executive
committee members to attend 75 percent of all meetings; and
maintain a permanent presence in the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee's offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
