<HEADLINE>
GM POSTS ROBUST SALES FOR FEBRUARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp., which on Wednesday reported
higher February sales, finally appears to be rebounding from last
summer's strike and joining its rivals in the robust automarket.
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing January for which GM was one of the only
automakers to report sales that were lower than in the previous
year, GM joined its competitors in posting a healthy gain in
February. The company reported total car and light-truck sales of
385,318 for the month, an increase of 17 percent from a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   GM's sales in February 1998 were extremely poor, however,
lowering the automaker's share of the car and light-truck market to
below 30 percent. The sales slump spurred the automaker to begin a
huge incentive campaign aimed at loyal GM owners.
</P>
<P>
   The successful promotion kept GM sales rolling until workers at
two parts plants in Flint, Mich., went on strike, closing nearly
all of GM's assembly plants for most of the summer. Since then, the
automaker has struggled to catch up to its pre-strike sales
momentum and inventory levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The month of February was a fantastic month for GM,'' said
Darwin Clark, GM vice president for field sales, service and parts.
``Our business was strong all across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   David Healy, an auto analyst at Burnham Securities in New York,
said the stronger-than-expected sales were largely because of an
end-of-the-month promotion for GM and dealership employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call that momentum,'' he added, noting that the
company's market share remained under 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company's higher February sales came with inventories at
only 60 percent of 1998 levels for its critical pickup trucks and
without huge customer incentives.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with other automakers, GM's February sales rose
largely on the strength of its trucks. Sales of its light trucks
totaled 177,328 in February, a 16 percent rise from a year earlier
and the best February in history for GM truck sales. GM's
redesigned and all-important full-size pickups, the Chevrolet
Silverado and the GMC Sierra, are apparently catching on with
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Combined sales of the two trucks rose 18 percent from a year
earlier for their best February in 21 years. Minivan sales were
also strong, up 40 percent for all models combined, a record
February for GM van sales. Sales of GM's large sport-utility
vehicles also rose significantly.
</P>
<P>
   GM reported car sales of 207,990 vehicles, up 19 percent from a
year earlier. That was largely due to sales of its midsize cars,
which rose 43 percent from the comparable 1998 period. The line
includes GM's newest models, the Oldsmobile Alero and the Pontiac
Grand Am. Sales of its Saturn models dipped overall, but the new
three-door Saturn coupe, introduced in November, sold well, up 39
percent. Saab, which is 50 percent owned by GM and which has two
new models, the 9-3 and 9-5, saw sales rise 36 percent, its best
February in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Cadillac division, which had put on huge dealer
and customer incentives late last year to prevent Ford Motor Co.'s
Lincoln from stealing its long-held title of luxury vehicle leader,
continued to pay for those sales. After dropping in January,
Cadillac's sales fell again in February, down 28 percent from a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every automaker reported higher February sales, many of
them posting records for the month. U.S. vehicle sales for February
totaled 1,287,634 cars and light trucks, a 13 percent increase over
February 1998. Car sales totaled 670,676, up 9 percent; light-truck
sales increased 17 percent, to 616,958 vehicles. That put the
seasonally adjusted annual selling rate for light vehicles at a
hefty 17 million cars and light trucks for the month.
</P>
<P>
   The continued strong auto sales keep surprising auto executives
and analysts, who keep increasing their forecasts for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This month came in stronger than we or the auto analysts
expected by orders of magnitude,'' said Clark of GM. He said that
at the start of the year, GM's forecast for 1999 total car and
truck sales was 15 million to 15.5 million vehicles. It is now
estimating that sales could be close to 15.8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
