<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MORE ARE ARRESTED IN STATE TREASURY PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A former high-ranking manager in the treasurer's office
and an outside ``heir finder'' were arrested Wednesday on charges
of stealing $2.4 million from a state account that has become the
focus of one of the biggest public corruption investigations in
decades.
</P>
<P>
   State Police apprehended former deputy treasurer Robert E. Foley
at a friend's house in Norwood Wednesday afternoon while Rhode
Island police later arrested Thomas Ciliberto in his hometown of
Woonsocket.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly portrayed Foley, 39, as the
mastermind of the complicated scheme to steal millions of dollars
from the Unpaid Check Fund, an account that holds unclaimed state
payments for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Foley _ among four people arrested since Reilly's investigation
began three weeks ago _ was the boss of John Trischitta, who was
arrested last month for his part in the alleged theft of $6.5
million from the treasury fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is almost beyond belief,'' Reilly, surrounded by a team
of investigators, said in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Foley is charged with larceny of $2.4 million, as well as
bribery. The Lexington resident will be arraigned in Boston
Municipal Court Thursday. Ciliberto, 51, faces charges of larceny
and bribery in the alleged theft of $812,000 of the $2.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   A person familiar with the ongoing investigation said the two
latest suspects had funneled money to Rhode Island corporations
they had created; some were ``dummy'' companies while others were
legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasurer Joseph Malone hired Foley in 1991 as director
of cash management. Sometime after, Foley cooked up a complicated
plot to siphon money out of the Unpaid Check Fund, which fell under
his aegis, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say there is evidence that by 1993, Foley stole
$1.6 million in one transaction, apparently on his own, with a
phony claim to an unpaid check. And, sometime between 1994 and
1995, he stole another $812,000 with the help of Ciliberto, who
allegedly paid Foley for information related to stealing the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they do not know if the money can be recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was one of five deputies in the office under Malone; the
recently elected treasurer, Shannon P. O'Brien, wanted her own hire
to supplant Foley long before the investigation came to light. His
last day was Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A professional accountant, Foley was partner in a Norwood
accounting firm, D'Ambra &AMP; Associates, before joining Malone's
office, and, according to his state ethics statement retained a 50
percent interest in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Records at the Secretary of State's office in Rhode Island show
that Ciliberto was president of Reinke Group Inc., a so-called
heir-finding business that helped clients track down money owed to
them. The company was dissolved in 1997. Investigators believe
Foley had a hidden stake in Reinke and would receive payments for
directing claims to it.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate and real estate records show that Foley's partner in
the accounting firm, Craig S. D'Ambra of Warwick, R.I., was also
involved in several real estate transactions with Ciliberto. Until
it went out of business, Reinke Group was listed in the Warwick
telephone directory at the same address as D'Ambra's home. D'Ambra
did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who was in 1993 promoted to deputy treasurer in charge of
the cash management division, oversaw the work of Trischitta, who
supervised the Unpaid Check Fund. Foley was responsible for signing
the millions of dollars in checks that Trischitta approved for
issuance to heir finders who had located individuals or firms to
which the state owed money.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent ripples of disbelief through the former treasury
administration. The case has turned into the largest theft of state
money in the commonwealth's history as well as the one of the most
damning indictments of state government since the corruption
scandals of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's top aide, Thomas Trimarco, said he was stunned that
someone from the office's inner circle had been implicted in a
scandle that otherwise had been blamed on ``one bad apple'' _
Trischitta, also known as ``Trixie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We put complete trust in him and to learn this is just
sickening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Squillace, former assistant treasurer in charge of the
Abandoned Property Division, which is where money from the Unpaid
Check Fund is transferred after 13 months, was also shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never have believed that this could have involved
Foley,'' Squillace said. ''
</P>
<P>
   But Tonia Duchano, whom Malone appointed to watch over the
Abondoned Property Divison _ which Foley also controlled at one
point _ had many conflicts with him before she left recently to
take a job in another state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie couldn't have figured out anything,'' Duchano said.
``And Bob Foley, he's very bright.''
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta, 47, of Stoneham, was arrested two weeks ago along
with Martin Robbins, 51, an heir finder from Peabody and New
Hampshire. Trischitta allegedly directed Robbins to $6.5 million in
uncashed checks in exchange for $50,000 in bribes and one-third of
the money. The $6.5 million, which Robbins deposited into a
BankBoston escrow account in November, has been returned to the
state, according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly would not say whether Foley knew about Trischitta's
alleged theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a more sophisticated scheme,'' Reilly said. ``It
involved in- and out-of-state companies. This has been ongoing for
the better part of eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Treasurer O'Brien moved to reassure the state that
the Unpaid Check Fund _ now frozen with $13 million in it _ is
safe, along with other accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put bluntly, the holes have been plugged,'' O'Brien said in a
press conference at her State House office. ``I'm standing in the
middle of it and I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Stephen Kurkjian and Frank Phillips of the Globe staff contributed
to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
