<SLUG> BC-BKC-CLANCY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLANCY IS USC'S QUIET MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's nearly impossible to find someone who has
seen USC forward Sam Clancy lose his temper. His high school coach
hasn't. Neither has his roommate.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy is so quiet, most find it difficult to gauge his
emotions. He's even-keeled to the point Trojans coach Henry Bibby
has tried to get Clancy to become more demonstrative.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way I am,'' Clancy said. ``I've always been
quiet. I'm not really a person who tries to pump a team up. I'm
laid back and I don't have too many worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's stoic demeanor has probably saved him from a stressful
first year at USC. If most true freshmen had gone through what
Clancy has, they probably never would have been able to recover and
start in 19 of the Trojans' first 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's college career got off to a controversial start before
he enrolled at USC. Last spring, the Pacific-10 Conference
conducted an investigation into allegations that the prep star was
paid $25,000 to attend USC.
</P>
<P>
   The news shocked Clancy and those who knew him at St. Edward's
High in Lakewood, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought him behind closed doors and said, `What happened?'
He looked in my eyes and said, `Nothing happened,' '' said Eric
Flannery, Clancy's high school coach. ``It's upsetting how a rumor
can go that far.''
</P>
<P>
   After a six-week investigation, the conference found no evidence
that Clancy received any cash payments. But the damage had already
been done to Clancy's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hope people treat him OK and don't have doubts,''
Flannery said.
</P>
<P>
   A more emotional player might be dogged by the allegations, and
let the situation ruin his season. But Clancy's ``What, me worry?''
attitude proved to be a perfect antidote for the stress of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't worry about it too much. I knew it wasn't true,''
Clancy said. ``I worried less because I knew everything was just a
lie. We just had to answer questions truthfully. I thought it was a
joke at first. I got over it. I know I didn't do anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Flannery was hardly stunned by Clancy's relaxed nature during
the heat of the charges, even after an investigator visited his
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even chuckled about it,'' Flannery said. ``He thought it
was ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy (6-foot-6, 235 pounds) has averaged six points and 5.7
rebounds, and has gotten better as the season has progressed. In
Pac-10 play, he leads the conference in blocked shots (1.6 per
game) and has recorded three double-doubles. He is a strong
candidate for the Pac-10's All-Freshmen team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been tremendous,'' Bibby said. ``Again, he's had his ups
and downs. We're working with him about being more excited for
games and more upbeat. We want him to be more emotionally
aggressive for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy gives himself a B-minus for his performance this season
but admits he sewed up a starting job faster than even he
anticipated. Junior Jarvis Turner started the season at power
forward and was expected to be the Trojans' go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   But Bibby liked Clancy and his rebounding skills, and soon
replaced Turner with the husky freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I didn't think I would start this year,'' Clancy
said. ``It came a little fast. I think once the Pac-10 started, I
think I did pretty well. I think I will be a four-year starter.''
</P>
<P>
   His roommate at USC, center Brian Scalabrine, labels Clancy the
player who has ``improved the most on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine believes the only thing holding Clancy back is his
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as showing emotions on the court, I've got to work with
him,'' Scalabrine said. ``Because when he shows emotions, he plays
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's quiet nature doesn't hurt as a roommate, however,
according to Scalabrine: ``I think Sam is a perfect roommate. If he
doesn't play or has a bad practice, he doesn't bring it home with
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
