<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIGEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEST FRESHMAN LEADS SETON HALL TO MODEST UPSET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They lost twice to the Irish in the regular season,
and needed a victory to stay in contention for the National
Invitation Tournament. Seton Hall's crafty point guard, Shaheen
Holloway, was battered. His backup, Ty Shine, was a freshman. Quite
talented, but still only a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   But Shine responded with a career performance Wednesday _ 17
points, 6 assists and 3 steals _ to help the Pirates eliminate
Notre Dame from the Big East tournament, 79-69, before a sleepy
morning crowd at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the day session of the tournament ended up being a
three-game, ho-hum affair.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4-seeded Syracuse routed No. 13 Boston College by the widest
margin in the tournament's 20-year history, 96-55, and No. 5-seeded
Villanova waited 34 minutes to finally wrestle the lead from No. 12
West Virginia before snuffing the Mountaineers' upset bid by 73-61.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall Coach Tommy Amaker decided that Holloway, the junior
from Queens, hadn't been himself since a shoulder injury last
month; and a stomach virus had limited him to just 23 minutes in
the past two games. So Amaker told Shine he was starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited,'' Shine said with a wide smile. ``I just wanted
to lead the team.''
</P>
<P>
   He did that by running the Pirates' halfcourt offense precisely,
propelling Seton Hall past the first round for the first time since
1996. The Hall plays top-seeded Connecticut (the nation's No. 3
team) Thursday at noon. Seton Hall (15-13) led the Huskies in both
games at halftime earlier this season before losing _ a fact not
lost on Amaker or his seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone talks that we played them tough, but we lost to them
twice,'' Amaker said. ``They'll be better. This is the showcase for
our league, and they're the best in our league. It will be an
unbelievable battle just to stay on the court with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shine had help Wednesday as Duane Jordan, a 6-foot-6-inch
senior, banged the Irish's towering frontcourt of 6-11 Phil Hickey
and 6-9 Troy Murphy for 18 points and 13 rebounds. He, too, is
looking forward to a potential NIT berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our good defense came good offense,'' Jordan said. ``They
were looking for me today, and the shots were falling. This is my
senior year, and we needed to win this one because we didn't want
fate to control the destiny of our NIT chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish (14-16) kept alive their streak of never winning a Big
East tournament game (0-4) by turning the ball over 23 times and
barely getting close enough to threaten. Led by the conference's
rookie of the year, Troy Murphy, the Irish closed within 69-64 with
2 minutes 5 seconds left, but Seton Hall went 10 for 10 from the
foul line down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing for the season to end today; we were hoping
to make a run in the tournament and probably earn an NIT bid,''
said Murphy, who scored 28 points and grabbed 15 rebounds. ``I
learned a lot this year and had a lot of fun, but it's still
disappointing to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second game, Syracuse stretched a 12-0 opening run into a
47-18 halftime lead and never looked back as four Orangemen _ led
by Etan Thomas' 19 points _ put up double figures against hapless
Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles (6-21) shot 34.7 percent from the field, 61.9 percent
from the free-throw line and turned the ball over 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought today we came out focused,'' Syracuse Coach Jim
Boeheim said. ``Defense was good, and we didn't let them get any
open shots. But we're just bigger and stronger than them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen (20-10) now face Villanova (20-9) in perhaps the
most competitive matchup of the quarterfinals. The Wildcats needed
21 second-half points from John Celestand _ including a 30-foot
3-pointer to finally get the lead with 5:52 left in the game _ to
repel a pesky, upset-minded Mountaineer team.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia (10-19) bloodied Villanova on the boards, 46-32,
and Elton Scott riddled them for 26 points _ including 12 points
from behind the 3-point arc _ until Celestand and the Wildcats
turned to pressure defense. They forced 13 second-half turnovers
and converted them into 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Celestand and Brown, who had 16 points, are both seniors.
``There's nothing can take the place of experience,'' Villanova
Coach Steve Lappas said. ``And these guys have played a lot of
games for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
