<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HILLARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IRAN'S IMPULSE FOR CHANGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 4: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The power of democracy is altering Iran. Unofficial results from
municipal elections show that Iranians overwhelmingly supported
moderate politicians associated with President Mohammad Khatami.
The voting mirrored the presidential election that swept Khatami to
power two years ago. Though conservative clerics remain the
paramount rulers of Iran, Iranians clearly are impatient to lift
religious repression and transform their country.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Constitution, adopted after Ayatollah Khomeini's 1979
Islamic revolution, provides for local elections, but none were
held for two decades. Khatami called last Friday's vote hoping to
create a more decentralized civil society that could support his
agenda of political and social change. His gamble apparently paid
off.
</P>
<P>
   The winners included liberal clerics like Abdollah Nouri, a
Khatami ally who was forced out of the national Cabinet last year
by clerical conservatives and who has now been elected to the
Tehran city council. The high turnout that carried many moderate
candidates to victory may now embolden Khatami to take further
conciliatory steps toward America.
</P>
<P>
   Washington would benefit greatly from the development of a more
moderate and internationally responsible Iran, and should do what
it can to encourage change. While continuing to support exchanges
by sports teams and cultural groups, the Clinton administration
should begin to ease trade restrictions against Iran in ways that
would have the most impact on ordinary Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   The White House rightly insists that normal relations cannot be
completely restored until Iran stops trying to build nuclear and
other unconventional weapons, severs its links with terrorism and
accepts peacemaking efforts between Israeli and Arab leaders. Iran
has distanced itself from terror and now concedes the Palestinians'
right to make peace with Israel. If further steps can be taken, the
Mideast will be a safer place and Iran may resume its traditional
role as a regional counterweight to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the White House should approve a request by an
American trading company, pending since last year, to sell three
million tons of grain and 400,000 tons of sugar requested by the
Iranian government. President Clinton also ought to ease
restrictions on American imports of Iranian carpets, leaving in
place only measures to discourage the exploitation of child labor.
Neither step requires Congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   American food sales would make it easier for the Khatami
government to subsidize the diet of families hurt by collapsed
world oil prices. Permitting carpet imports would allow the
creation of many new Iranian jobs. Iran's people have once again
voted for change. America should welcome their democratic choice
and extend new opportunities for friendship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0517 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-REDWOODS-NYT &LR;      03-03 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REDWOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE REDWOODS DEAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, March 4: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is much to celebrate in Tuesday's historic agreement under
which the federal and California governments will pay the Pacific
Lumber Company $480 million for 10,000 acres of redwood forests
along the northern California coast. Saving the largest privately
owned grove of ancient redwood trees in the world for future
generations is a tribute to the public officials and tireless
private citizens who made it happen. The deal is also a vindication
of the much-maligned Endangered Species Act, without which the
trees would surely have been doomed.
</P>
<P>
   But there is much more to this deal than the redwoods, and
despite all the celebratory noises in Washington and Sacramento, it
is far too early to claim victory. Under a so-called habitat
conservation plan, the company also has agreed to restrictions on
how and where it will harvest timber on the 200,000 acres it owns
outside the redwood groves. The purpose of these rules is to save
the habitat and improve the prospects of several endangered
species, notably California's coho salmon and a seabird called the
marbled murrelet.
</P>
<P>
   To many environmentalists and to Secretary of the Interior Bruce
Babbitt, this part of the deal is as important as the redwoods. If
the conservation plan works, it will greatly strengthen Babbitt's
argument that forging negotiated settlements with private
landowners covering entire ecosystems is a more secure way to
protect threatened wildlife than the litigious species-by-species
approach that has been the hallmark of the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   But whether it works will depend heavily on the willingness of
this administration and its successors to monitor the compliance of
Pacific Lumber, a company with a sorry environmental record and a
reputation for aggressive logging.
</P>
<P>
   The company pledges cooperation, but its history dictates
vigilance. Acquired in a leveraged buyout by a Texas businessman,
Charles Hurwitz, in 1985, Pacific Lumber more than doubled its
logging output to finance the purchase. In 1995 a federal judge
ruled that the company had violated the Endangered Species Act by
destroying the habitat of the murrelet. The company's operations
were further threatened when the California coho salmon, which
spawns in streams on Pacific Lumber property, joined the murrelet
on the endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   Hurwitz countersued in 1996, arguing that the government was
required under the Fifth Amendment to compensate him for land it
had prevented him from using. Rather than engage in a long and
problematical court battle, the White House decided to strike a
deal involving a buyout of several redwood groves and a
conservation plan covering the rest of the property. Congress
appropriated $250 million for the federal share, with California
paying the balance.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement nearly fell apart last Friday night, when the
company rebelled against new restrictions that had been urged upon
the government by its own scientists, including wider ``no cut''
zones bordering certain streams important to the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The company's president, John Campbell, said the rules would cut
its harvest below what it needed to remain profitable. The
government got the deal back on track with an exchange of vague
letters that Washington described as minor ``clarifications'' and
that the company described as a promise of more ``flexibility'' in
its logging operations.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of language that makes environmentalists
nervous. But what really ought to concern them is whether the
government will stick to the agreement and devote the time and
talent to police it, stream by stream, watershed by watershed.
Clinton and Vice President Gore will have every right to claim
credit for saving the redwoods. But history will also ask whether
they did anything for the birds and fish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
