<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6934 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT &LR;      03-03 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HILLARY IN NEW YORK: RETURN OF THE NEO-NATIVE?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, March 4: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memo to future presidential spouses: If you're feeling
overlooked, float a rumor that you might run for the Senate. So
many people were dying to pay $150 to hear Hillary Rodham Clinton's
luncheon address at the Plaza Wednesday that hundreds were exiled
from the main dining room, eating lunch with a public address
system. The place was abubble with incipient feminist triumphalism
and plain old Democratic opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   The press corps trailing Mrs. Clinton was perhaps not as large
as the 22-camera contingent that turned up when the former
vice-presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro announced she was
running for the Senate in 1992. But it was big considering that
Mrs. Clinton was not announcing anything more earth-shaking than
her belief that ``this is a great time to be a woman in America.''
It is not every day you see men from the British tabloids virtually
weeping in frustration at their inability to get a good position to
cover an address about the importance of public commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Within all her pleasant generalities, of course, Mrs. Clinton
had enough positive things to say about running for office to
encourage the local Democrats who are yearning for someone to save
them from His Fearsome Rudyness. She managed to lace her remarks
with a notable number of references to places she has been in New
York state _ that marvelous bus trip from Newburgh to Seneca Falls,
the inspiring gathering at the YWCA in Brooklyn. If she shied away
from political specifics, the same could not be said of her
less-than-subtle string of warm-up speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If California can send two women to the Senate, can't New York
do one?'' demanded Judith Hope, the head of the state Democratic
Party. Ms. Hope told the crowd that it was the least one could
expect from a state ``that gave the world'' a list of political
women that began with Eleanor Roosevelt and dwindled down rather
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the Plaza consisted of about 1,000 women and a
handful of men, virtually all of whom were elected officials hoping
to be asked to give the first lady more advice about her Senate
prospects. ``She's very thorough, but don't quote me,'' said one.
Mrs. Clinton is famous for her dislike of the media, and local
politicians have figured out that if they want to be confidants,
they had better be confidential. As much as it kills them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm usually more interesting than this,'' protested New York
City's public advocate, Mark Green, after he had most
uncharacteristically declined to say anything about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ubiquitous junior senator, Charles Schumer, who
lost his wife, Iris, in the press of the crowd, promised to ``be
there'' for the first lady if she runs. He also urged Mrs. Clinton
to wait and make her decision ``in a non-frenzied atmosphere,'' a
term that most definitely did not apply to the Plaza ballroom. ``I
say to the first lady, take a little time and think this through,''
said Schumer, as Mrs. Clinton stood next to him, her hands folded
demurely in front of her.
</P>
<P>
   That may have been the only controversial statement of the day,
since virtually all the state's Democratic politicians have been
urging Mrs. Clinton to make up her mind quickly. The first lady
could easily wait until the fall and still raise plenty of money
for the race, but if she chooses not to run, another candidate
could have a tougher time. ``She'll kill the Democratic chances if
she waits and then doesn't run,'' said one of her many
off-the-record advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said later that his own experience made him feel
strongly about the virtue of taking some time. Not only did he
devote months to mulling the pros and cons of a Senate run, he
said. ``I brushed my teeth with it. I went to the park with it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Schumer has his way, Mrs. Clinton will go back and brush her
teeth with the Senate option for some time, leaving the rest of New
York to wonder whether her contention that ``politics is really the
lifeblood of democracy'' was a secret signal of something big, and
whether she should be worried about the fact that her poll ratings
have dropped since she was first mentioned as a candidate. Perhaps
the public is beginning to feel that instead of a village, it takes
a resident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
