</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-ATTACKER-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CLAIMS `GHOST' DROVE HIM TO PUSH WOMAN TO HER DEATH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A man accused of pushing a Buffalo woman to her death
in front of a subway train told the police in a signed statement
that a ``ghost or a spirit or something like that'' sparked an
``uncontrollable urge'' in him just before the attack, according to
court documents released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The accused man, Andrew Goldstein, said in three handwritten
statements that he watched in ``horror'' as a subway train ran over
the woman, Kendra Webdale, 32, after he pushed her to the tracks in
a Manhattan station just after 5 p.m. on Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, according to the court papers, said he then turned to
the man next to him, raised his arms in the air and said, ``I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, 29, who has a long history of schizophrenia, waited
for the police to come and told arriving officers that he was a
``psychotic patient'' who had suffered a ``psychotic attack'' and
asked them to take him to a hospital, the court documents said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a sensation like something was entering me like a ghost
or a spirit or something like that,'' Goldstein wrote in looping
cursive handwriting that shifted from illegible to neat in the
three statements. ``When I have the sensation that something is
entering me, I get the urge to push, shove, or sidekick.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's statements were released Wednesday at his
arraignment in state Supreme Court in Manhattan on second-degree
murder charges in the killing of Ms. Webdale, a crime that
rekindled many fears among many riders of random attacks on city
subways despite the plunging crime rate. Goldstein's lawyer, Harvey
Fischbein, entered a plea of not guilty Wednesday and requested a
hearing to challenge the results of an examination by court
psychiatrists that concluded Goldstein was fit for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph T. Webdale Jr. and Kim Webdale, the victim's brother and
sister, attended the arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, a resident of Howard Beach, Queens, wrote in his
statements about the incident that his mother and his brother live
in the city and that his father is a radiologist in Delaware. He
said he did not know Ms. Webdale and did not even get a good look
at her, simply saying that ``the woman had blond hair.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The statements added tragic new details to the attack.
Goldstein, who had stopped taking his schizophrenia medication
according to law enforcement officials, visited Jamaica Hospital
Medical Center's emergency room in Queens the day before the attack
for treatment of a sprained ankle. But no one apparently noticed
him acting strangely.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hinck, a spokesman for Jamaica Hospital, said Goldstein
did not exhibit any behavior that merited a psychiatric evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein also said in his statement that he had carried out
other violent attacks before the subway incident. In those cases,
he described the same sensation of ``a force'' taking over his body
that he said caused him to become violent.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein wrote that in December 1992, he ran into a doctor's
office, ``punched a nurse'' and was institutionalized. In April
1997, he wrote, he felt ``a force like something overtaking me and
I have no control.'' He reacted by punching in his roommate's
bedroom door, he said. Goldstein said he was hospitalized for a
month after that incident.
</P>
<P>
   His statements also detailed his movements on the day he was
said to have attacked Ms. Webdale. There was little hint of the
random attack that was to come, and he made no reference to anyone
questioning his behavior earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein said he ate breakfast at a McDonald's near his home in
Queens that morning, then stopped by a supermarket to say hello to
a friend's girlfriend. Taking a bus and a subway to Times Square,
he wrote, he went to the Virgin Records store and listened to
Natalie Imbruglia and Madonna on compact disks. While listening to
music, he created pictures in his mind, and mentions in his
statement that he would ``like to direct someday.''
</P>
<P>
   After eating at another McDonald's, he wrote, he set out to
visit his brother at work and bumped into a woman he met while
institutionalized. With his brother not at work, Goldstein walked
to the Virgin record store in Union Square, where he said he again
listened to Madonna and to some classical music.
</P>
<P>
   He said he then ate at a nearby Wendy's restaurant and walked
around a department store for five minutes. Deciding to head home,
he walked to the subway station where the attack on Ms. Webdale
occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
