u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLOOMBERG-AD-COLUMN-N     03-03 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOMBERG-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: BLOOMBERG STEPS FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bloomberg Personal Finance, the monthly magazine for private
investors, is running its first major ad campaign to increase its
visibility among both the advertising community and the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, published by Bloomberg LP, the financial
information empire started by Michael Bloomberg, recently began a
$500,000 campaign in an eclectic mix of magazines _ including
advertising trade magazines, Time Out New York, Brill's Content and
Playboy _ that is intended to illustrate what it terms its ``secret
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bloomberg officials, Bloomberg Personal Finance,
which started as a bimonthly in November 1996 and became a monthly
a year later, provides two distinct ``secret advantages'': It gives
subscribers investment intelligence, while it gives advertisers a
readership that is predominantly male, relatively young (more than
half its readers are under 55), well educated and highly affluent.
</P>
<P>
   According to recent research by MRI Custom Research, the mean
net worth of readers' households is $1.4 million, while the mean
value of their investment portfolios is $900,000. The magazine's
circulation is now 215,000, double what it started with.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, by Doremus, a unit of Omnicom Group, are in black and
white except for a red Bloomberg logo and web site address. This
creates the feeling of reportage, said Rebecca Tudor-Foley,
executive vice president and creative director worldwide of
Doremus. ``We want to show people caught in the act, with the
secret advantage uncovered _ paparazzi shots,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four striking ads depicts a different situation that
illustrates the magazine's ``secret advantage''; most were
photographed by Robert Whitman, who has worked on advertising for
Dewar's. The first ad zooms in on a raincoat-clad young man,
reading a copy of Bloomberg Personal, whose logo peeks out from
above a copy of Playboy. In the trade version of the ad, the copy
says, ``Our readers enjoy a full hour with every issue,'' while the
consumer version says, ``Satisfy your second most basic instinct,''
and lists a toll-free subscription telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Another ad has a simulated image from an airport X-ray machine,
with one briefcase holding a passport, cell phone, change purse and
a copy of Bloomberg Personal. One ad shows a bride climbing out of
a limousine, clutching her bouquet and revealing a garter belt
decorated with the Bloomberg logo. And another ad shows a couple
kissing on a park bench; the woman has one hand reaching into her
boot, pulling out a copy of the magazine. Besides carrying the
Bloomberg logo, every ad also has the tag line ``the secret
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tudor-Foley said the campaign deliberately avoided the tone
traditionally set in personal finance magazines. ``There are
usually pictures of upscale readers, statistics for media buyers,
or exploitative headlines about the issue of the magazine,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   One major goal is to raise the profile of the magazine among
media buyers, Bloomberg said. ``A lot of them don't know who we are
or how important our brand name is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our second year as a monthly, and it's time to lift our
visibility with the ad agency community,'' added David Wachtel,
publisher of Bloomberg Personal Finance.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Bloomberg's campaign is running through July in
Advertising Age and the Adweek trade publications, in the February
and March issues of Time Out New York, in the March issue of
Brill's Content, and in the April issue of Playboy. In addition,
copies of each ad are being reproduced on postcards, which are
being mailed to more than 10,000 media planners, buyers and
supervisors around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Time Out ads are largely geared toward young media planners,
who Doremus believes read the publication during leisure time. ``We
want to complement what they see in the trade publications,'' Ms.
Tudor-Foley said. The ad in Brill's Content is intended to reach
``senior people in the media business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To reproduce the Playboy logo, Doremus approached Playboy
executives for their permission. Playboy complied, and also made a
deal with Bloomberg to run the ad in the April issue of Playboy,
whose circulation is more than 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun, and Hef loves the parody,'' said Playboy's
publisher, Richard Kinsler, referring to Hugh Hefner, the
magazine's founder. ``Because we're an icon, it gives us exposure.
It's a nice tie-in. Bloomberg is well known and respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives from both publications declined to specify what
Bloomberg paid for its ad in Playboy, though Wachtel said it was
not ``regular rates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
