<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-NINE-WEST-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES APPAREL GROUP'S STOCK FALLS ON NEWS OF NINE WEST
ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock of Jones Apparel Group Inc. declined 12.2
percent Wednesday, as the market frowned on the company's planned
acquisition of Nine West Group, the shoe retailer and manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Apparel, which sells women's clothing under the
Evan-Picone and Jones New York labels among others, announced late
Tuesday that it would buy Nine West for $885 million in stock and
cash and would assume $515 million of Nine West's debt. With Jones
Apparel's share price falling $3.19 Wednesday, to $22.75, the
deal's value was reduced by nearly $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, each of Nine West's 34 million common
shares outstanding will be exchanged for 0.5011 share of common
stock in Jones Apparel and $13 in cash. Partly on merger hopes,
Nine West's stock has risen 47 percent this year, including a gain
of 6.25 cents a share Wednesday, to $22.875.
</P>
<P>
   Investors expressed displeasure with several aspects of the
deal. For one, Nine West has had some big problems, including a
sudden slowdown in sales and an investigation by the Federal Trade
Commission into allegations of price fixing. Stock analysts doubt
that the company, which already accounts for roughly one out of
every five pairs of women's shoes sold in the United States, will
be the kind of turnaround and growth vehicle that Jones executives
predicted in announcing the combination.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Pope Murray, a footwear and apparel analyst for JP Morgan,
said, ``The market is not convinced that Nine West is additive'' to
earnings. Ms. Murray said she saw, ``a lower growth component with
a higher degree of risk'' than Jones did.
</P>
<P>
   Nine West needs to fix itself up and jump start sales again. But
investors are questioning whether Mark Schwartz, who is
chairman-designate of the new company, has the experience to do it.
Schwartz is president of Palladin Capital Group, a leveraged buyout
firm that advised Jones in the deal. As an investment banker at
Merrill Lynch, Schwartz worked with both Jones and Nine West on
their initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Britt, director of investor relations and financial
planning for Jones Apparel, noted that at Palladin Schwartz had
served as chairman of several companies, including retailers,
manufacturers and distributors in which it had a stake.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone call with analysts Wednesday, Schwartz said a
``turnabout is already under way.'' The company, which closed 100
stores last year, plans to close 60 more underperforming stores
this year. It now operates 1,095 outlets and sells its products
widely in department stores.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The major credit rating agencies Wednesday put Jones Apparel on
their watch lists with a negative outlook, but indicated a positive
outlook for Nine West.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts remained unconvinced that Jones Apparel
would find success in the shoe business, which is commonly thought
to be even more complicated to manage than apparel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't find it to be a very strategic move,'' said Josie
Esquivel, a stock analyst who tracks apparel and footwear companies
for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and was one of a half dozen analysts
who downgraded the stock this morning. ``I don't see a lot of
synergies between the footwear and apparel businesses. They will
still need two design staffs, two sales forces and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Faye Landes, who tracks retailers' stocks for Thomas Weisel
Partners, agreed. ``If there are synergies, they aren't readily
apparent,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy M. Ghriskey, portfolio manager at the Dreyfus Corp.,
which owned 970,200 Jones shares at the end of the year, said he
was concerned that Jones was entering unfamiliar territory. ``This
is a fairly radical departure from their traditional strategy,'' he
said. ``This takes them into manufacturing and retail in a much
bigger way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
