<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUMILIATED' LEWINSKY BREAKS SILENCE ON ORDEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Clarifies Lewinsky did not mention her abortion during the TV
interview.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abandoning the last vestiges of her privacy, Monica
S. Lewinsky has now told all in a new book and a teary television
interview as she launches an international quest to reverse the
personal and financial damage of her affair with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Wrathful one moment, rueful the next, the former White House
intern opened the post-impeachment chapter of the saga by assailing
the ``dubious methods'' of the independent counsel, Kenneth W.
Starr, asserting his deputies drove her to the brink of suicide,
and disclosing a startling twist in her tumultuous story: that she
obtained an abortion after she became pregnant by an unidentified
Pentagon offical in 1996 during the final months of her
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky, 25, who stands to make several million dollars in her
marketing effort, unleashed a flood of additional information of
varying significance in a two-hour interview Wednesday night on
ABC's ``20/20'' and in a 288-page book, ``Monica's Story.'' The
book, released to the news media Wednesday, goes on sale Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After watching in virtual silence for more than a year as her
affair with Clinton burst from secrecy to the threshold of a
constitutional crisis, Lewinsky spared little emotion as she
unfolded her version of events.
</P>
<P>
   She described her former friend, Linda R. Tripp, as a
``treacherous bitch'' for telling Starr about Lewinsky's affair
with Clinton and then acting as an informant for the independent
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to hurt her,'' Lewinsky said of Tripp. ``I felt like
an animal wanting to claw at her skin.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, Lewinsky said she still wakes some mornings and
misses him ``with every ounce of my being, my head, heart, and
body.''
</P>
<P>
   But she told Barbara Walters, her interviewer on ABC, that she
no longer loves Clinton, and she made no secret that she despises
him for abandoning her after the scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 million viewers were expected to watch the Lewinsky
interview on ABC, and bookstores were stocking 400,000 copies of
``Monica's Story,'' which retails for $24.95. Lewinsky was given a
$750,000 advance for the book and will receive 10 percent of the
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was not paid for the ABC interview, Lewinksy will
receive $600,000 for an interview with a British television station
this weekend. She also stands to make about $500,000 for photo
spreads in several European magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew he wasn't a very truthful person,'' Lewinsky
said about Clinton in the book, written by Princess Diana's
biographer, Andrew Morton. ``But the events of the last year have
showm him to be a much bigger liar than I ever thought. Now I see
him as a selfish man who lies all the time. That makes me very
angry and resentful.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lewinsky, who apologized on ABC to the country and Clinton's
family for the ordeal, blamed Starr most of all for the fallout
from the affair. She lashed out at the salacious nature of Starr's
eight-month investigation of the affair and the shocking details in
his report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying herself as ``probably the most humiliated woman in
the world,'' Lewinsky said she ``really felt raped and physically
ill with myself'' because of Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   She took special exception to her initital contact with Starr's
deputies, who questioned her for more than 10 hours at a
Ritz-Carlton hotel in suburban Washington when they first
confronted her in January 1998 about her affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky unloaded her anger in chapters of the book titled,
``The Starr Chamber,'' and ``Terror in Room 1012,'' which refers to
the hotel room where she was questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is investigating whether Starr's staff
improperly discussed a possible immunity deal with Lewinsky that
day and whether Starr wrongfully failed to tell the department
about his contacts with lawyers for Paula Corbin Jones, who was
suing Clinton at the time for alleged sexual harassment. She later
settled the suit for $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understandably, Starr's tactics have been a matter for grave
public concern,'' Lewinsky's book states. ``The whole exchange
about immunity was a waste of time except insofar as it exposed the
dubious methods employed by Starr's investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Lewinsky's book alleges, ``the nearest comparison to
the relationship between Starr and Lewinsky is the reaction of an
abused child in the presence of the abuser, or that of a
badly-beaten animal to its bullying owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office declined to comment Wednesday on Lewinsky's
statements.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, one of Starr's deputies, Michael Emmick, whom the
book describes as ``a revolting specimen of humanity,'' warned
Lewinsky she could face up to 27 years in prison for possible
crimes related to Clinton's alleged attempt to cover up their
affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if my stomach had been cut open and someone had
poured acid into my wound,'' Lewinsky said. ``I just felt an
intense stinging pain and overriding terror.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of prison apparently terrified her. ``I couldn't
bear to go to jail,'' she said in the book. ``I would come out an
old lady and no one would ever want to marry me.''
</P>
<P>
   In despair, she said, she considered hurling herself out the
10th-floor window, ``to crash to her death through the glass canopy
below.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky later was released and relied briefly for her defense
on William Ginsburg, a California lawyer and family friend who
specialized in medical malpractice cases. But soon she was unhappy
with Ginsburg too.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said Ginsburg became too enamored of the spotlight.
``Unfortunately, I think he could bitten by the bug,'' she told
Walters, ``and it became more about Bill Ginsburg than it did about
my well-being and my welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinksy's book asserts that her anger is mixed with an
``overwhelming feeling of guilt and shame for the anguish she has
caused not only her family and friends, but the president, his
family, and particulary Chelsea.''
</P>
<P>
   In her television interview, Lewinsky said Clinton sometimes
smiled at her even when he was with his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever think about Hillary Clinton?'' Walters asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about her a lot,'' Lewinsky said. ``But I never
thought she would find out.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she also thought about Chelsea because ``she means the
world to him, I mean, she is the most precious thing to him. I had
a very strong affinity for her.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Lewinksy's abortion, she did not mention it in the
television interview, although she answered in the affirmative when
asked if she had become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, she describes the man as a senior Defense
Department official who was single, a ``charming, craggy-faced
older man'' named Thomas. She said they had an affair for three
months but it ended after she discovered she was pregnant in
October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   She reluctantly decided to have an abortion, the book states,
``but she and Thomas fell out over the costs of the procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky said she told Clinton she was dating other men, but
never told him about her pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   With all that has happened since the scandal erupted, Lewinsky
said her personal goals of finding a husband and having children
remain far from fulfilled. ``This essentially traditional,
middle-class American girl is today reduced to hiding in the
shadows, a fugitive in her own land,'' her book states. ``She
exists in a modern-day Orwellian nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Lewinsky recently has ``enjoyed the companionship of a
young, single man,'' according to her book. The relationship is
significant, Lewinsky believes, because she has always been drawn
to married men, largely out of her insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``For her, the relationship has been both a revelation and a
reassurance, a first step into the real world of male-female
relationship,'' her book says. The relationship is described as
``her first faltering steps on a very long road to recovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
