</P>
<P>
   PET-ALLERGY (New York) _ When I adopted a big labrador mutt I
never dreamed I'd be allergic to her. But every time she flopped
down on the floor, little clouds of hair drifting into the air, I
sneezed. My eyes itched. I developed what felt like a chronic cold.
If she slept in the same room with me, I'd wake up with that
``tight'' feeling in my chest so familiar from an asthmatic
childhood. ``Get rid of the dog,'' my doctor said; control the
problem at its source. ``Open the windows,'' said Dr. David
Valacer, director of the Children's Allergy, Immunology and
Respiratory Center at New York Presbyterian Hospital. ``The dander
will be diluted by the air brought into the house.'' By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIEGO-RIVERA (Undated) _ Now that the cactus fence around his
house near Mexico City has been replanted, its vivid colors
restored, and offending additions removed, Diego Rivera can easily
be imagined on the third-floor bridge leading from his red studio
to Frida Kahlo's blue studio, pounding at her glass door and asking
his wife's forgiveness. The life of Rivera, a Rabelaisian omnivore,
was a legend wrapped in scandal surrounded by myth that played
against the backdrop of Technicolor buildings, as if he was a
figure walking through one of his own heroic canvases. By Joseph
Giovannini.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT4,5,13,16) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-ALONE (Undated) _ In her recent book, ``Living Solo''
(Andrews McMeel Publishing; $18.95), Adrienne Salinger investigates
the inner lives, dwelling places and somewhat eccentric indulgences
of people who, either by choice or circumstance, find themselves
living alone. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER-BRIGHT-HEADLIGHTS (Undated) _ Laurie Cribbs bought her new
Lexus LS 400 for its luxurious appointments, but what really
impressed her were its trendsetting super-bright headlights. The
technology that tamed the night for Ms. Cribbs is called High
Intensity Discharge, or HID, and it is an increasingly hard-to-miss
sight on the nation's roads. By Philip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT7) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HOME-TEXTILES (Undated) _ Not since the resourceful Scarlett
O'Hara swept down the grand stair in a red velvet gown made from
Tara's drapes has fashion enjoyed such an intimate affair with the
decor tastes of the day. From luxe cashmeres to of-the-moment
Ultrasuede, upholstery and decorative home textiles are in the
middle of a rare burst of synergy: some of the most popular new
fabrics are remarkably similar to those on fashion's runways. By
David Colman.
</P>
<P>
