<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW'S SHARP IN SPRING DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Jeff Shaw wanted to be at Dodgertown for two
weeks, and now that he's here, most of his thoughts are in
Washington Court House, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Funny what having an expectant wife, and training for a World
Series contender, will do to your mind. And your insides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be both places,'' said Shaw, the Dodgers' closer.
``It's been stressful. Stressful on her (Julie) because she's
pregnant and she knew I wanted to be here. She knew I wanted to be
here and she knew I wanted to be home.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw arrived in Dodgertown near noon Wednesday, two weeks after
pitchers and catchers reported. He will be on his way home the
moment Julie begins labor, and the Dodgers said they could charter
a plane for Shaw if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, who knows when that will happen? Originally, the due
date was Feb. 15. It was changed to Feb. 25, and now it's been
pushed to mid-March, which is why Shaw is here. But the instant his
cell phone rings, Shaw will be gone for a few days. He approximates
it will take him five hours to get home, which should give him
enough time to witness the birth of the couple's third child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be there for (Julie), and your kid's birth only
happens once,'' Shaw said. ``But I also needed to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the latter isn't all that true. Not after manager Davey
Johnson and pitching coach Charlie Hough saw Shaw throw for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may get his program and institute that next season for my
pitchers,'' Johnson said. ``It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, Shaw's been weight training, running and
pitching near his home. He's even thrown a few simulated innings,
something he wanted to do so he could prove to the Dodgers he's
been working hard. It paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he'd be as sharp as he was,'' Hough said. ``He
had outstanding command. For the first day, it was excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who saved 48 games for the Dodgers and Cincinnati Reds
last season, isn't expected to pitch in a spring training game
until he returns from Ohio. Whenever that is.
</P>
<P>
   Taking it slow: Johnson said he'll keep Todd Hundley, and his
right elbow, away from the catcher's position for the first week of
spring training games, electing to err on the side of caution.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley isn't the only player who will sit in Friday's
Grapefruit League opener against St. Louis. Second baseman Eric
Young will be held out to give his ailing back time to rest. Young
said he's been experiencing soreness in his lower back the past few
days. It's bothered his hitting and fielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stiffness,'' Young said. ``The fact that it's been
happening for a few days and hasn't improved, that concerns me.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he also anticipates holding center fielder Devon
White and left fielder Gary Sheffield out of the first few games.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Pitcher Mel Rojas returned to Dodgertown
after spending a few days in his native Dominican Republic
attending the funeral of his father-in-law. . . Much of the work
day was confined to the batting cages after rain halted an
intrasquad game. . . Tommy Lasorda is due into Dodgertown today and
former Dodgers president and CEO Peter O'Malley is expected to
arrive Friday. . . Tickets for individual games, and the April 3-4
exhibition games against the Yankees, go on sale today at 8:30 a.m.
at the Dodger Stadium advance ticket windows and at ETM Ticket
Machines. Tickets can also be purchased by calling 323-224-1HIT.
The team will host a season ticket open house at Dodger Stadium on
March 7 from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
