<SLUG> BC-NY-PIRRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRRO PLEADS NOT GUILTY TO FEDERAL TAX FRAUD CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind. )  (nk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Albert Pirro, the powerful real estate
lawyer and husband of the Westchester County district attorney,
pleaded not guilty Wednesday to federal charges of tax fraud and
accused prosecutors of trying to short-circuit his wife's political
aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to reporters after his arraignment at the federal
courthouse here, Pirro suggested that the ``pattern'' of state and
federal investigations into his business dealings seemed to
coincide with periodic attempts by Mrs. Pirro to seek higher
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have been at this a long time,'' he told reporters.
``I'm sure you can draw your own conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Connelly, a spokesman for Pirro, was more blunt, saying
that because of the indictment against Pirro, Mrs. Pirro has been
``sidelined as a potential senatorial candidate'' in next year's
election to fill the seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   For the last week, Pirro's associates have been reminding
reporters privately that the Pirro indictment helped force out a
strong Republican contender from a race in which Hillary Rodham
Clinton is being touted as the most fearsome Democratic prospect.
Although U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White, whose office brought the tax
fraud prosecution, lists herself as an independent, Pirro's allies
have noted that she was appointed by a Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Smilon, a spokesman for Ms. White, declined to discuss
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro also said Wednesday that he had passed a privately
administered lie-detector test when he amended his tax returns last
year and paid $957,000 in additional taxes and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, 51, and his brother and accountant, Anthony, 43, were
indicted by a federal grand jury last week on charges of failing to
report $1 million in income between 1988 and 1997 by listing
personal purchases as the expenses of Pirro-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
   The expenditures included a $123,000 Ferrari sports car,
Mercedes-Benzes for his wife and mother-in-law, a $40,000 gate and
a $3,700 awning for the Pirros' house in Harrison, N.Y, and the
legal bills for a paternity suit in which an Indiana woman proved
that Pirro was the father of her teen-age daughter.
</P>
<P>
   With several of the expenditures directly benefiting Mrs. Pirro,
she let it be known the day after he was indicted that she was no
longer considering a Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Pirro, with his lawyer, Roger L. Stavis, at his side,
also pleaded not guilty Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
