<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN SAYS N.Y. VOTERS WOULD REJECT MRS. CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NY-MRSCLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While studiously avoiding the word, Gov. Christie
Whitman of New Jersey suggested Wednesday that Hillary Rodham
Clinton was too liberal to prevail in New York's Senate race should
the first lady decide to enter that campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, responding to questions during a visit to Washington to
make speeches and meet with Republican congressional leaders, said
that Mrs. Clinton would be a formidable candidate should she decide
to seek the Senate seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a
Democrat who is retiring. But Whitman added that she felt a race
between Mrs. Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York would
expose the first lady as a proponent of big government and that
voters would reject her based on that philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, particularly, if she was running against Rudy
Giuliani, he would be successful,'' Whitman told a group of
reporters standing outside the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``She starts with a great deal of sympathy,'' Whitman said.
``She starts with great name ID, obviously, and she'd be a very
tough campaigner and candidate. But her philosophy is pretty
strong. She showed us with the one policy issue for which she was
given responsibility at the beginning of the president's first
term, health care. Her proposal would have yielded one of the
largest federal bureaucracies that we've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's prediction came even as Mrs. Clinton was in New York
doing nothing to tamp down the speculation that she would run for
the Senate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey governor is also the object of speculation about
a possible run for the Senate seat held by Frank Lautenberg, a
Democrat who, like Moynihan, has announced his intention to retire.
After a speech at the National Press Club, Whitman said she was
``going to think about that long and hard,'' but that she would
make up her mind soon. ``I'm not going to leave it for a long time.
I've given myself 30 to 60 days,'' she said, adding, ``I'm not
going to drag it on for months and months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
