<SLUG> BC-NY-ECON-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S JOB GROWTH IN '98 WAS BEST SINCE '84, STATE SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Companies in New York state added jobs in 1998 at the
fastest pace since 1984, and the number of jobs in the private
sector continued to grow in January, the state Department of Labor
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Private sector jobs grew by 2.3 percent last year, to 6.8
million, and 1,000 more jobs were added in January, according to
the Labor Department's newly revised figures. The figures are
adjusted for seasonal factors; without such adjustments, the number
of jobs would have fallen in January, as they do every year after
the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in the state fell to 5.2 percent in January from
5.4 percent in December, mostly because the jobless rate in New
York City fell to 7.6 percent from 8 percent, adjusted for seasonal
factors. In the rest of the state, unemployment remained flat at
3.8 percent, compared with a national average of 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration used Wednesday's news to argue that
the upstate economy was pulling out of the long slump that began in
the early 1990s. Growth upstate has lagged that in New York City,
where a booming securities market has helped spark an economic
surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the rate of growth downstate has been higher, the number
of jobs upstate is now at a record high,'' said Stephen Kagann,
chief economist to Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs in manufacturing continued to fall in the year ended
January, but the declines were relatively minimal in industries
that make things like industrial equipment and other so-called
durable goods. The biggest drops in manufacturing were in
businesses that are concentrated downstate, like the printing and
garment industries, which lost 6,900 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Service industries continued to boom, adding more than 100,000
jobs. Growth was especially strong in motion pictures, business
services and engineering, according to the Labor Department
figures. Jobs in retailing and construction also jumped in the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of jobs grew in the state by 1.9 percent; in the
city, the figure was 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   New York now ranks about 20th among the states in terms of job
growth, Kagann said. In 1992 and 1993, the state hovered in last
place among the states, because it was still losing jobs while
other states were growing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the unemployment rate in the city's five boroughs remains
high. The jobless rate in the Bronx is 9.7 percent; in Brooklyn,
9.6 percent; in Queens, 7.1 percent; in Manhattan, 6.9 percent, and
in Staten Island, 7.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
