<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-SCHOOL-DESEG-420-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SEES GOOD-FAITH EFFORT TO INTEGRATE HARTFORD SCHOOLS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. _ A Superior Court judge ruled Wednesday that
Connecticut had made a good-faith effort to desegregate the
Hartford schools after a landmark state Supreme Court ruling two
years ago, and ordered a group pushing for speedier progress to be
more patient.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, the latest in a suit first filed in 1989,
disappointed the families who brought the case. They point to the
racial isolation of black and Hispanic children, who were 93
percent of the city's student body at the time of the 1996 ruling
and today are 95 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 ruling , Sheff vs. O'Neill, the Connecticut Supreme
Court became the first state court in the nation to find that the
concentration of black and Hispanic students in an urban school
district could amount to a denial of equal educational opportunity
and a violation of segregation laws. Last year, the families went
back to Superior Court to argue that the state had not done enough
to remedy this segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Although the percentage of black and Hispanic students in
Hartford schools has actually increased since the Supreme Court
acted, Judge Julia L. Aurigemma found Wednesday that state
officials had responded ``expeditiously and in good faith'' to the
ruling by promoting interdistrict programs that allow urban and
suburban children to learn together, and by creating magnet and
charter schools to give parents a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislative and executive branches should have a realistic
opportunity to implement their remedial programs before further
court intervention,'' Aurigemma wrote. ``The best way to achieve
popular support is not to impose a judicially mandated remedial
plan, but to encourage Connecticut's populace as a whole, both
directly and through their elected representatives, to solve the
problems facing the state's schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Horton Sheff, whose son Milo became the lead plantiff
when he was a pupil in the Hartford schools, said after the ruling
that ``nothing substantial has changed'' in the Hartford schools.
Milo was in fourth grade in 1989 when the case was brought against
the governor at the time, William A. O'Neill, a Democrat who served
from 1980 to 1991. Milo Sheff, now 19, and studying business at a
community college.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sheff said that the legislature was more concerned about
luring the New England Patriots to Hartford than in improving the
schools there. ``I think the state has gotten its priorities mixed
up,'' she said. ``It seems like stadium, yes, schools, no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
