<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIGSKY-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE MAY GET SHORTCHANGED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Picture this:
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge men's basketball team is in first place
in the Big Sky Conference and driving for a regular-season
championship. The community starts to get behind the team;
attendance at North Campus Gym goes up and the crowds get a little
livelier.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the public relations nightmare for the cash-strapped
CSUN athletic department. Because of a lack of finances, the
university announces it is forfeiting the right, as regular-season
champion, to host the postseason tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A likely scenario?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legitimate question,'' CSUN head basketball coach Bobby
Braswell said. ``If we won our conference this year, would we have
the ability to host the tournament?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most disappointing things would be these players
worked so hard to get that homecourt advantage and then have that
advantage taken away for various reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Big Sky Conference isn't satisfied CSUN would be ready
to host next year's tournament should the Matadors win the
regular-season title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never pull a tournament from somebody because of
their site,'' said Big Sky assistant commissioner Ron Loghry.
``(But) if it doesn't go off well, maybe that spurs CSUN to go in a
different direction. Maybe getting a new arena becomes an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't an issue the athletic department had to face this
year. The tournament starts tonight at Weber State in Ogden, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Collins, CSUN's associate athletic director for business
affairs, is worried about how the school might pay for the right to
host the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN would have to pay a $160,000 guarantee to host the
tournament. The money is distributed to the six qualifying schools
for expenses such as hotel accommodations, airfare and per diem.
CSUN would also have to spend a portion of the guarantee on
promotions, officials and trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Gate revenue is how conference schools cover the cost of the
guarantee. But since North Campus Gym only seats 1,600, and because
1,200 tickets are supposed to be given to the competing teams and
media, that would leave CSUN 400 tickets to recoup more than
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Collins says not to worry about $100 ticket prices. She wants
the department to take an active role in acquiring corporate
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge we would love to meet,'' she said. ``If we
came up short . . . I would say `Let's try harder to fill in the
blank.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A larger arena is what Braswell and the players would like to
see.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my very first year, people were asking me about a new
arena,'' he said. ``I said `Hopefully we'll drive the university by
our success.' I'm not sure we're there yet, but we are headed in
that direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7101 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-SNOOP-LADN     03-03 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-SNOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY CONCERNS RAISED OVER PLAN FOR BANK SCRUTINY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The federal agencies that govern the nation's
banks and thrifts have proposed regulations that, if approved,
would force financial institutions to report to police any
suspicious _ but perfectly legal _ activity in their customers'
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the rules will hamper money launderers such as
drug traffickers and weapons smugglers. Opponents of the
regulations say that if the rules are adopted, someone depositing
an unexpectedly generous bonus check from their boss could be
inviting the scrutiny of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks have a private relationship with their customers. This
has the potential to undermine that,'' said Janet Eissenstat, a
spokeswoman for the American Bankers Association in Washington.
``You want to prevent fraud, but not at the expense of law-abiding
citizens, which are the majority of the banks' customers.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Know Your Customer'' program, as it is called by the four
federal agencies that proposed it last winter, will force banks and
thrifts to monitor their customers' transactions and financial
patterns. If a transaction deviates from that pattern _ such as a
large deposit or withdrawal _ the financial institutions will be
required to alert federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to help the nation's law enforcement agencies stop
money laundering and other illegal acts.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are being considered by the Federal Reserve
System, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., Office of the
Comptroller of the Currency and the Office of Thrift Supervision.
They are accepting public comments until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies, which collectively regulate all of the nation's
banks and thrifts, haven't said when a decision is due, although
officials with the FDIC say it could come by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   There's already been a backlash against the measure, chiefly
because of its Orwellian overtones that suggest an invasion of
privacy. Cries of outrage have been heard from coast to coast, from
boardroom to chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi Fernandez, a retiree from Granada Hills, said her first
reaction was, ``What nerve! How dare they invade my privacy. It's
very frightening to think that they would even consider something
like this _ going over people's accounts and seeing how they go
about their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition has even reached the highest levels of government.
Ironically enough, John D. Hawke Jr., the comptroller of the
currency who came in shortly after the regulation was proposed, is
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has very serious doubts whether this regulation will go,''
said OCC spokesman Robert Garsson. ``The banks won't be employed as
cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers have pointed out they already file reports for cash
transactions of more than $10,000 in accordance with the Bank
Secrecy Act of 1974. They feel the current proposal will be far
more invasive because it will require them to look for patterns in
the way customers handle financial transactions and report activity
that deviates from the norm.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal does pass, Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, has
introduced legislation that would kill it. Paul, a medical doctor,
was the Libertarian Party's 1988 presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The FDIC has received a record 130,000 comments about the
proposal, most of which are opposed to the measure. The other
agencies report getting several thousand of overwhelmingly negative
comments.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has made an unlikely alliance of both liberals and
conservatives, as the nation's two main trade groups representing
banks and thrifts have come out on the side of consumer groups
against the proposal as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Golinger, consumer program director for the California
Public Interest Group, a consumer watchdog, said the privacy breach
built into the proposed regulations is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is an unnecessary invasion of consumers'
privacy,'' he said. ``Banks will be coerced into looking into your
records whether you're a criminal or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks also are concerned because they'll be at a competitive
disadvantage since credit unions and brokerage firms won't have the
same restriction.
</P>
<P>
   America's Community Bankers, the Washington trade group
representing thrifts, said the policy would ``seriously breach
customer privacy rights, damage bank-customer relationships and
unnecessarily burden community banks.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrift group had a counterproposal: Instead, agencies should
target financial institutions that engage in riskier deposit
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Jim Eberle said law enforcement should look more
closely at the larger banks with international operations or
private banking practices for wealthy clients. He said it's more
likely that illegal activities such as money laundering will go
through them than the small thrift around the corner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0533 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
