officials with the FDIC say it could come by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   There's already been a backlash against the measure, chiefly
because of its Orwellian overtones that suggest an invasion of
privacy. Cries of outrage have been heard from coast to coast, from
boardroom to chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Bobbi Fernandez, a retiree from Granada Hills, said her first
reaction was, ``What nerve! How dare they invade my privacy. It's
very frightening to think that they would even consider something
like this _ going over people's accounts and seeing how they go
about their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition has even reached the highest levels of government.
Ironically enough, John D. Hawke Jr., the comptroller of the
currency who came in shortly after the regulation was proposed, is
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has very serious doubts whether this regulation will go,''
said OCC spokesman Robert Garsson. ``The banks won't be employed as
cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Bankers have pointed out they already file reports for cash
transactions of more than $10,000 in accordance with the Bank
Secrecy Act of 1974. They feel the current proposal will be far
more invasive because it will require them to look for patterns in
the way customers handle financial transactions and report activity
that deviates from the norm.
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal does pass, Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas, has
introduced legislation that would kill it. Paul, a medical doctor,
was the Libertarian Party's 1988 presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The FDIC has received a record 130,000 comments about the
proposal, most of which are opposed to the measure. The other
agencies report getting several thousand of overwhelmingly negative
comments.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has made an unlikely alliance of both liberals and
conservatives, as the nation's two main trade groups representing
banks and thrifts have come out on the side of consumer groups
against the proposal as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Golinger, consumer program director for the California
Public Interest Group, a consumer watchdog, said the privacy breach
built into the proposed regulations is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is an unnecessary invasion of consumers'
privacy,'' he said. ``Banks will be coerced into looking into your
records whether you're a criminal or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks also are concerned because they'll be at a competitive
disadvantage since credit unions and brokerage firms won't have the
same restriction.
</P>
<P>
   America's Community Bankers, the Washington trade group
representing thrifts, said the policy would ``seriously breach
customer privacy rights, damage bank-customer relationships and
unnecessarily burden community banks.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrift group had a counterproposal: Instead, agencies should
target financial institutions that engage in riskier deposit
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Jim Eberle said law enforcement should look more
closely at the larger banks with international operations or
private banking practices for wealthy clients. He said it's more
likely that illegal activities such as money laundering will go
through them than the small thrift around the corner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
