<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON AND 27 OTHERS ARRESTED IN PROTEST OF THE DIALLO SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty-eight people, including the Rev. Al Sharpton,
were arrested Wednesday when a noon rally by more than a thousand
people against the police shooting of Amadou Diallo blocked traffic
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, which came almost a month after the Feb. 4
shooting, showed that public anger over Diallo's killing has not
dissipated and that the case has begun to attract a more varied
group of participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first protest I've ever been to because this has
gone on for far too long,'' said Carolyn Cooper, 45, a Citibank
employee who said she took the day off. ``It shouldn't be illegal
to be out on the street if you're a black man or a black woman.
We're here on Wall Street because, unfortunately, you have to hurt
people in their pocketbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said during the rally that he was planning to get
arrested and called for others to commit acts of civil
disobedience. He and 10 protesters then sat in the intersection of
Broadway and Wall Street and blocked traffic. Seventeen others
blocked the doors and marched inside the offices of Merrill Lynch
in the World Financial Center.
</P>
<P>
   All 28 were arrested because they refused to move, Police
Commissioner Howard Safir said at police headquarters. All were
given summonses for criminal trespass or disorderly conduct and
released, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of Sharpton's call for civil disobedience,
Safir replied, ``The Rev. Sharpton apparently just wants to get his
picture in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Protests of the shooting have occurred almost daily since
Diallo, an unarmed street peddler and immigrant from Guinea, in
West Africa, was killed by four plainclothes officers in the
vestibule of his Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   And at least once, protesters have driven past the officers'
homes in a silent procession.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury is now considering whether to indict the officers.
Police officials have said the officers thought Diallo was reaching
for a gun. They fired 41 shots, 19 of which hit him.
</P>
<P>
   If indicted, they could face charges ranging from criminally
negligent homicide to second-degree murder.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The four officers are: Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard
Murphy and Kenneth Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as the demonstration got under way on Wall Street, a
52-year-old employee of Fordham University was arrested for making
threatening phone calls to Carroll's home in Suffolk County, on
Long Island. The suspect, Eric J. Johnson, of Brooklyn, was charged
with two counts of aggravated harassment and was released on bail,
police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
