<SLUG> BC-GLF-NORMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN, BACK FROM SURGERY, HAS NEW SLANT ON LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ At this time last year, Greg Norman was in severe pain,
struggling with a left shoulder injury that required surgery last
April. Seven months of recovery followed, and today Norman's
shoulder is sound and he has returned to the game with a more
appreciative perspective.
</P>
<P>
   So as he prepared for the Doral-Ryder Open, which begins
Thursday at Doral Golf Resort &AMP; Spa here, Norman insisted that no
matter how he performs this year, he will enjoy the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am under zero pressure,'' said Norman, who has won at Doral
three times, most recently in 1996. ``I can stop right now and
everything I have done in the game of golf, good or bad, has been
great. Yes, I haven't achieved everything that I wanted to achieve.
But I gather 99.9 percent in the world feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when I play now, I don't go back to prove that this guy was
wrong, because he wrote this about me,'' Norman said. ``I am not
going to do that anymore. I just want to do the things I do and
enjoy them. I have a totally unfiltered approach toward my game and
toward my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it will be interesting to see if Norman, a two-time winner
of the British Open, can at age 44 return to the pinnacle of his
profession. Because of last year's inactivity, Norman has dropped
to 31st in the world golf ranking. And 1998 was his first year
without a victory on the PGA Tour since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   However, Norman has fond memories of Doral and he will be one of
the marquee names at this week's tournament, where Michael Bradley
is the defending champion. Four of the top 10 players in the world
will play here this week: Ernie Els, Vijay Singh, Nick Price and
Justin Leonard. Still, several of the world's best are taking this
week off after competing at last week's Andersen Consulting Match
Play Championship. Tiger Woods is not playing this week, nor is
David Duval, Davis Love III or Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   Els was also going to skip Doral, but after losing in the first
round last week to Paul Azinger, Els changed his mind. ``I decided
early Friday that I was going to come down here and play,'' said
Els, a South African who has a home in Orlando, Fla. ``It is only a
two or three hour drive down here, so actually it worked out
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman is hoping for a perfect weekend, which would mean winning
again. He survived one round of match play last week, taking his
opening-round match against John Cook. But Norman was defeated in
the second round by Eduardo Romero of Argentina after squandering a
3-up lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the players' perspective, we enjoyed the match play
format,'' Norman said. ``The TV ratings were high as well, which
goes to show that you don't need the name players in a final to
stir up interest.''
</P>
<P>
   While Norman said his swing is pain free, it takes extra time
for him to warm up and to prevent stiffness after a round. ``It
takes a good 50 minutes,'' said Norman of his preround warm-up. ``I
need somebody else to grab hold of my shoulder and move it around.
I can't do that myself. As long as I'm playing, somebody has to be
there in the morning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
