</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PERP-PHOTOGRAPHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS OF PERPS, WITH SPEED AND FLASH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just a sampling of the ``perp walks'' that Marty
Lederhandler has known and loved as The Associated Press'
longest-working photographer:
</P>
<P>
   Willie Sutton, the notoriously slippery bank robber, 1952.
Lederhandler snapped his picture at a Brooklyn precinct house after
he was arrested for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, 1951. They were being moved from the
federal courthouse at Foley Square to the old Federal House of
Detention. (``There wasn't much of a crowd around,'' he said.
``Isn't that strange?'')
</P>
<P>
   Col. Rudolf I. Abel, the Soviet spy released from prison in the
United States and swapped in 1962 for Francis Gary Powers, the
American pilot shot down over the Soviet Union. (``It was in
Brooklyn. I can't even remember the year of that one.'')
</P>
<P>
   David R. Berkowitz, arrested and later convicted of being the
Son of Sam night-stalker, 1977. (``That was a mob scene.'')
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if there is any working photographer in New York
qualified to wax nostalgic for the ``perp walk'' _ the hallowed,
and now heavily litigated, police rite in which a ``perpetrator''
is walked past waiting news cameras _ it is Lederhandler, 81 and
still working full time.
</P>
<P>
   He has been at the job for 63 years, since Fiorello H. La
Guardia was mayor and film came on plates, not rolls.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when the gantlet of lenses outside a station house
was _ he swears _ almost dignified. No jostling television cameras
or jousting microphone booms. No one shouting, ``Did you really do
it?'' or ``Give us a smile,'' or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he said Wednesday, pausing between jobs over a
stack of buttermilk pancakes, ``every once in a while some guy they
were leading out would try to kick at you or spit.''
</P>
<P>
   But mostly it was a cooperative prisoner and a stony-faced row
of newspaper photographers, with ``suits and hats and shirts and
ties'' and boxy Speed Graphic cameras. ``We all had the same lenses
those days,'' he said, ``and everybody would stand 8 or 10 feet
back, and nobody was pushing or shoving.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, depending on the notoriety of the suspect, perp
walks can resemble riots with lots of expensive electronic
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a U.S. District judge in Manhattan issued a ruling
that caused the police to put them at least temporarily on hold.
The judge, Allen G. Schwartz, said they were a violation of privacy
rights, and he allowed a Manhattan doorman to sue the city for
embarrassment he suffered because of a televised perp walk after
his arrest on larceny charges. The charges were later dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In one form or another, the ritual had been around since before
Theodore Roosevelt was the city's police commissioner. But if it is
the end of an era for Lederhandler, he does not seem to mourn it.
</P>
<P>
   He spends no time chewing over the implication for the freedom
of the press or the rights of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what, you're supposed to try to get the picture. So
you're fighting to try to get him in a car window or someplace.
You're stalking him, if he's available for stalking.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the perp walk, it's, `He'll be out in 10 minutes.' You
line up. He comes out and into the car, and you've got your
picture. Nice. As far as the civil rights go, well, I don't know
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lederhandler and his late brother, Harry Leder, who was the
chief photographer for United Press International for more than
three decades, grew up in Brooklyn in the Depression and fell in
love with old folding cameras
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Simon, a Romanian immigrant, worked for an
auctioneer who sold off bankrupt properties. As a teen-ager,
Lederhandler helped out by working at a pharmacy, but he and his
brother spent more time in the pharmacy's basement, which they made
into a darkroom.
</P>
<P>
   They both longed to break into the fast, smoke-clouded world of
New York news photographers, so they got jobs as film messengers
and then photographers' assistants, carrying the bulky film plates
to theater doors or ringsides or station houses. ``Even that was a
glamorous thing, being down ringside at a Joe Louis fight or
Marciano. Or getting to see Maurice Chevalier.''
</P>
<P>
   As a messenger, Lederhandler quickly displayed the kind of wits
that landed him a job as a photographer after World War II:
</P>
<P>
   He was supposed to take film by taxi from Associated Press
headquarters in Rockefeller Center to the Daily News Building on
East 42d Street. Instead, he ran. ``Forty-sixth and Madison, I run
into the Roosevelt Hotel, take the tunnel into Grand Central,
across the terminal to Lexington and Forty-Third, and make a right
toward the building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was faster,'' he said, and then smiled slightly: ``And they
still paid me a dollar for the fare. I was making $12 a week at the
time. Some weeks, I doubled my salary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
