<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOG-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY EXPANDING CAMPAIGN AGAINST OWNERS OF UNLEASHED DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was 9 a.m., give or take a minute or two, and a
dozen dog owners at 91st Street in Riverside Park grimly snapped
leashes in place Wednesday, remembering the scene the morning
before, when mounted officers had given chase and apprehended those
who had missed the on-the-leash deadline.
</P>
<P>
   One dog owner, Judith Schwarz, spotted two mounted Parks
Department rangers waiting just outside the park and loudly
imitated a trumpet heralding a cavalry charge. ``They're keeping
the park safe from dog terrorists!'' she shouted, referring to the
term used by the parks commissioner, Henry J. Stern, for those who
flout leash laws.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rangers, J.D. Cohen, reminded Ms. Schwarz that dogs
are allowed to run free _ in certain areas of the park _ only
between 9 p.m. and 9 a.m., and informed her that she had not made
it under the 9 a.m. wire.
</P>
<P>
   Grudgingly, Ms. Schwarz gave her name and address, then
gratuitously volunteered her Social Security number, blood type and
the names of her pooches, Roxanne and Blue. Not to mention a
pointed comment or two about arbitrary abuses of power in a city
she called Giulianiville. Cohen responded by handing over a summons
that fined her $100 for each dog.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth day in the city's campaign to bring errant
hounds, poodles and spaniels to heel. The city is increasing
enforcement, raising fines and creating a corps of civilian
informers who will carry portable phones to report violations of
the leash law. While neighboring police precincts may soon become
involved, the initial crackdown is concentrating on Central and
Riverside Parks, where, the Parks Department estimates, dogs cause
$250,000 in damage annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is directed against a small minority of willful,
arrogant dog owners,'' Stern said. ``They're like die-hard National
Rifle Association members.''
</P>
<P>
   The NRA comment almost seemed calculated to infuriate the dog
folks, who like to portray themselves as embattled civil
libertarians with furry best friends. ``They're acting like the
Gestapo,'' said a man who said he feared municipal retribution and
would identify himself only as Lou. He did, however, reveal the
full name of his beagle: Wonder Dog.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities say the crackdown appears to be succeeding. A
survey by Parks Department workers in Riverside Park found that on
the first three Saturdays of February combined, about 200 of the
300 dogs in the park were off leash.
</P>
<P>
   But last Saturday just 13 of 97 were, said Ed Skylar, a Parks
Department spokesman. The department said that more than 200
summonses had been issued since the effort began Friday, compared
with 1,005 in all of last year. ``People obey the law when they
have to,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the commissioner said, the crackdown was drawing
support, with mail running 3-to-1 in favor of the tougher
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The next stage of the campaign will be to pass out portable
phones to volunteers, who will be instructed to try to persuade
people to leash their dogs before tattling on them. Other parks,
the first of which will probably be Prospect Park in Brooklyn, will
also be concentrated on, Stern said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
