<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-GEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADGETS, GIZMOS AND GEAR: NEW SNOW STUFF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Wyo. , Calif.)  (nk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flashy new shaped skis or lightweight snowboard boots can add
pizzazz to a trip to the slopes. But other innovations _ ones you
may not know to look for _ can be as enticing as a fast chairlift
on a slow day.
</P>
<P>
   SEE AND SKI: Following in your own footsteps on the snow may be
one way to try something new. Maptrek, a fledgling computer map
company in Vail, Colo., has been testing a new satellite-based
topographic system this winter. It enables resort guests to see
their route over hill and dale, see how many vertical feet they
skied, how fast and how many miles.
</P>
<P>
   For $20 a day, a skier attaches a small, coin-sized antenna to a
jacket collar. A wire leads to a pocket transmitter about the size
of a pager, which logs personal tracking information. At the end of
the day, the unit is taken back to Maptrek's ski area office and
downloaded into a desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The resort customer receives a color-coded, three-dimensional
topographic map with individualized pacing information. But the
setup may not be for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice for the additional information it gives you,'' said
Rene Lemble, a ski instructor at Vail. ``We find that people who
come here do it once or twice to see how they did. But it's mostly
for intermediate and advanced skiers. Beginner skiers usually don't
travel more than 200 yards in a day, so it's not that helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   By mounting an antenna at the 10,000-foot peak of Vail Mountain,
the company is able to use the worldwide global positioning system.
Sailors and hikers already are using the tracking system, which was
developed for the military.
</P>
<P>
   Hoot Gibson, president of Maptrek, said recently that his
company plans to make the system available next season at five
other mountain resorts: Northstar at Tahoe, and at Heavenly in
California; Copper Mountain and Beaver Creek, Colo., and at Grand
Targhee, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, the company's Internet site is:
www.maptrek.com.
</P>
<P>
   IN YOUR FACE: A sub-zero day on a mountain can drain the body of
warmth faster than most clothes can keep it warm. But Bruce
McCormick, an inventor from Houston, has come up with a face mask
that works like steam heat in a duct system.
</P>
<P>
   Referred to as the Polar Wrap Exchanger, the head gear looks
like a standard face warmer. But the design is deceiving. Inside
the mask is a patented system of copper coils that its manufacturer
calls a thermal exchange device. A series of tiny inner chambers
regulate the flow and velocity of air breathed in and then exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   The exchanger collects the warm, moist exhaled air, then
recycles it. The reused portion, about 8 percent of the previous
air intake, warms and adds moisture to the next cold breath of dry
air that is inhaled. ``It works best when you're sitting in a cold
chairlift,'' McCormick said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you're really exposed to the cold,'' he said.
``You have a high exposure to body heat loss until you get off, and
start creating body warmth by propelling yourself down the
mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Miracle, new products editor for Skiing magazine, said
recently that he had tested the Polar Wrap Exchanger hood this past
January at Loveland, Colo., ski area. ``It definitely does what
it's supposed to,'' Miracle said. ``It certainly is the most
effective warming gear I've ever worn. But its ability to eliminate
a skier from getting cold may be far-fetched.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two models available and the price ranges from about
$60 to $67.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, or to order, call (800) 967-WRAP.
</P>
<P>
   STONE THERAPY: There's also a way to combat apres-ski shivers. A
new kind of massage, LaStone Therapy, is appearing at spas in many
mountain resort towns. Developed in large part by Mary Hannigan, a
massage therapist in Tucson, Ariz., the technique uses heated
stones to treat tense, overworked muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the spa, therapists use as many as 50 stones heated
to a temperature of about 140 degrees. About 20 other stones,
usually made of rounded and polished marble, are cooled to the
point of freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Gathered from river beds and quarries, the mostly basalt stones
are smooth and flat so they do not irritate the skin. Therapists
use body oil to move individual hot rocks over various muscle
groups. A final touch with cold marble at the neck and spine often
finishes the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat opens the circulatory system, and the cold
constricts, keeping everything flexible,'' said Lisa DeKoster, spa
director at the Vail Athletic Club in Vail, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The LaStone Internet site is: www.lastonetherapy.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
