<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAKEMITSU-MUSIC-2TAKE     03-03 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAKEMITSU-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANDERING WITH TAKEMITSU IN HIS GARDENS OF THE MIND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Japanese composer Toru Takemitsu, who died three years ago,
often likened his pieces to gardens: specifically Japanese gardens,
made to be admired at a strolling pace, with frequent stops to
enjoy, perhaps, the foliage of a tree, or a flower, or a spider's
web, or a distant view.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the analogy fits almost everything he wrote, whatever
the style (and there were many), but his music's customary slow
andante may have come from a deeper inkling into how we listen.
</P>
<P>
   The irregular amble is the tempo of one thought supplanting
another, each lasting for the normal extent of time we think of as
the present, which is about two or three seconds. Music behaving
this way can seem to go at its own pace, because it is going at
ours.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing hurries it on from loitering at the speed of our
unfocused expectation. There are no commanding rhythms, no
structural requirements to be met. We hear this, then something
like this, then something like the last this. By comparison with
Takemitsu's music, Debussy's sounds fiercely directed.
</P>
<P>
   Takemitsu produced a large output, especially of orchestral
scores; in his last 10 years alone he wrote 14 pieces for large
orchestra and others for smaller groupings. Since his death, CDs
have made most of these works available, though his last orchestral
piece, ``Spectral Canticle,'' with violin and guitar soloists, has
yet to be recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are also gaps where the works of the 1960s
and early 70s are concerned, and it is often among these that the
best of Takemitsu is to be found.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, in the 50s, Takemitsu became an admirer of
Debussy and Messiaen, who were the main influences on his
compositions of that decade (including the 1957 Requiem for
strings, with which he made his name), and who returned to guide
much of the music he wrote from the mid-70s on.
</P>
<P>
   In between, he drew on more recent composers, especially John
Cage (in a couple of graphic scores of 1962) and Pierre Boulez, and
contributed a lot himself to the exploration of new orchestral
sonorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter'' (1971) is a wonderful example: a skein of frosty
sounds _ sustained string harmonics, percussion spangles, echoes
across the orchestra _ that gets right away from the
Debussy-Messiaen sound world that Takemitsu loved so much to
re-enter.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the pieces unavailable at present, though a 1981
recording by the Tokyo Metropolitan Symphony under the direction of
Hiroyuki Iwaki turns up in secondhand stores. Of other works from
the middle period, a new release by the same orchestra (Denon CO
18073), with Yuzo Toyama conducting, offers two: ``Coral Island''
(1962), a beautiful if over-Boulezian cycle of orchestral images
and interleaved songs with high soprano (the excellent Rie Hamada),
and ``The Dorian Horizon'' (1966), a striking set of glassy
surfaces created by two groups of strings playing without vibrato.
</P>
<P>
   Also on this CD are a sumptuous recording of ``A Flock Descends
Into the Pentagonal Garden'' (1977), which is the richest piece
Takemitsu produced as he was going back into his French-Japanese
garden of choice, and a fine performance of ``Archipelago S.''
(1993), for a chamber orchestra in separated groups. If you want
only one Takemitsu CD, this, of those in print, is the one to get.
</P>
<P>
   It is the fourth in a Takemitsu series on Denon, all with the
Tokyo Metropolitan Symphony, and all with excellent notes, by the
composer and by Japanese scholars. Another (Denon CO 79441)
contains what is probably still Takemitsu's most famous piece _
``November Steps,'' with shakuhachi (recorder) and biwa (lute),
written for the New York Philharmonic in 1967 _ though by no means
his best.
</P>
<P>
   Also here are Requiem and two works from the 80s: the violin
concerto ``Far Calls, Coming, Far!'' (one of several quotes from
Joyce's ``Finnegans Wake'' the composer used as titles) and
``Visions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Archipelago S.'' is included on a second new CD, from Oliver
Knussen and the London Sinfonietta (Deutsche Grammophon 453 495-2),
where it is accompanied by other works from Takemitsu's final
decade or so. During this period, the Debussy-Messiaen mixture
thinned out in favor of Debussy, and the biggest work on Knussen's
album, ``Quotation of Dream,'' for large orchestra with two solo
pianos (here played by Paul Crossley and Peter Serkin), has
figments from ``La Mer'' enveloped in luxurious swathes of original
music.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, the piece sounds like Debussy being composed and
taken apart again, but generally the effect is to make one wish one
were listening to Debussy uninterruptedly, preferably with Knussen
conducting.
</P>
<P>
   Other pieces on this disk, especially ``Archipelago S.'' and the
related ``How Slow the Wind,'' are the better for making their
Debussy references more subtly and maybe unintentionally: the music
just seems to be bobbing in the wavelets around the edges of
Debussy's sea.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Archipelago S.'' is the strongest work here, partly because of
its sparer textures and the return of unusual instrumental effects,
which Takemitsu had mostly avoided since the mid-70s. The recording
captures its spatial layout better than the Denon, but the Japanese
orchestra's performance is equally fine, and its mixed program
clinches the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about the top Takemitsu CD are more likely to be fueled
by a glorious and highly musical release featuring the clarinetist
Richard Stoltzman (RCA 09026-62537-2). Stoltzman is the soloist in
another orchestral work from Takemitsu's final few years,
``Fantasma/Cantos,'' and he performs with New York colleagues in
various chamber pieces: the trickling ``Waterways'' (1977), with
harps, vibraphones, piano and strings; the inward ``Quatrain II''
(1976), played here by the musicians for whom it was written
(Stoltzmann, Serkin, Ida Kavafian and Fred Sherry), and one of this
gentle composer's more robust compositions, ``Waves'' (1976), for
clarinet, horn, trombones and bass drum.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber pieces for more traditional combinations come on a new
CD featuring splendid young Japanese performers, the Ensemble Kai
(Bis 920). Here Takemitsu's two string quartets make a sharp
contrast: ``Landscape I'' (1961) is in the taut, vibrato-free style
of ``The Dorian Horizon,'' and ``A Way a Lone'' (1980) unfolds in
generous modal phrases, warmly supported.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Rocking Mirror Daybreak'' (1983), for two violins, shows
that Takemitsu did not entirely abandon his taste for the nervy
sounds of harmonics and nonvibrato playing, and this pleasant
compilation covers almost the composer's entire career, from 1951
(``Distance de Fee'' for violin and piano) to 1993 (the piano trio
``Between Tides'').
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the gap between these works is not so wide, for
Takemitsu's life had looped back, and the most extraordinary pieces
were all in the interim. (Even at his most extraordinary, though,
he was capable of a much more conventional style, notably in his
choral music, a disappointing segment of his output, and his film
scores, of which he wrote nearly 100, many of them recorded on
Japanese labels.)
</P>
<P>
   The piano music tells the same story, of a journey from close to
Messiaen (``Litany'' and ``Uninterrupted Rest,'' both essentially
works of the 50s) through fresh, vivid directions (``Piano
Distance'' of 1961, ``For Away'' of 1973) back to the
Messiaen-Debussy neighborhood (especially in ``Les Yeux Clos'').
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Piano Distance'' _ full of textural contrasts and
breathtaking pedal effects _ is by far the most exciting piece in
this repertory, ``For Away'' is fine, too, and there are a couple
of gems among the late pieces in ``Rain Tree Sketch'' and ``Rain
Tree Sketch II.''
</P>
<P>
   At least six pianists have made all-Takemitsu disks, but only
three are serious contenders: Kazuoki Fujii (Fontec FOCD 3109),
Roger Woodward (Etcetera KTC 1103) and Peter Serkin (RCA
09026-68595-2). Fujii adds an attractive harpsichord piece, ``Rain
Dreaming,'' and Woodward offers a big improvisation based on two
graphic scores.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are worth hearing; both have a keen sense of the
abrupt, though Fujii is all lightness and brightness, where
Woodward tends to be heavy and, at times, melodramatic. There are
also notable disagreements as to tempo: Fujii plays ``Rain Tree
Sketch'' almost twice as fast as Mr. Woodward, and it works both
ways.
</P>
<P>
   But not only is Serkin's collection more complete (``Rain Tree
Sketch II'' was composed after the other musicians made their
recordings), his playing is more thorough, more considered and more
nuanced. New listeners could also start here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
