<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MODERN-MUSEUM-FILMS-2     03-03 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERN-MUSEUM-FILMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE FILMS CAN REST EASY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't your typical Al Pacino movie, this small film about a
celebrity-obsessed thug that the box-office heavyweight had
lovingly acted in and dug deep into his pockets to produce.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``The Local Stigmatic'' never enjoyed financial
success, period, having landed on a dusty shelf after Pacino, who
spent four years editing and re-editing the film after it was shot
in 1985, failed to find a distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino was loath to abandon the work he considers his ``calling
card.'' So he did what a top-flight filmmaker might have done: he
donated it to the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film would not have had a home otherwise,'' Pacino said.
``It meant that a movie that I believed in could be viewed without
the burden of commercial success.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacino, although known as an actor, understood what a generation
of filmmakers are only too aware of: that their fragile life's work
could deteriorate unchecked _ and maybe not even be missed _ in a
dank corner of some movie studio storage closet.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Museum of Modern Art comes in. Since 1996, the
museum has campaigned to rescue contemporary works foundering in
back rooms and warehouses, and to fill in a gap in their collection
in the process. ``200 for 2000'' is exactly what it sounds like:
the museum's goal of adding to its collection 200 films by worthy
filmmakers by the end of the year 2000. With less than two more
years to go, the museum is not quite to the halfway point.
</P>
<P>
   That the most esteemed directors are often the most generous is
something that museum officials have counted on _ since the film
department was formed in the golden age of the silver screen in
1935.
</P>
<P>
   John Hay Whitney, who produced ``Gone With the Wind'' with David
O. Selznick, served as the first chairman of the museum's film
library, and in 1936, he sent the curator Iris Barry to Hollywood
to urge industry leaders to donate prints _ a radical concept at
the time but one to which the likes of Harold Lloyd, D.W.
Griffiths, Douglas Fairbanks Sr., Walt Disney and Mary Pickford
hearkened.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were good friends to the department, and that is a
tradition we have continued ever since,'' said Mary Lea Bandy, the
museum's chief film curator. ``Because, after all, our collection
is part of a much larger art collection that is trying to represent
the finest works of art of the 20th century in a very broad and
deep way.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 16,000 titles spanning the century of cinema, the
museum boasts one of the finest collections in the world. It is up
there with the Pacific Film Archives in Berkeley, Calif., the UCLA
Film and Television Archives in Los Angeles, the George Eastman
House in Rochester, the Library of Congress and the American Film
Institute, which houses its collection at the library but which
will occasionally pass along a film to another archive.
</P>
<P>
   The Modern's collection ranges from the kinetoscope subjects of
Thomas Edison and D.W. Griffiths to recent films like ``Fargo'' and
``The Bridges of Madison County,'' from the mainstream to the
experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1996, these films have been housed in the museum's
state-of-the-art, 36,000-sqare-foot Celeste Bartos Film
Preservation Center in Hamlin, Pa., with storage for the next 30
years, and 38 acres on which to build.
</P>
<P>
   What the museum doesn't have, however, is a comprehensive
collection representing the best of post-World War II American
cinema. ``It takes a long time to acquire quality prints that
interest us, simply because of availability, rights and the cost of
making the print,'' Ms. Bandy said. ``So you have to be extremely
patient, which we think we are, because we're acquiring for the
long run.''
</P>
<P>
   In the best possible scenario, the museum receives a completely
new or mint-condition print, struck directly from the negative. But
the museum is often presented with a print in good condition that
has been shown before, or a worn print that is valuable to the
collection.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some acquisitions are badly deteriorated _ especially in the
case of certain films made before the 1950s and shot on
nitrate-based stock, which is so flammable it can no longer be
projected. (Movies today are filmed on stock called, appropriately,
``safety acetate,'' or on polyester.) Archivists then copy
nitrate-based films onto acetate stock or preserve the original
color separation to make a print that the museum can project.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the question of who actually owns the print.
Usually it's the studio, which typically has a contract stating
that it owns the rights to the film, in perpetuity, on all current
media and any media yet to be developed. Depending on his clout, a
director may negotiate ownership of the negative or the right to
dispose of prints at will.
</P>
<P>
   Independent films are in a more precarious position, with
production companies often set up as a one-shot entity for a film.
The company owns the rights to the film, but doesn't necessarily
have the funding _ or the staying power _ to pay for storage fees
years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   And because an independent company will strike fewer prints than
a major studio, which may strike thousands, their cost per film is
higher _ somewhere in the tens of thousands of dollars for a single
print.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that studios don't care,'' said Leonard Maltin, the
film critic and historian. ``Rather, the number of films being
produced on a monthly basis that would have to be archived is
overwhelming, both financially and in terms of manpower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the idea that there ought to be independent
institutions who serve as caretakers comes in,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For MOMA's ``200 for 2000,'' directors have rallied to the task.
Martin Scorsese, a proponent of restoration and preservation who
mounted a campaign for better film stock after he saw his 1980
``Raging Bull'' wither, has donated most of his works.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he also sponsored the restoration of Jean-Luc Godard's
1963 masterpiece, ``Le Mepris'' (``Contempt''), a film that
inspired Scorsese's own career and that was acquired by the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen has donated most of his oeuvre, as have Clint
Eastwood and Oliver Stone. Pacino went back to the museum with
``Looking for Richard,'' his 1996 directorial debut. The estate of
Andy Warhol donated his films for safekeeping. The Rainer Werner
Fassbinder Foundation made a gift of some 20 features. And
independents like John Sayles, Hal Hartley and Joel and Ethan Coen
have welcomed the chance to have their works preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Directors may mourn their films. Ask Stone and he'll tally off
``The Doors,'' ``Talk Radio,'' ``Platoon'' and ``Salvador'' _ works
lost to either poor preservation or to bankruptcy proceedings,
where creditors are given license to dispose of a studio's
libraries by selling the films or even junking them.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly cautious, Stone has been contributing his work
since 1989. ``Every time there's a film, I've been trying to give a
mint-condition print to the museum.''
</P>
<P>
   That a director might not have a copy of his own film is often
unbelievable to the public, Maltin said. ``I think people believe
that the crisis of film preservation deals exclusively with films
of the past, and this is not so. The ultimate example is that when
they reissued `Grease' theatrically, they discovered that the
original negative was in appalling condition and was in need of
major rescue work, including the sound track.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `But I just saw it on TV or on video,''' he added.
``What they don't really understand is that unless you can project
that film on a movie screen in a theater the way it was first
shown, it doesn't really exist in its original form. You can have a
perfectly wonderful video copy, but it's a derivative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-03-99 2327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
