<DOCNO> NYT19990303.0544 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7124 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-$ADV07-     03-03 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-$ADV07-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 `NOT ABOUT NIGHTINGALES': SPECTACULARLY REALIZED TENNESSEE WILLIAMS
`THE HOTHOUSE': VINTAGE PINTER IN A FIRST-RATE REVIVAL `BRIGHT
LIGHTS BIG CITY': TALENTED CAST BUT A HOST OF PROBLEMS (For release
Sunday, March 7)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)(mk) 
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``My next play will be simple, direct and terrible _
a picture of my own heart. There will be no artifice in it. I will
speak the truth as I see it ... It will be myself without
concealment or evasion and with a fearless unashamed frontal
assault upon life that will leave no room for trepidation ... (It
will be) a passionate denial of sham and a cry for beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Williams wrote these lines in his journal in a mood of
``manic elation'' on Easter Sunday 1939. Having recently won a
special Group Theater award of $100 for three sketches titled
``American Blues,'' he suddenly felt certified as a playwright. He
was reborn, as he seems to have been periodically throughout his
life as well as after.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was 28 and, in truth, his life of obscurity was about
to end. A year later he received his first major production with
the Theater Guild's staging of ``Battle of Angels.'' It was a
failure, but ``The Glass Menagerie'' followed in 1945, the first of
the succession of remarkable works that would secure his position
today as one of America's three greatest dramatists, with Eugene
O'Neill and Arthur Miller.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Tom: The Unknown Tennessee Williams,'' Lyle Leverich
describes the playwright's Easter message as ``a manifesto for all
the plays and stories to come.'' Yet the later work did not emerge
from a vacuum. It was preceded by a number of earlier plays, some
of which were produced by groups in and around St. Louis; others
were left unproduced and more or less forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of these unproduced ``lost'' plays, ``Not About
Nightingales,'' written in 1938 and rescued from the archives by
Vanessa Redgrave, that is now at Circle in the Square on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   As staged by Trevor Nunn, the artistic director of the Royal
National Theater in London, the production is so spectacularly
realized that it both serves the play and celebrates the Williams
career, for which it can be seen as a kind of gaudy preface.
</P>
<P>
   The New York production also represents an Anglo-American
collaboration of an especially rich kind. It is a joint venture of
the Royal National, where it was first seen last spring, the Alley
Theater in Houston, where it played in June, and the Moving
Theater, also based in London. The latter is the company founded by
Ms. Redgrave, her brother, Corin, and Kika Markham (who is married
to Redgrave) to produce plays that, among other things, ``reflect
the contradictions and the problems of the times we live in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not About Nightingales'' is not characteristic Tennessee
Williams. It wears its social-political concerns openly. Like the
Federal Theater Project's Living Newspapers of the time, it was
inspired by a true story: the scandal about the Philadelphia
County, Pa., prison where four inmates were murdered _ cooked alive
_ after being locked in a room lined with radiators turned up to
produce maximum heat.
</P>
<P>
   The play is so brutal that it occasionally appears to be an
over-the-top mega-``Big House'' movie, the sort that in the 1930s
could be made cheaply and fast and give studios like Warner
Brothers the reputation of being socially relevant.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``Not About Nightingales'' is also ``simple, direct and
terrible.'' Though its artifice is apparent, the ``cry for beauty''
is genuine and moving, expressed in characters and events made
familiar by the ``Big House'' genre. Had the play not been written
by the man who became Tennessee Williams, I'm not at all sure that
it would ever have received the attention that is currently being
lavished on it.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Not About Nightingales'' is very much a Williams play. The
splendid production not only finds the work's theatrically vivid
life, it also deepens our appreciation of the playwright: how he
saw himself and how he dueled with his demons. In none of the great
plays that followed is there a graphic evocation of hell-on-earth
to match the one in ``Not About Nightingales,'' particularly as
staged by Nunn. The play's metaphors are not subtle, and neither is
the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the drama are early versions of two archetypal
Williams characters. Tom, the narrator and surrogate Williams
figure in ``The Glass Menagerie,'' appears here as Canary Jim
(Finbar Lynch), the trusty who pretty much runs the warden's office
and, as a result, is thought to be a stool pigeon by the other
inmates. Jim is a self-taught intellectual who reads Keats and
Spengler, lives uncaged in his mind, and survives by maintaining a
tight, humiliating control over his impulse to rebel.
</P>
<P>
   There also are the seeds of Big Daddy (``Cat on a Hot Tin
Roof'') and Boss Finley (``Sweet Bird of Youth'') in Boss Whalen
(Corin Redgrave), the prison warden. He is a big, shrewd,
mean-tempered man, a bully, possibly psychotic, whose omnipotent
authority has a way of neutralizing and bewitching everyone around
him. This would include Eva (Sherri Parker Lee), the young woman
who, desperate for work, takes a job as his secretary. Though she
falls in love with Jim, she remains quite helpless when the often
sozzled warden directs his attentions toward her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not About Nightingales'' is heavy on narrative (never a
Williams specialty), being about the events leading up to an
explosion of primal forces when Boss Whalen tries to put down a
hunger strike by packing off a small group of ringleaders and
innocents to what is called ``the Klondike.'' This is a room,
specially fitted with steam radiators, where the temperature can be
raised to 150 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The time of the play remains fixed in 1938. The location of the
island prison is not identified, but it would seem to be the Deep
South. The fact that the inmates are not racially segregated has
less to do with reality than with nontraditional casting.
</P>
<P>
   There are several four-letter words in the dialogue (nothing by
today's standards of street talk), possibly added by Williams long
after completing the first draft. Certainly he could never have
expected to hear such words spoken from any stage in 1938. The
production's comparative purity of language and the nontraditional
casting set the play outside of time, giving perspective to the
playwright's vision: For all of its stereotypical characters and
manners borrowed from 1930s movies, ``Not About Nightingales'' is
announcing the apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Elia Kazan's productions of ``A Streetcar Named
Desire,'' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof'' and ``Sweet Bird of Youth'' has
Williams been as well served by a director as he is here.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nunn has so beautifully integrated the British and American
actors that you have to check the program to figure out their
nationalities. Redgrave, not seen on a New York stage in years, is
a riveting, almost charming redneck madman. Lynch, Redgrave's Irish
co-star, plays the seething poet Canary Jim with a quiet power that
has the effect of disciplining and making comprehensible the wildly
grotesque melodrama. He is the production's humane focal point.
</P>
<P>
   James Black, an American actor who has long been associated with
the Alley Theater, is very fine in what could have been an early
Jimmy Cagney role, that of Butch O'Fallon, the fast-talking con who
initially organizes the hunger strike. He even looks a bit like
Cagney. The role of Eva, the warden's secretary, is more a function
of the plot than a character, though Ms. Lee, an American actress,
lends her an urgently dramatic authority.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway's Circle in the Square is still the most awkward major
theater space in New York, the stage being long and narrow with the
audience placed around its three sides. There does not seem to be a
seat in the house for which some part of the stage isn't hidden, or
so far away that the action becomes unnecessarily obscure. If you
are sitting in the best seats, facing stage-center, with the two
other playing areas of the long rectangle on your left and right,
you watch what is going on as if at a tennis match.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn can't change the shape of the house. Yet he fills the stage
(sometimes allowing the action to spill over into the aisles) so
efficiently that the play remains coherent, while moving with the
speed of light, even when the sightlines are not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Salute Tennessee. Salute everyone responsible for this latest
rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   `The Hothouse'
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hothouse,'' now being given a first-rate revival by the
Atlantic Theater Company, was never actually lost, but Harold
Pinter, who wrote it in 1958, put it aside to mull over and went on
to write ``The Caretaker.'' He didn't get back to ``The Hothouse''
until 1979, and directed its first London production himself in
1980. It was first seen in New York in 1982 in the Trinity Square
Repertory Theater production directed by Adrian Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the to-ing and fro-ing? I'm not sure. As is demonstrated
in the Atlantic Theater production directed by Karen Kohlhaas,
``The Hothouse'' is clearly vintage Pinter. It is not in the league
with such later meditative full-length plays as ``The Homecoming,''
``Old Times'' and ``No Man's Land,'' but it is close to being as
substantially eerie, disorienting and witty as anything he wrote
earlier, excepting ``The Birthday Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The setting: a government institution, which could be some kind
of sanitarium or maybe a place where a fascist government
discreetly hides enemies of the state. We never meet the
``patients'' (who have numbers instead of names), only the members
of the staff headed by Roote (Larry Bryggman), a beady-eyed,
magnificently pompous bureaucrat with an extremely short attention
span.
</P>
<P>
   The others include Miss Cutts (Kate Blumberg), Roote's mistress;
Gibbs (Jordan Lage), the institution's all-too-efficient No. 2 man;
Lush (Patrick Breen), who seems to be an almost normal fellow,
maybe because he drinks, and Lamb (Liam Christopher O'Brien), the
eager young newcomer to the staff. Poor kid. You know where lambs
are led.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of this one Christmas Day, everything goes wrong
for Roote: He learns that a male patient has been dead for some
time without his knowledge and that a female patient has had a
baby. He will not have it! Order is necessary if society is to
survive! He says that changes must be made, and then declaims at
length on why the rules should remain inviolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hothouse'' is classified as one of Pinter's political
plays, which it is. It is also very funny. Bryggman and his
associates are close to perfect. Note also Walt Spangler's severely
impersonal set, so brightly lighted by Robert Perry that we know
we're in a world that has lost its soul. It's a place without
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   `Bright Lights Big City'
</P>
<P>
   A lot of fine young talent is going nowhere in New York Theater
Workshop's attempt to make a ``Rent''-like musical out of ``Bright
Lights Big City,'' Jay McInerney's best-selling seminal novel on
his booze-swilling, drug-sniffing 1980s generation.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Michael Greif, who staged ``Rent.'' The cast is
eager to make good, and the music, by Paul Scott Goodman, has a
number of attractive things in it. Yet Goodman's book and lyrics,
as well as his own uneasy performance as the show's singing
narrator, keep getting in the way. His failure is not a surprise.
Even the movie adaptation couldn't make it, and it was written by
McInerney.
</P>
<P>
   A superficial read of the novel could spot the difficulty. What
happens to the story's unnamed hero as he goes from bad to worse,
attempting to manage life in Manhattan's fast lane, isn't as
important as how it is told. The distinctive voice, which speaks to
the reader in the second person, is full of hilarious, poignant
asides, digressions, opinions and apercus. These do not easily
translate into a musical in which most of the dialogue is sung.
</P>
<P>
   The accent and stage personality of the Scottish-born Goodman
are as alien to ``Bright Lights Big City'' as Steven Spielberg's
E.T. would be. Though his melodies often work, his lyrics assault
you with banalities. The sad thing: If, somehow, the book and
lyrics could be upgraded, the actors would certainly be able to
carry it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the noteworthy: Patrick Wilson, who plays the unstrung
hero, now named Jamie; Napiera Daniele Groves as his estranged
wife; Jerry Dixon as his wayward best friend, and Natascia Diaz as
the new woman in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it opened too soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
