<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-NYT     03-03 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON LET MO VAUGHN GO, BUT WHO WILL REPLACE HIM? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Mo Vaughn wasn't in the Boston Red Sox spring
training camp Wednesday. Roger Clemens wasn't there, either. But
then neither was Ted Williams, nor Babe Ruth for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Let it be said that the Red Sox, even without each of the last
three players, did finish first in their league or division. And
someday maybe they will finish first again without Vaughn. But this
year is not likely to be that day.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Red Sox miss Mo Vaughn? Does the Green Monster live at
Fenway Park?
</P>
<P>
   ``We all loved him in here,'' said Mike Stanley, one of three
players who may replace Vaughn at first base, though not in the
lineup or in the hearts and minds of his former teammates. ``There
isn't a guy in here who would say a bad thing about him. He's a
gamer, somebody who pumped you up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many guys that when they yell at you in the
dugout and the clubhouse you listen to. He's one of them. Other
guys you kind of just say sit down and be quiet. If this was
hockey, he'd be the one with the `C' on his chest. We all listened
to what he had to say. His clubhouse presence will be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the 158 home runs and 480 RBIs that he produced
the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is not in the Red Sox camp because he's in Tempe, Ariz.,
with the Anaheim Angels, the team that gave him $80 million for six
years after the Red Sox did everything they had to in order not to
sign him. And he left two years after the Red Sox let Clemens
leave, with General Manager Dan Duquette declaring that the
three-time Cy Young award winner was in the twilight of his career.
Now Clemens has five Cy Young awards and is pitching for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox eventually replaced Clemens with an expensive Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   And they wouldn't mind replacing Vaughn with Frank Thomas, but
the Chicago White Sox say they are not trading their first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Without Vaughn or a suitable successor, the Red Sox seem to have
virtually no chance to reach the playoffs, which means they would
end the 1900s with the one World Series championship they have had
since the 19th year of the 1900s. Meanwhile, Vaughn's absence has
already been noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot quieter camp than it's been in the past,'' said
John Valentin, Vaughn's former teammate with Boston and Seton Hall.
``He's a guy who talks a lot. He's vocal. He's a presence in the
clubhouse as well as on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The silence created by Vaughn's departure has generated spring
training talk that has focused on his absence and speculation about
how bad the Red Sox _ who made it to the post-season last year as
the American League wild-card team and then lost in the first round
_ will be without him. Bret Saberhagen, for one, has grown weary of
the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of hearing about Mo,'' the pitcher said. ``I really
am. Mo's with the Angels. There's nothing we can do. I think the
thing that will stop everyone from talking about Mo is if we go out
and start playing and winning. So I can't wait for the season to
get going and us winning games. Then we won't have to hear about Mo
anymore. I'm just worn out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman could be excused if he has grown tired of being
asked about Vaughn. Accepting an inflated contract of $26 million
for four years, Offerman represents the only splash the Red Sox
made in the free-agent market this winter. His .315 batting average
last season, the best of his career, has had some people mistakenly
looking to him to help fill the hitting void.
</P>
<P>
   But Offerman said: ``I wasn't brought here to replace him.
People have to understand that. There's no way you can replace that
guy. We're two different players.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman will play first or second base or both, depending on
other players, such as Jeff Frye, who could play second if he's
healthy, and Stanley and Reggie Jefferson, who are prepared to play
first or serve as designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   By shuffling Offerman on the right side of the infield, the Red
Sox could be taking a chance on rendering him less productive on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say at this point if that would happen,''
Offerman said. ``At this point I don't think it will affect me
mentally. If it doesn't affect me mentally, I don't think I'd have
a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams said it's too early for him to make out a
batting order, but he said he plans to open the season with a set
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to let these players know maybe what their role is to
start the season,'' he said. ``Those things can change, but you
have to start somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Red Sox have to begin life without Mo and the
offense he produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to replace the numbers,'' Valentin said. ``You can't
just replace 35 to 40 home runs and 100-some RBIs. But more
important, it's the presence in the lineup, too. Who he protects,
who he hits behind and in front of is very important, The opposing
teams are probably going to look at us a little differently without
him around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, Valentin added and others concurred, will have to
generate runs in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be a team that pitches well and plays good
defense,'' he said. ``We may not have the luxury of the three-run
homer at times. We may need to manufacture runs more. Not may. We
probably will.''
</P>
<P>
   But some baseball people aren't convinced that the Red Sox will
be able to do that. One veteran scout from another American League
team studied the Red Sox roster that adorned the wall of his
general manager's spring training office and said, ``That's the
weakest outfield I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to the collection of Troy O'Leary, Darren Lewis,
Damon Buford, Trot Nixon and Midre Cummings. The group doesn't seem
to offer much potential for the kind of productive hitting the Red
Sox will need to overcome the loss of Vaughn's punch.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Nomar Garciaparra, their remarkable shortstop, on
his own. Thirty-five home runs and 122 RBIs is terrific production
from a shortstop, but that could become meaningless if Garciaparra
doesn't have support in the lineup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
