<HEADLINE>
INDIGNATION IN GERMANY OVER ARIZONA DEATH SENTENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY BETH WARNER  
 and JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Ilona Vogt was adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen years on death row is enough punishment,'' said the
50-year-old office manager and firm opponent of the death penalty.
``There are other ways to punish people besides killing them.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Arizona death row inmate and German citizen Walter
LaGrand has been heavily covered by the German media, including
major articles in some of the country's largest newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been little public protest, the story has
stirred widespread indignation, some indifference and criticism of
politicians in both countries _ especially Arizona Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reaction among German politicians and political
commentators has been outrage at the frequent practice of the death
penalty in the United States. Acutely ashamed of the murderous
history of Adolf Hitler's Nazi regime, Germany abolished the death
penalty shortly after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   On German television Tuesday, government officials were
lamenting the fact that the United States was about to conduct
another execution even as Secretary of State Madeline Albright was
in China, complaining of human rights violations there.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Washington, a State Department spokeswoman
questioned Germany's decision to take the LaGrand case to the
International Court of Justice in The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Germany complained to the court that the United States violated
international law by not notifying German consular officials about
the arrest of Walter and Karl LaGrand 17 years ago on charges that
they murdered Kenneth Hartsock during a bungled bank robbery near
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   German officials say they could have ensured that the LaGrands
received better legal representation than what public defenders
provided in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germany has known about the consular notification issue for a
number of years but did not raise it with us until very recently,''
State Department spokeswoman Maria Rudenski said.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenski noted that while the LaGrands were born in Germany,
they came to the United States as young boys, spoke English
fluently and were familiar with the U.S. legal system.
</P>
<P>
   According to human rights watchdog Amnesty International, 72
citizens of 26 foreign countries are occupants of American death
rows. There are seven such individuals in Arizona, not including
Walter LaGrand, and three other German citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenski said one American citizen is on the death row of a
foreign country. She said an American man has been condemned to
death for pushing his wife off a roof to her death in a Caribbean
country. She was unable to obtain the country's name Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The responsibility of a country to notify the appropriate
consulate when a foreign national is arrested is spelled out in the
Vienna Convention on Consular Relations.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenski said the State Department has taken steps to ensure
that the 50 states are aware of the Vienna Convention. She said,
for example, that in 1996 an assistant secretary for consular
affairs wrote to the governor of each state ``to remind them of
consular notification.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona officials have conceded that they did not follow the
Vienna Convention, but they said the LaGrands received all the
legal protections that are normally provided to U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of executions in the United States has stunned
many German observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes America, which regards itself as God's own country,
so devilishly fanatic about the death penalty?'' the influential
German magazine ``Der Spiegel'' asked last week.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine continued, ``Why are over 70 percent of all
Americans, including deeply religious fundamentalist Christians who
regard abortion as murder, in favor of government-sanctioned
killing? What draws politicians of every stripe to the death
penalty, although the rest of the civilized world has long turned
away from it?''
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans were offended at the decision this week of Gov.
Jane Hull to reject not only the German plea to spare LaGrand's
life but also to reject the recommendation of the state's own
clemency board that the execution be delayed 60 days so that
Germany could take the case to the International Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``What difference would it make to her if they waited for two
months?'' asked Sofia Fielhauer, a reporter for
``Berlinerzeitung,'' a Berlin daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it seems that she was acting for purely political
motives, to show how tough she is.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets of Berlin, some Germans were critical of
their own politicians' intervention in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two aren't really even Germans,'' said house painter
Axel Heinisch, 38. ``I think that (German) politicians just wanted
to find something to make a stink about.''
</P>
<P>
   High school student Dario Goetzke was equally unmoved by the
fate of the LaGrands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They committed a crime in the United States, and I think they
should be punished there, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Dietmar Herz, a political science professor at the
University of Bonn, noted, most Germans are against the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is a major execution in the United States, the
issue of the death penalty will be discussed here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged by the failure of German political pressure to move
Gov. Hull, some Germans this week were suggesting an economic
boycott of the state that has long been a favorite vacation
destination.
</P>
<P>
   The current edition of Berlin's popular ``Tip'' magazine is
calling for a letter-writing campaign to pressure Hull to grant a
new trial to another German on death row. The object of the
magazine's concern is Berlin-born Debbie Milke, who is on death row
in the state prison in Perryville for the murder of her 4-year-old
son.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine wants its readers to sign a letter to Hull that
reads, ``Arizona is a beautiful state. You once said, `The people
here live from tourism.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But one does not like to vacation in a state of murderers.'' &QL; 
Mary Beth Warner is a correspondent. Warner reported from Berlin,
and Kammer reported from Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
