<SLUG> BC-TITANIC-CLOSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY'S `TITANIC' TO CLOSE AFTER FAILING TO TURN A PROFIT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The producers of the musical ``Titanic'' announced
Wednesday that they would close the $10 million production, one of
the most expensive in Broadway history, on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Michael David, one of the lead producers, would not say what the
show's exact loss was, but he said the musical had earned back more
than half of its initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of the musical was informed of the decision after
Wednesday's matinee performance. After its final performance,
``Titanic'' will have played 804 performances and 28 previews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We determined a dignified leave-taking was better than staying
too long,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   The show opened in April 1997 amid a spate of reports of
technical problems with the mechanized set, which simulates the
musical's central dramatic event, the sinking of the luxury cruiser
in 1912. The reviews were mixed to poor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, the musical seemed to gain strength after winning
five Tony Awards in June 1997, including Best Musical. By the fall
of that year, ``Titanic'' was the top-grossing show on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The musical's fortunes were also buoyed by a renewed interest in
the disaster spurred by the blockbuster film of the same name,
which swept last year's Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, the show's steam appeared to be running
out. It has been steadily losing money since early January.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the closing in New York, David tried to put a positive
spin on the occasion, saying that ``Titanic'' would continue to
tour in the United States and abroad well through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one feels really bad because of its history, and how we
fought for it,'' he said. ``But these days, New York is really just
the first chapter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
