<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA04-COX     03-03 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewinsky interview reveals little of Big Picture
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barbara Walters' wonderfully horrible and horribly
wonderful interview with Monica Lewinsky on Wednesday night on ABC
was the moment the mainstream media quit pretending. No more
pretense about obstructing justice or suborning perjury. It was a
peep show, in the great tradition of peep shows.
</P>
<P>
   It was sad and it was irresistible, the two things TV puts
together best.
</P>
<P>
   ``You found yourself alone with Bill Clinton and you lifted the
back of your jacket and showed the president your thong
underwear,'' Walters said, as she did throughout the night, with
almost comic straight-forwardness. ``Where did you get the nerve?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was me,'' the 25-year-old answered, giggling, her
trademark helmet of hair slicked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you become intimate so quickly?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was my sexual soulmate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have said oral sex is not sex. You call it what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Messing around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know what phone sex is. As best you can,
explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... It's fun!''
</P>
<P>
   We even got the famous interview tears, which have become our
kind of national stigmata, a dripping sign that we got from our
celebrity what we were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky admitted she'd had an abortion after becoming pregnant
by an older man at the Pentagon. She acknowledged that both her
parents considered suicide during the past year. ``People have no
idea what this has done,'' she sobbed. ``Behind the name Monica
Lewinsky there is a person and there is a family. There is so much
pain that has been caused by all this.''
</P>
<P>
   She then reached for a tissue from a box conveniently placed by
her chair.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the time Lewinsky would roll her eyes after yet
another frank question from Walters, exclaim, ``This is so
embarrassing,'' giggle a bit, then blurt out something like, ``I
think I tried to get him to want to have sex with me.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing here that had anything to do with any Big
Picture. It was all about a woman who said she never intended to
say anything about her affair and then on ``20/20'' told maybe more
than 30 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Today Lewinsky tells even more people. Her book, ``Monica's
Story,'' arrives in bookstores today and is already No. 1 on
Amazon.com's Hot 100 Bestsellers list. An interview with Britain's
Channel 4 airs tonight in 32 foriegn countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Lewinsky says that Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr's office ``was sick'' for asking so many detailed questions
about her sexual encounters.
</P>
<P>
   She said a first meeting with prosecutors made her so distraught
that she considered hurling herself from the 10th floor window of
the hotel room where they interviewed her.
</P>
<P>
   The book accuses the prosecutor of colluding with Paula Jones in
obtaining the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the Walters' interview, Lewinsky said she's no
longer in love with Clinton (``Sometimes I have warm feelings for
him ... sometimes I hate his guts''), that she just wants to get on
with her life, get married, have kids.
</P>
<P>
   But not until after the book and the overseas interviews.
</P>
<P>
   As literary agent and provacateur Lucianne Goldberg said on
CNBC's ``Hardball with Chris Matthews'': ``It's her movie. Let her
live it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
