<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-DOGWAR-NYT &LR;      03-03 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-DOGWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PEACE PLAN TO CALM BARKS AND SHOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The dog war rages on, and the stories from the front
line are not pretty. This week an elegant woman who lives on
Riverside Drive arrived half an hour late for a dinner party and
explained her tardiness in two words: ``Dog patrol.'' She grimly
displayed her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' she said. ``I'm still shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   She told of walking her Labrador retriever _ on a leash, as
required by law _along the promenade in Riverside Park near West
86th Street. Suddenly a dog-patrol vehicle appeared, and a menacing
voice emanated from the window on the driver's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approach the truck,'' the voice commanded, and she knew enough
about the dog patrol not to resist. She approached. When she got to
the truck, the driver grudgingly conceded a mistake _ ``I couldn't
see your leash'' _ but then detected another violation: her leash
exceeded the legal limit of six feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let me off this time,'' she said. ``I couldn't believe it _
dog owners have become public enemies. Approach the truck!''
</P>
<P>
   She shuddered at the memory. ``You know, I'm beginning to
understand how Jews felt in Nazi Germany.'' Her companions, in
deference to her trembling hands, refrained from pointing out that,
you know, it wasn't quite the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Reasoning with either side in this war is becoming difficult. On
Wednesday, the anti-dog partisans cheered on the patrol divisions
of trucks and horses as they swept across Riverside Park, trapping
dog walkers in a ruthless pincers movement. The dog freedom
fighters were busy posting manifestoes on fences denouncing the
Parks Department. As they watched the horseback patrols go by, they
also bitterly wondered why the rangers weren't wielding
pooper-scoopers for their animals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, peace may not be an impossible dream. With a couple of
simple steps, the city might be able to address everyone's
grievances, leaving New York with freer dogs, happier humans and
greener parks.
</P>
<P>
   The first step would be to give the Parks Department and the
public a new incentive to appreciate dogs. As things stand,
officials understandably see dogs as a nuisance, because the
animals damage landscapes that have been expensively restored and
groomed. And the majority of New Yorkers who don't have pets
understandably resent the idea of surrendering parkland to the
minority of dog owners.
</P>
<P>
   But what if dogs started paying their own way? What if the city
charged owners an annual park-usage fee of, say, $50 per dog?
Assuming that there are 750,000 dogs in New York City (estimates
typically range from 500,000 to 1 million), the fees would total
nearly $40 million a year, which is roughly a quarter of the entire
annual operating budget of the Parks Department.
</P>
<P>
   Officials would suddenly begin seeing dogs not as pests but as
profit centers. The money, besides paying for damage caused by dogs
and for the maintenance of enclosed dog runs, could also finance
improvements benefiting all park users.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a mechanism for collecting this money, because
dog owners are required to spend about $10 apiece on dog licenses,
although most don't bother. If the city enforced the requirement
and raised the fee, the extra money could all go to the Parks
Department, with the revenue from each license specifically
designated for the park near the dog's home.
</P>
<P>
   The second step would be to relax the leash law for certain dogs
in certain areas of the parks. The dogs would have to wear a
special tag, which would be available only to well-behaved dogs. To
qualify for the freedom tag, an owner might have to buy liability
insurance and certify that the dog is well behaved (perhaps by
having the dog pass the ``canine good citizen test'' developed by
the American Kennel Club).
</P>
<P>
   Could these measures bring peace? A leader of the dog freedom
fighters was optimistic. ``The ideas sound OK to me,'' said Jeffrey
Zahn, an Upper West Sider who is president of a group of dog owners
called Floral. ``Some people might complain about paying the fee,
but we all know that having a pet costs something. I think the vast
majority of owners would support it if it was going to the parks.''
</P>
<P>
   The supreme commander of the dog patrol, though, was politely
noncommittal. ``They're interesting proposals,'' said the parks
commissioner, Henry J. Stern. ``We could certainly use the money,
but Mayor Giuliani doesn't believe in new taxes.'' So for now, at
least, shuttle diplomacy has failed. Somewhere in Riverside Park,
hands are still trembling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
