<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SCOOPS, HOLD THE CHITCHAT 
OVITZ ENCOUNTERS 
A STAR'S BAR WARS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH COREY KILGANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The book party was for Peter G. Peterson _ a former
secretary of commerce and a founder of the Blackstone Group, a
merchant bank _ at the Council on Foreign Relations on the Upper
East Side of Manhattan on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There were funny speeches by Richard C. Holbrooke, President
Clinton's nominee to be chief delegate to the United Nations, and
Henry Grunwald, the former editor in chief of Time Inc., among
others. Holbrooke said that the title of Peterson's new book,
``Gray Dawn,'' which is about the aging of the population, made it
sound like a spy novel.
</P>
<P>
   The drama was near the door. Mortimer B. Zuckerman, the chairman
and co-publisher of The Daily News, was standing there listening
when in walked Barbara Walters of ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   The people between them tensed up, aware that The News had
scooped Ms. Walters' scoop that very morning. The News had printed
a two-page article with quotes from Ms. Walters' interview with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At first neither Ms. Walters nor Zuckerman made eye contact. But
when the speeches ended, they had a brief, polite conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, Mort was a friend and will continue to be a
friend,'' she said Wednesday, ``but when he walked up to me, I
said, `Not today, Mort, not today.' He said, `This could have
helped promote the interview.' I said we could live without the
honor.'' Zuckerman did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz Encounters &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actor Bill Murray told people at ``Saturday Night Live'' when he
was a host last month about an encounter with Michael Ovitz, the
former Walt Disney president who has been trying to corral clients
for his new talent agency.
</P>
<P>
   Murray asked what Ovitz, his former agent, had thought of his
performance as a steel tycoon in the Wes aNderson &UR;  &LR; film
``Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said he had not seen the movie. Murray said something like
``Good luck,'' and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ridiculous,'' a spokesman for Ovitz said Wednesday.
``They've been great friends for 20 years.'' Murray's agent,
Jessica Tuchinsky, said through a spokeswoman, ``This is the first
we have heard of that.''
</P>
<P>
   A Star's Bar Wars &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She was there, she said, because a number of bars have moved
into the neighborhood around her loft on West Broadway near White
Street _ among them the Bubble Lounge and the Liquor Store.
</P>
<P>
   As if waiting for a cue, composer and performer Meredith Monk
sat quietly Tuesday at a meeting of the TriBeCa Committee of
Community Board 1, which covers lower Manhattan. She listened as
her neighbors objected to a request from one of the owners of the
Liquor Store, Marcello Maiorani, to expand the size and operating
hours of his sidewalk cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Ms. Monk piped up, describing ``drunken people throwing
bottles at 2 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't sleep in the front of the loft anymore,'' she said.
``It's too noisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maiorani responded: ``I'm not calling you a liar, but I've not
seen this.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange ended with a community board employee, Judy Duffy,
saying that she felt that Ms. Monk's claims were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lives on the top floor, and she's the only one who
complains,'' Ms. Duffy said, referring to Ms. Monk. ``She has her
assistant call the community board all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Ms. Monk said that despite the expensive air purifiers she
had installed, her loft ``still gets filled with smoke'' from the
Bubble Lounge, on the ground floor of her building. ``My vocal
cords are getting damaged, and I literally can't breathe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
