<HEADER>
A7148 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOMELESS-WORKERS-N     03-03 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW-WAGE WORKERS TURN TO SHELTERS TO BRIDGE THE GAP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kenneth Lindo walks with bond traders and bankers
through the gleaming lobbies of Wall Street during the day, his
canvas messenger's bag heavy with checks and stock certificates
from the longest bull market in memory. But at night, he beds down
at the 30th Street Men's Shelter in Manhattan, rolling his winter
jacket in the sheet under his head.
</P>
<P>
   Until January, Lindo had a pillow to call his own, in a Harlem
room that cost $20 a day on his $5.50-an-hour pay _ almost 70
percent of his take-home income. At the shelter, he does without.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to get there earlier than 5 p.m. to get a pillow,''
explained Lindo, 44, as he loped through deliveries in the
financial district, where he has worked on and off for near the
minimum wage since he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   Lindo's double life illustrates a larger paradox. The booming
economy has provided employment for more low-wage workers like him,
but by driving up rents, it has made it harder for them to cover
the cost of housing, sending some to the city shelter system to
bridge the gap.
</P>
<P>
   And the system they encounter is in the midst of re-evaluating
the role work should have for its shelter residents.
</P>
<P>
   Recent court rulings cleared the way for the city to require
parents in family shelters to work for the city in exchange for
their beds, and the Giuliani administration is arguing for the same
authority in shelters for single adults. But how such a system
would work remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Would residents with pay from private-sector jobs still qualify
for shelter beds? Might they, like shelter residents in
Philadelphia, have to turn over a percentage of their earnings to
sleep there?
</P>
<P>
   Simply getting a steady bed in a shelter has become more
difficult for many people who work but cannot find affordable
housing. More than 69 percent of the city's 7,570 shelter beds are
now operated under contracts by private, nonprofit agencies, many
in programs geared to substance abusers or the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the specialized beds have been developed with a
therapeutic or rehabilitation approach that there are very few beds
available for men who are working and simply need a roof over their
heads until they can get housing,'' said Steven Banks, director of
the Legal Aid Society's Homeless Rights Project.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Wiviott, a spokeswoman for the city's Department of
Homeless Services, said that the recent overflow was temporary,
caused mainly by seasonal demand. Like most cities, New York does
not compile statistics on the number of people who are employed
when they enter the shelter system, she said, but she estimated it
as ``very minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   But for these working homeless, the nightly routine of long
waits, broken sleep and early morning ouster from unfamiliar beds
can threaten their ability to keep a job.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Wall-Carty, who works a mix of day and evening shifts as a
cook for the Houlihan's restaurant chain in Garden City, on Long
Island, was on the overnight circuit last month, and described the
trial of keeping up private-sector work while depending on a
rotating shelter bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was six days of hell,'' Wall-Carty said, ``and for three of
them I didn't sleep at all.''
</P>
<P>
   While many people think of typical adult shelter users as
chronically homeless derelicts or the mentally ill, a majority of
those who entered the New York City system between 1988 and 1995 _
nearly 60,000 men out of a sample of 73,293 _ left within two
months and did not return, or came back only briefly, over the next
three years, according to an analysis by Dennis P. Culhane, an
associate professor of social welfare policy at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in this group were not without problems, Culhane's
analysis showed: About a third came with histories of substance
abuse. But many, he said, were working people coping with crises of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People for whom the economy has really made life good have
trouble understanding why these people can't make it,'' said Mary
Ann Gleason, the executive director of the National Coalition for
the Homeless in Washington. ``But there's an inverse relationship
between a strong economy and the affordability of housing. You have
this direct rise in housing cost in proportion to what the market
will bear, but we haven't increased the minimum wage.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Proscio, former deputy commissioner for the New York City
Department of Homeless Services and now a consultant on urban
development, said there was another reason why the current robust
economy might cause more of the working poor to end up in shelters:
Employers hard-pressed to fill jobs without swelling labor costs
have hired workers passed over in a weaker economy, including some
with criminal records or histories of substance abuse that put them
at greater risk of losing their housing.
</P>
<P>
   Lindo, a divorced Army veteran who graduated from high school in
1973, puts himself in that category. He spent six days in a
detoxification program in early January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your life catches up with you sometimes,'' he said, describing
a 1995 drug conviction for which he is still on probation, credit
card debt from Christmas three years ago, and traffic tickets from
a stint as a taxi driver.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is trying to pay off the fines so he can drive a cab
again. The Wall Street messenger service he works for runs a mail
room under contract to a prominent investment bank. Lindo asked
that the companies not be named.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might not like it,'' he said, ``that I'm living in a
shelter.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
